<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-LIGHTNING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRETZKY COULD BE AT THE END 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Wayne Gretzky carefully guided the puck to Mathieu
Schneider, who blasted it from just inside the blue line. John
MacLean deflected it into the net for the decisive goal in the New
York Rangers' 2-1 victory over the Tampa Bay Lightning. In the
stands, children dressed in No. 99 jerseys held up signs pleading
with him to return next season. Gretzky is not sure. With two games
remaining in the Ranger season the question hangs in the air: Will
he or won't he retire after 20 seasons?
</P>
<P>
   John Davidson, the Rangers' television analyst and a longtime
friend of Gretzky's, said Sunday that Gretzky was about 80 percent
certain that the Rangers' final game next Sunday against Pittsburgh
would mark the end of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just time to think about things,'' Gretzky said Monday
night at Madison Square Garden. ``I said this before, that it's a
year at a time now. It's a lot different than it was last year. All
of a sudden it's become a bigger issue than maybe I had imagined.
It's become a hot topic. That's why I'm trying to talk about it.
We'll see what happens over the next five or six days.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Gretzky's agent, Michael Barnett, said: ``Only
time will tell. He certainly hasn't decided anything yet. When he
does, I'm sure he'll tell people that he feels need to hear it
first. When that is, no one knows. He's always maintained that he
would know before anyone else when it's the right time. I'm sure
that's still his belief. Everyone will respect that decision. At
this point, I do not believe he's made a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll wait until I meet with John,'' Gretzky said, speaking of
a postseason meeting with coach John Muckler. ``Nothing has been
decided. It's something that is obviously more at the forefront
than this time last year. But there is no decision at this time.
We're going to sit down at the end of this year and discuss what
the future holds.''
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky, who signed with the Rangers as a free agent on July 21,
1996, has one year left on his contract, which is a team option
worth $5 million. But the option is clearly Gretzky's.
</P>
<P>
   There are few milestones left for Gretzky, having passed his
boyhood idol, Gordie Howe, with his 1,072nd professional goal on
March 29. In sight are 900 regular-season National Hockey League
goals; he is six short. Even now, a long time since he signed with
the Indianapolis Racers in 1978, and with the disk problem in his
neck hampering him throughout the season, he leads the Rangers with
61 points.
</P>
<P>
   The bulging disk that sidelined him for 12 games still pains
him. Before the game, while preparing, he wore a neck brace as
protection. Whether he wants to play through the pain for a team
that has missed the playoffs in two consecutive seasons may be the
most telling part of the decision-making process.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Gretzky has maintained that he would not conduct
a farewell tour of the NHL. But as Davidson pointed out, if he
returns next year he will have no choice. Even in the indecision,
Gretzky has been subjected to scenes such as the one he saw in
Chicago on Friday night, when the fans stood and cheered for him,
moving him to tears on the bench. But it will be a decision that
will not be made rashly with Gretzky still maintaining that he has
not decided.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indications as far as Wayne retiring are in that
direction,'' Davidson said Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The indications,'' Davidson said, ``are that he's very
seriously thinking of looking at this upcoming weekend as his final
game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
