<SLUG> BC-WILSON-OBIT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
T. WILSON, FORMER BOEING CHAIRMAN, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAUL SHUKOVSKY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ T. Wilson, who led Boeing through the dark days of the
``Boeing Bust'' in the 1970s to record sales, died in his sleep
Friday night at his winter home in Rancho Mirage, Calif. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   The former chairman and chief executive, Thornton A. Wilson _
known simply to his friends as `T' _ wanted to fly airplanes as a
young man. But he broke his leg and ended up building airplanes for
Boeing instead. It was an accident that forever changed aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson went on build the Minuteman missile that helped define
the Cold War and committed billions of Boeing dollars to the risky,
simultaneous launch of the 757 and 767 aircraft that helped define
commercial aviation.
</P>
<P>
   When he turned the daily reins of the company over to Frank
Shrontz in 1986 following years of deep recession in the airplane
business, sales were at an all-time high and so was the backlog of
airplane orders.
</P>
<P>
   And when he stepped down as chairman the next year, Shrontz
said: ``T. Wilson guided the company from one of its lowest points
in the late 1960s to fiscal strength and market leadership today.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Sutter, sometimes called the father of the 747 and a retired
executive vice president of the commercial airplane company, said
Monday: ``When T left Boeing, it was an end of an era. T had
courage, the courage to launch two airplanes (757 and 767)
simultaneously. ... T was a very firm leader. You knew who was
running the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Boeing President Harry Stonecipher, while recalling
the ``old Boeing,'' recounted a conversation with Wilson in which
he told him, ``Boeing is arrogant. He (Wilson) responded: `And
rightly so!' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Sutter offered a different perspective. ``There
wasn't an arrogance at Boeing. Boeing had an edge, an edge on the
competition. We had ... the mental attitude to get in it to stay.
There was an espirit d'corps. And T was the leader. He made all the
big decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   E.H. ``Tex'' Boullioun, retired president of Boeing Commercial
Airplane Group, knew ``T as a good friend since 1950 when I was
shooting missiles up in the air for the company and T started on
the airplane business and invited me to come over and work with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``T was a good leader,'' said Boullioun. ``Even though he might
disagree with you, it wasn't a deal like `I'm right and your
wrong.' We'd go in big rooms and talk and it was like man and wife.
He could bark real hard and real loud. But he was very sincere and
very nice.''
</P>
<P>
   M. Lynn Olason, retired vice president and general manager of
the 747 program, Monday called Wilson ``a man of decisions. When he
got all the facts that he wanted, he would make a decision and that
was it. He loved airplanes. He was a great designer. He listened to
the designers.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson started working for Boeing in 1943 after getting an
undergraduate degree from Iowa State University in aeronautical
engineering. He got his master's degree in 1948 from California
Institute of Technology.
</P>
<P>
   His first job at Boeing was developing the B-47 swept-wing
bomber. Then he became a project engineer on the B-52. In the
1960s, Wilson ran the team that won the Minuteman ICBM contract for
Boeing and became the Minuteman general manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, he was named president and had the added duties of
chief executive officer in 1969. He was elected chairman of the
board in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is survived by his wife, Grace Miller Wilson; their three
children, Thornton A. Wilson III, Daniel Wilson and Sarah
Parkinson; and six grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who apparently died in his sleep, was found by family
members Saturday morning, Boeing spokesman Peter Conte said Monday.
The cause of his death was not known.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no memorial services, Boeing spokeswoman Amanda
Landers said. Remembrances can be sent to the University of
Washington, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and his wife spent half the year in Rancho Mirage and the
other half at their long time home in Normandy Park, south of
Seattle, Olason said.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
