A5762 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-HN     04-13 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ANGELS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rangers' pitching woes result in disappointing 3-4 homestand
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
ARLINGTON _ They brought him back home after a five-year hiatus to
further juice what already was one of baseball's most imposing
lineups. The Texas Rangers didn't necessarily expect to get a spin
doctor in the bargain, but they seem to have landed one of those,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of times when you get off to a great start, you tend to
relax,'' designated hitter Rafael Palmeiro said in assessing the
first week-plus of the season. ``You think it's going to be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost better to get off to a slow start to make us
realize that it's not going to be easy. It's not going to be handed
to us.''
</P>
<P>
   At 3-4, the Rangers are not off to a good start. Nothing is
looking particularly easy, either. If first impressions go for
anything, in fact, the defending American League West champions
couldn't feel too good about things as they packed their bags for a
12-game road trip that begins tonight in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The latest bit of bad news: a 13-5 loss to Anaheim on a sunny
Monday afternoon at The Ballpark in Arlington, giving the Angels
three wins in four games in this early AL West showdown. In the
series, the Rangers were outscored 34-15.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can't get much worse,'' manager Johnny Oates said.
``There's really only one way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   At the heart of the problem: A pitching staff that was
considered shaky at best now aspires to mediocrity after giving up
19 hits Saturday night and 20 more (10 of them doubles, an Angels
club record) on Monday. An overworked bullpen struggles under the
load of a succession of bad starts.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of clutch pitching, expected improvement in the
field has yet to materialize, due in part to a lingering shoulder
injury that has kept shortstop Royce Clayton out of the last four
games.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, not exactly a great beginning for a team with a $75
million payroll, one supposedly primed to improve on last year's 88
wins and a humbling Divisional Series sweep at the hands of the
Yankees. And as early litmus tests go, this series with the Angels
couldn't have gone much worse for the Rangers, who were embarrassed
by a team that seemed ripe for the taking.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim hit town with nine players on the disabled list,
including big offseason signee Mo Vaughn (ankle), shortstop Gary
DiSarcina (broken left forearm) and outfielder Jim Edmonds (groin,
shoulder). The Angels had other excuses, too, since they didn't
arrive at their hotel until 7 a.m. on Friday _ barely 12 hours
before game time _ after sitting through a lengthy rain delay on
getaway night at home.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Anaheim managed to win the first two games by a combined
score of 18-4, including a 10-0 Saturday night skunking in which
the Angels outhit Texas 19-3. The Rangers averted the sweep with a
6-3 win Sunday night, but Monday made that look more like an
aberration than a sign of life.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Clark, making his second start as a Ranger, labored through
five ugly innings, giving up eight runs and 11 hits in a
performance very much in keeping with the early trend.
</P>
<P>
   In the first seven games, the Rangers got only two starts of
more than five innings, both from Aaron Sele, who is 2-0 with a
0.71 ERA and feeling very much out of place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even the good pitches I threw weren't good enough,'' Clark
said after his latest shelling. ``It was just one of those days.''
</P>
<P>
   In just over a week, days like this have been far too frequent,
more than offsetting a respectable 5.1 runs a game from the
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way you can overcome 13 runs, 10 runs, eight
runs,'' Oates said. ``Mentally, you just can't do that everyday.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for a change of scene, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   ``Going on the road will be good for us,'' Palmeiro said.
``We've got some quality arms, some quality pitchers. It'll be good
to see if we can put all three phases together.''
</P>
<P>
   Those phases hardly were in sync Monday. After falling behind
1-0 on Tim Salmon's first-inning RBI double, the Rangers tried to
help Clark out with a three-run second, with Lee Stevens, Jon Shave
and Mark McLemore driving in runs, but the lead wouldn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim got a run in the third on back-to-back doubles by Randy
Velarde and Darin Erstad, then batted around in a five-run fourth,
with Salmon's three-run double accounting for most of the damage.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim made it 8-3 in the fifth when Troy Glaus doubled, went
to third on a ground ball and scored on a wild pitch, ending
Clark's misadventure. Todd Zeile's two-run homer in the bottom of
the inning cut the deficit to three, but that was as close as it
would get.
</P>
<P>
   So the Rangers hit the road to Seattle, Oakland, New York and
Minnesota. After an opening homestand they hoped would provide some
momentum, they instead find themselves facing an early crisis of
confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not this bad,'' Oates said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the evidence suggests otherwise.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
