<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMISSIONER'S USE OF DETECTIVES SETS OFF NEW ROUND OF CRITICISM
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani found himself defending Police
Commissioner Howard Safir once again Monday, acknowledging that the
commissioner had used eight on-duty detectives to provide security
at his daughter's wedding but calling it ``perfectly appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Safir both said the eight detectives, assigned to
the squad that is responsible for the commissioner's safety, were
necessary to provide adequate security for Safir and his family.
The detectives logged a total of 119 hours of work at the wedding,
costing the city more than $3,600.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a perfectly appropriate use of the detail,'' Giuliani
said.
</P>
<P>
   Without being asked, the mayor also said that he had no plans to
request that Safir step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police commissioner is not leaving,'' Giuliani said. ``He
is not going anywhere. The more unfair stories that you write about
him, the more I am convinced that he is doing a really good job and
people are threatened by it.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir also defended his use of the detectives at the wedding,
saying, ``I get threats every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's use of detectives at the wedding was first
reported Monday in The New York Post, which said the detectives
drove Safir's extended family to a photo session in Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Mode, a spokeswoman for the Police Department, said
Monday that limousines were hired for the wedding, but added, ``The
detectives may have given some people lifts, but it was all for
security reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has had to defend Safir a number of times in recent
weeks as the commissioner has faced scrutiny over whether he has
abused his authority.
</P>
<P>
   It began when Safir and his wife, Carol, took an
all-expenses-paid trip last month to the Academy Awards in Los
Angeles. That trip, paid for by a Revlon executive whom Safir has
described as a family friend, is now the subject of a city ethics
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, after the Safirs filed a lawsuit against a Queens
woman who had been involved in a car accident with Mrs. Safir two
years ago, Safir admitted that he had sent two detectives to the
woman's home to see if she posed a security risk to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilman Sheldon S. Leffler, chairman of the Public
Safety Committee, said Monday that he was disturbed by what he said
appeared to be a pattern of poor judgment by Safir. ``It has become
part of a pattern of the commissioner apparently thinking that
these uses of city police officers are part of the perks of the
job, when the opposite should be the case,'' the councilman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it sets a bad example for all the other cops,'' he
said. ``There are 40,000 cops on the force who are not supposed to
even take a free sandwich.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayor criticized news organizations for the way they have
covered Safir.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really do think that you are playing games with the police
commissioner,'' he said Monday at Shea Stadium, where he was
attending the Mets' first home game of the season. ``I understand
the game. It is a really cruel one and it's a nasty one and it's
trying to go after somebody in public life. And it's really a shame
that you do it and it's a shame that the media can't learn a little
more discipline in the way in which they handle it. I am not angry,
I am not lashing out. Somebody's going to write that tomorrow
because no matter how calmly I say something, that's what you
write.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the car accident, Safir said Monday that his wife had
dismissed the lawyer who filed the lawsuit on their behalf,
claiming that he never informed them about what was in the suit.
They replaced the lawyer, Martin Grossman, with Raoul Felder, a
friend of the family who has represented the Safirs before.
</P>
<P>
   The original suit, against Monica Nascimento, a concierge at a
midtown hotel who lives with her mother in Queens, asked for $1
million in damages for injuries to the commissioner's wife and
$250,000 because Safir was deprived of her ``companionship and
consortium.'' It contended that Ms. Nascimento was intoxicated from
drugs or alcohol, but offered no evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Felder said that he expected to file an amended suit and that
Safir would probably not be a party to it. ``I don't think it's in
his character to want to be one of the plaintiffs,'' Felder said.
</P>
<P>
   The amended suit, he said, would probably not accuse Ms.
Nascimento of being intoxicated. ``It's unknown how the allegations
of intoxication and the drug business came in there,'' Felder said.
``I don't think that comports with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Grossman did not return a call Monday afternoon seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said: ``This is a suit that was brought by an attorney
that I never met, who brought it on my behalf, who when I asked him
why, he said, `That's the way I always do it.' Well, that's not the
way it ought to be done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
