<HEADER>
A5766 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-ISLANDERS-     04-13 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-ISLANDERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTVIN TOO TOUGH FOR DEVILS' BEST SHOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The New Jersey Devils set a franchise
record on Monday night for most shots in a game with 57, but Felix
Potvin of the New York Islanders tied the team's franchise record
for saves, turning aside 55 attempts as the usually hapless
Islanders gained a 4-2 victory at Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils missed an opportunity to tie the Ottawa Senators for
first place in the Eastern Conference. The Senators were beaten,
2-0, by Florida on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin's performance was a rare bright spot for the Islanders,
who will miss the playoffs for the fifth straight season. After
becoming the backup goalie in Toronto when the Maple Leafs signed
Curtis Joseph as a free agent last summer, he eventually left the
team and was later traded to the Islanders, where he has struggled,
posting a 5-8-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that Potvin, traded for Bryan Berard in
what seemed a one-sided deal until Monday night, would not play
again this season after injuring his groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fun to be part of the win,'' Potvin said. ``I sure
tested the groin tonight. It was fine all night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils (44-24-11) still have a chance to catch the Senators
(44-23-13) because they have three games left to two for Ottawa,
the team that eliminated the Devils in the first round of the
playoffs last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't look at the scoreboard and say, `Ottawa is losing,'
because it doesn't matter whether Ottawa is winning or losing,''
said Brian Rolston, who scored the first goal for the Devils.
``What we want is to play solid hockey going into the playoffs, and
we didn't tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Robbie Ftorek and Rolston cited the Devils' lack of
patience in the offensive zone and their shot selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were pressing a little and I don't know why,'' Ftorek said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur, who made 19 saves for the Devils, said Potvin
was the difference in the game. ``He played real well,'' Brodeur
said, ``but we had our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Orszagh, playing in his 10th game for the Islanders,
opened the scoring with his first goal in the National Hockey
League, 12 minutes 17 seconds into the game. The shot fooled
Brodeur because it deflected off the stick of Scott Stevens, the
captain of the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   Mats Lindgren gave the Islanders a two-goal lead with his eighth
of the season, on a power play just five seconds before the first
intermission, sending the Devils to the dressing room trailing by
2-0 even though they were outshooting the Islanders by 19-11.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils dominated action in the first two periods but had
difficulty capitalizing against Potvin. Patrik Elias had numerous
chances from excellent positions but was unable to convert.
</P>
<P>
   Potvin faced 40 shots during the first two periods, the only one
that eluded him being Rolston's blast from near the point at 5:04
of the second on a power play. Potvin was screened by Dave
Andreychuk of the Devils on the goal, Rolston's 22nd of the season
and third in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Watt extended the Islanders' lead with his eighth of the
season at 8:09 of the third period. After Jason Arnott responded
with his 27th less than two minutes later, Claude Lapointe sealed
the victory for the Islanders with his 14th of the season with 2:19
left.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
