<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-ANNIVERSARY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMEMBERING THE DAY 50 YEARS AGO WHEN THE GROUND BEGAN TO CRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL BARBER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At 11:55 a.m. on a Good Friday 50 years ago Tuesday,
housewives around Puget Sound were tuned into KVI radio's ``Queen
for a Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle was savoring a win by its beloved Rainiers baseball club
over the Sacramento Solons the night before.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, city workers were streaming into the streets to begin
their lunchtime rush hour. Outside in the 58-degree weather, kids
on spring vacation were playing.
</P>
<P>
   At 11:56 a.m., it was all forgotten in the most destructive
earthquake this century in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 7.1 magnitude temblor centered near Olympia
cracked the ground and toppled walls around Western Washington. A
keystone on a cupola at the state Capitol in Olympia was shaken
loose, almost bringing down the dome.
</P>
<P>
   In Tacoma, the dome of the Carnegie Library buckled, and the
Pierce County Courthouse was so badly damaged it later was razed.
</P>
<P>
   Before the dust and fear settled, eight people were dead, 64
injured. The area took stock of damages of as much as $170 million
in today's dollars _ and its good fortune. It could have been much
worse, they said. Bricks and debris fell on streets packed with
lunchtime crowds, but few were hit. In most towns, the schools were
empty.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, Dorothy E. Rogers, now 77, was home in bed nursing a
cold at the Roy Apartments. She remembers leafing through a
magazine when the quake hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pictures on the wall began banging back and forth,'' she
recalled. ``I got up to go to the window, but I could hardly stand
up. I was sliding back and forth on a throw rug and I had to hang
on to the window sill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked into the alley and saw movement all around. I looked
up and saw the third-floor above us _ you could actually see it
bulge and sway out over the first-floor,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the city around her, frightened office workers and shoppers
raced into the streets. Trolleys skidded to a halt. Cars lurched
along the roads, jamming intersections. Clocks stopped. Water mains
burst. Lights flickered out.
</P>
<P>
   Though Seattle was on the northern fringe of the rumbling
ground, the force caused the Smith Tower, then the city's tallest
building, to sway violently. The old Seattle Hotel on Yesler Way
was too old to sway. It buckled, raining cement to the street.
Parked cars were flattened.
</P>
<P>
   Olympia suffered much more damage. Centered 30 to 40 miles
beneath the surface near the capital, the fault that caused the
quake is too deep to see even with today's machines, geologists
say.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Walsh a state Division of Geology and Earth Resources
geologist, says the 1949 quake essentially was caused by the Juan
de Fuca slab subducting into the Earth's mantle under the North
American plate.
</P>
<P>
   That means it caused the earth to move in a rolling nature, much
like a shaken bowl of jelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 1949 quake had been preceded by two 6 magnitude quakes in
1939 and 1946, which some (scientists) considered to be foreshots
of the 1949 earthquake,'' Walsh said.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said the ground held relatively firm in Olympia, where
scientists might expect to see liquifaction _ soil turning to
quicksand. It had been a dry year. Olympia could have suffered
more.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, a community died.
</P>
<P>
   A Post-Intelligencer photographer recorded the picture of Roland
and Linnea Lund, then nine and six years old, respectively, who had
attended Cascade School. It, along with Cascade and Lafayette
school in West Seattle, was extensively damaged and closed.
</P>
<P>
   But the demise of the Cascade school helped usher in the end of
old Cascade neighborhood, long a transitional residential area for
immigrants and the poor. The loss of its school took away the heart
of the community.
</P>
<P>
   The Lund children and a friend were playing with a friend near
their father's house at Howell Street and Denny Way when the ground
around them revolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was only six years old and I remember that moment,''
recalled Linnea Lund Benthien. ``I remember looking at my brother
and our friend and seeing the questions on their faces. My brother
was holding a capgun and I remember seeing it swaying in his
hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Roland Lund, now spokesman for the state Department of Labor and
Industries, ran into his father's house, not realizing it might be
unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard glass, everything, crashing around inside _ I was a
9-year-old kid and didn't know better. I ran back outside and by
then it was over,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Children elsewhere weren't as lucky.
</P>
<P>
   Among the eight dead was Marvin Klegman, 11, of Tacoma, a sixth
grader and Cub Scout who left school early to take his post as a
noon-hour crossing guard. He was crushed by bricks from a
fourth-floor dormer at Lowell Elementary School. A year earlier,
the fourth floor was condemned after parents urged it be torn down.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Klegman, now a Federal Aviation Administration attorney in
Redondo Beach, Calif., was in second grade when his older brother
died. He still has his brother's crossing guard vest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very close to Marvin. I would wait for him to come home
from school every day. I have pictures of us sitting together on
the school steps,'' Klegman told The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Rosen, also a second-grader, had walked out of the school
with Marvin after lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked back and people were pulling bricks off Marvin,''
said Rosen, now president of Rosen Supply Co. in Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   Marvin was buried two days later at Home of Peace, the Jewish
cemetery in Lakewood. School crossing guards formed a cordon of
honor.
</P>
<P>
   In Castle Rock, senior class president Jack Roller, was also
leaving school for lunch when he was killed by a falling brick. He
was 18.
</P>
<P>
   Adults died in Centralia, Olympia, Cosmopolis and Seattle,
killed by falling bricks and heart attacks. The injured suffered
broken bones, sprains and cuts from flying glass.
</P>
<P>
   One 29-year-old Seattle woman, Dorothy Hazel Rogers, (no
relation to Dorothy E. Rogers) was delivering a son by Caesarean
section when the quake hit. Their lives hung in the balance when
the quake knocked out the hospital's oxygen and anesthesia
equipment. Mother and child were later said to be fine.
</P>
<P>
   Before 11:56 a.m., the troubles of the world were held at arm's
length.
</P>
<P>
   Moviehouse newsreels showed President Truman urging Congress to
approve the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   The newspapers were following events in San Marino, Calif.,
where 3-year-old Kathy Fiscus had fallen into an abandoned well and
was clinging to life after 48 hours. Seattle's emergency officials
were pre-occupied taking reports of open wells here. They changed
their focus at lunchtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thousands of persons poured into downtown Seattle streets at
the height of the quake,'' the P-I reported, ``fleeing the danger
of falling buildings.
</P>
<P>
   ``They huddled in the center of streets, in parking lots and any
available open space, many women crying and children screaming as
the paralyzing fear of sudden disaster ran through the crowd.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Busy Bee on Third Avenue, bartender Bill Given vaulted
the counter to bar the door to his fleeing patrons. Seconds later
concrete boulders smashed into sidewalk outside.
</P>
<P>
   While there was great fear, there was little panic. At Boeing,
15,000 workers conducted an orderly evacuation, as did personnel at
military bases.
</P>
<P>
   In a day of near misses, one of the more dramatic happened at
the Tacoma Narrows bridge.
</P>
<P>
   In Gig Harbor, Jack Smith remembers his stepfather, Bill Grant,
was one of the state highway bridge builders breaking for lunch on
a barge below the towering span.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the earthquake flicked off a gigantic steel saddle
capping the northeastern tower, which was installed but not riveted
down. It rocketed 600 feet to the barge below just as the men were
opening their lunchboxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went right through the barge'' but missed the stunned crew,
Smith recalls from what Grant told him. One man was injured by
flying lumber and a nearby workboat steamed toward the barge to
help out.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time it got there, they were all up to their chests in
water,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what to think about that quake,'' said Smith, a
WWII veteran who has lived through several of them. ``I think a lot
of how you remember it depends on where you were at that day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
