<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARE THE YANKEES BETTER THAN THE BEST? 
</HEADLINE>
   (With BBA-YANKEE-STADIUM) 
 (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The 1999 Yankees could be better than the 1998 Yankees, who won
125 games and have ``Best Ever'' inscribed on their World Series
rings. Do not flip the page with derision at this suggestion. Do
not scoff at this possibility. Do not speculate that it is a
belated April Fool's joke. It is not.
</P>
<P>
   One of the beauties of baseball is comparing players and teams,
even if the difference in eras often makes it a thorny process. But
there is little difference from 1998 to 1999, so expect a season of
passionate debate about whether these talented Yankees are or can
be better than those talented Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Even speculating about the latest version of the Yankees someday
being superior to the 1998 version seems irreverent. Those Yankees
won more games than any other team in history, including a sweep of
the Padres in the World Series. Any resolution to this comparison
is six months away and, even if the 1999 Yankees keep the debate
percolating by winning a World Series, any resolution might only be
an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Still, six games into the season, the Yankees have performed
like a team intent on building a legacy. Sure, it is less than 5
percent of the season and injuries can undermine the most
formidable teams. Sure, it will be nearly impossible to duplicate
1998. Sure, there are innumerable reasons why a 5-1 team should not
be compared with a 125-50 team. Yet.
</P>
<P>
   But when Joe Torre, the proud manager of the 1998 champions who
will be back next month to manage the 1999 wannabes, was asked
whether the 1999 team can be better than the 1998 team, he did not
hedge.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' Torre said. ``Just because you don't win as
many games doesn't mean you're not a better team.''
</P>
<P>
   Six and a half weeks before the opener, the Yankees became
better by acquiring Roger Clemens from the Toronto Blue Jays for
David Wells, Graeme Lloyd and Homer Bush. The team with the best
record ever nabbed one of the best pitchers ever. Clemens, who has
not lost a game in almost a year, has brought leadership, intensity
and, so far, one of many victories to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Clemens, there is less pressure on David Cone to
stretch seven innings every start or for Andy Pettitte to hurry
back from a sore elbow. Clemens actually makes the confident
Yankees more confident and is a major reason the starters are 4-0
with a 2.12 ERA (he has a 1.93 ERA in two starts). That has
happened without Pettitte, whose 55 victories are more than anyone
else in the American League in the last three years, and with
Ramiro Mendoza, who was supposed to be a reliever and sixth
starter. After the champs received their Series rings on Sunday,
Clemens, his fingers naked, gazed at the ring on Torre's right
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how we're going to improve on this, but we're
going to try,'' Torre told him. Clemens simply kept staring. ``The
look in his eyes wasn't envy, it was hunger,'' Torre recalled. ``I
think that's what you get when you get a Roger Clemens.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's Tony Clark said Clemens gives New York ``a different
air,'' and Manager Larry Parrish cited the significance of having
Clemens and designated hitter Chili Davis, who is batting .500 with
three homers and seven runs batted in, for a full season. Parrish
forgot Orlando Hernandez, who will torment hitters for a whole year
and could win 20 after winning 12 in 21 starts last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hate to give them the World Series already,'' said
Parrish, who turned silent for 10 seconds and considered whether he
wanted to predict another title for the Yankees a few days into the
season. He bridled himself. ``But they are definitely going to be
having a shot at doing that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course they are. Analyze the roster and the only places where
the Yanks are not better or as equipped as in 1998 are in short
relief, because they do not have the luxury of a second southpaw
like Lloyd, and in bench speed, because Bush is gone. Quick,
someone send George Steinbrenner a sympathy card.
</P>
<P>
   With four No. 1-type starters, the rotation is better. Fronted
by Mariano Rivera, the bullpen is sound. Tino Martinez should
produce more because he was bothered by a nagging back injury last
year. Chuck Knoblauch underachieved a year ago and already looks
more confident. Derek Jeter could be the premier player in the
league. Scott Brosius might not drive in 98 runs again, but a No. 9
batter does not have to.
</P>
<P>
   Davis will provide more consistent production at d.h. The
combination of Jorge Posada and Joe Girardi will be better because
Posada will catch more. Bernie Williams won a batting title and is
still blossoming. Paul O'Neill will retire when he stops hitting
lasers. Some combination will handle left field.
</P>
<P>
   Could 1999 be another dream team?
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be better,'' Cone said. ``We could conceivably be in
better shape in terms of overall health. We had so many things
break right for us last year, some dramatic come-from-behind wins.
That's tough to match. But I still think that we're going to be in
a lot of games. Night in, night out, we'll have a chance to win
because of our pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees will win, and the debate will continue. See you in
October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
