<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEAVER AND MCCARVER ADJUST TO NEW JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Tom Seaver insisted that he ignored the carping when
he took Tim McCarver's place in the New York Mets' television booth
and, at the same time, became the organization's newest pitching
guru. The din was loud, so Seaver must have worn dandy earplugs at
home in Fresno, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an issue,'' he said outside the WPIX-TV booth at Shea
Stadium Monday before he threw out the first ball for the home
opener and then broadcast his third game of the season. ``It's the
mentality of regarding what a broad spectrum of people said when I
pitched. You can't control what people write.''
</P>
<P>
   The pitching side of his Mets' employment (his other
front-office duties are unspecified) is confined to spring
training, but he will talk to any pitcher who seeks his opinion. On
Monday, he spoke to Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd do that if I were just an announcer,'' Seaver said. ``You
owe it as a member of the fraternity.''
</P>
<P>
   But he confessed Monday to anxiety about returning to the Mets
after a long exile and to TV after a five-year absence. Perhaps
that was manifested in Seaver's errant ceremonial first pitch,
which must have tempted Mike Piazza, the ceremonial first-pitch
catcher, to bend despite his sprained knee ligament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was not Tom's personal catcher,'' the Mets spokesman Jay
Horwitz observed.
</P>
<P>
   During his first Mets game for WPIX, on Friday night in
Montreal, Seaver said he felt anything but comfortable, working
into a dither of preparation. ``You should have seen my hotel room
Thursday,'' he said. ``It looked like a bomb shelter. You're
paranoid you won't have that one crucial piece of information, but
you try to balance all that against 25 years of pitching inside my
brain.''
</P>
<P>
   If not yet memorable in the booth, Seaver seems at ease. Working
beside Gary Thorne will improve anyone making a decent effort. They
have rapidly meshed into a functioning team, as Thorne has engaged
Seaver with smart questions. Seaver avoided one question Friday
night about how he would pitch to Piazza by saying, ``At 54, I'd
pitch him very carefully _ hopefully when the lights are out.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver benefits by not having to assume any of the play-by-play
load, which he did without distinction on New York Yankee games
from 1990 to 1993 with Bobby Murcer and Phil Rizzuto. Leaving that
to Thorne is wise because he is one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   And Thorne will rescue his partner. A terrific play Friday by
Rey Ordonez, the Mets' shortstop, begged for comment by Seaver.
Noticing the silence, Thorne asked, ``What are you smiling at?''
Seaver said, ``He made that look so easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver's best analysis focuses on pitching; he was exasperated
enough with Montreal's lousy pitching Friday night to walk into the
Expo clubhouse Saturday morning and ask, ``Who was responsible for
the pitching yesterday?''
</P>
<P>
   His non-pitching insights are pedestrian, requiring that he more
quickly scope out strategies and view the full field as well as he
spies sinkers.
</P>
<P>
   And insights enhanced by personal anecdotes will help. When he
discussed pitchers' hitting, Seaver recalled, ``Koosman thought he
was Mickey Mantle.''
</P>
<P>
   Seaver will be judged by his candor. He can say what he pleases;
if he is blunt, viewers will feel he is not shielding any of his
students' feelings.
</P>
<P>
   WNYW's McCarver-Murcer Yankee team had a rockier start in its
first game last week. Murcer's introductory comments, likening the
Yankees to a multicourse meal, were overlong. McCarver bobbled a
few names and seemed nervous.
</P>
<P>
   But by Game 2, they struck a better rhythm with McCarver saying
Yankee catcher Jorge Posada has as good an arm as the Texas catcher
Ivan Rodriguez, and engaging in good repartee about pine tar,
catching a knuckleball and Derek Jeter's use of the top hand on his
bat to generate more power. By Sunday, they openly discussed
Orlando Hernandez's possible perfect game. Discussing the $63
million payroll disparity between the Yankees and Oakland, McCarver
said, ``For that money in 1965, they could have built two
Astrodomes.'' Murcer said, ``Thank Heaven that didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarver and Murcer create a warm, folksy blend. Yet, Murcer
should not be the lead play-by-play announcer for six innings.
Murcer has never been strong or careful enough for play-by-play.
McCarver should be the dominant voice.
</P>
<P>
   Masters Rating
</P>
<P>
   The well-produced final round of the Masters _ subtitled ``The
Major Tournament CBS Really Wishes Greg Norman Would Win'' _
generated a 10.7 overnight Nielsen rating, up 8 percent from last
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
