<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-VALENTINE-690&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING RECORD FOR VALENTINE (BUT WHO'S COUNTING?)
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBN-METS-MARLINS) 
 (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ That was not just another victory the Mets gained in
their Shea Stadium opener on Monday. The 8-1 conquest of the
Florida Marlins gave the Mets' manager a winning record in his
11-year major league managerial career. The team doesn't play
Tuesday, so Bobby Valentine can savor his over .500 mark _ 775
victories, 774 losses _ at least until Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Before the opener, John Franco was asked if the team felt any
pressure trying to win this one for Bobby. ``He didn't say
nothing,'' the Mets' veteran closer and team leader said, ``so I
guess there isn't that much pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Bobby Bonilla, whose two-out broken-bat single
was the key hit in a four-run surge in the fifth inning, was asked
how it felt to get Valentine on the winning side of the ledger.
``Nobody really knew about it,'' Bonilla replied, ``but it's nice
to see that happen.''
</P>
<P>
   All right, so the manager's won-lost record wasn't the most
emphatic thought on the players' minds. It evidently wasn't on
Valentine's either. ``You can't count years when you take over a
team,'' Valentine has said in rejecting the thought that he's a
losing manager, ``because it's not your team.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentine became a major league manager with the Texas Rangers
in May 1985. He went from June 20 of that season to last Sept. 16
without having more victories than losses. After he went two
victories over losses in the ensuing three days, the Mets lost the
last five games of the season, sending Valentine back to a losing
record and themselves home.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets cannot escape those final five games. One or two
victories would have catapulted the Mets into the playoffs as the
wild-card team, but the victories never came.
</P>
<P>
   Players and managers don't like to look back and dwell on what
happened last year. ``Last year was last year,'' they proclaim
robotically. ``This year is this year.'' But it is in the job
descriptions of fans and reporters to look back and continue to
scrutinize past seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But even Valentine allowed himself a comment Monday on the
difficulty the Mets had last season with the Marlins and the
Montreal Expos, who had the worst records in the National League.
The Mets have begun this season by beating those same two teams six
times in eight games, three of four each.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know their players better,'' Valentine said when asked why
the difference. ``We've scouted them better. Rather than saying
we're better than them and just throw our gloves out there, we've
prepared better for them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Valentine's first two seasons with the Mets, they did not
have their own person scouting teams in advance of games against
them. They used a service that provided films and reports on
players. For this season, however, the Mets hired John Stearns, one
of their former catchers, to serve as the advance scout.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Mets opened the season with a three-game series
against the Marlins, Stearns, who had watched them play 12
exhibition games in 17 days, submitted an intricately detailed
30-page report. The value of the report has been obvious in the
results of the games. Some of the Marlins have noticed a
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``They used to pitch me inside,'' first baseman Derek Lee said.
``They're pitching me outside this year. Maybe that is a case of
better scouting. Last year a lot of us were first-year players, so
they probably have a better idea of what we can do now.''
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Mark Kotsay said that ``maybe pitching-wise they
might show that they have scouted us out as hitters better,'' but
he offered another observation as to the difference between the
Mets' September failure and their April success.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference is it's not a pressure situation,'' he said.
``It's early in the season. Obviously you want to win ball games,
but there's not a playoff spot on the line right now. Last year
there was a lot of pressure for them to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a game won in April is one less a team has to win
in September, and winning six of the first eight beats losing the
last five.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A surprise guest was on hand for the winning home opener. Seated
in a third-base box with the co-owner Fred Wilpon was Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, the Yankees' first fan.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani attends a baseball game, it's virtually always at
Yankee Stadium, and he wears his ``lucky'' _ his description _
Yankees jacket. That apparel, of course, would have been in bad
fashion taste Monday, so he wore, at his suggestion, a Mets jacket
and cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like he was in pain, though,'' said Steve Phillips,
the Mets' general manager, who instantly looked as if he wanted to
swallow his politically incorrect words.
</P>
<P>
   As he sat through the game, Giuliani most likely was unaware
that the Mets' clubhouse was being flooded by backed-up sewer
water, a result of a pump problem the Mets said the city was
responsible for avoiding.
</P>
<P>
   Nor was it likely that the Mayor knew about Valentine's winning
record, but then, the manager's players didn't know either.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 0034EDT &QL; 
