<HEADLINE>
PHONING FOR `PHANTOM' TICKETS MAY BE ALLOWED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To camp out or not to camp out may no longer be
the question.
</P>
<P>
   Fans seeking tickets to the first showings of ``Star Wars,
Episode 1: The Phantom Menace'' had been told two weeks ago that
George Lucas and 20th Century Fox wanted movie theaters to limit
sales to same day only. That would have mostly prevented ticket
scalping during the first dozen days.
</P>
<P>
   But the mogul and studio have apparently relented in the face of
exhibitor complaints and will allow advance sales.
</P>
<P>
   How far in advance and how many tickets per customer are still
to be determined. The Hollywood Reporter, citing unnamed sources,
said Monday presales are expected to last at least a week prior to
the May 19 opening and could feature a credit-card system that
would limit multiple purchases.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Sherak, chairman of Fox Domestic Film Group, said no
definitive agreement has been reached on presales but added that
Fox has been trying to take theater owners' concerns into account.
The executive conceded two weeks ago that Fox could not force
theaters to ban advance sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working with the theater owners to work out the
best way to handle this,'' Sherak said. ``The whole idea has always
been to protect the public from ticket scalping.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Dergarabedian, president of Exhibitor Relations Co.
service, said the proposed advance-sales ban was problematical for
theater chains. He noted the potential difficulties of dealing with
patrons who would be frustrated over having no guarantee of seeing
the movie even after spending hours in lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Lucas and the studio may be loosening up how they do
this and try to make it a little easier for the ticket buyers,''
Dergarabedian said, adding that some kind of limit on the number of
tickets is likely. In any scenario, business will be huge, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to sell out no matter what the delivery is,''
Dergarabedian said. ``You'll have pretty quick sellouts that way if
you've got several ways of buying tickets. And I don't know how
you'd prevent scalping.''
</P>
<P>
   Although dozens of hard-core fans began forming lines last week
outside Mann's Chinese and Westwood Village theaters, advance sales
would likely be welcomed by many other patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd buy tickets over the phone without a second's hesitation
because I'm too old to stand in line for hours,'' said Altadena
resident Richard Manly, who plans to take his 13-year-old son,
Josh, to see ``Phantom Menace.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did it for `The Exorcist,' but that was back when I had the
energy for doing crazy things. I'm a middle-aged man now,'' said
Manly, whose son was born three years after the last ``Star Wars''
movie _ ``Return of the Jedi'' _ was originally released.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
