<HEADLINE>
PROCTOR JONES, 83, PUBLISHER AND AUTHOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ohio, N.C.)  (lb) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Proctor Patterson Jones, an author, photographer, publisher and
lawyer who was a presence in San Francisco for over four decades,
died there on April 2 at his home in the Pacific Heights section of
the city. He was 83.
</P>
<P>
   Jones began his career writing legal texts. But he turned
professional photographer, filmmaker and author and in 1970 founded
Proctor Jones Publishing Co. He was still its president at his
death.
</P>
<P>
   The company's book list reflected Jones' curiosity about French
and Napoleonic history, on which he wrote extensively. He also
published photographic books and mystery novels, contributing
himself to both genres.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a native of Cleveland, graduated from Western Reserve
University in 1937 and studied law at Harvard and Stanford
universities before serving in the military in North Africa and
Italy in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He received a doctor of laws degree at Western Reserve, now Case
Western, in 1948. That year he returned to Stanford to study
political science, from which grew four decades of public service
on many governmental boards in the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   His books about Napoleon included English editions of the
memoirs of Baron Fain, a cabinet official (1998), and of Louis
Joseph Marchand, the emperor's valet and friend (1998). He was a
contributor to ``Napoleon: An Intimate Account of the Years of
Supremacy, 1800-1914'' (Random House, 1992), which earned the 1992
Literary Award of the Napoleonic Society.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife supported San Francisco's museums, symphony and
opera, as well as several historic sites in France.
</P>
<P>
   Jones is survived by his wife of 52 years, Martha Martin Jones;
two sons, John of Los Angeles, and Proctor Jr. of San Francisco;
three daughters, Melinda Windisch of Greensboro, N.C., Greta Jones
of Raleigh, N.C., and Martha Griffinger of Piedmont, Calif.; 10
grandchildren, and three great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 0057EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN     04-13 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS ENJOY HITFEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Tex. _ No Mo? No problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels arrived in Texas Friday lacking Mo Vaughn and Jim
Edmonds and maybe a little confidence after the Cleveland Indians
shut them down in a season-opening series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas Rangers provided the necessary relief _ a pitching
staff that is trying to find itself. The result was three Angels
wins in four games, including a 13-5 victory Monday afternoon
before 24,601 at The Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   In the four-game series the Angels had 57 hits. They had 20 hits
Monday, including a career-high four hits by Troy Glaus, four by
Tim Salmon and three each by Randy Velarde and Darin Erstad.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was a record-setting day for the Angels:
</P>
<P>
   __ Their 10 doubles is a new club record, breaking the previous
mark of eight.
</P>
<P>
   __ The three doubles by Glaus tied a club record.
</P>
<P>
   __ The five RBI for Salmon tied a career high.
</P>
<P>
   Rangers starter Mark Clark (0-1) took the brunt of the attack,
giving up eight runs and 11 hits in five innings. But the Angels
didn't play favorites on this day, scoring in every inning but the
second and sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Every starter except designated hitter Chris Pritchett had at
least one hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can hit,'' said Erstad, who singled twice, doubled, walked,
drove in one and scored three. ``We've got guys who are unselfish,
who will do what it takes to win, who will situational-hit. Look at
Pritchett _ he has no hits yet, but he doesn't care. He gets a guy
over to third base so we can drive him in. Stuff like that is so
valuable. We've got a good mix of guys right now. Numbers come
second.''
</P>
<P>
   Those putting up the biggest numbers now are Glaus and Salmon.
Glaus is hitting .481 (13 for 27) with two homers and seven RBI in
seven games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put a lot of time and effort into the offseason,'' Glaus
said. ``I wasn't doing it for a little while but (for) the whole
offseason. Right now it's paying off.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus is only 22 and less than two years removed from playing at
UCLA. But he says that doesn't give him an excuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter who I am or how long I've been here,'' he
said. ``I'm up there to drive in runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon's five RBI give him nine this season. He's hitting .393
(11 for 28), which is significant because traditionally he's been a
slow starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if I'm trying to do anything different,'' Salmon
said. ``A lot of times in the past we're playing New York, Boston
and Cleveland at the beginning of the year. And they have the best
pitching staffs. Maybe that has something to do with my slow
starts. Now maybe we're not facing the best pitching, and we're
taking advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   While Glaus and Salmon have been the most noticeable, the
hitting has come from all over. Even Orlando Palmeiro and No. 9
hitter Andy Sheets had two hits apiece Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about it is we've got nine guys getting the job
done,'' Angels manager Terry Collins said. ``Those two guys (Glaus
and Salmon) have gotten a lot of hits, but everybody's getting
them. We're spreading it out.
</P>
<P>
   All the offense made it easy for the Angels pitchers Monday,
even if Ken Hill wasn't able to stay in long enough to get the
victory. Hill gave up five runs and five hits _ walking seven _ in
four-plus innings. Mike Magnante (1-0), the first of three
relievers, earned the victory with 21/3 scoreless innings.
</P>
<P>
   While winning three of four from the Rangers was nice for the
Angels, Collins wasn't anywhere near giddy. His memory is too good.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we came in here halfway through the season and won
three of four,'' Collins remembered. ``And at the end of the season
we couldn't beat them. We just have to win some games. No
statements are made April 12.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
