<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5792 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ORGANS-AZR &LR;      04-13 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOULD ORGANS HELP SICKEST OR STAY IN STATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ There's no question in Dani Bonham's mind about
``what'' should be done with her organs after she dies. The
Chandler mother of six has been a card-carrying organ donor ever
since a stranger 12 years ago donated his liver and saved her
2-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   It's the question of ``where'' her organs and those of other
Arizona donors will go that's being fiercely debated.
</P>
<P>
   Should people on waiting lists in Arizona get first dibs on
them? Or should they go to sicker people in other states?
</P>
<P>
   And should the sickest people in Arizona be at the top of the
list for organs that become available in other states?
</P>
<P>
   A bill in the state Legislature would make sure those on Arizona
waiting lists continue to be first in line for organs donated in
the state. It has drawn fire from doctors, ethicists and transplant
patients who say it is just a ploy to protect Arizona transplant
centers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Under the bill, patients listed at Arizona transplant centers
would be matched first. If there were no matches in Arizona, then
the organ would go to other centers in Region 5 of the federal
transplant network, which includes California, Hawaii, Nevada, New
Mexico and Utah. If it isn't matched regionally, then it is matched
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   That's how the current system works _ and many say it does a
disservice to people throughout the United States who need organ
transplants the most.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration argues that the system, which has
more than 60 different areas working inside 11 regions, doesn't
work fairly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, liver transplant patients in New York City wait 600
days while those in New Jersey, just across the river but in a
different organ-procurement area, wait an average of 56 days,
according to a 1997 federal report. &QL; 
Not close enough &QL; 
Or consider Fort Worth and Dallas. The cities are only 30 miles
apart but because they are in different areas, they don't easily
share organs. If a heart becomes available in Fort Worth, it is
sent to Houston instead of Dallas because Houston is the same
region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's ridiculous. It's a violation of patients' rights, of
human rights,'' said Pam Silvestri, of the Southwest Transplant
Alliance. Texas is considering legislation similar to Arizona's.
But Silvestri's group, which procures organs in southeastern Texas,
has lobbied hard against it.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is expected to revisit the controversial issue of organ
allocation this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona and Texas are two of seven states that have either
passed or considered laws as a response to federal efforts to get
organs to the most needy patients _ whether they are in the
neighborhood or across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   In their successful attempt to get Congress to delay any changes
until October, the United Network of Organ Sharing argued that the
system needs more organs, not more federal interference.
</P>
<P>
   If the rules change, only larger transplant centers would
survive and most of Arizona's five transplant centers would suffer,
said Jack Cremin, president and chief executive officer of the
Donor Network of Arizona. The non-profit group coordinates organ
donations for the state. It is part of the United Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran some numbers. If in fact we had to do mandatory
sharing, there would be only one liver from an Arizona donor to
remain in Arizona and that would go to UMC (University Medical
Center in Tucson),'' Cremin said. The center does the most
transplants of any hospital in the state. &QL; 
More fairness &QL; 
Federal officials say Cremin and other members of the United
Network are wrong _ and that the federal government just wants more
equity. It's up to the United Network and its members to come up
with a system that is fairer, said Jon Nelson, director of the
office of special programs for the U.S. Department of Health and
Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   But if more organs go to the sickest patients, then larger
hospitals, which tend to be the ones that treat those patients,
will end up doing the bulk of transplants. Under federal rules, a
transplant center must perform 12 transplants a year to receive
organs, Cremin said.
</P>
<P>
   He disputes charges that his group is just trying to protect
transplant centers.
</P>
<P>
   Cremin points to the liver donations as an example of how
Arizona already shares with other states. In 1998, 74 livers _ the
most scarce of transplantable organs and the first that would be
affected by any rule changes _ were donated in Arizona.
Twenty-seven went to people waiting on Arizona transplant lists and
the rest went to people in other states.
</P>
<P>
   But frequently, Arizona is on the receiving end of the organ
chain. In 1997, for example, a third of the hearts were imported
from other states, said Dr. Belton Meyer, the former medical
director of the Arizona Health Care Cost Containment System. Meyer,
an ethicist, was a former committee member of Donor Networks.
</P>
<P>
   The measure being pushed in the state Legislature is not
necessarily in favor of Arizonans: It's in favor of Arizona
transplant centers, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David Beyda, director of pediatric critical care and an
ethicist at Phoenix Children's Hospital, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a transplant center and it needs local support,'' he
said. ``You need organs to come into the transplant center, it ends
up becoming a business. This is not a big philosophical issue.
Organs are being made a commodity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about money, and we need to look beyond that.''
</P>
<P>
   People should think about the ethics behind the economics, says
Beyda. &QL; 
Tough questions &QL; 
Say you were an organ donor and you have a family member who is a
patient in Pittsburgh with 24 hours to live. Should your kidney be
shipped to that patient, or should it go to someone on an Arizona
waiting list who is out playing golf?
</P>
<P>
   Beyda, Meyer and other ethicists across the country argue that
allocating organs by ZIP code rather than by need is ``ethically
indefensible.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, there are more transplant programs opening up. This
summer, Mayo Clinic Hospital and Good Samaritan Regional Medical
Center will open liver transplant programs. Good Samaritan had a
program two years ago but closed it because of lack of staffing.
</P>
<P>
   Both Samaritan and Mayo are neutral on the bill pending in the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Valley patient groups such as the Arizona chapter of the
American Liver Foundation and the National Kidney Foundation also
said they are remaining neutral because their national groups
haven't weighed in.
</P>
<P>
   Some individual patient advocates have made up their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Cullison, executive director of the Arizona Liver
Foundation, said she backs the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't feel the need to rock the boat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But another, Dale Ester, former president of the Arizona
Association of Kidney Patients, said inequities hurt people no
matter what state they live in.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill came up too fast and it leaves patients wondering
what is going on out there. The message I got (from the
Legislature) was that they were not going to listen anymore. They
had made up their minds,'' said Ester, who had been on the federal
committee that wrote the 1997 report.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Sue Grace, chairwoman of the health committee and the
bill's sponsor, said she is pushing it because it protects
Arizonans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a donor state now,'' Grace said. ``There are states
that aren't doing as much as our organizations. It seems that we
are penalizing the state for doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Donor Network of Arizona doesn't keep a register of organ
donors. But according to federal statistics, Arizona's rate of
donors per million was 19.6 from 1994 to 1995. It ranks 45th among
the country's 66 organ procurement groups.
</P>
<P>
   Grace said she doesn't understand why this issue has drawn so
much ethical fire.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, however, predicts the Arizona Legislature will spark
other states to take similar defensive moves.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of curtailing the sharing of organs, the Legislature
should be more concerned with increasing donations, Meyer said.
</P>
<P>
   There have been some suggestions that more families of donors
would approve the donation if they knew where the organs were
headed, said Glenna Shapiro, director of the Arizona Kidney
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the loved one would like them to go to a Baptist in a
certain age group,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Shapiro said she recently led a focus group of potential organ
donors that demonstrated their diversity. One person in the group
wanted his organs to go to a young person with a full life ahead;
another person in the circle said, ``No, I want them to go to a
middle-age person because I don't know long they (the organs) could
last.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonham, the Chandler mother convinced of the value of donation,
is just as divided as the people in Shapiro's focus group. She's
not enthusiastic about more federal involvement, but she strongly
believes the sickest should get them the soonest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, as for my organs,'' Bonham said, ``they can pack them up
in the Igloo and send them to whoever needs them the most.'' &QL; 
Jodie Snyder can be reached at (602) 444-8667 or at
jodi.snyder(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
