<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLAZERS' STRATEGY WAS TAYLOR-MADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles Clippers continue providing
evidence that they play to the level of competition, which at 5-31
indicates the NBA is up to David Stern's chin in bad teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Clips' latest conquest was Sunday's 89-83 stunner in
Portland. This followed Saturday's pasting by the Trail Blazers in
Anaheim and gives the Clippers two wins in five games against the
league's two top teams by record _ the Blazers and Utah Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's victory was managed despite Portland holding a
nine-point lead late in the fourth quarter. The Blazers didn't
score in the game's final 2:27.
</P>
<P>
   Clippers forward Maurice Taylor, who scored 14 consecutive
points in the fourth quarter, said his outburst was easy to
explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (Blazers) weren't doubling me,'' he said. ``I could have
plenty of quarters like that if they don't bring the double team.''
</P>
<P>
   Portland decided against using that almost-automatic tactic
because Rasheed Wallace, the Blazers' quick and springy 6-foot-11
forward, had been solid defensively against Taylor most of the
weekend. The 6-8 Taylor, who prefers backing his way to the hoop
from the low post, was forced to change this strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play with your back to Rasheed,'' he said, ``because
he's long and quick off his feet. So I turned and faced him and
went from there.''
</P>
<P>
   And, for those scoring at home as Taylor was in Portland, credit
for that offensive approach should go to Elgin Baylor, the
Clippers' vice president of basketball operations. Baylor just
happens to be one of the greatest, if not the greatest, forward in
the history of forwards.
</P>
<P>
   __ `Cap' room: Point guard Sherman Douglas scored a season-high
19 points in the victory at Portland, and was expert at feeding
Taylor down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, coach Chris Ford named Douglas team captain for the
remainder of the season and Douglas has responded by taking charge
of the offense. But Douglas says his recent success is the product
of improved health.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting healthy and getting in shape is the most important
thing,'' said Douglas, who was signed to a one-year contract the
day before the season opener. He wasn't exactly fit as a fiddle
then and his lack of conditioning was exacerbated by subsequent
groin and thigh injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas, who will run the show tonight against his most-recent
former team, the 10-25 New Jersey Nets, is stepping lively now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting there,'' he said. ``I'm about 85 or 90 percent. We
need to go out now and show some consistency. After our other wins,
we've gone out there the next game and set basketball back a couple
thousand years.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Hawking Hudson: The second 10-day contract of CBA escapee
Troy Hudson expired Monday, but Baylor spent part of the day
working out a deal to keep the young point guard around for the
rest of the season and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson provided glimpses of what could be a bright future while
backing up Darrick Martin, but his minutes have been in sharp
decline since Douglas' return from the injured list.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
