<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TERM-LIMITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: DO-IT-YOURSELF TERM LIMITS 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 13:
</P>
<P>
   Reps. George Nethercutt, a conservative Republican from
Washington, and Martin Meehan, a liberal Democrat from
Massachusetts, share a peculiar problem. They first ran for office
promising self-imposed term limits. Now they have come to the point
when they vowed they would quit. Both are wondering if their
constituents would object to a self-imposed reprieve.
</P>
<P>
   Since it has become clear that the House of Representatives has
no appetite for passing a constitutional amendment that would
impose term limits across the board, many candidates for Congress
have promised their constituents that if elected, they will
voluntarily step down after a given number of years. U.S. Term
Limits, which specializes in getting candidates to sign these
pledges, says 10 House members will hit their self-imposed deadline
next year. Most seem content to leave on schedule, but a few,
including Nethercutt and Meehan, apparently like the job more than
they expected, and are wavering.
</P>
<P>
   Nethercutt beat Speaker Thomas Foley in 1994 in a campaign that
focused heavily on Foley's opposition to term limits. Nethercutt
made a point of promising to stay in office for no more than three
terms, but now his aides say he did not understand how important
seniority was in Congress. This page has long argued that term
limits are a bad idea, but nevertheless, this is a lay-down hand.
People who run for office should be accountable for what they say.
Voters are smart enough to understand that a vow to cut taxes or
fix education has to be taken with a grain of salt. But anybody can
keep a promise to quit. Many people voted for Nethercutt because
they agreed with him about term limits. If they had wanted
seniority, they would have stuck with Foley.
</P>
<P>
   Meehan, a fine legislator, says he made a mistake in promising
to limit himself to four terms, and that his constituents now would
be upset if he abandoned causes like campaign finance reform.
Pragmatically speaking, he does not have to worry. His district is
a safe one. If he runs again, the Democrats will nominate him, and
the Republicans are unlikely to waste money running a strong
candidate against him. But politics is not going to be improved by
demonstrating to voters that Meehan's party does not expect to hold
him to his promise, and that the public will probably be given no
satisfactory alternative to re-electing him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 0108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
