<HEADER>
A5797 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Rockets-HNS &LR;      04-13 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Rockets-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Talk helps Rockets end slump
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MINNEAPOLIS _ Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich, having covered all
the pregame Xs, Os and keys he cared to, spoke about ``passion,
fire.'' Hours earlier, Rockets players sat down for a players-only
meeting to talk about, among other things, passion and fire.
</P>
<P>
   In the grip of a sudden free fall from the heights of their
nine-game winning streak, the Rockets longed for a return to their
lost winning ways.
</P>
<P>
   It all seemed to have worked to the letter Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets built a big second-half lead, lost it, then faded
badly down the stretch. But at the brink of a defeat, they
recovered neatly to beat the Timberwolves 95-90 at Target Center.
The good old days of March were finally back.
</P>
<P>
   With their first road victory against a winning team this
season, the Rockets even picked up a half-game on the Lakers to
move percentage points ahead for the fourth seed in the Western
Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   But more than all that, they had a win they needed, having
invested far more emotion than in any of their four games since the
April 1 collapse in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been terrible to have it stolen from us after
everything we talked about at our meeting today, and everything
we've gone through the last week or so,'' Rockets forward Othella
Harrington said. ``To lose that way, today, it would have been bad,
really bad for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been, Tomjanovich said, ``devastating.'' Having
lost four of their past five games beginning with the crushing
defeat in Utah when they squandered a 15-point lead in the final
eight minutes, the Rockets recaptured the intensity that marked
their winning streak and built a 16-point second-half lead.
</P>
<P>
   They had run their offense as expertly as in the days when they
could not be beat. They had, as they had so often back then, found
the one hot hand at the 3-point line, getting 17 points they had to
have from Sam Mack off the bench. Scottie Pippen, though still
playing a limited role as a shooter, harassed Kevin Garnett into a
9-of-24 shooting night.
</P>
<P>
   The funk that had infected the Rockets since the April Fool's
Day collapse _ save the rout of the Warriors _ seemed to have been
fully lifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw passion and fire in the guys today,'' Tomjanovich said
as if that in itself was a victory. ``I mentioned two games, San
Antonio and Seattle, as far as coming out when it's an important
game playing with fire and passion. That first quarter set the
tone. We had a great second quarter. And held them off to 10 (going
into) the fourth quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   But with that, the Rockets suddenly lost their edge. The
Timberwolves found their shooting touch in the final minutes of the
third quarter, making five of six shots to end the quarter with a
10-4 run.
</P>
<P>
   After Charles Barkley posted up to push the Rockets' lead to 12
to start the quarter, the Timberwolves scored the next seven
points, and the lead that had been 16 less than five minutes
earlier was down to five. Barkley hit a pair of free throws and
Hakeem Olajuwon a hook in the lane for a nine-point lead, but
suddenly the Rockets' offense collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said, however, that the Rockets' control was taken from
them, and not by the Timberwolves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officiating was terrible tonight,'' Barkley said. ``We had
two blind mice. They let them get in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have seven players on the court at all times tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   A prime example might have been a fast-break layup Barkley
missed when James Robinson seemed to be intentionally fouling him.
Bryce Drew followed the miss to push the Rockets' lead to 10 one
last time, but the Timberwolves immediately cut the lead back to
six, Robinson making two free throws and Joe Smith a jumper.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen blocked a Garnett shot, his second rejection of Garnet,
and Mack went down for what seemed a momentum grabbing layup. But
three consecutive Rockets turnovers quickly sapped any momentum
they had taken. Smith hit two free throws and a 22-footer to move
the Timberwolves within four, 87-83, with 2:53 left.
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to inspire the Rockets to repeatedly go inside
to Olajuwon and Barkley. But they combined to miss three straight
shots, and Pippen threw away a pass to Olajuwon in the post.
Garnett pulled the Timberwolves within two with a finger roll with
1:58 left as part of a 10-2 Minnesota run.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley was called for charging Smith, and Robinson had an
18-footer for a tie.
</P>
<P>
   But when it missed, Barkley grabbed the long rebound, drove the
ball upcourt and found Mack in the corner for a 3 and a five-point
lead with 1:17 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just let the play develop,'' Barkley said of his sudden role
as point-power forward. ``I though Sam would go to the basket, but
I saw him out there at the 3-point line.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, the Rockets made just enough free throws to hold off
the Timberwolves and believe their lost touch from March
recaptured.
</P>
<P>
   ``We played with a sense of urgency,'' Pippen said. ``We have to
come out and be the aggressor and not get back on our heels. We
played hard-nosed defense, we stopped them from second-shot
opportunities. That was the difference in the game. We had to come
out and show some dominance. We've been down the past couple weeks.
It's times we get it back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
