<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-QBS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOING DEEP: QUARTERBACK DEPTH IN NFL DRAFT BEST IN YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Tim Couch. Akili Smith. Daunte Culpepper. Donovan
McNabb. Cade McNown.
</P>
<P>
   Call them the Class of '99, because these those five
quarterbacks definitely are the creame de la creame of what is the
deepest position in this year's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Each is expected to be selected in the first round Saturday,
with either Kentucky's Couch or Oregon's Smith being the top pick
overall by the expansion Cleveland Browns, and there is a distinct
possibility that quarterbacks could be selected in the top three
spots for the first time since 1971.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to determine exactly who goes where and when is like
taking orders from a group of kids in an ice cream parlor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It comes down to flavor. Which flavor do you prefer?'' said
Randy Mueller, Seahawks vice president of football operations.
``Each of these guys has strengths and very few weaknesses, but
what's the flavor you like best?''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, depends on whom you ask.
</P>
<P>
   While one scout gushes about Smith's arm strength, another is
awed by Couch's poise. While one general manager views McNabb's
scrambling ability as a definite plus, another wrinkles his nose at
the thought of the Syracuse quarterback running for his life from
phantom pressure. While one offensive coordinator looks at UCLA's
McNown and sees the next Steve Young, another sees a short passer
with a side-arm delivery. While one personnel director is enamored
with the size of Central Florida's Culpepper, another wonders how
big is too big to play the position in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   As Tom Modrack, director of football operations for the
Philadelphia Eagles, puts it, ``These quarterbacks are so close
together, you could just throw their names into a magic hat, pull
one out and you'd get a good football player.''
</P>
<P>
   Each is drawing so much attention because so many teams are in
the market for a quarterback, and some are downright desperate _
the Browns, Eagles and Cincinnati Bengals, who have the first three
picks; as well as the Chicago Bears and Tampa Bay Buccaneers; and,
to a lesser degree, the Seahawks, Miami Dolphins and Baltimore
Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   ``League-wide, there is a need for quarterbacks,'' said Pat
Mondock, Seahawks college scouting director. ``And this is
definitely a good group.''
</P>
<P>
   The best ever? That's going a little too far. This year's group
has numbers _ with Couch and Smith being followed closely by
Culpepper and McNabb and McNown sitting somewhere between the big
four and a second group that includes Tulane's Shaun King, Ohio
State's Joe Germaine, Miami's Scott Covington, Howard's Ted White
and Washington's Brock Huard.
</P>
<P>
   Each has put up impressive numbers.
</P>
<P>
   But to say Couch, Smith and company constitute a better group
than the 1983 class that started with John Elway as the first pick
overall and did not stop until Dan Marino was the sixth QB taken in
the first round is saying too much. Also included in that '83 class
were Jim Kelly, Tony Eason, Ken O'Brien and Todd Blackledge.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Blackledge's meager contributions, these six have
combined for 11 Super Bowl appearances, 24 Pro Bowl selections and
105 miles in passing yardage _ led by the future Hall of Fame trio
of Elway, Marino and Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say anyone in this group is going to be Dan Marino or John
Elway or Jim Kelly, no. No chance,'' Mueller said.
</P>
<P>
   OK then, the best class since that class of '83?
</P>
<P>
   ``Physically, they all have above-average arms, above-average
athletic ability, great delivers, quick releases,'' Mueller said.
``As a group, they're as good as any group in the last 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch, Smith and Culpepper put up numbers last season comparable
to those of Elway, Marino and Kelly in their final seasons at
Stanford, Pitt and Miami. But those QBs from '83 have, or had,
special qualities that can't be measured in yards or completion
percentages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest thing to evaluate about quarterbacks is what makes
them tick,'' Mueller said. ``That's what you don't know about this
year's group. That's what you won't find out about this group until
they've played at this level for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate the uniqueness of what happened 16 years ago, a
total of six quarterbacks were selected in the first round of the
next five drafts combined.
</P>
<P>
   Also consider that in the 29 drafts since the NFL-AFL merger in
1970, two quarterbacks or more have been drafted in the first round
only four times and a QB has been the first pick overall only eight
times _ including 1971, when Jim Plunkett, Archie Manning and Dan
Pastorini went 1-2-3; 1993, when Drew Bledsoe and Rick Mirer went
1-2; and last year, when Peyton Manning and Ryan Leaf were the top
two picks.
</P>
<P>
   There are reasons for this.
</P>
<P>
   It can risky to use a high pick on a quarterback, especially for
teams reaching to fill a need. For every Elway, there has been a
Dan McGwire. For every Terry Bradshaw, an Art Schlichter.
</P>
<P>
   A safer route is to opt for what looks like a sure thing. This
year, that would be the best player in the draft, Texas running
back and Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams; or the best athlete
available, Georgia cornerback Champ Bailey; or the rare commodity,
a tall, athletic corner in Arizona's Chris McAlister or a big-play
inside linebacker in USC's Chris Claiborne.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterbacks often push their way ahead of more secure picks
because of the position, which only makes this year's group that
much more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   All have touch, not to mention arm strength, mobility and
impressive athletic ability. But each also brings his own unique
touch to the table.
</P>
<P>
   Couch is the bumpkin, born in a one-stoplight town of 350 people
in the hill country of Kentucky, who blossomed into a
football-flinging gentleman the past three seasons for the
Wildcats.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is the former minor-league baseball player, who returned
to football only after flailing at curveballs during a three-year
stint as an outfielder in the Pittsburgh Pirates farm system.
</P>
<P>
   Culpepper was born in a prison, where his mother was serving a
term for armed robbery. He was raised by his grandmother, who also
had 14 adopted children.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb is a physical specimen who stands out even in this
impressive group, a gifted athlete who benches 380 pounds, has a
vertical leap of 36 inches and runs 40 yards in 4.45 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   McNown is the Doug Flutie of his generation, a plucky passer who
somehow gets the job done, and then some, despite not being the
biggest athlete on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the almost-overlooked fact that three of the top
five are black. When Smith, Culpepper and McNabb are grabbed up in
the first dozen picks or so, it will match the total of black QBs
taken in the first round in the entire history of the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being black doesn't matter,'' Culpepper said at the NFL
scouting combine of joining an elite group that includes Doug
Williams (1978), Andre Ware (1990) and Steve McNair (1995).
``People know you can play.''
</P>
<P>
   Being good, and having the potential to be even better, does
matter.
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: Free agent WR Sean Dawkins is scheduled to fly to
Seattle Tuesday night and meet with coach Mike Holmgren Wednesday,
which is believed to be the final step in Dawkins signing with the
Seahawks. ... FB Reggie Brown, a restricted free agents who was a
third-round draft choice in 1996, has agreed to a two-year
contract.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
