<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SHIPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: SAVING NEW YORK'S SHIPPING 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Tuesday, April 13:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman of New Jersey and Gov. George Pataki of
New York have long had profound differences over how to run the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey. At the moment, they have
an obligation to put those differences aside and conduct themselves
like allies for the sake of the regional economy.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the need to hang onto the lucrative business
generated by two major ocean cargo carriers, Sea-Land Service and
Maersk, which Maryland and Baltimore are wooing.The two companies
have set today as the deadline for receiving the authority's new
lease arrangements. The carriers have asked for a refurbished
terminal in New Jersey offering better berths, cranes to service
huge cargo carriers, and deeper channels. While the governors have
been bickering, Maryland sweetened its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Unless New York and New Jersey devise a creative
counterproposal, the region could lose two anchors of its maritime
economy that provide more than 80,000 jobs in cargo, freight
handling, rail and other businesses in New Jersey and about the
same number of east-of-Hudson jobs in freight forwarding,
warehousing, trucking, banking and insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki has some legitimate gripes. The authority spends at least
$200 million from profitable operations like Newark, Kennedy and La
Guardia airports on subsidizing deficit operations like the PATH
trains and the Port Authority bus terminal, which mainly serves New
Jersey. Cross-subsidies are crucial to financing transit in both
states. But those for PATH and the terminal are too high.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki wants a pool of investment dollars for New York
comparable to the value of the Sea-Land/Maersk improvements in New
Jersey. He would also restructure the authority itself so that
revenue and income from facilities in each state would be invested
in that state. But talks on such issues should not disrupt the
urgent business _ the possible loss of major shipping contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
