<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUFFER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTERS? NOT AT AUGUSTA'S MEDIA DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM MOORE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ Monday, I forgot my worries and the rainy weather
back home. I stopped and smelled the azaleas. I lived every
golfer's dream. I played Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   In a random draw of media members, 40 of us got an opportunity
to tee it up and hack it up. Masters, we were not.
</P>
<P>
   This was quite the round of golf. A sunny day, temperatures in
the high 70s, scores in the low 100s for many.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta was a bear, but not as grisly as I expected. The
fairways were generous, the rough manageable. The sand was like
fluffy snow. The fairways were mowed so closely that it was hard to
grab any blades to throw in the air to gauge the wind. The greens
were extremely difficult, but putts tracked to the hole if you
started them on line.
</P>
<P>
   I arrived around 7:30 a.m. for my 8:15 tee time, already knowing
the driving range and practice area were off-limits to us
non-member, non-green-jacket-wearin' media types.
</P>
<P>
   We were required to have caddies. When I checked in with the
caddie master, I asked him if I could have a funny caddie, a guy
with a sense of humor who could ease my apprehension on these
hallowed grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moses!' he barked, and Moses appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Moses was a 49-year-old from Nigeria who has been in Augusta
since 1978. He once caddied for two-time U.S. Open champion Andy
North. Today, he would caddy for a 12-handicapper with a reverse
pivot problem and a horrendous short game.
</P>
<P>
   When it was my turn to step up to the tee, I wondered if anyone
had ever used an X-out Ultra at Augusta. Today, somebody would. And
I still had that ball when I walked off the course.
</P>
<P>
   The best part of the round was getting a feel for what the
professionals faced during the final round. The wind was blowing
and swirling. The pins were in the same difficult Sunday positions.
</P>
<P>
   I am sorry to report that I did not bring Augusta to its knees
or even its calves. I did not have a single birdie. But I did not
have a triple bogey either. The highest score on my card was a 6,
and Tiger Woods and David Duval could not say as much after their
battles here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are the best player in this group,'' Moses told me, which
frankly was like telling Cheez Whiz it's slightly better than
Velveeta.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight: a par from the back tees at the 455-yard 11th
hole after my 3-iron approach hit a cart to the right of the green
and scattered its occupants. I decided to use a putter from 150
feet on my next shot and knocked it within 10 feet. I sank that
putt for par and hugged Moses.
</P>
<P>
   The lowlight: A double bogey coming in at 17 when I started
thinking about a par-par finish to break 85, causing the inevitable
choke, resulting in a chunked 5-iron and sand wedge that airmailed
the green and nearly came to rest on the 18th tee.
</P>
<P>
   The best hole for everyone was the 155-yard 12th, the par-3 with
the postage-stamp green in a picturesque setting. Groups backed up
there, everyone stopping to snap photos when they weren't dumping
balls into Rae's Creek.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, I totaled it up: 87 strokes, 44 on the front, 43 on
the back, 30 putts, seven pars and one memorable experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
