<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-INTERNET-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY INTERNET SPINOFF RUMORED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Rumors emerged Monday that The Walt Disney Co.
will take advantage of Internet mania and convert its Web holdings
into a separate publicly traded company.
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Infoseek, the entertainment giant's Web partner, had
no comment on a Wall Street Journal report that the companies are
exploring the spinoff of an Internet company. But Wall Street
reacted enthusiastically, pushing Disney shares up 93.75 cents to
$35.4375 -- its highest close in nearly a month -- while Infoseek
soared $9.75, or 12 percent, to $87.125.
</P>
<P>
   Disney and Sunnyvale-based Infoseek launched the Go Network
portal site in January as a way of luring customers and advertisers
through an easy-to-find ``hub'' for entering the Internet. Disney
bought 43 percent of Infoseek in June for $70 million and $165
million in promotional support when the stock was trading in the
$30 range, but it cannot expand the stake until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors may reflect investor impatience with Disney's stock,
which is 14 percent below May's all-time high. Disney stock rose
slightly after launching Go.com, but Web operations of
conglomerates have generally received lower valuations than
stand-alone Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Anya Sacharow, an analyst with Jupiter Communications, said an
Internet spinoff by Disney would not be a surprise in light of
similar moves planned by Time Warner Inc., CBS Corp. and Barnes &AMP;
Noble. ``I would view it as an aggressive way to consolidate and
grow the business,'' she said. ``With Disney's incredible marketing
power, Go will definitely continue to be one of the major sites.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Butt Jr., a Forrester Corp. analyst, said he was somewhat
skeptical about the report, despite the attraction of soaring
prices on Wall Street for Web properties. He cited Disney's and
Chairman Michael Eisner's reputations for keeping tight control
over assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Splitting it off seems to go against the Disney grain, so
doing it would mean the potential valuation would have to far
outweigh everything else,'' he said. ``If we were talking about
Rupert Murdoch, it would happen in a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
