<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
CELTICS BEAT CAVALIERS 
</HEADLINE>
 BKN-CELTICS-CAVALIERS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Their injured list is growing by the day, as their season is
winding down. Undermanned and with payback as the only incentive,
the Celtics Monday night delivered an offensive treat to a crowd
featuring Red Auerbach, Paul Gaston, and a lot of people who looked
like yellow seats.
</P>
<P>
   The result was a 103-89 snuffing of the Cleveland Cavaliers, a
team that had a lot more on the line but played like Vancouver
East. The Celtics shot 52 percent (their second straight game over
50), got a magnificent effort from Dana Barros (23 points, 13
assists, 4 steals, 48 minutes), and never trailed in exacting
revenge for one of their more dreadful thumpings of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Pitino basically went with seven players, as Kenny Anderson
(hamstring) and Walter McCarty (groin) were hors de combat. The
only non-center who saw any time off the bench was Greg Minor.
Antoine Walker played 47 minutes and Ron Mercer went 46 _ and this
was a day after they played the Bulls. The Cavaliers didn't play
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   No one, least of all the players, seemed to mind. The Celtics
led by at least 16 in every quarter in registering their second
wire-to-wire win of the season before 15,622, the smallest crowd
since Pitino came to town. The other wire-to-wire victory was
against Orlando Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in a while that we've gotten off to a
big lead and kept it,'' said Walker, who had 21 points, 8 rebounds,
and 6 assists. ``We played very unselfish basketball. We got a good
contribution from everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   This one was almost like a relay. The Celtics turned to ex-Cav
Vitaly Potapenko to get them out of the blocks _ and did he ever.
He was a steamroller in the first six-plus minutes, scoring 13
points and snaring five rebounds as Boston built a 15-point lead.
Pitino then took him out for a rest and Cleveland got back into the
game. The coach said later he thought Potapenko looked tired and
that he likes taking players out when they are ``on a high.'' You
figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing for us was the way we lost that game in
Cleveland,'' said Potapenko, referring to the 113-86 atrocity on
March 23 during the team's crisis du coeur. ``We played horrible.
It was ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics led by 9 after one and by 8 at the half. Then, it
was Mercer's turn. He had gotten off to a slow start _ 0 for 4 and
2 for 10 _ before catching fire in the second half (8 of 11). He
had 14 in the third quarter as the Celtics, as was the case in the
first two periods, blew the lead out and then let the Cavs get a
sniff. Your mother would have called it teasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played really hard,'' said ex-Celt Andrew DeClercq. ``We
didn't even show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Shawn Kemp, who led Cleveland with 23, all in the first
three quarters, ``The game had a lot of meaning, but we didn't play
like there was.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for Cleveland this was the proverbial 4-pointer, as they
like to say in Saskatoon, Yellowknife, and Medicine Hat. The Cavs
are in the thick of the playoff fight in the East and need every
win. In addition, they own Boston's first-round pick, so every
Celtic loss gets them closer to Wally Szczerbiak or whomever they
have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   They needed more than Wally World Monday night. The Celtics led
by 13 after three, but everyone expected a final damn-the-torpedoes
assault from Cleveland. It came, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs got within 87-79 with 6:50 to play. Mercer then popped
out, took a Barros pass, and drained a 20-footer. The Cavs couldn't
hit the rim in the following 24 seconds and that led to another
Mercer hoop. Then Barros picked Mitchell Butler's pocket and went
in for the layup. Cleveland called time, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was back to 14 and Cleveland was finished.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavs are in a three-in-three stretch for the second week in
a row, so that may have led to their early surrender. But that
doesn't account for their game-long indifference to competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a game that was very meaningful to us, I didn't see what I
wanted,'' coach Mike Fratello said. ``It wasn't the kind of effort
I was looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly what Pitino has been looking for _ and finally
got.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
