<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIZZA-HEALTH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIES SAY BEER, PIZZA MAY SLICE HEALTH RISK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY PETER HARTLAUB  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ There's good news for the scores of Americans who
love beer, pizza and pasta drenched in tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Now some doctors say such foods are not only good _ they're good
for you.
</P>
<P>
   Two separate medical stories released Monday found that beer and
wine can ward off ulcers, and that cooked tomatoes can fight
prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   For 60-year-old Richard Von Zup, the studies made lunch Monday
all that much more enjoyable, as he dug into a plate of fettucine
with mushroom and tomato sauce at a Los Angeles restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a regular tomato eater,'' said Von Zup, who owns a vitamin
manufacturing company. ``I'll eat a few more now knowing that it
will do me some good.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he also will feel better about popping open a beer for a
baseball game or sipping a good claret at dinner.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting of the American Association for Cancer Research in
Philadelphia, researchers announced they have found direct evidence
that a nutrient in tomatoes, called lycopene, can cause prostate
cancer tumors to become ``less aggressive'' and even shrink.
</P>
<P>
   In another study released Monday and published in the journal
Epidemiology, German doctors say new evidence suggests that
drinking a glass or two of beer or wine per day staves off an
ulcer-causing bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   But before college fraternity and city league softball team
members rejoice at the local pizza parlor, they should take heed:
Even the doctors who researched the studies are skeptical that
stuffing your face with tomato products and washing it down with
alcohol is the path to better health.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not be that easy,'' said Dr. Omer Kucuk, a researcher
on the tomato study at the Karmanos Cancer Institute in Detroit who
observed the effects of lycopene among 33 prostate cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   Kucuk and his colleagues administered two 15-milligram capsules
of lycopene extract per day _ which is equal to between two and six
pounds of the fruit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what that would equate to in terms of tomato
sauce or spaghetti or pizza,'' Kucuk said. ``It may not be feasible
in real life.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the research indicates that eating pizza sauce or other
cooked tomato foods, he said, might be even better than taking
tomatoes off the vine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lycopene is better absorbed in the gut if it's in cooked
or processed tomatoes, compared to, say, eating fresh tomatoes,''
Kucuk said.
</P>
<P>
   Lycopene has been a popular nutritional supplement for years and
is sold in capsule form without a prescription.
</P>
<P>
   Kucuk said while his study is the first to offer direct evidence
of the benefits of tomatoes in fighting prostate cancer,
population-based data from the 1990s already had pointed to the
phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   About 200,000 Americans contract prostate cancer every year.
Kucuk said there is about a 75 percent survival rate.
</P>
<P>
   For the beer and wine study, German doctors led by Hermann
Brenner from the University of Ulm observed 1,785 men and women 18
to 88, using a breath test to find smaller amounts of (ITAL)
Helicobacter pylori(END ITAL) in the stomachs of beer drinkers,
with even better results for those who indulge in wine.
</P>
<P>
   The results suggest that alcohol consumption ``may reduce the
odds'' of (ITAL) H. pylori (END ITAL) infection, Brenner said in
the study.
</P>
<P>
   But Dr. Bennett Roth, a digestive disease specialist with the
University of California, Los Angeles Medical Center, said it would
be wrong to suggest that people combat gastrointestinal diseases by
drinking liquor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the literature has suggested that large amounts of
beer and wine can damage the stomach lining,'' Roth said. ``There's
no scientific literature that I'm aware of that shows it to be
beneficial.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not the Germans are right, the positive health
effects derived from beer and wine have extended beyond the
stomach. Research has indicated that moderate alcohol consumption
can prevent heart disease and some forms of cancer.
</P>
<P>
   No need to convince Hollywood resident Kimberly Kyle, enjoying a
pasta lunch in Woodland Hills. ``I don't believe beer and wine in
moderation is bad. That convinced me.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
