<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 01:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5818 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLA     04-13 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS ARE KNOCKED OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A week after the Arizona Diamondbacks were ruffled by
Chan Ho Park throwing a pitch behind Matt Williams, they
retaliated.
</P>
<P>
   However, not how one might think the Diamondbacks would do it.
Instead, they did it old-school style. They did it by knocking the
ball out of the park.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Lee's grand slam was the highlight of a five-run third
inning as the Diamondbacks took out an opening-series-sweep worth
of frustrations on the Dodgers with a 12-6 win in their home opener
Monday night at Bank One Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Lee added a sacrifice fly and tied a club record with a fifth
RBI in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't just Park who had a miserable time of it. The
Dodgers bullpen was peppered for seven runs in three innings,
hurting itself with five bases on balls.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers cut Arizona's 5-0 lead to 5-4 on back-to-back RBI
singles by pinch-hitter Jose Vizcaino and Eric Young in the sixth,
but Onan Masaoka and Mel Rojas faltered in keeping the Diamondbacks
at bay.
</P>
<P>
   The first nine pitches Masaoka threw were balls. Masaoka, who
hadn't yielded a hit in his first two appearances, allowed one hit
in two-thirds of an inning. But his three walks were disastrous.
They led to an RBI single by pinch-hitter Bernard Gilkey and Lee's
sacrifice fly to right as Arizona went ahead 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   Rojas was able to bail Masaoka out in the sixth but got into his
own jam in the seventh. Again, it began with a walk to leadoff man
Steve Finley. Four batters later, Damian Miller's bases-loaded
single scored two and Jay Bell capped another five-run inning with
a long three-run homer to left as Arizona went ahead 12-4.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's homer was the culmination of a pitcher in classic free
fall for four batters. It began with Park walking his counterpart,
pitcher Andy Benes, to lead off the inning. Tony Womack singled and
Bell walked to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Park seemingly was ready to take control of the situation when
he got ahead of Lee 1-2, but Arizona's second-year first baseman
lined the next pitch, a hanging curve, over the right-field fence
for a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks increased their lead to 5-0 later in the inning
when Tony Batista stole home on the back end of a double steal,
though he could have crawled in from third. Dodgers catcher Todd
Hundley, who's yet to throw out a would-be basestealer this season,
tried to nail Luis Gonzalez at second, but the throw was short and
bounced into the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The five-run inning was payback for last Tuesday at Dodger
Stadium. Williams homered off Park early in the game, and after a
long foul ball, Park threw the next pitch behind Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Park said it was unintentional, but Williams and the
Diamondbacks believe it was done with intent. Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson rebuffs that notion.
</P>
<P>
   With the emotion and thought of retaliation eased for the moment
with Lee's grand slam, the Dodgers tried to cut into the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a thought: You know the Dodgers have a chance to score
when they don't have anybody on second or third base. Entering the
game, the Dodgers were 10 for 57 with runners in scoring position,
and they did little to improve that showing.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to advance Hundley after his leadoff double in the
second, Eric Karros continued with that thinking in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Raul Mondesi led off with his seventh walk of the season (he
didn't reach that mark until May 15 last year) and after Hundley
lined out, Karros smashed a 1-0 Benes pitch deep over the
left-center field wall for a two-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   Karros' second homer of the season pulled the Dodgers within
5-2. Karros also moved past Bill Russell and into fourth on the
Dodgers' all-time RBI list with 628.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers returned to their ways the next inning. Park led
off with a single and moved to second on a wild pitch. Young
walked, but Devon White, Gary Sheffield and Mondesi each failed in
their attempt to score the runner.
</P>
</TEXT>
