<HEADER>
A5819 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHMIDT-AZR &LR;      04-13 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHMIDT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANCER SURVIVOR'S GRADUATION WALK EXPECTED TO WIN OK; PALS
REJOICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LORI BAKER AND JENNIFER BARRETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ ``Schmidt walks.''
</P>
<P>
   The handwritten slogan that catapulted Mountain Ridge High
School senior Cameron Schmidt to national celebrity may become a
reality.
</P>
<P>
   As Schmidt was en route to a ``Today'' show taping in New York
on Monday afternoon, Deer Valley Unified School District officials
said that the board is expected to vote tonight to allow the
teenage cancer survivor to walk with his class at commencement May
20.
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Gerald Cuendet said board members, who were in
San Francisco attending a national conference over the weekend,
individually told him that they would make an exception to district
policy to let Schmidt participate in graduation, even though he's
three credits short of the 22-credit requirement.
</P>
<P>
   District policy says students must earn the credits required for
graduation to participate in the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Board members Susan Burke and Richard Eng said previously that
they support letting Schmidt walk because of his circumstances.
Board members Ted Carpenter, Joan Bennett and David Cantelme could
not be reached for comment Monday. It will only take three votes to
allow the exception.
</P>
<P>
   Cuendet said the board will vote on Schmidt's petition at a
meeting at 7 tonight ( april 13 ) rather than April 27, as
previously announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so proud of my son,'' Sandi Schmidt said after a Deer
Valley official called to tell her the board plans to let the teen
walk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He first fought for the hardest thing, his life. Now, his
fight to walk with his class will hopefully help other students in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Today'' show researcher Michele Leone also said she was
notified Monday by district spokeswoman Kim Sharp about the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt is scheduled to appear on ``Today'' at 8:15 this
morning. He appeared Monday on ``Inside Edition, '' ``Good Morning
America'' and `` Extra'', and many radio stations have called him
for interviews. A majority of the more than 300 readers who
telephoned or sent e-mail to ``The Arizona Republic''supported
Schmidt, though a small number of readers said the school district
should stick to its rules.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt was surprised by the attention his request received.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' he said before boarding a plane with his
father and a friend, Melissa Robbins, to New York City for the TV
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Robbins, one of the leaders of the student protest, said she was
shocked by the response to Schmidt's fight.
</P>
<P>
   He deserves to walk with his classmates because ``he's the most
courageous person I know,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt, 18, who managed to keep a ``B'' average at the north
Glendale school, despite having a bone marrow transplant,
chemotherapy and radiation treatments, has promised to finish the
three credits in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, his father, Bill, pleaded with Deer Valley
governing board members on his son's behalf. But it wasn't until
Friday, when other teenagers joined the fight, that Schmidt's
plight captured national attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schmidt walks'' was the rallying cry of about 800 Mountain
Ridge students who marched down 67th Avenue to show their support.
It was inscribed on T-shirts being worn by many students and
scrawled on car windows. It was circulated on fliers, in letters
and in e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Many classmates also vowed to boycott commencement. A local
radio station offered to host a graduation ceremony at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got ridiculous, it really did, but it's for a good cause,''
said senior Christopher Cheniae, 17. ``He's a measly three credits
short, and he's fought so hard. He deserves to walk.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday morning, students arriving at Mountain Ridge were
greeted by police cruisers. Glendale police spokesman Matt Brown
said the department sent 10 cars, each manned with two officers, to
patrol the campus after hearing there might be a repeat of Friday's
protest. The officers stayed for less than 30 minutes because only
about 10 youngsters showed up and the scene was peaceful.
</P>
<P>
   Sean and Tim Meredith, both Mountain Ridge juniors, were among
10 students picketing Monday across from the school, at 22800 N.
67th Ave. Holding ``Schmidt walks'' and ``Honk for Schmidt'' signs,
they vowed to be there every day until the board let Schmidt walk.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Sean Furlong, a friend of Schmidt's since junior high
school, was so certain his friend would not be allowed to walk with
the Class of 1999 that he called his relatives in New York and told
them to stay home. If Schmidt couldn't walk, neither would he.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he was ready to call back with some good news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ecstatic,'' Furlong said. ``I'm glad that I can be there
with him and share an important part of his life with him. That's
awesome they finally realized not letting him walk was a
mistake.'' &QL; 
Lori Baker can be reached at (602) 444-7120 or at
lori.baker(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
