<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5827 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      04-13 0657
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRADUATING MAGNA CUM HEALTHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ All of the many people who've rallied around cancer
survivor Cameron Schmidt _ his family, his friends, his classmates,
thousands of strangers _ are wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They were outraged that Schmidt wasn't yet being allowed to walk
across the stage during graduation ceremonies at Mountain Ridge
High School in Glendale.
</P>
<P>
   They were incensed that a young man who fought through
chemotherapy and radiation, and still managed to wind up only three
credits short of a diploma, isn't permitted to celebrate with his
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   They were infuriated with the bureaucrats of the Deer Valley
Unified School District who won't allow Cameron to participate in
commencement, particularly since he's not asking for a diploma,
just the chance to walk across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   They jammed meetings and staged demonstrations and filled
district phone lines and spewed from talk radio like a spigot
turned up fully to furious.
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers joined in. And radio commentators. And television
stations. They were wrong, too.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one way to describe a brave, determined 18-year-old
who's being discriminated against by idiot pencil-pushers:
</P>
<P>
   Lucky.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one word to characterize the parents of a young man
who beat back death only to be knocked down again by two-bit
despots:
</P>
<P>
   Blessed.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one adjective to use for the family, friends and
caring strangers who've watched as a kid who once suffered cancer
is forced to suffer fools:
</P>
<P>
   Fortunate. &QL; 
BEST DAYS OF HIS LIFE &QL; 
These recent days filled with controversy, with uproar, with anger
bordering on frenzy, are the best days of Cameron Schmidt's life.
</P>
<P>
   I know this from experience.
</P>
<P>
   In 1987, I became acquainted with a 17-year-old high school
student named Jon Fladhammer. He was funny. He was smart. He had
dreams of becoming an actor or a lawyer or a politician.
</P>
<P>
   He also had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   When I met him, he had only a few months to live and he knew it.
He'd already lost a leg to the disease. He never lost his sense of
humor.
</P>
<P>
   He never made it to graduation. He never got to appear on NBC's
``Today Show,'' as Schmidt is scheduled to do this morning.
</P>
<P>
   He never got to experience the beautiful, unrestrained luxury of
worrying about something as petty as a commencement ceremony. And
neither did his family.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, I've met too many others living the same
horror. &QL; 
``THINK OF OTHERS' LOSSES''
</P>
<P>
   In this state, and every state, are families who'll look with
envy at the graduation problems facing Cameron Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the mothers and fathers whose children didn't win their
battles with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the parents of kids from Gilbert, Glendale, Scottsdale
and Mesa who lost sons and daughters Cameron's age to automobile
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   Or of the friends and family of the two Apollo High School
students, also Schmidt's age, shot to death while walking to a
pizza party.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the Schmidts themselves, less than a year ago worrying
if Cameron would live or die.
</P>
<P>
   Now here he is, on TV, looking young and strong the way a kid
his age is supposed to look.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the knuckleheads at the school district have decided
to let Schmidt take part in commencement ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   It's the right thing to do, and it'll make all the people who
raised hell in support of young Cameron feel good about themselves,
as they should.
</P>
<P>
   But as victories go, it's way down on the list.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, it doesn't matter at all if Cameron Schmidt walks
across a stage during graduation.
</P>
<P>
   The important thing, the glorious thing, the thing worth
celebrating and the only thing that really matters is that, like
other normal HEALTHY kids his age, he walks. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini(at)pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
