<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUSKEY TOUCHES OFF MARINER POWER DISPAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Butch Huskey couldn't identify the music that's
sometimes played when he walks to the plate at the Kingdome. When
told recently it was the University of Washington fight song _
Huskey ... Huskies, get it? _ the Mariners' new left fielder broke
into a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guess they want people to like me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey had no help from the public-address system Monday night.
The song wasn't played, so he had to win over 24,650 fans himself.
</P>
<P>
   He did it with a run-scoring double and a two-run home run,
powering the M's to a 6-3 win over the Athletics. The Mariners got
their other runs on homers by their revamped double-play
combination: second baseman David Bell connected in the fifth and
shortstop Domingo Cedeno had a two-run shot in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Huskey's was the most impressive. As a New York Met, he had a
knack for prodigious drives. Monday night's blast was his first
Mariner home run, and it sailed 419 feet, deep into the bleachers
in left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know you've hit a ball good when you don't feel the ball
coming off the bat,'' he said. ``I didn't feel it, I just heard it.
I knew I hit it hard.''
</P>
<P>
   The homer broke a 2-all tie, and was followed two batters later
by Cedeno's blast, just his 13th in more than 1,100 career at-bats.
That was the last of a series of unusual plays in the sixth,
including a stolen base by Edgar Martinez and a pickoff throw to
nobody by Oakland's Jimmy Haynes. The pitcher didn't realize his
first baseman was playing off the bag, and Dan Wilson took two
bases.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps the most unexpected sight was Huskey corralling a
pop foul by Tony Phillips in the third. Huskey, a former Oklahoma
linebacker recruit listed at 6-foot-3, 244 pounds, sprinted across
the turf for the catch.
</P>
<P>
   To anyone who saw Huskey far behind the pack in spring running
drills, it was an eye-catching feat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a distance runner, but I can cover some ground in the
outfield,'' Huskey said. ``To be a good outfielder, you have to get
a good jump and you have to be able to run 50-60 feet in either
direction. I'm not going to run to the other foul pole to catch a
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   In 15 at-bats, Huskey has seven hits. A career .211 hitter in
April, he's enjoying the controlled atmosphere of the Kingdome _
it's preferable, Huskey said, to ``freezing my tail off in
40-degree weather'' in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Mariner newcomers had a hand in the win. Rookie
right-hander Freddy Garcia improved to 2-0 with another strong
outing, working 62/3 innings and allowing three runs.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Jose Mesa earned his second save in what was easily his
best outing this year. Mesa, who allowed four runs in one inning on
Saturday, had worked earlier in the day on making his motion more
fluid. His body had been going forward while his arm was going
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he gets it right, it looks so easy,'' Williams said.
``You wonder how he can throw so hard with such an easy delivery.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa threw in the mid-90s, but his best pitch was a 78-mph
curveball that froze Jason McDonald for the second out of the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had that curve for a long time, but they took it away from
me in Cleveland,'' Mesa said. ``They wanted me to throw just the
fastball and slider. But now that I'm a little older, I can throw
it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
