r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MADALYN-OHAIR14-COX     04-13 1474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADALYN-OHAIR14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In jail, two pieces of O'Hair puzzle
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin and Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ On March 24, when Texas investigators knocked on
the door of seven-time felon Gary P. Karr, they already suspected
him as an accessory in the 1995 disappearance of atheist Madalyn
O'Hair and her family.
</P>
<P>
   Karr, it appears, didn't disappoint them.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators had no warrants, yet an FBI agent later testified
that Karr invited them into his apartment in Novi, Mich., sat
voluntarily for 13 hours and admitted to concealing bodies, hiding
victims' property, acquiring vehicles and playing a key role in
transferring $600,000 to a San Antonio gold coin dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Karr stopped short of confessing to the killings of O'Hair, her
son, John Garth Murray, and the granddaughter she adopted as her
own daughter, Robin Murray- O'Hair.
</P>
<P>
   Even as investigators listened to Karr, their counterparts in
Austin questioned David Roland Waters, a former O'Hair employee
convicted of stealing $54,000 from American Atheists.
</P>
<P>
   Both men, who shared a cell in an Illinois prison in the
mid-1980s, were arrested on weapons charges after federal agents
found pistols in Karr's residence and ammunition in Waters'. It is
illegal for felons to possess either.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three weeks later, both men remain in cells _ Karr in
Detroit, Waters in Austin. Although many questions remain
unanswered, the two arrests have brought to light a series of
events 3 1/2 years ago that authorities believe offer intriguing
clues about the fate of the missing O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   Waters' Austin attorney, Patrick Ganne, said he believes federal
authorities are playing them against each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect they are waiting for one to break,'' Ganne said
Friday, insisting his client has nothing to tell authorities. ``I
think they thought he'd flip.''
</P>
<P>
   While Waters sat in jail, federal authorities, acting on
information from Karr, dug up portions of a 5,000-acre ranch in a
remote corner of the Hill Country west of San Antonio on Easter
weekend, and refused to say what, if anything, they found. A source
with knowledge of the investigation told the American-Statesman
they were looking for the bodies of the O'Hair family.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1995 disappearance of the O'Hair family, some friends
and authorities have speculated that the aging, ill atheist _ who
once described herself as the most hated woman in America _ sought
refuge overseas. Others, including her estranged son, Bill Murray,
suspected foul play.
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of that growing suspicion are the shared lives of
Waters, Karr and Danny Fry, a friend of Waters whose headless,
handless corpse was found near Dallas just three days after the
O'Hairs disappeared along with $500,000 in gold coins.
</P>
<P>
   Inexplicably, they left behind $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   To San Antonio jeweler Corey Ticknor, an order for $600,000 in
gold coins is unusual but not unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was O'Hair's son, Jon Garth Murray, who called him in
September of 1995 asking how to covert cash into gold coins. It
took two weeks to negotiate a price, work out the logistics and
make the exchange, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unknown to Ticknor, Murray, O'Hair and Murray-O'Hair had left
their Austin home in late August as if in a panic. They left behind
their three dogs, breakfast dishes on the table and O'Hair's
prescription for her diabetes and heart disease. Over the next
month, they stayed in touch with employees at the Austin
headquarters of American Atheists by cell phone.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 29, Murray, who had wired $600,000 to a bank in
northwest San Antonio from a New Jersey bank, met Ticknor in the
bank's conference room. Ticknor had the gold waiting in safety
deposit boxes. Only $500,000 of the coins had arrived, wrapped in
6-inch-by-6-inch-by-4-inch cardboard boxes. The rest was due in
three days.
</P>
<P>
   On a conference room table, Ticknor said he counted out the gold
as an off-duty police officer watched, then loaded it into larger
cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ticknor said Murray, who had come alone to the bank, appeared
calm as he wheeled out the 100 pounds of gold on a dolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officer and I escorted him to the car and put it in the
trunk,'' Ticknor said.
</P>
<P>
   The car, Ticknor said, was a rented Lincoln Towncar, not
Murray's 1988 Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   Murray promised to return for the rest of the gold in three
days.
</P>
<P>
   He never did.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Ticknor nor the American Atheists heard from him again.
</P>
<P>
   As Ticknor puzzled over Murray's abrupt disappearance,
authorities about 270 miles to the north in Dallas were puzzling
over their own mystery. In what appeared to be an unrelated
homicide, a corpse with its head and hands cleanly severed was
found in Dallas County.
</P>
<P>
   For three years, the body was unidentified, and the O'Hair
disappearance remained only a topic for cocktail chatter and
occasional news stories.
</P>
<P>
   When authorities in December 1998 finally identified the body as
Danny Fry, a Florida man and a friend of Waters, it shifted the
spotlight back to Texas, where Fry, Waters and Karr were together
at the time of the O'Hairs' disappearance.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, who at age 18 clubbed to death another teen-ager with
the fat end of a pool cue, found himself in the mid-1980s serving
time for another crime with Karr in Vienna Correctional Center in
Illinois. Karr, 50, who had a history of violent felonies from
armed robbery to kidnapping, was in the middle of a 30-year
sentence for the rape of a judge's 16-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Waters, 52, was released from prison in 1987. In the early
1990s, Waters spent time in Naples, Fla., with Fry, and by 1994,
Waters was in Austin working as general office manager for American
Atheists.
</P>
<P>
   That summer, O'Hair, whose caustic personality often led to
disputes with employees, accused Waters of stealing $54,000 while
she was out of town. According to court records, Waters
impersonated Jon Garth Murray and forged his signature to embezzle
money.
</P>
<P>
   Ganne, who represented Waters, said his client was acting under
orders from the O'Hairs. Ganne said the O'Hairs promised Waters a
$15,000 cut to divert money from the atheist organization to them.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1995, just four months before the O'Hairs disappeared,
Waters pleaded guilty to theft. Ganne said Waters agreed to plead
guilty in exchange for 10 years probation, plus an order to repay
$15,000, rather than risk 25 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   About that same time, Karr was released from an Illinois prison.
Meanwhile, Fry was leaving Florida to join Waters in Austin. Fry's
family has always contended he said little about what he was doing
in Austin except that he expected to make a lot of money.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Ganne acknowledged that his client, Waters, spent
time with Fry and Karr in Texas in 1995, but, he argued, that
doesn't mean Waters killed anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're pointing fingers with empty hands,'' Ganne said of
authorities. So far, authorities have filed no murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   When Karr let authorities into his apartment, they found two
pistols, a crime for a felon. When they executed a search warrant
at Waters' Austin apartment, they found 119 rounds of ammunition,
also a crime for a man on probation.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI also seized a half-finished manuscript on Waters' theory
of the O'Hairs' disappearance. Waters has always contended the
O'Hairs orchestrated their disappearance. Ganne said Waters had
paid a ghost writer $2,500 to help write the manuscript.
</P>
<P>
   Other than weapons violations, Karr is charged with transporting
stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   At Karr's March 26 detention hearing in Detroit, an FBI agent
testified that Karr accompanied one of the O'Hair family members to
a New Jersey bank to wire $600,000 to San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Yet how does a seven-time felon, four months out of prison, find
himself flying to New Jersey with the son of America's most famous
atheist?
</P>
<P>
   And if Karr, under an assumed name, felt it necessary to
accompany Jon Garth Murray to the New Jersey bank, why did a
seemingly unnerved Murray show up alone to pick up the gold?
</P>
<P>
   Who, posing as Murray, sold his Mercedes to an unsuspecting San
Antonio resident for a price below the car's value?
</P>
<P>
   Ganne said authorities can only place Karr or Fry, not his
client Waters, on a plane with Murray or selling the Mercedes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investigators refuse to say what they believe happened.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Bill Murray, O'Hair's estranged son who is a born-again
Christian and evangelist, fears he knows the answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are wherever they are going to be _ whether that's in
heaven or hell,'' he said. ``Praying over them is not going to
change that.''
</P>
<P>
   Laylan Copelin and Cara Tanamachi write for the Austin
American-Statesman, Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
