<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Not lazy, just an aesthetic personality
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ According to my father, I was born lazy and
then had a relapse. I'm beginning to suspect his diagnosis was
right on.
</P>
<P>
   Truth is, my energy seems to wax and wane depending upon the
task at hand. Movement just for the sake of movement not only
leaves me cold but makes me wonder why folks who still have their
wits about them want to abuse themselves so.
</P>
<P>
   In elementary school, a little running around made sense. I had
to hurry out to recess before ``Fat Nancy'' grabbed the best swing
or laid claim to the choicest patch of cinders for a killer game of
hopscotch. Heck, I even had to run all the way home from school
every day so that Arthur Cooper couldn't kiss me.
</P>
<P>
   It made sense to run three blocks to the ice cream store, but a
slow amble was the best I could muster for a trip around the corner
to my piano lesson. Once, when I got a ``U'' in penmanship, it took
all afternoon to drag myself two blocks home from school.
</P>
<P>
   Junior high school was tiring too. Most days I barely had enough
strength to paint my toenails much less memorize 41 prepositions.
Once, Mr. Paige, the mean old civics teacher, yelled at me for
scuffing down the hall. His exact words were: ``Are you too tired
to pick up your lazy feet?''
</P>
<P>
   In the ninth grade, just as I was bordering on complete body
shutdown, a miracle happened. I discovered boys and it didn't take
long for me to figure out that the picks of the litter hung around
school every afternoon for track practice.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, I was the fastest thing on feet, racing through the
neighborhood, jumping hedges and small children, even frightening
family pets, in my quest for speed and a slot on the girls track
team. My efforts paid off _ for a
</P>
<P>
   while anyway. I earned a place on the team and even snared
myself a boyfriend, but when the romance ended along with the track
season, inertia overtook me once again, bringing with it a torpor
my mother considered serious enough to treat with spoonfuls of
brown glop in a bottle.
</P>
<P>
   High school gym class did little to change my languid approach
to exercise. Learning to do a box step to Glenn Miller's
``Moonlight Serenade'' was okay, but when ``dipping'' gave way to
deep-knee bends, my body refused to make the transition. I tried
deck tennis for a week, but lost interest when I broke a
fingernail.
</P>
<P>
   Physical education was not an elective in our school, and any
excuse to escape its rigors, short of a full-body cast, fell on
deaf ears. Smitty, our barrel-shaped gym teacher, ran a tight ship.
Two blasts on her silver whistle
</P>
<P>
   meant one minute left to finish grippering our baggy-bottomed
gymsuits and line up on the practice field ready to sweat to the
beat of her bongo drum.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not sweating, you're not working,'' she'd bellow as
fifty or sixty of us fell into an indifferent, arm-flailing
rendition of a jumping jack. ``Up! Down! Three! Four!'' she'd
holler. My best friend Jeanne and I chanted along with our own
version: ``Up! Down! No more!'' We were determined to find a way
out.
</P>
<P>
   One morning, Jeanne did. She came to school with a miracle in
her pocket _ a note from her family doctor asking that she be
excused from all physical exertion because she was afflicted with
an ``aesthetic personality.'' We thought that sounded totally
glamorous, even though neither of us knew what it meant. I went
home and asked my mother if I could be aesthetic too. She said she
doubted it.
</P>
<P>
   It's been over 40 years now since Jeanne's diagnosis, but I've
never forgotten those magic words _ ``aesthetic personality'' _ and
even though the context is wrong, they do come in handy every year
about this time. I use them to explain why I'm unable to get on
with my spring cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison,
</P>
<P>
   Gibsonburg, Ohio 43431 or email: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
