   These columns for release Wednesday, April 14, 1999 are moving
today to clients of the New York Times News Service.
</P>
<P>
   All columns have moved, in the commentary (k) category. If you
have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the Cox News
Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOS, LAYOUTS and GRAPHICS CoxNet layouts are for sale over
the web, through the New York Times News Service's PageExpress
service, at www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   If a budget line or story is marked with photos or graphics,
those are available from the New York Times News Service at
212-556-4204. Or call CoxNet for more information at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   HOW TO REACH US
</P>
<P>
   Questions should be directed to CoxNet, the Cox News Service, in
Atlanta at 404-526-5456. We are staffed 8 a.m. to 10 p.m.
Monday-Friday, and 1-10 p.m. on weekends and holidays.
</P>
<P>
   The news manager is Paul Foutch, 404-526-5429,
pfoutch(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The day news editor is Tom Oder, 404-526-5887,
toder(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   The night news editor is Todd C. Duncan, 404-582-7282,
tduncan(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Washington Bureau:
</P>
<P>
   News editor Art Dalglish, 202-887-8338, artd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Foreign editor Rick Christie, 202-887-8316, rickd(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Bureau chief Andy Alexander, 202-887-8334, andya(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   GARCIA-COLUMN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ My idea of good time is arguing
with a judge. Please allow me to explain. Bob Perkins, the state
district judge, and I had a friendly disagreement about the
veracity of Lt. Col. Jose(accent) Enrique de la Pen(tilde)a's
account of David Crockett's final hours. De la Pen(tilde)a claimed
to witness the surrender and subsequent execution of the legendary
frontier politician and adventurer. The account is contained in a
journal penned in 1838-39, while de la Pen(tilde)a was imprisoned
on political charges. The Crockett passage is a brief one, but the
one that propelled the book into the spotlight that still follows
the gentleman from Tennessee. What got the judge stirred up was a
passing comment I made one evening about how the journal rang true.
Turns out the judge, another history buff, has studied Crockett and
doesn't believe the Crockett he knows would surrender. (Garcia,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ If the poobahs of the National Rifle Association
are wondering what that odd thing in their laps is, it is their
head. Missouri voters handed it to them last week, in a referendum
that quashed the NRA's attempt to bring them the joys of concealed
weapons. (Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ When last we left Winston Churchill, in the
late spring and early summer of 1940, he had just assumed the role
of Prime Minister of Great Britain, the Germans were racing through
Holland and Belgium, France was being humiliated in the field and
Adolf Hitler's bombers were lambasting England. So, what happened
after that? It has been 11 years since Volume 2 of William
Manchester's exceptional biography of the British wartime leader
was published and those of us anxious to read the continuation are
parched. (Howard Kleinberg is a columnist for Cox News Service.)
MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ROSENFELD-SHORTTAKES _ What to do when someone puts on an
offensive show of so-called art? Easy. Don't censor. Don't go.
Don't look. Let the marketplace speak, not the censors. (Rosenfeld,
Cox News Service) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   SCHUETT-COLUMN _ GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ According to my father, I
was born lazy and then had a relapse. I'm beginning to suspect his
diagnosis was right on. Truth is, my energy seems to wax and wane
depending upon the task at hand. Movement just for the sake of
movement not only leaves me cold but makes me wonder why folks who
still have their wits about them want to abuse themselves so.
(Schuett, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   BORDERS-COLUMN _ NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Tony Bennett left his
heart in San Francisco. I left my luggage in Orlando. And Atlanta.
And points in between. I've been on the road most of the past two
weeks, attending company meetings twice in Florida. Tough duty, I
know. It's hard to come back with a Florida tan and say with a
straight face what a long half-month it's been out of town. But God
is a practical joker, and getting there and back, then there and
back again, was no picnic. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily Sentinel)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
