<HEADER>
A6053 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASHLEY-JUDD14-COX     04-13 0421
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASHLEY-JUDD14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    One week in Peace Corps? Trust me, it's not enough
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ ``The life I might have lived,'' says
the headline in the newest issue of Marie Claire magazine. ``Ashley
Judd joins the Peace Corps.''
</P>
<P>
   For one week.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley Judd, famous actress, jets down to South America and
spends one week in the rain forests of Suriname.
</P>
<P>
   As a former Peace Corps volunteer in Africa, I can say that one
week is hardly enough time to get a decent case of ``the trots''
(read: gastrointestinal troubles). Much less understand what you've
gotten yourself into.
</P>
<P>
   I read on. Turns out Ashley Judd, like many people, once thought
about joining the Peace Corps. She went into acting instead.
</P>
<P>
   But Marie Claire, noted for its stunts (in one story, guest
editor Susan Sarandon was the recipient of a lap dance; in other,
Gwyneth Paltrow spent a few days on a deserted island), decided to
give Judd a tiny glimpse of what she missed.
</P>
<P>
   Here are photos of Judd toting buckets of water, lying artfully
in a hammock, taking a squat in the woods. She describes how she
falls in love with a ``sexy little'' pail in a local marketplace.
The brightly-colored local clothing is ``Lilly Pulitzer
amplified,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   And the villages she breezed through must be, like, poverty
amplified?
</P>
<P>
   At least Marie Claire bent this story in the right direction.
The magazine let Judd write what she saw, and instead of telling us
where we can buy her cute little tank tops it published the Peace
Corps' phone number and web site address.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could have done it when I was 22, joined the Peace Corps and
flourished, but maybe by telling you about my experience I have
done even greater good,'' Judd writes.
</P>
<P>
   She had her heart in the right place. But a week just doesn't
cut it.
</P>
<P>
   I invite Judd to join the Peace Corps for real. Here's a few
things she might see the next time around:
</P>
<P>
   _ A doctor cutting open a woman's circumcision scars _ without
the luxury of anesthesia _ so she can deliver her baby.
</P>
<P>
   _ Disabled men and women crawling through village streets with
flip-flops attached to their knees.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hungry people. Empty-stomach, four-to-a-plate hungry people.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to sound morbid. But sometimes the Peace Corps isn't
pretty _ no matter what you're wearing.
</P>
<P>
   Cara Anna writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
