<HEADER>
A6054 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMOUS-CITIES14-COX     04-13 1537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMOUS-CITIES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A town can stand out by anounting itself the capital of just
about anything
 &HT;    By Jeff Houck
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Paris is the city of lights. New York is
the city that never sleeps. San Francisco is the city by the bay.
Chicago has the Sears Tower, St. Louis has its arch.
</P>
<P>
   But what if you're a sleepy, one-stoplight town that's archless
and far from world-reknown? What if you're ... Okeechobee, Fla.?
</P>
<P>
   Well, you anoint yourself the Speckled Perch Capital of the
World and wear the title with pride. And you have an annual
speckled perch festival that attracts about 12,000 people a year.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't matter that state law says you can only catch, not eat,
the endangered speckled perch from Lake Okeechobee. Doesn't matter
that the main fish served at the speckled perch festival is the
ever-present catfish. What matters is that the speckled perch has
become an integral part of Okeechobee's identity and folks there
have been mighty proud of their title for going on 31 years now,
thank you very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lake itself is very vital to economy of Okeechobee
County,'' said Brenda O'Connor, the Okeechobee Chamber of Commerce
executive director. ``It's the largest festival we have all year
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Claiming to be the world's capital of anything gives a place a
unique claim to fame at a time when towns are becoming homogenized
by chain restaurants and retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart can't put ``Sailfish Capital of the World'' on enough
stationary. West Palm Beach is the center of the orchid universe,
Fort Pierce is ``Sunrise City'' and Boca Raton is ... not the condo
capital. It's the world's winter polo playground. (A city official
jokingly anointed Port St. Lucie ``Lizard Capital of the World''
before they chose to be known officially as ``A city for all
ages.'')
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Palm Beach County carries the banner of Golf
Capital of the World. Lots of places have lots of golf course, but
the county has more courses per capita than any place in the world.
Schwing!
</P>
<P>
   As a pure marketing gimmick, crowning a town with a ``world's
finest'' label works like a charm, says Richard Lilliquist,
executive director of the City-County Communication and Marketing
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Lilliquist's group gives out it's Savvy Competition award each
year to the town that best capitalizes on its resources to draw
visitors. Places like Monterrey, Calif., which doesn't have a
slogan, but which is known worldwide for it's elaborate aquarium.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a growing awareness of the power of brands in our
society and local governments are discovering that, too,''
Lilliquist says.
</P>
<P>
   The titles are adopted locally and usually related to a major
local agricultural staple, manufacturing product or natural
resource. There is no officially sanctioned body that deals out
official Capital of the World status, but some towns and counties
get serious by trademarking their titles to prevent others from
poaching.
</P>
<P>
   Few duplicates exist. No one but Gilroy, Calif., makes the claim
to being Garlic Capital of the World because no one really can;
Gilroy processes 90 percent of the garlic grown in the U.S. But
there are a couple Christmas tree capitals. A few salmon capitals,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the marketing goals, the capital disctinction helps a
town form an identity, Lilliquist said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Joe DiMaggio, as part of contract whenever he made
appearances, insisted on being announced as the world's greatest
living baseball player,'' he said. ``It's a part of the times. It's
important for people to feel important.''
</P>
<P>
   As if `The Sunshine State' wasn't enough
</P>
<P>
   Floridians can stand tall.
</P>
<P>
   Along with being known as the tourism capital of the world and
the lightning capital of the world _ and the bad driving and auto
theft capital of America _ towns and cities throughout the state
make their own quirky claims.
</P>
<P>
   Plant City proudly bears the moniker of the world's strawberry
capital. Lake Placid, 30 miles northwest of Lake Okeechobee, is
known for it's broad-leafed, green and pink caladium plants.
</P>
<P>
   Islamorada calls itself the Sportsfishing Capital of the World.
Fort Lauderdale, with it's Intracoastal Waterway nooks and
crannies, is ``the Venice of America.'' The Manatee Capital of the
World can be found amid the clear, warm winter waters of Crystal
River.
</P>
<P>
   Ybor City, east of Tampa, was the Cigar Capital of the World at
the beginning of the century and still brags about it's legacy even
though most of the world's premier cigars are produced in the
Caribbean nations.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Dania, near Fort Lauderdale, which backs up its
claim of the Antique Capital of the World by having more than 100
antiques dealers within one square mile selling everything from
small collectibles to the finest antiques. Other cities, like West
Palm Beach, may have their endless rows of antique stores but Dania
wins by saturation.
</P>
<P>
   I scream, you scream, we all scream for Le Mars, Iowa
</P>
<P>
   You'd think a place with sweltering heat and a seaside boardwalk
would pounce on the chance to be ``Ice Cream Capital of the
World.'' But landlocked Le Mars, Iowa, a few miles south of Sioux
City, nabbed the title for itself.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. The home of Wells' Dairy Inc., the largest
family-owned dairy in the U.S., almost a third of the town's 9,000
residents are employed making Blue Bunny ice cream, cottage cheese
and other dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   Along with building a new $3.5 million visitor's center
dedicated to, of course, ice cream, the town hosts the Ice Cream
Days festival each Fourth of July weekend, during which everyone
wears an upside-down ice cream cone hat. ``The same people who make
those cheese heads for the Green Bay Packers make our ice cream
hats,'' said Angie Watson, the visitor's center manager.
</P>
<P>
   A funny story: The town got its name when railroad baron John
Blair asked the _ count 'em _ six women he was traveling with to
name the place where the rail depot stood. Lucille, Elizabeth,
Mary, Blair's wife Anne, Rebecca and Sara got creative and used the
first letter of all their first names to spell out Le Mars.
</P>
<P>
   Deep in the heart of artichoke country
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes all it takes is a big crop or an abundant natural
resource to turn your town into something like the Artichoke
Capital of the World (that would be Castroville, Calif., by the
way.) Here are some others:
</P>
<P>
   Hibiscus _ Park Ridge, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Pickle _ Atkins, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Crystals _ Mount Ida, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Catfish _ Wisner, La.
</P>
<P>
   Zinfindel _ Lodi, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Lily _ Neepawa, Manitoba
</P>
<P>
   Furniture _ High Point, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Frog _ Rayne, La.
</P>
<P>
   Rice and duck _ Stuttgart, Ark. (Yes, both. They grow a lot of
rice and a raise a lot of ducks there.)
</P>
<P>
   Garlic capital? you can have it!
</P>
<P>
   How do you find Gilroy, Calif.? Head west until you smell it.
</P>
<P>
   We don't want to say it's a stinky place to live, but it is the
Garlic Capital of the World.
</P>
<P>
   Just 80 miles south of San Francisco, Gilroy processes 90
percent of the garlic grown in the U.S., well over 100 million
tons. It gets granulated, dehydrated into powder, crushed into a
paste or chalk, pickled and made into toothpaste and deodorant.
(Okay, we made up those last two.) And with a garlic processing
plant in town, the aroma is ever-present.
</P>
<P>
   Each July at the town's Garlic Festival, a bevy of garlic
delights awaits. There is no corresponding Breath Mint Festival,
but two years ago, organizers held a ``kiss off,'' where several
people ate a lunch laced with atomic portions of garlic. Then each
used a separate brand of breath freshener. A volunteer kissed each
participant to judge who had the nicest breath and the winning
freshener was named the festival's official breath mint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never met anyone who left town because of the aroma, but
about two years ago, someone wrote to say they were thinking about
moving to Gilroy, but they didn't like the smell of garlic,'' said
festival manager Chris Filice. ``We told them that we were sorry,
but that garlic is the livelihood around here and we weren't likely
to get the processing plant to move for them.''
</P>
<P>
   You say salmon, i say salmon
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone plays nice. Both Ashe County, N.C. and Lunenburg
County, Nova Scotia, claim to be the Christmas Tree Capital of the
World. And when it comes to salmon, Campbell River, British
Columbia, goes gill-to-gill with Ketchikan, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   We called to try and settle the dispute. Campbell River has
claimed it's title since 1982 because of it's enormous salmon fleet
and processing industry. Ketchikan hosts the annual King Salmon
Derby where fish weighing over 100 pounds have been caught.
</P>
<P>
   So we asked them to work it out. It got ugly quick.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't know anything. They're Canadian,'' said Shauna Lee,
Ketchikan's derby organizer.
</P>
<P>
   A Campbell River official who asked to remain anonymous became
snooty when told of Ketchikan's good-natured ribbing. ``For a place
that sponsors a sportsfishing tournament, that's so unsporting.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Houck writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
