<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elmore Leonard breaks pattern with `Get Shorty' sequel
 &HT;    By Jay Milner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elmore Leonard doesn't ordinarily write sequels to his best
selling novels. I can't think of a single one over the years I have
been an ardent fan of the man I hear is called ``Dutch'' by his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   But Leonard's ``Get Shorty'' was such an extraordinary hit, as a
book but especially as a movie starring John Travolta, that he
broke a pattern and came up with a sequel to ``Get Shorty'' called
``Be Cool'' (Delacorte Press, $24.95)
</P>
<P>
   In this one Leonard picks up ``Get Shorty'' hero, Chili Palmer
(aka Travolta), shortly after his second movie ``Get Lost'' has
bombed. ``Get Lost'' was the sequel to Chili's hit, ``Get Leo.''
But in Hollywood you're only as big as your latest movie, so Chili
is in danger of crashing as a Hollywood big shot producer.
Naturally, Chili doesn't give up easily. He plans to make a big
comeback with a new film about a pop singer. He is writing the
script by following the life and career of Linda Moon, a singer
with dreams of rising above her current gig as one of the group,
Chicks International, who do covers of Spice Girls songs.
</P>
<P>
   As he does time and again, year after year, Leonard moves his
story along as much with dialogue as with narrative. And his
dialogue is famously real and invigorating for the reader. There's
even more dialogue than usual in this Leonard story, and some may
feel it is too much of a good thing, but it certainly does move the
story along at a rapid clip and keep the reader (kept me, anyhow)
turning pages through the night.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't my favorite Elmore Leonard book, but it's not my
least favorite either. I'd put it somewhere in the middle probably,
which means it's more fun to read than most pop fiction.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Chili must deal with Russian mafia hit men as
well as the usual Hollywood hustlers. But he keeps on keeping on in
the entertaining Chili Palmer manner pulling together his new movie
by following Linda Moon around and doing what needs to be done to
save her life and keep her leading him toward a new movie that will
fuel his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Chili also must deal with the devious and often dangerous
presence of Linda's manager, a former pimp named Raji.
</P>
<P>
   What can I say about an Elmore Leonard novel at this point that
I haven't said, or read, before?
</P>
<P>
   If you are a Leonard fan, you'll enjoy this one. As I implied,
it might not be your favorite Leonard book, but it won't offend
you. And the movie might be better than the book, if Travolta
agrees to play Chili again and he's aided and abetted by actors of
the quality of Gene Hackman as he was in ``Get Shorty.''
</P>
<P>
   For years Hollywood seemed to be unable to transfer an Elmore
Leonard novel to the screen with real success. That's not the case
in recent years. I'm not sure why, but it's nice that we ardent
Elmore fans can lately look forward to seeing the movie as well as
reading the book.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard has published 35 books now and seems to be rolling right
along, since his books are automatic best sellers and, it seems
lately, automatic movies. ``Out of Sight'' and ``Get Shorty'' and
even the made-for-TV ``Maximum Bob'' have been transferred to the
screen without losing the Elmore Leonard ambiance, or touch, or
however you say it when the movie has a satisfying amount of the
same flavor as the book.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Milner writes for the Lufkin Daily News, Lufkin, Texas. He
is the author of the new non-fiction novel, ``Confessions of a
Maddog.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
