<HEADER>
A6056 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASHION-SANDALS14-COX     04-13 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-SANDALS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Slip into some slings, slides and sandals
 &HT;    By Christi Mays
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Take a load off.
</P>
<P>
   Lose the hose until next fall. Bury those heavy heals in the
back of the closet.
</P>
<P>
   Lighten up your footfalls this spring by slipping into some
slings, slides and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come spring and summer, women like the freedom of wearing
sandals and no hose,'' said Phil Greenawalt, manager of Nine West
Shoe Store.
</P>
<P>
   The good thing about sandals this season? Anything goes _ from
simple flat-soled slides (or mules as they're also called) to
strappy slingback sandals with a good-sized heel for a
sophisticated look.
</P>
<P>
   Brighten up your steps with pale pastel slingbacks or shock 'em
with fuchsia dress slides with slight heels. Liven things up with a
leopard-print, open-toe mule or dressy faux snake-skin sandals in a
variety of colors.
</P>
<P>
   The metallic shade of your choice is out there _ copper, silver,
gold, platinum or even a mix of precious metals shades can be found
in many shapes and styles. Pearly whites, iridescent plastics and
even colored suedes are hits.
</P>
<P>
   Suede for spring? That's right, in limes, oranges, reds,
purples, etc. Just watch out for that rain puddle!
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is getting a little bit more freewheeling with what
they want,'' Greenawalt said of the variety of sandals available
for spring and summer. ``There's not just one thing that
everybody's focusing in on.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer are sandals just meant for the beach, either. ``They
can go with anything _ jeans, shorts, skirts, even a nice summer
dress,'' said Sarah Hill, merchandising assistant in the shoe
department of JC Penney.
</P>
<P>
   Shoe store managers report that brown and black are always the
mainstay colors of choice in sandals. However, more women are
mixing fresh colors into their wardrobe for a casual chic look for
work or play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's got navy and black,'' said Brett Bartlett,
operations manager of Texas Shoe Sale. ``I think when the different
colors come out, like the greens and fuchsias, people like those a
little bit more because it gives a little color to their
wardrobe.''
</P>
<P>
   Keep two key points in mind when coordinating colored sandals
with outfits, Hill says.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to match the sandals with the basic color in your
outfit, whatever stands out and is noticed first,'' she said. ``Or
if you have a background color you want to bring out of your
outfit, colored sandals (that match the background color) are going
to bring that color out more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill, who wears dress shoes and hose to work every day, says she
would live in sandals if she could.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm not at work, 90 percent of the time I'm in sandals,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, younger girls are favoring clunkier, thicker soles,
Greenawalt said, while women like anything flat and light or with a
slight heel to it.
</P>
<P>
   When you're out doing a little sole searching this spring,
comfort is key.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women aren't just buying because it's a trend,'' Greenawalt
said. ``They're looking for something comfortable, but still
fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The slide with a lower heel or a hin wedge hits a home run in
the comfort zone, followed by thongs, slings and sandals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are going for lightweight, comfort and padding in
sandals,'' Greenawalt said. ``Ladies have a tendency, when they
purchase a dress shoe for a specific function, they'll put up with
less comfort. But sandals, they're really looking for something
that feels good on their feet that they can walk around in.''
</P>
<P>
   Look for thin elastic, crisscrossed-type sandals for a
barely-there feel. Mules made of microfiber material are airy and
quite comfy, too.
</P>
<P>
   When searching for sandals, Pay attention to quality and
workmanship, advises Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is more discouraging than buying a great pair of sandals
only to have one of the straps come loose from the sole. Most
sandals' straps are glued into the sole, even top brands, which
means they can pull out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have a leather sole, a lot of times, they'll have
stitching around them and they hold up a little better,'' Bartlett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Mays writes for the Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
