his alter ego, San Francisco Police Officer and part-time
ventriliquist Bob Geary, they're not taking their defeat in tax
court lying down. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   LUCAS-CHARITY (San Francisco) _ George Lucas is using the power
of the Force to help children's charities in 11 North American
cities. Lucasfilm announced it would release ``Star Wars'' Episode
I on May 16 in San Francisco, Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Denver, Los
Angeles, New York, Philadelphia, Seattle, Toronto and Washington.
By the San Francisco Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   BROWNIE-MARY (San Francisco) _ Brownie Mary, a leader in the
medical marijuana movement whose brownies laced with the drug eased
the pain of a generation of young AIDS victims, is dead. Brownie
Mary, whose real name was Mary Rathbun, was 77. By LARRY D.
HATFIELD.
</P>
<P>
   MISSING-TOURISTS (Eureka, Calif.) _ Grasping for a way to cope
with the unsolved murders of Carole and Julie Sund, the family of
the mother and daughter killed on a Yosemite vacation has started a
petition drive for tougher sentencing laws against violent
criminals. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   EV (San Francisco) _ As gas prices here edge toward the
$2-a-gallon mark, the attraction of electrically powered vehicles _
EVs to those who know and love them _ is becoming clear to many
embittered motorists. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-CONTRACT (San Francisco) _ The FBI is investigating the
award of a $116 million contract for a light-rail system to move
people around the San Francisco International Airport. A focus of
the probe, say people interviewed by the FBI, is how minority
subcontractors were hired for the job under a city affirmative
action program. By CHUCK FINNIE.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JACKSON-HIRING (San Francisco) _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson storms
through Silicon Valley and presses technology companies to hire
more minorities and engage in more business with minority-owned
firms. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   E-MAIL (Albany, N.Y.) _ Even patients in hospital beds are
demanding access to e-mail. The number of adult users in the United
States jumped from 23 million in April 1997 to 53 million last
December, 27 percent of the U.S. adult population, said Stuart
Gibbel, director of marketing for Cyber Dialogue, an online market
research firm. By KATE GURNETT.
</P>
<P>
   EBAY (San Francisco) _ EBay is going uptown. The San Jose-based
Web auctioneering site has confirmed a report that San Francisco's
prestigious Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield Auctioneer Corp. art auction
house will offer high-end goods on the site. The deal would be the
first permanent alliance between a real-world auction house and a
Web-based auctioneering site. By MATT BEER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   DIXIE CHICKS (Undated) _ This country band is no longer one of
the best-kept secrets on the Texas music scene. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICAN MUSIC (Houston) _ Last year the Houston International
Festival spotlighted the nations of western Africa. This year, the
festival shifts the cultural focus to southern Africa. By RICK
MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-LINDSEY (Undated) _ In ``The Color of Night,'' David
Lindsey uses a narrative device well-known to fans of western
movies: the old gunfighter who wants to retire but can't because
his past won't let him. By FRITZ LANHAM.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-WAR (undated) _ John Katzenbach's ``Hart's War''
(Ballantine Books, $24.95, 486 pages) is a fascinating and powerful
legal suspense novel set in a POW camp in Bavaria during World War
II. By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   OUTSIDE-MAIN (Undated) _ Recent surveys show that nature-related
trips represent the fastest-growing segment of the travel industry.
By the Houston Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   With OUTSIDE-RESERVE, OUTSIDE-PREPARE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-GIANTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ The tight-lipped Giants are as
unlikely to leak who they'll pick in the upcoming NFL draft as the
Pentagon is to tip off its military strategy in the Balkans. But it
doesn't take a spreadsheet and a hard drive full of draft models to
know that the team is in dire need of help on the offensive line.
By MARK SINGELAIS.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Attention homeless: This week 546
people who professionally agonize about the poor and the homeless
will be at the Fairmont Hotel talking about ethics and eating fancy
food. Yes, the convention of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors is in town. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
