<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 12:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6131 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NAU-JENKINS-AZR &LR;      04-13 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NAU-JENKINS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A ROLLER COASTER RECORD  
 FIRST A STAR, NEXT EXPELLED, NOW AT NAU  
 ATTN: UTAH EDITORS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLAGSTAFF, Ariz. _ The best college running back in the state
might not be the one just finishing spring drills at Arizona State.
And he might not be the guy preparing to help Arizona prove itself
worthy of an expected top five preseason ranking.
</P>
<P>
   He could be here, at Northern Arizona University, sporting a
baby face, wearing a retainer and unpacking a travel trailer full
of baggage collected on a trip that's taken him from Oxnard,
Calif., to Provo, Utah, and now to Flagstaff.
</P>
<P>
   Ronney Jenkins' football career has been been filled with
exhilaration and enough anguish to be worthy of daytime television.
Chart his career and you end up with a heartbeat pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Western Athletic Conference freshman of the year in 1996 for
Brigham Young University.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended the next season for violating the school's honor code.
Considered transferring to ASU but decided to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Married, then divorced.
</P>
<P>
   Rushed for 1,311 yards last year, including 171 against Arizona
State, and scored 15 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Expelled in December for violating the school's honor code
again. Transferred to NAU, a Division I-AA school where he becomes
immediately eligible.
</P>
<P>
   Married again three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, as polite and soft-spoken as a church usher, seems
undisturbed by all the changes he's endured since leaving the
security of his grandmother's home in Oxnard three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I adapt to things pretty well,'' said Jenkins, who turns 22
next month. ``I've been adapting to things all my life.'' &QL; 
Good prospects &QL; 
People at NAU are anxious to help, because rarely, if ever, does a
running back of Jenkins' ability show up on the campus of a Big Sky
Conference school.
</P>
<P>
   And rarely, if ever, has each of Arizona's three
football-playing colleges had a pro prospect at running back at the
same time.
</P>
<P>
   ASU's J.R. Redmond was an all-Pac-10 choice last year. Arizona's
Trung Canidate is an indispensable part of what could be one of the
nation's best offenses. Both might be considered early Heisman
Trophy candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But a case could be made that Jenkins is the best of the three.
As a freshman, he rushed for 733 yards on 128 carries (a 5.7-yard
average) and scored 14 touchdowns. Despite being hampered by minor
injuries last season, Jenkins averaged more than 5 yards a carry
and was a second team all-WAC selection.
</P>
<P>
   He has sprinter's speed and recently was timed in the 40-yard
dash at 4.4 seconds. He says his best time was 4.29 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's as good as anybody we've ever had around here,'' said BYU
Coach LaVell Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   NAU Coach Jerome Souers is not given to boastful statements, but
when asked about Jenkins, he can't suppress a dimpled smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to be any secret,'' he said, ``he's going to
have the ball in his hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Some NFL scouting services rate Jenkins, a junior next season,
as one of the top running back prospects in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins insists he isn't looking that far ahead. He's
concentrating on trying to fit in with his new teammates, learn a
new offense and adapt to a new environment that's far different
from the one he knew in Provo, which he admits is probably a good
thing.
</P>
<P>
   However adaptable Jenkins thinks he is, Provo and BYU were
difficult fits for him, as they are for many African-American and
non-Mormon athletes. It's more than the school's honor code, which
forbids drinking alcohol, sex outside of marriage and substance
abuse, among other things. It's dealing with a mindset that's
radically different from what non-Mormons are accustomed to,
Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thinks the same,'' he said. ``Everybody wants the
same things. It was so different from where I came from. It was
like a whole different country, a whole different world.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins went to BYU at the urging of his grandmother, Jean
Cobbs, who admired the school's values and thought it would be good
for her grandson to leave California. It's advice that she says she
now regrets giving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, he can put this behind him, and we'll leave BYU
right where it is _ Provo,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins, who turned down a scholarship offer from Southern
California, assumes responsibility for his mistakes at BYU. He
admitted violating the school's honor code twice by having
premarital sex. He considered transferring after the first time but
stayed because his grandmother thought he should.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also would have stayed after the second violation had
BYU officials decided to suspend him for only a few games. They
didn't, announcing last Christmas Eve that Jenkins had been
expelled.
</P>
<P>
   BYU officials couldn't comment about why Jenkins was dismissed,
but Edwards said Jenkins had never been in trouble with the law and
never had had a problem with alcohol or substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great kid,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   What bothered Jenkins most about his BYU experience was that
other people went to school officials with numerous accusations, he
said, including one that he was a gang member, which he denies. And
school administrators assumed he was guilty, he said, and wanted
him to prove his innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was always something,'' he said. ``You never knew what
was going to happen, who was going to say things about you, who was
going to tell on you about this. I always expected something to
happen.'' &QL; 
Honor code confrontations &QL; 
After the 1996 season, Jenkins was suspended for have sexual
relations with another student, Nikki McBride, whom he married just
a few weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   It is a relationship that has survived rocky times, he said.
While sitting out in 1997, Jenkins broke up with McBride and
married another woman, a marriage that lasted just over a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was wrong,'' he said of the marriage. ``I just
wanted to go back to school and try to start all over and stay out
of trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   And he did for a while. He showed up to camp last year
admittedly out of shape, and it affected his performance throughout
the year. That thought probably scares Sun Devils fans, who saw
Jenkins overpower ASU's defense last year in BYU's 26-6 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jenkins renewed his relationship with McBride, a
Mormon from New Jersey. Allegations followed that Jenkins and
McBride had violated the honor code again, charges made by a few
people who didn't like him, Jenkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins didn't dispute that he and McBride had been intimate.
That was enough to end his BYU career, a result that disturbed his
65-year-old grandmother, a woman who doesn't sit quietly by if she
thinks a family member is being mistreated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to tell people that I'm a lady going in and I'm a lady
coming out, but you may not like what you see in between,'' Cobbs
said from her home in Oxnard.
</P>
<P>
   She was particularly upset because she thought BYU officials
were slow to grant Jenkins a release and free him to accept a
scholarship at another school.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbs said she thought BYU officials had waited because they
wanted Jenkins to return to the team after he sat out another
season.
</P>
<P>
   Cobbs, along with her son and Jenkins' uncle, Dwayne Hall, told
them that was unacceptable and demanded that Jenkins be released.
Only then, she said, did BYU oblige.
</P>
<P>
   BYU officials, through a school spokesman, deny those
allegations. Jenkins and his family remain bitter about the events
of last December.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't throw the baby out with the bathwater in our
culture,'' Cobbs said. ``If you take a child out of his environment
and put him in your environment, it doesn't mean he's amoral or a
bad kid, he just doesn't know your environment.'' &QL; 
Helping non-Mormons &QL; 
BYU officials say they realize they have a problem with non-Mormon
_ and specifically African-American _ athletes coping in a place
that is overwhelmingly White and with a strict Mormon honor code.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a legitimate point there,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   Jenkins' family, as well as some of his Mormon teammates, urged
the school to do more to help non-Mormon students cope.
</P>
<P>
   According to Salt Lake City newspapers, 24 athletes were
suspended for honor code violations in the 1990s. Seventeen of
those were African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one liked what happened last December,'' said Carri
Jenkins, the university's director of media communications and no
relation to Ronney.
</P>
<P>
   The university has established a new student-athlete center,
which will be under the direction of a non-denominational chaplain.
The idea is to give non-Mormon athletes a comfortable place to go
for counseling and other help.
</P>
<P>
   The school is also preparing a video to explain the honor code
to prospective athletes. And all 30,000 students at BYU were
recently sent a letter that made it clear that ``encouraging''
fellow students to follow the honor code didn't mean ``they should
be out there spying,'' Carri said.
</P>
<P>
   Ronney endorses the changes, although they are being made too
late to help him. He is not dwelling on what happened to him at BYU
and has kept a low profile since arriving at NAU, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a talker,'' he said. ``I like to show people what I
can do and then let them talk about me.''
</P>
<P>
   That shouldn't take long, said NAU quarterback Travis Brown, who
became a fan of Jenkins' after only a few spring practices. Jenkins
reminds Brown of former NAU running back Archie Amerson, who rushed
for 2,079 yards in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would get accused of not carrying out my fakes because I
wanted to watch Archie,'' Brown said. ``That might be the case
again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   There is speculation that Jenkins will stay only one year at NAU
before leaving for the NFL. Jenkins said he would wait to see how
this season goes before making a decision. His family wants him to
stay in school and graduate, and Jenkins doesn't seem in a hurry to
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't grow up with money, and I still don't have any
money,'' he said. ``It's nothing to me. I've never been `up.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
