<HEADLINE>
HIGHER GAS PRICES GIVE ELECTRIC CARS A CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Once maligned as slow and bothersome,
electrically powered vehicles _ EVs to those who know and love them
_ are becoming the objects of affection to motorists embittered by
the skyrocketing fuel prices in California.
</P>
<P>
   Gas costs climbed 43.1 cents per gallon in the past three weeks,
bringing the average price per gallon of unleaded gasoline in the
San Francisco area to $1.71, the highest in the nation. The
nationwide average is about $1.10 per gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Kohenek, who markets the General Motors EV-1 through
Saturn dealerships, said the rise in consumer interest had been
evident. ``In the last two weeks I've been quite busy and getting a
lot more calls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those inquiring about GM's battery-driven two-seater
have mentioned gas prices as a motive for their sudden interest,
Kohenek added.
</P>
<P>
   EVs are still in the experimental stage and aren't likely to
save money over gas-powered cars, even at the prices drivers in
this car-loving state must pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is that the cost of new electric vehicles will
probably never be competitive with new gasoline cars for the simple
reason that batteries are inherently expensive, heavy and bulky,''
said Daniel Sperling, who directs the Institute of Transportation
Studies at the University of California at Davis. The institute is
preparing a study of electric vehicle operating costs for the
California Air Resources Board.
</P>
<P>
   Sperling said EVs would falter in the marketplace until the
battery system was replaced with fuel cell technology, which can
convert a variety of fuels into electrical energy without
combustion and with no toxic emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Greg West thinks he's getting a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   West, design manager for a San Jose technology company, leases
his EV-1 for $373 per month, which includes a state tax incentive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a complete bumper-to-bumper warranty for the three
years of the lease,'' West said. ``I don't buy tires, I don't buy
brakes. I figure that's worth about $100 a month.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, he said, ``I put about $14 worth of electricity on
the vehicle and drove about 900 miles. It would have cost me $50 to
$60 for my other vehicle, a 10-year-old Volvo wagon. With the price
of gas going up, that savings, of course, gets bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   William Dahlgren pays $485 for his four-seat Honda EV, which has
a similar all-inclusive warranty. He doesn't care about the cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm one of those people who just wanted one,'' he said.
Dahlgren had earlier owned a converted Renault electric car, and
during the early 1970s gas crunch he built his own electric
motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   There's a critical difference between gas and electrically
powered automobiles, and that is range.
</P>
<P>
   Dahlgren, who lives on the southern cusp of San Francisco, said
he could drive about 85 miles from one charge on his Honda EV.
</P>
<P>
   When fuel cells technology is perfected, the short-range problem
will disappear, Sperling said. ``The auto industry is looking to
(fuel cell technology) as the Holy Grail to solve all their
problems,'' he said. ``You get all the advantage of battery
electric vehicles without the range problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The wait won't be long. He said major American car manufacturers
had vowed that ``they're each going to have 100,000 fuel cell
vehicles on the road by 2005.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6141 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX     04-13 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPMAN-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISTORIAN QUESTIONS ALAMO'S BATTLE COUNT IN NEW MANUSCRIPT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The siege of the Alamo took place 163 years ago and we're still
not confident that we know exactly what happened.
</P>
<P>
   The battle lasted 13 days, we're pretty sure of that, and we
know for certain that Santa Anna and his Mexican troops won. We
thought we knew Davy Crockett died while slugging onrushing Mexican
troops with the blunt end of ``Betsy,'' his muzzle loader. But
maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   A Mexican officer wrote in his diary that Crockett was taken
prisoner and later executed. Some historians debated his claim, but
collectors paid $350,000 for the memoirs anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Now, an Austin historian says there weren't 189 defenders killed
at the Alamo as the monument out front says. In a manuscript being
reviewed by the University of Texas Press, Thomas Ricks Lindley
estimates that there were about 250 defenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Tom and he is well respected as an Alamo researcher,''
said Bruce Winders, the staff historian at the Alamo. ``We're just
waiting to see if the manuscript will be published.''
</P>
<P>
   Lindley's research indicates that there were forces from Goliad,
Bastrop and Gonzales at the Alamo that were never counted among the
garrison. There were also a few Tejanos brought in by Juan Seguin.
And it appears that some of the names that are on the list
shouldn't be. There is evidence that some of the men were elsewhere
when the battle took place.
</P>
<P>
   Winders said all of that is probably true.
</P>
<P>
   ``It isn't really a new revelation,'' Winders said of the
conflicting numbers. ``The number of defenders and the number of
attacking troops have always been under question.''
</P>
<P>
   Winders said the Alamo officially agrees that the number of
defenders should be around 200. The staff believes that Santa
Anna's army at the Alamo to have been around 2,500.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there were upward of 2,500 Mexican forces in San
Antonio on March 6, 1836,'' he said. ``In the past, Santa Anna's
army was numbered at a little over 6,000 and some people have
placed all of them in San Antonio, which they were not. Some were
on the road to San Antonio, some were east of there, near Goliad.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the question becomes, will the Alamo _ owned by the state,
and operated by the Daughters of the Republic of Texas _ change the
monument to reflect the additional names?
</P>
<P>
   Well, perhaps, but probably not any time soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there is solid evidence everyone can agree on, I'm sure
the list will be revised,'' Winders said. ``When Lindley's book
comes out, if it does, or any book for that matter, it will be
reviewed and people will judge it on its merits.''
</P>
<P>
   That can take years, and given the sensitive nature of the
Alamo, and what it stands for, the evidence will have to be nearly
irrefutable. The Alamo is not a roadside historical marker; it is
by state law a shrine to the men who died there, and Winders says
that gives it a different set of operating rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``The list of names is so potentially controversial,'' he said.
``When it comes to removing someone's name, there is an entire
family behind that name that will be upset. If you delete it, or
add someone else's name, you must have more than ample proof.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail:
Artc(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
