<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 eBAY MOVES UPTOWN WITH NEW AUCTION PARTNER  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A prestigious San Francisco art auction house
will offer high-end goods on the eBay Web site, giving the
everyman's auction an uptown image.
</P>
<P>
   The deal between San Jose-based eBay and the Butterfield &AMP;
Butterfield Auctioneer Corp. would be the first permanent alliance
between a real-world auction house and a Web-based auctioneering
site.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan to offer premium items for auction on our site from
Butterfield,'' said Kevin Pursglove, a spokesman for eBay.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet site usually offers more home-grown items, such as
used computers and ukuleles, which are sold and bought by
individuals. Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield has been holding estate
sales and art auctions since 1865.
</P>
<P>
   According to a prospectus recently filed with the Securities and
Exchange Commission, eBay said it had signed a ``nonbinding letter
of understanding to create a separate category of premium items on
the eBay Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   Those items, the prospectus said, ``would be sourced from
Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield and other auction companies.'' A
spokesman for Butterfield declined to comment, citing the company's
current quiet period, a federally mandated period of public silence
following the Feb. 12 notice that Butterfield planned to offer its
shares to the public.
</P>
<P>
   On-line auctions, where Web users bid by computer for a range of
goods and services, have been a runaway success on the Internet.
EBay is the most successful of the growing number of such sites.
Its popularity has made it one of the most visited destinations on
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good synergy,'' said Ron Rappaport, an analyst with
Internet market research firm Zona Research. ``EBay is known as the
superstore, and Butterfield has the prestige goods. This lets
Butterfield reach that huge market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
