<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-WAR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINE WAR NOVEL IS A POTENT LEGAL THRILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BOBBIE HESS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   John Katzenbach's ``Hart's War'' (Ballantine Books, $24.95, 486
pages) is a fascinating and powerful legal suspense novel set in a
prisoner of war camp in Bavaria during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Second Lt. Tommy Hart is the only survivor of a B-25 shot down
over the Mediterranean. Picked up by the Italian Navy, he is handed
over to the Germans and sent to Stalag Luft 13, a camp for
American, British and Canadian airmen. Daily activity includes
baseball and tunnel digging. Hart, a former Harvard law student,
spends his days reading legal texts and once a week bribes his way
into the camp's British compound to argue cases with Barrister
Phillip Pyrce and Hugh Renaday, a former Royal Canadian Mounted
Police constable.
</P>
<P>
   Life in Stalag Luft 13 changes radically when a new prisoner is
brought in _ 1st Lt. Lincoln Scott, a black pilot who is a Tuskegee
airman. He is immediately taunted by Capt. Vincent Bedford, a
racist from Mississippi and the camp's wheeler-dealer.
</P>
<P>
   Hart tries to make friends with Scott, but the very proud
scholar refuses to talk with anyone. When Bedford is found with his
throat slit in the officers' privy, Scott becomes the prime suspect
when blood is found on his flight jacket and boots.
</P>
<P>
   The camp's commandant agrees to let the Americans put Scott on
trial. Ordered to defend Scott, Hart is allowed to enlist the
services of Pyrce and Renaday. Scott admits being in the privy the
night of Bedford's murder but maintains that he is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   When Hart and Renaday inspect the murder scene they realize that
Bedford could not have been murdered there because there's no
evidence of blood. The Germans bring in Hauptmann Heinrich Visser
to monitor the investigation and the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The ranking American officer and his aides believe it is an
open-and-shut case. What Hart doesn't know is that the trial is
being timed to coincide with a major escape attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach artfully develops his characters layer by layer. Not
all the Germans are bad _ the commandant is a man of honor, as is
Fritz No. 1, one of the camp's guards. Yet Visser is the epitome of
Gestapo evil. There is honor and duty among the Americans, but
there is also deep-seated racism.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenbach's vivid descriptions of the usually boring routine of
the captured airmen immediately conjure up images from the movie
``Stalag 17.''
</P>
<P>
   As both a war novel and a legal thriller, ``Hart's War'' is a
compelling read. It's also a tribute to the men who served in World
War II, especially the Tuskegee airmen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In ``Biting the Moon'' (Henry Holt &AMP; Co, $25, 301 pages), Martha
Grimes has taken a break from her very popular police procedural
series featuring Scotland Yard Superintendent Richard Jury.
However, her new mystery is a very dark, uneven read.
</P>
<P>
   A very pretty young woman wakes up in a bed-and-breakfast in
Santa Fe, N.M. She doesn't know who she is and has no memories of
the past. The B&AMP;B owner says she was brought in ``dead asleep by
her daddy.'' Knowing the man will soon return, the girl gathers up
her backpack, takes his jacket, his money and his gun and heads for
the mountains. Eventually, she finds a deserted cabin and spends
her time learning how to shoot and rescuing animals from traps.
</P>
<P>
   Because her backpack has the initials AO on it, she names
herself Andi Olivier and begins creating a mythical family and
past.
</P>
<P>
   Andi periodically makes trips back to town to steal medicine for
the injured animals. About four months after she began hiding out,
Andi goes back to town and meets 14-year-old Mary Dark Hope, whose
real past is also tragic. Mary's parents are dead, her only sister
was murdered and Mary now lives with her loving caretaker Rosella.
When Mary takes Andi home, Rosella says Andi can stay.
</P>
<P>
   Then Rosella finds someone to watch over the girls and leaves to
spend 10 days with her family.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing Andi's story, Mary agrees to accompany Andi on a
trek to find ``Daddy.'' They learn to drive along the way as they
encounter illegal trapping, white water rafting, illegal big game
hunts, animal abuse, child abuse, child molestation and murder.
</P>
<P>
   What is so unsettling about ``Biting the Moon'' is that adult
after adult accepts the wild stories Mary and Andi tell and then
help them get into more danger. And when the book is over, there
are too many unanswered questions.
</P>
<P>
   According to a press release, ``Biting the Moon'' ``is the debut
of a new series featuring young heroines which will focus on the
prevention of animal abuse.'' I doubt Grimes fans are going to like
this new series.
</P>
<P>
   Bring back Richard Jury.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
