<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WAYS TO DISS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sketchy and skeevy: They could be buddies of Itchy and Scratchy,
the stars of the Simpsons' favorite cartoon show, but no: Both
words are slang in transition, making their way into mainstream
media after years of life on the margins, where most
self-respecting argot prefers to hang out.
</P>
<P>
   Sketchy _ meaning dubious, iffy, suspect _ has been standard
among teenagers for at least the past few years; one source traces
it to 1976, calling it campus slang for ``dangerous.'' But only in
the '90s did sketchy catch on widely enough to make its move into
grown-up prose.
</P>
<P>
   I first spotted this sketchy in print _ or, rather, on-screen _
in Slate, the on-line magazine. ``It is the fact that the airline
business is so capital-intensive that makes it such a sketchy
business,'' wrote James Surowiecki in his Moneybox column on April
1. It was no joke, though: Sketchy has been in Surowiecki's
vocabulary since at least 1995, he says. ``Initially my friends and
I used it a lot in reference to people . . . then quickly broadened
that to refer to almost anything that's not quite the way it should
be,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The new sketchy is not much of a stretch, though, from the old.
Colloquially, sketchy was already used to mean cursory, as in ``a
sketchy job of cleaning,'' and just an added dash of disapproval
gives us the current slang.
</P>
<P>
   Skeevy is a harder case. It means sketchy and then some _
repellent, nasty, disgusting _ but my slang dictionaries offered
slim pickings on its history. One called it a '90s word, another
put it in the '50s, spelled skevee and meaning ``a messy person.''
(One who leaves his skivvies on the floor?)
</P>
<P>
   A computer search, though, turned up a clue: A story in which
Denise Flaim, an editor and home columnist at Newsday, called
skeevy ``a word from my Queens youth.''
</P>
<P>
   In reply to a plea for more info, Flaim explained that skeevy is
familiar among colleagues who grew up in New York's outer boroughs.
``One thing our mostly blue-collar immigrant neighborhoods had in
common was a heavy concentration of Italian-Americans,'' she notes.
``So here's my etymological conclusion: It's derived from the
Italian word schifoso, pronounced ski-FO-zoe),'' which means
loathsome or filthy. ``The fact that skeevy is part of the lexicon
of `The Sopranos' cements it for me,'' says Flaim.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever its origins, skeevy is coming on strong: It's on the
lips of Katie Couric, in the pages of Redbook magazine and
Entertainment Weekly and (of course) People. And if those
endorsements don't persuade you to join the chorus, how about the
Christian Science Monitor, where a recent essay declared, ``There
aren't any skeevy things about God _ He is totally good.'' As a
usage testimonial, that one is hard to top.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(the word? Write or e-mail yours to Jan Freeman at The Boston
Globe, PO Box 2378, Boston, MA 02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com.
Include a hometown and phone number.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
