<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON NOT BEATEN BY WRIST SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The worst of it came April 3, when the Bruins played
the Philadelphia Flyers at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Allison had been nursing a wrist injury since March 17,
when he rammed it awkwardly into the boards in Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins shut out the Flyers, 3-0, but Allison was in great
distress. He thought the injury was bad enough that he might need
time off to allow it to heal. But Allison has stuck it out,
including a recent stretch of four games in six days, and believes
he has turned the corner _ finally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very frustrated during a couple of games, especially
Philly at home,'' said Allison, ``but that was the last time when
it's been a big issue.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Bruins off until Thursday, Allison didn't skate at
Monday's practice in Wilmington, and likely will skate only in a
limited way Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to skate but (coach Pat Burns) really didn't want
me to,'' he said. ``Conditioning isn't going to be a problem, so
why even do it? (Tuesday) I'll skate and try to stay away from the
battling and the shots for one more day. Then we still have another
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison, the Bruins' leading scorer with 73 points, has played
all 79 games so far and has no intention of missing any when the
regular season winds down with three games in four days beginning
Thursday against the Penguins. He'd rather tough it out to get
tuned up for the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was up and down for a while, but it's actually felt better
the end of last week,'' he said. ``That was the first encouraging
thing about it. It's no big deal if you get minor pain in it during
a game. It's when it gets to the point where you can't really
perform because you have no grip strength and no feeling in it. It
wasn't like that the end of last week, so it's encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now with this little rest here, hopefully it's not as much of
an issue. I'm not expecting it to be a major issue for the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest Allison came to crying ``uncle'' was after the
Montreal game last Monday. After the pain he had experienced
against the Flyers and the discomfort he went through against the
Canadiens, he thought it might be time for a break. After the game
against Florida Wednesday, he thought it really might be best if he
sat out the next night in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the Montreal game, I was like, `I'll see what happens,'
'' he said. ``Then after the first Florida game, it was a little
sore and I was thinking about the next night, but I was like,
`Why?' I've gone this long with two games left and then it didn't
actually feel too bad so there was no question I was going to play
Saturday after the game we lost in Tampa.''
</P>
<P>
   To Burns, Allison is an ironman. The coach said he's rarely seen
a player with the pain threshold of Allison. The major adjustment
the Bruins have had to make is how to use Allison on faceoffs. He
is normally very consistent on draws but has struggled. Burns said
when faceoffs were important, Allison seemed to win them, and when
they weren't, he would lose them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's kind of what was happening,'' agreed Allison. ``I'd be
going into draws trying to just do quick ones. I didn't want to get
into tie-ups. I did a couple of games and I'd get other guys to
take the neutral-zone faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``On my forehand, I'm usually pretty good. Most guys are better
on their backhands. I'm pretty even and I just couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison said the wrist has improved enough that he expects to be
in top form for the postseason, which the Bruins certainly need.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was going to sit out, it would've been done before, not
now,'' he said. ``We're going to play three in four nights so it's
a good test anyway to see how it feels. I don't want to make it an
issue. I want to worry about the playoffs and winning games and
going far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
