<HEADLINE>
GIANTS DESPERATELY NEED HELP ON THE OFFENSIVE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK SINGELAIS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The tight-lipped New York Giants are as unlikely
to leak their pick in the upcoming NFL draft as the Pentagon is to
tip off its military strategy in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   But it doesn't take a spreadsheet and a hard drive full of draft
models to figure out that the Giants are in dire need of help on
the offensive line, a point general manager Ernie Accorsi makes no
effort to dodge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to fortify that,'' he said. ``I won't get any more
specific than that. I'd be less than truthful if I said that wasn't
important to us.''
</P>
<P>
   That's as strong an indication as any that the Giants will enter
the draft on Saturday and Sunday trying to shore up the line. They
could take a lineman as early as their first pick, the 19th overall
in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants have had little fortune with No. 1 picks this decade.
Only Rodney Hampton, the 24th overall selection in 1990, developed
into a star, becoming New York's career rushing leader.
</P>
<P>
   Fate, however, appears to have dealt the Giants a good hand.
Offensive line depth, especially at tackle, appears to be one of
the strongest areas in this draft.
</P>
<P>
   Various draft pundits project six linemen as first-rounders:
Brigham Young University tackle John Tait; Boston College center
Damien Woody; Wisconsin tackle Aaron Gibson; Georgia tackle Matt
Stinchcomb; Eastern Michigan tackle L.J. Shelton and West Virginia
tackle Solomon Page.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA tackle Kris Farris, BC guard Doug Brzezinski and Penn State
tackle Floyd Wedderburn have been mentioned as high second-round
picks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the tackles, like the massive Gibson, who crushes the
scale at 6-foot-6, 380 pounds, might be moved to guard in the NFL
because they don't have the quickness to pass-block on the outside.
</P>
<P>
   If the Giants take a lineman with their first pick, don't be
surprised if he's plugged into the starting lineup right away. The
Giants have a hole at left guard because starter Greg Bishop, who
wasn't dominating, signed with the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   With little depth behind Bishop, the Giants probably will have
to plug in a rookie at left guard or move right tackle Scott Gragg
over to that position.
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi said that other than quarterback, offensive line might
be the hardest position for a rookie to learn. But in this era,
rookies are expected to produce right away because of the money
that's at stake. A team has to find out quickly whether a rookie is
good enough to warrant a long-term extension after his rookie
contract expires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get your value out of them,'' Accorsi said. Though Gibson
seems to be a good risk, Woody could be a smart No. 1 pick because
of his versatility. He can play guard, or he can slide over to
center if Brian Williams fails in his comeback after missing two
seasons with an eye injury.
</P>
<P>
   There is a slight chance the Giants will ignore need in the
first round and go with the best-available-athlete theory. That was
the case last season, when they also needed an offensive lineman
but chose safety Shaun Williams instead. They were stocked at
defensive back, but were stunned when Williams, easily the
highest-rated athlete left on their board, was available when New
York's turn came with the 24th pick.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, used as a nickel back last season, showed promise with
24 tackles and two interceptions. He also had 10 special-teams
tackles. The Giants haven't traded their first-round pick since
1975, a streak that figures to continue.
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi said recently that the price to trade up in the first
round probably would be too steep. The Giants aren't willing to
throw in their second-round pick or next year's first-rounder to
move up a few spots. Trading down also is a remote chance, Accorsi
said, unless the Giants get an outstanding offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
