u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUBA-HARVARD-BOS &LR;      04-13 0888
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBA-HARVARD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD TRIES TO CULTIVATE OLD LINK TO CUBA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIENFUEGOS, Cuba _ A faded carving in the base of a 25-foot palm
tree is the only visible sign of a century-old mystery that
stretches from the sugarcane fields of this Caribbean port to the
ivy-covered halls of Cambridge.
</P>
<P>
   ``HARVARD Biological Laboratory,'' the marker reads in sculpted
letters near the entrance to one of the largest botanical gardens
in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this century, these warm, rolling hills on
Cuba's southern coast served as perhaps Harvard's most unique
classrooms. For decades, students came here to do research, while
professors and scientists cross-breeded sugarcane plants or
experimented with rubber trees.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the Castro Revolution in 1959, which turned this and
the nearly rest of the country into state-controlled property. That
was followed by a US government embargo against the island, which
strictly limited American access to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Now Harvard is cautiously considering a return to Cienfuegos _
not as the prerevolutionary garden proprietor it once was, but as a
post-Cold War partner in research and cultural exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been looking at the possibilities of reestablishing
contacts and relationships,'' said John Coatsworth, director of
Harvard's David Rockefeller Center for Latin American Studies, who
visited the garden last year and has led much of the discussion
about rekindling ties. ``I think it would be great if Harvard could
rebuild its ties to the Cuban scientific community. There's a lot
we could learn from each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest in the garden has grown so much recently that
university officials are planning a workshop with Cuban officials
on future scientific exchanges. And the Massachusetts Historical
Society is planning an exhibit next month to explore the garden's
roots to New England families.
</P>
<P>
   Coatsworth and other Harvard officials insist that the
university has no desire to resume operating the Cienfuegos garden.
</P>
<P>
   But they argue that a new partnership could help refurbish the
200-acre facility, which has suffered from a lack of resources and
battles against the elements.
</P>
<P>
   Nestled between the Sierra Escambray mountains and the
Caribbean, the garden holds more than 2,400 species of plants from
tropical zones native in five continents. It possesses more than
300 species of palms, 89 different types of ficus, 80 varieties of
orchids, and 27 types of bamboo.
</P>
<P>
   The garden _ known today as the Jardin Botanico de Soledad _
attracts about 35,000 European and Canadian tourists a year.
Busloads arrive daily for the two-hour tour.
</P>
<P>
   But administrators concede that little research is conducted
now. The laboratories and structures that once teemed with Ivy
League researchers have grown mostly silent. And weeds have become
a new enemy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that we haven't had significant investment,''
said Leonardo Aloma, 68, a former baseball pitcher who has worked
at the garden for the last 30 years. ``More than anything we need
to preserve these collections.''
</P>
<P>
   The garden was begun in 1899 by Edwin F. Atkins, a Massachusetts
businessman whose family owned vast sugar estates near Cienfuegos,
including Pepito Tey, one of the country's largest sugar factories,
across the street from the garden.
</P>
<P>
   With a $2,500 donation, Atkins enlisted Harvard scientists to
study ways to create a stronger species of sugarcane through
cross-breeding, as well as to study pests and diseases that plague
tropical plants. In 1919, a $100,000 endowment was established for
the garden and the university was given a 99-year-lease to run it.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins died in 1926. The university's presence grew. It built
the Harvard House for professors and students and began amassing
its botanical collection. In World War II, the US government
sponsored research at the garden on the use of rubber trees, and
landscaping plants were sent to the US military base to the east at
Guantanamo Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Why Harvard left remains unclear. The Communist Revolution led
by Fidel Castro that came to power in 1959 quickly began taking
over private companies, including the Atkins sugar factory. But
some historians and local residents say the garden was never
formally nationalized.
</P>
<P>
   Others point to the 1962 US embargo, which restricted American
contact with the island. Whatever the reason, the garden stopped
appearing in the university's annual reports by the mid-1960s, and
its operations were taken over by the government.
</P>
<P>
   The embargo was amended four years ago to allow for more
academic and foreign-exchange programs. Since then, about two dozen
American universities have developed programs in Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the idea of Harvard returning to Cienfuegos is being
well received by local residents and government officials. Even
among Atkins' descendents _ where there are still some hard
feelings about losing the sugar mill _ there are those who say it's
time to move beyond old Cold War anger.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely have two countries had such interesting and complex
ties,'' said Chester Atkins, the former Massachusetts congressman
and the patriarch's great-grandson. ``There are enormous
opportunities for collaborative work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
