r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-E-MAIL-HNS &LR;      04-13 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-MAIL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-MAIL: IT'S E-VERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Dan Richardson sat in the cramped, green, pre-op
room of a Virginia hospital, an intravenous drip in his arm. Soon,
he would be wheeled him into an operating room for three hours of
spinal surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Then he spotted the telephone. There was still time. He had his
laptop computer. This school headmaster can't leave home without
it. He could e-mail!
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 57, is not alone in his fascination with electronic
mail. The number of adult Internet users in the United States
jumped from 23 million in April 1997 to 53 million last December
_2027 percent of the U.S. adult population _ said Stuart Gibbel,
director of marketing for Cyber Dialogue, an on-line market
research firm.
</P>
<P>
   Hotmail, the free Web-based e-mail system, boasts 30 million
subscribers. Personal daily messages in North America are expected
to skyrocket from 500 million last year to 1.5 billion in 2002,
said Mike Shirer of Forrester Research, a Cambridge, Mass.,
technology research firm.
</P>
<P>
   E-mailers send messages, from a word or line to a book-size
document, via computer. No paper. No pen. No envelope, stamp or
worrisome time zones. Pour your heart out at 2 a.m. without waking
anyone up.
</P>
<P>
   This quick hit links grandmothers, long-lost friends and, of
course, teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fascinating mixture of letter-writing and
telephoning,'' said John Suler, psychology professor at Rider
University in Lawrenceville, N.J. ``You communicate at your leisure
rather than on demand, and it lacks face-to-face cues, which
encourages people to open up a bit more. It's already as
influential in people's lives as the telephone.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Waitt, 64, of Rexford, N.Y., got a garbled telephone
message that a friend had died, but it was unclear who. To get
answers, she got on her computer. Vacationing in Aruba, she plunked
down $5 in a shop to e-mail home and check the condition of a
terminally ill friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons I like this because it gives me so
much information about the folks back home in Massachusetts,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Buck Malen, 48, a bassist for the band Susan and the Surftones,
keeps late hours. He catches up with e-mail and a cup of tea in the
late mornings. ``It's like Dad reading the morning paper or opening
the mail,'' he said. ``I've gotten in touch with an awful lot of my
friends who I would never be in contact with due to the cost of
phone bills, in Los Angeles, San Francisco, Miami, New Orleans
people all over the country,'' said Malen, who lives in Troy, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Malen likes jokes, too. He forwards his daily favorites to 40 or
50 friends.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, the jokes. The jokes. Some love 'em. Some hate 'em. Why do
so many people send them?
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? Duh! Because I like jokes!'' said Luis Morales, an
Irvine, Calif., graphic designer and sales manager whose territory
includes Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   He sure does. He sends jokes about five times a day, to about 30
friends, clients and co-workers in English and in Spanish. In the
midst of a national debate over inappropriate office banter,
Morales gleefully forwards sexist and ethnic jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are political (meaning Clinton) jokes, religious jokes,
and I'm sure there isn't a one of them that wouldn't offend someone
somewhere,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If bad jokes are bothersome, spam (junk e-mail) is a pestilence,
e-mail users say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears in my in-coming mailbox every day,'' Suler said.
``I find it offensive, since it violates the `personal space' of
e-mail. It also violates the old philosophy of the Internet being
strictly noncommercial.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail use is spiraling upward, Suler said. ``The more you
e-mail, the more relationships you develop, the more you need to
continue e-mailing in order to stay connected to your colleagues
and friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, head of school at Cape Henry Collegiate School in
Virginia Beach, admits he's compulsive. Every day he writes his
journal, then e-mails it to family, friends and colleagues. Not
everyone reads it. But many do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny because I kind of look forward to my little daily
message and I get this little glimpse into Dan's life,'' said
Meredith Davies Hadaway, vice president for college relations and
publications at Washington College in Chestertown, Md., a former
student of Richardson's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost feel like one of those people who watches someone on
the Internet. I watch him daily and I know his kids and I know Pat,
so it's great fun. I feel like, as long as he keeps doing that,
we're always going to keep in touch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
