u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-13 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENNOCHI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HANCOCK YIELDS TO THE MIGHTY YEN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN VENNOCHI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ah, the sweet simplicity of modern-day economic morality.
</P>
<P>
   It goes like this: the bigger the economic stake, the stronger
the urge to ignore assorted moral dilemmas.
</P>
<P>
   Consider China.
</P>
<P>
   China's Premier Zhu Rongji failed last week to close a deal for
China to enter the World Trade Organization. But don't count him or
a deal out. The reason is obvious in every stop on the Chinese
leader's ongoing six-city tour of America, including Wednesday's
scheduled stop in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It's business _ as usual.
</P>
<P>
   For another example, take a look at John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co. of Boston. Last week, it joyously joined three
Western insurers in winning approval from Beijing to sell life
insurance in China. ``We are delighted by this news,'' Hancock's
chief executive, Stephen L. Brown, said in a statement. ``China is
the major emerging market for US financial institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   And delighted Brown should be. All those Chinese _ 1.3 billion
of them _ potentially in need of whole life policies! Given the
Chinese government's track record for repression, some of those
lives may be more at risk than others, but surely Hancock's
actuaries can factor fallout from human rights violations into
their longevity tables.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington last week, Raymond L. Flynn, the former Boston
mayor and Clinton's former ambassador to the Vatican, joined
demonstrators who accused the Chinese government of violating
Tibetans' human rights. ``Seems like our foreign policy is more
concerned about trade deals, profits, and multinational
international corporations than it is with human rights and
religious freedom,'' said Flynn, now president of the Catholic
Alliance, a lay organization that mobilizes Catholics to become
politically active.
</P>
<P>
   Wake up and read the fortune cookies, Ray. Of course our foreign
policy is more concerned with trade deals and corporate profits
than it is with human rights, religious freedom, or even the
possible theft of nuclear secrets by the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton wavered last week and walked away from a
China-WTO deal. Perhaps he was distracted by the human rights
violations in Kosovo, where market expectations are relatively low
and morality concerns are consequently high. Or perhaps he was
worried that a deal with China would give his political opponents a
new reason to raise questions about surreptitious Chinese donations
to the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the rationale for Clinton's wariness, business
blanched. As Maurice R. ``Hank'' Greenberg, chairman of American
International Group, told The Wall Street Journal: ``To have missed
that opportunity and to have the prime minister, who went out on a
limb on many of the issues, to go home empty-handed that way is
just not only puzzling; it is hard for anyone who understands
US-China relations to get any kind of a sense of the thought
process on this.''
</P>
<P>
   A Hancock spokesman says Brown, too, has been a consistent
proponent of a WTO deal for China and has written letters to
Congress on China's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu's failure to seal a WTO deal has no effect on Hancock's
China venture, the spokesman said. Hancock's plans _ which are
essentially dictated by the Chinese government _ call for it to do
business with a Chinese joint venture partner selected by the
Chinese and to reinvest money from the venture back into China.
They follow months of careful negotiations and courtesy trips to
China; Brown even traveled there with George Bush as his personal
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock's top executive walked the walk with the Chinese and he
is not alone. Wednesday, when Zhu is scheduled to land at Logan, a
greeting party ordered up by the Chinese will be on the tarmac to
welcome the Chinese premier. It is expected to include the
governor, the mayor, a Hancock delegation, and other business and
academic representatives.
</P>
<P>
   After addressing an audience at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology, the premier will lunch at the Boston Park Plaza. The
luncheon is hosted by the China Forum _ a collaboration of
Boston-area business groups, including the law firm of Foley, Hoag
&AMP; Eliot. It is scheduled to include remarks by Governor Cellucci,
Hancock's Brown and Patrick J. McGovern, head of Boston-based
International Data Group, a worldwide publisher of technology
magazines and newsletters.
</P>
<P>
   The protest movement that began in Tiananmen Square happened 10
years ago this month. In a world based upon the ever-popular theory
of economic morality, that is ancient history. All the writing in
the world cannot force us to honor that still-searing image of a
single student standing up, in the name of democracy, to an armored
tank.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the yen is so much mightier than the pen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Joan Vennochi is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
