<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DRUGS COVERAGE COULD DOUBLE MEDICARE PREMIUMS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding a prescription drug benefit to Medicare
would increase the program's cost by 7 to 13 percent over the next
decade, the non-partisan National Academy of Social Insurance
reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   If the drug benefit were financed solely out of premiums, it
would roughly double the cost of Medicare for its 38 million
elderly and disabled beneficiaries, said Robert Reischauer of the
Brookings Institution, a leader of the academy's project on
Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first outside analysis of how much it would
cost for Medicare to cover prescription drugs by a group that does
not have a financial or ideological stake in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at five different ways of providing a drug
benefit using different deductibles, copayments and levels of
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Over the 10-year period, a coverage plan with a $200 deductible,
20 percent copayment and $2,000 maximum benefit, adjusted for
inflation, would add about 10 percent to the overall cost of
Medicare, the study indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Plans that paid all drug costs at thresholds over $1,000 to
$3,000 would, over the decade, increase Medicare expenses by about
7 percent to 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The question of a prescription drug benefit may be one of the
most difficult facing lawmakers who want to reform Medicare.
President Clinton has said he wants any Medicare reform to include
prescription drug coverage, but has not indicated how it would be
structured.
</P>
<P>
   A bipartisan commission on Medicare's future created by Congress
failed to adopt a reform recommendation last month, partly because
of deep divisions over whether _ and how _ to include a
prescription drug benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Several members of Congress are working on Medicare reform
proposals, and most are expected to include some form of drug
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most private insurance policies, Medicare _ which was
created in 1965 primarily to cover hospital and physician costs _
does not cover prescription drugs. Yet medication frequently is
replacing surgery as a medical procedure, and many Medicare
patients have chronic conditions that require costly drugs that
were not available when the program began.
</P>
<P>
   The average Medicare beneficiary last year paid about $200 in
out-of-pocket prescription drug costs, but a significant portion
pay far more, said Michael E. Gluck, the academy's director of
health policy studies. About 4.5 million beneficiaries paid more
than $1,000, and another 1.3 million beneficiaries paid more than
$2,000 for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study indicated that about 65 percent of retirees have
some form of drug coverage, either through supplementary
``Medigap'' policies, the state-federal Medicaid program for the
poor, or an employer benefit. But Reischauer said that percentage
is rapidly shrinking as employers stop providing health coverage to
former workers and the cost of Medigap insurance rises.
</P>
<P>
   The question facing policy makers is whether prescription drugs
should be covered through social insurance, similar to doctor and
hospital costs, or be left to individuals, Reischauer said. He
argued that drugs should be brought into the Medicare program and
covered nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Arrayed against a Medicare drug benefit are insurance companies
and the pharmaceutical industry. Both groups fear it would lead to
government control of drug prices.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
