<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 13:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6206 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWHAMP-TAXES-BOS &LR;      04-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWHAMP-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING FREE IS MYTH FOR MANY IN NEW HAMPSHIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JILL ZUCKMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, N.H. _ Don't get Patricia Schena started.
</P>
<P>
   From behind the counter at the Trolley Gift Card Shop on Main
Street, Schena begins a slow boil as she tells how she left
``Taxachusetts'' for New Hampshire, the no-tax state, six years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The taxes up here are outrageous,'' she fumes. ``God knows
what's around the corner. I think we already pay enough.''
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire has always prided itself on a utilitarian approach
to government. Its bureaucracy is small, its regulations
unobtrusive, and there's no income or sales tax. People here mean
it when they say, ``Live Free or Die.''
</P>
<P>
   But citizens also know that the state's aura of rugged
conservatism is a myth. Taxes abound, in the smallest of places,
from Salem's $10 residence fee to a tax on house buyers and sellers
to a legion of other obscure levies.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, a bipartisan group of lawmakers suggested an
entertainment tax on movie tickets, gym memberships, and even video
rentals, all in an effort to fund the public schools without
imposing an income tax.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, New Hampshire residents have the lowest tax burden,
as a percentage of personal income, in the country. But to
taxpayers and homeowners like Schena, the range of taxes, and the
proposals for more, feels like death by a thousand pinpricks.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you won't have to pay an income tax or a sales tax, but
they'll nickel-and-dime you to death,'' said John Camobreco, a
political science professor at the University of New Hampshire.
``Don't expect to get anything for free up here. If you go to any
state park, you'll pay. If you go to any state beaches, you pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The current focus on taxes results from the Supreme Court's 1997
ruling that the current system of raising money for education with
local property taxes is unconstitutional. The Legislature and the
governor missed an April 1 deadline the court set on school funding
because of the reluctance of political leaders to enact an income
tax.
</P>
<P>
   The battle over whom to tax, how to tax, and what amount to tax
has been dramatic and drawn out.
</P>
<P>
   The latest plan before the Legislature would step up the
scattershot approach to raising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the pending bipartisan proposal would include a new
statewide property tax, a new 8 percent tax on car rentals, a new 2
percent excise tax on car sales and leases, and a new 1 percent
consumption tax on services from lawyers, mechanics, and others.
</P>
<P>
   Existing taxes would go up under the plan. Cigarette taxes would
rise by 25 cents a pack, the real estate transfer tax would
increase to $7.50 per $1,000, and a business-profits tax would rise
from 7 to 8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, New Hampshire has been especially creative at
funding the government without a broad-based tax. More than 40
states use either an income tax or a sales tax. And states that
don't use one of those major taxes usually have another special
income stream.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska, for example, draws money from its gushing oil, forgoing
both an income and a sales tax. Wyoming has no income tax and
Montana has no sales tax, but both tax the extraction of coal from
the ground.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire doesn't have oil or coal or other minerals to
enrich its coffers. Instead, the Granite State has used a patchwork
approach to raising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The result, Schena says, is that every time she turns around it
seems like she has to pay another tax. For example, she pays both a
town tax and a fee to the state to register her car. She pays a
gasoline tax at the pump, and her husband pays a tax when he buys
his cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The state adds a communications tax on every telephone bill.
Many highways have tolls.
</P>
<P>
   To go hunting or fishing requires a license from the state,
which costs money. To visit a park there's another fee. Staying in
a hotel or eating at a restaurant means an 8 percent state tax.
</P>
<P>
   The state also collects money from people who save and invest.
Stock dividends and interest are taxed at a 5 percent rate. All
insurance policies are slapped with a 2 percent premium tax.
Inheritances face an unusually high 18 percent estate and legacy
tax, though there is an exemption for lineal descendants.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses have their own set of taxes to pay. There is the
business-profits tax and the business enterprise tax. And companies
that want to sell securities in New Hampshire must pay a securities
tax.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the system has stood the test of time. Doug Scamman, the
former Republican speaker of the House, said the Legislature has
long looked for the least disruptive method of raising money. That
has resulted, he said, in a mix of smaller taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``New Hampshire is rated amongst the top places to live,'' he
said. ``Part of it is the social ramifications of our tax policy.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just a public policy, but a mentality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I think the public prefers to be nickel-and-dimed
because you don't pay it out all at once,'' said William Pound, the
executive director of the National Conference of State
Legislatures. ``There's a psychology to it that makes it easier
sometimes to accept.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, New Hampshire's approach has had its advantages. Because
the state is long and narrow and borders Massachusetts, Vermont and
Maine, Scamman said the lack of a sales tax is a boon to retailers.
The system of many small levies also makes it more difficult to
raise tax rates.
</P>
<P>
   But the education funding crisis means that taxes, whatever
their form, now must go up. Schena, who used to live in Everett,
says she understands there's no such thing as living tax-free.
Still, she's feeling mighty miffed these days, especially since her
children are grown and out of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we moved from Massachusetts is because the taxes
were too high,'' she explained. ``They used to call it
Taxachusetts, and everyone ran over the state line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where do we go from here?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
