 &HT;    The Cox News Service spot news budget for Wednesday, April 14,
1999.
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TROOPS _ WASHINGTON _ The U.S. last assessed the
requirements of a ground presence months ago and Pentagon officials
say they haven't been asked to update that proposal, even as a
contingency. Given that the political and military dynamic in
Yugoslavia has changed immeasurably since NATO bombs began falling,
is that original plan still relavant, and if not how long would it
take to develop a new one? Has the question of whether U.S. troops
could reach the Balkan pennisula quickly enough to be effective
already been answered? Developing. (Montgomery, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TEXAS _ WASHINGTON _ What members of the Texas
congressional delegation are saying about the possibility of ground
combat troops in Kosovo. (Malone/Moscoso, Cox News Service). 20.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REFUGEES _ TIRANA, Albania _ Staggering toward the
Albanian border, the rag-tag refugee convoy was stopped near the
town of Dakovica by soldiers, who picked out an attractive young
woman, asked her age then ordered her to come with them. Terrified,
she ran and was shot dead, according to eyewitnesses who described
their horrifying encounter in a region where the Pentagon says Serb
forces may be systematically raping women in an army camp where as
many as 20 women are believed to have been killed. Developing.
(Albright-Kunstel, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON/POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-CABLE _ WASHINGTON _ Steve Case, chairman of America
Online, and telecom executives including James Robbins, president
of Cox Communications, testify at a Senate Commerce Committee
hearing Tuesday on whether Internet companies should have access to
high-speed cable networks. (Regan, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE _ WASHINGTON _ Adding prescriptions drugs to Medicare
would increase the program's cost by about 7 to 13 percent over 10
years, according to a study released Tuesday by the non-partisan
National Academy of Social Insurance. (Lipman, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MONEYREFORM _ Campaign finance reform advocates kick off a drive
Tuesday to pass reform legislation amid optimism that Republican
opposition to the measure will buckle this year. But reformers are
also divided over how to make a deal with the GOP, with many
Democrats ready to increase federal contribution limits in exchange
for a ban on soft money. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   GINGRICH _ The ``new'' Newt Gingrich returns to Washington
tonight for a high-profile fundraiser for his new PAC. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   SOFTWARE-FUTURE _ CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ Microsoft Chairman Bill
Gates lectures on ``The Future of Software'' as part of the MIT
Laboratory for Computer Science's 35th birthday celebration.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   OHIO-TORNADOAID _ Federal Emergency Management Agency officials
tour tornado damage in Warren, Hamilton counties. Expect some
announcement of disaster aid, services available. Update on Warren
Co. hotline for storm victims. (Rouse, Dayton Daily News). 10.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-CLINTON _ BOCA RATON, Fla. _ The First Lady is in town
for a $1,000-a-plate fund-raiser and to attend a Holocaust
memorial. (Crowley, P{alm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   BAMA-LOTTERY _ Alabama Senate votes on establishing a state
lottery. (MWilliams, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   LEADERSHIP-AWARD _ The University of Dayton and its National
Alumni Association announce an annual ``Leadership with Virtue''
award that they envision being national, perhaps international, in
scope _ sort of the Miami Valley's Nobel Prize. The award has been
in the works for 18 months, but UD folks acknowledge the Washington
scandals of the last year has added a sense of urgency and validity
to their efforts. W/glancebox of the seven virtuous characteristics
they're looking for. (Fisher, Dayton Daily News). 10-12.
</P>
<P>
   MADALYN-OHAIR _ On March 24, when Texas investigators knocked on
the door of seven-time felon Gary P. Karr, they already suspected
him as an accessory in the 1995 disappearance of atheist Madalyn
O'Hair and her family. Karr, it appears, didn't disappoint them.
Investigators had no warrants, yet an FBI agent later testified
that Karr invited them into his apartment in Novi, Mich., sat
voluntarily for 13 hours and admitted to concealing bodies, hiding
victims' property, acquiring vehicles and playing a key role in
transferring $600,000 to a San Antonio gold coin dealer.
(Copelin/Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BUDGET INFORMATION FOR SUBSCRIBERS OF THE NYT NEWS
SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Spot news budgets move daily at 2 p.m. and 6 p.m. Eastern.
Additionally, separate features and commentary budgets move at 10
a.m., and sports and business budgets at 6 p.m. Additional updates
are possible if news developments warrant.
</P>
<P>
   All times are Eastern unless otherwise noted. If stories will
move after 8 p.m., an ETA will be given.
</P>
