<P>
   &UR; FOR WEDNESDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Wednesday, April 14:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KOSOVO &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO's top commander, Gen. Wesley Clark
holds a detailed news conference on operations Kosovo and the rest
of Yugoslavia. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILITARY (Brussels) _ A military analysis on contingency
planning in NATO's Yugoslav campaign. By Michael R. Gordon..
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ A look at the impact of moving
300 more U.S. warplanes to the Yugoslav arena, plus the day's
military events. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COST (Washington) _ The Defense Deptartment asks Congress
for an emergency appropriation of about $3 billion to cover the
fight against Yugoslavia, and another $200 million for the refugee
aid. By Elizabeth Becker. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   KOVOSO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ Congressional leaders seek to
hold back congressional comment on the war while seeking a
consensus. President Clinton, seeking to keep things smooth, meets
with 60 or more members of Congress from both parties today over
Kosovo and gives a talk afterward. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Oslo, Norway) _ The U.S. and Russia fail to settle
their differences over NATO's bombing campaign in Yugoslavia after
what Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright calls ``an honest
discussion'' with Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INCURSION (Dateline to kum, Albania) _ Serb infantry
troops cross into Albania, exchange fire with Albanian border
police and seize control of a border village. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ Developments from the Yugoslav
capital. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   We are considering, among others, stories on reports of
systematic plundering by Serb paramilitary forces and activity at
the international war crimes tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (New York) _ The Chinese prime minister, Zhu Rongji,
tours New York. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-REACT (New York) _ Protests and other
Chinese-American reaction to Zhu's visit. By Vivian S. Toy.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (London) _ Sinn Fein tells peace talks in Belfast
that it is rejecting a proposal put forward by the British and
Irish governments to resolve the impasse on guerrilla disarmament
that is blocking the formation of a new government in Northern
Ireland. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   VATICAN-JEWS (Rome) _ A giant bronze menorah being put up at the
American seminary in Rome to commemorate the Holocaust. The
seminary is technically part of Vatican City, so it would be the
first permanent Holocaust memorial inside the Vatican. But the
sponsorship of the project, Jews from New Jersey and U.S. cardinals
who deal with interfaith issues, also underlines recent strains
between the Vatican and major Jewish organizations. By Alessandra
Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAXES (Washington) _ The Clintons and the Gores are to
release their tax returns. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   CENSUS (Washington) _ William M. Daley, the commerce secretary,
is to announce developments on the census. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-CONTEMPT (Washington) _ Folo on Monday's contempt
finding against the president by the federal judge presiding over
the Paula Jones civil suit. By John M. Broder.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-SENTENCE (Detroit) _ Following his conviction on
murder charges, Dr. Jack Kevorkian, the assisted suicide advocate,
is to be sentenced today. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   PRIESTS (Undated) _ The number of seminarians, Roman Catholics
studying to be priests, jumped 7 percent last year, the biggest
jump in years. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   LYNX-RETURN (Denver) _ A fourth Canada lynx reintroduced into
the Rio Grande National Forest has apparently starved to death.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At midday, the industrial average was up 44
points, or 0.4 percent, and the Nasdaq index was up 29 points, or
1.1 percent. Elsewhere, prices rose 1.3 percent in Tokyo and 1.3
percent in Hong Kong. They gained 0.8 percent in Frankfurt, half a
percent in London, 0.2 percent in Brazil and 1.5 percent in Mexico.
On the American debt market, the long bond was down 12/32 point. By
Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   With a separate.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT (New York) _ Credit market developments. By Robert
Hurtado.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Intel will report quarterly earnings
after the close. The consensus estimate is 55 cents a share, and
the ``whisper number'' is and 1 or 2 cents above that. By Lawrence
M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BROKER-EARNINGS (New York) _ Aided by gains in trading revenue,
Merrill Lynch's earnings grew 18 percent in the first quarter and
Paine Webber's 33 percent. Shares of other brokerage firms, notably
discount and on-line operations, rise sharply. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO-GEOTEL (Undated) _ Cisco Systems buys Geotel
Communications for $2 billion and says the purchase will help it
deliver voice communications over the Internet. Cisco is paying a
37 percent premium. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   TOYOTA-APPOINT (Tokyo) _ Toyota names Fujio Cho as its new
president. He succeeds Hiroshi Okuda, who will become chairman. The
new president has ties to the founding Toyoda family and enjoys
widespread popularity at the company and among its vast web of
suppliers. He is thus well-positioned to smooth the feathers Okuda
ruffled. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   LEARCH-LEXICON (Undated) _ One of the country's most successful
plaintiffs' lawyers, William Lerach, and his firm have been ordered
by a Chicago jury to pay $45 million in damages to one of their old
targets. Lerach and his firm, Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach,
have won millions suing companies for securities fraud and other
alleged misdeeds. But a jury found that they had severely damaged
the business of a Chicago legal and economics consulting firm,
Lexecon Inc. The jury is considering punitive damages today. By
Melody Petersen.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Motorola will report quarterly
earnings after the close. The consensus estimate is 24 cents a
share. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The column: Best Western is
continuing to expand globally, and while it is still heavily
patronized by leisure travelers, its share of business travelers
has been inching up; when normal air service resumes to cities in
and around Yugoslavia, Austrian Airlines will offer bargain fares
from Kennedy Airport; other items. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   KVAERNER-SHIPS (Franfurt, Germany) _ Kvaerner, Europe's biggest
shipbuilder, will exit the business and cut 25,000 workers in an
effort to reduce its debt by about $1 billion. It is unclear how
many of the 25,000 employees _ one-third of the labor force _ will
be laid off and how many would keep their jobs if assets are bought
by other companies. Kvaerner's shipbuilding profit has been hurt by
cost overruns at its yard in Finland, tough competition from Asia
and overcapacity in the industry. By Edmund L. Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-NEWBRIDGE (Tokyo) _ An agreement by the South Korean
Government to sell the ailing Korea First Bank to a consortium led
by Newbridge Capital, a private equity fund backed by the investors
Richard Blum and David Bonderman, has foundered over a disagreement
on how to value the bank's assets. By Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ECON (Moscow) _ The latest economic data in Russia have
bred some optimism. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   REALNETWORKS-XING (Undated) _ Realnetworks acquires Xing
Technology for as much as $75 million in stock, expanding its role
in the online-music market.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY &LR;  (``k'' code)
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Dowd's ``Liberties.''
</P>
