<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ADVENTURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSAL'S NEW THEME PARK PROMISES A WILD TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Was I really going to do this?
</P>
<P>
   Was I, at the advanced age of 58, going to allow myself to be
strapped in and then sent hurling and whirling on one of the
world's newest, fastest, and high-tech roller coasters?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, I was. And it was all in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   I was at Universal Studios' Islands of Adventure, a 110-acre,
$2.7 billion theme park that officially opens next month. People
who buy certain combination tickets can now visit, but when I went
in mid-March, the park was open only to employees and the
occasional newsman who never grew up.
</P>
<P>
   The ride that my reporting duty beckoned me to is named the
Incredible Hulk Coaster, after that great, green, gruesome,
superhero of TV and comic-book fame. As I shakily climbed into my
seat, I looked around. I was next to two strapping fellows in their
20s. Behind me and in front of me was a sea of teenagers. All
appeared eager to join in the pretense that we were about to be
shot out of a gamma ray booster.
</P>
<P>
   For me, it didn't take much pretending. Soon after the ride
began, we were blasted from zero to 40 m.p.h. in just two seconds,
with the same thrust as an Air Force fighter-attack jet. Then came
the loops and rolls: I saw the sky. I saw the ground. I went
weightless. I went upside-down. I went sideways. I almost lost my
eyeglasses. I almost lost my lunch. After two minutes and 15
seconds (or was it an eternity?), the ride was over and I literally
staggered off while my fellow passengers shouted things like
``Wow!'', ``Now that's fast!'' and ``That was the coolest! Let's go
on again!''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was just as well that I didn't learn until later that
our first complete loop had begun 100 feet from the ground. I
further learned that at night the metal coaster track glows green _
the approximate color of my face right about then. In all, we 32
passengers experienced seven rollovers and plunged into two deep
subterranean enclosures. When I calmed down, I actually took pride
in my accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios likewise is taking pride in its
accomplishment: creating what it proclaims to be the world's most
technologically advanced theme park. Islands of Adventure, in fact,
is a crucial part of a new 840-acre resort complex called Universal
Studios Escape. The other sections are the highly popular Universal
Studios Florida theme park and movie studio, and a new
shopping-dining-entertainment district called CityWalk. All are
within walking distance of the other, and boat shuttles will also
be available. Later this year, the first of the resort's hotels,
Portofino Bay, will open.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Islands of Adventure that will be generating most of
the talk. With the idea of offering something for all ages and
interests, the park consists of five themed islands surrounded by a
lake. Those islands are Seuss Landing, the Lost Continent, Jurassic
Park, Toon Lagoon, and Marvel Super Hero Island, where that Hulk
Coaster looms. There is also an architecturally wild Port of Entry,
where you can get oriented to the attractions, souvenir shops, and
eateries that dot the park.
</P>
<P>
   When I visited Islands of Adventure, the smell of paint was
fresh and the clang of construction was audible. Several key rides
were still being tweaked so I didn't get to go on them. Nor did I
get to watch the live-action shows that will be part of the park.
But I saw enough to opine that if people have the time and money
for yet another Central Florida attraction a few miles from Walt
Disney World, if everything works as it's supposed to, and if the
wait lines for the attractions are tolerable, Universal could have
a hulking hit on its hands. So watch your tail, Mickey Mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of the islands:
</P>
<P>
   Seuss Landing. This one's primarily for the kiddies, but anyone
should get a kick out of the ultra-vibrant colors, music, and
whimsy that bring to life the famous books of Theodor ``Dr. Seuss''
Geisel. If your children aren't familiar with the Seuss books, do
read them to the youngsters before you visit.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively gentle rides include the Cat in the Hat, which
takes riders through the pages of that classic book; the
Caro-Seuss-el, with a marvelous array of Seuss characters to ride
upon; and One Fish Two Fish Red Fish Blue Fish, where you might get
squirted if you don't follow instructions. There are also
interactive play areas such as If I Ran the Zoo and a Green Eggs
and Ham Cafe where, yes, you can have green eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Toon Lagoon. Here, two-dimensional comics characters get a third
dimension, and although some of them might seem some distance from
the cutting edge of comicdom _ Popeye and Beetle Bailey come to
mind _ the lagoon seems like fun. Dudley Do-Right's Ripsaw Falls is
a flume ride involving a 40,000-gallon lagoon, a drop through the
roof of a dynamite shack, and a dive 15 feet below water level.
Popeye &AMP; Bluto's Bilge-Rat Barges is a twisting, turning
white-water raft ride with a top speed of 16 feet per second. A
giant octopus and water cannons are also part of it, so count on
getting wet.
</P>
<P>
   Toon Lagoon also has interactive play areas and a Comic Strip
Lane inhabited by the likes of Hagar the Horrible and Krazy Kat _
80 ``classic'' characters in all. You can sate your appetite at
such places as Cathy's Ice Cream Parlor and a sandwich shop called
Blondie's Home of the Dagwood, with one humongous make-believe
sandwich sprouting from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   Marvel's Super Hero Island. The Incredible Hulk Coaster is only
one of three thrill rides on this island. I just missed visiting
the Amazing Adventures of Spiderman before it was closed for the
day for fine-tuning. Boo-hoo: I wish I could have experienced the
mixture of moving ride vehicles, a 3-D film, and special effects.
The attraction has been compared to Universal Studios Florida's
``Back to the Future: The Ride'' but without the jolting and
shaking and with even more effects. Be forewarned, though: One
feature is a ``sensory drop'' 400 feet into darkness.
</P>
<P>
   Emboldened by my Hulk adventure, I did go on Doctor Doom's
Fearfall, which consists of two 200-foot towers of steel. Zoom _
with feet dangling, I was fired to the top at breathtaking speed.
But the ride wasn't operating at full speed yet and the return to
the bottom was nowhere as fast as it's going to be. (I was kind of
glad about that.)
</P>
<P>
   Jurassic Park. Almost everybody loves dinosaurs, and these
fluidly moving animatronic creatures may be the next best thing to
a living, breathing dino. They will respond to visitors by blinking
their eyes, flinching at their touch, and, in the case of the
spitters, spurting water on unsuspecting guests.
</P>
<P>
   The Jurassic Park River Adventure takes you to the
dinosaur-infested park of book and movie fame. (A similar ride is a
hit at Universal Studios Hollywood). Watch out for Tyrannosaurus
Rex . . . and the 85-foot-plunge down what Universal maintains is
the longest, fastest, steepest water descent ever built.
</P>
<P>
   At Triceratops Encounter, you can actually pet a dino.
Pteranodon Flyers, a relatively mild ride, lets you glide through
the air on the back of one of these flying creatures, providing a
good view of the lush, tropical island. And after the ride, you can
walk in dinosaur footprints, which _ surprise! _ set off a roar.
The island also has an interactive Discovery Center where, among
other things, you can watch a raptor being hatched, and a Camp
Jurassic, where those spitters lurk and where caves and quarries
hold long-ago secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The Lost Continent. Are you ready for even more adventures? Then
welcome to the Lost Continent, perhaps the most visually stunning
of the islands, with its mountains and forests and dragons and
mythical gods.
</P>
<P>
   Poseidon's Fury is a multimedia presentation that puts travelers
in a battle between Poseidon (the water guy) and his archenemy Zeus
(the fire man). ``Weapons'' include more than 350,000 gallons of
water and 200 flame effects, not the least of them being exploding
25-foot fireballs.
</P>
<P>
   The Eighth Voyage of Sinbad is a stunt show featuring six water
explosions and 50 pyrotechnical effects, among them a 10-foot-tall
circle of flames.
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the Dueling Dragons attraction, which even some
hardened roller-coaster riders called speedy and scary. The ride
has two intertwined tracks that speed guests over, under, and
around one another. From the top of a 125-foot lift, the Fire
Dragon drops to the left, reaching 60 m.p.h. The Ice Dragon goes to
the right, hitting 55 m.p.h. Riders' legs dangle as they experience
five inversions and three near misses with riders on the opposite
track. At times, the tracks and their passengers are a scant 12
inches apart.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds frightening, but hey, I had conquered the Hulk Coaster.
So I made my way to the ride up a cavernous, winding path, shaped
like a ruined castle and decorated with skeletons and such. I soon
reached the area where you choose which side you want to ride.
``Fire or Ice?'' asked the ride hostess.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exit,'' I replied. The heck with the line of duty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
