<HEADLINE>
`TOMMY' MARKS A GENERATION'S SPIRIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's deaf, dumb, and blind, but he sure plays a mean pinball.
He's a sensation. And he wants you to see him, feel him, and touch
him. One more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Who's Tommy'' _ the rock opera by the Who's Pete
Townshend, first released as a double-album in 1969, made into a
garish Ken Russell movie in 1975, whipped into a $3.5 million
bells-and-whistles, Tony-winning Broadway hit musical in 1993 _
lives again.
</P>
<P>
   This thing has legs. You wonder: Is ``The Who's Tommy'' our
generation's ``Oklahoma!''?
</P>
<P>
   Scot Woolley, the play's musical director and one of the
keyboardists, has a laugh and says, ``I think it definitely a piece
that's representative of a generation, the generation that was
around for the upheavel of the '60s, and there are so many of them,
just by the nature of numbers. It kind of defines the generation in
their searching for answers to questions they maybe posed too young
in their lives. Musically, it is strong and lyrically Pete hit
something. It's not a dated work either. Although it's rock 'n'
roll chord progressions indicative of the British rock of the late
'60s, it doesn't scream'' that it's rooted in that era ``like, say,
the Beach Boys `Good Vibrations.'''
</P>
<P>
   The main difference between this ``Tommy'' and earlier
productions, say Woolley and Michael Seelbach (who plays the lead
role), is that it's tilted more toward a rock 'n' roll experience
and less toward a theatrical one. ``We've stripped it down and
taken away any `numbing' aspect, of people watching things fly
in,'' says Woolley, ``and keep you distracted from the story.'' The
staging includes steel tubing, multi-level risers and screens that
drop down for slide projections. Its actors dress uniformly in
black. The music, say Woolley and Seelbach, rocks. There are seven
musician and 18 singers. The emphasis is on the musical journey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great journey,'' says Seelbach, who is 21. ``Every
night it's about going through difficult times in your life, taking
responsability and forgiving peopele. It's about getting to look
out at the audience and sing right to them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of the musical, Tommy goes from being a severely
disabled, scorned and abused kid to a virtual messiah. The plot
line has always been a somewhat muddled, though when it went to
Broadway Townshend did some rewriting. This includes an ending that
does not focus on Tommy's downfall, but on group bonding. It's
happier now.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have perceived it to be that,'' says Woolley, 41. ``I
never understood `Tommy' as a kid and never made it all the way
through the movie. But for the finale song, I remember hearing
`Listening to you, I gather music . . . ' and in our production
it's kind of an everyman ending. What Tommy represents is: He's one
person who was done great disservices and he offers you an
opportunity for forgiveness, an opportunity to start over and that
involves the audience. He takes the high road by offering an olive
branch. There are so many religious overtones with this piece. It
does become spritutal, it feels good.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who tackles the role of Tommy follows in the
Who's Roger Daltrey's footsteps. Is this daunting?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, sure,'' says Seelbach, who played the role three years
ago on the road for a year. ``I certainly wouldn't compare myself
to Roger Daltrey, but other people went ahead of me (in this role)
luckily. I didn't go back and re-listen (to the Who's version). I
had seen the Broadway show, but I didn't go back and listen until I
was set in this, so I didn't get too much in my head what other
people have done.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This production,'' Seelbach continues, ``is very minimalist,
with rock 'n' roll set rigging, not much for set or costume
changes. It's fully staged, but it's more like a concert. The
director wanted people not to be wowed by the set. The Broadway set
was out of this world, but he wanted people to listen to it''
without distraction.
</P>
<P>
   Woolley says his aim for ``Tommy'' was the same as any musical
he's worked with: ``To find _ and this is gonna sound
artsty-fartsty _ but to find the essence of the truth in the song,
find the clarity that informs the muscial choices.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolley is asked to pick a song from ``Tommy'' and describe what
he tells the musicians and singers. He chooses ``Sensation,'' and
says it's about ``the feelings of someone who ultimately is a good
person and how that how fame can sway one's real meaning about what
they want to do with their lives. It's like Jim and Tammy Faye
Bakker started out with good intentions. `Sensation' is the first
moment where he feels something he's good at, playing pinball, and
is held up as an icon. Given the sycophantic nature of humans, we
get behind people who represent well, whatever. There's this mob
mentality, where people gravitate to him, where, just moments
before this'' he's being abused in ``Cousin Kevin.'' ``Sensation''
``is pivotal in Pete Townshend's view of fame and mankind's ability
to make you unfamous in a moment, which we see in pop music all the
time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The show at times is very dark,'' says Seelbach, ``but the way
it ends up, especiall in this production, he's hugging everyone
who's done him wrong, recognizing them and bringing them back into
his life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
