<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6218 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-WHITESOX-BOS &LR;      04-13 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITESOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOMAS HAS BAT, WON'T TRAVEL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It seems to happen every spring. Summer, fall, and
winter, too. Some lucky major league team is supposed to be the
beneficiary of a blockbuster trade with the White Sox for Frank
Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not going to happen unless somebody overwhelms the
White Sox, who are committed to the nine-year veteran who just
happens to be one of the best power hitters in baseball. He is the
centerpiece of the South Siders' ``The Kids Can Play'' campaign, as
Chicago, after a five-year quest to overtake Cleveland in the
American League Central with veteran talent, has gone on a youth
movement. Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Thomas is only 30 years old and as light on his feet
as any of his teammates, who average 26.2 years. Still, no one
would have blamed the White Sox had they moved him along after
losing Albert Belle and Robin Ventura in free agency over the
winter. But after listening to offers from several clubs, including
the Red Sox, general manager Ron Schueler decided Thomas was more
valuable to them than anyone he would bring in trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just see a rejuvenated Frank,'' said Schueler. ``He knows
what direction we are going. It's true Boston showed some interest,
starting prior to our winter meetings. But basically, we tried to
see if there was a fit and there wasn't. We just felt that in the
past year they've traded away many of the prospects that we really
like. And for what Frank meant to our organization and the kids,
there wasn't enough there for the White Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   His average dropped to .265 last year, but Thomas still had 29
home runs and 109 RBIs for the White Sox, who have finished second
in the AL Central for the last three years. He is a relative
bargain, accounting for only $7 million (plus incentives) of a $24
million payroll. His contract extension, signed in 1996, runs until
2006. Thomas says he wants to stay in Chicago and become a 10-5 man
next year. But first things first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back to basics and be the player I've always
been,'' said Thomas. ``That's my job. That's important to me. I
just have to be patient and be the same hitter I've always been.
I'm looking forward to being on this team and playing day in and
day out.''
</P>
<P>
   On the day of the home opener, Thomas was mobbed by the Chicago
media, largely because he was one of few recognizable faces on the
team. Ray Durham was the other big name. Outfielder Darrin Jackson,
who has played for both Chicago teams, also was no stranger. But
there were plenty of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's refreshing to see these young guys,'' said Thomas.
``They're not here just to be here. We're all here to compete and
play to a major league level. The expectations aren't the same. The
last two years we were expected to finish either first or second in
the division. But I think this team will surprise a lot of people.
So far, we fit in very well. We have a very good chemistry in the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Trade rumors have followed Thomas since he came up in 1990. Most
clubs admired his enormous build and slugging capability and
ignored his poor fielding. Thomas was a designated hitter in 146
games last year and played first base only 14 times. Manager Jerry
Manuel thinks he'll use Thomas in the field 50-60 games this year.
</P>
<P>
   But things in general are better. His feud with umpires over the
inside strike is over. So, too, are personal problems that affected
his mood from time to time.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas says he is happy about remaining in Chicago for one good
reason. Trades don't win pennants; players do. For two years he had
Belle as a teammate, and many expected the best 1-2 punch in
baseball to make history. But Belle suffered through the first
season while Thomas hit .347. Last year, Thomas had what he
considered a poor year, while Belle hit .328 with 49 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players set standards,'' said Thomas. ``Last year I didn't
live up to the standards that I have had the last seven years. And
that's mostly regarding my batting average. The power numbers were
there, although I did have fewer home runs. Bottom line is that I
drove in 109 runs last year. I can't be disappointed over that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trade talks don't bother me at all. It happens to all players.
I understand that players move around a little bit. I've probably
had 150 teammates. Sooner or later it's going to happen to me. I
understand that. I'd love to finish my career in Chicago. If I
start something, I'd like to finish it.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel has concerns other than Thomas. His young team opened the
year with two victories but then lost four straight. Pitching and
defense are the current evils. In a weekend sweep, the White Sox
lost to Kansas City by scores of 10-5, 9-4, and 3-1. Makes you
wonder whether a rotation of James Baldwin, Mike Sirotka, Jim
Parque, John Snyder, and Jaime Navarro has the stuff to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is doing his part, though. He is 12 for 19 (.632) with
two homers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best I've seen Frank swing the bat since I've been
here,'' said Manuel. ``Our offense has never been a problem. But
our young hitters are facing veteran pitching, some for the first
time, and it makes a difference.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas says it's nice to be looked upon as a role model and even
a hero. He is not a one-dimensional person, with more civic
commitments than even Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't feel 30,'' said Thomas. ``I feel more like I'm
25. I'm not making a resurgence. I feel like I'm definitely
playing. I'm not going anywhere. I'll be here. I'm looking forward
to a good season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
