<HEADER>
A6220 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-MARATH-KELLEY-ART     04-13 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATH-KELLEY-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNNY KELLEY (91) WILL SIT THIS ONE OUT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARWICH, Mass. _ You had to hear the voice to know Johnny Kelley
is okay.
</P>
<P>
   He looks terrific, resplendent in a blue 1999 Marathon jacket
over his white turtleneck. His eyes still have the Kelley twinkle,
and at 91 he looks and speaks strong as ever.
</P>
<P>
   But when the song swells out of him like the spring sunshine on
a Cape Cod morning -- with Kelley nailing every word and every note
of his trademark, ``Young at Heart'' -- you know that despite his
weekend decision to skip this year's marathon, he means it when he
says adamantly:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there in 2000 and hopefully I'll be myself long before
then.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelley made his decision not to appear this year's race as Grand
Marshal to avoid risking a reoccurrence of the pneumonia he
suffered following abdominal surgery last winter. Thus, after 63
years that have made Johnny ``The Elder'' Kelley a fixture and the
very symbol of the Boston Marathon, this year he says: ``I will be
there in spirit. I wish all the runners good luck.''
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 26, Kelley underwent surgery at Cape Cod Hospital to
repair a perforated colon. The operation, described as major by his
doctors, was declared a complete success. But Kelley's road to
recovery was set back when he contracted pneumonia, and he spent
the month of February recuperating.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1st he was released to Cranberry Pointe Rehabilitation
Center in Harwich, where he is making daily progress. From the bed
to a wheelchair last week and, by last weekend, he was walking with
a cane and looking forward to getting outside and moving his body
again.
</P>
<P>
   His overall health, despite the pneumonia, he says is excellent,
adding that a life of running has given him a strong heart. ``My
doctor tells me my heart is stronger than 99 percent of his
patients,'' says Kelley, who thumps his chest with his thumb as
reaches the line in his song, ``and if you can survive to
one-hundred and five . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Born on Sept. 6, 1907, John Adelbert Kelley, the oldest of 10
kids who grew up in West Medford, won his first Boston Marathon in
1935 after he finally learned to pace himself and not burn all his
energy in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Though he would go on to win another Marathon 10 years later and
finish as runnerup another seven times, along with three Olympic
appearances, to Kelley that first win was still the sweetest.
Ironically, it was a bottle of sugar pills that nearly cost him the
race.
</P>
<P>
   April 19, 1935 was Good Friday, and some 300,000 spectators _ a
relatively small crowd _ turned out in the ideal running weather as
Kelley took on national marathon champion ``Pat'' Frank Dengis from
Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley was running with two talismen given him by well-wishers _
a handkerchief from his aunt and a bottle of 15 chocolate glucose
tablets, wihch he popped throughout the race, hoping to gain energy
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   According to race accounts, Kelley, who had lost previous races
by burning out in the late going, paced himself and ran third most
of the way. Dengis ran even more conservatively, staying behind
Kelley until Wellesley, when the toolmaker who had fashioned his
own bronze championship meda,l blew past Kelley only to suffer a
sudden stitch that felt like ``a knife in the heart,'' forcing him
to stop short.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kelley streaked into the lead, his win was far from
assured. At Kenmore Square he had to stop and vomit up all the
glucose pills he had been chomping. Meanwhile, Dengis was over his
stitch and coming on at a gallop again, though he never seriously
threatened Kelley's two-minute winning margin. The time: 2:32:07.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later, Kelley won his second Boston in 2:30:40 _ the
fastest time in the world that year _ and, at 37, Kelley was making
jokes about his impending 40th birthday. ``They say life begins at
40,'' Kelley told a Globe reporter after his second win, ``and I
have three years before I get there.''
</P>
<P>
   With the appearance in the '50s of John J. Kelley, also
representing the Boston Athletic Association and the Boston winner
in 1957, John A. Kelley picked up the ``Johnny The Elder''
appellation, while John J. was of course ``Johnny The Younger.''
With The Elder becoming a symbol of longevity and The Younger
threatening to win several years into the 1960s, the two Kelleys
had become a famous mainstay of the world's most famous footrace.
</P>
<P>
   Long after The Younger stopped running Boston regularly, The
Elder was still hanging in, running every April for the next three
decades until 1992, when he announced _ at age 85 _ that he had run
his last full marathon. But even then, for another two years Kelley
ran the final seven miles, starting at his own landmark statue at
the beginning of the Heartbreak Hills.
</P>
<P>
   From 1995 to 1998 Kelley ran no more but rode in a convertible
at the head of the race as grand marshal, a position he would have
held this year and plans to resume in the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The long scoresheet of his life of running, beginning when shoes
were sneaker thin, covers eight decades _ so far. He holds New
England championships at every distance from three miles and up.
Nationally, he was champion 11 times in four events, including the
marathon in 1948 and 1950. He was 1937 and 1954 national champion
in 15,000-meters, and in 1943 and 1954 won the 20,000-meter crown.
He won the 25,000-meter national title five times, and made the
Olympic team in 1936, 1940, and 1948. At age 44, he narrowly missed
making it to the 1952 games.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley became the first road runner ever elected to the National
Track and Field Hall of Fame, whose officials had to waive the
retirement rules because, they reasoned, here was a runner who
might never retire.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley recalls that he wanted to be a baseball player, but was
not good enough to play seriously. When he was 12, his father took
him to see his first Boston Marathon finish, and when the top
runners _ Peter Trivoulidas, Arthur Roth, and Carl Linder _ came
sprinting through the finish to cheering throngs, Kelley remembers
he ``fell in love with it then.''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, even elite runners had to train on their own
time, and Kelley would work days for Boston Edison while training
evenings. His favorite spots were the Middlesex Woods and the
Medford Fells, running on dirt roads. ``It was a paradise running
in those places then,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Much has changed over eight decades _ including the explosion of
women's running and race sponsorship such as Boston benefactor John
Hancock _ but Kelley doesn't pine for the old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's better now,'' he says, ``much better. We have a lot of
wonderful girl runners. They're better than the boys, and more
honest (he chuckles). For them to run two hours and a half is just
amazing. I don't know how they do it.''
</P>
<P>
   And to another Boston Marathon icon who returns this year,
Kelley sends some heartfelt greetings from the Cape where he plans
to watch the race ``on telley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish Bill (Rodgers) all the luck because he's a very good
friend of mine and a great athlete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
