<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIMING FOR A NEW IMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Little Bear stories, written by Else Holmelund Minarik, are
beloved children's classics. So it is certainly a great occasion
when a new tale arrives. You can imagine how pleased I was, as a
father of two, to receive one of the very first copies of an old
favorite, ``Mother Bear's Robin'' _ revised by a consortium of gun
manufacturers and firearms trade groups.
</P>
<P>
   The gun industry, as you may have heard, finds itself cornered
by declining sales and a flurry of lawsuits. At least five cities
have sued gun makers for negligence in manufacturing and marketing
handguns. At the same time, Americans are beginning to realize they
don't need to add much more to the nation's current personal
arsenal of 230 million guns. So sales are stagnant.
</P>
<P>
   In response, the gun industry is attempting to diversify and to
soften its image. Now you can buy Smith &AMP; Wesson bicycles, Colt
clothing and stuffed animals, and Sturm Ruger golf club heads. The
remaking of the image is backed by new ad campaigns from the
National Shooting Sports Foundation and the National Rifle
Association. The foundation's ads stress safe handling of guns and
the popularity of shooting sports like hunting. As an ad executive
told the Wall Street Journal, the campaign is intended to educate
people about part of America's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The new Little Bear episode was delivered to my door by a child
armed with an M16 rifle claiming to be Little Red Riding Hood on
her way to grandmother's house in search of a wolf. Here's the
tale, ``Mother Bear's Robin,'' in its revised form, intended to
convey a wholesome view of America's gun heritage:
</P>
<P>
   One spring day, when Mother Bear was little, she found a baby
robin in the garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh how sweet you are,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She took the robin in the house, and made a little home for it.
The robin ate. It grew. It sang. Soon it could fly.
</P>
<P>
   But one day it was unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sing a song,'' said Mother Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot,'' said the robin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly about the house,'' said Mother Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot,'' said the robin.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Bear's eyes filled with tears. She took the robin out
into the garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love you, little robin,'' she said. ``But I want you to be
happy. Fly away, if you wish. You are free.''
</P>
<P>
   The robin flew, far up into the blue sky. It sang a high, sweet
song. Then down it came again, right down to Mother Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must fly out into the world,'' said the robin. ``But I will
come back. Every year I will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And it came back, Mother Bear, didn't it?'' said Little Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh no,'' said Mother Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``No?'' said Little Bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Mother Bear.
</P>
<P>
   The robin flew up into the air. It was happy. It was free.
</P>
<P>
   A gunshot rang out. The robin fell out of the air. A little boy
shouted hooray. The little boy ran to the robin. The little boy's
father ran to the robin. The little boy and the father stood
proudly over the robin. The robin was dying. It heard the father
speak to the little boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our heritage, my son,'' the father said. ``It is good.
We are good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, father. I am good,'' said the little boy. ``I am a good
shot.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at levingston(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
