<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAKING THE MEASURE OF THE GREAT DIVIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The stock market has divided the world into two camps: new
economy companies and old economy companies. The gulf between them
could not be wider.
</P>
<P>
   New economy companies do technology, including the Internet. Old
economy companies do everything else. The stocks of new economy
companies command tremendous price/earnings ratios, anywhere from
70 for Microsoft to 450 for America Online. Old economy companies
have ordinary multiples in the 10 to 25 range. A higher multiple
reflects greater optimism about a company's future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   New economy companies see nothing but blue skies ahead. Their
future consists of ever-expanding opportunities and technological
breakthroughs. Old economy companies have to worry about all the
traditional problems that have always plagued businesses: interest
rates, weak overseas economies, stiff competition.
</P>
<P>
   On some level the gap reflects an underlying reality. The
technology sector is growing much faster than the economy as a
whole. Analysts expect technology giants like Dell, Cisco Systems,
and Intel to increase earnings at a 20 to 25 percent pace;
corporate earnings overall are expected to grow at about 6 percent
annually.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going through a huge historical change,'' says Allen
Sinai, chief economist at Primark Decision Economics in Waltham.
``As the rest of the world adopts American technology there are
going to be huge opportunities for these companies. The market's
intuition contains a lot of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Hock, portfolio manager of John Hancock's Growth fund, is
another ``new economy'' champion. He points out that in the fourth
quarter of 1998 US spending on technology grew at an annual rate of
21 percent. All businesses must continue to make that investment,
says Hock, if they want to improve their productivity and drive
their costs down.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. But isn't it possible to accept the basic notion that
technology is changing the world and still be skeptical about the
levels certain technology stocks have reached?
</P>
<P>
   Ned Riley certainly thinks so. Riley, chief investment officer
at BankBoston, recently did a little reality test on Microsoft and
Cisco. He assumed that the companies maintained current growth
rates for the next 20 years and that revenue grew as quickly as
earnings. By the end of the 20 years, says Riley, the two companies
would have sales equal to 22 percent of the gross domestic product
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Illusions and dreams have replaced reality around some of
these stocks,'' says Riley.
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said about many of the Internet stocks. In a
matter of months, some of the ``new economy'' companies have
achieved greater market valuations than some of their
well-established ``old economy'' competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: ETrade, an on-line brokerage, has a market value that
far exceeds that of Paine Webber, a traditional brokerage. Never
mind that ETrade didn't make any money last year while Paine Webber
earned more than $400 million. The money-losing Amazon.com, the
on-line retailer, has a greater market value than Sears, Staples,
or TJX. More remarkable still, the market value of Priceline.com,
which sells airline tickets on line, is greater than the market
value of United Airlines. The former lost $112 million last year;
the latter earned better than $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders of the Internet companies say today's lack of
significant profits is not a sign of weakness, but rather the
result of heavy spending to build up brand names.
</P>
<P>
   Do these staggering valuations make sense?
</P>
<P>
   They don't if you think that the ``new economy'' is not quite as
new as its advocates would like to believe. While technology
companies may be able to ignore certain aspects of the old economy
_ does Priceline.com have to worry about the price of oil? _ other
old-fashioned problems aren't as easy to shake.
</P>
<P>
   Like competition. Lucent Technologies and Cisco Systems are two
of the hottest firms in technology. Both stocks sell at huge
multiples to earnings. Yet every business publication is filled
with stories about how the two companies are gearing up to go head
to head in the market for telephone and data equipment. Won't one
of them have to lose? And won't the competition depress profit
margins in the industry?
</P>
<P>
   In the Internet realm, Amazon.com recently announced its
intention of going into the auction business, turf currently
dominated by another Internet success story, eBay. You might have
guessed the news would have depressed eBay's stock price. If so,
you'd have been wrong. The stock has climbed steadily and now has a
market value of $22 billion. Pretty good for a company that earned
$2 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   And what about those ``old economy'' companies? Isn't it
possible that some of them won't be content to sit on the sidelines
and watch the upstarts eat their lunch? Might not some of them jump
into the Internet world and fight successfully to protect their
market share?
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time there won't be such a bright line between the
market's winners and losers,'' says David Testa, chief investment
officer for T. Rowe Price, a mutual fund company. ``There will be
shades of success and failure. The world is more complex than the
market currently suggests it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday might have been a day to see a little bit of a shift at
work. Friday after the stock market closed Compaq Computer
announced that its first-quarter earnings would come in well short
of expectations. Compaq's stock got hammered Monday. But after an
early sell-off, most of the major technology stocks finished only
slightly down for the day. Analysts said Compaq's problems don't
necessarily spell trouble for the broader technological sector.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment at least, the two-tier stock market is alive and
well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
