<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN HISTORY CAN BE FAMILY FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Family vacations are very much in. And if you think planning one
is difficult or you have no idea what to do, think again. No matter
where you turn, the travel world is ready with ideas and to assist
you.
</P>
<P>
   A few ideas:
</P>
<P>
   Adults may love history, but most kids find it boring, unless
they take the Revolutionary Fun Package to Virginia's ``historic
triangle'' _ Colonial Williamsburg, Jamestown, and Yorktown, plus
Busch Gardens Williamsburg and Water Country USA. Here a family can
mix history, learning, and fun, all in an affordable four-day
package beginning at $663 for a family of four. Included are
accommodations and unlimited admissions to the attractions. The
area is beautiful, fascinating, and within a day's drive or less
from one-third of the country. For information, call 800-400-2851.
</P>
<P>
   For an exotic outing, consider Thomson Safaris. Rick Thomson and
Judi Wineland, who have been in the safari business for years and
have been running their own family outings worldwide, have put
together their first Thomson Family Adventures catalog to some
unique places, from Australia and The Galapagos to Nepal and
Tanzania. The trips run 10-15 days and are limited to groups of
four or five families. Most trips are planned for school vacation
periods. Thomson Safaris is in Cambridge and can be reached at
800-235-0289 or on the Web at www.ThomsonSafaris.com.
</P>
<P>
   Abercrombie &AMP; Kent, which has been offering luxurious worldwide
adventures, now has a Family Holidays package for all ages. Many of
the programs are designed for multigenerational outings. For
information, call 800-323-7308 or visit www.abercrombiekent.com.
</P>
<P>
   The University of New Hampshire offers Familyhostel, a program
that combines learning with sightseeing and is ideal for families
with children 8-15. These 10-day trips also see grandparents with
grandchildren, single parents, even three generations of families
participating. The program grew out of the university's popular
Interhostel program for adults 50 and older. Most programs are to
Europe, but new this year is one to Costa Rica, and a New England
Sampler that runs from the university campus in Durham. For a
catalog, call 800-733-9753 or visit www.learn.unh.edu.
</P>
<P>
   Outside magazine is offering a summer planner with 117
``kid-approved adventures'' such as hiking, biking, and rafting.
Included are family trips from $640 to $1,580. The magazine is on
sale at newsstands through June 2.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas for family outings, where everyone can vacation,
include cruises, Disney World, and many resorts including Club Med,
which features circus programs at some locations. The best part of
these outings is that adults can find free time while the kids do
their things.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Low-cost flights &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Is it possible to fly to Europe this summer for just $169
one-way or to the Caribbean for $199 round-trip? If you are
flexible in your travel plans, fares like these are possible. The
fares are through Air Tech, a company that locates empty seats on
planes then sells those seats to its customers. Travelers can fly
within any three-day time period they choose. Air Tech issues a
Flight Pass, which is then exchanged for a ticket an hour before
the flight. Air Tech says travelers know before going to the
airport they will get a seat, and that most easily get the
destination of their choice, especially in off-peak periods. For
other destinations Air Tech says it will locate the lowest fare,
and also offers courier flights and hotel reservations. For more
information, write to Air Tech, 588 Broadway, Suite 204, New York,
NY 10012; telephone 800-575-TECH; or visit www.airtech.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Good deals &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A midweek getaway to Iceland from just $399 a person is
available from Icelandair Holidays. The package, which begins in
May, includes two nights' accommodations and breakfasts. A single
supplement is $40. Airport taxes, about $65, are not included. For
more information, call 800-223-5500.
</P>
<P>
   The Marriott Beach Resorts of St. Thomas is extending its
``First Anniversary $99 Celebration'' through the fall. The package
marks the resort's one-year anniversary of reopening and offers
guests a $99 food and beverage credit per room on stays of five or
more nights. Room rates are $210 between June 13 and Oct. 16. For
information, call 800-524-2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel show &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An international celebration of travel, adventure, and cultural
exchange will be the focus of Hostelling International's third
annual International Travel Day April 25 at the Hynes Convention
Center in Boston. There will be hourly presentations on topics
ranging from how to travel around the world to jaunts in New
England. Exhibitors from a variety of travel-related organizations
will also be on hand to answer questions. The Travel Day will be
from 11 a.m. to 6 p.m. Admission is $5 for non-Hostelling
International members, and free to college students with IDs and
those under 18. For more information, call Annabel Snowden at
Hostelling International at 617-779-0900.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Dude ranches &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Dude Ranchers Association is offering a free copy of the
latest edition of ``The Dude Rancher'' directory filled with
information on 100-plus ranches. For a copy, write to The Dude
Ranchers' Association, PO Box 471-G, LaPorte, CO 80535; call
970-223-8440; or e-mail
</P>
<P>
   duderanches(at)compuserve.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Hot destinations &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italy and Las Vegas will be the hottest single destinations for
tours and packages, according to a survey by the United States Tour
Operators Association. On a regional basis, Europe ranked first
internationally, followed by Australia/South Pacific and Asia. For
the fifth year in a row, Italy reigned as the hottest selling
single country worldwide. Tied for second place were China,
Australia, and Spain. Domestically, for the first time Las Vegas
came out on top, unseating perennial favorite Orlando, Fla., which
placed second. The USTOA survey also found that a continued strong
US dollar would have a favorable impact for US travelers to Canada
and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Family fun &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Let Freedom Spring, a weeklong celebration on Boston's historic
Freedom Trail, will be held April 17-25. The family fun program
includes characters and costumes, maritime events, tours and
lectures for all ages, music, and swords, guns, and battles.
Everything is either free or at low cost. Events will take place
daily and almost hourly along and a few steps off the trail that
winds through downtown Boston. For more information, call the
Freedom Trail Foundation at 617-227-8800.
</P>
