<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-MARATHON-NET-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON MARATHON GETS ON DIGITAL TRACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It is possible that more people will follow the Boston
Marathon this year from their computer screen than from the race
course or on TV _ and it's almost certain that they'll find out
more about how their friends or relatives are doing by watching on
line rather than up close.
</P>
<P>
   That's because for the first time the marathon's Internet Web
site will provide almost-instantaneous updates on how each of the
12,700 official runners is doing every 3.1 miles of the 26.2-mile
course. If everything works as planned, it will be the most
ambitious computer tracking of runners at any race ever, making the
event a milestone and a model for on-line sports offerings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll put out updates every 3 to 5 minutes, which is as close
to real time as we can get it right now,'' says Mitch Romm,
president of KIVEX.com, the official Internet provider for the
April 19 marathon. ``We expect 4 million hits during the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those logging on will be Peter Payack's 11-year-old son in
Cambridge, his mother in New Jersey, and his twin brother in
California. ``My identical twin thinks he's running the marathon
because his genes are running, so he'll want to `watch,' '' says
Payack, 49, who will be running his 20th marathon and 10th
Hopkinton-to-Boston race despite a knee that's missing nearly all
its cartilage and a multiple sclerosis affliction that can kick in
any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom will want to keep track to ensure that I'm alive,''
adds the Cambridge poet, teacher, and coach. ``And my friend Susan
always comes to watch me at about 3 o'clock. Now she'll know
exactly when to come, she'll know if I'm going to do a 4:20 or
something, and she won't have to worry about missing me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real good for people like that to participate, it'll get
more people interested.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just what Boston Marathon organizers have been hoping for
as they have fine-tuned their electronic tracking network.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 the Boston Athletic Association started handing out tiny
computer chips to all official entrants to lace onto their
sneakers. Electronic mats at the start, midpoint, and finish
recorded when each runner passed by with his or her chip, then
beamed the information via radio waves to a computer. The point was
twofold: to give runners accurate information on their times, and
to give race organizers a surer sense that the runners ran the
whole course.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 25-foot-wide maroon rubber mats were laid across the
road at 11 points along the course, giving organizers an even
better way of rooting out alleged cheaters such as John and Suzanne
Murphy, the California couple who in 1997 apparently lied their way
to the top of their age divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The BAA also launched a Web site in 1996, but it didn't have
much information on the marathon and didn't include any information
on how individual runners were doing during the race.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers last year also started transmitting to their Web site
information on individual runners during the actual race, but there
was a 20-minute delay transferring the data and concerns whether
the system would work properly discouraged the BAA from advertising
what it was doing.
</P>
<P>
   This year the association is confident the kinks have been
worked out. New communications circuits will send data 12 times
faster than a year ago. Backup servers will be on hand to prevent
the system from overloading the way it has before. And marathon
fans from around the world will be encouraged to log on as often as
they want while the race is underway.
</P>
<P>
   Hooking up will be easy. Users will simply go to the BAA Web
site _ www.bostonmarathon.org _ and feed in the runner's name or
number. If they aren't sure how to spell the name, or there is more
than one person with that name, they can enter the runner's
hometown and they will get a list of all entries from there.
</P>
<P>
   Following the race via computer will seem sterile to some,
devoid of the excitement of the crowds that line the course and the
thrill of watching runners race by or, in the case of
back-of-the-packers, summon the courage to plod on. But the on-line
solution is ideal for those who are unable to see the live TV
broadcast or are anxious to find out how runners they know are
doing.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not just runners' times that will be available on-line,
but also reams of information on how elite male and female runners
are doing, phoned in by hundreds of human monitors stationed at 19
sites along the course and equipped with digital wireless phones
supplied by Nextel Communications. The BAA site also has historic
information on the race, advice on where to watch from, and other
facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
   The BAA isn't the only one offering Boston Marathon coverage on
the Internet. In fact, there are so many companies doing it _ from
the Globe to USA Today, Runner's World, and several Japanese
publications _ that the BAA has started dispensing press
credentials to on-line providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first year we really view people covering the
marathon via the Internet as full-fledged media people,'' says BAA
spokesman Jack Fleming. ``It's obviously not a fad, it's not going
to go away and it's a great source.''
</P>
<P>
   While those providers offer up-to-the-minute information,
Fleming says that timeliness comes at a price: ``Their reporting is
not as good, they're sloppy and often inaccurate. There's no editor
checking it, no safety valve.'' The BAA also limits what the other
providers can do, denying them access to its instantaneous
information on runners and discouraging them from putting the
complete race results on their Web sites until two days after the
marathon.
</P>
<P>
   One reason on-line sites are so popular for the marathon is that
``runners are a particularly wired group. Their demographics are
more highly educated and affluent, which is the same people who
have Internet access,'' explains Eric Bauer, the executive news
editor at Boston.Com who is covering his fifth Boston Marathon via
the Internet. Working previous April classics for other Web sites,
he adds, ``We got e-mail from every continent, including
Antarctica, wanting to see how friends did.''
</P>
<P>
   It all sounds easy, but assembling the electronic network is
not. Equipment has to be collected from across America and Canada
to ensure there are enough mats and monitors to cover the course.
Then it has to be tested and retested in the days before the race.
``But we know the technology works, it's very accurate, it's the
most accurate thing I've seen out on the market,'' says Phil
Graceffa, the BAA's technology coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   As impressive as this year's on-line coverage is expected to be,
it may seem anachronistic in a year or two. By then the BAA Web
site hopes to be offering ``video streaming'' that beams out images
from the course.
</P>
<P>
   And over the next five or so years, says Fleming, ``the viewer
may be able to select what he or she wants to view. . . the viewer
would be the director and choose to watch the men's race, the
women's race, the wheelchairs, Heartbreak Hill, or the finish
line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
