</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NEGRO-LEAGUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CELEBRATING NEGRO LEAGUE BASEBALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY _ The story of the Negro Leagues is a fantastic tale
that many feel is bigger than the game of baseball itself. Now you
can relive its history and decide for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   The Negro League Museum, on the corner of 18th and Vine, is
evidence of the pain and glory that was an everyday experience for
more than 2,600 black athletes, coaches, managers, and owners over
a 40-year span.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a Hall of Fame. The very best of the Negro Leagues,
from Satchel Paige to Jackie Robinson, can still be found in
Cooperstown, N.Y. That was the goal ever since the league was
founded by Rube Foster in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   For those interested in more than a trip down memory lane, the
Negro Leagues gives you historic moments and feats of the men whom
museum officials insist were the first group of black entrepreneurs
to build an enterprise. The Negro League was born in a meeting at
the Paseo YMCA, only a block from the museum. It disbanded in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two decades, the Negro Leagues received scant
attention, mostly in the movies. But a series of reunions led to
recognition by Major League Baseball and the Hall of Fame in 1992.
Since then there has been a revival of the Negro Leagues. The
museum was established in 1995 and moved to its present residence
in 1997. John ``Buck'' O'Neil, a player-manager for the Kansas City
Monarchs from 1937-1955, is chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   The museum is located in what was considered the black business
area during that era of segregation. Games were played at Blues
Field at 22nd and Brooklyn. Players stayed at the Streets Hotel and
were well know in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Contrary to what Hollywood has depicted, Negro League baseball
was big business,'' says Bob Kendrick, director of marketing and
development. ``The players made a very decent living. Black owners
made a lot of money. They used to draw 50,000 in Comiskey Park in
Chicago. We were playing night games in 1930, almost five years
before they did in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do we introduce you to some great Negro athletes, but
we also show you that we were a part of changes that helped this
country. When Rube formed the Negro Leagues in 1920, that was
America's awaking to black empowerment. Collectively, a group of
black entrepreneurs got together to build an enterprises that
thrived for 30-40 years.''
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to separate the men and the legends. Even today,
most would concede that Paige was the Negro League's most famous
graduate. But it might surprise you that Jackie Robinson, the man
who broke the color barrier, was not included in a special museum
display of lifesize statues they call ``Field of Legends.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Field'' includes only players from the Negro Leagues.
``You have to remember, Jackie was only around us for one year,''
says O'Neil. ``The guys who have statues there were in their prime
when Jackie came along. They deserved to be there. Truthfully,
Jackie wasn't even the best player in our league at that time. But
I will say he had as much potential as anyone who has ever played
baseball. He was one of 40 percent of the players in our league who
had a college education. He was very smart and just the right man
to break the color barrier.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Field'' display includes statues of two managers _ Foster
and O'Neil. Actually, O'Neil should have been among the first
blacks elected to the Hall of Fame. But he is a member of the
Hall's veterans committee and won't be eligible until he resigns,
which O'Neil has refused to do.
</P>
<P>
   The Negro League museum, which occupies a 10,000-square foot
exhibit space, is part of a state-of-the-art building in which
baseball, jazz, and the Negro culture are all celebrated under one
roof. Located in central Kansas City, the entire complex covers
50,000 square feet. The Jazz Museum and the Horace M. Peterson III
visitor center are aimed at attracting community support, which
planners deem just as important as tourists.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil, 85, is a drawing card onto himself. Ever since his
television appearance in the Ken Burns documentary on baseball, he
has become a leading spokesman for the Negro Leagues and is in more
demand than many so-called major league stars. O'Neil takes it all
in stride. ``People need to know about Rube Foster,'' says O'Neil.
``He was far ahead of his time. He was thinking expansion as far
back as in 1920. He thought if he organized the black ballplayers,
the American League and the National League would take a ball club.
It didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Twenty-three years later, Bill Veeck wanted to buy the
Phillies and stock them with Negro League ball players. Judge
(Kenesaw Mountain) Landis wouldn't let that happen, either. In
fact, if Landis had been the commissioner, Branch Rickey would
never have been able to sign Jackie.''
</P>
<P>
   Exhibits in the museum are aided by audio visuals in two movie
theaters. Negro League memorabilia from the 1930s, 1940s, and 1950s
are available. One of the newest exhibits is a jersey worn by
Herbert (Chinck) Holmes, who played for nine seasons with the
Boston Royal-Giants, a regional team that played as far south as
Philadelphia and as far north as Canada. Holmes died in 1993,
according to his grandson, Tracey McDaniels of Dorchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   After failing in his bid to earn recognition in Boston,
specifically from the Red Sox, McDaniels says he contacted the
Negro League Museum, which put his grandfather's jersey on display.
</P>
<P>
   Both McDaniels and the museum say they are seeking further
evidence about a black team that played in New England in the
1930s. ``My grandfather would be proud to know his jersey would be
in a museum,'' said McDaniels. ``I would like one day to see the
Red Sox wearing a Negro League uniform in a game much like the
Royals wore a Monarchs one in Kansas City. For me, just knowing my
grandfather is getting some recognition makes me happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kendrick said the museum is designed to be a reminder of the
good old days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the 30's and 40's,'' he said, ``The corner of 18th and Vine
was the center of a Black Renaissance. Now we're back to try to
lead another Renaissance of a great Afro-American community. As we
look to the future, we're trying to return this area to a past when
it was alive and well. Naturally, the local community is thrilled
to have three cultural museums available. But we still have some
work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the segregated mandated businesses had a built-in fan
base. All those communities that had a successsful Negro League fan
base also had successful black economies. It's a bittersweet story.
You can almost show that the rise and fall of the NL in this
country runs parallel to the rise and fall of the black economy.
And truthfully, black economy has never recovered. That's why it is
more important for us to tell the story and preserve the story than
for us to duplicate Cooperstown.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Negro League museum resembles the major league shrine
in many ways. The difference is that there are more black faces in
this museum.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neil wishes ``that people could have seen that Josh Gibson
really could play major league baseball. Smokey Joe Williams, Cool
Papa Bell, Hilton Smith. Many of the records that are on the books
would have been so different.
</P>
<P>
   ``At Cooperstown, all you see are the Negro League players who
made the Hall of Fame. Here, we have them and something about all
those who played. In 1995, we had our 75th anniversary party and
over 200 ex-players showed up here. We planned another one here
this year but won't expect as many. Our average age is 70.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
