<SLUG> BC-GLF-MASTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLAZABAL REMASTERED HIS GAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUGUSTA, Ga. _ These are the lingering images of the 63d
Masters: David Duval, gallantly tring to win his fifth tournment of
the year and first major championship; Davis Love, fighting to hang
tough; Greg Norman, who had shoulder surgery last year, making a
brave run at tournament he dearly wants to win.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Jose Maria Olazabal, tears welling up in his
eyes, his head buried in his hands in the press building, after his
two-stroke victory. He won the Masters in 1994, but foot problems
had threatened to end his career. He was limping when he returned
to defend in 1995, and all he could do in 1996 was watch on
television as Norman squandered a six-shot lead in the final round.
</P>
<P>
   After having surgery on both feet, Olazabal thought his career
was finished. Now, this moment to cherish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult for me to experess how I feel at this
particular moment,'' he said. ``After what I went through, I'm very
proud of myself. I'm a real happy man at the moment. I feel happy
not just for myself but for all the people that supported me
through the bad times, my family, my friends. When I was at my
lowest, I never thought about this happening again. I thought I
would never play golf again.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all know that. I've said it quite a few times. To be here
standing in front of you with a green jacket is some achievement
that I didn't even dream about when I was so low. So it's great.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not comparable to the first one. The first time, it was
my first major event. I didn't have the knowledge or the time to
really enjoy the jacket, the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty sure I'm going to enjoy this one much more than the
one I had before for several reasons. The most important one was
because of the problems I went through to be here. It's my second
major event. I won my first one, it might have been a lucky week.
When you win two, and especially the way I did it, means a lot
more.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal was the third-round leader but bogeyed the third,
fourth, and fifth holes on Sunday, and as many as seven players
were squarely in the hunt over the daunting front nine.
</P>
<P>
   The final order was Olazabal (71_280), Love (71_282), and Norman
(73_284), followed at 284 by Bob Estes (72) and Steve Pate (73),
and at 285 by Duval (70), Phil Mickelson (71), Lee Westwood (71),
Nick Price (72), and Carlos Franco (73). The low round of the day
was Duval's 70, which included an eagle on the second.
</P>
<P>
   Norman, who had his surgery shortly after last year's Masters
and didn't play again until the end of the year, reawakened the
echoes when he rolled in a 25-foot putt for eagle on the 13th. But
Olazabal followed immediately with a 21-foot birdie putt to stay
tied for the lead. After Norman proceeded to bogey the 14th and
15th, Olazabal virtually salted it away with a birdie on the par-3
16th.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I tried to keep calm and make as many shots as
possible,'' said Olazabal. ``I didn't want to forget 16 and 17. I
made that putt on 16. It was just 3 feet, but it was down the hill
and lightning-quick, left to right. I don't know how the hell I
made that putt. I scrambled for a 4 on 17, and giving myself two
shots was crucial. I died for a 4 on that hole, and when I got that
4, I knew the jacket should be mine.''
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts went back three and four years, to the low and
lonely times in his career. Even his family was at a loss for what
to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``They couldn't say a word,'' he said. ``The situation was so
bad. Everybody was suffering. There is nothing they can say to you
that can cheer you up. I don't wish that to anybody. Without a
doubt, I just preferred to be alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most positive thing about my foot problems was that I
appreciate things more in life. I'm not talking about the game
itself. I'm talking about the usual things in life, just being able
to wake up in the mornings and do whatever you want to do. Go out,
enjoy the weather, enjoy the scenery. Just enjoy being on the golf
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal sat with Gary Player at the past champions dinner last
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `How are you playing?' '' said Olazabal. ``I
said, `OK, so-so. Not really great, not too bad.' He said, `How is
your confidence?' I said, `It's not really great.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked at me with those eyes and said to me, You know, you
have a great swing. If you didn't have a great swing, I wouldn't
tell you this. You have to believe in yourself. Look at me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept saying, `You have to believe in yourself. You play 18
holes. If you don't play well, it doesn't matter. You go to the
driving range. You go to the putting green. That's how you achieve
things.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he said it helped me. It helped me to believe in
myself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
