<HEADLINE>
GAMBLING PUT PENDERGAST IN A TERRIBLE FIX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It was just after noon. Kevin Pendergast stood behind
a Richards Hall lectern, scanning the young faces of the athletes
listening to him. That's the way the best professors do it,
constantly aware of the audience. Except Pendergast is not a
professor. He might tell you about his past days as a Notre Dame
football and soccer player. Or he might tell you about his most
recent days as a felon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I just got out of prison two weeks ago,'' Pendergast
said to a group of Northeastern University athletes Monday. ``I
know, standing in front of you guys, I probably don't look like
someone who has spent time in prison. But as I found out from being
there, it could be anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   There was silence for a while. Maybe there is never a good time
to tell someone you've been in prison, but at least you can
sometimes predict when a story is headed toward the dramatic
moment. Not Monday. Pendergast mentioned it casually. That's what
some people do when they cannot find a subtle way to reveal a
serious illness; sometimes they just blurt it out.
</P>
<P>
   But then Pendergast, 28, was in prison because of a serious
illness.
</P>
<P>
   He was a gambler. He was sent to federal prison for two months
after he and two others _ Bryan Irving and basketball player Dion
Lee _ were caught in a Northwestern University basketball
point-shaving scandal in 1995. His punishment could have been 20
years and a $1 million fine. But since he cooperated with the feds,
and agreed to do sports gambling seminars such as Monday's for the
next five years, a plea bargain was reached and the sentence was
reduced.
</P>
<P>
   Pendergast talked to the athletes about the January day in 1994
when he made a kick to help Notre Dame win the Cotton Bowl. Later
he would talk about what some people call one of the five greatest
games in college history. It was November 1993, when Boston College
beat the Irish, 41-39. Pendergast was the kicker on that team, but
his friend, BC kicker David Gordon, was responsible for the
decisive points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, I had a field goal blocked that game,'' he said,
``but I hasten to point out that a guy missed a block. Somebody
(BC's Daryl Porter) came shooting through the line. That's the
truth. You can watch the highlights. He could have high-fived me he
was so close.''
</P>
<P>
   He talked about his terrible credit, damaged by thousands of
dollars of credit-card debt. He mentioned how, as a convicted
felon, he can never be a doctor, lawyer, or stockbroker. He was
quite candid. So some of the questions he received were imprinted
with candor, too.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)How long was you locked up for?(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   The question came from an athlete sitting to the right of
Pendergast. There were some tense chuckles, some people had the
no-he-didn't-just-ask-that-question look on their faces. But
Pendergast had no problem with the query.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, bar none, the first thing people want to know is, `What
was prison like?' '' said the man who spent his 28th birthday in an
Otisville, N.Y., federal prison. He laughed at his unintentional
pun. Bar none. ``There's a lot more amenities than I would have
guessed. There's weights, pool tables, books, TV, cable, those type
of things.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was not assaulted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, nobody messed with me,'' he said. ``Nobody assaulted me or
got in my face. It wasn't like that. There were people there for
murder, people serving life sentences, the whole gamut. There was
still a level of respect. It was a pretty amazing experience, but
not one I would do over again if I had the choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people have questioned his sincerity. They say he is not
remorseful enough. He doesn't sob when he tells his story. He
doesn't shake his finger at athletes across the country and tell
them to beware of gambling. Some people who have seen the results
of a recent NCAA survey _ that 72 percent of student-athletes
gamble _ would probably like to see more tears for authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' said Pendergast, ``it's tough for me to take a
real moralistic stand on it. It's not what I'm about. My idea is to
get up and talk to the kids, let them know what happened to me and
let them assimilate all the facts.''
</P>
<P>
   What happened is that a National Merit Scholar became addicted
to gambling and went to prison. A young man who scored 780 out of
800 on his Scholastic Aptitude Test found himself in handcuffs. The
kid next door got a knock on his door from the FBI. A
singer-songwriter, a lover of everything from Hendrix to hiphop,
was forced to pause his dream of leading a band that would go big.
</P>
<P>
   He lost $20,000 the last time he bet on sports and said he will
never do it again. He doesn't complain about the hypocrisy of it
all. How the NCAA knows about and silently encourages betting on
basketball tournament brackets. How judgmental writers criticize
him while they work for newspapers that run betting lines. How the
nation seems surprised that he has a criminal record although he
doesn't meet the stereotypical profile of one: He is a young,
intelligent, white male.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the hypocrisy that bothers him. He will tell you
that he is not in a position to ``fill out a tournament bracket, go
play nickel slots, or buy a lotto ticket.'' It was all or nothing
for him and he wants nothing. Six years ago, his mother died of
cancer, so she didn't have to see him in the news. His father,
Paul, had to see it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always wished for him, more than for myself, that I could
undo what I did,'' he said. ``If I can't feel any regret for the
(expletive) I put him through over this, then when would I ever
feel regret?''
</P>
<P>
   It was just before 1:30. An anatomy class was entering Room 202
as Pendergast was leaving. I wish he could have stayed and spoken
with those students, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Michael Holley is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
