<SLUG> BC-LUCAS-CHARITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' SCREENING TO BENEFIT CHILDREN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ ``Star Wars'' director George Lucas is using the
power of the Force to help the charities that help children in 11
North American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Lucasfilm Ltd. announced Monday that it would release ``Star
Wars: Episode I: The Phantom Menace'' on May 16 _ three days ahead
of the general release _ in these cities to help raise money for
programs for children: Boston, Chicago, Dallas, Denver, Los
Angeles, New York, Philadelphia, San Francisco, Seattle, Toronto
and Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because `Star Wars' has always meant so much to children
around the world, I wanted to provide this opportunity to benefit
children in at least this small way,'' Lucas said in an
announcement made Monday on the film's Web site (www.starwars.com).
</P>
<P>
   The benefit screenings are expected to be a big draw, as well as
a huge boost for donations, because they are scheduled before the
general opening day, and anticipation is already high for the
sci-fi film.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, ``Star Wars'' fans began camping out Thursday in
front of Mann's Chinese Theater in order to be the first to see the
film on May 19.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations selected to benefit from the early release
cover a wide range of charitable needs. For example, the Los
Angeles screening will benefit the Elizabeth Glaser Pediatric AIDS
Foundation, while proceeds from the New York event will go to the
Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
