<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6283 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AFRICANMUSIC-HNS &LR;      04-13 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG VOCALS DEFINE ESSENCE OF SOUTHERN AFRICAN SOUND &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
 MUSIC-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two years ago, the Houston International Festival
spotlighted the nations of western Africa. This year, the festival
shifts the cultural focus to southern Africa. The 12 honored
nations are Angola, Botswana, Lesotho, Madagascar, Malawi,
Mozambique, Namibia, South Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Zambia and
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two decades, the American pop-music audience has
become more knowledgeable about music from other countries. The
growing interest has spawned its own marketing category, world
beat, which can include anything from authentic Third World folk
music to Western pop artists influenced by the music of Africa,
Asia or Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston International Festival has developed a reputation as
one of the leading presenters of world-beat artists. The festival
even sponsors its own annual awards presentation, the American
World Music Awards, voted on by an international panel of experts.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Houstonians would be hard-pressed to define the
difference between western African music and southern African music
</P>
<P>
   The largest southern African nation is the Republic of South
Africa. American listeners first heard South African music in the
1960s, when Miriam Makeba and Hugh Masekela toured and recorded in
the West. In the 1980s, Paul Simon used South African musicians on
his landmark ``Graceland'' album, which seamlessly blended Zulu
rhythms and vocal styles with sophisticated pop.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa has long had its own thriving record industry,
trailing only North American and European markets in terms of total
sales. The most popular indigenous South African style is probably
mbaqanga, or ``township jive,'' which is the style featured most
prominently on ``Graceland.''
</P>
<P>
   South African music centers more on vocals, rather than the
polyrhythmic percussions of western African music. Ladysmith Black
Mambazo perfected the traditional Zulu a cappella vocal style
called iscathamiya.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, black South African music shows influences of
European church music, as well as the modern Western forms of jazz,
rhythm and blues, rock and reggae.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe's music combines regional influences from the Congo and
South Africa with its own indigenous tribal sounds.
</P>
<P>
   The music of Angola and Mozambique sounds similar to Brazilian
music, reflecting centuries of Portuguese colonialism. Madagascar,
the most isolated African nation, boasts a unique Afro-Asian
musical heritage that has only recently been exported to the rest
of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Here are brief introductions to the African artists appearing at
this year's Houston International Festival.
</P>
<P>
   __ Angelique Kidjo _ Born in Benin, Kidjo is contemporary
Afro-pop's leading diva. Her latest album, Oremi, mixes funk and
soul grooves with pan-African melodies to create a true form of
world beat.
</P>
<P>
   __ Thomas Mapfumo &AMP; Blacks Unlimited _ Mapfumo's chimurenga
style translates the shimmering textures of the mbira (thumb-piano)
to the electric guitar. During Zimbabwe's war of liberation, he was
jailed for the outspoken political commentary in his songs.
</P>
<P>
   __ Samba Ngo _ Ngo is one of the leading exponents of Zairean
soukous style, which incorporates Afro-Cuban rhumba rhythms with a
distinctively African approach to electric guitar.
</P>
<P>
   __ Oumou Sangare _ The young singer from Mali updates the
ancient griot tradition _ the African ancestor of Delta blues _
with modern instrumentation. She has become a strong advocate for
the rights of African women.
</P>
<P>
   __ Abdullah Ibrahim _ The pianist is considered to be the Duke
Ellington of South Africa. In 1990, he returned to his homeland
after 14 years in exile. His playing and compositions bring the
sophistication of jazz and classical music to the South African
popular tradition.
</P>
<P>
   __ Stewart Sukuma _ The Mozambican crooner has combined a boyish
pop appeal with South African, Brazilian and North American flavors
to become the unofficial musical ambassador of Mozambique.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hugh Masekela _ The legendary South African trumpeter has
been mixing African rhythm and melody with American jazz for 40
years. His latest album is Black to the Future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
