<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6285 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LINDSEY-HNS &LR;      04-13 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LINDSEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPY OUTLIVES THE COLD WAR &HT;     

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By FRITZ LANHAM 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   All that brow-furrowing about what spy novelists would do for
material after the Cold War has of course proved needless.
</P>
<P>
   International crime lords substitute nicely for the lords of
international communism in the baddies role. The narrative switch
works especially well, since lots of Russian apparatchiks really
have morphed into Mafia-style dons. Art is never happier than when
it can imitate life.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Color of Night,'' David Lindsey yokes this approach to
villainy with a narrative device well-known to fans of western
movies: The old gunfighter who wants to retire but can't because
his past won't let him.
</P>
<P>
   The result is another stylishly written page-turner from the
Austin-based novelist. ``The Color of Night'' _ Lindsey's 10th
novel _ pits an attractive and plausible hero and heroine against a
predictably cruel, crafty and inescapable criminal mastermind.
Filling out the cast are appropriately colorful minor characters.
Within the conventions of the thriller genre, ``The Color of
Night'' is a satisfying, engaging, intelligent read.
</P>
<P>
   The early chapters are set mostly in Houston, although we don't
remain there long _ the action takes us to Vienna, Geneva, London,
Venice, Rome, and the lovely little town of Bellagio on Lake Como
in northern Italy, among other places.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Strand is an art dealer, specializing in drawings. In his
late 40s and widowed a year before, he lives and works in ``a
two-story home in the museum district, an expensive address.''
</P>
<P>
   Strand is competent and strong-willed but also circumspect,
sensitive, emotionally guarded _ a good but hardly perfect man,
capable of making mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   Called to a Houston town house, he meets an attractive
Asian-American woman, Mara Song, who is getting divorced and wants
to sell a fine set of drawings _ Balthus, Ingres, Klimt, Maillol.
</P>
<P>
   Harry likes the drawings. He also likes their owner. He and Mara
begin seeing each other, their relationship deepening slowly.
</P>
<P>
   They jet off to Rome, where Harry has business to conduct and
Mara has a home. Harry returns one day to discover someone has
slipped into Mara's house and left a tape sticking out of the VCR.
He pushes the tape into the machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``God. God. How could he have been wrong about it all,'' ends
the chapter.
</P>
<P>
   The tape shows the final minutes of his wife's life, before her
Land Rover plunged through a bridge railing and into a tidal stream
near Galveston. Harry discovers his wife's death was no accident.
She was murdered. And he knows by whom.
</P>
<P>
   We've sensed from the beginning that Harry is sitting on a pile
of money. Those museum-district houses don't come cheap. Now we
learn it wasn't dealer's markup that filled that fat bank account.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end of the Cold War, Harry had been an American spy,
running a ring of agents in Europe, using art-dealing as a cover.
Naturally, that was a morally murky world full of treachery,
divided loyalties and secrets within secrets. Even the good guys
sometimes had to employ unsavory types.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latter was Wolfram Schrade, a hugely wealthy German
crime baron with a passion for collecting drawings. Before
retiring, Harry organized a team of five agents and embezzled
millions from Schrade.
</P>
<P>
   The viperous Schrade has finally figured out where his money
went and is out for revenge, picking off Harry's friends one at a
time. The first to die was Romy, Harry's wife, who had worked for
Schrade and provided insider knowledge of his financial affairs.
Next is the team's lawyer _ his body discovered absent head and
hands. Then Meret, Harry's assistant and an entirely innocent
party.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, in good thriller fashion, the novel becomes a race: Can
Harry, with Mara in tow, stay one step ahead of Schrade, who seems
to have eyes everywhere? How can he get Schrade before Schrade gets
him? Can he protect Mara, who may or may not be what she seems? And
what of the involvement of the American spymasters _ Harry's old
bosses? Whose side are they on?
</P>
<P>
   Although much of the narrative sticks close to Harry's point of
view, we do jump outside and learn things he doesn't yet know. Thus
we see him as fallible, feeling his way forward, in many ways an
ordinary man caught up in extraordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Harry is no natural-born killer. Although offing Schrade
seems, ultimately, the only solution, Harry doesn't know if he can
do it. Neither do we.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Harry must wrestle with the moral ramifications of his
actions. Is it really OK to steal from a criminal? Didn't he know
in some part of his mind that sooner or later Schrade would come
after his tormentors, and thus doesn't he, Harry Strand, bear
responsibility for their deaths?
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey leavens the novel with these moral quandaries. He also
offers a convincing portrait of Harry and Mara wrestling with their
feelings for each other _ their fears, hopes, doubts. The Color of
Night is a thriller with a human face.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Lindsey's prose is clean and lucid. He peppers the
narrative with neat portraits _ of a very pregnant bomb-maker,
``huge damp splotches of perspiration staining the underarms of her
dress and the material between her distended breasts,'' and of a
South American crime lord reacting to the news he's been betrayed.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally the novel builds to an explosive climax in which a
second narrative thread, involving one of Harry's former
operatives, weaves into the first.
</P>
<P>
   Readers looking for a satisfying entertainment will savor ``The
Color of Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Lanham is the Houston Chronicle's book editor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
