<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPER EDITORS ARE TALKING ETHICS AND EATING FANCY FOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Attention homeless: This week 546 people who
professionally agonize about the poor and the homeless are at the
Fairmont Hotel here talking about ethics and eating fancy food.
Yes, the American Society of Newspaper Editors convention is in
town.
</P>
<P>
   Get those cardboard signs ready: ``Will trade touching human
interest stories for warmer newspapers to sleep under.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention Sisters of Perpetual Indulgence and Catholic Church:
Come on, let's have another fight. Rip up each others' good and bad
habits. Show those editors they don't have to look to Kosovo to
find intolerance and religious war.
</P>
<P>
   Attention local citizens: You may have noticed that the San
Francisco Chronicle is running a five-part series you're not
reading on newspaper credibility.
</P>
<P>
   This effort at appearing serious is taking place because the 546
editors, professors and experts on journalistic ethics (something
like musicologists of military music) are the most important
readers in town this week.
</P>
<P>
   Not that any of them will be reading anything beyond the
restaurant reviews. Like any other conventioneers, the editors are
here to eat, not listen to seminars like ``covering gays and
lesbians in your town'' and ``private lives and public people _ has
the press gone too far?''
</P>
<P>
   The session on gays is at 7:45 a.m. Friday, a time when no
hard-partying journalist is out of bed, so you can see how
important that is.
</P>
<P>
   And if you really want to hear the press going too far in
talking about public and private lives, and dishing the dirt on
politicians they know, wait until the editors get a good buzz on at
Postrio or Farallon.
</P>
<P>
   And now some words of warning to the visiting editors, besides
``Look twice at all nuns.''
</P>
<P>
   This is San Francisco, and a lot might come out of your
convention. Someone may even come out at your convention.
</P>
<P>
   During the U.S. Conference of Mayors three years ago, a friend
at the Fairmont informed me that a male mayor of a middle-sized
American city went up to his room and came down as a female mayor,
size 16 or so.
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen in San Francisco. On Wednesday, during his
keynote speech, Mayor Willie Brown may even talk completely
seriously, telling no outrageous jokes, speaking only the truth
about his doomed stadium-mall, the homeless who never go away, the
transit system that doesn't work, and the downtown parking he's
eliminated so his developer pals can throw up highrises.
</P>
<P>
   Naah. That only happens in ``Bulworth.'' San Francisco isn't
that deep into sharing inner feelings. Brown won't tell you how
much he hates the press. This is a guy who once screamed, ``Shut
up, press!'' during a news conference on his 49ers stadium-mall.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, stadium-mall. Brown wanted to combine football with food
courts and the Gap. It hasn't worked out.
</P>
<P>
   Brown won't yell at you, because only a handful of you are from
papers that regularly cover him. He'll charm most of you because he
is witty, intelligent and perhaps the second-best politician in
America.
</P>
<P>
   To put that in perspective, though, the best politician in
America recently was impeached and is losing a war with a small
Balkan country.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will be speaking to you on Thursday. Unlike
Brown, Clinton does have ex-girlfriends.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, after I criticized Brown for giving an ex-girlfriend a
$65,000 job and place to live on Treasure Island here, Brown
bragged, ``I have no ex-girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as I can tell from talking to his ex-girlfriends, it's
true.
</P>
<P>
   Now, some tips for editors visiting The City. Yes, we put it in
caps because we're so impressed with ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has been reduced to having one newspaper bar, the
M&AMP;M. The food isn't bad, but there's no smoking because this is
California. Newspaper people don't smoke anyway. And you wonder why
newspapers are in decline.
</P>
<P>
   Hanno's around the corner used to be a newspaper bar, but a few
years ago it was renamed the Tempest and became a bike messenger
bar. The bike messengers smoke and now they're unionizing. So it
goes in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   High-paid journalists, like TV anchors, editors and the
occasional columnist, sometimes may be found at Moose's in North
Beach. This is because of Ed Moose, whom all you visiting editors
probably know, because he knows everybody.
</P>
<P>
   The food is far too good for a place where journalists hang out.
On the other hand, nobody gives you an Evian-addled frown if you
order hard liquor.
</P>
<P>
   You can fall right out of Moose's into the heart of North Beach,
where the soul and the best of the cholesterol of San Francisco
reside.
</P>
<P>
   We know what you're here for. You're here to eat. Just pick a
place, and you probably won't do too badly. The best bet is to get
away from those seminars and discussions of readers' focus groups
and find a restaurant filled with real newspaper readers, and no
other editors in it.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the best smoke-filled rooms are filled with mesquite
smoke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1450EDT &QL; 
