<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BROWNIE-MARY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARY JANE RATHBUN, MARIJUANA CRUSADER, DIES AT 77 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LARRY D. HATFIELD  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mary Jane Rathbun, the feisty woman whose
marijuana-laced brownies eased the pain of a generation of people
dying of AIDS, died Saturday at Laguna Honda Hospital after a
lengthy illness. She was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rathbun, who was known as ``Brownie Mary,'' had used a
wheelchair since injuring her spine in a fall in August, according
to Larry Bittner, a longtime friend and the executor of her estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brownie Mary was a hero for our time, in a world with few
heroes,'' Bittner said Monday. She was ``selfless, thinking always,
even to the end, about others.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rathbun _ one of the earliest and most constant proponents
of using marijuana for medicinal purposes _ gained notoriety in the
1980s for baking and delivering marijuana brownies to patients in
the AIDS ward at San Francisco General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   She was arrested twice in San Francisco but, in 1992, city
supervisors honored her with a ``Brownie Mary Day.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she made 134 dozen a month during the heyday, 1984 to
1994,'' said Dennis Peron, who founded the now-defunct San
Francisco Cannabis Buyers Club with Ms. Rathbun. ``And you could
smell it all through her building. The old ladies there were all
cool about it. Hey, it's San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rathbun was born in Minnesota, named Mary Jane by her
unwitting, conservative, Irish Catholic mother.
</P>
<P>
   That coincidence vastly amused her, according to Bittner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given my background and reputation and my adopted name,''
Brownie Mary told Bittner recently, ``my poor old mother is surely
turning cartwheels in her grave. It serves her right.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rathbun moved to San Francisco after World War II and worked
for many years as a waitress. While she baked brownies for AIDS
patients, she was living on $650-a-month Social Security check. It
pained her, she said, that the lack of money limited the number of
AIDS patients _ whom she called her ``kids'' _ she could help.
</P>
<P>
   Her start in the marijuana brownie business wasn't so
altruistic.
</P>
<P>
   When she was arrested in 1981, she admitted she was in it for
the profit. But when she as arrested a decade later in Sonoma
County, she said, ``This time I wasn't in it for the bucks. This
time I was doing it for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   She used marijuana to ease the pain in her own arthritic knees,
she said, but she also never forgot those she helped. ``I get a
little marijuana every once in a while,'' she said in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``I save it up until I've got enough to make 20 dozen brownies
for my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rathbun became an activist in her teens when she traveled
with a group in the Midwest supporting the union rights of miners.
She married after moving to San Francisco and she and her late
husband had a daughter, who died in an automobile accident in the
early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   She had no known surviving relatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
