<SLUG> BC-DINING-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Food and dining stories from The N.Y. Times News Service for
Wednesday, April 15:
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-FUSION (Paris) _ Please don't tell Escoffier, but there
is a dessert in Paris called the wonton kumquat Nutella. Served at
a new Right-Bank restaurant called Cafe Mosaic, it comes in a
bamboo steamer. Its central feature is a very undessert-like
display of three soft wonton envelopes, each containing a whole
kumquat and a small puddle of molten Nutella. The thing is awful.
But in Paris, it may also be the wave of the future. Fusion has
come to France, and it feels funny. By William Grimes.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE-BISTROS (Paris) _ For generations bistros have been the
soul of Paris, casual neighborhood restaurants where regulars drop
in for local gossip and a reassuringly familiar meal. Almost as
important as the food is the setting, usually small, intimate and
aglow with stained or painted wood, etched glass and mirrors,
bric-a-brac, prints and posters. Lately there is a boom in bistros
that serve traditionally lusty cuisine at prices ranging from $20
to $100 for a complete meal for one, wine included. The concept is
so popular that some now require reservations as long as three
weeks ahead, which really compromises the spontaneous bistro
spirit. By Mimi Sheraton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   RAW-EGGS (New York) _ Nothing unusual about the egg yolk staring
up at me from a plate of tagliatelle at Babbo one night last week.
Except that the egg was raw. Totally uncooked. Cold. This was a
little disconcerting at first, but, once mixed in with the buttery
pasta and chunks of cured pork, the egg and the dish warmed up into
an irresistible indulgence, with an aftertaste of danger. Because
raw eggs can kill you. Or so we have been told. By Rick Marin.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   SIMPLE-COOKING (Undated) _ The column: Veal brisket (aka
boneless breast of veal). By Mark Bittman.
</P>
<P>
   With 1 recipe.
</P>
<P>
   LANGOUSTINES (Undated) _ On langoustines, the crustaceans
flooding into fish markets. By Molly O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   With recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MASTER-CHEF (Undated) _ The column: On warm chocolate tarts with
chocolate sorbet. By Claudia Fleming.
</P>
<P>
   With 2 recipes.
</P>
<P>
   VEGETABLE-COLOR (Undated) _ On the appeal of growing vegetables
in vibrant colors: magenta corn, yellow carrots, purple broccoli.
By Richard W. Langer.
</P>
<P>
   WINE-TALK (Undated) _ On a consumer survey that reveals regional
preferences. By Frank J. Prial.
</P>
<P>
   SPROUTS-EATING-WELL (Undated) _ Sprouts in springtime. By Marian
Burros.
</P>
<P>
   We expect to move all Living Section stories by early evening
with a ``d'' category code, unless otherwise indicated.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other stories
from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox News
Service, Hearst Newspapers, The Arizona Republic, Kansas City Star,
Fort Worth Star-Telegram, Los Angeles Daily News, San Francisco
Chronicle and Seattle Post-Intelligencer.
</P>
