<HEADER>
A6328 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-HIRING-HNS &LR;      04-13 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-HIRING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACKSON COURTS SILICON VALLEY, URGES MINORITY HIRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By EDWARD IWATA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The Rev. Jesse Jackson stormed through Silicon
Valley and kept up his full-court press on technology companies to
hire more minorities and do more business with minority-owned
companies.
</P>
<P>
   In whirlwind meetings from dawn to dusk Monday, the civil rights
leader talked with dozens of power brokers, including executives
from Apple Computer, Hewlett-Packard, Intel and Cisco Systems.
</P>
<P>
   During a telephone interview between stops, Jackson said an
hour-long meeting with Steve Jobs, the chief executive of Apple,
was ``productive and positive.'' The two ``share common interests''
and hope to work closely on projects in the near future, Jackson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're setting the foundation for strong, long-term
collaborations with high-tech companies,'' Jackson said. ``We're
moving into the substantive stage.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Jackson and his Rainbow/PUSH Coalition have
pressured technology companies to hire more African-Americans and
Hispanics. According to the U.S. Labor Department, blacks and
Hispanics make up 11 percent of the work force in the top 33
companies in Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also is encouraging high-tech companies to sign more
contracts with minority vendors, to sell more technology-related
products in minority neighborhoods and to add nonwhites to their
boards.
</P>
<P>
   In order to monitor the companies, Rainbow/PUSH has bought stock
in 50 high-tech companies and will attend shareholders' meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have management teams that look like America,''
Jackson said. ``Management lives in a relatively small world, with
no sense of markets beyond their limited cultural environments. One
company wasn't even aware of the existence of Black Entertainment
Television or Ebony magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson added: ``Let's dispense with the excuses and open the
doors, and you'll see many opportunities to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader also has drawn sharp criticism from some
quarters of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Rodgers, the chief executive of Cypress Semiconductor in
San Jose, recently likened Jackson to ``a sea gull that flies
around leaving droppings.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodgers didn't back off Monday, accusing Jackson of ``shaking
down companies'' for funding on minority projects. Executives who
disagree with Jackson's civil rights agenda are branded as racists,
Rodgers charged.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this guy needs a punch in the nose. He's offensive,''
Rodgers said. ``What if I walked into the Cuban district of Miami
and made a bunch of generalizations about people? That would be
pretty arrogant of me.''
</P>
<P>
   Like any other sector in America, Rodgers said, Silicon Valley
has its share of discrimination, but there is no widespread
``economic apartheid.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson declined to get into a public spat with Rodgers, saying
only that Rodgers is ``a phantom who doesn't exist, who doesn't
represent Silicon Valley.''
</P>
<P>
   According to a 1998 report by the National Science Foundation,
blacks and Hispanics make up roughly 3 percent of all scientists
and engineers in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Several studies also show that blacks, Hispanics and low-income
communities have much less access to Internet technologies than
others.
</P>
<P>
   Not all is gloomy news, though. Signs are surfacing that blacks
and Hispanics are making greater use of high-tech resources.
</P>
<P>
   About 43 percent of Hispanics and 40 percent of blacks are
expected to sign on to the Internet next year, according to a
report Monday by the technology firm Forrester Research and the
U.S. Internet Council, a private trade group funded by 33 high-tech
companies, including Intel, Microsoft and AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond Silicon Valley, Jackson has sought more economic clout
for minorities on Wall Street and in the auto industry. He's also
tried to get more black coaches and managers hired in Major League
Baseball and the NCAA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
