<SLUG> BC-READ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE SPIRIT TURNS LITERACY INTO PASSION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (with art) 
 
By MELISSA FLETCHER STOELTJE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The social swirl is intoxicating. Politicos, captains
of industry, nonprofit heavies, the mayor _ everyone is here,
quaffing coffee and gabbing it up.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Doughty navigates her way through the schmooze-fest.
Two tiny books dangle from her ear lobes. Shake her hand and you
can't help but absorb her effervescence. Maybe it's the crisp
British accent or the zesty, can-do demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Doughty charms, as anyone can attest who attended the Mayor's
Literacy Leadership Awards Breakfast, a thank-you in January to
those furthering the cause. It's by combining this charm with hard
work and near-missionary zeal that the diminutive Doughty has made
literacy Social Cause No. 1 in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Under her leadership, the Houston READ Commission, formed in
1988, has grown into the largest urban literacy coalition in the
United States, one emulated throughout the nation. She oversees an
annual budget of more than $4 million and travels the world to
spread her literacy gospel.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfasts with corporate swells and power elites are not really
Doughty's cup of tea. Her true constituency is the disenfranchised
folks whose inability to read sorely limits their lives. Her true
home is the decidedly less glamorous Houston READ Commission
office, a well-worn former shopping center in the inner city.
</P>
<P>
   About 130 organizations under the READ umbrella together reach
about 100,000 students a year, most of them adult learners.
</P>
<P>
   Doughty has spent 20 years traveling the world, teaching. Queen
Elizabeth II recently named Doughty a Member of the British Empire,
the most prestigious award for public service her nation can
bestow.
</P>
<P>
   To Doughty, battling illiteracy is part of the ongoing war on
social injustice. It's a key strand in the civil-rights fabric
America continues to weave.
</P>
<P>
   At heart, she is a freedom fighter. Truth be told, a bit of a
rebel.
</P>
<P>
   ``But she's not one to throw rocks,'' says Chase Untermeyer, a
computer-industry bigwig who is president of the READ Commission
board. ``She throws bouquets. After you get hit with enough
bouquets, she gets your attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Doughty, 50, was born in London but grew up in a tiny English
village, an isolated hamlet of hedgerows and sheep herds. One of
four kids, Doughty is the daughter of a minister father and a
community-minded mother. She attended a Catholic convent school,
where rules were rigid and strictly enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always in trouble,'' she says with a conspiratorial
snicker. ``I often had to stay in school on Saturdays and do
assignments. I didn't like authority one bit.''
</P>
<P>
   She launches into an extended riff on the ills of the English
and American education systems, whose institutions, she says, too
often sacrifice creativity and independence for efficiency and rote
learning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have that old Victorian concept of creating workers
to fill the mines, the factories,'' she says emphatically.
``Especially in neighborhoods of economic need, where illiteracy
and poverty go hand in hand, we foster that. We talk about giving
people the opportunity to work, but let's keep that minimum wage
low, let's make sure we're feeding that lowest level of the
workforce.''
</P>
<P>
   She felt constricted in the cloistered life of a minister's
child. ``I wanted to be out of school and doing something useful,''
she says.
</P>
<P>
   So when she was invited to become a volunteer in an overseas
literacy program after high school, Doughty jumped at the chance.
</P>
<P>
   She was assigned to Nyamandhlovu, a village deep in the African
bush whose name meant ``feet of the elephant,'' referring to the
dust stirred up during elephant stampedes.
</P>
<P>
   She was 17, away from home for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   Doughty's job was to teach English, along with two African
teachers, to students at an elementary school where, by government
rule, African children were allowed to continue only through second
grade. The rule was designed to perpetuate a ``two-tier society,''
she says, but the students weren't so easily dissuaded.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rather a lot of children who had very interesting birth
certificates,'' Doughty says, grinning slyly again. ``We had
students 18, 19, 20 years old who were desperate to get an
education, their parents absolutely adamant they would continue.
Never in my life have I seen such a desire to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   After a year her volunteer stint was up, and she returned to
England, went to college and became a teacher. She took on a class
of at-risk high-school students.
</P>
<P>
   ``They walked in the door disheveled, messy, smoking cigarettes,
just challenging the whole time,'' she recalls. ``They were like,
`What ya gonna do, miss? Would ya like a puff, miss?'''
</P>
<P>
   In the slowly growing belief that you must reach people where
they are _ an underpinning philosophy of the READ Commission _
Doughty looked her students in the eye: I have to be here. You have
to be here. What do you want to do? What are you interested in?
</P>
<P>
   War, they said. Terrible diseases. Grotesqueries.
</P>
<P>
   So she went to the library and checked out books on battles and
read them to her class. Slowly the kids started asking questions.
What happened again on that little island in Asia during World War
II? How little do you have to eat to become malnourished?
</P>
<P>
   ``We got to the point where we were actually learning things,''
she says, hooting.
</P>
<P>
   She married a young civil engineer (they're now divorced) and
soon their first of three sons (now all grown) came along. She and
her husband had agreed that, while their children were young, they
would alternate taking jobs in different countries as a way to see
the world. So, through the years, Doughty has taught school in Iran
and the United Arab Emirates, to students of all ages, on all
subjects.
</P>
<P>
   When her husband received a job offer from Houston, Doughty
reluctantly agreed to move. The Bayou City seemed less than exotic
after their world travels, but she fell in love with the city the
moment she arrived, she says. She became a writer.
</P>
<P>
   One night, a friend asked whether she'd be interested in
developing computer software for the Houston Independent School
District. Do what? She laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, she became a member of the district's technology
department, designing curricula for at-risk kids. Around that time,
Mayor Kathy Whitmire wound up a task force on illiteracy in Houston
by launching a coalition that would lasso federal money and
galvanize corporate support. The school district agreed to lend an
employee, Doughty, to serve as executive director of the new
Houston READ Commission.
</P>
<P>
   An appalling 52 percent of Houston adults are functionally
illiterate, meaning they cannot decipher such routine things as
prescription labels or bus schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Change this statistic, she says, and the quality of life in
Houston would soar. Crime would drop. Likewise drug use. Ditto teen
pregnancy. When people can read, she says, they make better
choices. They get better jobs. They gain hope.
</P>
<P>
   Is the READ Commission, in essence, doing what the schools
couldn't do?
</P>
<P>
   She pauses, smiles. The rebel has learned to rein in her words.
</P>
<P>
   ``We consider ourselves to be Houston's educational safety
net,'' she says. ``We are the underground school system that helps
to provide opportunities to those folks who fall through the cracks
in the system.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
