<SLUG> BC-PIANOCOMPETITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM HOMEMAKER TO METEOROLOGIST, THESE PIANO COMPETITORS RUN THE
CAREER GAMUT
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by PIANO COMPETITION-LIST) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WAYNE LEE GAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ Millions of people took piano lessons
somewhere along the way. Most of them will never get to play
Carnegie Hall _ or win the Cliburn gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   But a group of 97 amateur pianists will get their taste of
stardom this June, courtesy of the Cliburn Foundation, the same
folks who present the Van Cliburn International Piano Competition
every four years in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   At the International Piano Competition for Outstanding Amateurs,
these piano aficionados _ who might have made a career of music,
but instead chose it as an avocation _ will compete in a setting
reminiscent of the main Cliburn competition. They will play on the
stage of Ed Landreth Auditorium, where the main Cliburn used to be
held. Wearing concert finery, they'll perform music of Bach,
Chopin, Mozart _ much the same as competitors in the real Cliburn.
</P>
<P>
   A diverse and interesting group, those chosen from a field of
143 applicants include a meteorologist, the chief art critic of The
New York Times, the director of gaming tables at Harrah's Casino in
Reno, Nev., a railroad manager, a hairdresser, a number of
physicians, two flight attendants and a prime-time television
anchor _ who 14 years ago was third runner-up in the Miss America
pageant.
</P>
<P>
   But in some respects, the two Cliburn competitions are
dissimilar. The quadrennial Cliburn competition is aimed at young
professionals, and is limited to 35 of the most advanced and
polished pianists, ages 18-30, in the world. The leading music
competition in the world, it will be held again in Fort Worth in
May and June 2001. The top prize, including cash, engagements,
contracts and perks, is worth around a quarter of a million
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur competition, meanwhile, is limited to people who
make their living in something other than music, and who are
``older than'' 30. The top prize is $2,000. How often it will be
held remains to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   But the two competitions have something in common: Both promote
and celebrate the love of the piano and the rich repertoire that
has been written for that instrument.
</P>
<P>
   One area where the amateurs actually excel beyond the pianists
of the main Cliburn is in their remarkable diversity. Competitors
in the amateur competition represent 23 states and 10 countries.
Many were child prodigies who had extensive collegiate or
conservatory level training; many work in technical fields or in
medicine. And many are classic overachievers.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth-area competitors include Dr. Maria Fawcett, a staff
physician at North Hills Hospital in Fort Worth; David Hibbard,
manager of locomotive utilization at Burlington Northern &AMP; Santa Fe
Railroad; otolaryngologist John Ponder of Colleyville; homemaker
Judith Sherrard of Grapevine; and registered nurse Cynthia Riley of
Burleson.
</P>
<P>
   At the competition, which will be June 9-13 at Ed Landreth
Auditorium at Texas Christian University, all competitors will play
a 10-minute program in the first round. Up to 18 will be selected
to advance to the semifinal round to perform a 20-minute program.
Six finalists will perform a 30-minute recital. As in the Cliburn
competition, all competitors are free to select repertoire.
</P>
<P>
   Cliburn Foundation executive director Richard Rodzinski says
that some of the competitors in the amateur competition ``have
unbelievable repertoires. Some of them have been accumulating
pieces for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   He cited one competitor whose list of repertoire _ titles only _
was 21 pages long.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur competition will also provide a try-out ground for
several new ideas that may be incorporated into the next Cliburn
competition. A jury of music critics will select a winner, with the
idea that the main Cliburn competition may have a separate press
jury and press award in 2001. Likewise, there will be an audience
favorite award, which will be selected by a balloting of members of
the audience at the final round.
</P>
<P>
   And a new jury voting system, which is meant to more accurately
reflect the jury's opinions, will be tried out at the amateur
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth Symphony music director John Giordano, chairman of
the Cliburn competition jury, also will chair the jury for the
amateur competition, assisted by Gerard Bekerman, founder of the
Grand Amateur Competition of Paris, the only comparable event in
the world. Jurors serving for all three rounds will include John
Ardoin, former chief music critic of the Dallas Morning News; 1997
Cliburn Competition gold medalist Jon Nakamatsu; Germaine Deveze
and Sabine Lacoarret, both of the faculty of the Paris
Conservatory; Jack Roberts of the faculty of the University of
North Texas; Shields-Collins Bray, staff pianist of the Fort Worth
Symphony; and Carol Leone of the faculty of Southern Methodist
University.
</P>
<P>
   For the semifinal and final rounds, the jury also will include
Benedetto Lupo, bronze medalist of the 1989 Cliburn Competition;
Robert Garwell, dean of the School of Fine Arts and Communications
at TCU; pianist John Owings of the TCU faculty; pianist David Karp
of the faculty of Southern Methodist University; pianist Adam
Wodnicki of the faculty of the University of North Texas; pianist
Monte Hill Davis; Paul Pollei, director of the Gina Bachauer
Competition; and Alina Rubinstein, daughter of Arthur Rubinstein.
</P>
<P>
   A press jury will include music critics Daniel Cariaga of the
Los Angeles Times, Stephen Wigler of the Baltimore Sun, Richard
Dyer of the Boston Globe, Donald Rosenberg of the Cleveland Plain
Dealer, William Littler of the Toronto Star, Olin Chism of the
Dallas Morning News and Stuart Isacoff, editor of Piano Today.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   International Competition for Outstanding Amateurs
</P>
<P>
   June 8-12: Preliminary rounds are at 10 a.m., 3 p.m. and 8 p.m.
June 9; 10 a.m. and 3 p.m. June 10; 10 a.m., 3 p.m. and 8 p.m. June
11. Semifinals are at 2 p.m. and 7:30 p.m. June 12. Finals are at 3
p.m. June 13. At Ed Landreth Auditorium, University at Cantey, TCU.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets: Preliminary admission is $5 for each session, or $25
for a pass for the entire preliminary round. Semifinals admission
is $10 for each session, or $15 for both. Finals admission is $20;
all seating is general admission
</P>
<P>
   Information: (817) 335-9000
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Wayne Lee Gay is classical music for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7756, or e-mail:
wlgay(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
