 PageExpress budget for the week of April 12, 1999
<TEXT>
<P>
   PageExpress, a new service from The New York Times Syndicate,
consists of paginated pages built with content from Cox Newspapers
and The New York Times News Service. The pages are easy to retrieve
from a web site. You can use them just as they are or customize any
or all of the elements _ text, fonts, photos and graphics _ to suit
your needs.
</P>
<P>
   For more information on these pages, or to view a sample, use
your web browser to visit http://nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   For the password to download and use the pages, call Bob Farnell
at The New York Times Syndicate: 800-972-3550 or e-mail him at
farnellb &LR; nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Unless otherwise noted, pages are available after 2 p.m. Tue.,
April 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOCUS (Available by 2 p.m., Fri., April 16) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page will include two color photos.
</P>
<P>
   MURDER IN A SMALL TOWN: A multiple murder shakes up a small town
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Available by 2 p.m., Thu., April 15):
</P>
<P>
   Page will include five color photos, 1 color graphic.
</P>
<P>
   THE RETURN OF ROLLER DERBY: The crowd is screaming, the
announcers are hyperventilating, the skaters are rolling around on
the floor pulling each other's hair. Roller derby _ that
blue-collar brawler of a quasi-sport (and television staple) _ has
returned. (Includes two color photos of roller derby action.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PHANTOM MENACE COUNTDOWN: A 2-column color graphic,
``Countdown to 'Star Wars,''' outlining the number of days
remaining until ``The Phantom Menace'' opens.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: VIDEO REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CD REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NASCAR (Available by 5 p.m., Thu., April 15) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page will include four color photographs, one 2-column color
illustration and two 6-pica thumbs-up, thumbs down illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR LEAD STORY: To be determined. Art will include 3-column
color photo. WITH:
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH SERIES NOTES
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRACK GRAPHIC: A 2-column color illustration of
Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: WINSTON CUP STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BUSCH GRAND NATIONAL STANDINGS
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RACE AT A GLANCE: A preview of Sunday's Goody's 500 at
Martinsville Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOOD &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes five color photographs and two color illustrations
</P>
<P>
   PIZZA POINTERS: Ever wondered how hard it really is to throw a
disc of dough in the air and have it come back down in one piece,
in your hands, not on the floor? Well, pizza dough is floppier to
throw than a Frisbee or a basketball, but with the right advice,
it's not that hard. (Includes 3-column color photo of basketball
players holding pizza dough, and two illustrations of basketballs.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Tips for making the perfect pizza. (Includes four 1-column
photos depicting the steps in making a pizza.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPES: Pizza Dough, Quick Tomato Pizza Sauce.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: CYBERSPICE: Searching the Internet for ``seasonal eating''
produces a wealth of sites, some with helpful advice on how to
incorporate seasonal cooking into your routine and many with
wonderful recipes incorporating seasonal foods.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: RECIPE: Asparagus Parmigiano-Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHEELS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes three color photos.
</P>
<P>
   OLDSMOBILE ALERO: After more than 100 years in the business,
Oldsmobile has finally decided to do something about those pesky,
sales-eroding imports and rolled out an all-new car to fight them:
the 1999 Alero. (Includes 3-column color photograph of Alero's
exterior and a 2-column color photo of Alero's interior.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: AT A GLANCE: Fact box previewing the Oldsmobile Alero.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: THE MECHANIC: My appreciation of and fondness for
automobiles began long before I entered the field of auto
mechanics. My love affair with cars began when I was a mere child.
(Includes 1-column color mug shot of columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PERSONAL TECHNOLOGY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes seven color photos
</P>
<P>
   CHATTERBOTS: A new twist on an old technology is being used to
create human-like guides to Web sites. Chatterbots are programs
fueled by artificial intelligence software, which has been around
since the 1970s but never found a practical use. (Includes four
2-column color photos of a woman using chatterbox technology.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: NET WATCH: Just as TV can bring graphic depictions of war
and its aftermath to people around the world, the Internet can
provide breadth and depth of content regarding the conflict in
Kosovo. (Includes a 1-column color photo of refugees in a camp near
the Macedonian border.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECH NOTES: Are you in the market for a $2.5 million,
single-engine turboprop but just don't have the time to shop? A Web
site, www.buythebest.com, might be worth checking out. The site is
devoted to the really expensive and mildly practical. (Includes
2-column color photo of web site www.buythebest.com.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TECHNOBUDDY: The Internet and the computer world are being
bombarded regularly by meteor showers when it comes to viruses and
other malicious programs designed to invade your privacy or destroy
information on your hard disk. You need to know how to defend
yourself against such attacks. (Includes 1 column color mug shot of
columnist.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TRAVEL &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes three color photographs, one 2-column
illustration.
</P>
<P>
   A TALE OF TWO ALAMOS: There are two Alamos in Texas. One, you
have probably seen. The other, probably not. One is where the
legend was born and the other was born out of that legend.
Together, they make a whole; they tell the tale. (Includes 4-column
and 2-column color photos of Alamo Village, 1-column color photo of
tourists at Alamo Village.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MAP: A 2-column color map showing how to get to Alamo
Village
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FACT BOX: Facts pertaining to the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FACT BOX: Recommended books related to the Alamo.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS: Charleston, S.C., has been making news in
the performing arts since it staged America's first opera in 1735,
and this spring, the 300-year-old city will welcome dancers,
musicians and actors and their audiences for the 23rd Spoleto
Festival U.S.A.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes two B&AMP;W photos, four color photos
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA STORY: The idea was for the good guys _ U.S. Army
Rangers and supersecret Delta Force warriors _ to buzz into
Somalia, nab a couple of the warlord's lackeys and return to the
base in time for dinner. A milk run. But mistakes, as they say,
were made. Mistakes that led to the worst firefight involving
American soldiers since Vietnam. In ``Black Hawk Down: A Story of
Modern War,'' Mark Bowden tells of the events on the streets of
Mogadishu on Oct. 3, 1993, in visceral detail. It's a lucid,
authoritative account of the raid that's great military history and
great nonfiction storytelling. (Includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo of
soldiers standing by helicopter, 1-column B&AMP;W photo of beaten
soldier captured by Somali forces and a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: MICHAEL JORDAN: In ``Playing for Keeps,'' David
Halberstam documents Michael Jordan's rise as both a basketball
player and as a corporate commodity. Along the way, Halberstam
reveals how the NBA resurrected itself under Commissioner David
Stern, how the all-sports cable network ESPN came into being and
how Spike Lee found himself directing a Nike commercial _ while
also creating a basketball superhero. (Includes 2-column color
photo of Michael Jordan and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: CRIME: When it comes to dissecting the narrative
ideal, journalist Janet Malcolm is a top surgeon, perhaps the best.
She now turns her steely eye to the flawed narratives of trial law
in ``The Crime of Sheila McGough.'' (Includes 6-pica color photo of
book jacket)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes two color photos and one color graphic
(information box).
</P>
<P>
   GROUND ZERO FOR THE UNIVERSE: Some scientists who study the
universe without regard to the theories of creationists are
beginning to ask if Something did, after all, create everything _
not in six days of cosmic spectacle a few thousand years ago but in
the instantaneous ``big bang'' billions of years ago. (Includes a
3-column color photo of space taken from the Hubble Telescope.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FLORIDA STORMS: The great storms from earlier this century
are found only in fading snapshots. But if those storms were to
strike today, they would hammer a Florida of 15 million people,
gleaming megalopolises and coastlines packed shoulder-to-shoulder
with luxury high-rises. Researchers studied the economic impact of
the century's most ferocious storms as if they had hit today.
Adjusting for inflation, growth and increased property values, they
found that seven of the 11 costliest storms and 13 of the top 30
were storms that hit Florida. (Includes a 1-column color photo of
hurricane flags.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SIDS RISKS: Southeastern states continue to be a trouble
spot in the national public health campaign to reduce Sudden Infant
Death Syndrome, according to experts who met recently in Atlanta.
(Includes a 2-column color information box on steps to take to
reduce risks of SIDS.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MILLENNIUM BABY: If you are thinking it would be nice to
deliver your next child on Jan. 1, 2000, stop reading and get busy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: The recycling movement in America is being
hindered by government subsidies and tax breaks for industries
whose products compete with recycled materials, a coalition of tax
reform advocates, environmentalists and recycling groups recently
charged.
</P>
</TEXT>
