<P>
   &UR; BOOKS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes two B&AMP;W photos, four color photos
</P>
<P>
   SOMALIA STORY: The idea was for the good guys _ U.S. Army
Rangers and supersecret Delta Force warriors _ to buzz into
Somalia, nab a couple of the warlord's lackeys and return to the
base in time for dinner. A milk run. But mistakes, as they say,
were made. Mistakes that led to the worst firefight involving
American soldiers since Vietnam. In ``Black Hawk Down: A Story of
Modern War,'' Mark Bowden tells of the events on the streets of
Mogadishu on Oct. 3, 1993, in visceral detail. It's a lucid,
authoritative account of the raid that's great military history and
great nonfiction storytelling. (Includes 3-column B&AMP;W photo of
soldiers standing by helicopter, 1-column B&AMP;W photo of beaten
soldier captured by Somali forces and a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: MICHAEL JORDAN: In ``Playing for Keeps,'' David
Halberstam documents Michael Jordan's rise as both a basketball
player and as a corporate commodity. Along the way, Halberstam
reveals how the NBA resurrected itself under Commissioner David
Stern, how the all-sports cable network ESPN came into being and
how Spike Lee found himself directing a Nike commercial _ while
also creating a basketball superhero. (Includes 2-column color
photo of Michael Jordan and 6-pica color photo of book jacket.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW: CRIME: When it comes to dissecting the narrative
ideal, journalist Janet Malcolm is a top surgeon, perhaps the best.
She now turns her steely eye to the flawed narratives of trial law
in ``The Crime of Sheila McGough.'' (Includes 6-pica color photo of
book jacket)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &AMP; HEALTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Page includes two color photos and one color graphic
(information box).
</P>
<P>
   GROUND ZERO FOR THE UNIVERSE: Some scientists who study the
universe without regard to the theories of creationists are
beginning to ask if Something did, after all, create everything _
not in six days of cosmic spectacle a few thousand years ago but in
the instantaneous ``big bang'' billions of years ago. (Includes a
3-column color photo of space taken from the Hubble Telescope.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: FLORIDA STORMS: The great storms from earlier this century
are found only in fading snapshots. But if those storms were to
strike today, they would hammer a Florida of 15 million people,
gleaming megalopolises and coastlines packed shoulder-to-shoulder
with luxury high-rises. Researchers studied the economic impact of
the century's most ferocious storms as if they had hit today.
Adjusting for inflation, growth and increased property values, they
found that seven of the 11 costliest storms and 13 of the top 30
were storms that hit Florida. (Includes a 1-column color photo of
hurricane flags.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SIDS RISKS: Southeastern states continue to be a trouble
spot in the national public health campaign to reduce Sudden Infant
Death Syndrome, according to experts who met recently in Atlanta.
(Includes a 2-column color information box on steps to take to
reduce risks of SIDS.)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: MILLENNIUM BABY: If you are thinking it would be nice to
deliver your next child on Jan. 1, 2000, stop reading and get busy.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: HEALTH BRIEFS: The recycling movement in America is being
hindered by government subsidies and tax breaks for industries
whose products compete with recycled materials, a coalition of tax
reform advocates, environmentalists and recycling groups recently
charged.
</P>
