<HEADLINE>
HEADING FOR THE GREAT OUTDOORS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Grab your gear. We're getting away.
</P>
<P>
   We're going off the interstate. Leaving behind the daily grind.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to get back to nature. Back to basics. Back to fun.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps you already knew that.
</P>
<P>
   Recent surveys show that nature-related trips represent the
fastest-growing segment of the travel industry.
</P>
<P>
   Among findings:
</P>
<P>
   __ Camping is Americans' favorite outdoor activity.
</P>
<P>
   __ Each year, more than 300 million visitors pour into our 56
national parks.
</P>
<P>
   __ About 27 million people rolled away on biking vacations in
the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   __ One-half of U.S. adults (that's 98 million people) have taken
an adventure vacation during the same period. About 31 million
engaged in a ``hard'' adventure activity, such as white-water
rafting or mountain biking.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, experts say, an estimated 18 million Texans a year will
participate in nature tourism.
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for families, suggests Mark Evans, co-owner of
Texas River Expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``An outdoors adventure is one that eliminates television,
computers, phones and Nintendo,'' he says. ``People get back to
each other with nothing between them. They start talking and
interacting and playing. Then they can begin really enjoying one
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry about being a stranger to the great outdoors, says
Evans, whose rafting trips in Texas, Colorado and Idaho frequently
include camping novices.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recently did four family adventures,'' he says. ``Each
six-day trip had 25 guests. Of those 100, 22 had never been camping
before in their lives. Out of those 22, 15 are coming back on
another trip this year with us. They're taking shorter trips, but
they're coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   There are some caveats.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're expecting room service in your tent, you won't be
happy,'' Evans says. ``If you expect to be waited on hand and foot,
you won't like it. But if you want to have a new experience
outdoors and have a little adventure with it, you'll enjoy
yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The most important maxim for the outdoors novice, according to
Evans: ``Go with an open mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Options for a nature-oriented vacation are seemingly endless: a
weekend getaway to one of Texas' 122 state parks, a monthlong trek
in Nepal, a surf holiday in Hawaii, kayaking with whales in Canada,
rock climbing in Nevada, scuba diving in Lake Superior,
photographing giraffes in Botswana.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you'd just prefer to watch the kids splash in the
shallow waters of a river while lunch sizzles on a grill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Families today want adventure, but without the hassle,'' says
Andy Alpine, co-publisher of Specialty Travel Index. ``Trips need
to be geared to all ages and interests. Parents also need some
stress-free time alone, as well as quality time shared with the
kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Specialty Travel Index is a biannual publication that lists more
than 600 tour operators; it's available at many bookstores and
newsstands or can be accessed online at www.specialtytravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   You can get a good introduction to the gamut of nature
activities at next month's Texas Fly Fishing &AMP; Outdoor Show at
Aquarena Springs in San Marcos, sponsored by the Texas Parks &AMP;
Wildlife Department.
</P>
<P>
   The May 21-23 event promises a variety of activities for all
ages, including hands-on instruction in nature photography,
bird-watching and kayaking. In addition to dozens of
fishing-related classes, participants can take lessons in river
ecology, snorkeling and canoeing.
</P>
<P>
   Admission is $10, $25 for three days ($5 and $10 for children).
Class fees range from $4 to $65. Call 830-895-2424 or access
www.tpwd.state.tx.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
