<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTSIDE-PREPARE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BE PREPARED TO BATTLE ELEMENTS OUTDOORS 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Lions, tigers and bears are not your worst enemies
when you venture into the great outdoors.
</P>
<P>
   Think more of sun, bugs and unpreparedness.
</P>
<P>
   First, let's talk about the sun.
</P>
<P>
   It can take just 15 minutes of exposure to cause a bad burn. And
even a cloudy day is not without risk. Short of going nocturnal,
your best defense is covering up and slathering on.
</P>
<P>
   For clothing, invest in a wide-brimmed hat or cap and look for
lightweight and light-colored cottons that will protect from the
sun's rays while still feeling comfortable in heat and humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Your sunscreen should have an SPF (sun protection factor) of 15.
If you are going to be in the sun for prolonged periods, consider a
sunscreen with an SPF of 30 or higher.
</P>
<P>
   Use sunscreen early and often. Experts recommend applying it 15
to 30 minutes prior to exposure. And reapply sunscreen frequently,
particularly if you're in the water.
</P>
<P>
   Also pay attention to the clock. The sun's rays are at their
most intense from 10 a.m. to 4 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Be aware that some prescription medicines may make you more
vulnerable to sunburns. Antihistamines, sulfa drugs, diuretics and
some oral contraceptives are among those of concern. Consult your
doctor or pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   Eyes also can be damaged by overexposure. Wear sunglasses.
</P>
<P>
   If you do get a sunburn, the best treatments are aspirin and
soaking in cool water. Cortisone cream and other over-the-counter
lotions may provide temporary relief of sunburn pain.
</P>
<P>
   Watch out for for signs of sun allergy, which may appear like a
rash. If your sunburn seems to be getting worse several days after
exposure, you may have a sun allergy. Consult a physician.
</P>
<P>
   Other risks for sun lovers and outdoor enthusiasts are
dehydration and heatstroke. Combat these with water.
</P>
<P>
   Stay hydrated. Drink fluids even when you don't feel thirsty.
Take frequent breaks and get out of the sun. Wearing a brimmed hat
and clothing that allows perspiration to evaporate quickly will
help, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bugs are the bane of many outdoor adventures. Not only are
mosquitoes and ticks pests, but the creatures also can transmit
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Mosquitoes are most active early in the morning and at dusk. Be
prepared. Use a repellent that contains the chemical DEET. But
check with a doctor before applying any repellent on young
children. Often a better way is to apply it to their clothing, not
their skin.
</P>
<P>
   To avoid ticks, wear light-colored clothing as it makes the
blood-suckers easier to spot. Wear long-sleeved shirts and pants
and tuck your pants into your socks. Pest repellents that contain
DEET also can help.
</P>
<P>
   When outdoors, make frequent inspections for ticks. If you find
one, remove it carefully using tweezers. For best results, grasp
the pest as close to the skin as possible and pull with a slow,
steady motion. Rather than yanking it off, the goal is for the tick
to let go. Never squeeze the tick's body.
</P>
<P>
   Most important to a good nature-oriented vacation is being
prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Make sure you're ready for your holiday with pre-trip
conditioning. Biking, hiking and canoeing are just a few of the
activities that require physical stamina. Sore muscles and injuries
can ruin a vacation.
</P>
<P>
   If you are planning on hiking and backpacking, start a walking
regimen several weeks before your holiday. As your vacation
approaches, you may want to start carrying a backpack for trial
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Planning a beach holiday or rafting trip? Brush up on your
swimming skills. If you have children, consider taking a
water-safety course.
</P>
<P>
   No matter your destination, pack a first aid kit. You can buy or
customize a kit, and it should include protective gloves; plastic
bandage strips in several sizes; mole skin, gauze and first-aid
tape; antihistamines; aspirin, ibuprofen or other anti-fever and
anti-inflammatories; eye wash; tweezers and scissors; Imodium and
antacids.
</P>
<P>
   Be sure to pack spare glasses and contact lenses, as well as
extra prescription medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Last but not least, watch your alcohol intake. Alcohol can
increase your chances of dehydration. And whether you are operating
a recreational vehicle, a boat or bicycle, drinking and driving is
a no-no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
