<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SELLING-STARWARS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`STAR WARS' WAS A HARD SELL LONG AGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARLA MATZER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's inescapable. Whenever you turn on the TV or
look at a magazine or newspaper, ``Star Wars'' is there.
</P>
<P>
   Swanky Vanity Fair gave readers an upfront peek at the upcoming
movie with pages of photos. ``60 Minutes'' recently devoted not
one, but two program segments to George Lucas and his movie
franchise. Even fashionista bible Vogue featured ``Star Wars
Style.'' And that was all several months in advance of the film's
release.
</P>
<P>
   ``I liken this job to an avalanche,'' says Jim Ward, head of
marketing for Lucasfilm. ``We're all just trying to make sure
nobody gets crushed underneath it.''
</P>
<P>
   But long, long ago, in ... Van Nuys, where Lucas' Industrial
Light &AMP; Magic was first located, it was a different story.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science fiction was considered a very minor genre,'' says
Charles Lippincott, president of Creative Movie Marketing and head
of marketing for Lucas on the first film. Lippincott had met both
Lucas and ``Star Wars'' producer Gary Kurtz at USC's film school
and had done publicity for Alfred Hitchcock before working on
``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than `2001' and `Planet of the Apes,' there hadn't been
any real hits,'' says Lippincott. ``When we showed it to theater
owners (at an event put on by distributor Twentieth Century Fox),
the `big cigars' were like, `What is this? Where's Jacqueline
Bisset in her wet T-shirt?' (referring to 1977's `The Deep').''
</P>
<P>
   On May 19, ``Star Wars: Episode I _ The Phantom Menace'' will
open on about 4,000 screens. Lucas and Fox, which is also
distributing the new movies, reportedly have attached a long list
of conditions to exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's not a theater owner in the country who's not
dying to open ``Phantom''; they're all hoping that they'll be among
those anointed with the honor when theaters are announced (expected
to be this week).
</P>
<P>
   Theater owners in 1977 were so downbeat on ``Star Wars'' that
the movie opened on only 32 screens in the U.S. It had to open in
May, rather than the more competitive month of June, just to get
that many. It was considered de rigueur to open big movies in both
Hollywood and Westwood; Lucas only got his Hollywood theater,
Mann's Chinese, at the 11th hour due to a delay in the release of
the Roy Scheider picture ``Sorcerer.''
</P>
<P>
   Science fiction and comic book fans took to ``Star Wars''
immediately and have kept the movies, books and collectibles in
high demand ever since. The thing that's different this time around
is that the rest of the world has tapped into the geek network now.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media world is so different now than it was 22 years
ago,'' says Dale Pollock, author of ``Skywalking: The Life and
Films of George Lucas,'' which is being reissued to coincide with
``Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no E! Entertainment channel (22 years ago). There
was no Internet ... Fans discovered the Internet as a way of
communicating between themselves, and now Lucasfilm has learned to
use it, too,'' adds Pollock, now dean of North Carolina School of
the Arts' film school.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Phantom Menace'' movie trailer that started playing in
theaters late last year was instantly so popular that fans were
said to be buying tickets to shows just to see the trailer. Fans
and the media have analyzed every second of the trailer for clues
to the upcoming movie. An apparently stolen copy of the trailer was
auctioned off online for hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the original ``Star Wars'' trailer that started
playing in theaters around Christmas 1976 was laughed off the
screen. In ``Skywalking,'' Pollock writes that the response to the
trailer, in Westwood at least, was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (diminutive robot) R2-D2 fell over, there were giggles
and laughter. At the end, when it said, `Coming to your galaxy this
summer,' the audience groaned,'' recalls Ashley Boone, who was head
of marketing for Fox when ``Star Wars'' came out.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there was no buzz around ``Star Wars'' 22
years ago. Lippincott struck a comic book deal with Marvel for a
series of comics to launch in March 1977. It was very unusual at
that time for a movie to have such a pact prior to release, and
``Fox just thought it was dumb,'' Lippincott recalls. In another
unusual move, he took ``Star Wars'' posters and buttons selling for
$1 apiece to science fiction and comic conventions in the months
leading up to the film's release. Promoting movies at fan
conventions has since become commonplace.
</P>
<P>
   By the spring, word had started to get out that Lucas might have
a big hit on his hands, though no one could have predicted it would
become the top-grossing film to date at that time. Publicity,
including a six-page layout in Time magazine the week before the
movie opened, resulted in lines around the block at theaters.
</P>
<P>
   The final piece of the puzzle was merchandising and promotions.
Studios considered these areas peripheral in 1977, but merchandise
in particular would end up making Lucas very rich.
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola promoted the movie that summer with things like themed
cups at McDonald's. But it was small potatoes compared to today. In
1997, Pepsico announced it would devote a staggering $2 billion in
promotion to the prequels, including extensive TV advertising.
</P>
<P>
   In a very shrewd move, Lucas negotiated to retain the rights to
``Star Wars'' merchandise. While there had been entertainment-tied
merchandise for decades _ from Mickey Mouse to Howdy Doody _ ``Star
Wars'' would create a new benchmark for the merchandising of
live-action films.
</P>
<P>
   In May 1977, there were no ``Star Wars'' toys on the shelves at
all. While millions of posters, T-shirts, books and comic books
flew out of stores that summer, the toy deal with Kenner (since
bought by Hasbro) wasn't finalized until April 1977. All fans could
get for Christmas that year was a certificate guaranteeing them an
action figure when they became available in early 1978.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Phantom Menace,'' there will be dozens of toys on the
shelves by the time the movie opens. Hasbro and Galoob Toys _ which
has since been bought by Hasbro _ gave Lucasfilm a combined $225
million in stock and guarantees of at least tens of millions more
for the rights to make ``Star Wars'' toys. Lego's ``Star Wars''
sets have been best sellers since March, and fans are so eager for
the new batch of action figures that pirated images of the toys
have been circulating on the Internet for weeks in advance of the
toys actually hitting stores.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Lucasfilm maintains it's trying to contain the huge
buildup to the release of ``Phantom.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of studios would have been promoting this a year and a
half out,'' says Ward. ``They would have been doing things like
advertising on the Super Bowl. We purposely haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Forbes magazine estimated that Lucasfilm, if it
were publicly traded, would be valued at about $5 billion. It's too
bad for investors that the company is private _ but that's exactly
the way George Lucas wants it. He ultimately answers to no one but
moviegoers, which may be the biggest secret to his success. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
