<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR TUESDAY, APRIL 13
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Tuesday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(gc) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-NYT (moved on Saturday, Apr. 10)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Saturday, Apr. 10,
about reports from Kosovo refugees who said Serbian troops were
herding Albanians into a town near the Macedonian border referred
incompletely to the availability of confirmation from foreign
journalists in Kosovo. While many foreign journalists were expelled
soon after NATO began its bombing of Serbia on March 24, some
remain. Paul Watson, for example, has been filing dispatches for
The Los Angeles Times from Pristina, the Kosovo capital, but not on
that specific subject.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MICROSOFT-DIGITAL-MUSIC-NYT (moved on Sunday, Apr. 11)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, Apr. 11,
about Microsoft's plan to deliver music files over the Internet
misstated the amount the company invested recently in Reciprocal
Inc., a maker of technology to protect digital copyrights. It was
$15 million, not $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MAYER-NYT (moved on Friday, Apr. 9)
</P>
<P>
   The obituary of Helen Aberson Mayer, sent by the New York Times
News Service on Friday, Apr. 9, misstated the role of Harold Pearl
in creating the book. Pearl, a journalist who died in 1975, was the
co-author, not the illustrator.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-INTERNET-PRESCRIPTIONS-NYT (moved on Monday, Apr. 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Apr. 5,
about the dispensing of drugs on the Internet misidentified the one
ordered on line from a Spanish pharmacy by Keith Lamb of Columbus,
Ohio, who suffers from back pain. It was codeine, not oxycodone.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-CHOOSING-MATES-NYT (moved on Monday, Mar. 29)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, Mar. 29,
about evolutionary psychology misstated the affiliation of Dr.
David Buss, a leading researcher in the field. He is at the
University of Texas at Austin, not the University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   The essay also referred incompletely to his research methods. To
study the mating preferences of human beings, Dr. Buss and his
colleagues distributed questionnaires to some 10,000 people,
ranging in age from 14 to 71, in 37 countries; analyzed personal
ads and marriage statistics, and performed field studies and lab
experiments. The subjects of the questionnaires were not all
college students, and questionnaires were not the sole method used.
</P>
</TEXT>
