<HEADER>
A6389 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-CABLE-0414-C     04-13 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-CABLE-0414-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INTERNET ACCESS BATTLE REACHES CONGRESS
 &HT;    Moving in (f) financial and (w) Washington categories
 &HT;    By MARY BETH REGAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - In a step toward tackling a battle over high-speed
Internet access, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) will ask regulators to
study whether the technology will benefit all U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, chairman of the powerful Senate Commerce Committee, said
Tuesday he would introduce legislation requiring regulators to
study patterns of high-speed Internet access nationwide. The action
came after a two-and-half-hour hearing that pitted cable companies
against Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   The packed hearing focused on the battle between the industries
over whether cable operators should be required to open high-speed
data lines to companies such as America Online and Atlanta-based
MindSpring Enterprises in much the same way telephone companies
must carry traffic of competitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission, which has regulatory
power on the issue, has declined to get into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the most critical issues that we face today,''
said McCain. ``And it is important to ensure that the enormous
benefits of advanced telecommunications services are accessible to
all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other issues, McCain wants the FCC and the Commerce
Department's National Telecommunications Infrastructure
Administration to study whether broadband technology deployment
patterns could lead to ``telecom redlining,'' in which companies
avoid investing in low-income, rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   Such action would make it nearly impossible for residents in
rural, low-income areas to ride the information superhighway.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and other committee membersalso solicited recommendations
from industry executives about how to settle the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, recommendations ranged from cable operators'
call for a hands-off, market-based approach to Internet service
providers' suggestions for a ``light-touch'' regulatory scheme that
guarantees them access to high-speed cable lines.
</P>
<P>
   James O. Robbins, president and chief executive officer of
Atlanta-based Cox Communications, a publicly traded sister company
to Cox Newspapers, stressed that cable operators are entering a
highly competitive, new marketplace that requires billions of
dollars in investments.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Communications, for example, has spent $4 billion to date
building a high-speed data network. If Dulles, Va.-based America
Online or other Internet service providers want to use that
network, those deals should be negotiated between companies,
Robbins said. Government intervention ``would dry up investment''
and stall the growth of the Internet and e-commerce, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen M. Case, America Online's chairman and chief executive
officer, argued that the cable industry maintains a monopoly grip
on high-speed data lines. Today, Internet service providers can
only connect consumers to the Internet by using telephone or cable
lines. Telephone companies are required to allow those providers to
connect to consumers. Cable operators don't have the same
obligation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a country are confronted with a choice: Do we preserve
the open Internet marketplace...or do we move toward a closed
marketplace where success is determined by ownership of the wires
into the home?'' asked Case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable is requiring consumers who want a high-speed cable
connection to the Internet to buy the Internet service affiliated
with the local cable company,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other witnesses included Charles Brewer, chairman and chief
executive officer of MindSpring Enterprises, William L. Schrader,
chairman and chief executive officer of PSINet, Herndon, Va., and
Solomon Trujillo, president and chief executive officer of U.S.
West Communications, Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, who supported Case's position, was encouraged by
McCain's plan to introduce legislation. ``There's been a call for
action,'' Brewer said, ``And I see that as positive.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
