<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPROUTS-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BALM FOR SPRING FEVER? MICRO GREENS ARE READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Union Square Greenmarket shows all the symptoms
of serious spring. There's the fellow stripped to the waist
sunbathing, and there are the young women in pastel sleeveless
shirts eating ice cream as they stroll through on their lunch hour.
And especially, there are the riotous spring flowers: magnolias,
hyacinths, daffodils and tulips.
</P>
<P>
   So, why was there no asparagus in Union Square last Wednesday?
Where was the rhubarb? Why was the spinach still from the
greenhouse?
</P>
<P>
   At supermarkets now, asparagus is the hot seasonal item;
counters are heaped with strawberries, and rhubarb is placed right
next to them, along with ready-made pie shells. Most of us have
become so used to having whatever fruits and vegetables we want
whenever we want them that we have forgotten all about seasonality.
Those under 40 likely never knew it.
</P>
<P>
   The sobering reminder of the limitations of the Middle Atlantic
climate is the Greenmarket, still dominated this week by apples and
root vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are as anxious to rid your menus of root vegetables
as you are to shed your winter coat, if your palate is longing for
something tender instead of hearty, the market does have edible
signs of spring, even though they aren't quite authentic. The Hydro
Garden Farm stall sells mustard flowers, and everything at the
Windfall Farm stand has that tender young green look that comes
with the first leaves on the trees and the earliest blades of
grass.
</P>
<P>
   These sprightly collections of micro greens, the very first
leaves of plants, will certainly make you think of spring, even
though every leaf, with the exception of the chives and garlic
chives, was grown in a greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing and matching these micro greens is a wonderful new way to
play with your food. Even though virtually no nutrition information
exists for them, they are vegetables-in-waiting, so likely provide
some of the same nutrients.
</P>
<P>
   I bought all that were available: corn, with an intense raw corn
flavor that finishes with sweetness; crunchy sunflower that tastes
like its seeds; slightly peppery mizuna; broccoli, with the taste
of raw broccoli or cauliflower; arugula with a surprisingly strong
peppery finish; pea shoots that taste like tender raw English peas,
and watercress, the most peppery of all.
</P>
<P>
   I also bought grassy chickweed _ the stuff you thought you
didn't want in your lawn, along with chives, garlic chives and the
mustard flowers, which are like very delicate mustard greens.
</P>
<P>
   I tried dozens of combinations of these micro greens, with and
without olive oil, with and without oil and balsamic vinegar.
Alone, the greens are not that exciting, but a good extra virgin
olive oil brings out the best in them. If you use vinegar at all
you need only a drop for a salad for two; otherwise the flavor of
the greens is lost.
</P>
<P>
   The following combinations for micro green salads were
particularly harmonious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mizuna, broccoli and a very small amount of corn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arugula, sunflower and pea shoots.
</P>
<P>
   _ Broccoli, mustard flowers and chives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Chickweed, pea shoots and garlic chives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mustard flowers and a very small amount of corn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mizuna, chickweed and corn.
</P>
<P>
   _ Arugula, mizuna and pea shoots.
</P>
<P>
   Right next to the Windfall Farm stand I found another
nutritional windfall. Hawthorne Valley Farm, from the Hudson
Valley, makes wonderful cheese, yogurt and quark, a low-calorie,
low-fat version of cream cheese that is thicker than sour cream and
contains some of its tartness.
</P>
<P>
   Mixed with chives and garlic chives, it makes a delicious
alternative to cream cheese for bagels. Mix two tablespoons of
chopped chives with half a cup of quark, and you'll save 30-plus
calories and half the fat (3.5 grams instead of 7) for each
two-tablespoon serving.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1556EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
