<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0143 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6395 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAW-EGGS-ART-2TAKES-N     04-13 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAW-EGGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE EGG AND I, I, I, I, I, I, I 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Va., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By RICK MARIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Nothing unusual about the egg yolk staring up at me
from a plate of pasta at Babbo one night last week. Except that the
egg was raw. Totally uncooked. Cold. This was a little
disconcerting at first, but, once mixed in with the buttery pasta
and bacony chunks of cured pork, the egg and the dish warmed up
into an irrisistible indulgence, with an aftertaste of danger.
Because raw eggs can kill you.
</P>
<P>
   Or so we have been told.
</P>
<P>
   They have certainly taken a beating over the last decade, ever
since scientists discovered that Salmonella enteritidis, the
food-borne bacteria, could be transmitted from the inside, as well
as the outside, of the eggshell.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey Health Department went so far as to order
restaurants not to serve eggs soft-boiled or over easy. California
passed a law prohibiting restaurants from serving them raw or
undercooked. The authorities were cracking down, and home cooks
followed. They deprived themselves of fresh mayonnaise and
hollandaise, regarding them as practically toxic substances, and
forgot all about homemade chocolate mousse, ice cream and eggnog.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, you couldn't even get a proper caesar salad anymore.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past year or so, raw eggs have begun showing up on
menus all over the city. As diners have become more adventurous _
consuming seared tuna, the rarest of steaks and salmon tartare
without repercussions _ a little runny egg on the plate stopped
looking so perilous.
</P>
<P>
   And, for most people, it isn't: only 1 in 20,000 eggs is
contaminated with the salmonella bacteria, according to government
statistics. If you are unlucky enough to get that one egg, and you
are a healthy adult, you are risking symptoms much like a stomach
flu.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from the menus, and diners' reactions to them, more
people seem willing to take the risk. At Bolivar, on the Upper East
Side, the a lobster stew called chupa contains a poached egg just
waiting to be broken into the hot broth. A touch of the spoon sends
the yolk running bright and liquid into the broth and vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Brasserie Julien, also on the Upper East Side, serves its frisee
salad with lardons in the traditional French style, coated with the
liquid of an egg whose fragile flesh has been subjected to boiling
water no more than three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dale DeGroff, who was the bartender at the Rainbow Room and is
now at Blackbird in midtown, will be serving flips _ a 19th-century
pick-me-up mixing raw eggs with whisky, port or brandy.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Blauberg, the chef at the ``21'' Club, reports a revival of
requests for caesar salad and steak tartare, a house specialty.
</P>
<P>
   And a spinach salad with shaved lamb's tongue at Po, Babbo's
sister restaurant in Greenwich Village, came with a lightly poached
egg in the center, before the spring menu put the salad and that
pasta on hiatus.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be back,'' said Andy Nusser, the chef at Babbo. Nusser
said he had encountered no squeamishness from customers confronted
with a cold, raw egg in their noodles. ``It's just so perfect,
people can't argue with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt some people could, and certainly would have not so long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Blauberg of ``21'' said: ``Everybody used to ask, `Is there raw
egg in that?' Especially in the caesar, so I did it without the
egg.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the egg is back in the caesar at ``21,'' tossed, as always,
tableside. For the tartare _ a ``twofer'' in terms of gastronomical
promiscuity _ the raw egg is mixed into the raw meat in the
kitchen, before the plate is carried into the dining room.
</P>
<P>
   In August, California, that stringently health-conscious state,
eased up a law enacted in January 1998 that had banned restaurants
from serving raw or undercooked eggs. Under the revised statute,
exceptions can be made if the customer has been informed by the
waiter or with a note on the menu, that a dish contains such an
egg.
</P>
<P>
   If we as diners didn't get safer, did the eggs?
</P>
<P>
   A new study published in the Centers for Disease Control's
Morbidity and Mortality Report shows that between 1996 and 1998,
there has been a 44 percent drop in reported cases of salmonella
poisoning. The last major outbreak was in 1994, when 400 people in
16 states were sickened by Schwann's ice cream, the mix for which
had been transported in tanker trucks that had previously contained
raw eggs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The big scare before that was set off when four residents of a
New Jersey nursing home died after drinking salmonella-infected
eggnog. That was in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a reduction in the number of food-borne illnesses
associated with egg-based consumption,'' said Steven Grover, the
director of technical services and public health at the National
Restaurant Association, and a former public health and safety
regulator for the Virginia State Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   Grover said that ``eggs are quite a bit safer than they used to
be,'' thanks to refrigeration (people used to transport and leave
eggs lying around at room temperature) and more scrupulous
screening of the chickens.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to eat them for 20 years to run into one bad egg,''
he said. And then, the symptoms for healthy adults are stomach
aches, maybe diarrhea.
</P>
<P>
   Small children, the elderly or people with compromised immune
systems are more susceptible, and Grover advises they avoid raw
eggs.
</P>
<P>
   The American Egg Board in Park Ridge, Ill., follows Department
of Agriculture guidelines, a more conservative guideline, said
Elisa Maloberti, a spokesperson. ``We don't endorse the consumption
of raw eggs,'' she said. ``They are a perishable protein product,
and they can support bacteria growth.''
</P>
<P>
   That means cooking the eggs until they reach a temperature of at
least 140 degrees to kill any bacteria. At that temperature, the
whites are completely set, and the yolks have begun to thicken (the
center can still be runny).
</P>
<P>
   Many cookbooks, including the new ``Hay Day Country Market
Cookbook,'' by Kim Rizk (Workman, $13.95), take a similarly
cautious line. Suzanne Rafer, an editor at Ms. Rizk's publisher,
Workman, said most of her authors prepared caesar salads either
with hard-boiled eggs or none at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always say if something is made with a raw egg, we always
state it,'' Ms. Rafer said, ``and if a reader is unsure of the
quality of the eggs they buy, they should probably stay away from
that particular recipe.''
</P>
<P>
   The gray, or rather yellow, area between raw and cooked is
something many eaters of eggs seem to ignore. ``I don't know that a
raw egg is any less safe than those sunny-side-up eggs that people
eat every morning,'' Ms. Rafer said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the risk is the same _ if the eggs don't reach 140
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   But as for the chances of getting sick, Jill Snowdon, the
director of food-safety programs at the Egg Nutrition Center in
Washington, said, ``It depends on the quality of the egg and the
susceptability of the consumer.'' The odds, as in most of life's
actuarial gambles, favor healthy adults.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind _ along with Oscar Wilde's remark that ``an
egg is always an adventure'' _ I embarked on an egg binge.
Bolivar's chupa, washed down with a pisco saura, the frothy
Peruvian cocktail mixed with Chilean brandy and safely pasteurized
egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   Babbo's haute bacon-and-eggs. The caesar (italics)and(end
italics) the tartare at ``21.'' A raw quail egg on salmon egg sushi
at Next Door Nobu in TriBeCa.
</P>
<P>
   After three days on the raw egg diet, eating everything but
Rocky Balboa's five-egg morning shake, I was unpoisoned, but logy
with a mean cholesterol hangover. I asked DeGroff, the ``master
mixologist,'' for his morning-after remedy of choice, the Prairie
Oyster. Half a teaspoon of Worscestershire sauce, a dash of
Tabasco, one teaspoon of vinager, salt and pepper _ and one raw
egg. Swallow in one gulp. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
