<SLUG> BC-SIMPLE-COOKING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUICK, INEXPENSIVE VEAL BRISKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MARK BITTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few slow-cooked foods are as rewarding as a well-cooked beef
brisket. But getting it tender, juicy and flavorful takes so long _
my favorite recipe is a 12-hour job _ that I'm lucky to do it once
a year.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I regret not discovering veal brisket sooner. It
occurred to me only recently that one can get a delicious,
relatively quick-cooking form of brisket from a breast of veal with
the bones removed.
</P>
<P>
   The breast is a common cut that can be almost ludicrously cheap
(as little as 89 cents a pound), but it is rarely sold boneless.
And with the bones in, it is difficult to handle: to serve four,
you'll need a piece of meat that is too large to fit in most pots
and that takes forever to cook.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, any butcher, including virtually every supermarket
butcher, can quickly remove the bones and present you with a flat,
relatively compact cut that contains little fat and becomes tender
about twice as fast as the same cut of beef. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ask the butcher to start with a piece of breast that weighs four
to six pounds. Boneless, it weighs about half and will easily fit
in a large skillet. (Take the bones, too _ you're paying for them,
and they are among the best for making stock.)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Once the shopping is done, the battle is over. This recipe still
requires time, but almost no work or attention.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are no tricks or subtleties here. I use dried mushrooms
because of their convenience and intensity of flavor, but you can
substitute a half pound of fresh mushrooms. And a not-too-dry white
wine, like a riesling, adds a little complexity to the finished
dish. But the real flavor is in the meat.
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED VEAL BREAST WITH MUSHROOMS
</P>
<P>
   Time: about 90 minutes  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce dried mushrooms: shiitakes, porcinis or a combination
</P>
<P>
   1 2- to 3-pound boneless veal breast
</P>
<P>
   { cup white wine
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon butter, optional.
</P>
<P>
   1. Reconstitute the mushrooms by covering them with very hot
water. Strain through a fine sieve to remove any grit. Strain the
liquid, and reserve.
</P>
<P>
   2. Turn heat under a 12-inch skillet to medium-high, and let it
sit for a minute. Add veal, and brown on both sides, turning once,
for a total of about 6 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   3. Remove meat to a plate, and turn heat to medium. Add
mushrooms and about { cup of their liquid, along with wine. Bring
to a boil, and cook about 30 seconds, then return veal to skillet.
Season with salt and pepper, turn heat to low, and cover.
</P>
<P>
   4. Cook 60 to 90 minutes, turning once or twice and checking
occasionally to make sure the liquid is bubbling slowly; adjust
heat accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   5. When meat is tender, remove it to a cutting board. Turn heat
under skillet to high, and reduce liquid to a thick, saucy
consistency. Stir in butter if desired, and keep warm. Carve meat
against the grain into slices \ inch thick, and serve with pan
juices.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 8 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
