<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEGETABLE-COLOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PAINT-BY-NUMBERS GARDEN, CORN IS RED, CARROTS YELLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD W. LANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardeners are always searching for the latest vegetable
varieties to brighten the year's crop. Cooks constantly crave the
new ingredient that thrills the taste buds while catching the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Gardeners who are cooks, and vice versa, are discovering that
they can have the best of both worlds with superb-tasting
vegetables in startling colors: red sweet corn, yellow carrots,
purple asparagus, even black tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these vegetables are antique heirloom varieties, the
baseball cards of the gardening world, which were swapped among
devotees until the seed companies started developing them for
commercial distribution in recent years. Others are new hybrids,
developed specifically to bring the avant garde to ordinary seed
packets. Either way, they allow you to grow a visual delight not
available at the grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The splashiest of these novelties is no doubt Burpee's Ruby
Queen hybrid sweet corn. This fire-engine-red corn could easily be
confused with the purely ornamental Ruby Red, which is inedible to
the point of being able to break teeth.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby Queen, whose kernels are red inside and out, is wonderfully
tender and, thanks to the tinkering of botanists, is ``sugar
enhanced'': its sugars convert into starch more slowly than older
varieties, so the corn retains its sweetness longer after picking.
</P>
<P>
   Grown in rows like regular sweet corn, Ruby Queen requires no
tricks or special care to yield its colorful bounty. But you cannot
grow it within pollen's throw of some supersweet varieties of corn.
If you do, the kernels will be hard as flint: crossbreeding brings
out the part of its ancestry that was solely ornamental.
</P>
<P>
   In the kitchen, Ruby Queen retains its color when steamed or
placed in a microwave oven, but boiling will turn it yellow, with
no loss of flavor. Picked young, just after the ears have turned
from white to pinkish red and before any scarlet develops, the corn
is tender enough to eat raw. Mixed with green tomatoes, it makes a
striking, flavorsome chutney.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of tomatoes, how about a nice, sweet, tasty black one?
The fascination with black flowers _ witness the endless search for
a true black orchid or a black rose _ is beyond me, but in the case
of the tomato called Black From Tula, the oddball color is
coincidental.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd's Garden Seeds decided to bring back this heirloom
simply for its wonderfully sweet flavor. In truth, this tomato is
not quite up to its name, being rather more purplish brown, with
green on the shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Shepherd's also has a bright-orange tomato that when sliced stem
to tip gives you perfect little heart shapes. Again, this heirloom,
Orange Strawberry, offers, in addition to lots of flavor, the
chance to turn a simple dish into an artful presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Both of these appealing tomatoes can be started from seed
indoors. Planted now through the end of April and transplanted into
the garden come the end of May or the first week in June, when the
soil is warm, they will yield good summer crops.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the fence is Burpee's purple asparagus,
which requires patience from a gardener, as a good bed will take
three to five years to yield. If you want a more instant purple for
your table, try Purple Queen, a dark purple stringbean, from
Johnny's Selected Seeds. Excellent sliced raw in salads, this bean,
like the purple asparagus, will revert to green when cooked.
</P>
<P>
   There is also Sweet Sunshine, an iridescent, stubby sweet yellow
carrot from Burpee; the glowing Swiss chard called Bright Yellow,
and the two-toned Zephyr squash, both from Johnny's. Although every
year I vow not to grow any more summer squash because there's no
one left in my state to take the overflow, I do think I'll plant
some Zephyr this year.
</P>
<P>
   One-third of what is otherwise a perfectly normal yellow squash
is, in this variety, bright green. It should look great stuffed
with a crab gratin. And anyhow, as a gardener and cook, I just
can't resist the novelty.
</P>
<P>
   Picking Your Rainbow
</P>
<P>
   Here are some sources for vegetable varieties in unusual colors.
</P>
<P>
   BURPEE 300 Park Avenue, Warminster, Pa. 18991-0001; (800)
888-1447.
</P>
<P>
   JOHNNY'S SELECTED SEEDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 Foss Hill Road, R.R. 1, Box 2580, Albion, Maine 04910-9731;
(207) 437-4301.
</P>
<P>
   SHEPHERD'S GARDEN SEEDS 30 Irene Street, Torrington, Conn.
06790-6658; (860) 482-3638.
</P>
</TEXT>
