<HEADLINE>
FBI PROBES SAN FRANCISCO CONTRACT FOR LIGHT-RAIL SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The FBI is investigating the award of a $116
million contract for a light-rail system to move people around the
San Francisco International Airport, City Hall sources say.
</P>
<P>
   A focus of the probe, say people interviewed by the FBI, is how
minority subcontractors were hired for the job under a city
affirmative action program.
</P>
<P>
   It also is exploring a claim by a former city Human Rights
Commission secretary, Donna Rice Mason, that she was ordered by her
supervisor to alter agency documents to benefit one potential
subcontractor in the airport project.
</P>
<P>
   Comer Marshall, who resigned March 29 as the commission's
president, said the FBI had questioned him a day after his
resignation about the airport light-rail project.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said the questioning had dealt with how city contracts
at the airport and elsewhere were awarded, and specifically the HRC
staff's work on the airport ``people-mover'' project landed by ABB
Daimler-Benz Transportation, called Adtranz, for $116.6 million in
March 1998.
</P>
<P>
   City Hall sources said at least three other Human Rights
Commission and airport staffers had been quizzed by FBI agents
since December.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said he welcomed the scrutiny of the city's main
affirmative action tool. ``I want a fair program, because if there
is shady stuff going on, it affects the program and other minority
participants,'' said Marshall, who resigned when Mayor Willie Brown
said he would be replaced as commission president in a routine
rotation of panel leaders.
</P>
<P>
   FBI spokesman George Grotz declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Maravic Bamba, HRC executive director, issued a written
statement Monday saying she had not been contacted by any law
enforcement agency.
</P>
<P>
   Under the city's affirmative action in contracting law, the
Human Rights Commission establishes which local, economically
disadvantaged, minority and female-owned businesses are eligible to
receive bid preferences and serve as subcontractors on major public
works projects. The city awards these large contracts in part on
the basis of whether bidders promise to use certified minority- and
female-owned firms.
</P>
<P>
   The process came under the spotlight in an epic political and
legal fight for the airport train contract by two multinational
corporations, Adtranz and Mitsubishi Heavy Industries. The
companies pitted high-powered lobbyist against high-powered
lobbyist, lawyer against lawyer and PR firm against PR firm.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Adtranz hired a private investigator to scrutinize
the qualifications of its competitor's proposed subcontractors.
</P>
<P>
   After the city's Airport Commission selected low-bidder
Mitsubishi, Bamba blocked the award, saying Human Rights Commission
staffers had concluded that two of the local firms tapped by the
company weren't bona fide local minority-owned enterprises. And a
female-owned outfit wasn't qualified to perform the tasks
Mitsubishi assigned it, Bamba said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The contract was put back out to bid, and Adtranz submitted the
lower offer: $116.6 million, compared with Mitsubishi's $128.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   One of the matters that has caught the investigators' attention
is an allegation by former commission secretary Mason that she was
ordered to alter documents in the wake of the bidding for the
airport light-rail contract.
</P>
<P>
   Mason, who was fired Feb. 6, 1998, has filed a grievance
protesting her firing, seeking her job and back pay.
</P>
<P>
   In documents filed with the city on March 31, 1998, Mason said
Zula Jones, a top-ranking HRC manager, ordered her to change the
date on a letter certifying the Jefferson Co. as eligible for the
airport project. The Jefferson Co., a San Francisco firm owned by
black businessman James D. Jefferson, was in line for a $10 million
share of the project as a proposed subcontractor to Adtranz.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the secretary said, she was ordered by Jones to go into
the office on Saturday, Sept. 27, 1997, to change the date of the
letter from the Jefferson Co. requesting its certification,
according to documents in the grievance case.
</P>
<P>
   The second demand, Mason says, was made because a newspaper
reporter was due in the office on Sept. 29, 1997, to examine
Jefferson's affirmative action file under the California Public
Records Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jones was distraught,'' the grievance says. ``Jefferson's
letter requesting certification was later than the date of the
certification letter itself. So on Saturday, Sept. 27, 1997, in the
HRC offices, Donna was directed . . . by Ms. Jones to alter the
date of Jefferson's certification request letter. The electric
date-stamp machine in the HRC office was opened, and the date was
rolled back.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson, a past president of the San Francisco Black Business
Chamber of Commerce, was an early adviser to the HRC on creation of
the city's affirmative action contracting law. He said he hadn't
been contacted by the FBI and had no knowledge of Mason's
allegations against Jones involving his Human Rights Commission
certification.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
