<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels) _ NATO's top commander, Gen. Wesley Clark
holds a detailed news conference on operations Kosovo and the rest
of Yugoslavia. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic map.
</P>
<P>
   KOVOSO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton's national
security team fanned across the Congress today trying to sell the
Balakan air camapign to a divided Congress just back from a two
week recess, and Republican leaders worked to head off lawmakers
seeking early votes on ground troops. Opinion was sharply split
with some members of Congress urging Mr. Clinton to began preparing
for ground troops and others vowing to vote against a deployment
that they charged would keep the United States in the Balkans for a
decade. By Alison Mitchell and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S. (New York) _ The Chinese prime minister, Zhu Rongji,
tours New Yorkseeking to drum up new investment in his country and
entertaining a parade of corporate executives and government
officials. By Joseph Kahn.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TAXES (Undated) _ President and Mrs. Clinton earned
$508,889 last year and paid $79,480 in federal income taxes, a far
smaller figure than most Americans at that income level because the
couple made large charitable gifts with proceeds from a book Mrs.
Clinton wrote. For the last two years the Clintons paid more than
twice as much in taxes as the law required because of how they
handled proceeds from ``It Takes A Village.'' But royalties from
Mrs. Clinton's new book, about presidential pets, went directly to
charity. Meanwhile, Vice President Al Gore and his wife, Tipper,
gave more than $15,000 to charity, up from the $327 in 1997 which
drew wide criticism. By David Cay Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KEVORKIAN-SENTENCE (Detroit) _ Dr. Jack Kevorkian was sentenced
to 10 to 25 years in prison today for the videotaped death of a Lou
Gehrig's disease patient. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   L.A.-NFL (Los Angeles) _ Last month, the National Football
League announced that Los Angeles was its first choice to receive
the league's as yet un-named 32d franchise, bypassing a firm bid of
$200 million in public financing from Houston in favor of Los
Angeles's lucrative television market, which is bigger than many
states. But there's a catch: Los Angeles, the town that couldn't
keep a team, now has not one but two competing proposed stadiums
and owner groups, each of them featuring ``guys with egos the size
of Montana,'' in the words of one City Hall aide. By Todd S.
Purdum.
</P>
