<HEADER>
A6468 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-TALK-NYT &LR;      04-13 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINE TALK: AMERICAN DINERS STICK TO AMERICAN WINE LABELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By FRANK J. PRIAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a survey 10 years ago, Wine &AMP; Spirits magazine discovered
that the wine most frequently ordered in well-known American
restaurants was chardonnay from Sonoma-Cutrer Vineyards in Sonoma
County, Calif. In the magazine's most recent survey, the winner,
once again, was Sonoma-Cutrer's chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Does this mean that Sonoma-Cutrer is the best chardonnay
producer in the world? It certainly is a fine winery with legions
of fans, but what this survey really indicates is that among
American wine drinkers, loyalty to a certain vineyard _ the
magazine calls it brand loyalty _ is clearly important.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the top 10 wineries in the new survey, taken late last
year, have been among the top 10 in this annual poll since 1989:
Kendall-Jackson Vineyards, Jordan Vineyard and Winery, and Robert
Mondavi, in addition to Sonoma-Cutrer. Of the top 50 wineries this
year, 20 have been on every list.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine did not list specific wines that diners preferred,
but rather the wineries that produced them. This is because a
winery or shipper may have half a dozen or more wines on a given
restaurant's wine list. For example, Sonoma-Cutrer offers three
different chardonnays; some restaurants may carry just one, some
all three.
</P>
<P>
   It is also apparent from this year's survey, which polled 393
restaurants around the country that are listed in the Zagat
Survey's regional editions, that American diners resoundingly
prefer American wines, mostly from California.
</P>
<P>
   Of the top 50 wineries, 43 were American. Not one of the top 10,
which include Beringer Vineyards, Ferrari-Carano, Cakebread
Cellars, Chalk Hill, Silver Oak Cellars and Clos du Bois, is in
another country. Two of the top 50 are in Washington state: Chateau
Ste. Michelle, which came in 23d, and Columbia Crest, 37th.
</P>
<P>
   Among the foreign wineries, Santa Margherita, a major producer
in northeast Italy best known for its pinot grigio, ranked the
highest, in 12th place; Veuve Clicquot, the Champagne house, is the
highest-ranking French name to appear, in 17th place. Attesting to
the outrageous prices being asked by the better-known Bordeaux
wines is the fact that not one Bordeaux name is on the list.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Santa Margherita, two other Italian wineries appeared:
Antinori, in 18th place, and Ruffino, 39th. Three other French
wineries _ Louis Jadot, Louis Latour and Joseph Drouhin _ also made
the top 50.
</P>
<P>
   No Spanish wines, no German wines, no wines from South America
and none from Oregon or New York State made the list.
</P>
<P>
   In spite of intense efforts to woo them away, American wine
drinkers prefer California chardonnay, cabernet and, of course,
merlot. The two most preferred brands, Sonoma-Cutrer and
Kendall-Jackson, are known as chardonnay producers; the rest of the
top 10 are known mostly for cabernet, or for both cabernet and
chardonnay.
</P>
<P>
   Price is not as much a factor in diners' choices as one might
assume: the average price paid for a bottle of a top 10 wine was
$46.90, with the average price of a Jordan wine at $61.57 and of a
Silver Oak wine at $86.70.
</P>
<P>
   The newest poll probably gives a more accurate indication of
restaurant wine sales than the first one, which drew only 100
responses. Josh Greene, publisher and editor of Wine &AMP; Spirits,
said the enlarged database showed that while many of the leaders
have remained in place over the years, restaurant patrons have
begun to experiment more. Some of the experimentation may be among
those diners who are unwilling to pay the current high prices for
top wines.
</P>
<P>
   Chardonnay may still be the most popular varietal, but its share
of the market has been dwindling steadily since the poll was begun.
Red wines now account for almost 55 percent of the most popular
wines sold in American restaurants. ``The current restaurant scene
is quite different from 1989, when chardonnay ruled,'' Greene said.
``Today, red wine is what's on order, in many cases _ or what's
sold out or wildly priced.''
</P>
<P>
   Sales of merlot, the star red wine of the last decade, have
slowed, partly because of shortages, Greene said, while pinot noir,
something of a crossover wine for people who want red wine with
fish, has been moving ahead.
</P>
<P>
   To me, the poll shows that restaurant wine buying is still
driven as much by snobbishness and insecurity as it is by common
sense. And it gives the lie to the wine country mantra that wine is
food, an integral part of any good meal. At $40 to $80 a bottle,
it's got little to do with eating well; it's mostly a statement
about money recently acquired.
</P>
<P>
   If it is true that the consumer is beginning to look for
alternatives to high-priced wines, restaurateurs should pay heed.
For example, I know for a fact that many restaurateurs have simply
stopped buying Bordeaux wine. ``With the prices I'd have to charge,
my customers would think I'm a crook,'' said John Foy, owner of
Sonoma Grill, in East Rutherford, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   But are customers complaining about prices? Apparently not
enough. Besides, to restaurant owners it's too tempting to take big
markups while the market for high-priced wines lasts. The fact is
that there are dozens, probably hundreds, of good wines available
at affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the Barolos retailing at $140 a bottle; there are
countless wines from other parts of Italy, including Sicily and
Sardinia, at astonishingly reasonable prices. There are still
plenty of little-known French wines worth trying and even a few,
but not many, American wines to be found at low prices.
</P>
<P>
   The article in Wine &AMP; Spirits said that many of the restaurant
owners who responded to the survey expressed their uneasiness over
the current inflated market and ``have been steering customers
toward the sort of wine they might enjoy if or when a correction
comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps they are, but it isn't yet apparent on many wine lists.
One can only hope that more restaurateurs will see things this way
and begin to search out some wine bargains _ and without murmuring
piously, as so many do, ``Ah, but then we'll just have to raise the
food prices.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
