<HEADER>
A6471 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LANGOUSTINES-ART-NYT &LR;      04-13 1184
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANGOUSTINES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SHRIMP AND THE LOBSTER GET COMPETITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Maine, Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MOLLY O'NEILL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like many immigrants to the United States, the little
crustaceans known as langoustines have been arriving here in
greater numbers because of bad times elsewhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   These creatures, which look like sawed-off lobsters and taste a
little like lobster and a little like shrimp, have long been a
delicacy in European restaurants but have played second fiddle to
shrimp in the United States. Then along came Hurricane Mitch.
</P>
<P>
   As it raged along the coasts of Central and South America last
October, the storm wiped out hundreds of shrimp farms that supplied
the North American market. Within months of the devastation,
particularly in Ecuador and Honduras, shrimp from Asia started
filling in the gap. But in the interim, chefs and adventurous home
cooks started asking fish suppliers for langoustines, and that
demand has not abated.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Polcano, manager of the fish department at Balducci's in
Greenwich Village, points out that before the hurricane,
langoustines cost $12.99 a pound and were not a big mover. After
the hurricane, when demand jumped, the price rose to $15.99, ``and
I sell more and more every week,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like anything unfamiliar that is pushed into the limelight,
langoustines have to battle some misconceptions as to what they
are. They are frequently confused with langoustes, or spiny
lobsters, the slender, tough-shelled cousins of the American
lobster. Langoustines are also often sold as prawns, though
biologically they are only distant cousins.
</P>
<P>
   Most of them that are sold here come from waters off Iceland,
Norway, the Brittany coast of France and New Zealand, though they
are also caught in the Adriatic and the Mediterranean. Usually
about 7 inches long and about as wide as a fat thumb, langoustines
have narrow, elongated claws and shells as thick as hard-shelled
crabs. Their meat, which resides entirely in the 1- to 2-inch-long
tail, is delicate but rich.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike shrimp or lobster, langoustine meat begins to deteriorate
immediately after the creatures die, due to a bacteria underneath
the shells that breaks down the meat and turns it mushy, said Rod
Mitchell, the owner of Browne Trading Co., a seafood and caviar
importer in Portland, Maine. For this reason, whole langoustines
are usually available only by special order; their tails are most
frequently sold cooked and frozen. Happily, the blue and brown
crustaceans, whose shells turn ruby red when cooked, lose little
when frozen.
</P>
<P>
   But because their flesh is extremely fragile and perishable,
langoustines can take only a short blast of high heat in a skillet,
wok or on the grill. They can be treated like crayfish on the
bayou, boiled in a spicy broth, chilled and eaten right from their
shells. They can be sauteed with lots of garlic and tossed with
pasta and parsley, or marinated in olive oil and lemon and broiled
on kebobs.
</P>
<P>
   Brushed with butter or olive oil and quickly turned on a very
hot grill, langoustine tails remain moist and succulent, tasting
sweet, faintly briny and buttery. They make a great warm-weather
meal.
</P>
<P>
   But since langoustines arrived in the United States as a luxury
good, rather than as a huddled mass of cheap food, the crustaceans
are finding a home in more elaborate, highly nuanced dishes. Marc
Murphy, the chef of La Fourchette in Manhattan, balances the
richness of grilled langoustines by serving them with wilted
arugula and a sharp gazpacho sauce. In Boston, Lydia Shire, the
chef and owner of Biba, uses langoustines as a delicate base note
in mildly curried fritters that she serves with a sweet and sour
peach chutney. Eric Ripert, the chef at Le Bernardin in New York,
emphasizes the richness of the shellfish by using them in butter
and cream sauces for mild white fish.
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, any misunderstanding of langoustines will be
short-lived. Their sweet, succulent, delicate flavor is sure to
make them as much a commodity in the American kitchen as they have
long been in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   GRILLED LANGOUSTINES WITH WILTED ARUGULA AND GAZPACHO SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from Marc Murphy, La Fourchette
</P>
<P>
   Time: 35 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe plum tomatoes, cut in quarters
</P>
<P>
   2 stalks celery, cleaned and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 red onion, cleaned and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 fennel bulb, cleaned and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon horseradish
</P>
<P>
   Tabasco to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil plus more for grilling
</P>
<P>
   3 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 pound arugula, rinsed and patted dry
</P>
<P>
   12 langoustine tails, shelled.
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup flat-leaf parsley.
</P>
<P>
   1. Heat a stove-top or charcoal grill. To make the sauce, place
the tomatoes, celery, onion, fennel, horseradish, Tabasco, 1
tablespoon olive oil and 1 clove garlic in a food processor, and
process for 2 minutes. Pass through a fine sieve, and season to
taste with salt and pepper. Chill.
</P>
<P>
   2. In large skillet over medium high heat, warm 2 tablespoons
olive oil and 2 crushed garlic cloves. Add arugula and toss for one
minute, until wilted.
</P>
<P>
   3. Cut langoustine tails lengthwise, brush with olive oil and
grill for 2 minutes. To serve, place arugula and parsley at center
of 4 plates, set grilled langoustines on top and drizzle sauce
around.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GINGERED LANGOUSTINES AND SNOW PEAS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes, plus 2 hours' marinating
</P>
<P>
   1 inch-long piece of fresh ginger root, peeled and minced
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon minced fresh chili pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 pound langoustine tails, shelled
</P>
<P>
   2 cups snow peas
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons dry sherry
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Juice from two limes
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch fresh mint leaves
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded iceberg lettuce, plus 8 large leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Combine ginger root, garlic, chili pepper, sesame oil and two
tablespoons vegetable oil in a large bowl. Add langoustines, toss
well and refrigerate for 2 hours.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat remaining vegetable oil in a large skillet or wok over
high heat until nearly smoking. Using a slotted spoon, remove
langoustines from marinade, place in wok and stir, cooking for 2
minutes. Add snow peas, toss and cook for another 2 minutes. Add
soy sauce, sherry and one tablespoon water. Stir, cook for one more
minute and remove from heat. Add salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   3. Using a slotted spoon, remove langoustines and snow peas from
wok, reserving cooking juice. Strain one tablespoon of cooking
liquid into a large salad bowl. Whisk lime juice into this mixture.
Add basil, mint and shredded lettuce, and toss.
</P>
<P>
   4. To serve, place a portion of shredded lettuce and some
langoustines on each large lettuce leaf. Roll leaves up, and eat
with fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
