<SLUG> BC-MEDICARE-TRIALS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MEDICARE BILL WOULD COVER CANCER TRIALS
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Medicare ought to cover the routine cost of
clinical trials for cancer treatments, a bipartisan group of
lawmakers said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their comments came at a news conference following the
introduction of a bill to extend Medicare coverage to recognized
cancer clinical trials. President Clinton has offered a similar,
but less encompassing, proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're hopeful that we will be successful this year,'' said
Sen. Connie Mack, R-Fla., who sponsored the legislation with Sen.
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va. The two introduced a similar bill during
the last Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Rockefeller noted that Medicare covers routine patient costs _
hospital and doctor charges _ for cancer treatments that are not
part of clinical trials, but does not cover those same charges if
they are incurred as part of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``That discourages people from wanting to be in trials,''
Rockefeller said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. George J. Bosl, chairman of the department of medicine at
the Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center, said the number of
young people participating in cancer clinical trials outnumbers the
number of elderly in those trials by three or four to one.
</P>
<P>
   About one out of five clinical trials results in some form of
change in treatment, Bosl said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
