<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-GUARDS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS URGED TO SPEND MORE ON CUSTOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With trade in commerce and illegal drugs booming, a
Texas congressman urged a House budget panel Tuesday to hire more
Customs Service agents and pump more money into the agency's
computer technology.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas, told the House Ways and Means
trade subcommittee that the increase is necessary because of the
growing trade across the U.S.-Mexico border and crackdown on
narcotics smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customs is our first line of defense,'' Rodriguez said, whose
congressional district includes the border counties of Starr and
Zapata.
</P>
<P>
   He is calling for 2,000 additional Customs inspectors and agents
nationwide and $1.2 billion over seven years to upgrade the
computer and automation system that processes commercial traffic at
land ports of entry.
</P>
<P>
   Customs currently employs roughly 20,000 workers and agents at
301 ports of entry. The agency collects about $22 billion annually,
while processing 450 million people who enter the country,
according to the General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative
arm.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton proposed a budget of $1.9 billion for the
Customs Service next year, including $163 million for computers.
The Clinton budget proposes no new positions.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Philip Crane, R-Ill., chairman of the Ways and Means trade
subcommittee, applauded Customs agents for their diligence against
smugglers but warned against overzealous law enforcement that could
delay legitimate commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``Customs faces enormous challenges, and every day Customs
officers rise to meet these challenges,'' Crane said. ``We believe
that Customs officers should be fairly compensated for their
duties, including overtime duties.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said a 200 percent increase in trade between the
United States and Mexico in recent years has strained resources and
entry ports in Texas, where long lines of traffic and delays have
become routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``As people living and working on the border see it, the U.S.
Customs Service is part of the underdeveloped infrastructure,''
Rodriguez said. ``Increasing the agency's budget should be natural
in the face of booming trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Salamone, chairman of the American Association of
Exporters and Importers, said U.S. businesses have concerns about
the Customs Service's computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   Salamone said Clinton's request for $163 million to upgrade the
computers used by the Customs Service ``inadequate.'' At that rate
of funding, the upgraded computer system would not be completed for
eight to 10 years, instead of the proposed four to seven years,
Salamone said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1706EDT &QL; 
