<HEADER>
A6504 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRUE-HEMINGWAY-ART-NY     04-13 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRUE-HEMINGWAY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEMINGWAY GETS A KICK IN A KICKOFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ ``I'm not leaving anything behind,'' the writer Tobias
Wolff declared. ``I'm just throwing everything out.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Big bonfire,'' agreed the novelist Francine Prose.
</P>
<P>
   The authors, scholars and fans gathered over the weekend for the
Hemingway Centennial Conference at the John F. Kennedy Library here
had varying opinions on the wisdom and taste of producing a work
like ``True at First Light,'' the posthumous Ernest Hemingway novel
about an African safari, edited by his son Patrick from a longer
manuscript. The book is to be published by Scribner this summer and
is expected to be the last of his leftover works.
</P>
<P>
   Debate over such posthumous, unrequested efforts _ and over the
possible impact of the book on how Hemingway is viewed _ rumbled
loudly at the conference. Stephen Plotkin, curator of the Hemingway
collection at the library, called the buzz about the book ``a
subtext for everything that happened here.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was a consensus among a handful of writers
interviewed on the topic, it was on the moral of the story: the
necessity of writing the authorial equivalent of a living will.
Either that, they said, or leaving nothing at all to be tampered
with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson for all writers is, leave explicit instructions
about exactly what you want,'' said Rosina Lippi, a first-time
novelist who was honored at the conference.
</P>
<P>
   The Nobel laureate Derek Walcott was asked what it would mean if
he were to leave an unpublished manuscript behind, and he
responded, ``It means that I should learn to start burning
everything I own.''
</P>
<P>
   There the consensus ended, however. Writers could all agree on
their dread of having their unfinished works pulled from bureau
drawers and published posthumously. But even after many had heard a
long excerpt from ``True at First Light'' at a group dinner on
Saturday night, they remained split over its merits and the
justification for publishing it.
</P>
<P>
   Some guests at the dinner called the work a barely edited first
draft and said its publication was in poor taste. Others reacted
with pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoyed it,'' said Jeffrey Marshall, a retired librarian who
helped underwrite an exhibit of manuscripts at the conference. ``It
sounded like the real Hemingway, the kind of dialogue the narrator
would have with his wife in `The Green Hills of Africa.'''
</P>
<P>
   Walcott said: ``Anybody great, we're all interested in the
relics. If you found an unfinished Gauguin, you'd still want to see
it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Homero Aridjis, the president of International PEN,
cautioned that publishing posthumous works ``is something that can
be very dangerous because it can be against the spirit of the
writer.''
</P>
<P>
   Even centennials can be dangerous, he added. This conference,
for example, seemed to be intended as a kickoff for a year of
Hemingway celebrations, but it also included a fair amount of just
plain kicking. Of Hemingway, that is, as a racist, sexist,
anti-Semitic, anti-environment, ugly-American relic of the old
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I won't offend with heresy when I say that Hemingway
never had both feet down on Africa, never really was in Africa,''
Nadine Gordimer, the Nobel prize-winning author, said. ``For a
country is its people, Africa is its people,'' and Hemingway
``chose Africa as one of those panoramic three-dimensional
postcards where at first light animals seem to leap out of the
thorn bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Others mentioned the environmental incorrectness of Hemingway's
hunting habits and the misogyny inherent in his portrayal of women.
Such criticisms, popular for years and responsible for a certain
decline in Hemingway's popularity, resounded side by side with
unstinting praise for his style and the progress it represented for
American literature.
</P>
<P>
   Speakers and panelists at the conference also included Saul
Bellow, Peter Matthiessen and Kenzaburo Oe.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Gordimer was tough on Hemingway, she was even tougher on
those who are already trying to read the forthcoming novel for the
light it may cast on the facts of the author's life. She found that
``distasteful to say the least,'' she said, and considers that
whether Hemingway actually slept with a young African woman, as the
narrator does in the book, ``doesn't matter a damn in the
achievements of Ernest Hemingway.'' She added, ``It's an insult
indeed to his lifelong integrity to his art to regard his work in
this shabby, prurient way.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On Ernest Hemingway's centennial,'' she concluded, ``too much
will be speculated about him, too much spoken about him, too much
written about him, including my own part in this. When we go home,
let us leave his life alone. It belongs to him, as he lived it. Let
us read his books''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
