<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMBULANCE-TIMES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY AMBULANCE SERVICE RESPONSE TIMES DECLINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PENN  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Metropolitan Ambulance Services Trust
failed to meet its required response-time targets in five of six
Kansas City Council districts in February _ the first full month to
be examined since altered response-time records were discovered
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   And the MAST service provider will be fined for the late
responses. It has already been fined more than $1 million for late
responses over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The February numbers show significantly less success at on-time
performance than do the response times for January, which were
collected before the alterations were discovered and are now being
audited.
</P>
<P>
   MAST has a maximum ``target'' response time on life-threatening
emergencies of 8 minutes and 30 seconds. Every call that takes
longer results in a fine charged to Emergency Providers Inc., the
employee-owned service contractor for MAST. In addition, much
stiffer penalties are imposed whenever fewer than 90 percent of the
citywide response times fail to meet the target within a
three-month period.
</P>
<P>
   January records indicate that 90.2 percent of response times
citywide met contract targets. But in February, citywide on-time
performance dropped to 82.1 percent. The records are arranged by
city council district, and calls in five of the six districts
failed to meet the standard.
</P>
<P>
   A sharp drop in on-time performance is also demonstrated by
comparing February 1999 to February 1998. A year ago, the reported
citywide rate of on-time emergency calls in February was 93.3
percent, compared to this year's 82.1 percent. Four of the six
districts met or exceeded response-time targets in February 1998,
compared with only one in February of this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response times are terrible,'' said Jack Campbell, the
physician who oversees the city's emergency medical system, which
includes MAST and the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm appalled at just how low they are,'' Campbell said. ``But
I'm not surprised since they were given inaccurate information
before that to work with.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the manager of communications for Emergency Providers
Inc. resigned after admitting that he altered response times to
make them look more favorable to Emergency Providers Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The amount of the fine for the January-February-March period has
not been calculated, but MAST Executive Director John Sharp said it
would be ``higher than average.''
</P>
<P>
   Fines have averaged $126,000 per three-month period for the last
two years, a total of more than $1 million, because of slow
response times.
</P>
<P>
   From January 1998 to December 1998, Emergency Providers Inc.
paid $520,157 in fines to MAST. From July 1996 to June 1997 _ when
the organizations used a different fiscal-year calendar _ Emergency
Providers Inc. paid $569,119.
</P>
<P>
   Louie Wright, president of Local 42 of the International
Association of Fire Fighters, said he wasn't surprised by the slow
response times or the level of fines imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Local 42 have been campaigning for the city Fire
Department to take over ambulance service, arguing they can deliver
the service more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's ever been an agency that cries out for a
performance audit, it's MAST,'' Wright said. ``I think MAST
warrants a serious investigation. Frankly, I think the situation
with MAST is much worse that anyone realizes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sharp said the drop in on-time performance can't be
immediately blamed on the altered records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, response times for February fell far short,'' Sharp
said. ``But response times will vary from month to month. We can't
assume that they're different because of the alterations.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said officials will have to wait until the audit is
concluded before knowing for sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``After we conduct the audit, the issue will be crystal clear,''
Sharp said.
</P>
<P>
   A committee appointed by the city manager is expected to
consider the merits of a Fire Department-based emergency medical
system in a few weeks. And response times are expected to be an
issue in the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Don Pickard, a spokesman for Emergency Providers Inc., said the
response times need lots of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're never happy with response times. If we were at 91
percent, we'd want them to be at 92 percent. We do understand that
our primary concern is patient care. And we're going to do
everything we can to get ourselves in compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no excuse will suffice, Pickard said, Kansas City has a
much higher standard for ambulance service than many other cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we fell short of the standard this time. We still believe
the system works.''
</P>
<P>
   The contract between Emergency Providers Inc. and MAST requires
separate performance records for each of the six council districts;
the districts will be redrawn and reduced to four later this year.
Even when Emergency Providers Inc. meets the target for on-time
performance in a district, fines are imposed for every emergency
call that does not meet the response-time target. Emergency
Providers Inc. is hit with a $20 penalty for every minute an
ambulance is late in responding to a life-threatening call.
</P>
<P>
   For non-life-threatening calls, the fine is $15 a minute; the
standard for non-life-threatening calls is 9 minutes and 59
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Sharp admitted that the response times for February are poor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although EPI's response times in February would be considered
great in most cities, they fall short of what MAST expects,'' Sharp
said. ``Response times for March initially appear to be
significantly better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharp said he was confident that Emergency Providers Inc.'s
citywide response times in April would come close to meeting MAST
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Further improvement in response times may still be needed in
certain areas. Patient care is our first priority. We won't be
satisfied until EPI's response times are fast and reliable in every
part of the metropolitan area that we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Emergency Providers Inc. is armed with the correct
data, it must work quickly to improve service, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he thought that airing the response-time issue before
the special committee begins its deliberation is important.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for the system that this issue was discovered,''
Campbell said. He said ambulance and personnel deployments based on
the flawed response times will have to be revised. ``The contractor
is going to start from scratch. We're essentially talking about
creating a whole coverage system.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
