<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-CAMPUS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SPRINT CAMPUS CLOUDS OFFICE MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The only thing Sprint Corp. dominates more
than the local real estate market is Kansas City conversation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a day goes by that people don't ask me about the impact of
Sprint,'' said Don Thompson, managing director of Trammell Crow
Co.'s Kansas City, Mo., office. ``I don't think Sprint even
knows.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint occupies more than 10 percent of the leased office space
in the Kansas City market, according to figures compiled by Kansas
City real estate firm Colliers Turley Martin Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   That's a huge chunk of real estate. Microsoft doesn't even claim
10 percent of greater Seattle's office market.
</P>
<P>
   But as the company's 247-acre corporate campus in Overland Park,
Kan., prepares to open, people are asking the $700 million
question: What's going to happen to all that space the company
currently occupies?
</P>
<P>
   Brokers, tenants, investors, commuters and the just plain
curious want to know what will happen when Sprint moves.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint executives want to know that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have demands that ebb and flow,'' said Faye Manker,
Sprint's vice president of real estate. ``It is never a static
equation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's ever-changing demands are causing many people to talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think of another Midwestern city with the same situation,''
said Gregory Swetnam, principal and director of commercial
brokerage for Kessinger//Hunter &AMP; Co. ``You can't. Talk about
putting all your eggs in one basket.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, Sprint has been laying baskets of golden eggs for
building owners by gobbling down every inch of space it could get.
</P>
<P>
   Current estimates show that Sprint leases at least 3.7 million
square feet in the Kansas City area. The entire market of leasable
office space in Kansas City is 34.6 million square feet, according
to Colliers.
</P>
<P>
   This fall, Sprint will open the campus with 1 million square
feet of office space. The rest of the campus will open in phases.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's current estimates indicate that the company plans to
vacate 2.2 million square feet of office space around town, Manker
said.
</P>
<P>
   The company likely will stay in about 500,000 square feet that
it leases and is still uncertain about its continued occupancy in
about 800,000 square feet of leased space. The company also owns
about 1.2 million square feet of office space.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's consistent with what we know today,'' Manker said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint is keeping its options open on so much space because the
telecommunications industry is changing so fast and because the
company itself is growing so fast.
</P>
<P>
   The campus was designed to handle at least 14,500 workers, but
real estate sources said the company plans to have as many as
18,000 or 20,000 local employees within four years.
</P>
<P>
   In calculating space needs, Sprint is assigning about 230 square
feet a person, Manker said. That means the campus could handle
nearly 17,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   That calculation and Sprint's projections for future growth,
Sprint's recent leases on additional office space and a deal with
the city of Overland Park to increase worker density on the site
are causing some real estate experts to conclude that Sprint has
outgrown the campus before it even opens.
</P>
<P>
   ``They obviously feel they need more space,'' said Ted Murray,
president of Grubb &AMP; Ellis//The Winbury Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take the long-term leases as a good sign, said Brad Hakes,
regional vice president for Liberty Property Trust, which owns a
Sprint-occupied building.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint recently signed leases on a former Universal Underwriters
building in Kansas City, a former Mobil credit facility in Lenexa,
Kan., and a former Black &AMP; Veatch office also in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint recently told real estate brokers that it planned to keep
as many as four floors in One Kansas City Place in downtown.
Previously, brokers speculated that the company would keep just one
floor in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think some of the fears are worse than the reality will turn
out to be,'' said R. Lee Harris, president of Cohen-Esrey Real
Estate Services Inc. ``Sprint has an appetite for space and most of
the space either won't come or stay on the market very long.''
</P>
<P>
   Some landowners said Sprint hasn't said what they plan to do
with the space they are leasing.
</P>
<P>
   Barrett Brady, senior vice president for Highwoods Properties
Inc., said Sprint hasn't notified his company about imminent plans
to vacate properties it leases from Highwoods.
</P>
<P>
   Such signals are encouraging some developers to proceed with
construction plans, even though some lenders are keeping a tight
grip on money for projects that don't have tenants signed before
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This uncertainty is not good for Kansas City,'' said Natalie
Wolfe, vice president of CB Richard Ellis Inc. ``None of this helps
secure long-term financing from lenders who want to know what's
going to happen in the market.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe should know because she recently tested the appetite of
lenders with a plan to build a $13 million, 85,000-square-foot
office building near the Sprint campus.
</P>
<P>
   As construction of new speculative buildings proceeds and Sprint
pull-outs loom, most experts don't expect buildings to sit empty
for long.
</P>
<P>
   MC Real Estate Services estimates that vacancy in the entire
real estate market could rise from about 8 percent to about 12
percent to 14 percent, based on current construction and
employment-growth rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see it peaking in 2001 to 2002,'' said Ned O'Connor,
president of MC Real Estate. ``The gap will close, but it will take
about 24 months to close. We expect vacancy to be 5 to 8 percent in
2004.''
</P>
<P>
   The uncertainty caused by the looming Sprint vacancies has other
effects on the market.
</P>
<P>
   Some large institutional investors aren't even looking at Kansas
City for investment properties. The city is already too small to
attract the huge real estate investment trusts, but the Sprint
vacancies are an extra warning signal.
</P>
<P>
   Investment purchases haven't completely disappeared. Des
Moines-based insurer Principal Financial Group bought a property
not occupied by Sprint in the last 18 months and Liberty Property
Trust of Malvern, Penn., took the plunge with a fully occupied
Sprint property.
</P>
<P>
   Rent wars are getting tougher. Tenants want to delay rent
negotiations until the Sprint vacancies hit the market and
landlords are demanding premiums for short-term leases.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three years, rental rates grew nearly three times
faster than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have taken the supply element out of the equation,''
Swetnam said.
</P>
<P>
   By renting so much space itself, Sprint forced other tenants to
consider pricier class-A space because lower-cost space wasn't a
choice, Swetnam said.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor said average rates increased as much as 15 percent in
the last three years, more than twice the historical rate. For
example, a building that rented for $16 a square foot now costs in
excess of $20 a square foot.
</P>
<P>
   Land prices shot up, too.
</P>
<P>
   Along the Tomahawk Creek Parkway, land prices shot up from about
$4 a square foot to $10 a square foot in the last 18 months, said
D. Michael Posten, principal and vice president at Colliers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bubble in demand created by Sprint has given people a
false sense of the value of their land,'' Posten said.
</P>
<P>
   Some market observers warn focusing on building-vacancy rates
and rent prices could distract people from other key questions for
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``The question isn't about rental rates or absorption rates,''
said Lawrence Glaze, president of Glaze Commercial Real Estate
Advisors. ``The question is can the demand for workers be
staffed.''
</P>
<P>
   Low unemployment rates suggest that there aren't many workers to
recruit for job openings. If a company can't hire workers, it can't
put people in the buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Others wonder if the eat-or-be-eaten telecommunications industry
will change Sprint. Some think the campus could be a poison pill
that protects against a takeover, but others see the $700 million
campus as little more than a rounding error in a
multibillion-dollar merger equation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in the phone industry, Sprint will be
withdrawing from as much as 2.2 million square feet and some
landlords are bracing for the Sprint exodus.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never like to lose a tenant that you have,'' said Charles
Hunter, president of Kessinger//Hunter and trustee of EHMD
Properties LP Trust, which owns the most property leased by
Sprint.``But we all lose tenants when companies move or
consolidate. That's part of the risk. To put it bluntly, this goes
with the territory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
