<HEADLINE>
TAX HEADACHES FROM KANSAS CITY GET U.S. SENATE HEARING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Complaining about all those tax forms as April 15
nears?
</P>
<P>
   Don't expect much sympathy from people like Brian Gloe of Kansas
City, Mo., who told a U.S. Senate committee Monday that every year
his printing business has to file more than 180 IRS forms and
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a strong background in accounting and I don't even
try to do the taxes myself,'' said Gloe, co-chief executive officer
of Rosse Lithographing in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Gloe testified before the Senate Committee on Small Business at
the request of the chairman, Republican Kit Bond of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Bond wants to streamline tax regulations for small businesses,
which account for 40 percent of all taxes collected by the IRS.
Metropolitan Kansas City alone has more than 62,000 businesses with
250 or fewer employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``When small business owners say the tax filing and
record-keeping is too much, we ought to listen and start making
some changes,'' Bond said. ``How's a small-business owner supposed
to know which forms are necessary, much less how to complete them
accurately?''
</P>
<P>
   IRS Commissioner Charles Rossotti testified at the hearing
Monday and agreed there is a large burden on small business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not focused on this enormously large and important
part of our economy before,'' Rossotti acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Bond's staff surrounded Rossotti and other witnesses with large
charts and graphs illustrating more than 200 tax forms and 700
pages of instructions that confront small-business owners and the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something is wrong here,'' Bond said, holding up a stack of
forms as thick as a big-city phone book. ``We need to take most of
these forms and get rid of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the senator dropped the stack in a round trash barrel
in the hearing room.
</P>
<P>
   Gloe could only hope that isn't what happened to some of the
forms his company has filed during the 10 years his family has
owned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you get everything filed correctly, it seems to get
lost here (in Washington) and you have to refile it,'' Gloe told
the committee. ``It would be nice if you only had to file once and
that was the end of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gloe said his company's tax filings include 33 forms, schedules
and supporting schedules and 120 W-2 forms, even though he only has
62 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Businesses have to file forms on credits, expenses,
depreciation, appreciation, debts, assets, interest, benefits and
many other matters. Often, they also have to file forms verifying
that they filed forms, Gloe said.
</P>
<P>
   Gloe said he has four full-time employees in accounting but has
to hire outside help to file tax forms. The company spends about
$72,000, or 16 percent of its net income, preparing for and
reporting taxes, Gloe said.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of small business owners share Gloe's frustration, said
Matt Gunther, small business advocate for the Greater Kansas City
Chamber of Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just highly time-constraining,'' Gunther said, with
businesses commonly spending 5 to 10 percent of their revenue on
accounting and tax matters. The chamber has encouraged Bond to seek
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti said he knows first-hand the tax preparation challenges
for small business because he started one himself in 1970 and his
father ran a printing business not unlike Gloe's.
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti said the IRS has to change misguided regulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole idea was to meet the needs of specific internal
groups inside the IRS,'' Rossotti said. ``They were not designed to
the point of view of a participating taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rossotti said plans are under way to make filing and paying
easier, and that he liked Bond's idea of having a committee of
small business owners review proposed changes in forms and
regulations to help simplify them.
</P>
<P>
   He said the IRS is establishing a system of educating and
helping small businesses and self-employed taxpayers. A special
``taxpayer advocate'' for those persons will be appointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new approach,'' Rossotti stated, ``will provide small
businesses and the self-employed taxpayers with a clearer voice and
a helping hand within the IRS.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
