<P>
   TERRORIST SUSPECT &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ He sits in isolation, behind the razor wire and thick,
smoked-glass windows of a federal jail in New York, far from the
Fort Worth tire shop and Arlington apartment where he worked and
lived. In the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, Wadih
El Hage is allowed to see only his defense lawyers and the guards
who surround him. He is able to make just three phone calls a
month, and only to people such as his wife who have been approved
by the federal government. He is not allowed to use the exercise
track on the jail's roof, the government says, for fear that he
will be killed by a sniper so he can never reveal information about
terrorist groups around the world. Life for El Hage _ a father of
seven who lived with his family near the University of Texas at
Arlington campus _ has changed dramatically since he was accused of
being an international terrorist. In September, he was charged with
``conspiracy to kill United States nationals'' in the Aug. 7, 1998,
bombings of U.S. embassy buildings in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es
Salaam, Tanzania. By JACK DOUGLAS JR. and KIMBERLY DURNAN. Story
will move in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
