<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, April 14, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A high wind warning for gusts as high as 70 mph was issued
Tuesday for Guadalupe Pass in west Texas as a potent low pressure
system approached from New Mexico. Wednesday, the low will arrive
over the western Gulf States, setting the stage for volleys of
volatile weather.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will develop early Wednesday across
parts of eastern Texas, eastern Oklahoma, Arkansas and Louisiana as
humid air streaming northward from the Gulf of Mexico is lifted
along and ahead of a cold front associated with the potent low.
Then, later in the day, a second round of showers and thunderstorms
will erupt as a potent jet stream disturbance trailing the cold
front renews the lifting of humid Gulf air with vigor. Some of
these storms will approach severe levels, with large hail, damaging
straight-line winds and tornadoes possible in a few storms.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the low, chilly air will invade northwest Texas
on strong winds from the north. Farther west, the cool spell along
the southern California Coast will end today as a warm ridge of
high pressure arrives aloft from the Pacific and developing
offshore breezes push low clouds and cool maritime air out to sea.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds circulating around a low pressure system stalled over the
Canadian Maritimes will cover parts of northern New England as far
south as Boston. A few snow showers and flurries will dust the
mountains of northern New England. Winds from the northwest will
average 15 to 25 mph with higher gusts along much of the Northeast
Seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Wet Caboose
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the rainiest April day on record at the Los Angeles
airport as 1.35 inches of rain were measured. The city's previous
wettest April day was April 27, 1960, when 1.26 inches of rain
fell. The disturbance that produced the deluge was the caboose in a
train of Pacific disturbances the past two weeks that caused
mountain snows, coastal rains, thunder and high desert winds over
the Western States. The potent disturbances then moved east and
spawned a few severe thunderstorms over the Middle West. Wednesday,
the caboose will raise the risk of severe storms across the western
Gulf States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
