<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANOTHER WORLD' LEAVES ORBIT  
 ENEMIES TRY TO EXPLAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When NBC decided to cancel its soap opera ``Another World'' this
week, some heavy considerations came into play.
</P>
<P>
   Only one NBC entertainment show had been on the air longer than
the 35-year run of ``Another World.'' That's the ``Tonight'' show.
All told, only two other NBC shows are older: ``Today'' and ``Meet
the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not as if the show was holding onto its longtime fans. In
most cases any time a network interferes with a soap opera, even on
days when war breaks out or a president is impeached, soap fans
react with a venom now seldom seen in a world of 100-plus channels.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, as news of the cancellation of ``Another World''
reached its remaining fans, the outcry was more like an
out-whimper. NBC said its offices in Burbank, Calif., received
fewer than 50 calls about the decision.
</P>
<P>
   That lack of interest has been reflected in the ratings, which
have been among the lowest for network soaps. This season ``Another
World'' lost almost a quarter of the young women viewers that soaps
use as their selling base to advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   It ranked 10th among the 11 network soaps among women aged 18 to
49.``Sunset Beach,'' also on NBC, was 11th.
</P>
<P>
   That did not make the cancellation any easier for the cast.
Linda Dano, who has played Felicia Gallant for 17 years, said
Tuesday: ``It's painful. I also think it's tragic for the soap
industry when a show goes off after 35 years. That's not a good day
for network television.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, she said, given the recent ratings, the news was hardly a
shock. ``I knew when I signed my contract for this year that it
might be the last,'' Ms. Dano said.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest problem has been that many of the show's stations
around the country have been moving ``Another World'' around their
schedules, even postponing it for days at a stretch to create time
for local programming. That made it next to impossible for NBC to
promote its prime-time shows during ``Another World.''
</P>
<P>
   So NBC used the cancellation as part of a strategy to remake its
daytime schedule. NBC ceded a two-hour block from 5 to 7 a.m., to
its affiliates as a way to get them to agree to broadcast its new
soap ``Passions'' at 2 p.m. daily, after NBC's one hit soap, ``Days
of Our Lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, NBC executives expressed regret at having to drop
``Another World.'' As one put it, ``I remember my grandmother
watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Carter &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Enemies Try to Explain
</P>
<P>
   At a time when India and Pakistan are worrying the world's
diplomats with contradictory signals _ one moment scheduling
tit-for-tat nuclear tests, the next having their prime ministers
embrace at the border _ an unheralded public television program in
New York managed to bring the Indian and Pakistani ambassadors in
the United States together last week to be interviewed. It is
believed to be the first time officials of the two countries have
appeared on one program.
</P>
<P>
   The program, ``Asian America,'' is seen on WNYE, the New York
City Board of Education's public television station and syndicated
nationally by PBS. It appears on Wednesdays at 7:30 p.m. in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Although they arrived at the same time and even shook hands, the
two ambassadors, Naresh Chandra of India and Riaz H. Khokhar of
Pakistan, refused to be interviewed together. Each spent 15 minutes
being questioned by William J. Holstein, a senior writer for U.S.
News &AMP; World Report and a veteran reporter on Asian affairs who
also serves as a guest host for ``Asian America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The depth of their antagonism is so great, they can barely
speak to each other,'' Holstein said. ``Although the prime
ministers have exchanged visits now, there are five decades of
hostility at work here and three wars fought in the last 51 years.
This is one of the world's most dangerous conflicts, and very few
Americans understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is how he persuaded the two ambassadors to appear on the
program, Holstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They both want the U.S. to understand they are capable of
rational discourse and aren't nuclear hot-heads ready to shoot off
missiles,'' he said, although India did test fire a missile just
last Sunday, angering Pakistan. ``The one thing they both agreed to
was the need for Americans to develop a deeper understanding of the
subcontinent.''
</P>
<P>
   Holstein said ``Asian America'' contributed to that
understanding, being the only American television program on Asian
issues that is broadcast in English. It is produced by two
Korean-American sisters, Jung Sook Koh and Hwi-sook Taylor, who
started it five years ago and still work unpaid, raising money for
the program from grants.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to do something on a shoestring budget that is
very valuable,'' Holstein said. ``That's why I got involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrie Mifflin &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
