<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 17:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FRANCE-BISTROS-ART-2T     04-13 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-BISTROS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEANWHILE, BACK IN THE BISTROS, IT'S THOROUGHLY FRENCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By MIMI SHERATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ For generations, bistros have been the culinary soul of
Paris, casual neighborhood restaurants where regulars drop in for
local gossip and a reassuringly familiar meal. Almost as important
as the food is the setting _ usually small, intimate and aglow with
stained or painted wood, etched glass and mirrors, bric-a-brac,
prints and posters, all against the rippling hum of voices and the
tinkle of glass and silver that signify contentment.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the French embrace culinary exotica, the appeal of the
classic bistro, for a taste of Paris past, is undiminished. Lately,
in fact, there is a boom in bistros, new and old, that serve
traditionally lusty cuisine at prices starting at $20 for a
complete meal for one, wine included.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is so popular that some new-old bistros now require
reservations as long as three weeks ahead, which really compromises
the spontaneous bistro spirit.
</P>
<P>
   Such bistros produce dishes in varying degrees of excellence,
from the meticulously superb to the comfortably homey. Bistros are
so popular that many new ones, like La Regalade and Le Villaret,
have opened in the last seven or eight years. Like their
100-year-old forerunners, they offer thoroughly French fare, albeit
with a few lightened, stylish variations.
</P>
<P>
   As much as I value culinary creativity, given only three or four
days in Paris, I play it safe and opt for the old. On just such a
schedule last November, I searched out the traditional, earthy,
bistro flavors and aromas that have defined French cooking for me
since my first visit, in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   My quintessential bistro is the Restaurant des Beaux-Arts in
Saint-Germain-des-Pres. Admittedly, nostalgia is always the plat du
jour, since I had my first Paris meal in this snugly cozy place
with some impecunious painters who were almost nightly patrons.
</P>
<P>
   Across from the Ecole des Beaux-Arts, this bistro caters to art
students and neighborhood antiquarian book dealers and up until the
1960s used to save regulars the 25-cent charge for napkins by
storing each for a week in a chest of 56 small drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Only drawer No. 4 remains active, accommodating a 40-year client
who hates the modern paper napkins and dines there every Sunday on
that bistro classic, boeuf bourguignon. The present owner, Laurent
Bargeau, who took over from his father, says that the restaurant is
about 100 years old and that Oscar Wilde as well as Picasso were
among the regulars.
</P>
<P>
   Choosing well for the price is the trick here, where a
two-course prix-fixe is about $10 for lunch (figuring 5.8 francs to
the dollar) and where a thoroughly satisfying three-course dinner
with wine runs about $22. The appetizers are classic _ escargots;
nicely burnished onion soup; jambon persille, the fork-size chunks
of ham set in its green-gold aspic, and a salad of slim haricots
verts with bacon topped with a poached egg and tomatoes (though
sometimes unripe).
</P>
<P>
   One of my favorite main courses is the nurturing pot-au-feu, a
restorative dark brew of broth-softened leeks, carrots, turnips,
potatoes, spoon-tender beef and a marrow bone served with coarse
salt. That, or the boeuf bourguignon or the entrecote topped with
marrow, along with frites (not always as crisp as they might be) is
a great buy anywhere at $15.
</P>
<P>
   With these prices, one does not dally, either in the snug
ground-floor room with its green walls and mirrors on which daily
specials are painted, or in the more private low-ceilinged
upstairs. But I have never felt unduly rushed, and the memories,
charm and soul-warming fare, plus the house wine, Touraine rouge
(about $3.50 for a two-glass carafe), inevitably lure me back.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, regulars at Chez Catherine _ business clientele at
lunch, local residents for dinner _ are as thoroughly bourgeois as
the neighborhood. This is a set-piece of a local bistro, hidden
away on a quiet street near the Galeries Lafayette department store
on Boulevard Haussmann.
</P>
<P>
   Catherine Guerraz took over the former Le Poitou and now offers
engaging starters like ravioli with cepes in a smoky cream sauce
that owes more to France than to Italy. Even better was the gateau
des foies de volaille, a hot mousse of chicken livers that is a
classic of French cooking. Silky, bean-size chicken kidneys and
crunches of cockscombs enliven a light tomato sauce.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Braised squab with tiny, oniony green peas is a quintessential
bistro dish, rendered soft and mellow in a way that might seem
overcooked to nouvelle palates but that develops the richest, most
sensual flavors. Slightly chewy steak aux poivre has its proper
mantle of black peppercorns, cream and a hint of Cognac.
</P>
<P>
   Other benchmark dishes are cassoulet and confit of duck.
Satisfying desserts include tarte Tatin, the apples and crust
nicely firm although insufficiently caramelized, and a creme brulee
accented by pistachios and pears. There is a long, tantalizing wine
list with very decent buys like a 1995 Gigondas, Domaine des
Espiers, for about $24. My three-course meal came to about $33.
</P>
<P>
   The most convincing new-old bistro is La Regalade (a bit out of
the way, near the Porte d'Orleans) even though this is hardly a
neighborhood hangout, what with reservations made weeks in advance
by habitues from all quarters of Paris, the United States and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Owned by the chef, Yves Camdeborde, and his wife, Claudine, who
efficiently runs the convivially noisy dining room, this handsomely
rustic place opened in 1992 but looks as though it has been there
forever. Seating is elbow to elbow, as might be expected where a
truly excellent three-course meal is offered for about $32.
</P>
<P>
   As tempting as the other appetizers are, I can never resist the
incomparable cochonnaille, the huge basket of homemade sausages
well cured to taste antique along with a terrine or two of
delightfully unctuous pates, complete with cutting board and knife
for all-you-can-eat self-service.
</P>
<P>
   I always hope they'll take the basket away while I still have
room for the hearty main courses like beef braised with carrots and
red wine or the lightly salt-cured pigeon with lentils. From fall
to winter, I go for the properly crusted cassoulet or the dark and
spicy blood sausage, boudin, nested on buttery mashed potatoes, or
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Desserts like the individual Grand Marnier souffle and the
vanilla pot-de-creme are much better than the bland rice pudding
and the omelette norvegienne (French for baked Alaska). The modest
wine list is adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Another bistro of the 1992 vintage is Le Villaret, a crowded and
young-spirited spot that feels genuine despite its atypical,
half-timbered brick walls.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrations at finding it in the hectic whirl around the Place
de la Republique disappeared as we tucked into a meal of old
flavors in new guises, for about $32 a person, without wine.
</P>
<P>
   Appetizers like consomme of hare with wild mushrooms, or
fricasse of asparagus and artichokes in a peppery sauce fleshed out
with a flaky phyllo packet of boned calves' feet can be followed by
andouillette sausage of boneless pigs' feet with cepes, braised
lamb's tongue fragrant with sherry, and game in season. Pain perdu
(French toast) with warm clementines made a lovely dessert, as did
the vanilla pot-de-creme with madeleines.
</P>
<P>
   The owners, Oliver Gaslain and Joel Homel, are so proud of their
limited but well-chosen wine list that they serve no water. But it
is available, self-service, from a tap near the bar. Schtick,
French style.
</P>
<P>
   CHEZ CATHERINE 65 Rue de Provence, 75009 Paris; telephone (011)
33-1-45-26-72-88.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT DES BEAUX-ARTS 11 Rue Bonaparte, 75006 Paris; (011)
33-1-43-26-92-64.
</P>
<P>
   LA REGALADE 49 Avenue Jean-Moulin, 75014 Paris; (011)
33-1-45-45-6858.
</P>
<P>
   LE VILLARET 13 Rue Ternaux, 75011 Paris; (011) 33-1-43-57-89-76.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
