<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-OLD-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: OLD MOVIES EVERYWHERE, BUT NOT A ONE TO WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Along with other customers or prisoners of Cablevision who
reside in lower Westchester County, N.Y., and have a taste for old
movies, I am a member of a deprived class. For amid the dozens of
channels that cater to viewers who want to hear about the weather
or meet cheery chefs or keep up to the minute on lacrosse or buy
something they didn't know they needed from earnest hucksters,
there is a gap that strikes at the heart of movie fans: you will
not find Turner Classic Movies (TCM) on the menu.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, there is no shortage of old movies, notably on American
Movie Classics (AMC), where you can catch the occasional golden
oldie, like ``A Foreign Affair'' and presentable perennials like
``Gypsy'' and ``Indiscreet'' and then catch them again and again
and again. But the offerings there or on the hit-and-miss Movie
Channel only make one thirst for what is regularly available to
Manhattan residents on Time-Warner's cable system.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday TMC, not to be confused with TCM, will offer its
premium, pay-extra subscribers a shot at such forgettables as
``Under Fire,'' ``Black Scorpion'' and ``Dead Tides.'' On the down
market TBS, Tuesday night's double feature consisted of ``Die Hard
2: Die Harder'' and ``Delta Force II: The Colombian Connection.''
</P>
<P>
   This Saturday evening in prime time, for example, AMC occupies
itself with ``Three Coins in the Fountain, ``The Prince and the
Showgirl'' and ``Teen-Age Caveman,'' by no means its limpest or
most familiar lineup, but not a bubbling fount of excitement; TNT
resorts to ``Rocky IV'' and ``The Road Warrior''; TMC catches up
with ``Jerry Maguire,'' which has been making the cable rounds for
quite a while, and TBS dredges up something called ``Mortal
Kombat.'' Meanwhile, Turner Classic Movies will run ``The Time
Machine'' (1960) and ``The Picture of Dorian Gray'' (1945). It's
not that these are, strictly speaking, classics, but they are
high-quality efforts that haven't long since worn out their
welcome. And if you're really into what must be called classics,
you can revel after midnight in ``Dr. Jekyll and Hyde'' (1932),
``Treasure Island'' (1934) and ``Tarzan, the Ape Man'' (1932).
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of nights when Turner Classics succumbs to
programming desperation (a double bill Tuesday starred Dennis
Morgan), but sprinkled in are some real oldies that have at least
curiosity value and may stir memories in viewers of a certain age,
like Monday's lineup of ``The Nuisance'' with Lee Tracy (1933),
``Solitaire Man'' with Herbert Marhall and Mary Boland (1933) and
``Arsene Lupin'' with John Barrymore (1932).
</P>
<P>
   All right, I know that ``The Fighting 69th'' is not one of the
great Warner Brothers efforts, but I would settle for watching
James Cagney and Pat O'Brien do the fighting this Friday, only I
won't find it on my screen. And what more could a fan ask of a
Sunday night that consisted of ``Ninotchka,'' ``The Whole Town's
Talking'' and ``The Informer,'' while on AMC, I was stuck with
``The Green Berets''?
</P>
<P>
   Generations that have been watching television since they were
in cribs are unlikely to share the warm feelings of those of us who
grew up with Cagney, O'Brien and the gang, which may be why
Cablevision has decided it is not worth the investment to find a
place for Turner Classic Movies on its schedule. There's doubtless
more profit in running ``Antz'' as a pay-per-view treat for the
kids.
</P>
<P>
   Cable customers don't have a lot of say in what is imposed on
them, but at the least the nostalgia-driven among us and those of a
younger set who have somehow succumbed to the charms of the old
movies can let their local monopoly know that they feel deprived.
There must be a movie buff of a lawyer around in search of a
class-action suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
