<P>
   COMPAQ-PROFITS _ AUSTIN, Texas _ As it struggles with sagging
profits, Compaq Computer Corp. hosts more than 4,000 customers in
Houston for its semi-annual Innovate conference, where it is
expected to talk about its disappointing earnings and introduce new
enterprise products. CEO Eckhard Pfeiffer will try to create some
positive momentum with the help of Craig Barrett, CEO of Intel
Corp. (Mahoney, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   MCI _ ATLANTA _MCI WorldCom was selected as a primary vendor to
upgrade Delta Air Lines' data communications network. The
three-year, multi-million dollar contract is the first phase of a
larger project. (Kanell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   JOBS _ ATLANTA _ The warpspeed growth of technology and the
Internet have created an enormous need for people who can create,
build, run and manage computers and software. The demand is
particularly heavy in the field of information technology. Because
schools can't produce these grads fast enough (there are 500,000
jobs to be filled nationwide), companies have to be creative in
finding workers. Microsoft, for example, is financing the creation
of its own future workforce by training people such as pharmacists
and architects to become info technology professionals. arranging
for fotos. (Joyner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   INFO-TECHNOLOGY _ Association for Information and Image
Managment meets in Atlanta Monday through Thursday. Information
technology manangers descend on Atlanta to find out abpit
infomanagement, using technology in the workplace and electronic
commerce, service, and sales and marketing. Linus Torvalds, creator
of Linux computer operating system is the keynote speaker.
(Kannell, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   SUNTRUST _ SunTrust Banks Inc., the nation's 10th biggest bank,
said first-quarter earnings rose 6 percent as trust and mortgage
fees grew. Synovus also reports earnings. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
