A6572 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HONGKONG-JEWS-NYT &LR;      04-13 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONGKONG-JEWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOGRAPHER DOCUMENTS JEWISH ENCLAVE IN HONG KONG 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ It nearly came apart over the red jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Frederic Brenner, a documentary photographer at work on an epic
project about the Jewish Diaspora, wanted all 600 of his
strong-minded subjects to slip on matching Chinese silk jackets for
a group portrait in front of the compact synagogue that nestles in
a forest of skyscrapers here.
</P>
<P>
   But Brenner was dealing with Hong Kong's Jews, a collection of
1,600 or so people about as fractious as any Jews he had
photographed in his travels through 42 countries. Uncompromisingly
devout or determinedly secular, Hong Kong's Jews rarely agree on
anything.
</P>
<P>
   Some people complained that the jackets were reminiscent of Mao
and sent the wrong signal for a people used to oppression. Others
said Hong Kong's Jews should wear symbols of their own heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Yet after relentless cajoling and no little bullying, Brenner
persuaded most to put on the jackets. And on a slate-grey morning,
the 40-year-old photographer snapped a vivid record of a Jewish
enclave in a capitalist bastion on the edge of the world's last
communist empire.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong photograph and another group portrait taken in
front of Mao's portrait facing Tiananmen Square in Beijing are the
penultimate chapter in Brenner's own Odyssean journey. For 20 years
this French-born photographer has documented Jews in alien
surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   The project, called ``Chronicle of Exile,'' has yielded five
coffee-table books and been exhibited in New York, Paris, Tel Aviv
and Buenos Aires. It is to be completed in 2001 after Brenner
returns to home ground to produce a final chapter on Jews in
Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``This project started with an intuition,'' said Brenner, an
intense, dark-haired man who speaks fervently and with the sort of
ready-made quotations that find their way into art books and
newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a highly assimilated Jewish family in Paris, Brenner
traveled to Israel at the age of 20 to take pictures. He said he
realized that Jews in Israel had recreated an Eastern European
shtetl, an identity that was fading elsewhere. So he set off for
remote corners of the world in a kind of race to memorialize Jewish
enclaves before they vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only after 8 or 10 years was it clear that I was piecing
together the fragments of a puzzle,'' Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   The puzzle is how Jews at once embrace and stand apart from
their adopted lands. He has explored that paradox with elaborate,
meticulously staged photographs that are striking for their
incongruous images.
</P>
<P>
   In one shot from his essay on American Jews, women celebrate a
Passover seder in a maximum-security prison. In another, called
``Jews With Hogs,'' the members of a Jewish motorcycle gang glower
from their Harley-Davidsons (known as hogs) in front of a Miami
Beach synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   To Brenner's delight, China provided rich possibilities for his
brand of odd juxtaposition. In the Hong Kong photo, people spill
out of a synagogue, while behind them a banner with Chinese
characters flutters from a typical Hong Kong high-rise. The banner
celebrates the Jewish holiday Purim.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Brenner won rare permission from the city to use the
giant portrait of Mao in Tiananmen Square as the backdrop for a
picture of the 180 Jews in the city. Some of them are wearing the
controversial silk jackets, and several are posed with bicycles.
Standing on a table directly beneath Mao's visage is a Torah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you believe this?'' Brenner says, pointing gleefully at
the photo of the Torah. ``This is the most subversive image you
could imagine in front of one of the most potent symbols of
socialism.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a project about outsiders, the Jews in Brenner's China
portraits seem disconnected from their environment. There are
precious few Chinese faces in the photos, though slightly more in
the Beijing portrait. It is clear from the photos that the Jews of
China are not assimilated into this vast country. They exist as an
expatriate subculture, a ripple in the sea of 1.2 billion Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   So why make five long trips, bicker over red jackets and
negotiate with truculent Chinese bureaucrats to photograph them?
</P>
<P>
   ``China is the ultimate `other' that the Jews will never be,''
Brenner said. ``It is the ultimate expression of the Diaspora. Jews
don't define themselves as being in a place. They define themselves
as being on a journey.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite that, Brenner was keen to evoke a sense of place. The
red silk jackets were supplied by David Tang, the flamboyant owner
of Shanghai Tang, which specializes in what could be called Mao
retro chic. To Brenner, they captured Hong Kong's style and
obsession with status.
</P>
<P>
   Such allusions were not lost on the would-be photo subjects.
Some objected that Brenner was going to make Hong Kong's Jews seem
like shallow materialists. He listened patiently to their
objections but did not give an inch. When a handful of people
balked at putting on the jackets the day of the shooting, Brenner
shunted them to the fringes of the photograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an artist; far be it from me to try to get into his
mind,'' said Rabbi Mordechai Avtzon of the Chabad congregation
here, who stayed out of the photo rather than wear a jacket.
</P>
<P>
   For all the grumbling, Brenner attracted people from all four
Jewish congregations in Hong Kong, although before the shoot some
liberal Jews refused to enter the synagogue that was the backdrop
for the picture because it is controlled by Hong Kong's Orthodox
Ohel Leah congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My project was the first that brought this community
together,'' Brenner said with endearing immodesty. ``It was like
mixing mayonnaise; sometimes it mixes well and sometimes it
doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   For Brenner, coming to Hong Kong was the logical culmination of
a journey that began in Israel. With its thrusting skyscrapers,
frenzied financial markets and jet-set populace, Brenner sees Hong
Kong as the perfect home for a transient people on the cusp of a
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jews,'' he noted, ``have lived in a global village for
4,000 years, ever since God spoke to Abraham.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
