<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN15-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TALL TALES AND SHORT STORIES: My cyber's lost in space
 &HT;    By Joe Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANGELINA COUNTY, Texas _ If everything had gone according to
plan, I'd be writing to you from somewhere deep in Dixie.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, here I am still stuck at home.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, but it was a fine plan.
</P>
<P>
   The home office in Atlanta _ the only city in the world where
there are people who can fire me _ had deemed that I should be
newly equipped with a new computer. Never mind I have yet to fully
figure out the one I've been using for the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The new one would be quicker, faster, better. The idea, I think,
is that they hoped it would make me quicker, faster, better.
</P>
<P>
   They would overnight it to me (can you remember when
``overnight'' wasn't a verb?), I'd piddle with it for a few days
and then I'd bring it with me to Atlanta to be tutored as to its
nits and nuances. After which, I'd be free to go my own way.
</P>
<P>
   My way _ the way I planned it _ was to drive south in the
general direction of Savannah, where I have never been but have
read about in the book ``Midnight in the Garden of Good and Evil''
and long to while away long evenings thereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   The plan was for my wife to fly to Savannah from Texas, we would
spend a couple of nights _ maybe even staying up until midnight
just to see what would happen _ then she would fly back home and
I'd drive onward southward, seeing what there was to see and
writing what there was to write.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, I planned to end up in Key West to look up whatever
evidence remains of Ernest Hemingway's years as a resident, this
being the 100th anniversary of his birth _ a good place to be and a
good reason to be there.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, my Cousin Bubba was figuring to take off a few days
from the tire store and meet up with me somewhere along the way,
way down there in Florida, to relive one more time a motor trip we
made almost 40 years ago, talking big, eating heartily and drinking
responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   Never gonna happen.
</P>
<P>
   I never got the computer.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere between there and here, somebody else got the
computer.
</P>
<P>
   That's what our company cyberman tells me the overnight express
company told him, that the computer was stolen along the way,
probably by one of their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Say la vee, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Say goodbye to my trip, said I.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, eventually I'll get another computer. Eventually, I'll go to
Atlanta and have it prayed over. But the rest of the trip is
doubtful.
</P>
<P>
   Later this month my wife has a trip of her own. First week of
next month I'm scheduled for minor eye surgery. In June I'm
supposed to be in China. Regardless, Bubba can't just up and leave
the tire store whenever he wants, not with people wanting tires.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever stole the computer stole what would have been a nice
couple of weeks of my life.
</P>
<P>
   (Joe Murray, editor-publisher emeritus of the Lufkin (Texas)
Daily News, is senior writer for Cox Newspapers. E-mail address is
jmurray(at)lcc.net; mailing address, P.O. Box 151108, Lufkin,
Texas, 75915.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
