<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLECTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PHOTOGRAPHIC TREASURES OF A SECRET COLLECTOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Mo., N.Y.)   (af)  
 By MARGARETT LOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before he died suddenly last year at 81 of a heart attack, David
Feigenbaum led the secret life of a collector of Citizen Kane-like
obsessiveness. He filled almost every inch of his two-story house
in Marblehead, Mass., with things, including books, guns, model
boats, Civil War and World War II paraphernalia and an old Scottish
Bible collection.
</P>
<P>
   In the basement, together with old manuscripts, historic
letters, coins and jewelry, was an extraordinary cache of
mid-19th-century daguerreotypes, including more than 200 made by
Southworth &AMP; Hawes of Boston, a recognized master of the form.
</P>
<P>
   Most daguerreotypes come in small sizes, but 70 of the pieces in
the Feigenbaum collection are extremely hard to find whole plates,
measuring 6{ by 8{ inches. The studio's partners, Albert S.
Southworth and Josiah J. Hawes, were famous for making portraits
marked by a radiant naturalness and artistry. And their studio drew
Boston's cultured elite, much as Nadar's in Paris became the
gathering place for that city's intellectuals.
</P>
<P>
   In recent decades specialists in daguerreotypes have seldom come
across an unknown whole-plate Southworth &AMP; Hawes, making the
discovery of the Feigenbaum photographic collection, which will be
offered at Sotheby's in Manhattan on April 27, even more unusual.
</P>
<P>
   Daguerreotypes, each of which is an in-camera positive image on
a polished silvered metal plate, were very popular in the United
States of the 1840s and 50s. They were by and large portraits, but
in the Feigenbaum collection are several cityscapes, including a
whole-plate modernist study of a glorious cloud-filled sky above a
roof line, its roofing tiles and a skylight nicely detailed.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-19th century it was technically difficult to take
such a picture. The risk was that the sky would be overexposed to
get the details in the roof line or that the roof line would be
underexposed, reducing it to a silhouette, to get the sky.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century French landscape photographer Gustave Le Gray
resolved the problem by combining a paper negative of the sky with
that of the sea.
</P>
<P>
   David Feigenbaum was born in 1917, the only child of Abraham
Feigenbaum, founder of the Tremont Camera Exchange, a
carriage-trade camera store in Boston. After his father died in the
1950s, David Feigenbaum managed the store for some years. He closed
the camera shop in 1957 and worked as an X-ray technologist in the
radiology department of Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   His surviving relatives knew he was a collector of sorts, but he
never talked about it. A niece, who asked not to be identified by
name, recalled a few hints of her uncle's acquisitiveness. One time
she told him that she didn't know what to throw out during a spring
cleaning. ``Why would you even think of throwing anything out?''
she remembers him asking.
</P>
<P>
   Feigenbaum enjoyed the frequent company of friends and such
pastimes as sailing and walking. He was also something of an
eccentric. Early in the 1990s, a few years after his wife's death,
when friends and relatives arranged to have a meal with him or an
outing, he would wait for them outside his house, his niece said.
Afterward they would deposit him outside his house. He never
invited anyone in, and the windows were always closed, the curtains
drawn.
</P>
<P>
   After Feigenbaum's death, his sister-in-law made the funeral
arrangements. She finally got to see the mind-boggling interior of
his house. A few weeks later she went with her two children and
son-in-law to Marblehead and with a crew and began to clear the
house.
</P>
<P>
   The cleanup squad initially assumed they were dealing with
wall-to-wall junk. ``I said, `Let's take a match to this place
because there's so much junk,''' recalled the niece. Her husband's
first thought on seeing the inside of the house was the warehouse
scene at the end of ``Citizen Kane.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the next few weeks, 32 tons of trash _ old newspapers, old
cans of food, jars, bottle caps _ were pitched into Dumpsters. But
then the surprises emerged: 16th-century manuscripts, 1865 tickets
to the Ford Theater, a letter from a family member in Custer's
army. Inside two safes in the basement were coins, jewelry, Patek
Philippe watches and unset sapphires and rubies.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the cleanup, a relative spotted crates marked
``Eastman Kodak Co.'' He opened one, picked up a few daguerreotypes
in their original slatted plate boxes, and knew he was looking at
something out of the ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   Most daguerreotypes unearthed from America's attics are
unexceptional. Under the process, which was developed in France by
Louis J.M. Daguerre in the 1830s, a daguerreotypist makes an image
by exposing a painstakingly polished plate in the camera. The
process also requires the sitter to hold still for as long as 30
seconds, which led to exceedingly stiff portraits.
</P>
<P>
   Yet a select group, including Thomas M. Easterly of St. Louis,
and Southworth &AMP; Hawes, produced images that have the fluidity of
photographs taken by later artists using faster lenses and film.
Southworth &AMP; Hawes, in particular, knew how to make the kind of
technical improvements that would allow for shorter exposure times
and greater clarity, depth and tonal range.
</P>
<P>
   George Romer, director of conservation and museum studies at the
George Eastman House in Rochester, said the Feigenbaum trove can be
traced to a sale by Holman's Print Shop of Boston, which
represented the Hawes family, in the 1930s and 40s. At the time a
few collectors bought sizable numbers of the pieces, which were
subsequently given to the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New York,
the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and the George Eastman House.
</P>
<P>
   Feigenbaum's heirs have already sold his house and much of its
contents. None of them are collectors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
