<HEADER>
A6578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-TICKET-ART-2TAKES     04-13 1004
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-TICKET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS CHARITABLE FUNDS DROP, MUSEUM VISITORS PAY MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JUDITH H. DOBRZYNSKI with GERALDINE FABRIKANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ever so quietly the Metropolitan Museum of Art has
raised its suggested admission price to $10, from $8. Visitors to
the museum have been learning of that 25 percent increase only
after they climb the granite steps and read signs above the ticket
booths inside.
</P>
<P>
   The price jump, which went into effect March 1, is necessary to
shore up the museum's finances, Met officials say. Even with the
new fee, the museum expects to close the books for its current
fiscal year, which ends June 30, deeper in the red than last year,
when the deficit totaled $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Both the ticket increase and the deficit are legacies, in part,
of the fix the Met has been in since mid-1997, when the Reader's
Digest Association, the magazine and book company, woke up to
stagnant sales and faltering expansion efforts and began a
retrenchment that included a cut in its stock dividends.
</P>
<P>
   Years earlier, Lila Acheson Wallace, the philanthropic grande
dame and co-founder of Reader's Digest who died in 1984, had
established an organization that made the museum the beneficiary of
dividends from a chunk of Reader's Digest Association stock and
other assets. The handsome annuity from the company's dividends
reached more than $16 million in 1996, or nearly 15 percent of the
Met's operating budget, which then was about $110 million and is
now about $120 million.
</P>
<P>
   As Reader's Digest has slashed its quarterly dividend to 5 cents
a share from 45 cents a share in 1997, the payout to the Met's
Wallace fund dropped to $2.6 million this year from $6 million in
fiscal 1998 and $12.2 million in 1997. Unless the company's board
reverses course and raises the dividend rate, next year's
contribution will be $1.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Philippe de Montebello, the director of the Met, makes no
apologies for raising admissions to help make up the shortfall.
``It is without any embarrassment that we do this,'' he said. ``We
are not cutting programs or services, and we are keeping galleries
open. And it is not a fixed price of admission.''
</P>
<P>
   The Met's policy says that people may pay what they wish, though
they must pay something. And many do pay less than the suggested
amount. With the Met's previous suggested price of $8, individual
contributions averaged between $5 and $6.
</P>
<P>
   De Montebello said he did not think visitors would stay away
because of the increase: ``Why should they? It's still
`suggested.''' He continued, ``And it's a bargain compared to other
institutions around town.'' The Met maintains that attendance has
not been affected.
</P>
<P>
   The troubles at Reader's Digest have also hurt other cultural
institutions that were favorites of Lila Wallace and her husband,
DeWitt Wallace, who died in 1981: Lincoln Center; the Wildlife
Conservation Society, whose flagship is the Bronx Zoo, and Colonial
Williamsburg in Virginia are all beneficiaries of organizations
that hold Reader's Digest stock. So are two Hudson River basin
preservation groups, Memorial Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center in
Manhattan and Macalester College in St. Paul.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Wallaces created a separate fund for each
institution, each has different assets, grant policies and
trustees. So each organization can decide how to cope for itself.
So far, only the Met has taken an action that touches consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Trustees of the Wildlife Conservation Society's Wallace fund,
for example, have chosen to dig into the rising value of its stock
assets, including Reader's Digest stock, which has rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have done with the support of the Wallace board is to
choose to spend 5 percent of the total market value of the fund,
which has put us on the prior level of funding,'' said John Hoare,
the controller. ``This year our grant will be $7.2 million. Last
year it was $6.6 million.''
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln Center has also offset the dividend loss by using some
stock gains. ``Our first cut would come in the next fiscal year,''
said Bernard Gersten, the executive producer of Lincoln Center
Theater, one of the center's seven arts groups. ``And it will be
about $500,000, while our budget is expected to be about $28
million.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Schneiderman, co-chairman of the New York City Opera, said
that the opera's first cut would come in June. ``We are trying to
raise more money,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise Colonial Williamsburg plans to make up for dividend
declines with a new policy that bases its annual grant on the
capital appreciation and dividends of the assets in its fund
instead of solely on dividends. ``We are hoping the policy shift
will be in place by 2000,'' said Kathy Whitehead, the chief
financial officer.
</P>
<P>
   The Met has tapped into a reserve fund, money from previous
Wallace grants that went unspent, to help make up for the dividend
cut. But between 1997 and fiscal year 2000, it will suffer a drop
of nearly $11 million from the Wallace fund.
</P>
<P>
   Like the other Wallace beneficiaries, the Met is spending money
carefully and trying to replace lost money with new donations.
``You can assume that all departments and individuals at the museum
are looking at every possible option,'' de Montebello said. ``We
want to stabilize the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Met is also asking more from visitors because it has
more leeway with them. Theater and opera tickets are already steep,
and movies, the barometer used by many museums as a guide in
setting admission fees, typically cost $9.50 in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As for rival Manhattan museums, general admission at the Solomon
R. Guggenheim Museum is $12 _ no ``suggested'' about it _ to see a
far less comprehensive collection. Tickets for the Museum of Modern
Art are $9.50, and for the Whitney Museum of American Art, $9.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Blockbuster exhibitions cost more: $15 at the Guggenheim, $12.50
at the Modern and $12.50 for the Whitney's coming ``American
Century'' show. But the Met never asks more for them.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has the Met been as aggressive as others at raising prices.
The last increase was in July 1996. Since 1992 the Met's suggested
donation has risen 67 percent from $6, while the Guggenheim's
admission fee has climbed 71 percent, from $7, in the same period,
and the Whitney's has jumped 80 percent since 1992, when it was $5.
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney also sneaked through something of an increase last
November, when it quietly eliminated its free hours on Thursday
evenings. Instead, visitors must pay something. Thursday evening
revenues have since jumped from $80, or about 10 cents a person, to
$800, or about $1.18 a person, the museum said. And beginning May
6, only the first Thursday evening of the month will be pay as you
wish; for the rest of the month visitors will have to pay the usual
admission.
</P>
<P>
   De Montebello said he would not follow the course of some large
museums, which mount a blockbuster every year, often of Monet or
other Impressionists, specifically to draw crowds. ``I still have
integrity,'' he said. ``We won't do an exhibition just for the
gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he added, ``those exhibitions take three or four years
to organize. It's not like the opera, where if you want to do
`Aida,' I suppose you can scramble and get sets from downstairs.
Loan exhibitions take years to do the scholarship and to arrange.''
</P>
<P>
   The deficit is real now. For the fiscal year that ends in June,
``there's no question it will be up'' from last year's $1.5 million
total, said Deborah Winschel, the Met's chief financial officer,
``but it won't be a huge jump.''
</P>
<P>
   The size of the deficit will largely depend on the popularity of
the Met's next big exhibition, ``Cezanne to Van Gogh: The
Collection of Dr. Gachet,'' which opens May 25, a look at the
paintings collected by and painted by van Gogh's last doctor.
</P>
<P>
   And another problem looms. The Met has been getting about $16
million a year from New York City, but as usual, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani has proposed a budget cut, this year of about $2.1
million.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it happens every spring. But this year City Council members
have been saying they will not mount their usual fight to restore
cuts to cultural programs, leaving the Met and other institutions
in the lurch.
</P>
<P>
   De Montebello declined to discuss that prospect and its
potential impact. ``I'd rather not think about that melancholy
thought,'' he said. ``I don't want to contemplate it. It's
unimaginable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1800EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
