u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TOYOTA-APPOINT-NYT &LR;      04-13 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOYOTA-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOYOTA NAMES NEW PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ Toyota Motor Corp. on Tuesday ended months of
speculation about who would succeed Hiroshi Okuda as its president,
appointing a close aide of the Japanese automaker's founding family
to replace him.
</P>
<P>
   Okuda, a darling of the media and investment communities, will
become chairman, which in Japan is considered a less responsible
position than president. He will replace Shoichiro Toyoda, a
third-generation scion of the family that created the company, who
will become honorary chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing Okuda will be Fujio Cho, 62, who most recently served
as right-hand man to Toyoda when he was chairman of the Keidanren,
Japan's leading business association. Cho also is known for his
ties to the Toyoda family, whose influence at the company is far
out of proportion to the tiny percentage of shares it still owns.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most important, Cho enjoys widespread popularity among
Toyota's vast network of suppliers, who were mistrustful of Okuda's
cost-cutting efforts. So he is well positioned to assure a smooth
transition.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will take effect after the annual shareholders'
meeting in late June.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had anticipated Cho's appointment ever since Okuda
stunned corporate Japan in January by announcing that he intended
to vacate his Toyota post to take charge of the Japan Federation of
Employers' Associations, or Nikkeiren.
</P>
<P>
   That announcement raised speculation that Okuda's management of
the company had been called into question. One rumor suggested that
the changes Okuda had made at Toyota _ many of them imposed quickly
and with little deference to tradition and convention _ had upset
Eiji Toyoda, Shoichiro's cousin and the family patriarch.
</P>
<P>
   Okuda himself said he thought the job required more energy than
he, at 66 years old, could provide. But that explanation was not
widely accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The most intriguing of the ``Okuda ouster'' theories _ and the
one given the most credence by analysts and executives at other
Japanese auto companies _ suggests that he ran afoul of Toyota's
``home boys,'' the insular community of parts manufacturers,
dealers and service providers situated in and around the company's
headquarters in Toyota City on the outskirts of Nagoya.
</P>
<P>
   Those vendors, having seen Okuda's success in cutting costs
inside Toyota, anticipated that he would soon try to reduce costs
associated with them. Toyota makes more than 70 percent of the
vehicles it produces in Japan, buying the parts for those cars
largely in Japan from suppliers in which it often holds ownership
stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Those suppliers have high costs and charge more than competitors
abroad. That means Toyota pays more for most parts than its rivals
pay, a problem it must solve.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in March, Okuda, the first non-family member to
run the company, laughed at the suggestion of tension between him
and the Toyoda family. He also refused to comment about his future
at the Nikkeiren but said he looked forward to doing something new.
</P>
<P>
   During his four years as Toyota's president, he reduced costs,
expanded the company's product lineup and ushered it into what he
calls the ``5 Million Club,'' the group of automakers that produce
more than 5 million cars a year.
</P>
<P>
   His penchant for blunt off-the-cuff remarks and his broad smile
are traits not usually displayed by senior Japanese executives. He
was well liked by foreign journalists and helped give Toyota a
human face _ and his public-relations staff ulcers.
</P>
<P>
   Tetsuo Kitagawa, Toyota's spokesman in charge of the foreign
press, is known for chain-smoking through interviews and briefings
conducted by Okuda.
</P>
<P>
   In one recent moment of unusual candor, he complained about his
appointment to the Prime Minister's Economic Strategy Council,
saying it wouldn't accomplish anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't being outspoken supposed to be a good thing?'' he asked,
when questioned about the remark. Later he conceded: ``It is true
that in Japan, we have had a saying that silence is golden and
eloquence is, well, I'm not sure exactly what, but something bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But the very things that endeared him to foreign investors and
reporters may have led to an abbreviated tenure as Toyota's top
executive. Comparing his situation to that of Nobuyuki Idei, the
president of Sony, another high-profile and controversial Japanese
corporate leader, Okuda said, ``our personalities may have been
criticized for wanting or suggesting change.''
</P>
<P>
   Okuda said he thought more people like him and Idei would
continue to gain top jobs in Japan, not only in business but
politics. He denied speculation, though, that he has considered a
political career.
</P>
<P>
   Asked to identify his best achievement, he said, ``If there is
one thing I can be proud of, it is that we needed to change and in
driving that message home, we did change.''
</P>
<P>
   Many feel he paid a high price for that achievement, that it may
have cost him his job, but Okuda said no. ``As you know, salarymen
don't make so much money, so I could not afford a high price,'' he
answered and smiled one of his characteristic grins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
