<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-NEWBRIDGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREA FIRST BANK SALE TO FOREIGN CONSORTIUM UNRAVELING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ A financial deal widely interpreted as a sign that South
Korea was recovering from its economic malaise is in danger of
coming undone.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement by the South Korean government to sell the ailing
Korea First Bank to a consortium led by Newbridge Capital Ltd., a
private equity fund backed by the American investors Richard Blum
and David Bonderman, has foundered over a disagreement about how to
value the bank's assets and establish a sale price, people involved
in the dispute said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are differences,'' said Sandy Park, a spokeswoman for
the Financial Supervisory Commission, which is overseeing the
overhaul of South Korea's battered banking system.
</P>
<P>
   She said it was impossible to say whether those differences
would prove insurmountable. ``It's hard to tell at this time
whether the investors want more time to try to work on coming to
agreement or whether we have to find another buyer,'' Ms. Park
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Newbridge official said the consortium was committed to
completing the deal as it was described in a memorandum of
understanding between the group and the government. ``We continue
to believe that deal is in the best interests of Korea First Bank,
Newbridge and the government,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, which includes GE Capital, signed a deal Dec. 31
to buy 51 percent of Korea First, one of two banks nationalized to
help satisfy concerns of the International Monetary Fund when it
extended a $57 billion economic rescue package in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation about the disagreement between Newbridge and the
government has been brewing for some time in the South Korean
press, and the publicity could merely be posturing aimed at winning
better terms for the South Korean government.
</P>
<P>
   But many deals have fallen apart in South Korea since the
country committed itself to eliminating barriers to foreign
investment, which it needs to repair its economy. Buyers and
sellers have vastly different ideas about how Korean assets should
be priced and what constitutes liability.
</P>
<P>
   Newbridge itself canceled plans to buy Haitai Beverage, a unit
of South Korea's bankrupt Haitai group, and in general, the flood
of foreign investment that had been expected has instead been a
trickle, despite legions of investment bankers camped out in
Seoul's five-star hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between the government and Newbridge seemed to
symbolize the end of South Korea's deep economic decline and the
beginning of the surge of foreign investment that the country had
been awaiting.
</P>
<P>
   It was seen as the first large vote of confidence in the South
Korean government's promises to embrace market forces, improve
financial disclosure requirements and eliminate inappropriately
close relations between government and business, and it underscored
the speed with which the government was moving to repair a
debt-burdened financial system.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the government has agreed to sell 70 percent of
Seoul Bank, the other bank it nationalized, to HSBC Holdings. And
on Monday a group of investors led by Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. said it
had agreed to pay $500 million for a 17 percent stake in Kookmin
Bank, one of South Korea's largest and soundest banks.
</P>
<P>
   That investment, Goldman's largest in Asia, along with the
general sense that South Korea is well down the path to economic
recovery, may have made the government reconsider its deal with the
Newbridge consortium, which is focused on the price it will pay and
how much risk it will assume.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environment has definitely changed there since the
beginning of the year,'' said one financial buyer who has been
scouting in South Korea for deals. ``There's a political drift away
from pushing ahead hard and opening the market.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement with Newbridge has apparently foundered on the
issue of how to value the assets that will remain on Korea First's
books. The value of those assets will establish the price Newbridge
will pay.
</P>
<P>
   Newbridge has apparently priced those assets at what it regards
as fair market value based on Western methods of evaluating bank
loans, known as mark-to-market accounting, while the government is
using book values, which are probably somewhere near the face value
of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   South Korean banks typically did not write loans down much below
face value; if they had, more loans would have been thrown into the
non-performing category, requiring banks to increase their reserves
against potential losses. Thus the book value of Korea First's
loans may not reflect what they are actually worth today.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Newbridge's use of market pricing is an effort to
ensure that it gets the best price possible.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean government has pledged to adopt mark-to-market
accounting, but Ms. Park said the shift would have to be gradual.
``It's hard for us just in one day to completely change our
system,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
