</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINN FEIN'S OBJECTION DEEPENS PESSIMISM AROUND BELFAST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ The political wing of the Irish Republican Army said
Tuesday at peace talks in Belfast that it had rejected a proposal
by the British and Irish governments to resolve the impasse on
disarmament that is blocking the formation of a new Northern
Ireland government.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Mitchel McLaughlin, chairman of Sinn Fein,
the political wing of the IRA, deepened the growing pessimism
around the talks. The negotiations resumed Tuesday after a 12-day
suspension to examine the two governments' framework declaration.
</P>
<P>
   The action also isolated Sinn Fein as the sole objector among
the parties to the document. Those parties include the Social
Democratic and Labor Party, made up mostly of moderate Catholics,
and the Irish government in Dublin _ two delegations that share
Sinn Fein's long-term goal of unifying the predominantly Protestant
North with the largely Catholic Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The talks broke off inconclusively April 1 on the eve of a Good
Friday deadline, despite the presence of the British and Irish
prime ministers, Tony Blair and Bertie Ahern
</P>
<P>
   The accord promising the return of home rule to Northern Ireland
and seeking an end to three decades of sectarian violence was
reached on Good Friday a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   There is growing urgency to put the full settlement into effect,
because of the imminence of the most politically volatile period in
Northern Ireland's year, the Protestant Orange Order marching
season, which has sparked provincewide violence in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   The process for an accord has faced many hurdles and 11th-hour
crises. But the dispute over disarming, called ``decommissioning''
in the parlance of the negotiations, is proving to be the most
daunting.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is a demand by the Ulster Unionists, the largest
Protestant party in the province, that the IRA make a ``credible
start'' at decommissioning before Sinn Fein is permitted to occupy
the two executive seats to which it is entitled in the new
power-sharing Northern Ireland Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature is the centerpiece of the Good Friday agreement
and becomes effective only on the transfer of home-rule powers from
the British Parliament here. That defining move, in turn, awaits
the creation of the executive branch of the government.
</P>
<P>
   The original accord set no obligation for disarmament before the
Assembly and other agencies were set up. Sinn Fein is adamant that
it will not allow such a ``precondition'' to be created now. It has
repeatedly said that it cannot ``deliver'' such action from the
IRA, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The party further points out that it has met all the demands set
out in the accord and that the vote it attracted in the elections
last June to the new body gives it an absolute right to the two
Cabinet seats.
</P>
<P>
   Disarmament provokes deep-seated opposition among republicans,
or those who seek closer ties with the Irish Republic, because they
see it as an act of surrender. And they are not convinced that the
Catholic minority in Northern Ireland will never again have to use
physical force to protect itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Ulster Unionists have contended that even if the accord does
not specifically demand disarmament now, it is unacceptable to let
a party participate in legislative politics ``with arms under the
table.'' That argument has become such a powerful and broadly
accepted one in the overall debate that if the impasse causes the
failure of the peace settlement, almost all the blame will be laid
on Sinn Fein.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the end of the marathon talks on April 1 at Hillsborough
Castle, outside Belfast, the two prime ministers brought forth
their document, which painstakingly sought to marry the two
antagonistic positions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a precondition, disarmament would be only an
``obligation,'' and a ``voluntary'' one at that. Guns would not
actually be ``decommissioned.'' They would be ``put beyond use.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of the executive would not be ``named'' at first, but
``nominated'' with a month before officially occupying their
positions. In that time, some arms would be put beyond use in a way
that would be verifiable by Gen. John de Chastelain, chairman of
the independent disarmament commission.
</P>
<P>
   That would enable Sinn Fein to say it was in the executive
without having had to agree to a precondition on disarmament, and
the Ulster Unionists could say a disarmament demand had been met
before Sinn Fein's Cabinet rank was official.
</P>
<P>
   The British Secretary for Northern Ireland, Mo Mowlam, said
Tuesday that despite the Sinn Fein disparagement of the
Hillsborough Declaration, as the proposal has been called, it would
remain the basis for seeking a final agreement. Blair and Ahern are
expected to return to Belfast this week to try to rescue the talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
