<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-KOSOVO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME KEY SENATORS URGE PREPARATIONS FOR GROUND TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN and MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Although Congress remains split on the use of
ground forces in Kosovo, leading senators of both parties said
Tuesday that the North Atlantic Treaty Organization should start
preparing for an invasion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., a member of the Senate Foreign Affairs
Committee, said congressional leaders continue to support the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, I would make it very clear we are
prepared to use anything necessary to achieve our goal,'' he said
after an hour-long meeting that President Clinton held with him and
57 other members of Congress, most of them from committees dealing
with national security.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky., a member of the Senate
Appropriations defense subcommittee, said a ``widespread opinion''
among members is that the president should not rule out the use of
ground troops and that ``obviously, the way to keep the ground
option available would be to do some pre-positioning.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., who also serves on the subcommittee,
said ``infrastructure'' such as landing strips, fuel depots and
communication centers would have to be built before any large
contingent of troops could be sent to the Balkans from U.S.
military bases in Ramstein, Germany, or Aviano, Italy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just thinking that it would be a realistic thing to do
because this is not simply flying out of Ramstein or Aviano and
saying, `Here we come,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Suggesting that a troop buildup might entice Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to sign a peace agreement, Sen. Richard Lugar,
R-Ind., a member of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, said,
``We have to be prepared to fight this to the finish.''
</P>
<P>
   Military experts have worried that without significant
preparation by NATO engineers, any invasion by NATO troops would
bog down because of poor road, rail, port and communications
systems in the Balkan region.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Lt. Gen. William Odom, a former director of the
National Security Agency, has said that any assault on Kosovo, a
province of Serbia, the dominant state in Yugoslavia, could take
several weeks or longer to prepare.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting between Clinton and lawmakers came as NATO's
military commander, Army Gen. Wesley Clark, was requesting some 300
more U.S. planes and helicopters as well as more air power from
NATO allies, although he did not say how many.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen is expected to approve the
request quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The reinforcements would be supplement the 500 U.S. aircraft
that are already part of NATO's 700-plane force. The additional
planes would include ground-attack jets such as Air Force F-15s and
F-16s, radar-jamming planes such as Navy EA-6Bs to disrupt and
attack Serb air defenses, and refueling tankers such as Air Force
KC-135s to allow allied pilots to stay aloft longer.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., a GOP presidential contender, said
the request for new planes demonstrates a lack of success in the
air campaign. ``To request an additional 300 aircraft three weeks
into the war is not an indication that everything is on track,'' he
said in a speech at the Center for Strategic and International
Studies here.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would ask Congress soon for an emergency
supplemental appropriation to finance the war. Administration and
congressional officials have estimated the cost at $3 billion to $5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Ala., chairman of the Senate Appropriations
Committee, referring to questions about funding the war, said the
Pentagon would get the money. But he added that he was ``very
concerned about how we handle this total operation.'' He was
referring to a debate over paying for the war from the expected
federal budget surplus or from spending cutbacks in other areas.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., a member of the House
International Relations Committee, said at a news conference here
that the air offensive is unconstitutional because ``we are engaged
in a war that has not been declared.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday Campbell introduced two resolutions _ one to formally
declare war on Yugoslavia and the other to order the troops
withdrawn. He said he was invoking the War Powers Act of 1973,
which requires both chambers of Congress to vote on a military
action 60 days after it has begun. In this case, the chambers would
have to vote on the two measures next month. If Congress refuses to
declare war, Campbell said he will go to federal court seeking a
ruling that Clinton's military actions in the Balkans are
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   However, House Majority Leader Richard Armey, R-Texas, said he
had reservations about Campbell's resolutions and is considering
asking the Californian to withdraw the measures.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk with lawmakers, Clinton emphasized that the air
bombardment of Iraq leading up to the use of ground forces in the
Persian Gulf War in 1991 took 44 days _ and urged lawmakers not to
rush to judgment.
</P>
</TEXT>
