San Francisco _  ALLERGY  _ When Tom Walton swiped a scallop off
his wife's plate in a fancy restaurant, he never expected what
happened next. In two minutes, he was on the floor, staring up at a
crowd of concerned faces, including the two doctors and a dentist
who had caught him as he collapsed backward. The suspected reason:
one little shellfish. And Walton's not alone. Chefs report
increasing special requests from food-allergic diners, who face
illness or death if they eat the wrong thing _ and those diners
report that hidden ingredients can make dining out a nightmare. &HT;    With resource bar. 
 By Janet Fletcher  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
