<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: This column profiles Northern California growers, 
 anglers and artisans who make the region such a culinary 
 wonderland. Over the next few months, we'll take you from field 
 to forest to factory to look at the wealth of ingredients 
 stocking our larders. As a bonus, Georgeanne Brennan will offer 
 tips for using the bounty in fresh, innovative ways.  
   
   
   
 AT THE SOURCE: A Cuke of a Special Stripe  
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  The Ferry Plaza cucumber guy. That's what some
people call Nick Atallah.
 &HT;    At this farmers' market in San Francisco _ and at nine other
markets in the Bay Area and around Sacramento, the Lebanese-born
Atallah and his wife, Jane, sell a top-quality edible-skin cucumber
he has dubbed ``Mediterranean''.
 &HT;    ``This is the cucumber I grew up with,'' Atallah says of the
inch-wide, 5-to-6-inch-long seedless cuke. ``When I came here,
Jordanians called it the Jordanian cucumber, Egyptians called it
the Egyptian cucumber, Israelis called it the Israeli cucumber, and
Iranians said, `No, no, no, this is the Persian cucumber.' So I
decided to call it the Mediterranean cucumber to please everyone.''
 &HT;    Not only is he a culinary diplomat, but when it comes to cukes,
Atallah _ who holds a doctorate in water resources engineering from
the University of California at Davis and has raised cucumbers
since 1986 _ is also an agricultural perfectionist.
 &HT;    Atallah grows his Mediterranean cucumbers in greenhouses at his
farm, Madison Growers, in Yolo County. The greenhouse extends the
season and controls the environment so the cucumbers mature with
optimum flavor, crispness and shape.
 &HT;    He trellises the vines and trains them to grow seven feet up. As
the cucumbers develop, they dangle down through the foliage,
growing straight _ not crooked. He harvests 75,000 pounds of cukes
a season, which he claims is small in the commercial scheme of
things.
 &HT;    Come harvest time _ now through October, with peak from June
through September _ Atallah and four workers hand pick the cukes
``at the exact point of ripeness,'' he says. ``We pick them today
and sell them tomorrow.''.
 &HT;    At 5 to 6 inches long, ``crispness and texture are best. When
the cucumber is longer than 6 inches, you can cut a cross section
and see the center start to hollow. This means the cucumber is
starting to overmature,'' he says.
 &HT;    Atallah's cucumbers are not organic according to state
regulations because he uses a commercial fertilizer. But he forgos
all pesticides, relying instead on beneficial insects in the
greenhouse environment to control pests.
 &HT;    Atallah's Mediterranean cucumber has a thin, medium to dark
green skin, which, unlike some other cucumbers, isn't washed,
treated with chemicals or waxed after harvest. ``Because the skin
is so thin, you can eat this cucumber whole. You can pick one up at
the market and eat it right there,'' he says, laughing.
 &HT;    Want to? You'll find Jane Atallah at a stand at the Ferry Plaza
Farmers' Market in San Francisco on Saturdays, and at the Thursday
and Saturday farmers' markets at the Marin Civic Center.
 &HT;    Atallah's Mediterranean cucumber is also sold at Monterey Market
(1550 Hopkins St., Berkeley) and Hatam (821 B St., San Rafael). The
Atallahs also grow greenhouse tomatoes, peppers, Japanese
cucumbers, pot basil and French Charentais melons, which they sell
at their stand in season.
 &HT;      
  
 
 HOT TIPS ON COOL CUCUMBERS  
 
Here are some tips for handling and using Mediterranean cucumbers. &HT;    Five or six Mediterranean cucumbers make up a pound. To store
them, wrap them in paper towels (which absorb the cucumbers'
moisture), then in plastic bags, and refrigerate them up to 10
days.
 &HT;    Nick Atallah's Mediterranean cucumber is ideal for cutting into
spears for dipping as an hors d'oeuvre and for slicing and chopping
in salads. Because the skins are edible, they're perfect for Greek
salads.
 &HT;     
   _ Maria Cianci &HT;     
 
 GEORGEANNE'S KITCHEN: Try These Appealing Cucumber Recipes  
   
 By Georgeanne Brennan  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Here are a few intriguing ways to use Mediterranean cucumbers. The
recipes also will work with hothouse (English) or regular
cucumbers.
<P>
   &UR; Braised Cucumbers with Dill.  &LR; Peel cucumbers, if desired, and
halve them lengthwise. Scrape out the seeds, then cut the cucumbers
into thin slices. Saute in melted butter for about 1 minute. Add a
little chicken broth and cook for 2 to 3 minutes longer. Sprinkle
with minced dill. Serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cucumber and Onion Salad.  &LR; Peel cucumbers if desired, and
thinly slice. Add thinly sliced onion. Put the cucumbers and onions
in a bowl of ice water and let soak for 20 minutes. Drain and pat
dry. Place in a bowl and add rice wine vinegar, a little salt and
chopped cilantro. Chill before serving..
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cucumbers with Goat Cheese and Tapenade.  &LR; Cut cucumbers into
thin slices. Spread each slice with a little tapenade, top with a
dollop of soft goat cheese and garnish with minced red onion.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cucumber, Dried Tomato and Yogurt Salad.  &LR; Cut a cucumber in
half lengthwise. Peel (if desired) and seed it. Sprinkle with a
little salt and place the halves face-down on paper towels. Wipe
off the salt with more paper towels, then grate the cucumber.
</P>
<P>
   Mince about 1 tablespoon dried tomatoes. Roast a little cumin
seed in a frying pan.
</P>
<P>
   Mix together the grated cucumber, tomatoes, cumin, 1 cup plain
yogurt, about 1 tablespoon minced fresh mint, a dash of cayenne and
salt to taste. Cover and refrigerate for an hour. Serve chilled.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Cucumbers with Tomato and Stilton.  &LR; Peel cucumbers, if desired,
then cube them. Cut tomatoes into wedges. Mince red onions.
</P>
<P>
   Combine about 2 or 3 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil with an
ounce or so of Stilton cheese, a little red wine vinegar and
pepper. Mash together, but leave the cheese still a little lumpy.
</P>
<P>
   Put the cucumbers, tomatoes and a little onion in a bowl. Pour
the olive oil mixture over them and turn to coat.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange red leaf or other lettuce leaves on a platter; add the
cucumber mixture, crumble more Stilton over the top and sprinkle
with the remaining red onion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Georgeanne Brennan, a food and garden writer who lives in Yolo
County, is the author of ``Aperitif'' and ``The Food and Flavors of
Haute Provence.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
