<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LOOTERS-0414-C     04-13 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LOOTERS-0414-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OFFICIALS: LOOTERS MAKE DROPPING FOOD AID IN DIFFICULT
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0414; KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ In a sign of how difficult it is to coordinate
a refugee crisis on a foggy day, two U.S. Navy helicopters on
Tuesday unloaded six tons of food aid at the wrong airstrip -- only
to have it looted by enterprising mountain people in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The stolen boxes of food weighed about six tons -- enough to
feed about 10,000 of the roughly 95,000 refugees in this border
town for one day. UN officials, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said the theft will not cause hunger in the refugee
camps because they have sufficient stockpiles of other food, at
least for the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials confirmed Tuesday that the helicopters were
sent from the USS Inchon, a mine countermeasures ship stationed in
the Adriatic Sea that has been running humanitarian supplies into
Albania over the last two days. Since early Tuesday morning, they
said the ship had delivered more than 66,000 pounds of daily
rations in over two dozen helicopter flights.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials had no information on Tuesday's specific
incident of looting supplies, but no one ruled it out as
implausible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of looters in that area,'' Pentagon spokesman
Kenneth H. Bacon said.
</P>
<P>
   UN aid officials here learned of the episode Tuesday when the
American pilots of the two Navy helicopters made their way to the
office of the UN's World Food Program on the fourth floor of the
Hotel Turizmi, asking to use a satellite phone to call their
commanding officers.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots told a UN duty officer that they landed on this
drizzly day at an Albanian military airstrip located about two
miles south of this refugee-packed border town.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots said they had flown from an American carrier in the
Adriatic and had been directed where to bring the food by air
controllers at the Rinas Air Field in the Albanian capital of
Tirana, whose control tower has come under the direction of U.S.
Air Force air controllers within the last 48 hours. The pilots
didn't give the name of the carrier on which they are based.
</P>
<P>
   UN officials said they were told that one Navy chopper set down
just inside the boundaries of the Albanian base and the other
landed in a field just outside the boundaries. The site is known as
the Meteor Air Base, according to Albanians interviewed on the
scene.
</P>
<P>
   Navy personnel aboard the copters managed to unload about six
tons of food. But there were no security guards to protect the
cargo, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Within minutes, many people showed up and began carting away the
food, the Navy pilots told UN officials. UN World Food Program
officials said the cardboard boxes of food never reached the
agency's warehouses in Kukes, although some of it may have reached
Kosovo refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers Washington correspondent Scott Montgomery
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
