<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6609 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-QUICKCOOK-SFCHRON &LR;      04-13 2238
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUICKCOOK-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON  
 EDITORS NOTE: Here is a recipe to make on the weekend, with  enough
leftovers to use throughout the week in two other recipes 
 plus suggested ideas for other dishes. Recipes follow, plus 
 suggestions in optional trim.   THE WEEKEND COOK: Pass Up the Loin Chops and Go for the Shoulder  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
 
 
SAN FRANCISCO _ A request for pork chops for this column led the
Food Department down an interesting path of collaboration. As often
happens when people brainstorm an idea, no one can predict the
results and what does come up in the end can be a happy surprise
for all. It happened to us with today's Quick Cook.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pork chops are versatile, relatively inexpensive and popular.
But they present a problem for developing recipes that result in
leftovers. Because modern pork is so lean, saving leftovers for use
throughout the week could result in overly dry meat.
</P>
<P>
   My challenge: Choose the most suitable pork chop and cooking
method to make the request work.
</P>
<P>
   My solution: Bypass the lean and lovely loin chops, and choose a
fattier chop to keep the meat tender. Use a moist heat cooking
method to further minimize the danger of drying out the meat.
</P>
<P>
   I chose a shoulder chop (also called a bone-in shoulder blade
steak), which the butcher cut an inch thick for me. Then I braised
the chops in Zinfandel, which pairs well with pork.
Serendipitously, the richly flavored liquid that resulted has many
other uses.
</P>
<P>
   With spring here, I decided to serve the chops with a rhubarb
compote. But the color of the available variety of rhubarb was a
psychedelic purple-pink when cooked, so a staff member suggested
taming the tone with apples. That worked _ I used just enough apple
to mute the color but keep the integrity of the rhubarb's flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Another co-worker suggested serving the chops with polenta to
soak up the deeply flavored braising sauce. Extra polenta could
also be used later in the week.
</P>
<P>
   For the polenta, we used a recipe from `'The San Francisco
Chronicle Cookbook.'' This oven-baked soft polenta, devised by chef
Gary Danko, cooks almost by itself.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, a Food Section intern developed the recipe for the
weeknight baked polenta.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the pieces of one idea building upon others gelled into a
whole. What's more, leftover pork, polenta, rhubarb compote and
fragrant braising liquid are wonderful in easy combinations to use
during the week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; MASTER RECIPE: PORK CHOPS BRAISED IN ZINFANDEL &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   8 pork shoulder blade steaks, each about 1-11/4 pounds and 1
inch thick
</P>
<P>
   13/4 teaspoons salt + salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large onions, halved lengthwise, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 (750ml) bottles Zinfandel
</P>
<P>
   12 small sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Cut the pork steaks in half. (One half will contain the bone,
the other will be boneless.) Season lightly with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Heat 2 tablespoons of the oil in a large Dutch oven over high
heat until the oil ripples. Add the onions and 1/4 teaspoon salt;
saute, stirring constantly for 5 minutes. Reduce heat to medium and
saute, stirring occasionally, until the onions are golden, about 20
minutes. Transfer the onions to a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Return the pan to the heat. Deglaze with 1 cup of the wine,
scraping up any browned bits on the bottom of the pan, then add to
the onions.
</P>
<P>
   Wipe out the pan and return it to high heat. Add the remaining
tablespoon oil. When it ripples, add the chops (work in batches)
and saute until golden, 11/2 to 2 minutes per side. Transfer the
chops to a bowl as they are browned and continue with the remaining
chops.
</P>
<P>
   When all the pork has been browned, discard any excess fat and
return the pan to high heat. Deglaze with 1 cup wine; boil for 30
seconds. Remove from heat.
</P>
<P>
   Spread half of the onions in the pan. Add two layers of chops,
and half of the thyme. Spread the remaining onions over the chops.
Layer in the remaining chops and top with the remaining thyme. Pour
in any accumulated pork juices and the remaining wine. The wine
should just cover the chops. Add 11/4 teaspoons salt. Cover and
bring to a boil over high heat, skim the fat and froth, cover,
reduce heat and simmer until the meat is cooked through and tender,
30 to 35 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Transfer the meat to a bowl; cover and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the cooking liquid, pressing gently on the onions.
Discard the thyme. Reserve the onions. Degrease the liquid. There
should be about 7 cups.
</P>
<P>
   Return 3 cups of the liquid and half of the onions to the pan.
Simmer for 3 minutes. Season with additional salt and pepper, if
necessary. Add 4 to 6 pieces of pork, depending on size; baste the
meat with the liquid, reduce heat and simmer for 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To serve:  &LR; Portion the meat onto plates. Ladle some of the
liquid and onions around the meat. Add spoonfuls of Rhubarb-Apple
Compote and Soft Polenta (see recipes)
</P>
<P>
   Cool the remaining liquid to room temperature, cover and
refrigerate for use throughout the week. (If there is chilled fat
on top, remove and discard it before using.) Let the onions and
remaining pork cool to room temperature, pack into separate
containers, cover tightly and refrigerate.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 620 calories, &LR;   &LR; 73 g protein, 2 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 33 g fat (10 g saturated), 257 mg cholesterol, 699 mg sodium, 0 &LR; 
 &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: RHUBARB-APPLE COMPOTE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup + 2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   11/2 pounds rhubarb, trimmed, cut into 3/4-inch dice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound red-skinned baking apples (such as Rome Beauty),
cored, cut into 1-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the sugar and water in a saucepan. Heat, stirring
occasionally, until the sugar melts. Stir in the rhubarb, apples
and salt. Cover and bring to a boil. Boil for 2 minutes. Uncover
and boil hard for 3 minutes. Reduce heat to medium-high. Simmer the
mixture briskly, stirring once or twice, until the fruit is
thickened and the bubbles breaking on the surface have a
``heaving'' sound, about 15 minutes. Stir in the cayenne pepper. If
desired, break up the apple chunks a little with a wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Serve about 1/2 cup of the warm compote with the pork chops. Let
the remaining compote cool to room temperature, then cover and
refrigerate it for use throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 3 cups.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER TABLESPOON: &LR;   &LR; 25 calories, &LR;   &LR; 0 g protein, 6 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 0 g fat (0 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 12 mg
sodium, 0 g &LR;   &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKEND RECIPE: GARY DANKO'S OVEN POLENTA (SOFT) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   From ``The San Francisco Chronicle Cookbook,'' (Chronicle Books,
1997).
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup minced onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup polenta
</P>
<P>
   6 cups boiling water (measured after it comes to a boil)
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a Dutch oven; add the onion and saute over
medium heat until translucent. Add the polenta, stiring to coat
with the oil, and cook until heated through. Gradually whisk in the
boiling water and return to a boil. Add the salt.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 35 to 45 minutes. The finished polenta should mound
slightly. Remove from the oven and whisk until well blended.
</P>
<P>
   Serve half of the polenta with the pork chops.
</P>
<P>
   Use a little oil to grease an 8x8x2-inch glass baking dish.
Spread the remaining polenta in the dish, smoothing the top with a
spatula. Polenta could be 1/2 to 1 inch thick. Let cool. Cover with
plastic wrap and refrigerate for up to 4 days. Use for
Pork-Zinfandel Sauce with Baked Polenta (see recipe).
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4, with leftovers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 125 calories, &LR;   &LR; 1 g protein, 14 g carbohydrate, &LR; 
 &LR; 7 g fat (1 g saturated), 0 mg cholesterol, 533 mg sodium, 1 g &LR; 
 &LR; fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: LAYERED SALAD WITH MEXICAN FLAVORS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   This salad comes together even more quickly when you use
packaged shredded lettuce and cheese and store-bought guacamole.
The cilantro may be prepared on the weekend and stored airtight in
plastic bags.
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Dressing &LR;
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   21/4 teaspoons ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   11/4 teaspoons dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup + 2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Salad &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 head (about 13/4 pounds) iceberg lettuce, finely shredded
(about 10 cups)
</P>
<P>
   1 good-sized bunch cilantro, leaves and tender stems only
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch scallions (including green tops), thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces (about 3 cups) shredded sharp cheddar cheese
</P>
<P>
   1 can (2.25 ounces) sliced black olives, drained
</P>
<P>
   4 cups diced pork (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   4 Roma tomatoes, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Guacamole
</P>
<P>
   Sour cream
</P>
<P>
   Tortilla chips
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Combine the vinegar, cumin, oregano, salt and cayenne; stir
until the salt dissolves. Whisk in the oil. Let stand while you
layer the salad.
</P>
<P>
   Layer the salad ingredients in a clear glass bowl, starting with
one third of the lettuce, topped by one third of the cilantro, then
one third of the scallions. Sprinkle in half of the cheese, then
half of the olives. Layer in half of the pork, all the tomato
slices, half of the remaining lettuce, half the remaining cilantro,
half the remaining scallions, the remaining cheese and olives.
Layer in the remaining pork, cilantro and scallions, then top with
the remaining shredded lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the dressing and pour it evenly over the salad. Jiggle the
bowl slightly so the dressing works its way to the bottom. Cover
the salad and refrigerate for at least 15 minutes and up to 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Serve the salad at the table, garnishing each serving with
dollops of guacamole, sour cream and tortilla chips.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 810 calories, &LR;   &LR; 49 g protein, 12 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 64 g fat (22 g saturated), 175 mg cholesterol, &LR; 
 &LR; 1,177 mg sodium, 5 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; WEEKNIGHT RECIPE: PORK-ZINFANDEL SAUCE WITH BAKED POLENTA &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups pork braising liquid (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   3 cups finely chopped pork (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   2 cups canned crushed tomatoes in thick puree
</P>
<P>
   Braised onions (from Master Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Chilled polenta (from Weekend Recipe)
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil, as needed
</P>
<P>
   Instructions:
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the braising liquid, pork, tomatoes and onions in a
medium-size heavy saucepan. Bring to a boil over high heat. Boil,
uncovered, for 10 minutes. Reduce heat and simmer briskly until the
tomatoes break down and become incorporated into the sauce and the
sauce is reduced and slightly thickened, 20 to 25 minutes. Season
with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, cut the chilled polenta into triangles or other
desired shape. Lightly brush a baking sheet with olive oil.
Transfer the polenta triangles to the baking sheet. Bake,
uncovered, until they are heated through, 10 to 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the triangles among 4 heated dinner plates. Pour the
sauce over the polenta. Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 or 5.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 395 calories, &LR;   &LR; 25 g protein, 28 g
carbohydrate, &LR;   &LR; 20 g fat (4 g saturated), 77 mg cholesterol, 1,203
mg sodium, 3 &LR;   &LR; g fiber. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; More Ideas for Leftovers &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Leftover pork and its braising liquid pave the way for numerous
weekday dishes:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Stewed Pork and Pinto Beans. &LR;  Saute chopped onions, garlic and
green pepper for 5 minutes. Season with chile powder; saute for 30
seconds. Add some pork braising liquid and a generous amount of
chopped braised pork. Simmer for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add a can of drained, rinsed pinto beans. Simmer for 10 minutes.
Season to taste. Mixture should be slightly soupy. Serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Meaty Onion Soup. &LR;  The pork braising liquid makes fabulous
onion soup. Heat a few cups of it and as much onion as possible in
a medium-size saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Toast thick sourdough croutons topped with grated Swiss cheese
until the cheese melts and is bubbly. Place 1 or 2 croutons in each
soup bowl. Ladle the braising liquid over the croutons. Sprinkle
with freshly ground pepper. Serve with additional grated cheese, if
desired.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Double-Duty Sauce &LR; . Make double the amount of Pork-Zinfandel
Sauce (Master Recipe). Save half of it to toss with pasta or to
spoon over twice-baked potatoes, rice pilaf or mashed sweet
potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Pork and Beet Salad with Zinfandel Vinaigrette. &LR;  Reduce 1/2 cup
of the pork braising liquid to 3 tablespoons over high heat. Cool
briefly. Combine the reduction with 3 tablespoons red wine vinegar.
Season with salt and pepper. Whisk in 6 tablespoons olive oil. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Dice some braised pork, then combine it with double the amount
of diced beets, some thinly sliced celery and chopped scallions.
Toss with most of the dressing.
</P>
<P>
   Toss the remaining dressing with frisee lettuce. Arrange the
frisee on plates and pile the pork mixture on top. Garnish with
chopped pecans and crumbled blue cheese.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Never-Too-Much Rhubarb. &LR;  Use the leftover rhubarb for dessert:
Heat it and spoon over vanilla ice cream; serve cold topped with
sour cream or spoon it over rice pudding; fold together equal
amounts of rhubarb and vanilla-scented whipped cream, then layer
with ladyfingers in parfait glasses.
</P>
</TEXT>
