<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLASSIC-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Bay Area Classics profiles food-related businesses 
 more than a half century old. 
 &HT;       
   
 Cliff House Still Charms Guests and Ghosts  
   
   
 By Maria Cianci  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; SAN FRANCISCO  &LR; _ We often hear that a restaurant can create a
certain mood. At the Cliff House in San Francisco, the mood is as
mercurial as the weather.
<P>
   When the sun shines on the Pacific Ocean and the water sparkles
a picture-postcard blue, the view from a window table of the Cliff
House, perched 100 feet above the ocean, can make even the most
desolate soul feel happy.
</P>
<P>
   But when a storm rages and wind and rain thrash its rocky perch,
the Cliff House feels like an excitingly dangerous bastion on the
western edge of a foggy gray continent. One can almost see ghosts
of the Cliff House's past rising with the whitecaps below _ and
there are many ghosts who could tell a tale of this restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The Cliff House has perched in the same location for 136 years.
In 1863, the first Cliff House was built as a dining establishment
for well-to-do travelers, among them prominent San Francisco
families and three U.S. presidents. In 1881, wealthy businessman
and later San Francisco mayor Adolph Sutro bought the property and
the adjacent 80 acres to develop a seaside attraction: ocean-fed
public swimming pools called Sutro Baths.
</P>
<P>
   The Cliff House burned down on Christmas Day, 1894, so Sutro
rebuilt _ this time a haughty eight-story French chateau-style
structure crowned with an observatory. In 1907, it, too, met its
demise by fire. Two years later, Sutro's daughter, Emma Sutro
Merritt, rebuilt it, choosing a smaller, sturdier, more modest
structure of neoclassic design. This third incarnation stands today
as the central part of the Cliff House.
</P>
<P>
   In 1952, Emma's son sold the Cliff House to George Whitney, a
developer who, in turn, sold it to the National Park Service in
1977. The ruins of the adjoining Sutro Baths, which burned in 1966,
became part of the Park Service property in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The public considered Sutro's chateau ``an eyesore, too
grandiose. The Park Service has accounts of people clapping when
they saw it burn to the ground,'' says Michael Hountalas, general
manager of the Cliff House and vice president of the concessionaire
for the establishment's two restaurants, gift shop and other food
and beverage outlets. Hountalas assumed the day-to-day operations
in 1993 from his father and stepmother, Dan and Mary, who had run
the Cliff House for the previous 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   When the Cliff House was rebuilt in 1907, public reaction was
mixed, says Hountalas. ``Some people liked it. Some people said it
looked like a pill box.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cliff House has always operated as a restaurant. ``It was
never a hotel. That's a common misconception. Although there were
some rooms that could be leased. With a lady friend. Whom one might
have just met,'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't really a bordello out here. There were just some
seedy times for the Cliff House before 1881. Sutro cleaned all that
up. He was speculating that the whole area could be turned into a
destination for San Franciscans and visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, the entry level dining room (named the Sea Food and
Beverage Co.), with huge windows overlooking the Pacific, a dark
wood and green color scheme, framed photos of celebrity guests and
Art Deco accents); two adjoining bars (the Phineas T. Barnacle and
the Ben Butler); and a more modest restaurant upstairs are the main
dining and drinking establishments.
</P>
<P>
   For as long as Hountalas can remember, the Cliff House has been
known for its seafood and steak menu sporting some classic San
Francisco dishes. Crab is an especially strong seller. ``We can't
take the Crab Louis off the menu,'' says Hountalas, who claims a
customer even called his father at home when they tried to.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the kitchen has updated the menu, cutting
back the fried fish dishes, increasing the use of fresh herbs,
sauteed and broiled fish preparations and giving an Asian influence
to some dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Come 2001, the Cliff House will undergo even more changes _ an
$8 million to $10 million renovation to restore the property to its
1909 appearance. The two-year renovation will affect every part of
the structure, proceeding in stages so the restaurants can remain
open.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that won't be renovated is the view. On a clear day,
it extends due west past conical-shaped Arch Rock _ seemingly at
arm's reach from the dining room windows _ to the Farallon Islands,
south beyond the sweep of Ocean Beach and north to the round of
mainland called Land's End.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get whales and wild sea lions coming between us and Arch
Rock. We can't turn the window tables,'' Hountalassays. ``Customers
stay forever.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1825EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6612 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TASTE-WAFFLE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-13 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TASTE-WAFFLE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The San Francisco Chronicle's panel of 
 professional tasters tries a different product available in 
 supermarkets.   
   
   
 TASTER'S CHOICE: The Best Blueberry Waffles Skimp on Fat  
   
 By Robin Davis  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  On recent trips to grocery stores, we noticed
seven different frozen blueberry waffles. The panel has tasted
waffles (Kellogg's Eggo brand took top honors in 1995) but never
the blueberry variety.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today's tasting included one low-fat and one wheat-free.
Surprisingly, the low-fat waffle was the panel's favorite, and the
wheat-free came in third, over perhaps the best-known brand.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Safeway Select Healthy Advantage &LR;  (eight waffles in the
10.2-ounce box for $2.49 at Safeway) significantly outscored the
other waffles. These have 3 grams of fat per serving vs. the 7 to 9
grams in most of the other brands. Three tasters commented on the
good blueberry flavor, and one liked the crisp but moist texture.
Others found the waffle bland and mushy. Four would buy it; one
might buy it.
</P>
<P>
   The only organic brand came in second:  &UR; Van's  &LR; (six waffles in
the 8-ounce box for $2.59 at Whole Foods). Two panelists wanted
more blueberry flavor, while two others liked the amount of
blueberry. One panelist particularly liked the texture. Three would
buy it, one might buy it, and one would not.
</P>
<P>
   Third place went to &UR; Waffle Heaven &LR;  (six waffles in the 11-ounce
box for $2.59 at Real Foods), the only wheat-free, gluten-free,
dairy-free waffle the panel sampled. Two panelists liked the
crunchy texture, but others thought it was too hard. Three disliked
the artificial blueberry flavor. One would buy it, one might buy
it, and three would not.
</P>
<P>
   Panelists were divided on  &UR; Kellogg's Eggo  &LR; (10 waffles in the
12.3-ounce box for $2.29-$2.39 at many supermarkets), which scored
only one point lower than Waffle Heaven. Panelists thought the
waffle was too crunchy; one described it as tasting like a waffle
ice cream cone. Others disliked the artificial yellow color, but
two liked the flavor. One would buy it, two might buy it, and two
would not.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Trader Joe's &LR;  (eight waffles in the 11-ounce box for $1.69 at
Trader Joe's) came in fifth. Panelists liked the appearance but
described the flavor as strange and fake. Two might buy it; three
would not.
</P>
<P>
   Two waffles scored too low to rate: Krusteaz and Safeway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Panelists were John P. Carroll, cookbook author; Shelley Handler,
consultant and food writer; Donna Katzl, chef-owner, Cafe For All
Seasons, San Francisco; Roland Passot, chef-owner, La Folie in San
Francisco and Left Bank in Larkspur and Menlo Park; and Kirk
Webber, chef-owner, Cafe Kati, San Francisco. All products are
tasted blind.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
