<HEADER>
A6614 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SECRET-CAKE-SFCHRON &LR;      04-13 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SECRET-CAKE-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON   EDITORS NOTE: Each week, The Chronicle offers readers the recipe 
 for an outstanding dish at a Bay Area restaurant, plus the 
 chef's secrets for making it a success.  
   
   
 SECRETS OF SUCCESS: 4 Divine Layers Build This Chocolate Cake  
   
   
 By Michael Bauer  
 c. 1999 The San Francisco Chronicle  
   
 SAN FRANCISCO _  German chocolate cake is a classic, but Mary Jo
Thoresen, who oversees the pastry kitchens at both Enrico's and
U.S. Restaurant, has improved this ever-popular cake.
<TEXT>
<P>
   She creates four layers of moist, finely textured cake and
spreads each with a rum glaze and the gooey coconut pecan mixture.
Then, when she finishes assembling the layers, she caps it all with
rich chocolate icing.
</P>
<P>
   With all these layers, she gives people what they crave: the
buttery, candylike filling. It's so delicious, you simply can't
stop eating it.
</P>
<P>
   This classic cake is part of the dessert offerings at U.S.
Restaurant, a 100-year-old North Beach institution that was revived
and remodeled last year by the partners who also run Enrico's. At
U.S. _ which stands for Unione Sportivo _ the aim is to serve
hearty Italian/American food to a local crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The standard pastas and main courses are always on the menu, but
there are also two regular daily specials, and loyal customers know
when their favorites will appear, like pot roast every Wednesday.
But whether it's pot roast, lamb shanks or roast lemon chicken, the
highlight of the meal will be Thoresen's desserts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  U.S. Restaurant, 431 Columbus Ave. (at Stockton), San &LR; 
 &LR; Francisco; (415) 362-6251. Open daily for breakfast, lunch and &LR; 
 &LR; dinner. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; THE SECRETS &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Cutting the cake. &LR;  Splitting each cake into two layers helps
distribute the filling throughout.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The syrup. &LR;  Each layer is brushed with a rum syrup that helps
keep the cake moist and adds additional complexity.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; GERMAN CHOCOLATE CAKE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Ingredients: &QL; 
 &UR; The Cake &LR;
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces unsweetened chocolate
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces semi-sweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces unsalted butter, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   11/2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs yolks, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla
</P>
<P>
   4 egg whites
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Filling &LR;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pecans, toasted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   11/3 cups unsweetened shredded coconut, lightly toasted
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Syrup &LR;
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Rum to taste
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Chocolate Icing &LR;
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces semi-sweet chocolate, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons light corn syrup
</P>
<P>
   11/2 ounces unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Instructions: &QL; 
 &UR; To make the cake:  &LR; Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Butter two
9-inch cake pans and line them with baker's parchment, including a
collar around the sides.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the unsweetened and semi-sweet chocolates and the water
in the top of a double boiler set over barely simmering water. Stir
occasionally until the chocolate melts. Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Using an electric mixer, cream the butter and 11/4 cups of the
sugar until light and fluffy. Slowly mix in the melted chocolate.
Add the egg yolks 1 at a time, mixing thoroughly after each
addition.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the flour, baking soda, baking powder and salt.
</P>
<P>
   Add the dry ingredients alternately with the buttermilk and
vanilla to the chocolate mixture.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate bowl and using clean beaters, beat the egg whites
until foamy. Add the remaining 1/4 cup sugar, 1 tablespoon at a
time, beating until the whites hold medium-firm peaks.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the egg whites into the batter. Pour the batter into the
cake pans.
</P>
<P>
   Bake for 25 to 30 minutes, until a skewer inserted into the
cakes comes out clean. Place the pans on a rack and let cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the filling:  &LR; Combine the heavy cream, sugar and egg
yolks in the top of a double boiler over simmering water. Stir
constantly until the mixture reaches 170 degrees F (approximately
10 minutes). Remove from heat and pour through a fine strainer into
a bowl. Stir in the butter, salt, toasted pecans and coconut. Cool
to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the syrup:  &LR; Combine the sugar and water in a saucepan
and heat just until the sugar dissolves. Let cool to room
temperature, then stir in rum.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To make the icing:  &LR; Place the chocolate in a heat-proof bowl.
Heat the cream and pour it over the chocolate. Add the corn syrup
and butter and stir (not whisk) until smooth. Cool to a spreadable
consistency.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; To assemble the cake:  &LR; Turn the cooled cakes out of their pans.
Carefully peel off the parchment. Using a long, serrated knife,
carefully cut each cake into two layers. Divide the filling into 4
equal parts. Place the bottom layer on a plate, brush lightly with
the rum syrup. Spread one quarter of the filling on the layer,
spreading it all the way to the edges of the cake. Place a second
layer on top and repeat the process. Continue until all 4 layers
are stacked and frosted. Spread the chocolate icing on the sides of
the cake.
</P>
<P>
   If you wish, put some icing in a pastry bag fitted with a tip of
your choice and pipe a border around the perimeter of the cake.
</P>
<P>
   Refrigerate until chilled before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8 to 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PER SERVING: &LR;   &LR; 1,115 calories, &LR;   &LR; 12 g protein, 102 g &LR; 
 &LR; carbohydrate, 78 g fat (45 g saturated), 291 mg cholesterol, &LR;   &LR; 567
mg sodium, 4 g fiber. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
