<SLUG> BC-CRUISE-MISSILES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE SEEKS TO BOOST CRUISE MISSILE INVENTORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Air Force's inventory of cruise missiles has
been so depleted by the Kosovo crisis and operations in Iraq that
the service will soon start a $52 million program to convert some
of its fleet of nuclear-capable cruise missiles into conventional
weapons, military officials said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has given a high priority to boosting stocks of the
Air Launched Cruise Missile following recent military operations in
which over half the inventory was depleted, the officials added.
</P>
<P>
   The Navy has fired hundreds of Tomahawks _ cruise missiles
launched from ships and submarines _ in attacks on Iraq and
Yugoslavia, but has a large inventory of about 2,000 missiles
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   The White House Office of Management and Budget recently
approved an Air Force proposal to remove the nuclear warhead from
92 cruise missiles and fit them with conventional explosives. The
cost of converting the missiles is about $565,000 per missile, half
the price of a new version.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force hasn't purchased a new Air Launched Cruise Missile
since the late 1980s and converted nuclear variants through 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But any additional converted missiles wouldn't be available for
more than a year because Seattle-based Boeing Co., the missile's
manufacturer, would require at least that much time to reopen a
shuttered assembly line. Once up and running, the production line
would yield about 12 refurbished missiles per month, the Air Force
said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Kennett, a spokesman for Boeing, said the company was
``working closely with Air Force officials on this issue and stands
ready to support them.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the shortage is stepped-up military operations.
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of allied aerial attacks against Iraq in December,
the Air Force had about 240 Air Force cruise missiles but fired 90
during four days of raids, said an Air Force official who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   By the time NATO began attacks against Yugoslavia on March 24,
the Air Force was down to 150 missiles, which are fired by B-52H
bombers. It is unclear how many the Air Force has launched thus far
in the conflict, but estimates are that the inventory has dipped
well below 100 missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Among military planners and political leaders, satellite- or
computer-guided cruise missiles are a favored weapon for attacking
heavily defended targets because they are highly accurate but don't
put pilots and costly aircraft into harm's way.
</P>
<P>
   David Ochmanek, a senior defense analyst at the Rand Corp.,
which has performed numerous in-depth studies for the Air Force on
air power, said experts long have advised the service to buy more
of the systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take long to run through an inventory of a couple
hundred cruise missiles against a country like Yugoslavia,''
Ochmanek said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth Bacon, the senior Pentagon spokesman, acknowledged
earlier this month that the Air Force inventory was low.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something we do worry about. We have a supply now, but
it won't last forever,'' he said. ``We certainly have enough to
continue striking important targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Air Force expends all of its cruise missiles in
Yugoslavia, Ochmanek said the Navy has sufficient numbers of
Tomahawks that can perform similar duties, although those missiles
have a shorter range and less punch.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Meaghan Mariman, a Navy spokeswoman, said the service fired
from ships 330 Tomahawks against Iraq in December, more than 100
against targets in Yugoslavia and still has about 2,000 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to see a cruise missile shortage as
necessarily having a big impact on this operation,'' Ochmanek said.
``It may, however, have negative implications for the next
operation, wherever that may be fought.''
</P>
<P>
   The Navy is considering a program to upgrade older-model
Tomahawks with more accurate guidance systems and more powerful
warheads, but no new missiles are planned until at least 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
