<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GOOD DECISIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Finally, a Little Rock judge finds President
Clinton guilty of obstructing justice and a Little Rock jury finds
Susan McDougal NOT guilty of obstructing justice.
</P>
<P>
   About time, too. Both decisions are legally sound an culturally
important.
</P>
<P>
   Judges need not tolerate blatant lies, from presidents or anyone
else. And juries need not buy legalistic swill from independent
counsels who harass defendants out of malice and frustration,
persecuting rather than prosecuting their targets.
</P>
<P>
   Is this a great country or what?
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Susan Webber Wright held Clinton in civil
contempt of court for making ``intentionally false'' statements
under oath in the Paula Jones case and thereby undermining ``the
integrity of the judicial system.''
</P>
<P>
   The practical effect is more annoying than alarming. It will hit
him in the pocketbook for more court costs, jeopardize his standing
to practice law and further tarnish his reputation in the eyes of
history.
</P>
<P>
   It is an appropriate sanction that fits the fibs, unlike the
partisan impeachment circus that made fools of both the perpetrator
and his pursuers.
</P>
<P>
   Wright said she was ruling in part because she wished to deter
others ``who might themselves consider emulating the president of
the United States by willfully violating discovery orders of this
and other courts ... '' Bottom line: Clinton set a bad example,
which could not be ignored.
</P>
<P>
   But although the judge was clearly ticked off, she was properly
concerned about the constitutionality of being so tough on Clinton
that he could no longer adequately carry out his official duties.
In other words: No possibility of criminal contempt charges and
potential jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Wright pointed specifically to the president's statements during
his Jones deposition that he did not remember ever being alone with
Monica Lewinsky and never had sexual relations with her. Seven
months later he admitted before a grand jury to being alone with
her ``from time to time'' and having had an ``inappropriate
intimate relationship'' with her.
</P>
<P>
   None of this is a surprise. Everybody already knows the
president lied about Lewinsky. And thank goodness it comes too late
to have any political impact on Congress. We've been there, done
that. The hideous impeachment game is over.
</P>
<P>
   (The House of Representatives impeached Clinton for perjury
before the grand jury and for obstruction of justice but rejected a
proposal to cite him for false statements in the Jones case. The
Senate acquitted him of the charges in February.)
</P>
<P>
   There is no appetite to revive that act. Too much damage has
already been done to both parties. Even Rep. Bob Barr, R-Ga, who
had demanded Clinton be impeached before the world ever heard of
Lewinsky, conceded in a CNN interview that there is no political
will to reopen the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be impossible to get anywhere (with that) now,'' Barr
said. The conservative congressman added that he also agreed with
those who felt Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr made a mistake in
imprisoning McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   She is a far more sympathetic figure than the president, a
victim rather than a predator, a little fish rather than a powerful
shark.
</P>
<P>
   She is certainly uncommonly stubborn. But there is no evidence
that this youthful woman is lying when she says she knows nothing
that would incriminate the president in the failed 1980s Whitewater
real estate venture. And the Little Rock jury found entirely
credible her stated fear that if she did not make up some evil
charge against Clinton, Starr's implacable hostility had made it
clear he would indict her for perjury.
</P>
<P>
   Starr had her sent to prison in shackles for civil contempt for
18 months because she had refused to testify before a grand jury
against Clinton. When she continued to resist testifying after that
sentence expired, Starr additionally charged her with criminal
obstruction of justice, a stupid tactic that smelled of revenge and
vindictive prosecutorial overkill.
</P>
<P>
   She did tell the Arkansas federal jury what little she says she
knew, which indeed did not harm Clinton and was not what Starr
wanted to hear. After the jury acquitted her of obstructing justice
and deadlocked on two counts of criminal contempt, Starr refused to
accept reality and give up. Incredibly, his office announced that
retrying her on the two mistrial charges was ``definitely an
option''.
</P>
<P>
   It is an option only a legal madman would pursue. Starr's
campaign to break McDougal is over, just as the impeachment crusade
is over.
</P>
<P>
   Our judicial system is not perfect. But in these two instances
it has proved that neither presidents nor independent counsels may
arrogantly defy basic legal principles and common sense with
impunity. This is good indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
