r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISTSUSPECT-1000     04-13 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISTSUSPECT-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI BELIEVES THAT TEXAS MAN WAS CRUCIAL TERRORIST LINK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JACK DOUGLAS JR. 
and KIMBERLY DURNAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He sits in isolation, behind the razor wire and thick,
smoked-glass windows of a federal jail in New York, far from the
Fort Worth tire shop and Arlington apartment where he worked and
lived.
</P>
<P>
   In the Metropolitan Correctional Center in Manhattan, Wadih El
Hage is allowed to see only his defense lawyers and the guards who
surround him. He is able to make just three phone calls a month,
and only to people such as his wife who have been approved by the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   He is not allowed to use the exercise track on the jail's roof,
the government says, for fear that he will be killed by a sniper so
he can never reveal information about terrorist groups around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Life for El Hage _ a father of seven who lived with his family
near the University of Texas at Arlington campus _ has changed
dramatically since he was accused of being an international
terrorist. In September, he was charged with ``conspiracy to kill
United States nationals'' in the Aug. 7, 1998, bombings of U.S.
embassy buildings in Nairobi, Kenya, and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania.
More than 250 people were killed, 12 of them Americans; thousands
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage, 38, has also been charged with lying to FBI agents and
to a federal grand jury in New York about what the government
alleges are his close association with Osama bin Laden, the wealthy
Saudi exile accused of masterminding the bombings. Bin Laden, the
government says, ``is as dangerous to American interests as any man
in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   El Hage and three other co-defendants in an ongoing, worldwide
criminal investigation are scheduled to appear for a hearing in a
New York courtroom this week. If convicted, he could receive life
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In Tarrant County, El Hage was known as a man who spent time
with his young children and as a member of an Arlington mosque. He
managed Lone Star Wheels and Tires in the 3500 block of East
Lancaster in Fort Worth, where his boss recalls him as a
responsible employee.
</P>
<P>
   Moataz Al-Hallak, the spiritual leader of the Islamic Society of
Arlington, said he knew El Hage only as a member of his mosque.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a nice, soft-spoken person, helpful and very friendly,''
Al-Hallak said. ``Anybody who came to know him, liked him. This is
the impression that he left in our community.''
</P>
<P>
   But within bin Laden's circle, prosecutors say, El Hage was
known as ``Norman'' _ the chief accountant, records keeper and
administrator for bin Laden's dispatches of death and destruction
for American ``infidels.'' El Hage, government documents assert,
was bin Laden's ``personal secretary'' in terrorist activities.
</P>
<P>
   Many details of the government's case against El Hage remain
secret, barred from public view in sealed files. But federal court
documents that are open to the public in New York reveal that the
Arlington man was the focus of federal investigators a year before
the embassy bombings, and is suspected of being connected with
crimes in locations ranging from Somalia to Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   In September 1997, the same month El Hage moved to Arlington, he
came under the watch of federal authorities who began to suspect
that he had close ties to bin Laden, according to court documents.
He was called to testify before a New York grand jury investigating
the bin Laden organization, and he was later linked to the embassy
bombings when his name was connected with a suspect arrested in
Kenya.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, El Hage was denied a request to telephone
Al-Hallak from jail. Assistant U.S. Attorney Patrick Fitzgerald
expressed concerns in a court hearing that if the two communicated,
they might use ``coded correspondence'' and ``cryptic references''
to plan future acts of terrorism, including ``murder and conspiracy
to murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Moataz Al-Hallak has served as a contact between members of
the bin Laden organization,'' Fitzgerald added.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak, in a rare interview, adamantly denied the
allegations, saying he has nothing to do with bin Laden. He said he
preaches a religion that abhors terrorism or any other form of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really shocking and surprising. I really do not know
what they are talking about. This is absolutely false,'' Al-Hallak
said. The 38-year-old cleric said that no one with the federal
government has ever tried to question him. He learned of the
allegations from a reporter, he said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal official, who did not want to be identified, said
Fitzgerald's comments about Al-Hallak were based on undercover
intelligence work that has not yet warranted an interrogation. The
mosque he leads is not under investigation, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   A native Syrian whose wife is from America, Al-Hallak said
``there are a lot of good things I can learn'' from people in this
country. In return, he said, he can ``offer something to this
society.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
