<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ADVANCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Despite slow start, Braves batters getting job done
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The Braves are feeling a little lucky to be 5-3
at this point. How else do you explain winning five of eight games
while your team is hitting .238?
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are ranked 12th in that category out of 16 National
League teams, puzzling for a team that hit the ball so well during
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively we're not doing what we're capable of,'' said
Brian Jordan, who at .423 is one of only three regulars in the
lineup hitting over .250. ``Pitching is still ahead of hitting
right now. Everybody is being anxious, trying to do too much,
making the big hit instead of just relaxing and doing what you're
capable of doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Klesko (.423) and Javy Lopez (.261) are the other two over
.250. Chipper Jones is barely above .200 (.206). Bret Boone needed
two hits on Monday to raise his average to .222. Then you've got
Otis Nixon (.148), Andruw Jones (.172) and Walt Weiss (.190)
bringing up the rear.
</P>
<P>
   The hitters who are getting the most at-bats, and charged with
getting the offense rolling, are doing the least with them. The top
three hitters in the order _ Nixon, Boone and Chipper Jones _ are a
combined 17 for 88 (.193). When Nixon singled and scored in the
first inning Tuesday, it was the first time a Braves leadoff hitter
had scored this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The top three guys ain't swinging the bat, ain't getting on
base, ain't doing nothing,'' Chipper Jones said. ``We've just got
to be patient. It'll come.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones knows that starts with him. Outside of his three-hit game
against the Phillies on April 6, Jones is hitting .138 (4 for 29)
including his 0-for-5 on Monday,
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I touched in spring training was golden,'' Jones
said. ``Now it's like mud. I can't buy one. My mom could have been
lobbing them to me (Monday), and I couldn't have hit one. You just
have to laugh it off and hope somebody else gets a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan has been doing his share. He leads the team in home runs
(two), RBIs (seven) and runs scored (nine). He also has scored both
winning runs in the two Braves last at-bat wins over the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, it was one of the hitters struggling the most _
Andruw Jones (nine strikeouts in 29 at-bats) _ who drove him in
both times. There's a lesson there for Jones and the rest of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's focused in only those at-bats,'' hitting coach Don Baylor
said. ``Let's get focused in for all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Those two wins that give the Braves reason to believe that can
and will do better.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those wins, they build character,'' Chipper Jones said. ``They
build chemistry. They give you a feeling of invincibility _ that no
matter how far down you are, you can come back.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
