</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ROBINSON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons' Robinson wants arrest incident to be 'a reminder'
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Eugene Robinson rejoined the Falcons on Tuesday, a lot
little lighter in the wallet and ``humbled'' since his arrest on
the eve of Super Bowl XXXIII for attempting to solicit oral sex in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   While joking with teammates about their golf games, and often
talking as fast as ever, the free safety seemed at times unchanged.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition to signing a new contract to reduce his 1999
salary from $1.8 million to $1 million, he acknowledged that he
will be branded forever by the incident.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm wrong; I stand before everybody,'' said Robinson, who
missed the first two-plus weeks of the team's offseason workout
program. ``I am deeply humbled, and (grateful) for this
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to get away from it,'' he said. ``I want it to
be . . . a scar I will always remember. I don't want it to affect
what I do as a football player, but as Eugene Robinson the person,
I want it to be a reminder to stay next to the Lord.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, 35, was third on the Falcons last season with 92 total
tackles, second with four interceptions and made the Pro Bowl for
the third time in his 14-year career.
</P>
<P>
   But his speed and tackling skills appear to be in decline, and
his salary was to increase from $750,000 last year to $1.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons re-signed cornerback Ronnie Bradford last
month, coach Dan Reeves said Bradford might move to free safety.
</P>
<P>
   Upon hearing that, along with league-wide rumors Atlanta was
going to waive him, Robinson called Reeves last week from his home
outside Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves told Robinson he needed to be in the workout program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't have anything to do with (Robinson's arrest),''
Reeves said. ``It was because he had such a slow start last year.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach also told Robinson that he would have to take a pay
cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``We also had to justify letting our leading tackler (linebacker
Cornelius Bennett) go,'' Reeves said. ``We just had to look at what
would be most fair to the team, and the players.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson could earn more with incentives, but he's got to make
the team to earn a cent other than the $70 per workout as mandated
by the collective bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a money thing. I've got money,'' he said. ``I want to
. . . do something that's right. This is . . . a new beginning. I
have goals. I want to get back to the Super Bowl and do it right. I
want to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves said Bradford still will work at free safety in training
camp, and Robinson concedes that he could still be cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always a very real possibility,'' he said. ``If I get
cut on the basis of my performance, that's different. I can take
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has maintained a low profile since the Super Bowl,
screening calls to his home and declining interviews on ABC's''
20/20,'' ESPN's ``Up Close,'' CNN-SI and ``The Oprah Winfrey
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   He was high profile in the locker room Tuesday before and after
an 8 a.m. workout.
</P>
<P>
   ``He talked to me a little bit,'' starting center Robbie Tobeck
said. ``There's things we got to talk about and work out, but we're
glad to see him in here and working out. There's a lot of guys that
wonder, `What if? What if?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back, you . . . wonder if the game would have been
different. 'Bitterness' is a strong word. I think it is more
'wonder.'''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson will participate in the final 12 1/2 weeks of the
program. ``It's important for me to lock arms with the guys and
sweat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There will be no record of Robinson's arrest on the misdemeanor
charge because he entered a pre-trial diversion program that called
for him to take an HIV test and an AIDS awareness course.
</P>
<P>
   He knows, however, that he can never erase the question whether
his misdeed influenced a 34-19 loss in the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``Could it have? Yes. No. Maybe,'' he said. ``The thing is, when
they look at the Super Bowl . . . it's in the history books. I
can't do anything about it, not one iota, and that's why I was
hoping for the chance to do this again with this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a new beginning. I will not be held hostage by
the past. I got my entire life ahead of me.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
