<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6636 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOBS-COX     04-13 1555
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOBS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Companies get creative when searching for employees
 &HT;    EDS: This is the first of a new Atlanta Journal-Constitution
feature called Tech Jobs that will focus on careers in high tech
industries.
 &HT;    By Tammy Joyner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the ongoing war for workers, Tommy Rainwater may be
the high tech industry's secret weapon.
</P>
<P>
   The 28-year-old is a former designer of trade show exhibits and
knows what it takes to get people to notice a product. He's now
putting that know-how to work for Macquarium Intelligent
Communications, an Atlanta firm that helps companies design
websites, kiosks and other interactive technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same techniques used to guide a person through various
points in an exhibit booth apply to someone using a website or
CD-Rom,'' said Rainwater who now makes between $10,000 and $15,000
more as a communications specialist at Macquarium. Last fall,
Rainwater created a deck of large 3-D game cards using a Jack, King
and Queen as part of a sales pitch to an online entertainment
company. Rainwater's work helped Macquarium land the account to
build a website.
</P>
<P>
   Rainwater along with five architects Macquarium has hired in the
last few years are becoming the company's ``first line of
defense,'' in helping Macquarium determine what clients need ,
president Marc Adler said.
</P>
<P>
   The fast growth of technology and the Internet have created an
enormous need for people who can create, build, run and manage
computers as well as the software that goes in them. The heaviest
demand is in the field of information technology where companies
are desperate for computer programmers, database administrators,
systems analysts, software developers, web designers and countless
other jobs - many of which didn't exist a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the nation's universities are only able to churn out
a fraction (40,000 to 50,000 IT students a year) of the prospects
needed for the estimated half million unfilled IT jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Promises of cushy perks, fat paychecks and bonuses only offer
short-term solutions because a prized IT catch can often be lured
away with better benefits by competitors. Competition has sent IT
salaries into the stratosphere making it even harder for companies
to compete in a field where products and demand change rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for highly specialized, rapidly changing IT skills ``puts
a lot of pressure on the job market that traditional avenues aren't
able to fill,'' said Walker Smith, an Atlanta-based trend tracker
for market research firm Yankelovich Partners. ``If you have five
years working on the Internet, you are ancient. There is not a
premium on experience and more education. You're really forced to
go outside (normal channels). You don't advertise for people with
lots of experience. You have an odd phenomena.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the number of high tech jobs in Georgia has
surged. High tech employment in Georgia grew 54 percent between
1990 and 1997, U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics show. Such rapid
growth has helped propel the state into the top 10 states in high
tech employment, according to the American Electronics Association
recently reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the number of available workers hasn't kept pace with the
demand. The worker shortage is particularly pronounced in Metro
Atlanta, the Southeast's second largest high tech market, behind
Northern Virginia and could become a critical issue for Atlanta
which according to DRI McGraw Hill is expected to lead the nation
in job growth through the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by KPMG for Metro Atlanta Chamber of Commerce
estimates there are about 20,000 unfilled IT jobs in the state.
About 75 percent of those jobs are in the Atlanta area, says
William J. Todd, president of the Georgia Research Alliance, a
technology development partnership of universities, business and
state government. In response, Georgia Tech this Spring plans to
enlist its graduates to help recruit IT prospects _ particularly
software engineers _ to Georgia from places like California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Metro Atlanta ) chamber and Department of Industry Trade
and Tourism have an excellent reputation for recruiting companies
to move to Georgia,'' said Todd, who plans to help recruit IT
workers. ``This (recruiting) effort is a variation on that theme.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the IT shortage is so great that it's forced
companies like Macquarium, Microsoft and Manhattan to get creative
in filling jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just thinking outside the box,'' Adler said of his
decision to add Rainwater and the architects to the staff. ``You
have to choose nontraditional methods in a competitive environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started thinking of character traits of individuals. You
hire skill sets. You don't hire positions. If you're hiring skills
sets you can think about who understands designs, who understands
communication of a brand.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of the architects, ``You're talking about screen
real estate versus physical real estate,'' Adler said. ``There's a
lot of parallels.''
</P>
<P>
   For their parts, Microsoft and Manhattan Associates of Atlanta
are even financing the creation of their future workforces,
capitalizing on the rampant job-hopping and career-switching that
is taking place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.S. is at an alltime low for unemployment. So it's not
like there's a lot of people out there,'' said Nancy Lewis, general
manager for training and certification worldwide at Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Deanna Dubberly of Alpharetta, Ga. is switching to computers
after nine years as a pharmacist, with the help of an $8,000 loan
from a Microsoft program aimed at getting more people into the
field of IT.
</P>
<P>
   Dubberly used the money to buy a new computer and pay the
program's $5,000 tuition. She started working part time in December
so she could focus on the training which has often meant 40 hours a
week in class.
</P>
<P>
   Under the program, Dubberly says she's learned how computer
networks run and different ways computers talk to each other. She
expects to get her certification in the next couple of months.
Participants are not guaranteed a job once they complete the
program.
</P>
<P>
   She eventually wants to work on developing a computer network
that would link hospitals, doctors' offices and pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping to use my certification to mesh the health industry
and computer world,'' said Dubberly. ``There's a huge gap for
health care workers. A doctor's office can't talk to a pharmacy.
There should be some way that we in the health care field should be
able to talk to each other over the various networks.''
</P>
<P>
   Dubberly is just one of thousands of non-IT people Microsoft has
helped trained since starting its Microsoft Skills 2000 in May
1997. Last year, for instance, the 2000 program introduced 125,000
new people into the industry. In addition, about $115 million in
loans was disbursed during the first year of Microsoft's Skills
2000 IT Career Loan program, which is administered by Servus
Financial. That number is expected to double in the second year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Microsoft 2000 program has drawn all sorts of people into
IT,'' Lewis said. ``People are coming from all professions. There
are policewomen, bank tellers, cab drivers, engineers and doctors
who are moving into IT careers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a similar vein, Manhattan Associates has hired industrial
engineers and people with MBAs and trained them to become software
designers, engineers and programmers. The company's workforce has
grown from 25 when it moved to the Atlanta area from California in
1995 to nearly 600 today. Many of the hires have come from Georgia
Tech, where the company has built a strong working relationship
with the faculty there and given $1.5 million to the endowment of a
chair to build a supply chain studies program. Manhattan Associates
helps clients, which range from Nordstrom to Sports Authority to
Polo, organize their warehouse and distribution systems with
software that provides logistics, distribution and transportation
solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a shortage of software developers due especially to
the Year 2000 problem,'' said Alan Dabbiere, Manhattan Associates
president and chief executive. ``We've very much been able to
leverage engineering skills _ from mechanical electrical, civil ,
chemical, aeronautical and industrial engineers.''
</P>
<P>
   So can an architect or trade booth builder become an information
technology whiz?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been great for us,'' said Adler, MacQuarium's 26-year-old
wunderkind of the 50-employee company, who admits the transition
has been relatively smooth. It generally takes about six months for
the nontraditional IT people to make the adjustment, Adler said.
The company also has designers on staff with fine arts backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The architects, for example, ``have 3D skills. They're not just
theorists. They have practical hands-on knowledge how to use
high-end software,'' Adler said. They can quickly grasp concepts
because ``they have the spatial understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's worked well for the company which creates everything
from kiosks in malls and movie theaters to satellite communications
and CD-Roms as well as intranet and e-commerce systems.
</P>
<P>
   Tammy Joyner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
