<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6641 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASCIST-BOOK-REVIEW-N     04-13 1078
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASCIST-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE FASCIST REVOLUTION': GRASPING THE APPEAL OF FASCISM 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By RICHARD BERNSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The ethnic cleansing being carried out by the Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic in Kosovo makes this enlightening volume on the
nature of fascism by George Mosse especially timely. As Lawrence
Wechsler noted in The New Yorker last week, Milosevic is a classic
fascist. His appeal is to a kind of fanatical Serbian nationalism;
he is popular; he has fused the historic sense of Serbian
victimhood with a cult of blood vengeance against non-Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Mosse, a distinguished student of European and especially German
history who taught for many years at the University of Wisconsin,
does not speak specifically of Milosevic. But his new book, ``The
Fascist Revolution,'' certainly brings the Serb dictator to mind.
Mosse rejects the view of fascism as a kind of thin veneer imposed
by force and terror and maintained there by a manipulative leader
glorified by a huge and monolithic propaganda machine.
</P>
<P>
   In Mosse's view, fascism, as his title suggests, was a genuine
revolutionary movement, comparable in this sense to communism.
Fascism (in this sense unlike Communism) was constructed on the
basis of popular consensus and arose out of deeply ingrained values
and traditions. Far from being a thin veneer, a sort of
nonideological terror that merely manipulated nationalist and
racist emotions, it profoundly changed the societies in which it
came to power and imposed a complete world view, a different vision
of history and its meaning on them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fascist myth was based upon the national mystique, its own
revolutionary and dynamic traditions,'' Mosse writes. ``It also
encompassed remnants of previous ideologies and political
attitudes, many of them paradoxically hostile to fascist
traditions. It was a scavenger which attempted to co-opt all that
had appealed to people in the 19th- and 20th-century past;
romanticism, liberalism and socialism as well as Darwinism and
modern technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosse is a serious scholar who treats some of these matters as
if he were leaping into the middle of an ongoing discussion among
other scholars, and that makes the going a bit tough sometimes for
lay readers. The early chapters are especially demanding in this
regard, with Mosse not always clear about the theme he is meaning
to pursue. But as the book continues, the tone becomes more
impassioned, the argument more vigorous.
</P>
<P>
   Having rejected the argument that fascism came to power on the
basis of terror alone, Mosse wants to explain the reasons for
fascism's appeal, and to do so he delves deeply into such subjects
as racism and nationalism, the fascist manipulation of images of
masculine beauty, the conjunction of what he calls ``the occult''
and the fascist revolt against the ordinariness of urban,
capitalist life.
</P>
<P>
   Racism and, of course, hatred of Jews, was so important a part
of German fascism that many probably believe that racism itself,
and the concomitant belief in Aryan superiority, are practically
synonymous with fascism. Not so, Mosse contends. A nonracist
fascism is imaginable, he argues, and such a fascism did exist for
more than a decade in Italy (until Mussolini turned officially to
anti-Semitism in 1938). ``Nationalism did not have to be racist,''
Mosse writes. ``Racism was just one among several alternatives from
which nationalism could choose.'' Nationalism did rely on the
racist alternative in Germany, where the creation of a
``countertype,'' supposedly a kind of opposite to the Germanic
ideal, provided an ``eternal enemy'' on which the country's
historic grievances could focus.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most illuminating of Mosse's chapters has to do with
the heritage of the French Revolution, an event that was formally
repudiated by fascism but that, in Mosse's view, actually created
the mass politics that later enabled fascism to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Revolution and fascism rested on the concept of the
``general will,'' the idea of the mass of people acting together
for a transcendent national purpose. Both fascism and the
Revolution evoked utopias, perfect societies for which the
individual could be sacrificed. Both organized vast public
festivals of fealty to the new order. In both, Mosse writes,
``popular sovereignty was affirmed and controlled through giving
the people a means of participation in the political process _ not
in reality, but through a feeling of participating, of belonging to
a true and meaningful community.''
</P>
<P>
   The central point is that fascism did not spring full grown out
of the heads of a few theorists or even out of the condition of
Europe after World War I. As a ``scavenger'' doctrine, it used what
it could to give itself substance, but what it used was deeply
entrenched in European culture and tradition.
</P>
<P>
   In a probing chapter describing the appeal of fascism to French,
German and Italian intellectuals, Mosse argues that fascism was
not, as it is often proclaimed, ``an aberration from the dominant
current of European history and thought.'' Nor was it ``a
pragmatic, activist response to the immediate historical
situation.'' Many intellectuals, like the once-celebrated French
writer Louis-Ferdinand Celine, saw fascism as a means to realize
values that they had long prized.
</P>
<P>
   In this sense, too, certain strains of occult belief, a
mysticism of blood and soil, contributed to fascism's appeal. Mosse
draws a complex set of links among nationalism, anti-Semitism, the
cult of the leader and late-19th-century mysticism. Like fascism
itself, he argues, the occult is a reaction against bourgeois
society with its rational calculation, its belief in progress
through science. Mysticism enabled the Germans to ``be artists,''
as Mosse puts it, ``to recognize that their true soul was an
expression of the cosmic spirit of the world based upon nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Mosse develops other themes, including the role of the theater
in Germany in fostering Nazi ideals, and the homoerotic nature of
the cult of beautiful youth. His arguments are not always easy to
grasp, but they come from long consideration of a vexing
phenomenon, which is given a full and many-sided explication in
these pages.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `THE FASCIST REVOLUTION'
</P>
<P>
   Toward a General Theory of Fascism
</P>
<P>
   By George L. Mosse
</P>
<P>
   230 pages. Howard Fertig. $35.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1843EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0223 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6642 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIMON-DANCE-REVIEW-AR     04-13 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIMON-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANCE REVIEW: YOUNGSTERS LEND A SPORTY INNOCENCE TO BALLET 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Very young dancers bring an extra verve and emotional
wholeheartedness to performing that is seldom sustained as they
mature and become full-fledged professionals. Those qualities are
celebrated in the Kids Dance matinee programs presented by Eliot
Feld's Ballet Tech company on Saturdays and Sundays at the Joyce
Theater, in a season that ends May 9. The programs, performed for
the most part by children training in the company school, also
offer the chance to see interesting new commissions as well as
highlights of the senior repertory, danced with a special twist.
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of the Kids Dance matinee Saturday was ``Joggers,'' a
trio choreographed for student dancers by Feld in 1997 to goofy,
bouncy music by Dick Koomans that perfectly fits the dance.
``Joggers'' adroitly mixes relaxed jogging with ballet and stylized
bits of other track moves. But its greatest charm is the way it
uses its young dancers' freshness and innocent intensity of focus.
So tall and skinny they looked like colorful string beans in Frank
Krenz's sleek sports outfits, Christopher Osborne, Emmanuel
Robinson and Jonathan Sulaiman managed to be elegant, sporty and
amusingly competitive in the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Red, white and blue pompons are everywhere in Feld's ``Half
Time,'' a fast-paced suite of seven dances set to music by Morton
Gould. The costumes are covered with stars and stripes, so that the
dancers often look like small abstractions of the American flag.
But for all its rah-rah spirit, the choreography demands a
practiced technique and savvy performing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Half Time'' got both from its lead dancers, Amon Bey, Melissa
Urrutia, Jabin Waterman and Tiffany Smile. Ms. Smile stood out for
her serene embodiment of the Statue of Liberty, moving slowly in
front of a wall of pompons jiggling in witty syncopation in the
sweet and tart ``Old Glory'' number.
</P>
<P>
   The racial composition of the student company mirrors that of
New York City, a rarity in dance today, helping to give the dances
an extra edge of urban energy. To see that rainbow of skin tones
represented in the closing dance in ``Half Time,'' set to ``The
Battle Hymn of the Republic,'' was a doubly affecting experience at
a time when New Yorkers have been forced to confront racial
stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   The program opened with Feld's 1998 ``Simon Sez,'' set to a
score by Steve Maitland, a work for jiggling senior dancers,
bead-stringing junior dancers and stagehands who build a high
platform for the cast to stretch on. Nothing happens in the piece,
choreographically or musically, at excruciating length. One aim of
the ``Kids Dance'' programs must be to engage young audiences in
the stimulating art of dance. ``Simon Sez'' could well send them
racing back to their participatory video games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1844EDT &QL; 
