<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONEYREFORM-COX     04-13 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYREFORM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Blue Dog' democrats call for campaign reform
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the stampede for campaign cash in the 2000
elections already at full tilt, Congressional Democrats today
launch a new effort to reform the way elections are financed.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Democrats, known as the Blue Dogs, will begin
collecting the 218 signatures needed to force a vote on a sweeping
campaign finance reform measure, which House Speaker Dennis Hastert
(R-Ill.) has so far declined to schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to get this bill passed out of the House by Memorial
Day and over to the Senate if we have any hope of passing it and
having it be effective for the next round of elections,'' said Rep.
Jim Turner (D-Texas), who is leading the petition drive.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt, even among opponents of campaign finance
reform, that House Democrats, joined by some moderate Republicans,
will succeed. A similar petition drive last year forced former
Speaker Newt Gingrich to bring the bill to the floor, and the
reform measure passed overwhelmingly with 252 votes.
</P>
<P>
   But reform advocates once again face the prospect of a Senate
filibuster led by Sen. Mitch McConnell (R-Ky.), who has
successfully defeated campaign finance reform in the Senate nearly
every year since 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're clearly not going to allow a bill supported by every
single Democrat to pass in the Republican Senate,'' McConnell
declared Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But the political dynamics of campaign finance reform have
changed somewhat since McConnell led a successful filibuster
against campaign finance reform last September.
</P>
<P>
   Reform proponents began their effort last year toward the end of
the 105th Congress, when it was quickly buried by President
Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   This year, reformers are beginning early. ``The House acting
earlier gives us more time,'' said Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.), the
chief Republican sponsor of campaign finance reform in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   This year, there are also several new Republican senators who
have indicated more of a willingness to vote for reform. Sen.
George Voinovich (R-Ohio), for example, said he is committed to
reform but hasn't endorsed any particular measure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Republicans have an obligation to come back with
meaningful campaign finance reform,'' Voinovich said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said that several GOP senators have told him privately
that they recognize the need to act on a bill this year.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Congress, calls for reform continue to mount.
</P>
<P>
   This year, a coalition of major businesses has put forward a
reform proposal that would ban so-called soft money donations to
the political parties by corporations, unions and individuals. The
soft-money ban, along with several other reforms, were needed to
restore voter confidence in politics, said Edward Kangas, chairman
of Deloitte Touche Tohmatsu and a member of the task force that
developed the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fund-raising arms race is taking its toll on everyone,''
Kangas said. ``Businesses feel mounting pressure to give to
campaigns because their competitors do.''
</P>
<P>
   The House bill that is likely to pass this year would ban soft
money and thus cut off the major source of money that parties have
used to evade the contribution limits to candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also expand the definition of ``express
advocacy,'' forcing groups that run independent political
advertisements during a campaign to raise their money according the
federal contribution limits.
</P>
<P>
   The ban on soft money and new rules relating to express advocacy
are the most controversial elements of the bill, sponsored by Reps.
Marty Meehan (D-Mass.) and Chris Shays (R-Conn.).
</P>
<P>
   McConnell and many other Republicans argue that both provisions
would violate the First Amendment right to free speech.
</P>
<P>
   McConnell has sent some recent signals that he might be open to
deal-making on campaign finance if the bill also increased the
contribution limits to candidates, which have been frozen at $1,000
per election since 1975. He and others have tossed out new limits
of $3,000 to $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   But McConnell called an absolute ban on soft money an
``unacceptable deal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That ends up putting the parties of being unable to engage in
issue advocacy, which every group in America exercises as their
constitutional right to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats, however, are open to the idea of raising
contribution limits as part of a larger reform package. Meehan, the
Democratic sponsor of the House bill, said he would look at raising
contribution limits as a ``last resort.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see soft money made illegal,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Such talk has alienated the campaign finance reform purists, who
argue that candidates already have access to too much money.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ... are desperate for campaign finance reform at any
cost and that is what is most worrisome,'' said Ellen Miller of
Public Campaign, which advocates federally financed elections.
``They have lost sight of what reform is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
