<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRE14-COX     04-13 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Firefighters say wind helped flames spread quickly in Atlanta
mill
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The first three firefighters to arrive at the scene of
a reported trash fire in the old Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill had
called for a hose to put it out when flames suddenly surged up
around them, forcing them to flee for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mill No. 1 at the Cabbagetown landmark was five stories high,
and each floor was supported by massive, age-dried wooden pillars
and beams, some perhaps a foot square, Atlanta Fire Battalion Chief
Bill Brockman said Tuesday. The heavy oak floors were permeated
with oil from the mill machines used over the years.
</P>
<P>
   None of the huge windows had glass in them, and the wind was
gusting through at 30 to 40 miles an hour. A veteran firefighter
working the scene Tuesday said wind and oily wood can turn a little
fire into a furnace in seconds.
</P>
<P>
   By late Tuesday, Brockman said, firefighting efforts at the mill
were scaled back to three engines, two ladder trucks and 18
firefighters. Crews were still pouring water onto hot spots within
the old building's walls, which were still standing for the most
part.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll probably go on for a couple of days'' before it can be
declared safe, Brockman said. The section of Boulevard around the
entrance to the mill remained blocked off to autos creating massive
rush-hour traffic jams.
</P>
<P>
   But even as fire hoses played streams of water on the wreckage,
workmen continued gutting other buildings on the old mill grounds,
scheduled to be turned into loft apartments. The sound of
jackhammers played a staccato counterpoint to the rumble of fire
engines pumping water.
</P>
<P>
   The other buildings, one already renovated and occupied, were
saved from the spectacular fire by the wind, which instead blew
flames onto tinderbox wooden houses in Cabbagetown, destroying or
damaging half a dozen.
</P>
<P>
   What started the trash fire on the fifth floor is still under
investigation, Lt. Roy Awana, chief of fire investigation, said.
Contrary to earlier reports, Awana said, there was no indication
that cutting torches were in use on the fifth floor or the roof.
Initial investigation indicated the only power tools in the general
area were circular saws being used by workmen to cut away a section
of the roof, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Brockman said three engines and two trucks responded to the
trash fire call _ ``our normal assignment for a building of that
size.''
</P>
<P>
   Its three firefighters ran up to the fifth floor, Brockman said,
and called for a ladder truck to extend its aerial ladder up to a
fifth-floor window. The ladders carry hoses and connections, and
it's much quicker to use them than to try to lay hose up stairs in
such a building, Brockman said.
</P>
<P>
   But before the ladder could be set up, the trash fire turned
into an inferno.
</P>
<P>
   The roof and four floors collapsed to the bottom of the
building, and Brockman said the smouldering debris within the walls
is at least several feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Brockman compared the mill fire to a 1981 fire at the abandoned
Westco Hat building on Trinity Avenue. The first three firefighters
to enter that building found only a small fire on the third floor.
The next thing anyone knew, all three came leaping out of a third
floor window _ two of them on fire.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie firefighter Scott Duncan, 21, was killed, and two
veterans were permanently disabled. That fire was ruled arson, set
by a vagrant who lived in and around the building.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Warner writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
