<HEADER>
A6654 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HER0-FIREMAN-COX     04-13 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HER0-FIREMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hero firefighter thrust into spotlight
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Being heroic is easy, Atlanta firefighter Matt Moseley
found. It's what comes next that is hard.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone wanted to see him, thank him, touch him. The TV network
morning shows successfully sought individual predawn interviews.
The media in England called. Of course, local reporters were
clamoring constantly for his attention.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the elected officials. Vice President Al Gore
called. Mayor Bill Campbell, who has fought with the firefighters
union in which Moseley is a key player, wanted to talk to him. The
governor expected him at noon even though his shift should have
ended five hours earlier and it had been more than 30 hours since
he slept.
</P>
<P>
   Today it continues at City Hall with another ceremony to thank
him for pulling a construction worker off a crane 220 feet above a
roaring fire Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to getting my anonymity back, hopefully by
the end of the week,'' Moseley said as he was swarmed by reporters
at the Capitol when Gov. Roy Barnes recognized Moseley for this
role in the daring rescue of Ivers Sims at the Fulton Bag and
Cotton Mill.
</P>
<P>
   A state pilot maneuvered the helicopter while Moseley dangled in
high winds and smoke at the end of 50-foot-long nylon cord.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very few things in modern life that excite us,''
Barnes said.
</P>
<P>
   This was certainly one of them, the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley's marathon work day started rather routinely at 7 a.m.
Monday. He expected it to be just like most other days he's had
since joining the Atlanta Fire Department in 1996 after spending
two years with the Fayette County Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Moseley, 30, of Locust Grove south of Atlanta, went to a
chemical spill in the morning, then ate lunch at Fire Station No. 4
on Ellis Street. He planned to spend the afternoon training, but
``it turned out I had something else to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first crew called to the 120-year-old Cabbagetown mill,
Moseley headed to the top of the building with another firefighter,
expecting to ``get some hoes and knock it down.'' but the pair met
``Mr. fire and made a hasty retreat to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Within an hour, Moseley was hooked to a harness in a rescue
broadcast around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The hours that followed were a whirlwind of cameras, interviews
and more firefighting. The media calls came until 2 a.m. Tuesday
when he was sent to a house fire that took two hours to put out.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the station house, Moseley had 30 minutes before he had
to get ready for a round of appearances on ``MSNBC,'' the ``Today
Show'' and ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There were so many,'' he said, ``I can't remember them all.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Moseley met with Campbell followed by the governor. He
stood impassively at the foot of the Capitol steps, his hands
clasped in front of him, as Barnes praised him for demonstrating
``extreme courage, consideration'' in a ``dangerous and delicate
rescue.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously exhausted but still graceful, Moseley shook the hands
of children and tourists, softly thanking them for their praise
while politely tolerating more questions from reporters armed with
cameras and microphones.
</P>
<P>
   What next, they wondered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go to the house and relax,'' Moseley said with no
hint of sarcasm. ``I think I'd much rather be up in the helicopter
than doing this.''
</P>
<P>
   He's back for another 24-hour shift Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Rhonda Cook writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
