<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0414-     04-13 1296
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0414-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVAR STORY OF WOMAN'S DEATH FITS PENTAGON ALLEGATIONS OF SERB
RAPISTS
 &HT;    1000&AMP;add
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414; KOSOVO-LOOTERS-0414.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ As her family fled their decimated village, a
young bride exchanged jackets with her brother-in-law to protect
him from Serbs hunting down Kosovar men. Little thought did the
beautiful 22-year-old Shpresa Halimi give to becoming prey herself.
</P>
<P>
   But just after dark Monday, the young woman was spotted by a
helmeted Serb militiaman as her refugee caravan rumbled into the
town of Dakovica. It is the place the Pentagon reported last week
that Serb forces had been systematically rounding up young refugee
women to rape and sometimes to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Four Kosovar eyewitnesses told Cox Newspapers Tuesday that the
Serbian paramilitary soldier grabbed the tall, dark-haired woman
from the tractor wagon to keep for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Then, her father-in-law Ferhat Halimi related, the soldier
turned his head, looking for other women.
</P>
<P>
   Shpresa took the moment to try to escape, but the Serbian saw
her and riddled her back with Kalashnikov bullets from her head to
the base of her spine, said Halimi, who was inches from her when
she was shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are completely destroyed now,'' the bereaved husband Rasim
Halimi, 29, said just hours after the family crossed the border
into Albania on Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The tale of the Halimi family of Slatina is the latest crest in
the tide of tragic stories the Kosovar refugee population has lived
in recent weeks, as NATO warplanes bomb Serb military targets in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The flow of refugees into countries neighboring Kosovo has
slowed since the Serb-run government of Yugoslavia apparently began
intermittently closing the border and turning back fleeing Kosovar
Albanians last week.
</P>
<P>
   But descriptions of life inside Kosovo, given by some of these
more than 4,000 refugees who were allowed to cross the border
overnight Monday, suggests that ethnic Albanians remaining in
Kosovo remain in hellish conditions.
</P>
<P>
   While impossible to confirm, details of the more than two-week
odyssey of the people from the Kosovo village of Slatina were told
with no deviation by more than a dozen people. Their story lends
credence -- and chilling reality -- to the Pentagon accusations
given at a Washington briefing last week and repeated Tuesday by
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our evidence ... comes from the women who have been taken to
that camp and are now in the refugee camps inside Albania,'' Cook
told reporters at the Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``a number of aid workers'' -- including Americans in
the area -- ``have heard the same story from a number of women.''.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday the Halimi family and others from Slatina, a
strategically critical village overlooking the Pristina airport in
Kosovo, had gathered their tractors and wagons on the muddy edge of
this Albanian border city and were grieving losses that embraced
not just one beautiful woman.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before that killing, they said, a 13-year-old boy was
shot dead and his mother fatally wounded when Serb forces sprayed
gunfire into the makeshift plastic sheet covering their wagon as
they travelled. The reason? Their tractor had stalled.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   And a 16-year-old and his grandfather also were shot, the
refugees said, when the Serb troops first came to their village
late last month and told them to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything was stolen -- the chickens, bread, televisions.
They burned the books,'' said Arta Berisha, 19. ``We left our
houses because they shot at us. We went into the mountains to live.
(Monday) they told us to leave the mountains.''
</P>
<P>
   They spent 13 days in the open, often under rain. Early
mornings, villagers sometimes would sneak into town to retrieve
food or clothes when the Serb militia weren't in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Rahim Imeri, 60, said that on Monday morning a messenger came
from the Serbian forces at the airport down the mountain and
demanded the villagers send two envoys to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Imeri and two villagers descended to meet the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, 'If you don't get out in two hours we will kill you
all,''' related Imeri, a town leader. ``At about 12:10 (p.m. local
time) they came and attacked us. There was fear and panic.''
</P>
<P>
   A Serb unit shot over the heads of the villagers, who rushed
onto their wagons and left for refuge in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, they said, Serb militia threw stones and shot at
the tires of their wagons. They saw not a single unscarred village.
</P>
<P>
   After traveling about 45 miles, the Slatina villagers were
stunned by the shooting of the boy and his mother. More bloodshed
would follow.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Four people in the wagon with Shpresa Halimi told separately
what happened next.
</P>
<P>
   Less than half an hour after the shooting, their wagon was
stopped by Serbia militiamen lining both sides of the road, said
Ferhat Halimi, the father-in-law of Shpresa.
</P>
<P>
   Halimi said one Serb came up close to the wagon, looked at the
girl and asked in Albanian, ``How old are you?''
</P>
<P>
   She answered that she was 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, Get down.''' He grasped her by the arm and forced her
onto the ground, said Halimi and three other relatives who related
the story.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Serb turned his attention to another woman in the
wagon, Zahida Hahdini, a niece of Ferhat Halimi.
</P>
<P>
   ``'Hey you. You come down,' he said. I didn't move,'' remembered
Hahdini, a blonde-haired 32-year-old mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, I thought, 'If they ask me my age, I would say
more -- maybe that I am 40 -- so they wouldn't take me''' said
Hahdini.
</P>
<P>
   But then Shpresa, already out of the wagon, ran to the back of
it where her father-in-law was sitting. She crouched behind the
wooden cart, four eyewitnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her to come to me, and I grabbed her hand,'' said
Ferhat Halimi.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbian militiaman saw Shpresa had fled, abandoned the
notion of finding another woman, then ran round the back of the
wagon.
</P>
<P>
   He opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was killed in my hand,'' said her father-in-law Ferhat
Halimi, weeping.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs told them to get out, to move on immediately, and
beckoned the next tractor in the caravan to come ahead, too, never
mind the body in the street.
</P>
<P>
   The driver of the following tractor refused to ride over
Shpresa, so the paramilitary shooter grabbed the woman's body and
pulled it off to the side of the road, the family related.
</P>
<P>
   By late morning Tuesday, after the caravan had crossed out of
Serb-controlled territory to the safety of Albania, Shpresa
Halimi's death was sinking in.
</P>
<P>
   Her brother-in-law Arsim Halimi, 25, was wearing Shpresa's black
parka, sitting on the edge of the wagon with his face in his hands,
heaving with sobs.
</P>
<P>
   Half an hour later, more composed, he told how she had traded
her coat for his black leather jacket, so he would be less
noticeable to Serbian militias who think the leather jacket is a
favorite of Kosovo independence fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She tried to cover me, to protect me. She was a little afraid
to go on this trip, but she was more worried about us,'' said Arsim
Halimi, referring to himself and to his brother - Shpresa's husband
of less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   What the husband Rasim Halimi lost perhaps is embodied in the
name of the woman who died. Shpresa means ``hope'' in English.
</P>
<P>
   When asked what could he envision ahead in life, Rasim Halimi
bowed his head and was silent for a long moment. Finally he
answered through tears: ``Just to live free.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
