<HEADER>
A6659 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TERRORISTSUSPECT-2ndT     04-13 1075
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TERRORISTSUSPECT-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: to this society.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it is proven that El Hage participated in the embassy
bombings, Al-Hallak says he will be ``the first one to condemn his
actions.''
</P>
<P>
   But the imam says he is skeptical that prosecutors have a strong
case against his friend, ``based on the fact that they made such
allegations against a person like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Al-Hallak said that in the past he has not cared about American
politics. But based on how federal authorities have handled the El
Hage case, ``I don't have trust in the government, to be honest
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   El Hage was not available to be interviewed.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Schmidt, who became El Hage's new defense attorney after
another lawyer was fired in March, said he believes that the
government is being too hard on him in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still perplexed by the restrictions placed on my client
and how his contacting the imam (in Arlington) would be a danger,''
Schmidt said in an interview in his Manhattan office, where 11
boxes of files on the government's case sit on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt said he believes that authorities are overstating what
they consider evidence simply because of El Hage's race and faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about what seems to be a feeling of anti-Muslim
sentiment in the United States. ... It seems to breed hysteria,''
said Schmidt.
</P>
<P>
   In the court documents, the government depicts El Hage as a
globe-trotting terrorist with indirect links to murders in New York
and Arizona and to the World Trade Center bombing in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Lebanon, he was born a Christian and converted to
the Muslim faith. He became a citizen of the United States after he
married an American woman named April Ray.
</P>
<P>
   He lived in north Fort Worth in the mid-1980s and later spent
time in Afghanistan, Sudan and Kenya, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage first met with the FBI in New York on Sept. 23, 1997,
nearly a year before the embassy bombings and just after returning
to Arlington. He was asked about his involvement in bin Laden's
organization, known as ``al Qaeda,'' Arabic for ``the Base.'' An
FBI affidavit said El Hage lied about whether he knew that one of
bin Laden's top military commanders, Abu Ubaidah al Banshari, had
drowned.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, El Hage went before a federal grand jury which,
according to documents, was interested in the ``tactical goals and
corresponding terrorism targets'' of al Qaeda. The grand jury also
wanted to know whether El Hage, among others, provided ``logistical
support and training'' to terrorist forces who attacked American
and United Nations forces in Somalia in 1993 and early 1994.
</P>
<P>
   El Hage was asked at the time whether he still worked for bin
Laden. The panel also wanted to know about his relationship with
Fazul Abdullah Mohammed, nicknamed ``Harun,'' who the government
said was El Hage's ``deputy'' in Kenya, and a suspected terrorist.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1997, the FBI and other law enforcement officers
approached El Hage twice in Arlington, and each time El Hage lied
about what he knew of al Qaeda operatives, government documents
say.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the embassy bombings, authorities in Kenya arrested a
suspect, identified as Mohamed Sadeek Odeh, who said he was a
``close friend of El Hage.'' Odeh described the Arlington man's
``background in accurate detail,'' an FBI agent wrote. But when
agents later interviewed El Hage, he denied knowing Odeh and said
he did not recognize the man's picture.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury, jolted by the embassy bombings, stepped up its
investigation of El Hage, and questions were asked about his
efforts to obtain ``chemical weapons,'' a federal indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also said documents were found in Kenya that
``bore the name and code name'' of El Hage, and mentioned his
international travels ``to procure chemical weapons and their
components'' for the bin Laden organization.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents in New York show that the government also
suspects that El Hage, while living in Texas, tried to purchase
firearms for Mahmoud Abouhalima, who was later convicted in the
World Trade Center bombing. Abouhalima never picked up the guns
obtained by El Hage, the records show.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have also linked El Hage to Rashad Khalifa,
described as a ``radical'' Islamic preacher who was murdered in the
late 1980s in Tucson, Ariz., at a time when El Hage lived there.
Court transcripts say El Hage ``entertained'' an unidentified
``tall man from New York'' who tailed Khalifa several months before
he was murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say they also want to know more about El Hage's trip
to Brooklyn in 1991 to take temporary control of the Alkifah
Refugee Center, a now-closed storefront on Atlantic Avenue that
once recruited rebels to fight the Soviets during the Afghan war.
</P>
<P>
   A day after El Hage's arrival, according to court records, the
center's founder, Mustafa Shalabi, disappeared. He was found slain
a week later in his apartment, which contained literature on
terrorism, police said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we're not saying that this defendant (El Hage) physically
carried out that murder,'' Fitzgerald told a judge in September.
But the prosecutor said it was suspicious that El Hage seemed to be
around when the killings occurred in Arizona and in New York, and
that he tried to buy guns for a person who later helped bomb the
World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   But it was El Hage's movements in Afghanistan, Sudan and Kenya
that established him as a terrorism suspect _ and a player in the
embassy bombings, Fitzgerald said in a packed courtroom in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``People around him were principally responsible for the
bombing,'' he said, adding: ``His role is not to put a bomb down.
His role is to set up logistics, engage in coded correspondence,
move money and give false stories.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 15, 1998, while living in Arlington, El Hage was
subpoenaed to reappear before the grand jury in New York. He
boarded a plane by himself, but undercover FBI agents were close
behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether he knows it or not, he did not come alone,''
Fitzgerald told a U.S. magistrate several days later, after El Hage
had been taken into custody.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was surveilled from the moment he was subpoenaed, 24 hours
a day, around the clock, until he got to the grand jury; to make
sure he didn't go anywhere. ... the government didn't trust him,''
Fitzgerald said.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
