   The New York Times plans 4 pages of stories, photos and graphics
on the continuing crisis in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-NATO (Brussels, Belgium) _ NATO's top commander, Gen.
Wesley Clark holds a detailed news conference on operations Kosovo
and the rest of Yugoslavia. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-CONGRESS (Washington) _ President Clinton's national
security team fanned across the Congress today trying to sell the
Balkan air campaign to a divided Congress just back from a two week
recess, and Republican leaders worked to head off lawmakers seeking
early votes on ground troops. Opinion was sharply split with some
members of Congress urging Clinton to began preparing for ground
troops and others vowing to vote against a deployment that they
charged would keep the United States in the Balkans for a decade.
By Alison Mitchell and Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-COST (Washington) _ The Defense Department asks Congress
for an emergency appropriation of about $3 billion to cover the
fight against Yugoslavia, and another $200 million for the refugee
aid. By Elizabeth Becker. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-PENTAGON (Washington) _ After refusing for more than two
weeks to share detailed information about the progress of Western
air strikes against Yugoslavia, NATO and the Pentagon have begun
slowly to open the spigot of information. By Philip Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DIPLO (Oslo, Norway) _ The Russian foreign minister said
Tuesday that Moscow remained opposed to an international security
force in Kosovo as part of a peace plan without the approval of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. This fundamental difference
between Russia and the United States appeared to blunt any prospect
that real progress would be made in the near future toward a
diplomatic solution in Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-BELGRADE (Belgrade) _ The most liberal member of the
Yugoslav government has sharply attacked the misuse of Serbian
patriotic unity for anachronistic ideological and political ends,
throwing down an indirect challenge to President Slobodan Milosevic
and his more nationalist and leftist allies, including Milosevic's
wife. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MACEDONIA (Stankovic) _ Serb paramilitary groups and
Yugoslav soldiers systematically expelled tens of thousands of
ethnic Albanians from a ten mile by twelve mile wide swathe of
southeastern Kosovo last week, refugees arriving here said Tuesday.
By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-INCURSION (Kukes, Albania) _ Serb infantry troops cross
into Albania, exchange fire with Albanian border police and seize
control of a border village. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-VOLUNTEERS (Tirana, Albania) _ Feature on fifty Kosovar
Albanians who have returned home to fight. Their stories seem to
confirm reports that Kosovo expatriates are returning in strong
numbers to join the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army, whose
battles against the Yugoslav government brought the crackdown a
year ago that has led to the current crisis. By Anthony DePalma.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBELS (Paris) _ France's Defense Minister said today
that the Serbian campaign against armed ethnic Albanian rebels in
Kosovo was raising questions about whether the NATO allies should
try to arm the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army. By Craig R. Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-TRAIN (Washington) _ The NATO warplane that destroyed a
passenger train crossing a bridge in Yugoslavia spotted the train
after it was too late to abort the attack, but circled back for a
second strike against the bridge after realizing the damage to the
train, NATO's senior general said today. By Steven Lee Myers.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-WARCRIMES (The Hague) _ Prosecutors at the war crimes
tribunal in The Hague have built a strong case to indict the
Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, on charges of war crimes,
diplomats and lawyers close to the tribunal say. But they say the
prosecutors are now depending on NATO governments for crucial links
they need to bolster their case. By Marlise Simons.
</P>
