<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-L.A.-NFL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL'S L.A. SEQUEL THREATENED BY OWNERSHIP SQUABBLE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Conn.)  (nk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ This metropolis unblushingly bills itself as the
entertainment capital of the world, and from Hollywood studios to
thrill-ride theme parks, oxygen bars and big Pacific rollers, it
can back up the boast. But when it comes to professional football,
the most popular sport in the country, Los Angeles has been stuck
in its own end-zone.
</P>
<P>
   Now that is about to change. Maybe.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the National Football League announced that Los
Angeles was its first choice to receive the league's as yet unnamed
32nd franchise, bypassing a firm bid of $200 million in public
financing from Houston in favor of Los Angeles' lucrative
television market, which is bigger than many states and could help
the league's slipping TV ratings.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a catch: Los Angeles, the town that couldn't keep a
team, now has not one but two competing proposed stadiums and owner
groups, each of them featuring ``guys with egos the size of
Montana,'' in the words of one City Hall aide. The league gave L.A.
until September to meet a range of demands, including a strong show
of support from the local business community, or lose the franchise
to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' quest says much about the difficulty of uniting
this disparate city of semiconnected suburbs around any idea, and
about its boosters' determination not to accept any status that
could be seen as second-class. It also bespeaks the tremendous
economic power of professional sports teams and their attraction
for wealthy owners, if not for municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Football is the No. 1 sport in America,'' said Michael Ovitz,
the onetime super-agent and current entertainment manager who is
leading a bid to build a new Spanish-style stadium and shopping
complex called the Hacienda on a vacant site in the suburb of
Carson, south of Los Angeles International Airport, with towering
mission bells that would ring on a home-team touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you not have football in this city? It doesn't make any
sense,'' Ovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   The other proposal is led by the billionaire insurance and
construction executive Eli Broad and Edward P. Roski Jr., a real
estate developer who co-owns the NHL's Kings and the NBA's Lakers
and helped develop the new Staples Arena where those teams will
play downtown. Their plan would dramatically revamp the Coliseum
into a state-of-the art stadium, topping its famed peristyle facade
with bat-wing canopies and luxury suites.
</P>
<P>
   So far, neither side has moved to compromise, though the city
establishment has shown a clear preference for reviving the
Coliseum as part of its efforts to revitalize the greater downtown
area. But unlike Houston, or Hartford, Conn., which recently lured
the New England Patriots with a pledge to build a $375 million
stadium, Los Angeles has shown no willingness to spend direct
public money on a new stadium, except for tax breaks on the revenue
a team might generate and freeway improvements already completed
near the Coliseum. Carson has offered a $150 million bond issue,
plus $30 million in cash, but the site there is a former dump that
would have to be cleaned up.
</P>
<P>
   League officials make it quietly clear that their preference
would be for a unified proposal from the two groups. But both sides
here, while pledging cooperation, are waiting for the next move by
the league, perhaps as soon as next week when its expansion
committee arrives for a two-day tour of the sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's still a bit of confusion owing to the lack of
specifics from the league, in terms of a concrete choice,'' said
City Councilman Mark Ridley-Thomas, whose district surrounds the
Coliseum site and who has spent three years promoting it. ``The
league will have to make the next step.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles's relationship with football has not been easy.
First the Rams decamped to Anaheim, in nearby Orange County, and
then, in 1995, to St. Louis. That same year, the Raiders abandoned
a star-crossed 12-year sojourn at the Coliseum and returned to
Oakland, leaving the nation's second-largest city without an NFL
team _ outclassed by the likes of Charlotte, N.C., Green Bay, Wis.,
and Jacksonville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Angelenos did not care about football, the argument went. The
Coliseum, on the edge of the South-Central neighborhood torn by the
1992 riots, was not safe, the skeptics said. Too much traffic, too
little parking, too little vacant land and a lack of public
investment seemed to doom the city's hopes of attracting another
team.
</P>
<P>
   As the would-be owners jockey for advantage, plenty of skeptics
remain unpersuaded of the need for a team. A Los Angeles Times poll
last year found that only 38 percent of respondents considered it
at least ``somewhat important'' to have a team in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're economic boons for the region,'' Joel
Kotkin, a senior fellow at the Pepperdine Institute of Public
Policy in Malibu said of sports franchises. ``They may be economic
boons for people who have downtown real estate. Something like a
Staples Arena, which will be full a great deal of the time, and
bring in groups, yes. But football teams?''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Basically a bunch of rich white guys go to the
games. I can't figure out how that makes much of a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   John Macks, a former political consultant who now writes for
``The Tonight Show,'' said: ``I grew up in Philadelphia and worked
in Washington. There it was the Eagles and the Redskins and it
defined your existence. Here nobody cares. First of all, it's not
raining and snowing on a Sunday in November. There are other things
to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Roski acknowledged that rampant rowdyism at Raiders' games at
the Coliseum had left him unable to persuade his wife to go to
games there, adding: ``I could get my son-in-law; he had no
choice.'' But he said that since the Raiders left, the University
of Southern California has continued to play at the Coliseum _ the
site of the 1932 and 1984 Olympics _ without incident, ``and I'm
very hopeful that a team can get started and grow here.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has made it clear that it does not want the choice of a
site to dictate the choice of owners. Because Roski holds the
exclusive rights for the state-owned Coliseum site, that could be a
stumbling block, and he has offered to give up those rights if
necessary. Similarly, Ovitz said that if his rival bid at Carson,
which is backed by the billionaire grocery magnate Ron Burkle and a
bevy of movie stars like Tom Cruise and Kevin Costner, is seen as
an impediment to returning a franchise to Los Angeles, he would
step aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm selling L.A. first and selling location second,'' Ovitz
said.
</P>
<P>
   When the league made its announcement last month, civic leaders
were quick to float a scenario in which Ovitz would give up his
bid, and join Roski's group as a minority owner. But so far,
neither side is giving up, and league officials suggest the league
may simply select a site, then auction ownership rights to the
highest bidder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we're all flying a little bit blind and waiting for
some direction,'' Roski said. ``We've done everything that the
league has asked us to do along the way. It would really be a shame
for this thing not to go through, so I think everybody's going to
work very hard to get it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
