<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIT-GATES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GATES GIVES $20 MILLION TO MIT COMPUTER LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE _ The Massachusetts Institute of Technology's
Laboratory for Computer Science received a $20 million gift from
Microsoft Corp. chief executive Bill Gates, the latest donation to
the school toward the construction of a new technology center.
</P>
<P>
   The gift, from the William H. Gates Foundation, was announced
Tuesday at a ceremony marking the 35th anniversary of the lab, one
of the main centers for software development at the university.
</P>
<P>
   MIT's Michael Dertouzos, the lab's director, also disclosed
details of a five-year research initiative called ``Oxygen.'' It
will focus on research designed to make access to computer networks
simpler, partly through advances in handheld, wireless computers
that can tap into larger information-storage devices. The project,
to be based at MIT's new technology center, will be funded
primarily through the Department of Defense.
</P>
<P>
   Gates's latest gift follows a donation of $25 million that he
and fellow Microsoft executive Steve Ballmer made to Harvard
University in 1996 to fund computer science work there. Gates
attended Harvard as an undergraduate in the 1970s before dropping
out to start the Redmond, Wash., software giant he still heads.
</P>
<P>
   MIT's ongoing computer research also deserved significant
support, Gates said in a press conference Tuesday at MIT.
Researchers at the lab make up ``one of the few groups that has the
power to make the breakthroughs'' in software research, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Such advances are needed in areas such as software testing and
design, said Gates in a speech earlier in the day at the school.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, he added, about 5 percent of the United States
population is ``leading the Web lifestyle'' _ in other words, using
on-line sources and e-mail on a regular basis. Nearly 29 percent of
the country uses the Internet at least occasionally, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for both those numbers to increase quickly, Gates said,
computer hardware and software must become easier to access from
remote locations. Ultimately, he said, people should be able to
``take the Web for granted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to make it simpler, cheaper, and more relevant,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For MIT, Gates's gift is the third donation toward the
development of a facility designed by noted architect Frank O.
Gehry.
</P>
<P>
   The building, to be known as the William H. Gates Building, will
be part of the Ray &AMP; Maria Stata Center, named after the founder
and chairman of Analog Devices Inc. of Norwood. Stata and his wife
donated $25 million toward the project in late 1997. In addition,
MIT last year received $15 million toward the center from Alexander
W. Dreyfoos Jr., founder of Photo Electronics Corp., a maker of
color-photography equipment.
</P>
<P>
   With a scheduled completion date of 2003, the Stata Center's
total cost is estimated at $104 million. It will replace the
school's historic ``Building 20,'' which has housed research
projects on everything from radar to artificial intelligence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
