NYT-04-13-99 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6676 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-INCURSION-ART-     04-13 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INCURSION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUGOSLAV FORCES ATTACK ALBANIAN BORDER POST
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ Yugoslav troops briefly took over an Albanian
border post Tuesday afternoon, lobbing mortar shells onto Albanian
territory and setting five houses ablaze, international observers
and Albanian officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The bold daylight raid heightened tension along Yugoslavia's
Kosovo border with Albania and provoked warnings from American
officials against widening the scope of the Balkan war.
</P>
<P>
   Lightly armed Albanian border police withdrew from the remote
border post in Kamenica, (pronounced Kah-meh-NEE-tsah), in northern
Albania, as the Serbian troops advanced. Albanian officials said
that as the police forces retreated, regular army units advanced to
resist the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Angeli, spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, which monitors the border, said the raid
started at around 1 p.m. and lasted for just over an hour. The
Serbian troops advanced about half a mile before stopping and
returning across the border into Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had any evidence that Yugoslav forces wanted to go
deeper inside Albania,'' Angeli said.
</P>
<P>
   No casualties were reported on either side, Angeli said. He had
no information on whether forces of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
separatist Albanian rebels in Kosovo, had been engaged as the Serbs
returned to their base.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are believed to have bases in Albania near the area
where the raid took place. Kosovo is a province of Serbia, which is
the major republic in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Although brief, the raid is considered among the most serious in
a series of attacks on the border that observers say have been
escalating since the NATO allies began bombing Yugoslavia three
weeks ago,
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav officials quickly denied Western reports that it had
sent troops into Albania or had intended to draw Albania into the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Serbian state television, Milivoje Novkovic,
director of the Yugoslav Army Information Center, called the
reports of an attack a ``heinous lie,'' spread by terrorists in
Albania who want to make it seem like ``an alleged Yugoslav Army
invasion of Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   But Albanian officials have reported numerous border attacks
from Yugoslavia during recent weeks. They accuse Yugoslavia of
attempting to provoke Albania, where thousands of troops from the
NATO allies are already stationed.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Albanian government gave the allies access to
Albanian air space and military bases. Twenty-four Apache attack
helicopters from the United States are expected to arrive in
Albania shortly, where a special base is being set up to support
them.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright said Tuesday that the
reports of an incursion by Serbian forces were being thoroughly
checked. But she made it clear that the United States and the
allies will not tolerate such provocations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have said very clearly that we condemn Serbian efforts to
try to widen this conflict and NATO has made very clear it would
consider with the utmost seriousness any attempt by the Serbs to
act beyond their borders,'' she said at a news conference in Oslo,
where she was meeting with Russian officials to discuss the
conflict in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Observers from the European group stationed in the Kamenica area
_ in the rugged mountains of northern Albania, about 70 miles north
of the capital, Tirana _ said that the intensity of incidents at
the border has increased recently. But Tuesday's was the first in
which Serbian troops actually crossed the border and entered
Albanian national territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our monitors were able to see the houses in flames,'' said
Angeli, the group's spokesman. ``And we also know what happened
because when the border police withdrew from their post they
informed us immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning to their posts later this afternoon, the border police
found several unexploded mortar shells that had to be cleared away.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the fifth consecutive day of confrontation along the
border,'' Angeli said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the attack at Kamenica might have been staged in
retaliation for some earlier incident, but he had no details.
</P>
<P>
   The European group also reported another attack in Albania on
Tuesday, about six miles from the Albanian border. Two rockets
landed in the countryside, just north of the refugee camps set up
here in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   Observers reported hearing deafening explosions. When they
checked, they found that no one had been injured, but that the
force of the explosion killed five cows.
</P>
<P>
   The European group said it believes the rockets were launched in
Yugoslavia, not an errant firing from a rebel camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot confirm that but it is obvious it came from the
other side,'' Angeli said. ``That is what our monitors told us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
