<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GINGRICH-COX     04-13 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GINGRICH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ex-speaker takes up political agenda at fund-raiser
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Newt Gingrich, the self-styled revolutionary who
now commands princely sums for his oratory, will star at a
$1,000-a-head dinner here tonight to benefit a charity and his
future in politics.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing his involvement with GOPAC, the Republican organization
he once led, Gingrich is offering his most generous contributors
fancy dinners and regular meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's dinner is Gingrich's first major fund-raising event
since he left office in January. It is part of a two-day Washington
visit for big givers to the Friends of Newt Gingrich political
action committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Salute to Newt gala is expected to draw some of the
capital's top lobbyists, including former Gingrich aides and
colleagues in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Actress Mary Tyler Moore will introduce Gingrich and praise his
work on behalf of juvenile diabetes, and a portion of the event's
proceeds will go to research into the disease. Jay Leno, host of
NBC's ``Tonight Show,'' will roast Gingrich via videotape.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 members of Congress, including Speaker Dennis
Hastert (R-Ill.), are expected to attend, although Gingrich
spokesman Mike Shields said votes in the Senate and House of
Representatives could keep some members away.
</P>
<P>
   That is a far cry from recent years when GOPAC dinners were
aired live on C-Span and the House's voting schedule neatly
conformed to Gingrich's political obligations.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the political message Gingrich's supporters hope to
deliver this evening is that Gingrich remains relevant despite
having given up his seat in Congress after last year's
disappointing Republican showing in midterm elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way for people to know that Newt Gingrich is still
interested in public issues,'' said Matt Towery, the former Georgia
state legislator and Gingrich campaign chairman. Towery is part of
a Georgia contingent that is expected for tonight's event.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich has been seen in neighborhood coffee shops and at local
airports, but he has not given a public speech in the capital since
November, shortly after he announced he would step down as speaker.
</P>
<P>
   He has granted no interviews, aside from an appearance on Leno's
show.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Gingrich has joined the conservative Washington think
tank American Enterprise Institute as a senior fellow and the board
of Forstmann, Little &AMP; Co., a mergers and acquisition firm.
</P>
<P>
   He is at work on a book and on forming a consulting business,
and he is giving speeches for fees reported to be as high as
$50,000 an appearance.
</P>
<P>
   His political supporters also have kept Gingrich's PAC account
flush. It ended 1998 with $275,000 in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Shields would not say how much money might be added to the
account through tonight's fete or how many tickets have been sold.
But he said he expects the 500 seats in the Capital Hilton ballroom
to be filled.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, drawing on his success in attracting campaign cash,
also has recently signed his name to a fund-raising letter sent by
the Republican National Com- mittee.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, sent the first week of March, went to fewer than
100,000 Republican donors, RNC spokesman Michael Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Sherman writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
