<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6691 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VATICAN-JEWS-500&AMP;ADD-     04-13 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VATICAN-JEWS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.) 
MONUMENT TO HOLOCAUST ERECTED IN VATICAN GARDEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Catholic and Jewish leaders Tuesday erected a stark
reminder of the Holocaust in a garden that belongs to the Vatican:
a 4-foot-high bronze menorah specially fitted with six candles to
symbolize the six million Jews who were killed by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   The menorah, which was delivered by a group of Jewish leaders
from New Jersey and New York, was placed in a corner of the
courtyard of the Pontifical North American College of Rome, a
seminary which, while standing outside St. Peter's, is Vatican
property.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first permanent Holocaust memorial on Vatican
territory, and it was placed there on Yom ha-Shoah, the annual day
of remembrance of the six million Jewish victims, as a symbol of
the growing reconciliation of Catholics and Jews after the
Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a another very positive sign how far the process of
dialogue between the Catholic Church and the Jewish people has
come,'' said Cardinal Edward Cassidy, president of the Holy See's
Commission on Religious Relations with Jews, standing alongside
several rabbis before lighting a candle on the menorah. ``Even just
a few years ago we could never have imagined such an event could
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But other comments by religious leaders at the ceremony, as well
as those of some who did not attend, mainly underscored some of the
disputes straining relations between the Vatican and leading Jewish
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, Jewish-Catholic relations have never been
better,'' said Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World
Jewish Congress, who was not invited to the event. ``But
paradoxically, Vatican-Jewish relations have gotten worse over the
last few years.''
</P>
<P>
   The original idea for the menorah came from Gunther Lawrence,
executive director of the Interreligious Information Center of New
York City. His proposal was immediately accepted by Cassidy and the
leaders of the North American College. On Wednesday, the American
Jewish and Catholic delegations are expected to make a joint
presentation of a miniature of the menorah to Pope John Paul II at
his weekly general audience.
</P>
<P>
   But the project was launched without the approval or the
cooperation of some of the leading Jewish organizations, such as
the World Jewish Congress or the Anti-Defamation League.
</P>
<P>
   The two highly influential organizations had attacked as
inadequate the Vatican's apology for the failure of most Catholics
to resist the mass killing of European Jews. The Vatican document,
entitled ``We Remember: Reflections on the Holocaust,'' was
released a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   What is simmering beneath the criticism is a deep rift over the
role of Pope Pius XII during the war. The Vatican, which contends
that he never spoke out publicly against Nazi atrocities only out
of fear of mass retaliations and that he personally helped save
thousands of Jewish lives, has plans to make him a saint. Jewish
groups dispute the Vatican's defense of Pius XII, and bitterly
oppose any plans to beatify him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Partly because of the clashing views of Pius XII's role in the
Holocaust, major Jewish organizations have also been highly
critical of the Vatican's handling of its World War II archival
materials, complaining that the Vatican has withheld key documents
from public scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In return, those organizations have been rebuked by Vatican
officials. In his address Tuesday, Cassidy reminded his audience of
a speech he wrote last February expressing disappointment over
Jewish organizations' failure to respond to a Vatican offer to
jointly examine 12 volumes of documents relating to the Holocaust
that have already been made public. The cardinal complained of
``insensitivity on the part of some Jewish organizations in
relation to what we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish figures who attended Tuesday's ceremony expressed
sympathy for the Vatican position. Rabbi Jack Bemporad, who is the
director of the Center for Interreligious Understanding at Ramapo
College, in New Jersey, and a veteran of interfaith conferences,
delivered a speech defending the pope and Cassidy.
</P>
<P>
   Others in the group also expressed disagreement with the stance
of organizations like the World Jewish Congress. ``This is not a
time to be strident,'' said David H. Lincoln, senior rabbi of
Manhattan's Park Avenue Synagogue, who said kaddish, the mourner's
prayer, at the ceremony. ``There are important things we can do
between Catholics and Jews given the total cooperation we already
have.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinberg said that while there is some diversity of opinion
within Jewish organizations, he suspected that Vatican officials
had deliberately sought out Jewish leaders that are outside the
mainstream of Jewish opinion. ``I have to say today's event raised
my suspicion that they are playing an old game of playing
favorites,'' he said, ``and that is not the way to engage in
genuine dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence, who conceived of the Holocaust memorial three years
ago and persuaded an Israeli artist, Aharon Bezalel, to create it,
said the sculpture speaks for itself. ``We are taking something
very Jewish and putting it on Vatican ground,'' he said. ``Surely,
everybody can unite on that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
