<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      04-13 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESSIONAL LEADERS URGE CLINTON TO PREPARE FOR GROUND WAR 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional leaders urged President Clinton on
Tuesday to begin preparations for a ground war in Kosovo, even as
the House and Senate shied away from voting this week on
authorizing the commitment of U.S. troops to battle Yugoslav
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The extraordinary push from Republican and Democratic lawmakers
to use ground troops as part the overall NATO campaign in the
Balkans came in a meeting at the White House in which Clinton
offered a ``forceful'' presentation, as one participant put it, of
the damage inflicted on Serb military operations by three weeks of
bombing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also asked the 58 members of Congress in the meeting for
approval of billions of dollars in emergency funding to help pay
for the war effort through the end of this fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen plans to present a detailed
assessment of the costs in a hearing Wednesday on Capitol Hill. But
administration officials said Tuesday that estimates range from $3
billion to $4 billion incurred thus far to as much $10 billion to
$12 billion if the NATO air campaign continues well into the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The president said the money, which is likely to come from the
budget surplus, is also needed for the U.S. relief effort for
Kosovo refugees and to provide ``urgently needed assistance to
front-line states'' bordering Yugoslavia, ``who are struggling to
preserve their own stability as they cope with refugees and turmoil
in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These expenses are an immediate and urgent emergency. They are
necessary so that we and our NATO allies can continue to pursue
this mission,'' the president said in brief remarks at the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Following the meeting with Clinton, House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Texas, said the president believes the air campaign ``is
working'' and there ``is no need for the insertion of ground
troops.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the president's briefing, Armey said a ``general
consensus'' has emerged among congressional leaders to put off what
could be a potentially divisive vote on committing U.S. ground
troops and declaring all-out war against Yugoslavia. He said
Republican and Democratic leaders believe that the NATO air
campaign needs more time to work before moving to a full-blown
debate on the floor over what to do next.
</P>
<P>
   Armey's view was echoed by other lawmakers attending the
meeting. They said Clinton reminded them that the allied Desert
Storm operation against Iraq included 44 days of nearly continuous
bombing. But the NATO pounding of Yugoslavia, which started 21 days
ago, has been hampered by bad weather, preventing allied planes
from achieving as much damage to military targets as NATO
commanders had hoped for at this stage in the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said Clinton stressed that the
alliance ``needs to be calm and determined, and proceed forward in
a very methodical way'' because ``there's a lot that yet can be
achieved by air.''
</P>
<P>
   But while Clinton emphasized his belief that the bombing effort
alone eventually will force Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
to pull his forces out of Kosovo, Kerry said the president did not
rule out the use of ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard from the president ... that he does not personally
believe at this time that they will be necessary to achieve the
goal,'' Kerry said. ``But he did say that nothing is off the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry and several other lawmakers urged Clinton to begin
planning for an allied invasion of Kosovo, beginning with the
placement of supplies, equipment and support personnel in
front-line states in the event Milosevic continues his refusal to
bow to NATO demands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said that NATO does have a plan for ground forces,
but so far allied commanders have not begun preparations for using
them.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Richard Lugar, R-Ind., who pressed the case for preparing
more forcefully than anyone else in the meeting, said a NATO ground
war against Serb forces is inevitable unless Milosevic can be
convinced that his military will be ``eliminated'' and his hold on
power ended. But to do that, Lugar said, NATO must undertake
visible planning for a ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb., however, said he sees evidence that
ground troops are already engaged in the fight and called the
debate over whether to commit them ``a phony issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got three men captured. Our troops cut rail lines (from
other countries into Yugoslavia), and we're sending 4,000 into
Albania in support of Apache helicopter operations,'' Kerrey said.
``We've crossed the Rubicon here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerrey, a Medal of Honor recipient who lost a leg in the Vietnam
War, cautioned against underestimating the determination of
Milosevic and his military to dig in and hold out against the air
campaign. He suggested that a ground fight could be long and
bloody.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got personal experience with how trenching tools defeated
B-52s,'' he said. ``If their will to fight remains, we've got a
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of committing U.S. troops to a ground war in the
Balkans has thrown Congress into turmoil about what position to
take. While some members openly call for the commitment of U.S.
forces and would support a declaration of war against Yugoslavia,
others would like to end U.S. participation in the air campaign by
denying funding to continue the operation.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, said Tuesday, however, that
``all of us'' should support the funding ``we need to do this
job,'' if for no other reason, because U.S. forces are engaged in
combat. But she said there are ``still many questions about where
we go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., meanwhile, is pressing the GOP
House leadership to schedule a vote on whether to formally declare
war on Yugoslavia or to order the president to end involvement of
U.S. forces in the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, who believes the United States is ``engaged in a war
that has not been declared,'' has filed a resolution with the House
that would force a vote on the matter by May 15 under the terms of
the 1973 War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   He said if the leadership fails to allow the vote, he plans to
file a motion in federal court in hopes of having Clinton's
commitment of forces declared unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
