<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA'S ECONOMY STARTS TO STABILIZE, SAYS REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NEELA BANERJEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After months of decline, the Russian economy is
beginning to show some stability, according to a monthly report
issued Tuesday by an independent research organization and the
government.
</P>
<P>
   The April issue of the report, ``Russian Economic Trends,''
noted small increases in consumer spending and industrial
production in February and a falling inflation rate in March.
</P>
<P>
   Together, such shifts substantiate a widely held opinion here
that the effects of last August's economic crisis have not been as
dire as feared. Russia has so far averted hyperinflation, a free
fall in the value of the ruble and a continued steep drop in
economic output.
</P>
<P>
   But the report's authors and other economists said that such
stability could prove temporary, especially if Russia's political
situation, shaky in the last few weeks, grows more volatile or if
the government fails to receive a badly needed refinancing package
it is now discussing with the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   The economic indicators ``give ground for cautious optimism,''
said Peter Westin, an economist with the Russian European Center
for Economic Policy, an author of the report. ``But how sustainable
is the trend?''
</P>
<P>
   Industrial output rose 2.5 percent in February to the highest
level since May-June 1998. Construction, agriculture and retail
trade also grew. The increases, however, are driven by the
devaluation of the ruble, not by government policy, the report
concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The ruble has fallen from an exchange rate of about 17 cents in
August to 4 cents, resulting in a sharp decrease in imports because
they are so much more expensive when purchased in rubles. But some
Russian manufacturers have increased production to fill the supply
shortage.
</P>
<P>
   ``The devaluation has been a huge shot in the arm for domestic
producers,'' said Peter Boone, head of research at the Moscow
brokerage firm of Brunswick Warburg.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer spending increased in March for the first time since
August, most likely as Russians spent some savings for purchases
they feared would get more expensive because of inflation.
</P>
<P>
   Yet inflation itself rose in March by 2.8 percent, compared to
4.1 percent in February. Over all, inflation has risen at an
annualized rate of about 97 percent over the seven months of the
crisis; while severe, that hasn't proven catastrophic to the
economy, said Rudiger Ahrend, director of the Russian European
Center for Economic Policy.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the relatively low monthly inflation rates is
that wages and pensions have held steady. Though the earning power
of most Russians has fallen precipitously, many have found ways to
adapt to increased hardship and have not really pressured the
government to raise state salaries or fix prices. The government
itself has taken steps to minimize inflation, raising the supply of
money by a moderate 25 percent in the last several months.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many economists believe it would take very little to
destabilize the economy.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that the wrenching economic changes needed in
industry and banking will be legislated soon, since parliamentary
and presidential elections are scheduled in the next 15 months. And
even with the signs of stability noted by the report, there are
troubling trends.
</P>
<P>
   The government's foreign-currency reserves, for example, fell to
a four-year low in March to $10.8 billion, partly because of
central bank purchases of rubles to prevent the Russian currency
from falling too steeply.
</P>
<P>
   The drop in reserves comes as Russia tries to restructure
payments on $150 billion in foreign debt, which consumed 40 percent
of the budget earlier this year. An IMF mission in Moscow is
negotiating a loan refinancing package with the government, and a
recommendation by the mission could come next week.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials went to Paris on Tuesday to begin negotiations
with nations that hold part of the foreign debt. The Russians are
expected to ask the creditors to forgive as much as 75 percent of
the debt and restructure payments due this year and next.
</P>
</TEXT>
