<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6700 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAVED-GUY-COX     04-13 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAVED-GUY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rescued crane operator describes mill fire from over 200 feet in
air
 &HT;    By Jennifer Ffrench-Parker
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Each day, after a 1 1/2 hour drive from Woodland,
Ala., to Atlanta, Ivers Sims climbs dozens of stairs in the center
of his crane 220 feet above the Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill.
</P>
<P>
   He takes his lunch, a radio to communicate with his co-workers
below and a meter to measure wind gusts. ``I stay up there eight to
12 hours a day,'' he said, adding that he comes down only for
bathroom breaks.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was to be a normal day. His Hammerhead crane was lifting
heavy beams in and out of the 1800s mill building that was being
gutted for residential loft apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Around 2 p.m., he noticed smoke curling up from the inside the
old building. At first it wasn't enough to alarm Sims, 49.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a small fire,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He watched some of his co-workers scurry from the top of the
building and put a hose to the fire. But it never occurred to him
to hurry down, Sims said Tuesday after a news conference at Atlanta
Medical Center, where he was treated for smoke inhalation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was more worried about them,'' he said. ``I stayed just in
case there was something I could do to help put it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the fire _ fanned by 30 to 40 mph gusts of wind _ started
to spread. For the first time Sims thought of himself. He realized
he couldn't get down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to worry about myself then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Brown, area director for the Occupational Safety and Health
Administration's Atlanta West Area Office, said Sims was trapped
because heat from the fire cut off his escape down the central
stairway in his crane.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the potential for a serious incident, but happily it
turned out OK,'' said Brown, who had staff at the old Cabbagetown
mill soon after the drama began unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose office inspects construction sites and workplace
accidents, said being trapped by fire in a crane is not a usual job
hazard for crane operators like Sims, who number 1,220 in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more typical for cranes to collapse or for workers below
to be struck by materials dangling from cranes,'' said Brown whose
office oversees Georgia's 32 western and northern counties
including Fulton.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, Brown said, OSHA has investigated about five
construction accidents involving cranes including one in Atlanta in
which a cement bucket dangling from a crane hit and killed a worker
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA is not investigating Monday's incident at the mill, Brown
said.
</P>
<P>
   Sims, a soft-spoken man, was rescued after about an hour and a
half on the crane. The cab he spends his days in caught fire from
the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost red hot,'' he said. ``It was a blessing the wind
was blowing so strong. It kept the heat off me.''
</P>
<P>
   To escape the heat that made his shoes ``real hot,'' Sims
crawled to one end of the crane and laid on his belly.
</P>
<P>
   While he waited, he kept in touch by radio with his supervisor.
He also spoke with Atlanta Mayor Bill Campbell.
</P>
<P>
   They told him someone would come to get him.
</P>
<P>
   Sims worried that the wind would make it difficult for the
helicopter and the firefighter to reach him.
</P>
<P>
   When Matt Moseley was lowered from a helicopter to get him, Sims
said he told the firefighter to be careful where he stepped because
the crane was hot.
</P>
<P>
   He had already worked out in his mind that he would have to wear
a body harness. He followed Moseley's directions and put his leg
through the harness and hooked it around him.
</P>
<P>
   As the helicopter lifted the pair to safety, Sims, who has been
a crane operator for 10 of his 21 years in construction, said he
felt no fear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am used to heights,'' he said. ``I was just a little worried
the line might break.''
</P>
<P>
   Safely rescued, he wanted to ``kiss the ground'' but was hustled
off on a stretcher to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Sims, who had been at the Fulton Bag and Cotton Mill
construction site for about six months, said he would take about
three weeks off but intend to be back on the job for his employer,
Jasper Construction Co.
</P>
<P>
   Crane operators like Sims are in demand in Atlanta's boom
economy. Statewide, they average an hourly wage of $12.96, said
Mike Wald, a regional economist with the U.S. Department of Labor,
Bureau of Labor Statistics. in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   OSHA's Brown said there are enough cranes towering against
Atlanta's skyline for construction workers to call the Hammerhead
cranes ``the state bird of Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   Thrust into the public spotlight by his predicament, Sims said
he didn't mind the attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am glad to be here,'' he said. ``I don't mind as long as I
was here.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Ffrench-Parker writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
