NYT-04-13-99 1936EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0250 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6701 &Cx1f; taf-z
s t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-SHANGHAI     04-13 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CHINA-SHANGHAI-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHANGHAI: A VESSEL FOR CHINA'S TREASURES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, April 18)  
 (bl)  
 By SETH FAISON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the center of China's largest and most cosmopolitan city,
Shanghai's city fathers have completed a showcase of urban planning
that reflects the times. A park in the middle of Shanghai, a
long-neglected city that has been pegged by Chinese leaders as a
model for the entire country, now embodies the best of China's
efforts to become a more sophisticated and a culturally richer
society.
</P>
<P>
   The park is still called by its original name, People's Square,
in keeping with the Communist political orientation that continues
to govern China. Yet People's Square now actually seems to offer
city residents a place to enjoy on their own terms, rather than at
the instruction of a paternalistic state. Visitors are welcome. In
fact, Shanghai's leaders are so proud of the square, they hope and
expect it will draw lots of tourists.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The jewel of this revitalized area is the Shanghai Museum, a
marvelous contemporary building the color of sand and the shape of
an ancient Chinese urn, designed by a team of local architects. It
houses a majestic collection of Chinese art, easily the finest in
the country.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Catty-corner across the square is a spanking new opera house,
the Shanghai Grand Theater, another distinct architectural triumph
in a land where hasty construction in recent years has littered
China's cities with excess chrome and garish colored glass. The
opera house, designed by a French architect, Jean-Marie
Charpentier, has a curved roof that opens toward the sky like a
giant offering plate. ``Aida'' was performed there last fall, and
concerts and other performances are held nightly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The park that lies in between these two new cultural monuments,
with pleasant pathways lined with flowers and greenery, completes
the square's sudden, more civilized, incarnation. A new City Hall
on the far side of the park may look dull compared with its
neighbors, but at least it avoids the Stalinist excesses of most
government buildings elsewhere in China. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, People's Park reflects the remarkable
transformation that Shanghai has witnessed in this century. In
colonial days, when the city was dominated by French and British
and American traders who divided it into foreign ``concessions''
with competing governments, police forces, and styles of dress, the
park was home to a race track where straw-hatted foreigners could
parade in their Sunday finery. After the Communist revolution in
1949, the area became a barren square of concrete, a place to hold
mass rallies.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, People's Park was the site of rallies by Red
Guards, who often dragged ``bourgeois'' offenders to its center to
be punished. In the years that followed, the square remained bleak
and empty, as Shanghai languished and fell behind other areas of
China.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1990s the city was given the go-ahead, and the
money, to redevelop Shanghai into China's premier metropolis, and
People's Park was transformed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One component, the Shanghai Museum, for years was housed in a
dank old bank building that belonged to Shanghai's biggest
gangster, Du Yuesheng, before the revolution. In 1992, eager to
find a better showcase for their high quality collection, the
museum's directors took a risk, selling their old building to a
real estate developer for $25 million _ even though they had no
place to move. The collection was without a permanent home for four
years while the museum directors raised the rest of the money
needed for a new building and battled the city's bureaucracy for
the right to give it a prominence befitting its rich contents. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foreign donors, many of them Shanghai-born emigrants in New
York, London and Hong Kong, provided part of the financing. The
directors also relied on foreign connections to arrange visiting
exhibitions and to obtain modern lighting and humidity systems.
When the museum opened in 1996, its 11 exhibition spaces were named
for prominent foreign donors, who had contributed around $10
million in total.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum houses a first-class collection of bronze, porcelain
and Chinese painting, as well as impressive displays of
calligraphy, jade and classical furniture. Visiting exhibitions
often include 20th-century art. Even better, the presentation is at
once impeccable and accessible to those unfamiliar with Chinese
art, with labels in both Chinese and English.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum costs only $2.50, or 60 cents, for anyone with a
student card. A recorded guide costs an additional $5, and narrated
in Chinese, Japanese, French or excellent English, is well worth
it.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The exhibition of ancient bronzes on the ground floor may have
been given a premier location because it is the area of expertise
for Ma Chengyuan, the founding director of the museum, who recently
retired. Tastefully decorated in dark green, the hall is lighted
only dimly, which gives an extra luster to the pieces on display,
positioned on plexiglass stands that are so simple as to be nearly
invisible.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bronze epitomizes China's ancient civilization, and bronze
artifacts became treasured possessions of Chinese aristocrats in
the earliest known Chinese societies, more than 2,500 years ago.
Although bronzes are often denied star billing, the bronzes in the
Shanghai Museum are so impressive that they should not be passed
up. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 400 pieces on view, though the museum owns
more than 6,000 pieces altogether. Many of those on display remain
well preserved because they accompanied their owners to the grave. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although first made as simple implements, by the height of the
Shang Dynasty (16th to 11th century B.C.) bronzes were made with
designs of brilliant and intricate beauty. A popular form was the
three-legged ding, a vessel often decorated with animal-shaped
masks.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some of the finest examples were originally designed as vessels
for wine, food or water, although Chinese nobles collected them in
a strict social system that specified how many bronzes one could
own, depending on social rank. A duke, for instance, might be
allowed to own seven, or five, or three or only one, depending on
his rank. To question one's allotment of bronzes was to challenge
the entire social system on which rank was based.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Spring and Autumn Period (770-476 B.C.) brought a flowering
of China's bronze age. One of most most striking pieces is a wine
vessel in the shape of an ox, with curved horns and a ring through
its nose, bug-eyed as though it had just been fired in a mold that
would keep it standing in the same position for millenniums.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ground floor also houses a sculpture gallery and an
exhibition hall. On the second floor, the ceramics section is
particularly rich. As a welcoming explanation at the entryway puts
it bluntly: ``Pottery belongs to all mankind, but porcelain is
China's creation.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The collection, displayed in one extended gallery, encompasses
ceramics from the pottery of neolithic times, to the creation of
celadon in the first century A.D., to the polychromed pottery of
the Tang Dynasty and the fine white porcelain of the Song Dynasty,
up to the 20th century.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Yet the prizes here are the pieces that chronicle the invention
of underglazing blue porcelain in the 13th century A.D. that
brought a new richness and depth to the finish of porcelains.
Perhaps bringing Chinese ceramics to their finest moment, a
mountain town called Jingdezhen became the center of production for
porcelain, a position it held until the 20th century. Today,
Jingdezhen is still producing porcelains, but most of them are
cheap imitations intended to be sold as antiques.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The museum's calligraphy and painting galleries on the third
floor are beautifully designed, with wooden floors and traditional
Chinese roofing. Scroll paintings, many of them a delicate mixture
of painting and calligraphy, are magnificently displayed on
specially designed tables that tilt toward the viewer. The visitor
may notice that the dim lighting brightens as soon as an overhead
sensor detects his approach, then dims again to prevent fragile
paintings from fading from exposure to the light.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A charming tea pavilion on the second floor offers a distinctly
Chinese setting for tea, with carved wooden windows of the Qing
Dynasty set into the walls. The museum store on the ground floor is
excellent, offering a broad choice of ceramics, silk, stylized
boxes, jewelry and screens, and a particularly fine choice of art
and history books. Silk scarves, at $5 to $10, are good value. So
is jade jewelry, from $5 to $100. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Shanghai Museum, at 201 Renmin Dadao in People's Park, is
open every day from 9 a.m to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
