<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFRICA-WILDLIFE-970(     04-13 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFRICA-WILDLIFE-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH AFRICA'S PROBLEM OF POACHING GOES BEYOND ANIMALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   DONALD G. McNEIL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BETTY'S BAY, South Africa &UR;  &LR; _ Poachers take their chances when
they raid the small but fertile section of coastline that Mike and
Linda Tannett watch from the porch of their retirement getaway
here.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Tannett, 56, has decked a 31-year-old poacher with one
punch, grabbed his car keys and kicked him across a gravel road so
hard he scraped the skin off his legs.
</P>
<P>
   On quiet afternoons, Mike Tannett, 58, has made arrests while
unarmed and barefoot. But after dark he sometimes sits up late in
the dunes with his night-vision scope. If he spots figures slipping
into the water, he radios for a friend with an assault rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Poaching in South Africa is not restricted to the dramatic
things everyone has heard of, like elephant tusks and rhinoceros
horns. Those animals are generally safe here, thanks to well-armed
rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, some of the things hauled out of the wild are so
obscure that their names are hard to pronounce. At the moment,
three of the biggest prey items are cycads (pronounced SIGH-kud),
buchu (BOO-choo), and perlemoen (PAIR-luh-moon). The first is
stolen only for the rich, the second for the poor, the third for
Chinese restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the funny names, they are no laughing matter.
</P>
<P>
   Perlemoen is the local word for abalone, and with its price
reaching $135 a pound in Asia, the trade is worth millions. A
low-intensity war has been going on over perlemoen on the coast.
People have been shot, beach houses burned down, police cars
flipped over and mercenaries hired by landowners.
</P>
<P>
   Cycads are ancient plants that date back 300 million years and
were nibbled by dinosaurs. The rarest have sold for up to $15,000
before ending up in Johannesburg gardens or as decor on the grounds
of casinos. The battle to preserve them is fought more with science
than bullets as rangers try to find every wild one and hide a
microchip inside that can finger any new owner as a thief.
</P>
<P>
   Buchu is of the rutaceae family of aromatic herbs, with smells
ranging from licorice to lemon, once used by the Khoi-khoi, the
original inhabitants of the Cape, to treat everything from bruises
to kidney problems. In the 19th century, it was a lucrative export
to Europe, and an 1824 law made it a misdemeanor to ``tear up'' the
plant. It is not yet endangered, but illegal pickers have been
caught with hundreds of pounds of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest problem is a lack of knowledge of what's really
happening to African wildlife,'' said Superintendent Piet Lategan,
commander of the South African police's Endangered Species Unit.
</P>
<P>
   The unit, founded 10 years ago to catch ivory and rhino horn
smugglers, has expanded to fight the growing trade in snakes,
tortoises, cactuses, aloes, parrots, and even rare beetles, not to
mention the smugglers of lemurs from Madagascar and chimpanzees
from central Africa who change planes in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Enforcing these laws can be trickier than catching drug
smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Jurisdictions are a hodgepodge. A forest by the seaside might be
run by a local parks department while the tide pools a few yards
away ``can be the responsibility of some guy in Pretoria who never
sees the ocean,'' said Craig Spencer, a conservation officer.
</P>
<P>
   Also, identification is a problem. Customs agents are seldom
beetle buffs; and a beat cop asked to help raid a nursery might not
know a cycad from a cyclamen.
</P>
<P>
   Lategan said he once caught a man with 197 scorpions. It
definitely looked suspicious, he said, but he himself could not
tell if they were an endangered subspecies. He put five in an
envelope and headed for a flight to a university town with an
entomology department. The security guard at the airport asked,
``What's in the envelope?'' he said. ``I said, `Pets.' He took one
look and waved me through.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, this being South Africa, the issue has a racial aspect.
Many ardent conservationists, like the Tannetts, are
English-speaking whites, while poachers, especially near Cape Town,
tend to be impoverished people of mixed race.
</P>
<P>
   Their ancestors have gathered abalone and lobster for centuries
_ or millenniums, if you count the Khoi-khoi ancestry to which some
lay claim _ and they argue that their birthright is being snatched
away just as it has become valuable.
</P>
<P>
   They have long been resentful because, under the old apartheid
government, the biggest shellfish quotas went to whites connected
with the governing National Party. And now, the new black-led
government, trying to turn the ship of state around and make it
deliver housing, electricity and water, has bigger things on its
mind than the abalone.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, crime has flourished. Near Hawston, a depressed
fishing village, gangs have become so big that they intimidate the
police, said Maria Hauck, a University of Cape Town criminologist
who studies the industry. ``Up to to 40 guys, with guns and
radios'' can guard a stretch of beach while their divers take out
tons at a time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some gangs rent beach houses to hide in, monitor police radios
and hide nail-studded boards in the sand to pop the tires of any
vehicles that try to surprise them at work, the police and local
residents say. Inside Hawston, they attacked police vans trying to
make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   In Betty's Bay, which is so small it doesn't even have a police
station, poachers have tried intimidation. Tannett, a founder of
Sea Watch, a civilian group that has arrested more than 500
poachers and recovered $150,000 worth of abalone since 1995, has
been beaten up and his car has been rammed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poachers came down my driveway at 1 a.m. and shined a light on
my bed,'' said Spencer, the local nature conservation officer, who
works with Sea Watch. ``I was in the shower and all I could do was
crouch down because I was nowhere near my gun. Luckily, my dog
started barking and they left.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The shallow waters of Betty's Bay, once the coast's richest
stretch, have lost 90 percent of their abalone and lobsters,
Tannett said.
</P>
<P>
   Cycads face the same kind of devastation. They resemble thick
palm trees, but with fernlike leaves and a fat central seedpod that
looks like a cross between a pine cone and a pineapple. There are
about 35 species in South Africa, and the practice for collecting
rare ones began about 20 years ago. A few are exported, but most
end up in the gardens of the wealthy. Now, two-thirds of the
varieties face extinction in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cycads are a very sorry story,'' said David Newton, national
representative for Traffic, the international organization that
fights the smuggling of endangered species. ``I know of one species
which has only one plant left, on an inaccessible cliff face, where
there were once hundreds and hundreds.''
</P>
<P>
   Legally, three permits are required even to dig one up at home
to move to a new house _ collecting, export and import _ under the
Convention in International Trade of Endangered Species, the same
one that covers ivory. There are cycad nurseries, but the plants
take 15 years to reach salable size.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Johannesburg landscape gardener was arrested
selling them from his home for about $2,500 each. The buyers had no
way of knowing the plants had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   But the police, helped by a parks board agent, did. Each plant
had a microchip hidden inside that, as a scanner was passed over
it, transmitted a serial number indicating its species, age, and
where it should still have been _ a state forest in Mpumalanga,
hundreds of miles away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
