<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YAGER-COX     04-13 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YAGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yager foe reunited with his daughters
 &HT;    By Clint Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Philadelphia millionaire who vowed to crush
Atlanta children's activist Faye Yager as part of his strategy to
find his missing daughters now has the girls at home.
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Lynn, 9, and Genevieve Marie, 7, were recovered by
millionaire Bipin Shah on Saturday in Lucerne, Switzerland, where
they were living with their mother. Ellen Dever, Shah's former
wife, remains abroad, according to a news release issued Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Yager is the controversial operator of the Children of the
Underground, a network of safe houses that hides children, and
generally their mothers, from allegedly abusive fathers.
</P>
<P>
   In several interviews last spring, Yager said she helped Dever
disappear with the children in June 1997, despite the fact that no
one had accused Shah of harming the girls.
</P>
<P>
   Shah attracted worldwide media attention in December 1997 when
he offered a $2 million reward for information leading to the
return of his daughters. In January 1998, Shah filed a $100 million
lawsuit against Yager, the wife of an Atlanta pediatrician, in
federal district court in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, Shah said last year, was filed to gain access to
information such as telephone records and to pressure Yager by what
he called ``bleeding Faye Yager financially.''
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys on both sides Tuesday declined to comment on what
role, if any, Yager played in the recovery of Shah's children.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI knew where to find Dever and the children and was in the
process of attaining a provincial warrant when Shah was reunited
with his daughters, said Linda Vizi of the Philadelphia FBI office.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant is issued for local authorities to execute, Vizi
explained, ``because we can't just go into another country and take
people.''
</P>
<P>
   The warrant for Dever's arrest is still pending and the case is
still under investigation, Vizi said.
</P>
<P>
   The hunt for his children cost $3.2 million, Shah said in a
statement. The search, which focused on Europe early on, sent
investigators scurrying from Finland to South Africa. Shah was in
contact with more than 125 bounty hunters looking for a chunk of
the $2 million reward. None of the reward will be distributed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The return of the children came by Mr. Shah's own
investigative efforts and the $2 million reward has been officially
withdrawn,'' said Albert Momjain, Shah's Philadelphia attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Shah, in his statement, said he will not be granting interviews,
citing the need for privacy during a period of readjustment.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Chilivis, the Atlanta attorney representing Shah, said he
and his client haven't fully discussed the situation since the
children returned and could not comment about the future of the
lawsuit against Yager.
</P>
<P>
   Yager remains under investigation by a federal grand jury in
Philadelphia for her role in the abduction of the Shah children.
</P>
<P>
   Yager, who operated the Children of the Underground network for
more than a decade, moved last summer from suburban Atlanta to
Brevard, N.C., where she operates an inn. She said last fall she no
longer helps women and children go underground. Efforts to reach
Yager by telephone Tuesday were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   Clint Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
