<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0257 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6715 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-HEALTH-HEARING-NY     04-13 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-HEALTH-HEARING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE PANEL HEARS FUNDING REQUESTS FROM DISEASE VICTIMS'
ADVOCATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In the official government record, the hearing that
began Tuesday in Room 2358 of the Rayburn House Office Building
will be listed as ``public witness testimony.'' Unofficially, it
was long ago called ``Mother Teresa's waiting room,'' a moniker
that could not be more apt.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for three days this week and two next, the sick and
afflicted and their lobbyists are gathering in an annual telethon
of sorts: the desperate competition for research funding to cure
disease. Hundreds of ailments are represented, from the most common
cancer to the rarest genetic disorder. Even erectile dysfunction
got a mention.
</P>
<P>
   So many people asked testify before the subcommittee that holds
the pursestrings to the National Institutes of Health that two
thirds of them were turned down. The rest were selected by lottery
for the privilege of delivering a five-minute spiel _ time limits
strictly enforced _ to the 15 members of the panel, most of whom
did not show up.
</P>
<P>
   The competition is a rite of springtime in Washington, as
certain as the blooming of the cherry blossoms, and in recent years
it has hardly been polite. But with advances in biomedical research
spilling out of laboratories at an unprecedented pace, and talk
among lawmakers of doubling the budget for the National Institutes
of Health over the next five years, the faithful of Mother
Theresa's Waiting Room have cause for optimism, as well as
congeniality.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are no longer fighting amongst themselves,'' said Mary
Woolley, president of Research!America, a nonprofit advocacy group
that lobbies for more money for research. ``The disease groups are
not pitted against each other. This concept of robbing Peter to pay
Paul is one that I hope has been banished forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Or if not forever, then at least while the money holds out. For
1999, Congress gave the Institutes a $2 billion budget increase,
bringing the total budget to $15.6 billion. While President Clinton
has suggested a more modest hike for 2000, of $320 million, members
of both parties in Congress say they are hoping for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``My sense is that everyone feels that we are doing well and all
ships are rising with the incoming tide,'' said NIH Director Harold
Varmus. ``We're fairly happy campers right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Happy perhaps, but never completely content, as Tuesday's
hearing revealed. Doctors pleaded with the panel for more money for
research in general, and their interests in particular. ``In the
vernacular of Jerry Maguire, the movie, `More money, more money,
more money for NIH,' '' Dr. A. Paul Kelly, president of the
Association of Professors of Dermatology, told the panel.
</P>
<P>
   There is no similar public testimony session in the Senate, so
the hearings before the House Appropriations Committee's
Subcommittee on Labor, Health and Human Services and Education is
the only chance for patients to talk to appropriators in a public
forum. The session was laden with hearbreaking stories, most of
them carefully orchestrated to grab the attention of the media and,
more important, Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., who chairs the
subcommittee and was the only member to sit through the entire
hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Kimmitt Rainey, a Senate aide, testified about the
devastating loss of her son to Sudden Infant Death Syndrome in
1996. As she spoke, her new baby, a girl, squirmed in the stroller
beside her. ``I know that my personal story touched Chairman
Porter,'' she said afterward. ``I could see it in his eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Reeve, the actor who was paralyzed when he fell off
his horse, is on the docket for Wednesday. Doug Flutie, the
football player whose son is autistic, is also scheduled to appear.
Jim Kelly, the retired quarterback for the Buffalo Bills, testified
Tuesday, describing in wrenching detail the life of his
two-year-old son, Hunter, who suffers from Krabbe Disease, a rare
neurologic disorder. The child cannot move any part of his body on
his own. He has never smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been surrounded by tough individuals throughout my
entire career,'' Kelly said. ``But never have I witnessed more
strength and toughness than that of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity counts in the quest for research funding, but a tale
that can bring tears to the eyes counts even more, lobbyists say.
``I'll take my SIDS lady over any celebrity,'' said Dale Dirks, the
lobbyist who accompanied Mrs. Rainey. ``Because she's got a
compelling story to tell and she's a real person. And all of us
have kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Porter listened intently, seemingly taking the stories to heart.
To Mrs. Rainey, he confided that, as a new grandfather, he worries
about SIDS. When a doctor asked for more money for vision research,
he mentioned his mother-in-law has retinitis pigmentosa. He told a
representative from the Asthma and Allergy Foundation of America
that his sister has asthma.
</P>
<P>
   Because Congress does not appropriate money on a
disease-by-disease basis, the patient advocates are angling for a
brass ring with a more subtle effect: a mention in the report that
accompanies the subcommittee's bill. The NIH pays close attention
to the report, and how the committee parses its language can make
all the difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a code in the words,'' said Michael Stephens, a
former staff director for the subcommittee. ``They might say, `The
committee is aware of X disease. The committee urges that the
importance of this disease be reflected. And then, the most that
anybody ever gets: `Within the increase provided, X should be set
aside for this disease.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the hearings have taken on the tenor of a family
reunion. Committee staff members tell the story of the boy with a
disfiguring port wine stain on his face; one year, he showed up
with a clear complexion from laser surgery. For a time, an AIDS
patient came with his wife; when she didn't show up a few years
ago, nobody had to ask why.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, 17-year-old Erin Bosch, who suffers from a congenital
heart defect, appeared for the third time. She recently had surgery
to reduce the size of her enlarged heart, a procedure, she hastened
to tell Porter, that was pioneered with federal money. The
congressman brightened when he saw her; she took that as a good
sign. ``I feel like I make an impact,'' she said, ``when he
remembers me from year to year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1948EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0258 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6718 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414-C     04-13 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON SEEKS $4 BILLION FROM CONGRESS, AS NATO ESCALATES
BOMBING
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0414; KOSOVO-LOOTERS-0414.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. tab for waging war with Yugoslavia and
tending to its refugees could top $4 billion, the Pentagon said
Tuesday, as President Clinton said the addition of hundreds of
fresh warplanes would escalate the campaign ``to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   As the air war entered its fourth week, Clinton told
congressional leaders that he
</P>
<P>
   is prepared to continue the strikes for ``months'' if necessary,
noting that weather conditions have favored bombing during less
than half of the first 21 days of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also told the bipartisan gathering that he has not ruled
out sending ground forces into the embattled Yugoslav province of
Kovoso. He stressed, though, that he remains opposed to that
option, gave no indication that he is preparing for it in any way
and stressed that he would first give the expanding air campaign
far more time to take its toll on Serb forces in the field and the
regime in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not favor the use of ground forces, but he did say
that that option should not be taken off the table,'' said Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who was among the congressional leaders
attending the two-hour White House meeting. ``What was stated here
very clearly today, most importantly by the commander in chief, is
that this air campaign is going to go on for weeks and months, if
necessary, to achieve our objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark,
the supreme allied commander, said the troops reporting to Serb
leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, are
``vulnerable to collapse,'' and would come under ``greater and
greater,'' attack in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Milosevic) has an apparent high degree of willingness to
accept damage,'' Clark told reporters. ``But the damage he's going
to accept is going to be greater and greater and greater.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of 82 fresh U.S. warplanes en route to Europe
over the next several days, the NATO air armada assembled against
Yugoslavia has roughly doubled -- to nearly 700 aircraft -- since
the strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, has asked for 300 more fighters, bombers and support
aircraft, which the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff is expected to
approve within days.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said the additional
deployments would likely require the call-up of Air Force reserves
-- some of which are already flying refueling tanker missions -- as
well as civil service and Army reservists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 24 Apache attack helicopters are expected to be on
the ground and operational from a base near the Albanian capital of
Tirana as early as this weekend, said Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles
Wald, vice director for strategic plans and policy for the Joint
Chiefs. Wald declined to say whether Clark had asked for additional
helicopters in his most recent request.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would send Congress, over the next several days,
a request for emergency supplemental spending -- government
payments not already authorized in this year's budget -- to cover
the U.S. portion of the costs of the NATO air strikes and refugee
support operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number is not firm yet, but I would guess that it'll be in
the range of three-to-four billion dollars,'' Bacon said. ``It
could be over four billion.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bacon said, depending on how much longer the air
strikes continue and what shape additional elements to the campaign
might take, the war-fighting portion alone could well top $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That figure does not include regular salaries for the pilots and
soldiers involved in the NATO operation. Those payments are part of
the Pentagon's annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   The figure would be primarily to cover the premium such forces
receive for performing hazardous duty and for the costs of fuel,
bombs, cruise missiles and other sorts of materials being used for
the NATO mission.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there's the refugee assistance: nearly 800,000
meals, thousands of tents, tens of thousands of blankets, in
addition to hundreds of intercontinental flights of giant cargo
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea of the cost,'' Clark said. ``I suspect
it will be substantial, but I would suspect it will be far more
substantial for Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   In three weeks of strikes, Clark said, U.S. and allied pilots
have flown 5,924 sorties. Of those, 1,687 have been combat
missions. The rest have been refueling tankers -- flying roughly
2,000 sorties -- and reconnaissance and flight control aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   On 10 days out of the first 21 of the mission, Clark said, more
than half of the combat missions were scrubbed because of heavy
clouds and fog that concealed targets or restricted the
effectiveness of precision bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those constraints, NATO pilots and sea-launched cruise
missiles have destroyed roughly 200 bridges, headquarters
buildings, ammunition sites and other major targets, in addition to
scores of tanks, trucks and other military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated strikes on refineries and oil storage depots have
destroyed roughly 70 percent of the fuel supplies in Yugoslavia,
Clark said, a measure that has forced troops inside Kosovo to park
armored vehicles wherever they can be hidden and horde precious
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic indication of the vigilance with which NATO forces
are pursuing fuel sources, Wald, the air force general, showed
footage of an F-16 attack jet destroying a tanker truck on a
highway in Kosovo with a precision-guided bomb.
</P>
<P>
   With an unknown number -- U.S., NATO and United Nations
estimates run from 250,000 up to 700,000 -- of ethnic Albanians
hiding in remote mountains with minimal food and shelter, Clinton
said military planners were searching for ways to assist them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very large problem. We are aware of it,'' Clinton said
during remarks from the Rose Garden. ``We know what the obstacles
are, and we're doing our best to overcome them.''
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to rule out air drops, citing the danger such
missions would pose to NATO pilots and the possibility that aid
dropped by air for refugees would instead be taken by Serb troops
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
