<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6720 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-GIULIANI-HNS &LR;      04-13 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GIULIANI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI PRAISES BUSH'S LEADERSHIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By R.G. RATCLIFFE 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
Tuesday that critics of Gov. George W. Bush's foreign policy should
focus on Bush's leadership abilities, not the limits of his
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ronald Reagan was elected president of the United States,
one of the questions was: Did he have any foreign policy
experience?'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said Reagan proved as governor of California that
he had leadership qualities that would serve him well as president,
with policies carried through by President George Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the 12 years of the Reagan-Bush administration
and compare that to where our foreign policy is today, a lot of
Americans would say that maybe leadership is the real key to
whether you can handle foreign policy well,'' Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has undergone criticism recently for being slow to
articulate a policy on the military intervention in Kosovo and then
strengthening it through a series of statements.
</P>
<P>
   Bush guaranteed Americans that he will be ready to serve as
foreign policy leader if he becomes president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm up for the task,'' Bush said. ``When I swear in, I'll be
ready to assume the job.''
</P>
<P>
   But aides to rival Lamar Alexander questioned his overall depth
of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Rath, an Alexander adviser who is a former attorney general
of New Hampshire, complained of the ``halo effect'' around Bush's
governorship and questioned how much leadership could be learned
from being the Texas chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Texas governor is different from many others in terms of the
power,'' Rath said, alluding to the relatively limited
constitutional scope of the office.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kennedy, a national strategist for Alexander and former
Iowa Republican chairman, said Bush may approach issues such as
education with bite-size proposals like those advocated by the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a real threat they may start looking more like Clinton
Jr. than Bush Jr.,'' Kennedy told reporters. ``It's time to start
talking big again and dreaming bold.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani and Bush met at the Texas Governor's Mansion. While the
men spoke like a mutual admiration society, neither specifically
endorsed the other in their potential 2000 races.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani is exploring a possible race for New York's Republican
nomination to the U.S. Senate, while first lady Hillary Clinton is
looking at seeking the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be one of the great campaigns in the history of the
United States Senate the way the rumors are shaping up,'' Bush
said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said Bush could help lead the Republican Party back to
national victory. But Giuliani also praised New York Gov. George
Pataki, who is looking as a possible favorite-son candidacy for
president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was asked about his differences with Giuliani, who supports
abortion rights and gay rights. Bush is opposed to abortion and to
adoptions by gay parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good people can disagree on a variety of issues in the
Republican Party,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told Texas reporters that he realizes that his vow to stay
in the state until the Legislature ends its session May 31 has hurt
his presidential organizing in Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who say I'm late getting there, they are absolutely
correct,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
