<SLUG> BC-CHANDELIERS-ANTIQUES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVING UP THE CANDLE POWER  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Conn.)   (af)  
 By MITCHELL OWENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until the invention of electricity, the world was obsessed with
light: how to get it, how to increase it, how to use it. And no
century explored it with more style than the 18th.
</P>
<P>
   The Age of Reason was also the Age of Reflection. Chandeliers
dripped with cut-glass lusters, moldings glimmered with gold leaf.
Mirrors were placed behind blazing candles and opposite sunny,
full-length windows.
</P>
<P>
   And surprisingly, at least some chimney pieces of the day were
literally architectural jewels, studded, paved and highlighted with
paste diamonds (in other words, rhinestones).
</P>
<P>
   ``There was such a need to magnify the light candles gave out,''
said William Jay Iselin, a former Christie's associate who now
works with the eminent Paris antiquary Ariane Dandois. ``Anything
that could refract light, to up the candle power, so to speak, was
embraced.''
</P>
<P>
   Recently exhibited at the Palm Beach International Art and
Antiques Fair, one of Iselin and Ms. Dandois' most spectacular
finds is a formally carved, rhinestone-studded chimney piece, circa
1790.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of paste diamonds _ some classically clear, others a
murky, mysterious amber _ flicker across its surface, embedded in
painted copper panels of peacock-blue. Some of the rhinestones are
arranged into what appear to be palm trees or perhaps stylized
fountains. Others are formed into ovoid medallions and double
swags, their facets throwing off sparks of light as readily as a
river of solitaire diamonds around the throat of one of Thomas
Gainsborough's powdered beauties.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of such a fireplace in a crowded room, illuminated by
candles and a blazing fire, must have been like a late Georgian
version of a mirrored disco ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It probably would have been used in a small reception room or
a ladies' drawing room,'' said Iselin, who noted that the chimney
piece, which is about 12 feet high and 14 feet wide, is for sale at
$95,000. ``It's too delicate in appearance for a gala room or a
man's library.''
</P>
<P>
   As intriguing as the lavish use of rhinestones, however, is the
chimney piece's construction: each inset blue panel is made of
copper. Rhinestones were a rare enough decorative material 200
years ago, but painted copper panels were seen even less often. And
when they were used, most can be traced to George Brookshaw, a now
undeservedly obscure English decorative painter turned
cabinetmaker.
</P>
<P>
   Though his name rings no bells like that of his occupational
compatriots, Thomas Chippendale or Robert Adam, the Birmingham-born
Brookshaw (1751-1823) was immensely talented. Often mistaken for
the work of the highly collectible Italian artist Michelangelo
Pergolesi, his painted secretaries, commodes and, yes, chimney
pieces, were greatly admired by the Georgian cognoscenti, as much
for Brookshaw's exquisite paintwork _ wicker baskets overflowing
with flowers, usually executed on a white or ivory ground _ as for
their sometimes startlingly costly construction.
</P>
<P>
   An artist at heart, and apparently indifferent to the
inappropriateness of the materials he used, Brookshaw once
fashioned a commode of solid mahogany, only to obliterate the
costly wood under layers of painted flora. The Iselin-Dandois
chimney piece, however, is made of painted and gilded pine, which
indicates a certain amount of economical common sense on
Brookshaw's part.
</P>
<P>
   Costly or not, Brookshaw's creations ended up in some of
England's finest houses. The fifth Duke of Beaufort ordered one of
the cabinetmaker's marble chimney pieces, which is still at the
Somerset family seat, Badminton, in Gloucestershire.
</P>
<P>
   A variety of lesser but equally discerning connoisseurs also
patronized Brookshaw's establishment, at 48 Great Marlborough
Street in London, where he advertised classes in painting for
``ladies of fashion'' as well as for the Prince of Wales, later
George IV, who commissioned at least one commode for Carlton House,
his Frenchified London bachelor pad, in 1783.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, mysterious financial reverses spelled the doom of
George Brookshaw's furniture business after only 20 years or so.
After a period of purposeful anonymity, during which he adopted
multiple aliases, Brookshaw resurfaced, this time as a master
engraver of botanical books like ``Pomona Britannica'' and ``A New
Treatise on Flower Painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Brookshaw's output as a cabinetmaker is limited, choice
pieces, like the rhinestoned chimney piece, continue to show up and
be admired. But not every (rhine)stone has been left unturned,
apparently: Iselin and Ms. Dandois' rarity may not be the only one
of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Though identified vaguely as an ``Adam-style fireplace'' in the
October issue of House and Garden, a Brookshaw chimney piece
appears to grace the living room of Crown Prince Pavlos of Greece
and his American wife, Marie-Chantal, in Greenwich, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   All the evidence is there: inset copper panels, rhinestones
gathered into sparkling swags, palmlike panaches and concentric
ovals. But the royal couple's treasure has been smothered under an
oily layer of spinach-green lacquer. With some gentle coaxing with
paint remover, another example of Brookshaw's singular genius may
once again come to light.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
