<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-BUSH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI VISITS BUSH BUT NEITHER MAKES ENDORSEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ New York Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani on Tuesday
encouraged Gov. George W. Bush to run for president, but he stopped
short of formally endorsing him, noting that another Republican
governor is considering a White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's one of the real stars of the party,'' Giuliani
said after meeting with Bush at the Governor's Mansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe it would be a good thing for the country and a good
thing for the party,'' Giuliani said of a Bush candidacy. ``He has
an ability to unify that the Republican Party, that any party,
would need.''
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani did not give Bush his political blessing _ a formal
endorsement. In New York, fellow Republican Gov. George Pataki also
is considering a run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to see who runs first before you can make a
choice about that,'' Giuliani said. ``Governor Pataki hasn't
decided whether he will run. But as I said before, Governor Pataki
would make a fine candidate for president. ... He's been an
enormously successful governor.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The more very good candidates we have, the better off the
party's going to be,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, a Republican who has sometimes run afoul of his party,
is considering running for the Senate in New York next year. That
race may turn out to be as high-profile as the presidential
campaign if first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton decides to run on the
Democratic Party ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'd make an excellent (Senate) candidate,'' Bush said
of the mayor. ``It could be one of the great campaigns in the
history of the United States Senate, the way the rumors are shaping
up.''
</P>
<P>
   But the governor also didn't provide a formal endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I imagine I'm going to be focusing on my own race, but he's a
good guy, I like him,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush wouldn't say if he would tap Giuliani as a running
mate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the first thing I've got to do is get the nomination,
should I decide to run,'' he said. ``It's too early to be talking
about the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has formed an exploratory committee, which so far has
raised an estimated $7 million. He has pledged not to make a
decision about the presidency until the state Legislature wraps up
its current session in May.
</P>
<P>
   After the session, he will travel to different parts of the
United States before making a final decision on whether to
officially enter the race. He is expected to be in Iowa on June 12
to help raise money for Republican Rep. Greg Ganske.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at it, nothing is set in stone at this point,''
said Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker. ``We will be traveling to Iowa
in June. We're in the process of nailing down the particulars. It
probably will be that day (June 12).''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he will visit New York, but he doesn't know when.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to go up there; it's a very important state,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   During their visit Tuesday, Giuliani said he told the governor
that a Republican could win in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although, it's seen very often as a Democratic stronghold,
Republicans can win,'' he said, noting his success as well as
Pataki's.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe he would be a very strong and competitive candidate
in Yew York, and of course every poll that's been taken indicates
exactly the same thing,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
