<SLUG> BC-OBIT-WILSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THORNTON WILSON, 78, EX-BOEING CEO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo.)   (bl)  
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Thornton A. Wilson, a former chairman and chief executive of
Boeing Co., died April 10 at his home in Palm Springs, Calif. He
was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, died in his sleep and was found by members of his
family, said Peter Conte, a spokesman for Boeing. The cause of
death remains unknown, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, nicknamed T, retired in 1987 after 42 years with Boeing.
He was best known for developing and producing the Boeing 757 and
767 jetliners. He was also remembered for guiding the company
through a painful reorganization in the late '60s and early '70s,
laying off 60,000 workers during what became known as the Boeing
Bust.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts, which came in the wake of slow aircraft sales and
Congress' cancellation of the supersonic-transport, or SST,
program, devastated the Seattle area, where Boeing is based. But
the company was slowly revived over the next two decades; it now
employs 218,000 people worldwide, including about 90,000 in the
Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was born in Sikeston, Mo., on Feb. 8, 1921, and graduated
from Iowa State University in 1943 with a degree in aeronautical
engineering. He joined Boeing that year, leaving briefly for a
teaching assignment and advanced study at Iowa State and a year at
California Institute of Technology, where he earned a master's
degree in aeronautical engineering in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   He also became overall project engineer of the B-52 bomber
program during the latter stages of its design and then led the
proposal team that won the contract for the Minuteman
intercontinental ballistic missile.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson was elected vice president of Boeing in 1963 and in 1964
was placed in charge of operations and planning for its corporate
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he was named executive vice president. He
became company president in 1968 and chief executive a year later.
He remained in that position until 1983. He became chairman of the
board in 1972 and stayed in that post until 1987. He became
chairman emeritus and continued to serve as a member of the board
until April 1993.
</P>
<P>
   A close friend, Dean Thornton, described Wilson as
unpretentious, decisive and clearly in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could make the hard decisions,'' said Thornton, who worked
as president of the Boeing commercial airplane group and an
executive vice president of Boeing Co. in the late '80s and early
'90s. ``You never had much question about who was the boss.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson received numerous awards and honors during his career,
and, in 1983, he was inducted into the National Aviation Hall of
Fame for his engineering and managerial accomplishments with
Boeing. And in 1987, the Museum of Flight in Seattle named a new
143,000-square-foot gallery after Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson is survived by his wife, Grace, and three children,
Thornton A. Wilson III of Seattle, Daniel A. Wilson of Newcastle,
Wash., and Sarah W. Parkinson of Enumclaw, Wash., and six
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6730 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ASTEROID-WORLD-BOS &LR;      04-13 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASTEROID-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST EARTH-BOUND ASTEROID BEING REPORTED CAREFULLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a discovery eerily reminescent of one made just a year ago,
astronomers have found an asteroid that will be coming quite close
to Earth in a few decades, and that even has a real but minuscule
possibility of an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Last year astronomers made a similar discovery of an asteroid
that had a slight possibility of hitting Earth in about 40 years.
In that case, it quickly turned out the Earth was safe after all,
and astronomers have been arguing ever since about the way that
report was disseminated. Now, another very similar, possibly
threatening, asteroid has been discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The object, called 1999 AN10, was described in a detailed
scientific paper posted on a website by three astronomers. But
unlike last year's case, no information has been sent out directly
to the public and the press.
</P>
<P>
   The asteroid is thought to be about a mile in diameter _ similar
to the one last year _ and could possibly come very close to Earth
in 2039. There is even about a one-in-a-billion chance that it
could strike the Earth that year, with devastating consequences.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, don't panic. That's actually less than the risk that
an unknown asteroid or comet might hit Earth on any given day, and
therefore is not anything to be too concerned about. What might be
more worrisome is its long-term potential.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 600 years, according to astronomers Andrea Milani,
Steven Chesley and Giovanni Valsecchi, the asteroid could remain
very close to Earth, and if it comes close enough to be affected by
Earth's gravity its orbit could become so chaotic that it is
impossible to predict for more than a decade or two ahead. In that
case, it could require constant, careful monitoring for centuries
to guard against a possible impact.
</P>
<P>
   This is only the second time in history _ or perhaps the first
time, depending on whose analysis of last year's discovery you
believe _ that an asteroid has been discovered that has a small but
non-zero possibility of striking the Earth within a few decades.
Even though the actual likelihood is vanishingly small, that makes
it an interesting find. Some people have questioned the wisdom of
the changes in the way such information is disseminated as a result
of what many astronomers considered a serious public embarrassment
last year.
</P>
<P>
   British anthropologist Benny Peiser, who has written extensively
about the effects of past impacts on the Earth, Tuesday circulated
an e-mail message questioning the fact that this discovery, unlike
last year's, has not been the subject of any public announcement or
press release. While acknowledging that the risk is tiny and not
something that anyone should lose any sleep over, Peiser said he
found the lack of public notice disturbing, suggesting that it
reflects an overreaction to astronomers' embarrassment about last
year's announcement followed by a swift reversal.
</P>
<P>
   But astronomers contacted Tuesday said that in fact, they see
this as a perfect example of how such information should be
handled. The astronomers who made the calculations of impact
probabilities have circulated their unpublished paper to several
colleagues around the world who specialize in such calculations, in
order to make sure their conclusions are correct. Some astronomers
contacted Tuesday said that all the comments so far from such
specialists have been positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I commend them for the process of being careful,'' said
Richard Binzel, an astronomer at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology who specializes in asteroids. Many astronomers felt that
last year's press release about an asteroid called XF11 was
premature and caused unnecessary public alarm.
</P>
<P>
   Binzel stressed the very low odds of an impact predicted by
Milani and his colleagues. Binzel has suggested the use of a hazard
scale that would allow all such discoveries to be given a simple
classification, similar to the Richter scale for earthquakes, to
allow people to judge their seriousness. ``On a scale of zero to
5,'' he said, ``this thing is a zero.''
</P>
<P>
   And astronomer David Morrison of the NASA Ames Research Center
said that there was no reason for this finding to be disseminated
publicly. Last year the asteroid in question was still visible in
the sky for a few more weeks and it was important to alert
astronomers around the world to make every possible observation of
it to pin down the orbit, but in this case the asteroid is already
in a part of the sky where it cannot be observed for months, so
there is no such urgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing to do, even if we thought it was dangerous,''
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 1959EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS &LR;      04-13 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURY MAY GET REVAMP IN WAKE OF PROPERTY SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- Massachusetts' Abandoned Property Division will get
some unwanted attention this week as discontent mounts with its
handling of some $100 million in unclaimed assets.
</P>
<P>
   The treasury division is supposed to try to match rightful
owners with their lost property, everything from jewelry stashed in
a forgotten safe deposit box to stocks left moldering in brokerage
accounts to gift certificates customers never redeemed at
retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But businesses that must deal often with the division are fed
up, saying the process is time-consuming and not effective. The
businesses, including banks, financial services companies, and
hospitals, are set to file a flurry of bills that would:
</P>
<P>
   --Narrow the definition of abandoned assets.
</P>
<P>
   --Impose a three-year statute of limitations, after which the
assets would not have to be turned over.
</P>
<P>
   --Prohibit the use of outside ``bounty hunters'' to audit
businesses' books in search of unclaimed belongings.
</P>
<P>
   --Establish an appeals process to dispute such audit findings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant issue,'' said David Floreen, senior vice
president of the Massachusetts Bankers Association, a sponsor of
one of the bills.
</P>
<P>
   The public, meanwhile, is not being well served, state officials
concede.
</P>
<P>
   Even with $100 million sitting in the abandoned property
account, only 3 percent of all businesses in Massachusetts are
complying with system's rules governing how to turn over assets to
the treasury, officials have found. State Auditor Joseph DeNucci
last month issued a scathing report on the division. He cited,
among pages of other concerns, a Beacon Hill vault strewn with
items that treasury employees had never logged.
</P>
<P>
   And even state Treasurer Shannon P. O'Brien is grappling with
logisitical and staffing problems associated with the division,
which on Sunday will publish its largest annual list ever, with the
names of more than 38,000 people thought to have assets in the
account.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday O'Brien is scheduled to announce a task force aimed at
fixing many of the problems, although she disagrees with some of
the changes pushed by the business community because she believes
they would impinge on personal property rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned that some of business's bills might go
too far,'' O'Brien said.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors of the bills say they are not trying to play off
publicity generated by the alleged thefts of nearly $9 million from
a related treasury account known as the Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they say legislation was filed before that scam came to
light in February. They say the division under former treasurer
Joseph D. Malone was too aggressive in searching out languishing
assets but not so in looking for the owners. Instead, Malone, with
political fanfare, would turn over unclaimed property to the
state's general fund.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prior treasurer sort of expanded this program of going
after abandoned property and pushed the envelope. Stuff they never
went after before, such as unredeemed gift certificates, credit
receipts, account receivables . . . could now be considered
abandoned property,'' said Donald Baldini, senior vice president
for legislative policy at the Associated Industries of
Massachusetts, which has sponsored a bill to overhaul the system.
</P>
<P>
   Malone could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   AIM wants to narrow the definition of abandoned property,
excluding such things as credit balances between, say, a vendor and
a manufacturing company. The group, which represents 5,000 members,
also wants to impose a three-year limit on record searching done by
freelance bounty hunters that paid a percentage of their find by
the treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Baldini said current law does not provide a clear statute of
limitations. ``They can go back as far as they want and allege that
abandoned property was not turned over,'' Baldini said.
</P>
<P>
   AIM believes those bounty hunters should be paid an hourly rate
or flat fee, rather than a percentage, to discourage overzealous
searches. And the group wants an appeals process established.
</P>
<P>
   There are few rules governing the bounty hunters, and no
mechanism for investigating disputes between industry and those who
seek to profit from turning assets over to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Bounty hunters are different from ``heir finders,'' two of which
were implicated in the Unpaid Check Fund scam. Bounty hunters turn
property over to the state for a percentage of the take. Heir
finders try to find the rightful owners of that property for as
much as a 30 percent fee. Money from the Unpaid Check Fund is
supposed to be transferred to the Abandoned Property Division after
one year.
</P>
<P>
   Property is generally considered abandoned if it is left dormant
for three years. There are exceptions to that rule. Safe deposit
boxes have a seven-year time frame. And traveler's checks can be
dormant for 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   Hospitals have their own concerns in turning over pre-payments
for services after a patient has died.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not really talking about rings and watches, which is
what everybody thinks,'' said a spokeswoman for the Massachusetts
Hospital Association.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2004EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0269 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6736 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414-1     04-13 1165
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRIKES-0414-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: adds new 23rd, 24th grafs on Serb troops crossing Albanian
border
 &HT;    CLINTON SEEKS $4 BILLION FROM CONGRESS, AS NATO ESCALATES
BOMBING
 &HT;    With KOSOVO-REFUGEES-0414; KOSOVO-LOOTERS-0414.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. tab for waging war with Yugoslavia and
tending to its refugees could top $4 billion, the Pentagon said
Tuesday, as President Clinton said the addition of hundreds of
fresh warplanes would escalate the campaign ``to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   As the air war entered its fourth week, Clinton told
congressional leaders that he
</P>
<P>
   is prepared to continue the strikes for ``months'' if necessary,
noting that weather conditions have favored bombing during less
than half of the first 21 days of the mission.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also told the bipartisan gathering that he has not ruled
out sending ground forces into the embattled Yugoslav province of
Kovoso. He stressed, though, that he remains opposed to that
option, gave no indication that he is preparing for it in any way
and stressed that he would first give the expanding air campaign
far more time to take its toll on Serb forces in the field and the
regime in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does not favor the use of ground forces, but he did say
that that option should not be taken off the table,'' said Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., who was among the congressional leaders
attending the two-hour White House meeting. ``What was stated here
very clearly today, most importantly by the commander in chief, is
that this air campaign is going to go on for weeks and months, if
necessary, to achieve our objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark,
the supreme allied commander, said the troops reporting to Serb
leader Slobodan Milosevic, president of Yugoslavia, are
``vulnerable to collapse,'' and would come under intensifying
attacks in the days ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Milosevic) has an apparent high degree of willingness to
accept damage,'' Clark told reporters. ``But the damage he's going
to accept is going to be greater and greater and greater.''
</P>
<P>
   With the addition of 82 fresh U.S. warplanes en route to Europe
over the next several days, the NATO air armada assembled against
Yugoslavia has roughly doubled -- to nearly 700 aircraft -- since
the strikes began March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Clark has asked for 300 more fighters, bombers and support
aircraft, which the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff is expected to
approve within days.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth H. Bacon said the additional
deployments would likely require the call-up of Air Force reserves
-- some of which are already flying refueling tanker missions -- as
well as civil service and Army reservists.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 24 Apache attack helicopters are expected to be on
the ground and operational from a base near the Albanian capital of
Tirana as early as this weekend, said Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles
Wald, vice director for strategic plans and policy for the Joint
Chiefs. Wald declined to say whether Clark had asked for additional
helicopters in his most recent request.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he would send Congress, over the next several days,
a request for emergency supplemental spending -- government
payments not already authorized in this year's budget -- to cover
the U.S. portion of the costs of the NATO air strikes and refugee
support operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The number is not firm yet, but I would guess that it'll be in
the range of three-to-four billion dollars,'' Bacon said. ``It
could be over four billion.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bacon said, depending on how much longer the air
strikes continue and what shape additional elements to the campaign
might take, the war-fighting portion alone could well top $4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   That figure does not include regular salaries for the pilots and
soldiers involved in the NATO operation. Those payments are part of
the Pentagon's annual budget.
</P>
<P>
   The figure would be primarily to cover the premium such forces
receive for performing hazardous duty and for the costs of fuel,
bombs, cruise missiles and other sorts of materials being used for
the NATO mission.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, there's the refugee assistance: nearly 800,000
meals, thousands of tents, tens of thousands of blankets, in
addition to hundreds of intercontinental flights of giant cargo
aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any idea of the cost,'' Clark said. ``I suspect
it will be substantial, but I would suspect it will be far more
substantial for Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   In three weeks of strikes, Clark said, U.S. and allied pilots
have flown 5,924 sorties. Of those, 1,687 have been combat
missions. The rest have been refueling tankers -- flying roughly
2,000 sorties -- and reconnaissance and flight control aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   On 10 days out of the first 21 of the mission, Clark said, more
than half of the combat missions were scrubbed because of heavy
clouds and fog that concealed targets or restricted the
effectiveness of precision bombs.
</P>
<P>
   Despite those constraints, NATO pilots and sea-launched cruise
missiles have destroyed roughly 200 bridges, headquarters
buildings, ammunition sites and other major targets, in addition to
scores of tanks, trucks and other military vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated strikes on refineries and oil storage depots have
destroyed roughly 70 percent of the fuel supplies in Yugoslavia,
Clark said, a measure that has forced troops inside Kosovo to park
armored vehicles wherever they can be hidden and horde precious
fuel.
</P>
<P>
   In a dramatic indication of the vigilance with which NATO forces
are pursuing fuel sources, Wald, the air force general, showed
footage of an F-16 attack jet destroying a tanker truck on a
highway in Kosovo with a precision-guided bomb.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO forces continued to pound Serb positions on the ground,
Albanian authorities said roughly 50 Serb infantrymen crossed over
that country's mountainous border with Kosovo and briefly seized
the village of Kamenica, about one mile inside Albanian territory.
Albanian troops drove the Serbs back after an hour and a half of
fighting, Tirana reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, officials denied that Serb forces had fought their
way into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   With an unknown number -- U.S., NATO and United Nations
estimates run from 250,000 up to 700,000 -- of ethnic Albanians
hiding in remote mountains with minimal food and shelter, Clinton
said military planners were searching for ways to assist them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a very large problem. We are aware of it,'' Clinton said
during remarks from the Rose Garden. ``We know what the obstacles
are, and we're doing our best to overcome them.''
</P>
<P>
   He appeared to rule out air drops, citing the danger such
missions would pose to NATO pilots and the possibility that aid
dropped by air for refugees would instead be taken by Serb troops
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
