<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6738 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     04-13 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFERMAN OFF TO A DRIVING START 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- It is the lament of many Boston ballplayers. They
arrive in the Hub, rent a place, get a car, and attempt to drive to
work. Approaching the ballyard, they see the light towers, but
still they cannot get to Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Offerman tripled to knock in two runs in Tuesday's 6-0
home-opening victory over the White Sox. He is 15 for 32 (.469) at
the plate this season, but 0 for 2 at finding Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drive twice and get lost twice,'' Offerman said after
Tuesday's nifty victory. ``Yesterday and today. I don't know. I
look and I see and it looks like I'm going the right way . . .''
</P>
<P>
   And before he can say, ``Charlie on the MTA,'' the Fenway light
towers are in his rear-view mirror.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox don't play Wednesday, but Jose has a plan for Thursday.
He's meeting Red Sox traveling secretary Jack McCormick at the
Hilltop Steak House off Route 3 in Braintree. He'll follow
McCormick _ Braintree to Big Dig to Fenway. The road-rage answer to
Tinker to Evers to Chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easier than trying to explain how to get here from
there,'' said McCormick.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman hasn't had any trouble finding his way around the bases
in his short Red Sox career. He had at least two hits in each of
the Sox first six (road) games, and came home to a hero's welcome.
Fans applauded madly when he was introduced before the game. Many
stood. One fellow, Joe Lewizke, an engineer at the Foxboro Company,
wore a gray sweatshirt that said, ``Mo Who?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jose Offerman really came here against a lot of odds,''
explained Lewizke. ``He had tough shoes to fill and he's done a
great job. It's amazing how quickly things can turn around.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Maligned Sox general manager Dan Duquette is having a
better week than the person who bought the winning lottery ticket
at Star Market. The Duke sits smugly, offering only standard
Dukespeak, while Mo Vaughn (0 for 2) limps around the Angel
clubhouse on crutches and Offerman sprays the ball and runs the
bases like Roberto Clemente.
</P>
<P>
   It would be hard to find anyone who predicted this scenario.
</P>
<P>
   There was laughter coast-to-coast when the Duke signed Offerman
to a four-year, $26 million contract and said he could replace Mo's
``on-base capability.'' Other general managers were mortified by
the signing and Offerman became a target for standup comics,
columnists, and talk-radio callers.
</P>
<P>
   There was great titillation in these parts (much of it from
yours truly) about the prospect of Duke squirming when fans booed
Jose and Mo returned to Fenway as the American League's All-Star
first baseman.
</P>
<P>
   We joked about the beginning of the ``Jose Offerman Era.'' The
switch-hitting slasher was destined to be one of those guys who
never had a chance with the Boston fandom. Remember Stan Papi? He
was ridiculed because he came in a trade for popular Bill Lee. More
recently, nice guy Pete Carroll has been pummeled because he is the
antithesis of predecessor Bill Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like the same deal for Offerman until his
tour-de-bases through Kansas City and St. Petersburg. By the time
the Sox completed their 5-1 road trip, Boston fans were ready to
embrace Offerman as the poster child for the new,
pitching-speed-and-defense, ``go-go'' Red Sox.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked again in the home opener. After taking a called third
strike in the first inning, Offerman came up with two on and two
out in the third and cracked a triple to the triangle in center. It
was his third triple of the season (he led the American League with
13 three-baggers last year).
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought the ball was gonna travel that much,'' said
the 30-year-old Dominican. ``Then I saw it and I thought I had a
good chance to get at least a triple.''
</P>
<P>
   And thus a cult hero was born. For now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited what I am doing right now,'' said Offerman. ``I
like to start this way.''
</P>
<P>
   He handled the ``What about Mo?'' question with the same
deftness he displayed throughout spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever understands this game has to understand that there's
no comparison,'' said Offerman. ``I can't compare myself to Mo
Vaughn. We do different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Things might be different by July if the Sox sag and a power
outage pulls the plug on their wild card hopes. But seven games
into the 1999 season, Offerman is hitting .469, the Red Sox are
6-1, and a fan is cheered when he wears a ``Mo Who?'' shirt on
Opening Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to feel the fans feel that way,'' said Offerman. ``I
feel happy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was not a perfect Fenway opener for Offerman. After
the game, he had to drive home to Braintree in the afternoon rush
hour. And we know that when you play for the Red Sox, sometimes
just driving home is tougher than driving home runs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
