<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6739 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INFO-TECHNOLOGY-COX     04-13 0836
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INFO-TECHNOLOGY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AIIM conference kicks off in Atlanta
 &HT;    By Tatiana Lichnerova and Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The magician's patter was mostly lost in the boom of
competing spectacles, but he continued gamely on.
</P>
<P>
   He groped for the obligatory bunny, taking the animal from his
equally inevitable female assistant, smiling, but silent at his
side. The bunny went into a box _ to be scanned, the magician said.
And by turning the faux crank on the front of the box, he produced
a flattened paper version of the rabbit then showed an open box to
prove the flesh and blood version was gone. Moments later, he went
to another box, pumped in the ``scanned'' picture, then opened the
container to show the rabbit.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beneath the banner proclaiming the magic of Ohio-based
Cranel Inc., the magician's grin was persistent as his assistant
skittered away with the hapless bunny.
</P>
<P>
   Crowd noise, music and seemingly dozens of emcees with
microphones competed for attention. And this wasn't even the only
magician. Not far away, another trickster boldly did card tricks,
his moves duplicated on a large screen above his stage. Passing by
were what looked like a group of high school cheerleaders. On
another nearby stage stood a young man dressed in apparent
imitation of a stereotypical 1950s greaser. There were booths for
companies hailing from Atlanta, from Palo Alto, from Madrid, from
Stuttgart. Among them the crowd streamed. Like stones in the flow,
here are there stood another patron was pulling out a cellular
phone.
</P>
<P>
   It was, in short, another one of those high-tech conferences
that bring hundreds of thousands of people to Atlanta each year.
</P>
<P>
   This one is the Association for Information and Image Management
International, which began in earnest Tuesday at the World Congress
Center as the exhibition floor opened and a high-ranking executive
from America Online gave the keynote. This morning, the featured
speaker will be Linus Torvalds, inventor of Linux, the little
operating system that is starting to to scare mighty Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   About 35,000 information technology specialists were expected to
attend, according to AIIM conference officials. As they wandered
the aisles Tuesday, they could be forgiven for occasionally being
distracted by the sideshows and the noise.
</P>
<P>
   This was about technology and business.
</P>
<P>
   And there was software and hardware, toys for the mundane
corporate purpose, as well as the deep-pocketed consumer whim. For
instance, you might look at the Pioneer New Media Technologies
booth and recall that you have been thinking of putting together
your own movie, something that would include your own video clips,
pictures, and data files. The only thing you need is a recordable
DVD drive. And about $5,400. Oh, and about $40 for each blank DVD
that you want to record on.
</P>
<P>
   Pioneer offers the DVR-S201, a device that can store up to 4.7
gigabytes of data _ the equivalent of seven compact discs _ it can
record more than two hours of video. It can store important data by
the boatload and is mainly pitched toward small companies that make
industrial multimedia or presentation materials, but like many
techno-toys, it seems likely to trickle down to consumers sooner or
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a huge backlog of orders for this thing,'' said Brad
Roseborough, senior manager for Pioneer. ``By June, they ought to
be shipping in larger quantities.''
</P>
<P>
   DVD discs may not replace CDs quickly, but when they do, it
seems it will be for keeps. The life expectancy of DVDs is about
100 years, if they are treated well, compared to less than half
that for CDs, Roseborough said.
</P>
<P>
   Over at the Meta4 booth, consultant Gabriel Duaso was
demonstrating ``knowledge management'' software meant to enhance
productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Meta4, whose North American headquarters are in Atlanta, makes
systems that are meant to assess the expertise of a company's
workers and keep that information updated. Documents that a worker
uses can be evaluated and then ranked so that the next person
looking for help can quickly see which to read.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just one person,'' Duaso said. ``It's the democracy
of the company.'' Across the exhibition floor, Robert Foley, vice
president of Maryland-based CereSoft, touted systems that can read
handwriting _ turning near-scribbles into digital data.
</P>
<P>
   Selling for $9,000 and up, the system is particularly useful for
insurance companies and government agencies that must sift through
thousands of forms filled in by human beings, each with a script
using something less than perfectly crafted letters. Through
mathematical algorithms, all but the worst writing can be
translated into data _ digital, readable and manipulable, Foley
said.
</P>
<P>
   And the technology is still getting better.
</P>
<P>
   ``In three years, you'll see teller machines where you can put a
check in and cash it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
