<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6740 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      04-13 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN, ON THE LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- A pitching line sometimes tells you all you need to
know. If you see that a Roger Clemens or a Kerry Wood has a ``0''
under the BB and a ``20'' under the SO, you don't need a doctorate
in Moundology to know that someone has thrown a spectacular game.
</P>
<P>
   Merely studying Bret Saberhagen's line from Tuesday, though,
doesn't give you an understanding of just what type of thoroughly
professional pitching performance it was. It is a pretty good line,
too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
IP &UR;  &LR; ! H ! R ! E ! BB ! SO &QL; 
6 2/3 !  &UR;  &LR; 6 ! 0 ! 0 !  &UR;  &LR; 3 ! 5 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What it does not reveal are the 22 pitches in the first inning
and the 26 in the second. It doesn't tell you about the
bases-loaded mess in the first and the two-on, one-out jam in the
second. It doesn't explain how out of sync he was to begin with, or
how he managed to keep the White Sox from scoring while he was
trying to figure out why he was so uncomfortable out there. It
doesn't make it clear that only an intelligent veteran pitcher
could have dealt with the early circumstances well enough to last 6
2/3 innings and become the winning pitcher in a 6-0 Red Sox Opening
Day victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself lucky to get out of those first two
innings,'' said Saberhagen, who, two starts and 12 2/3 innings into
his 16th major league season is carrying a 0.00 run average, earned
or otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Did he say lucky? Not quite. Luck, Branch Rickey always told us,
is ``the residue of design.'' That wasn't luck. That was
intelligence. That was experience. That was, well, pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't panic,'' pointed out pitching coach Joe Kerrigan.
``It's the self-discipline to believe in yourself. You're trying to
work through this and find your mechanics.''
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen is a man who prides himself on being able to put the
baseball exactly where he wants it (how about 13 walks in 177 1/3
innings in 1994?), and in the first couple of innings Tuesday, the
ball was disobedient. Behind this guy. Behind that guy. A base hit
by Ray Durham to lead off the game. A walk to Frank Thomas. A walk
to Magglio Ordonez. What was going on?
</P>
<P>
   ``Bad mechanics,'' Saberhagen explained.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, bad mechanics. That's solvable. Pain would be something
else, and that was the good news. These days, Saberhagen is feeling
no pain in his reconstructed right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like last year,'' he said. ``This year, all I have to
do is think about how to get out this particular hitter, and I
haven't been able to do just that for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   It took two innings to figure things out. There would be a
between-innings videotape viewing. There would be a consultation
with noted expert Pedro Martinez. The conclusion? ``I was rushing
myself,'' he decided.
</P>
<P>
   While all this was going on, there was the matter of the five
baserunners and the long counts. He was the proverbial one pitch
away from big trouble in the first and second innings. That pitch
never came. What did come were very much-needed called third
strikes to Jeff Liefer and Paul Konerko in the first and to Durham
and Mike Caruso in the second.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he makes a bad pitch,'' explained catcher Jason Varitek,
``that doesn't mean he can't make the next pitch a great pitch.
That's what a Cy Young winner can do.''
</P>
<P>
   When he took the mound in the third, it was with a 3-0 lead,
courtesy of a two-run triple by Jose ``Maybe I Should Renegotiate''
Offerman and an RBI single by Darren Lewis. A veteran pitcher knows
what must be done in that situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never want to give any runs back after your team has
scored,'' confirmed Saberhagen. And he didn't. The Chicago third
went as follows: Thomas fly ball, Liefer ground out, Ordonez caught
looking. Saberhagen was in command.
</P>
<P>
   They never really touched him after the second. Although the
third was his only 1-2-3 inning, he thereafter did not allow more
than one baserunner per inning, departing with two away in the
seventh after Caruso dumped his 102d pitch into center field for a
harmless single.
</P>
<P>
   Do the math. He threw 48 pitches in the first two innings. He
threw 54 pitches in the next 4 2/3 innings. That's the Bret
Saberhagen he likes to see in the mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, indeed. The White Sox were looking at the full package.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first few innings, I wasn't able to get my breaking ball
over,'' he said. ``I couldn't even throw my fastball for strikes.
Then I was throwing my fastball and curve to lefties and fastball
and change to righties. After that, I started throwing the change
to the lefties and the curve to the righties. When you mix it up
like that, they can't just look for two pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the where is just as important as the what.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's fun to catch,'' said Varitek, ``because he loves to throw
inside and they know he means it. When someone can come inside like
that, it gives you so many more options.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a man who missed an entire season (1996) after Mets team
physician David Altchek performed radical reconstruction surgery on
his right shoulder. This is a two-time Cy Young Award winner who
went through the tedious and lonely rehab process and who
painstakingly worked his way back with minor league stints in
Lowell, Trenton, and Pawtucket. This is a man who won the Sporting
News American League Comeback Player of the Year award last year
while pitching the entire season in pain from what he refers to as
an ``impingement'' in his shoulder. And now this is a man who says
he is like a ``kid in a candy store'' because the scar tissue in
his shoulder is broken up, and he can pitch without discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   A healthy Bret Saberhagen has always been a winning major league
pitcher. If there is any candy being dispensed, it's the poison
variety he has been serving up to American League batters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
