</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PLANS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lawmakers: U.S. plans aimless
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _Walking through a refugee camp in Macedonia last
week, Rep. Saxby Chambliss (R-Ga.) was struck by the number of
signs on each tent listing the names and hometowns of a multitude
of missing family members.
</P>
<P>
   Those handwritten cardboard signs waving in the wind served as a
potent reminder to Chambliss of how many families have been torn
apart by the three-week-old war.
</P>
<P>
   Inside the tents at the Brazda-Stankovic camp near the Kosovo
border, Chambliss heard story after story about the Yugoslav Army
busting into homes and ordering families to flee at gun point. The
refugees told him how men had been arbitrarily separated from their
families and never heard from again. How children barely as tall as
his knee cap were ordered by the Serbian military to walk for days.
</P>
<P>
   The stories Chambliss heard at the hastily erected refugee camp
only strengthened his belief that Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic is a ``Balkan thug and international murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   But it also reinforced his frustration with the way the Clinton
Administration has handled war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this administration has a plan for how to get
out,'' said Chambliss, a member of the House Armed Services
Committee. He said the Clinton Administration also erred by telling
the American public that ground troops would not be considered as
an option when they may have to be called upon.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss is opposed to using ground troops at the moment,
citing Kosovo's mountainous terrain and the determination of the
Serbian forces to defend their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would run the risk of losing many, many soldiers,''
Chambliss said. ``But by the same token, I think it is a mistake
for the administration to carry out a military operation without a
contingency plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss notes that the United States has ``never been involved
in an operation where we have achieved a military victory without
ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss predicted that Congress would oppose the use of ground
troops without three things: a clear and defined objective of what
will be accomplished; a clear and defined exit strategy; and an
invitation from all of the NATO member countries to send troops.
</P>
<P>
   Chambliss visited the camp with House Armed Services Chairman
Floyd Spence (R-S.C.) and fellow committee member Rep. Lindsey
Graham (R-S.C.)
</P>
<P>
   The trio visited six countries in nine days to assess NATO air
strikes in Yugoslavia and Kosovo. It was an emotional journey that
left all three visibly moved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can walk away from the camps without having
a heavy heart for what the Kosovar Albanians are going through,''
Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   But Graham, like Chambliss, said he is not convinced that the
right way out to defeat Milosevic is to send American troops to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``A ground war is politically unfeasible and militarily
unwise,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to be successful we need to expand the target
list and aggressively pursue the air campaign,'' Graham said. ``We
must give our pilots and military planners more discretion over
target selection and carrying out the mission.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned that politics and bureaucracy are getting in the
way of the bombing campaign,'' Graham said. ``Our pilots and airmen
are being put at undue risk in an effort to minimize collateral
damage. While losses can be minimized, we cannot make war
pain-free. Soldiers are trained to kill and break things. We must
not let a 'zero-collateral damage policy' prevent us from executing
our air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Carr writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
