<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6743 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STEALTH-TECHNOLOGY-BO     04-13 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEALTH-TECHNOLOGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS PROBABLY SOLD PIECES OF DOWNED STEALTH FIGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. CHANDLER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Photos of the F-117 Stealth fighter that was shot down over
Bosnia more than two weeks ago show that the wreckage had been
picked clean within hours after the crash, but it's unlikely that
the debris will provide any useful information about the plane's
design that was not already well known, analysts said this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pictures several hours after the crash showed it had been
picked clean,'' said aerospace analyst John Pike of the Federation
of American Scientists in Washington. ``All of the sort of intact
stealthy stuff,'' _ such as the special radar-evading materials
from a large section of wing seen in the first photos of the crash
site _ ``went off very fast,'' Pike said, as seen in later
pictures. ``I assume it was quickly auctioned off in very spirited
bidding.''
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace engineers in Russia, among other places, are
undoubtedly studying these materials by now, Pike said, ``but
they're probably not going to get an awful lot'' of information
from it.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons why aerospace engineers and analysts,
while chagrined by the loss of the plane in hostile territory, are
not losing sleep over the potential technology gains to those who
analyze its parts. Primarily, they say, it is because the
technology that went into that plane, designed to provide little or
no radar reflection to those attempting to track it, was developed
back in the 1970s. The secret technologies for Stealth aircraft
have progressed considerably since then.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, most of the information about the F-117 itself is
already well known to anyone who is interested. The plane has been
displayed at air shows, where any paying visitor could walk right
up to the plane and examine it and take pictures, said Peter Young,
an Air Force colonel and visiting lecturer in aerospace engineering
at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Aeronautics and
Astronautics Department.
</P>
<P>
   In a lecture at MIT a few weeks ago, Steven Justice of
Lockheed-Martin, the chief engineer of the F-117, demonstrated some
of the plane's radar-reflectance characteristics by using a widely
available plastic model kit of the plane, Young said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The configuration is fairly well known, the materials are
fairly well known, the things done to elude radar are well known,''
Young said. Any foreign analyst who gets a chance to analyze a
piece of the wreckage, he said, will probably find that ``it just
confirms what people already knew.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russians, Young said, have already designed fighters for the
export market that include some Stealth features. British and
French aerospace companies are also said to be working on such
designs. But none of them are likely to be influenced by the loss
of this F-117, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians and the Chinese are thought to be about two decades
behind the United States in aircraft technology, Pike said, which
is approximately the age of the technology used in the F-117. The
specifics of the the plane's design, Pike said, were in large part
dictated by the limitations of the computers available in the 1970s
for its design.
</P>
<P>
   ``Current-generation computers can produce designs that are
curved, rather than faceted,'' Pike said. The only reason the F-117
``had such hard angles is because that was the most complex shape a
computer could handle back then.''
</P>
<P>
   And the materials used to provide ``low-observability'' on radar
screens are well known around the world, Pike said. As long ago as
World War II, Germany had been experimenting with antiradar
materials to use for the periscopes on their submarines. ``It's not
like there's some singular, mystical ingredient,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, engineers in many places would be very interested in
seeing a piece of an F-117 firsthand. ``Anybody who works on radar
evasion wants to get a big piece from the leading practitioner,''
Pike said, and US Stealth aircraft design is acknowledged to be far
ahead of any other nation's.
</P>
<P>
   Young pointed out that much of the plane's success in evading
radar detection rests with the small details of how pieces are
assembled. Most such details could already have been gleaned from
photos taken at an airshow, and there's not likely to be anything
learned from the wreck ``that a good adversary wouldn't know
about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The F-117 was the first plane designed from scratch with radar
evasion as its primary design criterion, but that choice entailed
many compromises, analysts say. Speed, efficiency, and
maneuverability all suffer somewhat as a result.
</P>
<P>
   None of the plane's other features, such as its navigation and
communication systems, are anything special, Pike said, and would
be of little value to an adversary. ``They concentrated all the
development on the Stealth, and everything else was just ordered
out of a catalog,'' Pike said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said Pike, ``one of these falling into the hands of the
Russians or the Chinese was not part of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if, at the end of the day, it doesn't cause anybody to do
anything different, simply being able to analyze actual samples
instead of just speculating about it is going to be useful for
weapons and aircraft designers, even if it just confirms what they
already knew.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2011EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
