<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6744 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-CONTEMPT-BOS &LR;      04-13 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CONTEMPT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SCANDAL, CONTEMPT CITATION SEEN AS CLINTON LEGACIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When President Clinton was found in contempt of
court Monday for lying about his sexual relationship with Monica S.
Lewinsky, the news was somewhat dulled because Clinton was dealing
with Kosovo. But when history is written, scholars say the Lewinsky
story and the contempt citation are likely to be the president's
enduring legacies.
</P>
<P>
   Barring some unforeseen circumstance in which the Kosovo
conflict turns into the equivalent of World War III, the scholars
said, Clinton has little hope that his war actions will overshadow
his impeachment. And the ruling that Clinton was in contempt of
court for lying in his deposition in the Paula Jones sexual
harassment suit may have sealed his fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard Nixon had a war for most of his time in office and
that is not what we remember him by,'' said G. Calvin Mackenzie, a
professor of government at Colby College. While Nixon certainly is
remembered for the way he conducted the Vietnam War, it is Nixon's
Watergate dealings and resignation from office that became his
legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said in a recent CBS-TV interview that he didn't regard
impeachment as ``some great badge of shame,'' and he has insisted
that it be balanced off by his many accomplishments as president.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday the president refused to comment on the contempt
citation, and he walked away from journalists when they tried to
question him after he spoke about Kosovo in the Rose Garden.
Clinton lawyer Robert Bennett also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could appeal the contempt citation, but he has little
enthusiam for that, according to sources familiar with the matter.
Such a fight might lead to weeks of hearings and even testimony
from Lewinsky, followed by a possible referral of the matter to a
prosecutor. Clinton is likely to accept the penalty of paying
several hundred thousand dollars in legal fees and the possible
revocation of his law license, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials hope that a successful, quick war effort
in Kosovo could be a big boost. But Clinton himself has proven how
fickle public opinion can be about foreign affairs; he beat
President Bush in 1992 despite Bush's victory in the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's contempt of court citation was not surprising, given
that US District Judge Susan Webber Wright had hinted at it in a
September ruling. But Republicans viewed it as a vindication of the
House vote for impeachment, even though the House failed to approve
the article that specifically charged Clinton with lying in the
civil deposition. Despite the House's failure to approve that
article, Senate Republicans noted repeatedly that they believed
Clinton had lied and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said there was a symmetry to two judicial actions on
Monday, and it provided what one analyst called ``an elegant
conclusion'' to the past year's focus on the Lewinsky story. The
contempt citation affirmed that Clinton lied under oath. And the
acquittal by an Arkansas jury of Clinton's friend Susan McDougal
affirmed the view that independent counsel Kenneth W. Starr had
gone too far in his effort to investigate the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a delicious conclusion for those who attacked both
Clinton and Starr in the last year,'' Brookings Institution scholar
Stephen Hess said. ``It is about where both deserve to be. It is a
punishment fitting the crime.''
</P>
<P>
   But is the Lewinsky story really over? That depends in large
part upon Starr, who suffered a setback Monday when a Little Rock
jury found McDougal not guilty of obstructing Starr's investigation
and deadlocked on two contempt charges. McDougal's attorneys in
effect put Starr on trial, arguing that the prosecutor has been so
zealous in going after Clinton that he tried to get McDougal to lie
about her knowledge of the president's Arkansas business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   The jury agreed with that defense, and Clinton quickly issued a
statement wishing her well. But Starr may decide to retry McDougal
on the contempt charges.
</P>
<P>
   Just hours after that victory came the contempt citation and the
setback for the president. And in issuing it, Wright may have
opened the door a little wider for Starr to try to indict the
president for perjury or obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   While Starr is unlikely to try to indict Clinton while he
remains in office _ which many legal scholars said would be
unconstitutional _ he could try to indict him after he leaves the
White House. It depends on whether Starr believes that the House
impeachment vote and the contempt of court citation vindicate him
for his investigation and that he has an obligation to pursue an
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Starr would not discuss the contempt citation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will testify Wednesday against renewing the independent
counsel law, the Associated Press reported. He opposes renewal
partly on grounds that it violates the constitutional separation of
powers between the executive and judicial branches. Many lawmakers
of both parties want to eliminate or modify the statute allowing an
independent counsel to investigate possible illegal activities by
the highest-ranking members of an administration.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
