A6748 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAMA-LOTTERY-COX     04-13 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAMA-LOTTERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Filibuster in Alabama aimed at slowing down lottery movement
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. _ Alabama's Bible-belt backbone was up Tuesday
as Gov. Don Siegelman's lottery bill triggered a Senate filibuster
featuring dire predictions of the state's moral downfall should the
measure pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot ignore the fact that there will be divorce
problems, domestic abuse problems, homelessness and addiction
problems if you pass this gambling bill,'' said Sen. J.T. ``Jabo''
Waggoner, a Republican lottery opponent. ``How many of you are
going to go home this weekend and tell your momma, `Momma, I voted
for a gambling bill and I'm proud of it?'''
</P>
<P>
   A Senate vote had been expected Tuesday, but, with the
filibuster, now likely will not come before Thursday. Alabama's
House passed the lottery bill 70-31.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman, a Democrat who broke a long-running Republican lock
on the Governor's Mansion last fall by campaigning on an
``education-lottery'' platform, wants Alabama residents to vote on
a lottery in a constitutional referendum, perhaps as early as this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   If passed, Alabama would become the seventh Southern state with
a lottery. The issue has been raised in Tennessee, South Carolina,
North Carolina and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman would model Alabama's lottery after Georgia's, with
proceeds estimated at $150 million a year going to fund college
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers are also scheduled to take up a bill that would allow
video poker terminals at greyhound tracks. Unlike the lottery bill,
however, the video gaming proposal would become law if passed, not
going to the voters in a referendum.
</P>
<P>
   Siegelman made the lottery his top campaign issue last fall,
when he unseated Republican incumbent Fob James. His supporters
cite polls showing a majority of Alabama residents want a vote on
the lottery, and that the proposal would pass if put on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Lowell Barron, the Democratic leader in the Senate,
predicted the measure would pass, but not until opponents _ largely
Republicans _ have plenty of time to state their opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to cut off debate prematurely,'' he said.
``But I don't have any doubt we'll pass the lottery bill. We have
the votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Alabama currently allows betting on greyhound racing, but has
watched as casinos in neighboring Mississippi have mushroomed and
Georgia's lottery has provided scholarships for thousands of
college-bound students.
</P>
<P>
   But the idea of expanding gambling offerings with active state
involvement seems to have struck a raw nerve in the conservative,
church-going state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a good way of running our state,'' said Sen. Bill
Armistead, another Republican lottery opponent. ``What we need to
be looking at is legitimate ways of raising revenues, not taking
the last dollar from poor people who can't afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Williams writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
