<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-GEOTEL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO ADDS GEOTEL TO NETWORKING FOLD FOR $1.92 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER AND RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GeoTel Communications Corp., a six-year-old maker of software
for routing customer calls, will be purchased by giant computer
networking company Cisco Systems Inc. for $1.92 billion in stock.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Tuesday underscores the growing compatibility
of telephone networks and computer systems based on Internet
standards. It would give San Jose-based Cisco, an Internet hardware
specialist, access to GeoTel's software for managing customer calls
to corporate ``call centers''. Cisco would be better able to offer
products combining voice traffic with data.
</P>
<P>
   The deal represents a bonanza for GeoTel, founded six years ago
on a $7 million initial investment. Tuesday's agreement values each
share of GeoTel at $58.64, or 33 percent higher than its price
before the deal was announced.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel earned a profit of only $9 million last year. But the
Lowell, Mass. company has made a name for itself selling software
to customers like American Airlines, Fidelity Investments and
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   Now, such customers are looking to combine customer voice
traffic with data sent via Internet standards, an area where
Cisco's hubs and routers dominate. Six months ago, GeoTel began a
partnership with Cisco to create products in this area, and the
merger is the logical reflection of the emerging market, the
companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Listwin, the Cisco executive vice president who will oversee
the new unit, said the growth of electronic commerce will only
accelerate the convergence. ``We see selling GeoTel software with
our hardware to the `New World Order' of companies like
Amazon.com,'' Listwin said, referring to the on-line bookseller
based in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   John Thibault, GeoTel chief executive, added: ``We looked at our
strategic alternatives and Cisco was a compelling partner because
of its strength in a combination of data and voice switching.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, GeoTel considered a similar deal with Cisco
competitor Lucent Technologies Inc., said a person familiar with
the matter. The companies declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco has steadily acquired smaller technology companies over
several years, but the GeoTel purchase represents the largest since
1996. Then, Cisco bought StrataCom Inc., a maker of high-speed
switches, for $4.5 billion.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel will remain as a separate unit of Cisco with Thibault as
its head. No layoffs are expected among GeoTel's 310 employees, the
two companies said.
</P>
<P>
   After the deal is completed, Cisco will have more than 1,000
employees in Massachusetts, mostly based in its regional
headquarters in Chelmsford.
</P>
<P>
   The merger was approved by boards of both companies Monday
night. It still requires approvals from GeoTel shareholders and
certain federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Under the terms of the agreement, Cisco will exchange 0.5138
shares of its common stock for each of GeoTel's 32.7 million shares
outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco shares closed Tuesday at $114 1/8, down 3 5/8. GeoTel
stock rose 11 11/16 to close at 55 15/16.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel Senior Vice President Lou Volpe said the agreement also
includes conditions under which breakup penalities would be paid if
the deal isn't completed, but he declined to describe these
details.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel was established in 1993 with a $7 million investment from
Fidelity Investments and Matrix Partners, the Waltham, Mass.
venture capital firm. The company sold its first public stock in
1996, and last year had sales of $44.85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault estimates the market for call center equipment at $5
billion a year, an industry that employs 130,000 people nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel's software coordinates database records for customer
sales representatives. For example, a caller to an insurance
company looking to buy a policy after watching a national
television ad could be switched automatically to a sales agent at
the closest regional branch, depending on the area code of the
caller's phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, calls from customers who owe money on their credit
card accounts could be automatically routed to a collections
representative.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the merger allays fears that GeoTel, which has
focused mainly on phone networks, could be swamped as call-center
consumers embrace the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a gaping hole in terms of GeoTel's general strategy
going forward, which is how they're planning to address the
next-generation network,'' said Ted Jackson, senior analyst at US
BancCorp Piper Jaffray. ``This is a good way to solve that''
problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Herbert Tinger, First Albany Corp. analyst: ``Cisco wants
to get into telecom in a big way, and this is the quickest way to
get major customers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Telecom is the last big industry that's still heavily based on
proprietary hardware, but that's starting to change because
everybody wants to bring e-mail or text-chat services'' to
traditional telephone customers, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
