<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV20-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HOME IS WHERE THE HEARTACHE IS
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Tuesday, April 20)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From here, looking over there, you would think it would be a
blessing to board a transport plane, even the back of a truck, and
get the heck out.
</P>
<P>
   But places like Kosovo or Bosnia and others where people are
forced out remain home. It is where people did normal things, like
go to school, fall in love and have babies. Where they know what
spring smells like, when it isn't overpowered by smoke and death.
It is the place they will dream of no matter where they land, the
place in the old photos for those lucky to have family pictures.
</P>
<P>
   The lure of home even when it's being destroyed from inside and
out was enough to bring some Bosnian women back, according to
Deborah Lubar, an American writer and actor, whose works focus on
women in war zones. Recently in California as part of a lecture
tour on Bosnian women refugees, Lubar offered a perspective on what
happens after ethnic cleansing and peace accords. ``After the world
has stopped paying attention,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   She's been to Bosnia twice in the last three years, interviewing
women in Sanski Most, a refugee city 15 minutes away from the city
of Prijidor in Bosnia. Many of the women used to live in nice homes
and work at good jobs in Prijidor, but Prijidor is now in the
Republic of Serbska and off limits to many of its former
inhabitants, including these mostly Muslim women.
</P>
<P>
   Technically they are considered displaced persons, not refugees,
because they live in their own country. But Lubar points out,
``They feel they are not at home. They have lost their identity.''
</P>
<P>
   Everything they had is gone, including many of their husbands
who disappeared or were killed in the war. Many of their children
are moved far away, because they say there is no future in their
homeland. The women, middle- aged and older, feel it's too late for
them to start over in a new land.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, an economist unable to find work, told her, ``It's
hard to know who we are anymore. We've lost our friends. Our
husbands were killed. People don't see us as we were anymore.''
What strikes Lubar is how much the displaced people of Yugoslavia,
no matter which group, are no different from many Americans.
``People with decent, good lives'' and unprepared to have it all
wrenched away.
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian refugees she knows were run out of their homes
during the 3 1/2 year conflict. She said what's happening in Kosovo
now is just ``a speeded-up version of what happened in Bosnia.''
</P>
<P>
   She wondered how the women knew what to take when ordered out of
their homes. They told her they didn't know. They stuck what they
could in a bag and left. One woman said it was summer and she left
in a dress and high heels.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said to me, `Why did I wear high heels?'''
</P>
<P>
   Many of them made it to other parts of Europe but returned after
the 1995 Dayton Peace Accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of these women were doctors, nurses and teachers, even a
judge. But outside of Bosnia they were treated like barbarians.''
Working as maids in different parts of Europe, they said their
employers treated them as if they had never seen a refrigerator
before. Because of the language difficulties the women couldn't
explain that, indeed, they used to own houses that were larger than
the ones they were cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted to come back home,'' said Lubar, ``just like the
Albanians are going to eventually want to come home to Kosovo.''
Being a refugee is not the same as being an immigrant. It's not a
choice. One day you're an established member of the community and
the next day you're one of a thousand on a road, carrying your life
in a plastic shopping bag. You become an international dilemma _
the refugee problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Albanian refugees from Kosovo who fled to Macedonia were
moved again this week, ordered to get on city buses and taken to
the airport and flown to Turkey and Norway. Some were relieved to
go. Some resisted. They worried that the farther they were removed,
the harder it would be to get back.
</P>
<P>
   Right now Kosovo doesn't look like any place anyone would ever
want to return to. But they will. And then what?
</P>
<P>
   The Bosnian refugees told Lubar they felt as if their
civilization was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The men are worse, though. She said the women eventually open up
and talk about their experience, even about the rapes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot fathom what happened to them because on the
outside, they're personally lovely. They wear makeup and little
scarves around their necks. I think because of the rapes it was
very important to recover their femininity, their beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   But the men refugees, she said, don't talk about what happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they are even more shattered. They couldn't save their
families. They feel utterly impotent.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
