<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBREGA-DANCE-2TAKES-     04-13 1295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBREGA-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERFORMER OF MANY FACES, ALL BRAZILIAN  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Antonio Nobrega, a Brazilian performer who will be making his
United States debut at the Kennedy Center's American Dance Festival
April 27 through 29, trots out a variety of characters in
``Figural,'' the one-man show he will use to greet North American
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   The figures he conjures, through mime, dance, music and
acrobatics, are not simply creatures of the artist's fancy but a
string of types meant as a showcase for Brazil's culturally rich
northeast.
</P>
<P>
   That is because Nobrega, more than most performers these days,
feels himself on a mission greater than exploring his own emotions.
In his case, he has set out to do no less than preserve Brazilian
culture, both inside and out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   To Brazilians, Nobrega is perhaps the most popular performer of
music and dance from the northeast, which serves as an artistic
wellspring for the rest of the country. In recent years, Brazil's
northeast has undergone a cultural resurgence, with the release of
films, books, music and dance from the area.
</P>
<P>
   The region's music, from the spirited forro to the fusion of
choro to the African drums of groups like Olodum, is now a staple
of the Rio de Janeiro club scene, and Nobrega himself typically
sells out the Canecao, one of the top concert halls for popular
music in Rio.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent telephone interview from his home in Sao Paulo,
Nobrega said he considered Brazil's northeast ``the most
representative area of Brazil, if you talk about anything cultural
at all.'' Salvador of Bahia was the first capital of Brazil, in the
early 1500s. And from Recife, in the neighboring state of
Pernambuco, came the country's first export, the sugar cane
produced by African slaves. It was here that the cultures that form
Brazil _ Indian, African and European _ first mingled and made
music.
</P>
<P>
   One of Nobrega's recent shows in Rio, ``Wood That the Termites
Don't Chew,'' recreated the traditions of traveling minstrels of
the arid northeast, performers who visit towns and play for the
spare change tossed from windows. Nobrega credits some lyrics and
music to texts and traditions more than a century old.
</P>
<P>
   True to the minstrel shows of the northeast, Nobrega's wife and
children took part in the show, swirling around the shacks and
clotheslines on stage for the exuberant umbrella dances of frevo.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, audiences will see Nobrega alone, performing one
of the first pieces he choreographed and wrote for his repertory.
In ``Figural,'' he dons the brilliant costumes and masks by Romero
Andrade Lima, among Brazil's most talented costume designers, to
portray a scoundrel, a saint, a beggar woman in rags and Casanova,
who dances with a doll.
</P>
<P>
   He portrays a clown, Tonheta, to tie the images together in the
second part of the show, using humor and music to comment on life's
sad parade. Tonheta, who plays several instruments at once, is the
only character not to wear a mask.
</P>
<P>
   ``What most distinguishes the work of Antonio Nobrega,'' wrote
Barbara Heliodora, dance critic for the Rio daily O Globo, ``is his
total delivery of himself as an instrument of creation.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the character changes of ``Figural,'' ``there is not
one gesture, not one look, that calls attention to Nobrega's person
or personality,'' wrote Ms. Heliodora, who has called the
performer's talent and technique ``exceptional.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobrega, 46, came to dance only as an adult. He originally
trained in classical music, encouraged by his father, a doctor in a
sanitarium. In the late 1960s, he played violin with two
orchestras, the Chamber of Paraiba and the Recife Symphony. He then
joined the Armorial Quintet, a group of classically trained
musicians who sought to promote Brazil's native, as against
strictly European culture.
</P>
<P>
   nn$taf-z &QL; 
s exxnt26 nt22 nt06 nt10 nt32 &QL; 
sexx &QL; 
 &UR; BC-NOBREGA-DANCE-2NDTAKE-$ADV18-NYT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: European culture. &LR;  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was with the Armorial that Nobrega picked up the rabeca, a
four-string instrument of country music similar to the violin. The
move would redirect the artist in him utterly.
</P>
<P>
   In the following years, Nobrega gave himself over to researching
Pernambuco, his native state. Economically, the northeast is the
poorest piece of Brazil. If Brazil is sometimes nicknamed Belindia
_ part first world like Belgium and part Third World like India _
Pernambuco belongs firmly in that second end of the definition. But
culturally, the northeast is Brazil's richest area, Nobrega
realized.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the art with a distinctly Brazilian flavor, from the
books of Jorge Amado to capoeira, a form of martial arts borne of
slavery and balletic in its symmetry, came from the northeast.
</P>
<P>
   ``The roots of Brazil are there,'' said Roberto da Matta, a
Brazilian anthropologist at the University of Notre Dame in
Indiana. He noted that the music of the Bahian composer and singer
Dorival Caymmi opened the way for bossa nova, while Olodum has
played with Paul Simon. ``Music in Brazil is an essential element:
it's considered the equivalent of money here,'' da Matta said.
``You have three forro disks, some local food _ which is really
national food _ and it's like having a bank account.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobrega studied Brazilian modern dance with Klauss Vianna, and
learned pantomime, mimicry and acrobatics at the Dmitri School of
Theater in Switzerland. Later, he went to the Advanced School of
Circus Art at Chalons-sur-Marne in France.
</P>
<P>
   He calls ``Figural'' a ``synthesis'' of archetypes from the
northeast, ``little choreographic designs that spring form the
Brazilian imagination, adding, ``The figures represent a Brazilian
mythology.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Brazil's population, at 163 million, and its Portuguese
language provide an instant market for everything home-grown, from
computers to line dances, as an artist Nobrega decries the
dominance of United States pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the health of the world, culturally speaking, lies in
what is a part of your soul,'' he said. ``If you cut out that soul,
you leave a sad people.'' On the Rio radio dial, a listener is as
likely to pick up American as Brazilian music. If it is Brazilian,
it often sounds like American music that just happens to be sung in
Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of globalization will be true only on the day that
it creates genuine contact,'' he said. ``I'm speaking about my
country, which is completely colonized by your country, and by the
worst elements. The music of yours that makes it here is not the
best of your music, it's the junk. The same with the television and
movies. It's a kind of cultural imperialism.''
</P>
<P>
   On a more selective level, Charles and Stephanie Reinhart see
Brazil exerting an important influence on American culture. The
couple, artistic advisers for dance at the Kennedy Center, invited
Nobrega as the only foreign performer in a series about American
dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at the history of dance in the United States, a
major part of the fusion that's happened has come from Latin
America,'' said Reinhart. ``In the early years of modern dance, you
have Catherine Dunham drawing on Caribbean and Brazilian movements.
It's part of our heritage in that it's part of what's formed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinhart said he had seen Nobrega rehearse ``Figural'' at his
Sao Paulo studio several years ago and thought his work a good
panorama of Brazilian movement. ``I think that what he's done, he's
done in a new way, even though it's old,'' he said. ``It's like
Picasso and the African sculptures: what's modern and what's not
modern? It was innovative and yet based on his interpretation of
tradition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
