<SLUG> BC-CREDIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREASURIES WEAKEN AS MAJOR DEBT SALES NEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ROBERT HURTADO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Treasury bond prices sagged Tuesday under the weight
of the large calendar of corporate and agency borrowers planning to
sell their debt over the next few days.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate bonds give investors an attractive alternative to
Treasuries because the yields are higher, so the rates on
government paper have to rise to stay competitive. Securities firms
arranging the corporate sales often sell Treasuries ahead of the
offering, and that also tends to raise yield, which moves in the
opposite direction from the price. They do that as a precaution
against rates rising before the corporate deals are done, replacing
the government securities when the sales are complete.
</P>
<P>
   Among the corporate borrowers expected to sell about $9 billion
soon, are the Inter-American Development Bank, Freddie Mac, and the
Associates Corp of North America. Inter-American priced a $1
billion global bond issue Tuesday through Lehman Brothers and
Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. The 10-year bond was priced to yield
5.755 percent. That is about 65 basis points, or hundredths of a
percentage point, above a Treasury security with a comparable
yield.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond dropped 20/32, to 96
16/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction from
the price, rose to 5.49 percent, from 5.45 percent Monday,
</P>
<P>
   Reports on consumer prices and retail sales left market
expectations of continued economic growth with little inflation
unchanged and raised the likelihood that the Fed will not push up
interest rates soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the world we said we always wanted,'' said Donald
Fine, chief market analyst at Chase Asset Management, ``strong
economic growth with low inflation. The stock market continues to
rise, and people are having trouble finding things to get upset
about. The bond market, in turn, is expected to stay within its
current range as a by product of an unchanged FOMC stance, with the
long bond centered at 5.50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Consumer Price Index rose only two-tenths of 1 percent in
March, a smaller-than-expected increase. Fine said that along with
a minimal one-tenth of 1 percent rise in the core rate, the
inflation statistics continued to impress market participants. But
he said the relatively benign lift in gasoline prices may be
masking a much larger jump in the April data to be released in May,
as pump prices around the country have surged since the March data
were compiled. The key issue, he added, is whether fuel price
increases will continue, because if they do, the indirect effects
on transportation and other components of inflation could be
considerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first glance,'' Fine said, ``the 0.2 percent increase in
retail sales seemed to suggest a noticeable slowing in the growth
of consumer spending, but in light of past data revisions and
giddiness in the stock market, this conclusion would undoubtedly be
premature.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
