<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WILL-AND-GRACE-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HE'S SELF-INVOLVED, HE DOES HEADSTANDS, HE'S WILL'S PAL JACK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill.)   (af)  
 Margy Rochlin's most recent article for the Arts and Leisure
section was about Rachel Griffiths.  
 By MARGY ROCHLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Right up there on Sean Hayes' list of Worst Jobs
Ever was the time he was paid to entertain guests at a lavish Bel
Air party by performing the Charleston. ``It was so embarrassing,''
said Hayes, who doesn't blame Jack Nicholson, Don Rickles or the
other assembled celebrities for blithely ignoring him and his
partner when they simply merged into the crowd, hunched over and
began frantically waggling their knees. ``Everybody was standing
there, chatting, not watching. Then every so often, someone would
turn their head and give us this look like, `What are you doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the nature of show business is that the craziness
that leads in one instance to humiliation can be the guiding
principle behind a successful character on a sitcom. As proof,
witness Hayes' Jack McFarland on NBC's hit series ``Will and
Grace.''
</P>
<P>
   In his rendering of the wisecracking, unconditionally
self-involved gay sidekick to Eric McCormack's stolid gay lawyer,
Will Truman, Hayes doesn't just act the part; he stages a one-man
floor show. Often, he half-sings his dialogue or amplifies the zing
of a punch line by, say, striking a gaudy pose.
</P>
<P>
   In one bit, in which the ever-responsible Will helps Jack
unravel his tax problems, Hayes dressed up an uncomplicated line
(``Can we talk about something else?'') by flipping into a
headstand on a chair and bicycling his legs.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, when ``Will and Grace'' had its premiere, television
pundits took up column space debating whether America was ready for
a show about the sometimes touching and always complicated intimacy
between best-friend roommates, one of whom is openly homosexual
(Will) and the other, a love-hungry heterosexual career gal (Debra
Messing's Grace). But viewers pronounced the discussion moot by
declaring their love for Hayes' Jack.
</P>
<P>
   After three episodes, the NBC promotions department decided to
use Hayes' breakout status to hype the show by broadcasting a
30-second Jack spot, complete with a fever-pitch montage of Jack
footage and a goofy Jack theme song.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was floored,'' reported Hayes, 28, whose friendly, upturned
face may be familiar because he has spent the last seven years
appearing in television commercials, for everything from Doritos to
Bud Light.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone was thrilled with Jack. Gay rights groups saw
his flamboyant character as perpetuation of a gay stereotype.
That's a sensitive subject with the show's executive producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so hard to comment on that,'' said Max Mutchnick (``I'm
the gay one''). ```Jack's too gay' and `Will's not gay enough.' To
what standard? Who is measuring that?'' David Kohan adds: ``All I
can say is that our goal is to write these characters as honestly
as we possibly can. We know people in real life that are very much
like Will and Jack.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Jack is based on a real person, an old friend. ``An
East Coast preppie with a real sense of entitlement and an odd view
of the world'' who has mixed feelings about the honor, says
Mutchnick. ``It depends on how he's medicated at the time,'' said
Kohan, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine what the real Jack, a Los Angeles interior
decorator, might make of his alter ego's dressing room on the
Studio City back lot. ``I know, it's boring,'' said Hayes, seated
on a beige couch in a bare-walled cubicle whose only flash of color
was a dying dieffenbachia in the corner.
</P>
<P>
   Before ``Will and Grace,'' Hayes' television experience had
amounted to guest appearances on purgatory-hour episodics like
USA's ``Silk Stalkings'' and failed tryouts during the 1997 pilot
season, when he was passed over for ``Veronica's Closet'' and
``Dilbert'' (an animated series).
</P>
<P>
   ``When I read for it, it was a live-action show,'' said Hayes of
the latter. ``I guess I was so bad they decided to make it into a
cartoon.''
</P>
<P>
   It was his star turn as a heartsick gay photographer in a
cloying independent film called ``Billy's Hollywood Screen Kiss''
that caught the eye of an NBC casting executive, who found Hayes at
the Sundance Film Festival and faxed him the entire ``Will and
Grace'' pilot script. The gesture forced Hayes to invest some good
faith money in his future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hotel guy went, `Here's your fax,''' said Hayes. ``And
then, `That'll be 40 bucks.'''
</P>
<P>
   Not much later, Mutchnick and Kohan found themselves in a
meeting with a lanky, blue-eyed actor who had the wraparound smile
and comic timing to pull off a character that on paper might not
always be likable.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hayes lives by himself in a two-story apartment in
Hancock Park, he spent his early years amid a crowd. The youngest
of five children, he grew up in the Chicago suburbs, watching his
mother try to make ends meet on her paycheck as the director at a
nonprofit food bank. As for his father, he merely watched him come
and go.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left my family when I was 5, 7, 9 and 12,'' said Hayes.
``It was crazy. He was an alcoholic. My mom basically raised us
all. He never contributed a dollar.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 8, NBC removed Christina Applegate's exceedingly
average series ``Jesse'' from its Thursday lineup and bequeathed
the golden 8:30 p.m. post-``Friends'' time slot to ``Will and
Grace.'' It's a move that is sure to boost the ratings and give
Hayes' mother even more to talk about with neighbors and
co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so proud,'' said Hayes. ``I'm glad that she can say,
`That's my son!' And I'm glad she's finally got something to hold
over my dad's head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
