<HEADLINE>
THE NEW YORK ARTIST IS NOW FROM EVERYWHERE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What defines a New York artist at the end of the 20th
century? The question surfaced with the announcement that the works
to be exhibited at the next Whitney Biennial, due to open in March
2000, would be chosen by a team of art professionals who neither
work at the museum nor live in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Maxwell L. Anderson, the museum's director, spoke of giving the
show a ``national perspective.'' Hugh Davies, director of the
Museum of Contemporary Art, San Diego, La Jolla, and one of the
biennial's outside organizers, said that the biennial had been a
``New York event'' since the 1970s, and that California's
representation had been ``limited.''
</P>
<P>
   After 25 years of having New Yorkers select the show, it could
be interesting to reverse the gaze, as theorists might say, and see
what non-New Yorkers come up with. It remains to be seen just how
different the biennial they choose will be from its predecessors _
very, somewhat or not much at all.
</P>
<P>
   But it was surprising to have the us-them, New York-America
split invoked, as if we were back in the 60s, when New York, or
more precisely Manhattan, tended to be indifferent to and ignorant
of nearly everything beyond its borders.
</P>
<P>
   Life was simpler then. A New York artist was someone who lived
in New York, made New York art and took up a lot of room in New
York shows like the Whitney Biennial, which irked non-New York
artists. In all likelihood, the New York artist was a living white
male.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 20 years, New York has become more open to non-New
York artists with every passing season, especially after the sudden
shock _ as in ``we are not alone'' _ of the German and Italian
painters, whose work arrived in New York in full force in the early
1980s. For a sense of this shock, consider Sigmar Polke's ``Spider
Man,'' a large work on paper from 1971-74 and one of the standouts
in the bracing survey of the artist's early drawings currently at
the Museum of Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   It arrived on these shores in 1982, eight years after its
completion, for Polke's first New York show, at the Holly Solomon
Gallery in SoHo _ sudden proof that New York's idea of the art of
the 1970s was up for revision.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the notion of a New York art or the New York artist
has grown fuzzy around the edges. But maybe it was never really all
that clear-cut anyway. Even in the 60s and 70s, there were artists
who were prominent in New York but didn't live here.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Nauman, for example, has qualified as a New York artist in
terms of stature and ubiquity since the early 70s. So has Ed
Ruscha. But both artists began their careers in Los Angeles, and
Nauman has lived in New Mexico since 1979, although no one calls
him a New Mexican artist.
</P>
<P>
   Younger California artists who, like Nauman, are becoming
honorary New Yorkers because their work is so visible here include
Paul McCarthy, Charles Ray and Mike Kelley. Among newly emerged
artists, Kara Walker lives in Providence, R.I., and Ellen Gallagher
in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, there are artists who leave New York without losing
their New York-artist status: the appropriation artist Barbara
Kruger has lived mostly in Los Angeles since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   These days, when jet planes and e-mail have made the world
smaller for everyone, we might almost talk about the dilution or
diaspora of the very concept of the New York artist. It's not so
much that the New Yorkers have left town; it's just that the term
itself is being scattered to the four winds, divvied up,
appropriated and reshaped by artists from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of nomadism may have a certain theoretical cachet these
days, but it also has a strong reality, no less so in the art world
than everywhere else. Contemporary art is now made by people from
all kinds of backgrounds and locales, and they are giving it a
diversity unimaginable in the 1970s, when the term pluralism first
came into use.
</P>
<P>
   New York is becoming less and less important as a place for
artists to live and work, and more and more a central ``clearing
house'' for a global contemporary-art scene. Showing in New York
remains a primary way that artists from around the world establish
themselves. (Another method is getting picked for a string of the
big international biennials.)
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, a geographically diverse roster of artists
seems almost de rigeur among New York galleries. They now routinely
represent artists from several states, if not countries and
continents: California, Rhode Island, Minnesota, but also China,
Korea, Brazil and Norway. And artists from all over are not only
showing in New York but spending quite a bit of time here too. They
visit, live here half time, or even settle here.
</P>
<P>
   On this score, the terse biographical data included in
exhibition catalogs make increasingly interesting reading. In the
1995 Whitney Biennial, Gabriel Orozco was listed as living in
Mexico City and New York; he listed only New York for the 1997
biennial. That show also included Ilya Kabakov, who claimed Moscow,
Paris and New York; the photographer Antonio Martorell, who
designated Puerto Rico and New York; and the American
choreographers William Forsythe and Amanda Miller, who both live in
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   In other recent exhibition catalogs, home to the Japanese
photo-artist Mariko Mori is Tokyo and New York; to the Italian
performance artist Vanessa Beecroft, it's Brooklyn and Milan. The
last word, for the moment, may be found in a recent catalog of the
work of Douglas Gordon, a film and video artist from Scotland. The
bio simply says ``Douglas Gordon lives and works in Glasgow, and .
. .''
</P>
<P>
   Catalog biographies can reflect both the political turmoil of
recent decades and the increasingly complex cultural strands being
woven into the fabric of contemporary art. The artists (and
sisters) Rachael and Toba Khedoori, for example, whose parents are
Iraqi, were born and reared in Australia and now live in Los
Angeles. Rirkrit Tiravanija, who is Thai, was born in Buenos Aires,
reared in Thailand, Ethiopia, Malaysia and Canada, and now lives
mostly in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, New York remains a center partly because it has
a history of being one, but mostly by dint of sheer numbers. There
are more galleries, artists and full-time critics here than
anywhere in the world. But as the scene continues to expand, even
this concentration contributes to a kind of decentralization.
</P>
<P>
   The New York art world is splintering into so many different
groups, stylistic factions and neighborhoods that, outside of one's
immediate circle of friends and colleagues, it is becoming
impossible to keep track of who lives here and who's just passing
through. And what's more, it doesn't matter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
