<HEADLINE>
US SEEKS WAYS TO HELP ALBANIANS STILL INSIDE KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LOUISE D. PALMER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Worries are mounting in the White House over how to
come up with a viable plan to reach hundreds of thousands of ethnic
Albanians trapped inside Kosovo as fresh waves of refugees report
that many are battling hunger, cold, sickness, and death.
</P>
<P>
   How many thousands is anyone's guess. Since the air strikes
began and Yugoslav President Solobodan Milosevic expelled foreign
observers and journalists from the province, no one -- not the
Pentagon, NATO, or the United Nations -- has been able to get a
grip on the number of ``internally displaced'' Albanian Kosovars or
the depth of their plight. Nor have they settled on a strategy to
respond to this invisible crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real answer to that question is that . . . it is a very
hard one, and we are working on it,'' President Clinton said after
a meeting on Kosovo with members of Congress. ``It is a huge
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem has become more pressing since Serb forces sealed
the Kosovo border crossings last week and drove an estimated
100,000 refugees back into the country. According to the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees, as many as 700,000 ethnic
Albanians have been routed from their homes but are still in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At a NATO briefing Tuesday, Gen. Wesley Clark, the Supreme
Allied Commander, said airlifting food posed a risk to NATO planes,
which continue to take Serbian missile and anti-aircraft fire. ``A
slow-moving transport plane would be vulnerable to such fire,''
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said there was no guarantee humanitarian supplies
delivered through an air drop would benefit those in need -- or be
seized by Serbian military forces and police.
</P>
<P>
   There are is another concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a secure drop zone, a big enough area controlled by
the people you want to benefit, you can't ensure that the hungry
people rushing to retrieve the stuff you drop out of plane don't
get shot,'' explained a State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the administration is also considering a
number of additional options, none of which he considered
promising.
</P>
<P>
   Among the options:
</P>
<P>
   _ Air drops by non-NATO, neutral countries such as Switzerland
or Sweden. The idea has only lukewarm support because the Serbs
have ignored Sweden's neutral position in the past and because it
would still not address the question of who on the ground would
receive supplies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Funneling relief supplies to Kosovar Albanians through
Montenegro, which does not have a hard border with Kosovo since
both are Yugoslavian provinces.
</P>
<P>
   _ Convincing the Bulgarians, Russians, or Greeks to ferry in
supplies on behalf of the international community.
</P>
<P>
   ``All are pretty thin reeds, but we are exploring them to see
what we can build out of them,'' the official said. ``We speculate
and guess that things are horrible on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The State Department official also said the options were
stop-gap measures and that support was growing for sending in
ground troops to secure the province so that international relief
groups can move in.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no other way to address this situation in any
systematic way,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, policymakers and members of the international relief
community are expected to point to the plight of displaced Kosovars
to bolster the case for the immediate introduction of NATO ground
troops at hearing of the Senate Subcommittee on Immigration
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Massacres are only one method of ethnic cleansing available to
the Serbs,'' said Bill Frelick, senior policy analyst at the US
Committee for Refugees, a private advocacy group that publishes the
annual World Refugee Survey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Starving people out was a tactic used in Bosnia, where the
Serbs surrounded people, shelled them, prevented food from getting
in, cut them off, and left them to die from starvation or
disease,'' Frelick said, ``and they are doing it again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
