<HEADLINE>
DESPITE CHANGES, MASTERS STILL PARTIAL TO POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fear not, golf traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   Course changes to Augusta National Golf Club might have tempered
some players' decisions when faced with the risk-reward dilemmas
that make up the fabric of the Masters Tournament. But the
off-season tweaking did not turn the course into a safe haven for
par-shooting Robogolfers, as some had feared.
</P>
<P>
   Augusta remains a dream layout for those who prefer dice-roll
golf, not a potential U.S. Open venue with buzzcut rough. But
players must now be more judicious about when they roll those dice,
rather than automatically stepping up to the table at every par 5.
</P>
<P>
   That is the lesson we learned at the 63rd Masters. And that
stands as a change for the better.
</P>
<P>
   Without the rough that reappeared in 1999, long hitters could
routinely spray drives on Augusta's watery, back-nine par 5s _ the
central holes in most final-round dramas _ yet remain confident of
reaching the green in two shots with a 7-iron. That is no longer
the case.
</P>
<P>
   A missed fairway now means indecision in club selection and a
possible flier out of the rough that could lead to disaster. The
risk factor is enhanced, making the rewards more meaningful for
those willing to roll the dice.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's being aggressive, and there's playing stupid,'' said
Davis Love III, who finished as the Masters runner-up to Jose Maria
Olazabal. ``If you're in the rough at No. 13 or No. 15, there's no
reason to go for the green unless you have a perfect lie, because
you can't stop the ball. Just getting over the water on those holes
is not an issue any more. There's no point in making double bogey
just to prove you're man enough to go for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hit a good drive, however, and the reward is there for a
potential eagle. And the type of shot that separates the Masters
from other major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, short-and-straight types like Lee Janzen, a two-time Open
champ, surfaced early in the week. But the top names on Sunday's
leader board routinely attack Augusta with aggression and pizzazz:
Olazabal, Love, Greg Norman. So do fellow top-10 finishers David
Duval, Phil Mickelson, Lee Westwood and Nick Price.
</P>
<P>
   ``You still need a power game to win here,'' Duval said. ``But
the second cut of rough makes you think more about when and how you
use it. It was the biggest of all the course changes, from my
standpoint.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods, one of the PGA Tour's longest hitters, said the
rough made it impossible for him to bag birdies from the same
locations where he sprayed drives while setting a tournament
scoring record (18 under) in 1997. But given a good driving week,
Woods said his mark could be broken in a future Masters with
Augusta set up exactly as it was for the 1999 event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely,'' Woods said. ``The changes won't make that much
difference to the power hitters if they keep it in the fairway and
hole some putts. I just didn't make anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Woods hit more greens in regulation (50 of 72) than
anyone in the Masters field. But he was next-to-last among cut
survivors with 126 putts, 17 more than Olazabal.
</P>
<P>
   And the Masters remains a putting contest, even for the big
hitters. That will never change, no matter how much they tweak the
rest of the course.
SPOTLIGHT ON ...Hale Irwin IRWIN CAN BREAK SLUMP, TIE HAGEN THIS
WEEKEND
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of what happens at this week's PGA Seniors
Championship, Hale Irwin will make history.
</P>
<P>
   If he wins for a fourth consecutive time in Palm Beach Gardens,
Fla., Irwin will join Walter Hagen as the only player on any tour
to capture one major four consecutive times. If he fails to defend
his title, Irwin will reach the final weekend in April without a
Senior Tour triumph for the first time since he became eligible to
play a full schedule in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Irwin would prefer historic scenario No. 1. And he
couldn't be headed to a venue more conducive to breaking his
0-for-1999 slump at Senior Tour events.
</P>
<P>
   In 12 career rounds at PGA National Golf Club, Irwin's scoring
average is a sizzling 69.08 at the 6,722-yard, par-72 layout. He
won by 12 strokes in 1997, the largest landslide in tour history at
a 72-hole event. He bested Larry Nelson by seven shots last season,
matching his average margin of victory at this event.
</P>
<P>
   But Irwin is not counting on a cakewalk in his quest to join
Hagen, the PGA champion from 1924 through '27.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question I like the course. It's been good to me,
and that gives me a boost of confidence,'' said Irwin, who set
Senior Tour earnings records in 1997 ($2,343,364) and 1998
($2,861,945). ``But the odds are still stacked against me. A lot of
things have to break your way to win a major championship, much
less four in a row.''
CHIP SHOTS COLONIAL FIELD UPDATE
</P>
<P>
   MasterCard Colonial officals have issued sponsor's exemptions to
seven players for the May 20-23 event: Esteban Toledo, Duffy
Waldorf, Brian Watts, Frank Nobilo, David Ogrin, Mike Hulbert and
Dave Stockton Jr. Inclusion of those players brings the total
number of commitments to 87, including two of the top three players
in the world rankings: No. 1 David Duval and No. 3 Davis Love III.
</P>
<P>
   Tournament officials have five exemptions yet to bestow for the
1999 event, as well as two champion's choice spots selected by a
vote of past winners.
ELS SKIPPING AREA STOPS
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, winner of the 1995 GTE Byron Nelson Classic, has
informed tournament officials that he will skip this year's event
(May 13-16) to prepare for the Deutsche Bank-SAP Open in
Heidelberg, Germany. The German event is scheduled May 21-24,
overlapping Colonial week.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Nelson officials said Els is the only competitor
committed to play in Germany who has told them he would miss their
event for travel reasons. Other high-profile PGA Tour players on
the commitment list in Germany include Tiger Woods, Mark O'Meara
and Nick Price.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson officials said they expect Woods, the 1997 Nelson winner,
to compete at the Four Seasons TPC Las Colinas because he has
inquired about hotel arrangements for that week. But he has not
made an official commitment.
Brooks' scouting report
</P>
<P>
   Mark Brooks will be attempting to survive the cut at the MCI
Classic Hilton Head Island, S.C., when the first paying customers
tee off Friday at the Brooks-designed Southern Oaks Golf Club in
south Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   The course marks the first 18-hole project that Brooks has
overseen from blueprint to completion. For those seeking an early
scouting report, Brooks said to expect a traditional layout with
none of the oversized waste areas or island greens made popular in
recent years by Pete Dye and others. Also, don't look for a
signature hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe in them,'' Brooks said. ``I hope 18 different
guys play the course and come away with 18 different ideas about
which hole is best.''
</P>
<P>
   From the front tees, which can play as short as 5,600 yards,
players are required to hit only one drive over water. The back
tees, which measure 7,300 yards, will present a much greater
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we did a really good job with routing the holes, and
with the bunkering. We tried not to make all the bunkers the
same,'' Brooks said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the clubhouse remains under construction, Brooks is
low-key about Friday's opening but plans to be on hand for a
grand-opening gala this summer.
INSIDE THE NUMBERS Repeat after me
</P>
<P>
   Harbour Town Golf Links, site of this week's MCI Classic, has
crowned a multiple winner of the event 17 times in its first 30
tournaments. Topping the list is defending champ Davis Love III, a
four-time winner. A breakdown: Golfer Titles Years Davis Love III 4
1998, 1992, 1991, 1987 Hale Irwin 3 1994, 1973, 1971 Payne Stewart
2 1990, 1989 Fuzzy Zoeller 2 1986, 1983 Tom Watson 2 1982, 1979
Hubert Green 2 1978, 1976 Johnny Miller 2 1974, 1972
nn
</P>
