<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALVESTON PREPARES FOR `BEACH PARTY WEEKEND' 

</HEADLINE>
 PARTY-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KEVIN MORAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALVESTON, Texas _ More than 100,000 people may swarm the
beachfront here this weekend to participate in what has become one
of the biggest _ and most costly _ events on this island resort
city's annual calendar.
</P>
<P>
   The city will spend more than $200,000 to pay overtime to its
own police officers and hire several hundred other area officers to
control traffic and prevent the gridlock that has occurred in some
previous years. Tens of thousands of cars are expected to invade
the island during the three-day event, which begins Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have a lot of people at the beach party and
it's going to be very expensive,'' said Police Chief Kim
Schoolcraft.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly called ``Kappa Weekend'' because it was associated with
a national black college fraternity, this weekend's happening now
is dubbed simply ``Beach Party Weekend.'' The event began about 15
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It will radically alter traffic patterns on the island, and
visitors to Galveston need to pay attention to signs and police as
they enter the city on Interstate 45, Schoolcraft said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the vast majority of those who attend the event are
day-trippers from the Houston area, many others stay the weekend,
filling hotels and packing restaurants and gift shops. In years
past, crowds have overwhelmed some businesses and restaurants and
many local people have complained of rowdy behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Because most people attending the event have tended to cruise
the beach in their cars, police last year began channeling the
Beach Party Weekend traffic into a huge one-way route running east
on Broadway then back west along Seawall Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints were fewer last year than in 1997 because traffic
kept moving.
</P>
<P>
   Police are reminding people that it is illegal to consume
alcohol or have glass containers on Seawall Boulevard, and that
they will cite violators. The fine and court costs add up to
$246.25 for alcohol consumption and $106.26 for carrying glass
containers.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's crowds, especially, could be huge and could include
people from states far away, the chief said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on the weather, we expect anywhere from 75,000 to
120,000 people,'' Schoolcraft said.
</P>
<P>
   She said doubts about whether Atlanta officials would allow a
similar gathering in their city this weekend caused students at
many predominantly black Southern colleges to make plans to head
for Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta event, called Freaknik, began on a small scale in
the early 1980s and peaked in 1994 with a raucous street party
attended by about 200,000 people. Although Freaknik is being held
again this weekend, Atlanta officials have taken steps to crack
down on rowdiness.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Freaknik attracted only about 50,000 young people.
</P>
<P>
   Another similar event is the Black College Reunion in Daytona
Beach, Fla., which was held last weekend. Police said more than
100,000 people attended but things went smoothly until a rash of
violence Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Two shootings occurred _ one of them fatal _ and there were at
least two stabbings, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In Galveston, officials are hoping their preparations will lead
to another weekend as relatively problem-free as last year's event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting ready for a big crowd,'' Schoolcraft said. ``We
pray for peace.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
