<HEADER>
A6791 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-AIRWAR-BOS &LR;      04-13 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-AIRWAR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NUMBERS INDICATE KOSOVO ACTION HAS A LONG WAY TO GO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRED KAPLAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Here's one sign that the air war in Yugoslavia
could go on for quite a while: After 21 days, officials revealed
Tuesday, NATO attack planes have flown 1,687 sorties.
</P>
<P>
   That's a lot _ but it amounts to fewer than 1/10th the number
flown in the 43 days of Operation Desert Storm, the 1991 air war
against Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The two wars are different in many ways, but the numbers suggest
what many officials and analysts say President Clinton needs to
make clearer _ that the battle over Kosovo has just begun and is,
by no means, an in-and-out thing.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, a Massachusetts Democrat and one of 50
legislators who met with Clinton Tuesday, said later in the day
that US forces might have to be involved, in one way or another,
not just for ``a matter of weeks'' but rather for ``months or even
a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said he believes NATO will eventually force Serbian leader
Slobodan Milosevic to withdraw from Kosovo and let the ethnic
Albanian refugees return to their homes. But others are less
certain, especially if NATO refuses to send in ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   The 300 additional US warplanes that NATO requested Monday
_which, along with extra planes from other allied air forces, will
bring the total in the area to nearly 1,000 _ are designed
precisely to make the operation go faster.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, said in Brussels Tuesday
that allied pilots have had only seven days of good flying weather
since the campaign began. On 10 days, cloud coverage was so dense
that more than half the sorties had to be canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``With more planes they'll be able to hit more things in a given
24 hours,'' said John Pike, a weapons specialist at the Federation
of American Scientists, a private group. ``They can take greater
advantage of breaks in the weather.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy of this air war seems to be following the principle
that Gen. Colin Powell, then chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
laid out in Desert Storm _ isolate the enemy soldiers in the field,
then destroy them.
</P>
<P>
   Clark Tuesday listed the targets struck to date: supply routes,
bridges, fuel refineries, command centers, radio relays, and,
increasingly, the troops themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon said the ``new phase'' in the
bombing campaign, to begin when the extra planes arrive, will
amount to ``a more intense version of the current phase.''
</P>
<P>
   However, several analysts note, it's one thing to bomb targets,
another to destroy a fighting force, and another thing still to
accomplish the main goal, which, as Clark put it, is ``to cause
Milosevic to change his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombing campaigns through history have aimed at the same kinds
of targets that NATO is aiming at now. Some have done so
successfully. But few, if any, have by themselves changed an
opponent's mind.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in the Vietnam War, the US Air Force mounted an
earth-shaking air campaign, called Rolling Thunder, to disrupt the
flow of supplies from North Vietnam to the Viet Cong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rolling Thunder did reduce the flow from the North by over 90
percent,'' said Robert Pape, professor of national security studies
at Dartmouth College. ``The problem was we couldn't get that last
10 percent _ and they were able to keep going on that.''
</P>
<P>
   Eliot Cohen, professor of strategic studies at Johns Hopkins
University's School for Advanced International Studies and the
director of the US Air Force's official, five-volume history of the
Gulf air war, made a similar point.
</P>
<P>
   Bombing supply lines and petroleum refineries, Cohen said,
``works only when you make the other guy consume fuel and
ammunition.'' And the only way to get him to do that is to force
him to move his tanks and fire his bullets _ in other words, to
engage him with troops on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's minimal impact in attacking logistics lines and
petroleum refineries if they're just sitting there, dug in,'' he
said. ``My guess is, they've also thought ahead of time about
hiding supplies, too.''
</P>
<P>
   As for disrupting Milosevic's ability to control and communicate
with his troops, it may be worth noting that in the Gulf War, 580
air strikes were mounted on Saddam Hussein's command-control
facilities _ 260 against Iraq's leaders and their workplaces. Yet,
the Air Force later concluded that ``despite the lethality and
precision of the attacks,'' Hussein's ability to command his forces
``had not collapsed. ... The system turned out to be more redundant
and more able to reconstitute itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, other analysts, including some who have been
skeptical of past US military ventures, are more optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   William Arkin, a former US Army intelligence officer, said:
``There comes a point in a bombing campaign when the enemy starts
to unravel.'' In Kosovo, he said, this point will not take very
long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Yugoslav army is a force dependent on its garrisons. As
you destroy their garrisons and their logistics, that army
atrophies,'' Arkin said. ``If NATO ground forces are needed to go
in there, it will be to mop up a badly defeated Yugoslav army.''
</P>
<P>
   Pike agreed. He foresees the war ending in six weeks or so, with
an international security force leading refugees back into Kosovo.
``The question becomes, how much gunfire accompanies the security
forces?'' he said. ``My own view is, given another several weeks of
bombing, the Serbian forces will be in the same shape as the Iraqi
forces were when we started the ground war over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen and Pape are less hopeful. In the Gulf War, Iraq's tanks
sat defenseless on the Kuwaiti desert's flat terrain _ while the
Serbs' are dispersed in villages or hiding in forests, much harder
to hit or even see.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Gulf War, the allied bombing destroyed just 20
percent of Iraq's tanks, artillery, and armored personnel carriers.
``It's not impossible to get them,'' Pape said, ``but it's very
difficult, and it will take a long time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
