<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0307 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CHISOX-REDSOX-BOS     04-13 1269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHISOX-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SABERHAGEN LEADS RED SOX TO 6-0 DRUBBING OF CHICAGO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- If the Olde Towne wants to celebrate the fast start of
the Red Sox, who shut out the Chicago White Sox, 6-0, in Tuesday's
home opener to run their record to 6-1, Bret Saberhagen says party
on. Just don't expect the team to join in yet.
</P>
<P>
   Let there be songs in praise of Saberhagen, who ignored
48-degree temperatures and gusts of 35 miles an hour to deliver
another turn-back-the-clock performance with a suddenly pain-free
shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Trumpet flourishes for newcomer Jose Offerman, who gave the Sox
their first lead in Fenway Park by tripling to the triangle in his
second at-bat in home whites, driving in two runs and scoring a
third on Darren Lewis's single in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   A snappy guitar riff for Derek Lowe, who tightroped his way out
of a bases-loaded jam in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   A clash of cymbals for Troy O'Leary, whose three-run home run
into the White Sox bullpen sealed the outcome in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Even a good-natured waaaahh-waaaahh for John Valentin, who
passed Lewis on the basepaths to kill a first-inning uprising, one
of those daffy did-that-really-just-happen? moments you expect in a
T-ball game, not on Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   But Saberhagen, for one, was happy that in the winners'
clubhouse Tuesday afternoon, there was no music blaring. Only
cartoons on the big-screen TV.
</P>
<P>
   Strike up the band in October, not for an April win against the
youngest team in the American League, one that the day before being
blanked by the Red Sox lost an exhibition to its Triple A team.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just go out and play ball,'' said Saberhagen, who gave the
White Sox just six singles in 6 2/3 innings and departed to a
standing ovation from a sellout crowd of 31,874 that broke through
the day's chill and left him feeling warm and fuzzy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be really tough for somebody who didn't watch the
game to come into our clubhouse after a game and tell if we won or
lost. It's good we don't have music in the clubhouse. With music
playing, everybody gets too excited when you win. Then when you
lose and don't have the music on, there's too much emphasis on one
loss.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis here, one week into a season that represents the
team's best start in 44 years, was plain for everyone to see,
assuming they could see through the holes in their ski masks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure I'm happy and pleased that we're 6-1,'' said old hand
Valentin, ``but you've got to put it in perspective. We've played
good ball, and we've gotten good pitching. That's the reason we're
6-1.''
</P>
<P>
   For the sixth time in seven games, Sox pitchers limited the
opposition to three runs or fewer. All of the starters save Pat
Rapp have gone at least six innings, the measure of a quality
start, and staff ace Pedro Martinez and Saberhagen already have two
wins apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Saberhagen, who threw six shutout innings in 76-degree
temperatures in Kansas City last Wednesday, had some trouble
weathering the first two innings. He loaded the bases in the first,
walking two batters, including Magglio Ordonez on four pitches,
before striking out Paul Konerko on the next three.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, he gave up one-out singles to Brook Fordyce and
McKay Christensen, before catching two more hitters, Ray Durham and
Mike Caruso, looking at third strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so scatter-brained, my mechanics were so off, I didn't
know where the ball was going,'' Saberhagen said.
</P>
<P>
   But after that, he was locked in, allowing just three more hits,
two of them bloopers, before being replaced by Lowe with two out in
the seventh after Caruso's floater to center dropped in for a
single.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd, already grumbling because manager Jimy Williams
lifted Saberhagen with a 3-0 lead after a yield of 102 pitches,
threatened to turn mutinous when White Sox strongman Frank Thomas
dropped a ground-rule double just inside the right-field foul line
and Lowe walked Jeff Liefer on four pitches to load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   The murmurs turned louder and darker when Lowe, who had
surrendered home runs in each of his previous two outings, went to
a 3-and-0 count on the next hitter, Ordonez. A mock cheer greeted
Lowe when he finally threw a strike, but to the relief of both the
pitcher and his critics, Ordonez rapped a one-hopper back to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would not believe how happy I was when the guy hit the
ground ball back to me,'' Lowe said. ``After those seven straight
(balls) and those boos, I was looking for something positive to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After a winter in which the mere mention of his name caused
negative vibes, Offerman continued his rousing rebuttal. He
launched his third triple in seven games (and 15th hit overall)
after White Sox starter Jim Parque did the unpardonable, walking
the bottom feeders in the Sox order, Jason Varitek and Donnie
Sadler, with two out and nobody on.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman, greeted with warm applause during pregame
introductions, received his first Fenway Park standing O after his
hit rattled around the 420-foot sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans like him,'' said general manager Dan Duquette, whose
own name had picked up some mud after he lavished a $26 million
contract on Offerman. ``He's an exciting player, a clutch player.''
</P>
<P>
   Offerman's hit not only gave the Sox the lead, it also allowed
Valentin to exhale after his base-running boner in the first
inning, when the Sox had the bases loaded with one out and came
away with nothing. Valentin, who had singled after Lewis's base
hit, was on second after Parque walked Mike Stanley on a full
count.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary whacked Parque's first pitch on a line to left. On a day
when the wind wasn't howling from left field, it might have been
off the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis remained a couple steps off the third-base bag, preparing
to tag and score on what should have been a routine sacrifice fly.
Routine, that is, until Valentin took the turn like Jeff Gordon
hugging the curve at Talladega and chugged past a shocked Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``My experience,'' Valentin said, mocking his own brain lock.
``When I saw it come off the bat, I said, `There's no way this is
catchable.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Question: Did you know you had passed Lewis?
</P>
<P>
   Valentin: Obviously.
</P>
<P>
   Question: And what thought ran through your mind at that
instant?
</P>
<P>
   Valentin: Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   Question: Have you ever passed a base-runner before, or even
passed on the turnpike?
</P>
<P>
   Valentin: Nope. I usually do the speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   In the eighth, Valentin, who walked ahead of Stanley, was in no
danger of getting a speeding ticket. All he had to do was jog when
O'Leary crushed an 0-and-2 pitch from lefthanded reliever Bryan
Ward over the new advertising signs on the visitors' bullpen.
Performance.com indeed.
</P>
<P>
   New Boston reliever Mark Guthrie, who lived in Scituate until he
was 11, worked a 1-2-3 ninth, and the Fenway organ sang out the
news of another Sox win. It'll be the White Sox here again
Thursday, with Martinez bidding for win No. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a good pitching staff,'' said Pedro's older brother,
Ramon, who made his first appearance in a Red Sox uniform Tuesday
during introductions, though he is still rehabilitating his
surgically repaired right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I get 100 percent,'' he said, ``I can help this team a lot.
If they play the same way they've been playing, they have a chance
to win a lot, like they did last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine, the Sox hoping to get help from a pitcher with a blown
shoulder. Who comes up with these ideas?
</P>
<P>
   That's one question nobody thought to ask Saberhagen.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
