<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO COMMANDER GIVES FIRST DETAILED DESCRIPTION OF AIR CAMPAIGN'S
IMPACT
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ The NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
delivered the first comprehensive assessment of the campaign
against Yugoslavia on Tuesday, saying that the allies had damaged
every broad sector of the Serbian military, but that President
Slobodan Milosevic appeared determined to ride out the air war and
showed no sign of withdrawing from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an hour-long presentation, Clark used an array of statistics
and a blizzard of maps, photos and videotapes to make his case that
the alliance had the firepower to grind down Yugoslavia's military
and was proceeding methodically toward that goal.
</P>
<P>
   Underscoring that the Serbian military has endured only a small
dose of NATO's striking power, Clark confirmed Tuesday that he will
seek still more allied warplanes, pushing the air armada to more
than 1,000 aircraft. The reinforcements would include 300
additional American planes, he said. Senior officials have said the
Pentagon was planning on approving the request.
</P>
<P>
   After almost 1,700 bombing runs, Clark said that NATO had caused
damage to every broad strategic area, such as air defense, command
centers, oil production, military units in the field and military
transport. None were considered to be destroyed, he said, although
NATO does contend to have destroyed many individual targets within
the broader areas.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clark stopped short of declaring that the alliance would
win a victory from the air. He said only that Yugoslav's military
was potentially ``vulnerable to collapse'' if enough military
pressure was applied, but tried to sidestep any political question.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether NATO's political leaders had been too slow to act
against Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic earlier this year,
Clark said, ``You're asking judgments about political leadership,
which it's not appropriate for me to give.''
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks of air attacks intended to cause Milosevic so
much military pain that he would withdraw his troops and agrees to
allied conditions for a settlement, Clark acknowledged, Milosevic
does not appear to be cowed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we have said from the outset, this is likely to be as long
and difficult as President Milosevic makes it,'' Clark said. ``And
we're approaching it very systematically.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark spoke at NATO's headquarters here as Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and the Russian Foreign Minister Igor S. Ivanov
met in Oslo, but failed to resolve their differences over NATO
insistence that an allied military force police any peace in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, President Clinton and congressional leaders from
both parties tried to avert any attempt by Congress to vote on the
eventual use of ground forces in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   As the military commander of a 19-member alliance, Clark, who
has had about as much personal contact with Milosevic and his top
generals as any NATO diplomat, confronts a complex political, as
well as military, equation. His aim is to send the Serbs a message
that NATO has the firepower to break their will while trying to
reassure Western political leaders and voters that the alliance
would use only the minimum force that was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The task has not always been easy. Since the attacks began three
weeks ago, NATO says the bombings have been hobbled by bad weather,
a limited number of aircraft and political constraints. Critics
have complained that the alliance was withholding crucial details
in an effort to mask disappointing results.
</P>
<P>
   A four-star Army general, Clark, 54, is not an obvious choice
for Pentagon to send before the world's television cameras to sing
the praises of air power. On Tuesday, however, he did so in a
measured and qualified way. His methodical, technocratic style
contrasted with the blustery manner of some of his predecessors,
like Gen. H. Norman Schwarzkopf during the 1991 Gulf War, a plus
for an alli- ance that is still skittish about the notion of ground
forces and eager for a negotiated solution.
</P>
<P>
   Seeking to solidify Western support, Clark began by documenting
the steady Serbian military build-up in Kosovo in recent months.
His presentation was intended to show that Milosevic had repeatedly
violated his promises to withdraw from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But it also inadvertently raised questions about the adequacy of
the alliance's military planning, which initially relied on limited
air attacks to punish the Serbian forces for their assaults on the
Albanian population in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, in a remarkable personal aside, Clark recalled in
some detail an October meeting he had in Belgrade with a leading
Serbian general, who insisted that the Yugoslav military could have
finished off the Kosovo Liberation Army, Albanian separatist
rebels, in two more weeks if it had been permitted to continue its
sweep of Albanian villages and towns.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said to him, `Yes, and you created about 400,000
homeless people in this process in a campaign that's totally
disproportionate to any reasonable definition of a threat. It's a
political problem and you've tried to solve it by force,' '' Clark
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and the general had a ``long dialectical discussion''
and added: ``That's when I realized that there was still this very
strong proclivity to believe that this problem was a problem which
was appropriate to be solved by military force and the target would
be the population, since they couldn't get at the KLA directly.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with another politically sensitive issue, Clark said
there was little NATO &UR;  &LR; could do to ease the plight of the hundreds
of thousands of Albanians that have been driven from their homes by
Serb forces and are now homeless within Kosovo with very little
food.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, NATO ambassadors asked Clark to look into ways to
provide food and medicine to the civilians there. But Tuesday, the
NATO commander said it would take 60 to 100 flights of slow-moving
transport planes each day to drop relief supplies and that the
aircraft might be shot down by Serb's air defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our view on this is that, frankly, this is a problem that's
caused by President Milosevic,'' Clark said. ``He needs to address
this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Offering new data, Clark noted that the alliance had flown 5,924
missions, but that only 1,687 of these were bombing missions.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the distances involved, a larger percentage of the
alliance's missions consist of flights by refueling planes than in
previous air campaigns. And since Belgrade demonstrated its
potential to lash out by dispatching two Russian-made MIG warplanes
over Bosnia last month, the alliance is also maintaining constant
air patrols around Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Clark insisted, however, that NATO's bombing strikes were
effective since the vast majority of strikes are being carried out
with laser-guided bombs and other precision-guided munitions.
</P>
<P>
   For much of the campaign, Clark acknowledged, the bombing
attacks have been handicapped by poor weather. Over three weeks, he
said, NATO forces had enjoyed good weather on only seven days. On
10 days, he said, more than 50 percent of the bombing missions were
canceled because of bad weather.
</P>
<P>
   Clark sought to turn these statistic into a public relations
advantage, noting that the allies' striking power could grow
substantially as skies clear over the Balkans over the next several
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Describing the bomb damage assessment, Clark said the alliance
was in a race, trying to damage Serb supplies and equipment faster
than the Yugoslav military could replace or repair it.
</P>
<P>
   NATO, for example, has destroyed 70 percent of Yugoslavia's
storage capability for fuel, Clark said. Belgrade, however, is
continuing to receive fuel from oil foreign oil tankers. NATO is
hoping friendly nations will order those shipments stopped.
</P>
<P>
   For all the bombing, however, Clark conceded that there is no
evidence that the Serb military is withdrawing from Kosovo. At
40,000 troops, the Serbs force have even increased slightly since
the NATO bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen no evidence of any pull-back of Serb military or
police forces,'' he said. ``They are moving into defensive
positions in some areas. In other cases, they are continuing with
the pattern of ethnic cleansing and village destruction. And in a
third set of instances, they are regrouping, refitting,
reconstituting and preparing for future operations.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Milosevic, Clark said the goal was to pressure him to
accept the allied requirements for a Kosovo accord by striking the
security forces and military command and control he relies on to
maintain his hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   But a slide in Clark's presentation suggested that Milosevic
would not be easy to intimidate. ``Milosevic's Willingness To
Accept Damage Is High,'' it read.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
