<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HURRICANE-TORN CENTRAL AMERICA STILL WAITING FOR FINANCING 
 

</HEADLINE>
 AMERICA-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JENALIA MORENO 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Last fall's Hurricane Mitch killed more than 9,000
people and destroyed everything from power lines to major bridges.
</P>
<P>
   The floods and mud slides that came with the killer storm swept
away bridges, factories and hospitals in countries that can't
afford to replace them.
</P>
<P>
   While food and money poured in from international relief
agencies, the region needs more than just temporary aid. It needs
$8 billion to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   A region with a gross domestic product of $24.2 billion can't
foot the bill for recovery on its own, according to the Economic
Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The World Bank and Inter-American Development Bank, among
others, pledged $6 billion in loans to help rebuild El Salvador,
Guatemala, Honduras and Nicaragua.
</P>
<P>
   But the region won't see most of this money until this summer,
after a high-level meeting in Stockholm, Sweden, in late May.
That's when the four nations detail how they plan to spend the
money needed to rebuild roads, bridges, hospitals and schools.
</P>
<P>
   In a sort of dress rehearsal for that meeting, Central American
government officials and funding organizers will meet Wednesday and
Thursday at Texas A&AMP;M University's George Bush Presidential Library
in College Station.
</P>
<P>
   Key players attending the meeting in Stockholm will discuss how
to rebuild the region's telecommunications and agriculture
industries and its roads and bridges.
</P>
<P>
   Until the financing comes through, Central Americans and all the
people involved in the effort live in a state of limbo.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a lot of inaction,'' said Dennis Wright, business
acquisition planning adviser for Brown &AMP; Root Services Corp. in
Houston. ``Six months has passed and very little substantive work
has been done. Today, you may come away with the perception that
life has returned to normal because the people have learned to
accommodate the inconveniences.''
</P>
<P>
   While the companies have been unable to close a deal, they've
been out selling their services.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, 16 U.S.-based companies went on a week-long trade
mission to the region with David Aaron, Commerce Department
undersecretary for international trade.
</P>
<P>
   They saw how Central Americans have pushed aside debris, put up
temporary bridges and made makeshift fixes because they can't
afford to rebuild, said Wright, who was on the mission.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department plans two more such trips to the region
later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``These long-range relationships will benefit the United States
and Central American countries for a long time to come,'' Aaron
said during a telephone conference with reporters while he was in
Managua, Nicaragua. ``We're trying to get in on the ground floor.''
</P>
<P>
   The need for work has drawn construction, telecommunications and
water purification companies from around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department's trade mission was a follow-up to
President Clinton's trip to Central America. Clinton is trying to
push a $950 million aid package for the four countries through
Congress now.
</P>
<P>
   But that measure does not tackle the region's problems of debt,
poverty, economic development and low levels of education, said
Economic Policy Institute economist Robert E. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's package, ``is a proposal for trade enhancement,''
wrote the economist for the Washington D.C.-based economic think
tank. ``Humanitarian assistance and relief designed to simply
replace what was lost will only set the stage for future disasters
of even greater magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Much to the frustration of businesses interested in selling to
Central Americans and even more so to those living in the region,
reconstruction will not begin until after the Stockholm meeting.
</P>
<P>
   American businesses have made some sales there.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Weiss, president of Dallas-based Global Water Technologies,
said the trip boosted sales for his 12-person company, which had
not done business in Central America before the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss wanted to show Central Americans how his water
purification system could remove contaminants. He said he expects
$2 million in sales from the trip and could make another $18
million in sales this year if international aid comes through.
</P>
<P>
   He described a typical exchange with a potential customer:
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Do you like the system?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `Yes.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Do you like the price?'
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `We love it.'
</P>
<P>
   ``We said, `Have you got the money?'
</P>
<P>
   ``And they said `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   Once the reconstruction begins, exports to Central America
should skyrocket, with much of it flowing through the Gulf Coast.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few months, Chiquita Brands International and Dole
Food Co. have sent ships carrying relief supplies to Guatemala and
Honduras from the Port of Freeport in Texas, which receives most of
this region's bananas.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's trade with the region remained the same last year at
$486 million.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. trade with Central America increased slightly last year to
$19 billion from $17.3 billion in 1997, according to the Census
Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   So, until the bidding for the big projects begins, U.S.-based
companies compete with their foreign counterparts by literally
bridging Central America's gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Baker Concrete Construction/Conspan based in Houston donated a
20-foot bridge to Honduras. The company plans to send this
prefabricated bridge to Honduras by plane and show the government
an example of its work. It could translate into more sales of the
company's bridges for the hundreds of spans wiped out by the storm.
</P>
<P>
   After the hurricane, Brown &AMP; Root Services worked for Chiquita
as consultants for flood control protection of its plantations.
Brown &AMP; Root officials would like the job of overseeing and
directing the hundreds of companies needed to rebuild Central
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little concerned that they may try to piecemeal it to
fix it,'' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
