<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MAGICMAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magician Blaine leaves the public speechless
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On a busy New York sidewalk at dusk, magician David Blaine stops
a woman out for a walk and asks her to think of the name of someone
important to her. While she's thinking, a yellow taxi drives by on
the street behind them with the name ``Dawn'' scrawled on the side,
graffiti-style. Blaine points it out to her, and she freaks.
</P>
<P>
   And so will most viewers of Blaine's magic act tonight on ABC.
It's a magic show for people who don't like magic shows _ no
spangle-bedecked assistants, no white tigers, no sawing anybody in
half, no bombastic music. In short, no Vegas. Just Blaine, walking
around city streets in Manhattan and Memphis, accosting passers-by
and pulling off simple but astonishing tricks that leave them
open-mouthed in amazement.
</P>
<P>
   He does a card trick, and makes the chosen card appear inside
his victim's shoe. He swallows a long black thread, then lifts his
shirt and appears to pull it directly out of the skin over his
stomach.
</P>
<P>
   Other professional magicians say Blaine doesn't bring anything
new to the craft, that it's all just packaging. But so much of
magic is packaging, and Blaine's is just flat-out funkier than
anybody else's. Working completely outdoors in public with regular
people makes his act seem street-savvy. And then there's the magic
man himself: hip black T-shirt and jeans, Marine buzz cut, swarthy,
handsome, charismatic.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if Blaine has taken a misstep in his careful
image-crafting lately, it was that publicity stunt of being buried
under a New York sidewalk for seven days. It seemed so hokey, so
Copperfieldian, compared to the millennial coolness Blaine has
cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, ABC ran Blaine's first special. It wasn't a
blockbuster in the ratings, but everyone who saw it was obsessed
with talking about it the next day. Don't be fooled: Watch Blaine
tonight, and get ready to catch your jaw.
</P>
<P>
   GRADE: A-
</P>
<P>
   For links and more on Blaine and magic in general, go to:
www.linkingpage.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
