<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARENTS-EZZO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIBLE-BASED PARENTING PROGRAM HAS MANY CONVERTS, CRITICS 
</HEADLINE>
 METHOD-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ For Lori and Scott Hashimoto, the first seven weeks of
parenthood were, by their own admission, ``hell.''
</P>
<P>
   Little Blake would cry. Lori would nurse him. He'd cry some
more. And so it went, round-the-clock, as the weeks rolled by in a
blur of broken sleep. Weary and discouraged, Lori even developed
blisters from her infant's strong and frequent sucking.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, that giant sucking sound was Scott and Lori
pulling the plug on ``child-centered'' parenting.
</P>
<P>
   They turned instead to a controversial ``Bible-based'' program
whose popularity has alarmed mainstream parenting experts and
created dissension among conservative Christians.
</P>
<P>
   The Hashimotos, who live in Lynnwood, Wash., say the parenting
program developed by Gary and Anne Marie Ezzo of Chatsworth,
Calif., restored their sanity and quieted Blake's distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within two weeks, he was sleeping through 10 to 12 hours
without having to cry,'' says Scott, 35, an occupational therapist
with a home health agency. ``We got him on a routine during the day
and that's what stabilized him.''
</P>
<P>
   But many pediatricians and lactation experts say the Ezzo
routine comes at a cost, and babies pay the price. In extreme
cases, they say, babies are at risk of failure to thrive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've suddenly boiled over,'' said British psychologist
Penelope Leach, author of the still-popular child-development
guide, ``Your Baby &AMP; Child'' (Alfred A. Knopf, 559 pages, $35),
first published in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   Leach, a founder of the British branch of the World Association
for Infant Mental Health, said she plans to voice her alarm over
the Ezzo program at an April 20 talk at Seattle's Tools for Parents
Lecture Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's called sticking your neck out,'' Leach said in a
phone interview from London.
</P>
<P>
   Despite having no formal training in the field, the Ezzos, who
have five grandchildren, are not shy about bucking established
views on child development, as popularized by authorities such as
Leach and Dr. T. Berry Brazelton.
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos' advice: For trouble-free days and nights, put your
newborn on a feeding schedule and don't rush to pick her up when
she cries. After all, they say, God did not immediately answer
Christ's agonized cries on the cross, and half an hour of crying
won't hurt a baby that's kept clean and fed on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your baby will not lose brain cells, experience a drop in IQ
or have feelings of rejection that will leave him manic-depressive
at age thirty,'' says ``On Becoming Babywise,'' the secular version
of their church-based program.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand,'' it adds, ``if you want a fussy baby,
never let him cry, and hold, rock and feed him as soon as he starts
to fuss. We guarantee, you will achieve your goal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Appalled'' by such advice, Leach says the American Academy of
Pediatrics has been too timid in responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there must be a lot of people out there who are as
sickened by (the Ezzos) as I am,'' Leach said.
</P>
<P>
   The American Academy of Pediatrics has taken no position on the
Ezzo program but, in response to widespread concern among its
membership, is evaluating it and other parenting programs.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Kyle Yasuda, president of the Washington state chapter of
the academy, said he does not recommend the Ezzo approach to his
patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does raise some flags,'' he said, adding that he is
concerned about nutritional and behavioral aspects of the program.
``This kind of regimented approach doesn't sound like a nurturing
environment to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos initially recommended four-hour feeding intervals for
infants, but now say 2{- to three-hour ``parent-directed'' feedings
are fine.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such adjustments, infant development specialists are
still concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to throw those books away!'' said Katy Brock
Jameson, clinical manager for the department at Seattle's Swedish
Hospital that does home visits and education for new moms.
</P>
<P>
   She said she has seen babies fail to regain their birth weight
after two weeks on the Ezzo schedule. Although some kids can
probably adapt, she said, ``in other cases I believe there may be
damage done.''
</P>
<P>
   Lactation specialists say nursing on demand, up to 12 or even 18
times a day in a newborn, optimizes the supply and fat content of
the mother's milk while also quenching infant's thirst, building
its immunity, stimulating bowel movements and providing comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they cry for prolonged periods, it burns up calories that
can otherwise be used for growth,'' Jameson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos' course materials are marketed through Growing
Families International (GFI), their $4-million-a-year, for-profit
company, which they refer to as a ministry.
</P>
<P>
   Churches _ especially conservative, evangelical churches _ are
the prime venue for their classes, including their core course,
``Growing Kids God's Way.'' According to GFI, Ezzo materials have
been used by about 6,000 churches _ involving nearly 1.5 million
parents _ in 95 countries.
</P>
<P>
   The Ezzos also have a secular following through the books ``On
Becoming Babywise'' and ``On Becoming Babywise Book Two'' by Gary
Ezzo and Dr. Robert Bucknam, who wrote the forward (both books from
Multnomah Press, $9.99).
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason why our material has been so successful is because
it works,'' said Robert Garcia, GFI's executive vice president and
the Ezzos' son-in-law. (The Ezzos declined to be interviewed for
this story.)
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said failure to thrive is not an outcome of the Ezzos'
feeding method. ``I think it's something that just happens with
babies sometimes,'' he said, adding that the Ezzo program gives
parents ``hope'' and ``relief'' from being ``almost a slave to the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   Raising children is not a matter of chance, he said, it's a
matter of ``right parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   The program's bedrock principles are that the husband-wife
relationship is paramount, and that children should begin early to
learn self-control, respect, unquestioning obedience and honesty.
</P>
<P>
   In a philosophy that frequently clashes with established ideas
of child development, they also teach that infants are born with a
``sin nature.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, instead of viewing temper tantrums as a normal and
fleeting stage, the Ezzos teach in ``Growing Kids God's Way'' that
``a temper tantrum is the ultimate rejection of parental
authority.''
</P>
<P>
   Defying conventional wisdom, they recommend structured playpen
time to help babies develop orderliness, mental focusing skills and
creativity _ which they call a function of boundaries, not freedom.
</P>
<P>
   They also encourage ``high-chair manners'' for babies as young
as 8 months, with a swat or hand squeeze if baby fails to use sign
language for ``please'' and ``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in late toddlerhood, Ezzo discipline follows a flow
chart that culminates in spanking, or ``biblical chastisement''
with a flexible tool chosen to inflict pain without causing injury.
The Ezzos have suggested a rubber spatula would do the job.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Ezzos' written words seem harsh and unambiguous,
families who take the courses say they emphasize positive
discipline and flexibility aimed at cultivating goodness in their
children's hearts.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hashimoto suspects the program's very success has spawned
professional jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Leach, however, laments that parents today find moderation
``boring.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing I do or say amounts to a kind of child-rearing
program,'' Leach said. ``That's what people seem to want _ a
formula.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach sees the Ezzo approach as part of a growing movement
toward authoritarian parenting that is polarizing the issue of how
to raise children.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, Leach said, parents are hit with research on
critical brain development in the first three years of life _
creating panic in new parents who make minor ``blunders.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, they're sold the notion _ via Judith Rich
Harris' controversial book, ``The Nurture Assumption'' _ that what
they do as parents makes no difference, because peers are more
influential.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do think we have made the whole business of being a parent
so impossibly difficult,'' Leach said, ``that anything that looks
simple is going to get a hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Ezzos have won a fiercely loyal following. ``On
Becoming Babywise,'' published in 1995, is the
eighth-most-requested parenting book at Ingram Book Co., the
nation's largest trade book distributor.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon.com, the online bookseller, has posted 80 highly
emotional reader reviews of ``Babywise.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What a blessing to our family,'' wrote one Oregon reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started `Babywise' when our child was 6 weeks old and have
not looked back since,'' wrote a mother from Yuma, Ariz., who said
her infant was constantly crying and unhappy before they bought the
book.
</P>
<P>
   But other readers are aghast.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know a couple who used this book and the baby suffered
failure to thrive and nearly was hospitalized,'' wrote a Montana
reader.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington state reader called the book ``child hate in
disguise,'' and an Ohio reader wrote, ``If you are looking for a
convenient way to have a child who falls into a schedule and
doesn't bother you too much ... GET A DOG!''
</P>
<P>
   Bellevue pediatrician Don Shifrin said he's concerned by the
program's one-size-fits-all approach, which he believes sets
parents up for failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian community itself is divided. Focus on the Family,
a conservative group led by psychologist James Dobson of Colorado
Springs, Colo., says the Ezzo program is ``far too rigid'' and
misapplies scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Community Church in Sun Valley, Calif., where Gary Ezzo
was formerly associate pastor, has disavowed the Ezzo program.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the Christian Research Journal dissected the Ezzo
program in a 14-page article with 111 footnotes. Although it found
some benefits, the thrust was highly critical.
</P>
<P>
   ``GFI is more than a parenting ministry _ it is a cultic
community,'' the article charged.
</P>
<P>
   The Hashimotos, who now have three sons, say critics overreact
to a program that, in their view, creates loving, thinking parents.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, they spank occasionally, with a hand or a wooden spoon
(which the Ezzos don't recommend).
</P>
<P>
   But they say life overall is happy and relaxed, with well-fed,
well-trained children who are pleasant to be around.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the most appealing thing (about the program) is that
we enjoy our children when they're young,'' Scott Hashimoto said.
``For me, I feel offended when people say I'm stifling my child's
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   He says any child-rearing method can be misapplied. And while
the Ezzos seem to promise otherwise, he says no child has a
guaranteed outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is,'' Hashimoto said, ``a lot of people turn out good
and a lot of people turn out bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
