<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-DIPLO-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT MEETING WITH RUSSIAN FOREIGN MINISTER PRODUCES MEAGER
RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ The Russian foreign minister said Tuesday that
Moscow remained opposed to an international security force in
Kosovo as part of a peace plan without the approval of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   This fundamental difference between Russia and the United States
appeared to blunt any prospect that real progress would be made
soon toward a diplomatic solution in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a meeting at an airport hotel here, Igor S. Ivanov, the
Russian minister, and Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
discussed Yugoslavia. The meeting lasted more than three hours and
included other issues important to the Russian-U.S. relationship,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the encounter was as much about ensuring that
Washington-Moscow ties did not go off the rails over Kosovo as it
was about Kosovo itself, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Albright had spoken to Ivanov by phone almost daily since the
bombing began, and last week Vice President Al Gore reached out to
Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, urging him in a phone conversation
to help pursue a diplomatic solution in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The phone contacts Tuesday yielded a ``narrowing of the gap'' on
some issues, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   With Ivanov beside her at a news conference, Albright read out
some principles that the two sides could agree on: the need for a
``verifiable end'' of violence; the withdrawal of ``military police
and paramilitary forces'' from Kosovo; and the unconditional return
of all refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Polite but firm, Ivanov said Russia could not agree to an
international security force in Kosovo without ``the agreement of
the leadership of Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The international presence is one of the most complicated''
matters, he said. ``It is complicated because the leadership of
Yugoslavia comes out against any kind of military presence in
Yugoslavia.''
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has absolutely refused to entertain an outside force
in Kosovo, arguing that the province is the sovereign territory of
Serbia and Yugoslavia. His opposition was a major reason why he did
not sign the peace accords devised at Rambouillet, France, a
refusal that directly led to the NATO air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said Tuesday that the Russian reluctance to endorse an
international force before Milosevic gave his assent was compatible
with the Russian behavior during the peace talks in Dayton, Ohio,
that led to the end of the war in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   There, the Russians refused to sign the accords _ which included
a NATO-led international force _ until Milosevic agreed to sign it
at the final ceremony in Paris. Russia went on to become part of
the peacekeeping force in Bosnia and Russian soldiers remain in the
force despite Moscow's differences with NATO over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the meager results of the meeting Tuesday, Ivanov did
not rule out trying to be helpful. ``If we have to go to Belgrade,
if we have to go to Washington, we will go,'' he said of further
efforts to find a diplomatic resolution.
</P>
<P>
   But, in reality, a senior Clinton administration official said,
movement toward finding a diplomatic resolution was minimal because
Milosevic had not yet been hurt enough by the air assaults to send
out any real feelers for a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to assuage the Russians, Albright has started to
describe the international security force, which is envisioned as
escorting refugees back to Kosovo and staying there, a little more
ambiguously. Instead of calling it a NATO-led force, the secretary
now describes it as having a ``NATO-core'' with ``other elements''
contributing.
</P>
<P>
   This configuration essentially conforms with the setup of the
NATO-led force in Bosnia, where the Russian troops are part of the
force but their direct commander not a NATO officer.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   State Department officials tried to point out Tuesday that
because the Russians had been helpful in trying to put together the
peace settlement at Rambouillet they could be brought back into the
mainstream of international opinion on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Albright was trying to play on fears in the Russian leadership
that Russia could become isolated if it hangs on to its fairly
unfruitful relationship with Milosevic, administration officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leadership has felt extremely frustrated at watching
NATO and the United States act in Kosovo without any checks from
Moscow and sees its position as one of weakness, the officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia has acted boldly to jolt the Moscow-Washington
relationship. Moscow has frozen its relations with NATO, walking
out of the Permanent Joint Council that was formed for the purpose
of advising Russia about NATO activities.
</P>
<P>
   And while President Boris Yeltsin has pledged that Russia will
stay out of the Kosovo conflict, he warned last week that this
could change if the United States contemplated sending ground
troops to fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, the Clinton administration warned Moscow not to
share Russian intelligence with the Yugoslav military, saying that
such a move would bring serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said they were concerned that a Russian
intelligence ship, the Liman, positioned near the aircraft carrier
Theodore Roosevelt, appeared to be trying to count the planes
taking off from the carrier. But Pentagon officials said that so
far they had found no evidence that the Russians were handing
intelligence to Belgrade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
