<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRAIN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESTRUCTION OF TRAIN WAS `UNCANNY ACCIDENT,' NATO COMMANDER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (sw) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The NATO warplane that destroyed a passenger train
crossing a bridge in Yugoslavia on Monday spotted the train after
it was too late to abort the attack, but circled back for a second
strike against the bridge, NATO's senior general said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   On the second pass, the jet struck at the oposite end of the
bridge, which by then ``was covered with smoke and clouds,'' said
the NATO commander, Gen. Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   ``And at the last minute, again, in an uncanny accident, the
train had slid forward from the original impact,'' he said, ``and
parts of the train had moved across the bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   A cockpit video of the second strike showed a missile headed
directly into the train, hitting it for the second time, and
damaging the tracks on the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the initial strike on the train could not have been
avoided since the aircraft first fired long before the pilot
actually saw the train.
</P>
<P>
   But according to Clark's account at NATO headquarters in
Brussels, the aircraft attacked the bridge over the Juzna Morava
River near Grdelicaa second time, because the first missile had
struck the train and not the bridge itself.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has justified destroying bridges and roads in Yugoslavia,
saying a major objective of the air and missile strikes is to cut
off transportation links used to resupply Yugoslavia's military and
police forces in Kosovo. The Pentagon announced on Tuesday that 11
bridges had been destroyed so far in three weeks of attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Clark and other NATO officials declined to discuss the type of
aircraft or weapon involved in the attack, citing security for
future missions. However, officials here in Washington said the
aircraft was an American F-15E, firing a newly modified bomb known
as an AGM-130. And while Clark referred at several points to the
jet's pilot, the F-15E in fact has a crew of two, a pilot and a
weapons officer, who controls the bombs and missiles.
</P>
<P>
   The AGM-130, which can be fired at a considerable distance from
its target, is initially guided by satellite. As it nears its
target, the pilot or, in the case of an F-15, the weapons officer,
can guide it the rest of the way using the video image, such as the
one shown at NATO's headquarters on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the explanation offered on Tuesday, it was not clear why
the aircraft returned to strike the bridge again, knowing a train
was on it, since NATO's stated aim has been to avoid killing
civilians. ``He believed he still had to accomplish his mission,''
Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav authorities said the attack on the train killed at
least 10 people and seriously injured at least 16 others. The
authorities escorted journalists to the scene as part of an effort
to portray NATO's strikes as cruel and unjustified.
</P>
<P>
   Clark expressed regret for the strike and emphasized that NATO
was doing everything possible to avoid civilian casualties. ``It's
one of those regrettable things that happen in a campaign like
this,'' he said, ``and we're all very sorry for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The attack underscored the impossibility of avoiding what
Pentagon officials euphemistically call ``collateral damage,'' even
when the vast majority of the bombs and missiles being used rely on
lasers, radars and satellites to guide them with remarkable
precision.
</P>
<P>
   By showing footage of the strikes, NATO clearly hoped to dispel
criticism that the attack on the train had been wanton. As the
first missile homed in on the bridge, the train entered into view
in what Clark called ``a flash of movement.'' The video ended
seconds later when the missile struck.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the train coming in,'' he said. ``And unfortunately, he
couldn't dump the bomb at that point. It was locked. It was going
into the target.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
