<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS' INCURSION INTO ALBANIA RAISES MORE QUESTIONS FOR NATO 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRAGG HINES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ If NATO leaders won't take a ground war to Slobodan
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president can take one to them.
</P>
<P>
   The brief incursion into Albania by Serb forces Tuesday is a
provocative and potentially explosive development.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the scale and duration of any repetition,
Milosevic's attempt to widen the Kosovo conflict could be his
wiliest bid yet to crack NATO's unity in the Balkan conflict. And
the alliance's response to this nose tweak from Belgrade and any
encore can help answer _ or, more ominously, deepen _ questions
about how well the NATO campaign against Milosevic was thought
through before it was begun.
</P>
<P>
   The cross-border incident drew predictable cries of outrage from
the alliance and the Clinton administration. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright promised ``serious consequences'' for such
behavior but did not detail her threat.
</P>
<P>
   Given Milosevic's history of testing and toying with Washington
and NATO, the Serbs' hour-long raid into Albania should not have
been unexpected. Also, his forces had been shelling the border
region for several days.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have begun to use Albania as a base of operations _
``like a big aircraft carrier,'' said one defense establishment
wag. The government in Tirana has all but handed over the keys to
enable NATO to use its nation for military and humanitarian
purposes. Also, the much-discussed and much-anticipated Apache
helicopters being dispatched by the Pentagon for close-in fighting
in Kosovo will operate from Albania.
</P>
<P>
   That could be an alluring target for the Serbs. As Maj. Gen.
Charles Wald, a planning chief for the Joint Chiefs of Staff, made
plain at the Pentagon briefing Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just helicopters that are going,'' Wald said.
``There's a force protection package ... fighting vehicles and
infantry folks.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be almost unreasonable to expect Milosevic, who seems
to have an exquisite appreciation of Old Testament justice, to
overlook this point. And NATO will be lucky if the raid Tuesday is
a one-of-a-kind.
</P>
<P>
   That the daylight incursion could be the first of many is a
sobering point for NATO planners to ponder _ on several levels.
</P>
<P>
   First, the allies have promised Albania, as well as Macedonia,
protection from Serb aggression. And they repeated it Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Politically, we've conveyed some very strong messages to the
neighboring states,'' State Department spokesman James Foley said,
pointing out that NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana ``has made
clear that the security, the territorial inviolability of the
neighboring states, are of direct and material concern to the
alliance, and that the alliance will react if there are attacks on
those territories, particularly in conjunction with the presence of
NATO forces on those territories.''
</P>
<P>
   At some point the Albanians would have the right to ask NATO to
make good on the pledge. That would add to the planning and
logistical headaches that already exist in Brussels, Belgium, the
NATO headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   If it's just border protection, that's difficult on any
long-term basis from the air. And it's no snap from the ground, as
the three U.S. servicemen being held captive in Serbia found out
one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   And if there are engagements between NATO and Serb forces along
the border, it soon becomes a ground war, no matter how briefers on
either side try to dress it up.
</P>
<P>
   That leads to the second problem for NATO. The polls in the
United States and western Europe showing that qualified support for
using ground forces against Milosevic would almost certainly wilt
if the casualty reports shot up.
</P>
<P>
   Casualties, in turn, would almost certainly lead to new
challenges to NATO unity.
</P>
<P>
   Foley addressed the point in attempting to assess Milosevic's
motivation for the Albanian incursion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think clearly Belgrade is fishing around trying to create
diversions, trying to in some way knock the allies off their
evident and united track to confront his aggression,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   Foley added that ``none of these ploys have succeeded thus far,
and none are going to.'' His forecast: ``Total unity and
determination to continue this campaign through to success.''
</P>
<P>
   And that will be the answer until the coalition cracks and he
has to come up with some alternative spin.
</P>
<P>
   All this attention is very strange for Albania, the poorest
nation in Europe with an estimated per capita income of $830 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Even at the height of the Cold War, it was barely an asterisk in
anyone's geopolitical equation. Stalinist strongman Enver Hoxha
closed his nation, which is about the size of Maryland, to the West
(and practically everyone else), but no one really missed it. From
1946, when an American mission was basically kicked out, until 1990
there was no direct diplomatic contact.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's a U.S. ``aircraft carrier.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
