<HEADER>
A6825 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT &LR;      04-13 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESIONAL LEADERS WORK TO AVOID VOTE ON GROUND TROOPS IN
BALKANS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: please note change in byline) 
 (ac) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With some members of Congress pushing for ground
troops in the Balkans and others adamantly opposed to such a
deployment, congressional leaders worked Tuesday to head off any
vote this week that would showcase divisions and undercut the
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with a two-and-a-half hour session at the White House
for 58 members of Congress, President Clinton and his national
security team mounted a concerted effort Tuesday to rally Congress
behind an intensified air campaign. ``Now we are taking our allied
air campaign to the next level, with more aircraft in the region,''
the president said after the session.
</P>
<P>
   An array of senior officials, including Sandy Berger, the
national security adviser, Defense Secretary William Cohen, Gen.
Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, and
Thomas Pickering, the undersecretary of state, went from party
caucus to party caucus on both sides of the Capitol, arguing that
the bombing campaign should be given more time to work. Time and
again they argued that of the 18 days that the air camapign had
been waged, only eight of those days had had clear weather.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers said that for the most part both parties were rallying
around the air campaign, but they described a sharp division in
Congress over how extensive a military commitment the United States
should make if the air strikes do not succeed.
</P>
<P>
   After the White House meeting, Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., called
for accelerated planning and preparation for the deployment of
ground troops in Kosovo. ``Nothing should be off the table,'' he
said. ``We should be committed to use whatever is necessary to
achieve the goal, and nothing short of achieving the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. John McCain, a Republican presidential hopeful said in
a speech that NATO had to begin ``fighting this war as if it were a
war with huge stakes involved, instead of some strange interlude
between peace initiatives.'' He said, ``To that end we should
commence today to mobilize infantry and armored divisions for a
ground war in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the political spectrum, Rep. Tom Campbell, a
California Republican, pressed ahead with plans to force a vote on
the war under the 1973 War Powers resolution, introducing two
measures calling for the withdrawal of American troops from the
region or, alternatively, a declaration of war. ``We are presently
at war and it is an unconstitutional war,'' he said. Under House
rules, the resolutions would come to a vote no later than early
May.
</P>
<P>
   Both Trent Lott, the Senate majority leader, and Tom Daschle,
the Senate minority leader, said that if the president were to
commit American ground troops in the Balkans, they would want to
see a vote first in Congress. But they insisted such discussion was
premature.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will come a time when we will be better able to assess
whether other actions are necessary,'' Daschle said. ``This is not
that time.'' Lott said, ''I don't think we ought to speculate on
ground troops.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders quickly took up an offer by Cohen to send a
high-level congressional delegation to the Balkans this weekend to
see the situation first-hand.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders and their aides said that any significant
vote on Congress would be delayed until next week at the earliest
when Congress could take up an emergency request from the
adminstration to pay for the operation through the end of the
fiscal year on Sept. 30 _ a time frame that suggested a prolonged
bombing campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Tuesday Republicans leaders trod a careful line,
noting that they had past misgivings about the Clinton
administration's policy in the Balkans, but would support it now
that the air campaign was underway. Recalling that he had voted in
March against the bombing campaign, Lott said, ``I've always had my
doubts about how this was going to go. But that is history.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Armey, the House majority leader, said, ``Once our
people are engaged in an action, it is time, in my estimation, to
cease any debate about whether or not that action should or should
not have been undertaken, give our full support to that and expect
that it be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   But some rank-and file members were more clealy concerned about
the scope of the commitment. ``No one seems to know how long we're
going to have to bomb or whether we're ever going to be able to
stop bombing,'' said Rep. Floyd Spence, chairman of the House Armed
Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Congress said that Clinton and his national security
team insisted to them that the air campaign would continue for
weeks and months if necessary. ``I am impressed with the
forcefulness with which they present their belief that this is
working,'' Armey said, ``and therefore they anticipate no need to
insert ground troops. They do not rule it out, but they are clear
that they do not believe it is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Speaker J. Dennis Hastert said he still needed time to
assess the mood of his caucus before making decisions about any
votes on the Kosovo deployment. And in the Senate, Republicans said
that there was sharp criticism of the administration policy in a
closed-door Republican caucus. But Lott, they said, urged
Republicans to temper their criticism of the Administration for now
and not push for any immediate votes on ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very concerned and every possible viewpoint is
being expressed,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, a Maine Republican.
Noting that the air strikes had not forced Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic to negotiate, as had first been expected, she
said, ``The president's official goals have failed.''
</P>
<P>
   At a caucus of House Democrats too, lawmakers said there were
sharp divisions over ground troops.
</P>
<P>
   Porter Goss, chairman of the House Intelligence Committee, said
the briefings from President Clinton's top foreign policy advisers
and the assessments he had received from the military and the
Central Intelligence Agency left him thinking no one knows whether
Milosevic will break under the pressure and that it was
``impossible to predict at this point'' how long the war will take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
