<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS FACE TOUGH ROAD TO PLAYOFFS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ When it comes to clinching the fifth seed in
the Western Conference, the Anaheim Mighty Ducks are so near, yet
so far.
</P>
<P>
   If the Ducks can beat sixth-place St. Louis tonight at the Pond
and follow that up with a victory over the Kings at the Forum on
Thursday that would assure them a first-round playoff match up
against Phoenix, thus avoiding longtime nemsis Detroit. The Ducks
finished 3-1-2 against the Coyotes this season and defeated Phoenix
in the first round of the 1997 playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the two wins don't figure to come easy. Center Steve Rucchin
is not expected to play in either game due to a lingering groin
injury and the availibility of defenseman Jason Marshall is very
much up in the air.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was checked head-first into the boards by Phoenix's
Dallas Drake on Sunday and will miss tonight's game for sure. After
that nobody really knows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about injuries this time of year, Anaheim coach
Craig Hartsburg said after practice Tuesday. ``We will keep it our
business ... we don't need everybody to know our business. I don't
think other teams are going to talk a lot about injuries this time
of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to suck it up and get the job done. We've played
without Rucchin, (Teemu) Selanne and (Tomas) Sandstrom this year.
</P>
<P>
   With Pascal Trepanier, gone for the season due to torn ACL,
Hartsburg will look to little-used Dan Trebil to pick up that slack
against a Blues offense that's led by the unheralded Pavol Demitra
(36 goals, 86 points), Pierre Turgeon (31 goals) and Norris Trophy
front-runner Al MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   Trebil has 53 games of NHL experience, but only three this
season, having spent most of the year in the minors after being
injured in training camp. He hasn't played since March 21.
</P>
<P>
   But Trebil, who did play in nine playoff games with the Ducks
back in 1997, said he's not nervous about playing in the team's
biggest game of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of the games have been so big lately, each game has been
the biggest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   None bigger than this one, however.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who currently lead St. Louis by a point, certainly
don't want to fall a point behind the Blues with only two games to
play. They would then need help from the Coyotes or Kings, against
whom the Blues finish the season, and Anaheim's season finale
against San Jose on Saturday could be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's come down to one game, said Rucchin, who will only be
able to root his teammates on from the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't playing our best as a team, he said, referring to
the Ducks' recent four-game winless streak. ``But the 3-0 win over
Phoenix was impressive. There's nothing better than coming off a
big victory.
</P>
<P>
   But Rucchin's coach continues to try and downplay the importance
of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big game, but we've said all along we don't care who we
play, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartsburg insists the team can't get caught up looking for a
certain matchup.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you start thinking like that, that's when you are going
to get burned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt Anaheim, which is just a point away from
clinching sixth, would prefer to avoid the re-tooled Red Wings for
as long as possible. The Ducks were 1-3 versus Detroit this season
and are 4-15-5 against the Red Wings in franchise history, not
including the Detroit's four-game sweep in the second round of the
'97 playoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
