<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PENTAGON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AND PENTAGON MORE FORTHCOMING WITH PRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After refusing for more than two weeks to share
detailed information about the progress of Western airstrikes
against Yugoslavia, NATO and the Pentagon have begun slowly to open
the spigot of information.
</P>
<P>
   At its daily briefing, the Pentagon provided its first detailed
account since the bombing campaign began on March 24 of the total
number and types of targets destroyed by NATO warplanes and cruise
missiles.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, Gen. Wesley Clark,
the supreme commander of the alliance, gave reporters his first
comprehensive assessment of the progress of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At the Pentagon, Kenneth Bacon, its chief spokesman, said:
``What you're seeing is both NATO and the Pentagon are becoming
more open. Basically as we've become more comfortable with the
operation, as we've realized what we can do and cannot do, we've
been more forthcoming.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the decision to release more information was
prompted in part by the realization that Yugoslav forces now
understand the tempo and tactics of the attacks. ``The Yugoslavs
have had three weeks to see what we're doing and the pattern of the
operation,'' he said. ``So it doesn't make a lot of sense to hold
off on the information.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark said he had ordered information withheld in the earlier
briefings because ``I wanted to be sure we had flexibility in our
operations _ that I understood exactly what was required to be
protected in order to protect the air crews.''
</P>
<P>
   News organizations had complained that at the early briefings by
NATO and the Pentagon, officials refused to say exactly how many
attack missions had been made against Yugoslav forces, how many of
the missions had been completed, how many bombs had been dropped or
what, precisely, they had hit.
</P>
<P>
   Editors at several news organizations, including The New York
Times, have formally protested to the Defense Department over the
restrictions on information.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's briefings in Brussels and Washington, military
spokesmen provided totals of the number and types of large targets
hit _ including 11 fuel-storage installations, 11 bridges and four
ammunition storage sites _ and a map to identify their location in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO, reporters on Tuesday were shown video clips of some of
the attacks carried out this week, including one on a Yugoslav
bridge in which 10 civilians on a train were reportedly killed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2106EDT &QL; 
