<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2NDT     04-13 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-2NDTAKE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
 
STENKOVAC ,  Macedonia: ... were burned.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The next day, two adjacent villages located roughly five miles
southeast of Urosevac were attacked by paramilitary forces,
according to refugees. Sami Tahiri, a 61-year-old retired teacher,
said regular Yugoslav Army soldiers first came to his village,
Sojeve, and warned the 230 families over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Then last Tuesday, Serbian paramilitary soldiers in black masks
roared into the village in jeeps. Most of the villagers fled into
the hills, but two young men were captured, an Albanian and a
Muslim who had fled the war in Bosnia. Both were killed, he said,
and an elderly couple were burned alive in their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who stayed were killed,'' Tahiri said.
</P>
<P>
   As ethnic Albanians watched from surrounding hills, the
paramilitary forces torched two-thirds of the homes in the village,
he said. Houses in the nearby village of Terstenik were also
torched.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, Serb forces shelled the Albanian village
of Preshtina, which lies roughly five miles in the opposite
direction of Urosevac, to the West. Jonuz Bytyqi, a high school
teacher from Urosevac who had fled to the area after NATO bombing
began, said he woke to the sound of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Six shells, he said, impacted in Preshtina, injuring no one. But
30 shells fired on the adjacent village of Zaskok killed at least
four people. Residents of both villages fled immediately after the
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the shells hit a tractor near where I was,'' Bytyqi
said. ``I couldn't sleep at all after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Wednesday, refugees said that Serb paramilitary units
carried out a separate attack on Varosh, an Albanian village on the
main road three miles south of Urosevac. Zeqir, who was sleeping in
a nearby field after fleeing the earlier attack on his own village,
said one young man who refused to leave his home was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the pattern of attacks on Thursday, Serb forces
shelled and then burned Zlatar, an Albanian village seven miles
west of Urosevac, according to Lulzim Shala, a refugee who fled the
village with his wife and two young daughters. It was the attack
farthest away from the city, according to the refugees from the
area who arrived here Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Shala said he and his family then fled to a nearby village,
Mirosale. That was attacked over the weekend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters' access to Kosovo is limited by the Yugoslav
government, so the accounts of the attacks could not be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   All of the refugees said they ended up fleeing to Urosevac after
the attacks, and believe they were intentionally driven into the
town. They said thousands of other Albanians are hiding in Urosevac
and the surrounding hills and running out of food.
</P>
<P>
   In a surreal end to their cat-and-mouse game with Serb forces,
the refugees said they were allowed to simply buy a $20 train
ticket in Urosevac Monday morning and ride in a packed train to the
border, they said.
</P>
<P>
   With many Serbian-run stores in Urosevac refusing to sell food
to Albanians and paramilitary forces randomly looting houses and
beating ethnic Albanians, the refugees decided the time had come to
flee with their families. They predicted thousands more would
follow.
</P>
<P>
   ''You cannot stand it psychologically,'' said Bytyqi, the high
school teacher. ``For 21 days, I never knew what was going to
happen next.
</P>
<P>
   ``I promised myself I would not leave,'' he said. ``But my
daughter lost ten pounds from the tension and I have two sons. I
came here for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
