<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEEDMONEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Venture catalysts provide advice, money to small startups
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
A new breed of startup consultant and investor has sprung up in the
Bay Area.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to dispensing cash, these so-called venture
catalysts provide plenty of advice to help entrepreneurs hone their
strategies, develop their markets and recruit management talent.
</P>
<P>
   While most big-name venture capital firms put a partner on the
board of companies they invest in and allocate maybe a day a month
for hand holding, partners of catalyst firms invest much more of
their time.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Comaford, founder of Artemis Ventures in Sausalito,
says she spends as much as a week per month helping an individual
business software or e-commerce client build its enterprise.
</P>
<P>
   The venture catalyst firms have been a godsend to startups
ranging from Vanishing Point, which specializes in long-term hair
removal and other nonsurgical skin treatments, to Again
Technologies, a vendor of financial software.
</P>
<P>
   Like wealthy individual investors who are often dubbed angels,
venture catalyst companies are filling a niche vacated by some of
the more established venture firms.
</P>
<P>
   Confronted by a record number of business plans and needy
entrepreneurs, the big VCs increasingly are investing larger
amounts in later-stage companies to avoid stretching their
partners' time and talents too thin.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves room for venture catalysts to provide $500,000 of
``seed capital'' in most cases to nurture startups until they are
ready to graduate to the next investment round.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lea Reed, editor of the Venture Capital Journal,
compares smaller VC investor/consultants and the growing number of
angel investor networks to ``preparatory schools'' that get
entrepreneurs ready for bigger institutions.
</P>
<P>
   More than 30,000 high-tech business plans are submitted to U.S.
venture capitalists a year, but less than 3 percent obtain
financing, according to Artemis Ventures. In most cases, that's
because the entrepreneurs don't have the right connections with the
right VCs and they don't present their plans in the best way.
</P>
<P>
   One Artemis client that realized it needed a helping hand is
Again Technologies. The San Mateo company was started in 1995 by
former Gap information systems executive Gopi Mattel and Visa
systems administration director Yelbert Yamaki to develop software
to help companies track and pay sales incentives and other variable
commissions and bonuses.
</P>
<P>
   With less than $100,000 of their own money and the help of
software engineers enlisted by Mattel's brother in India, the
founders bootstrapped their way to $500,000 in sales last year and
signed some big-name customers like Clorox and Southern California
Edison.
</P>
<P>
   But Yamaki said, ``It was hard running a business and looking
for capital at the same time.'' In addition, he acknowledged that
he and Mattel know a lot about variable compensation but
comparatively little about marketing and raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Again Technologies was introduced to Artemis in September at a
Center for Software Development showcase in San Jose, where
entrepreneurs were presented to potential investors.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Artemis has committed $500,000 to the company and
helped it refine its business and marketing strategy, attract board
members and introduce it to other venture funds.
</P>
<P>
   Like other VC firms, Artemis' help does not come cheap. In
addition to taking a hefty chunk of stock in the companies it
counsels, it has charged a monthly retainer.
</P>
<P>
   But Yamaki is pleased with the results. ``Ending up with a
smaller portion of a large company is better than a large portion
of a small company,'' he said. ``Artemis has helped with our
business plan, changing it from a strategic operations document to
something geared to investors as well. And they are
well-networked.''
</P>
<P>
   Comaford may seem an unlikely Henry Higgins, who turns
unpolished businesses into financial fair ladies. She dropped out
of high school in Los Angeles at 16 and ran off to New York, where
she modeled lingerie for Bloomingdale's. She later attended
college, where she first aspired to become a Shakespearean scholar
but then became enraptured by BASIC programing language and
computers.
</P>
<P>
   After writing some accounting software for Domino's Pizza,
Comaford went to work for Microsoft. Then she started a contract
programming company and took more than 30 Microsoft employees with
her.
</P>
<P>
   She helped start four other companies including San Francisco's
Planet U, an online consumer promotions company that expects to go
public in the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, Comaford started Artemis Ventures (named after the
mythological Greek huntress) to help build multiple companies at
the same time. ``After being a serial entrepreneur,'' said the
hyper-energetic Comaford, ``I decided I wanted to be a parallel
entrepreneur working on several companies at once; the only way to
do that is to create a venture capital company and finance
companies as you build them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 37-year-old Comaford has raised $15 million from ``high
net-worth individuals'' for her $20 million venture fund and has
invested in a handful of business-to-business software companies.
These include ELetter, a San Jose online mailing service for
business, which like Again Technologies hired Artemis to refine its
strategy, find directors and advisers and prepare it for the big
investment leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Venture Strategy Partners of San Francisco is another venture
catalyst firm that focuses on consulting. The $25 million fund is
an outgrowth of Venture Strategy Group, which began in 1996
advising companies across various industries on how to build their
brands.
</P>
<P>
   Since June, it has seeded a handful of startups with about
$500,000 each. These include Flooz.com, a new e-commerce site
started by iVillage co-founder Robert Levitan that lets users
e-mail personal greeting cards with an online gift certificate;
A.G. Ferrari, an Italian-style foods emporium; and Vanishing Point,
which has taken laser hair removal, nonsurgical cellulite reduction
and wrinkle removal out of the doctor's office and into boutiques
staffed by nurse practitioners.
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Point has two ``studios'' in San Francisco. The
company was started by Melisse Shaban, who previously managed 220
Body Shop stores and then built and sold the Aveda beauty products
company to Estee Lauder.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her experience, Shaban said Venture Strategy's services
have been essential. ``They've helped build our brand by
interpreting demographic data and conducting exit interviews with
consumers,'' said Shaban. Venture Strategy General Partner Joanna
Rees Gallanter ``is an integral part of our board and an extension
of our management team.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Point is based in Raleigh, N.C., but it opened its
first shops in New York, San Francisco and Miami, where Shaban said
there are good populations of target customers. They include
``wealthy, educated, self-indulgent consumers who buy branded goods
and who are interested in healthy living and are driven by the
desire to improve their personal appearance.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Point's shop on 18th Street near Castro specializes in
long-term hair removal (six to 12 months) using two $100,000
medical laser devices. The cost per treatment, whether beard, back
or bikini line, is about $80 for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Point's second store, which just opened on Fillmore
Street near Lombard, offers additional services for a similar price
with doctors on call in case of a problem. Treatments include or
will include a ``micro peel'' to exfoliate and improve the skin and
therapeutic cellulite massage to break down the tissue walls that
trap fat.
</P>
<P>
   An affiliated doctor also will come in to treat varicose veins
and inject collagen and Botox (a diluted strain of botulism) to
eradicate wrinkles and furrows in the brow, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Strategy Partners and other investors, Shaban
hopes Vanishing point will grow from five to 120 locations within
five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
