<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CISCO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Big Cisco Push Into Internet Phones
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Cisco Systems Inc. accelerated its push into the Internet phone
market yesterday with a $2 billion deal to buy GeoTel
Communications, a Massachusetts telecommunications company that
helps businesses route incoming calls.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose networking giant said the purchase will help it
offer consumers a way to surf the Web and talk to a company's
customer service staff at the same time. Cisco said it will use
GeoTel's software to create products that let Web surfers click on
an icon and connect to a live call center operator.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco will exchange 0.5138 shares of Cisco common stock for each
share of GeoTel. The deal values GeoTel at $60.50 a share _ a 37
percent premium over GeoTel's closing price of $44.25 on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel's technology is important for Cisco, which is in a race
with Lucent Technologies Inc. and Nortel Networks to provide gear
for phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications providers are migrating to Internet-based
networks that can carry voice, video and data simultaneously. Cisco
wants to be able to offer those companies the same value-added
services they enjoy on traditional networks _ such as routing
incoming calls from customers who are on hold to an available
operator. Buying GeoTel will help Cisco gain that technology,
industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   But a $2 billion price tag for GeoTel, which had only $45
million in revenue last year and after-tax income of $9 million,
surprised several industry watchers.
</P>
<P>
   Some speculated that the purchase may have a specific purpose _
to help Cisco on its contract with Sprint Corp. Cisco is developing
core technology for Sprint's Integrated-on-Demand Network _ a huge
project that will allow the long-distance giant to carry voice,
video and data over a single network. GeoTel also has a strong
relationship with Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most logical explanation for the size of the deal may be
significant pressure from key customers,'' said Hilary Mine,
executive vice president of Probe Research in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Sprint announced it would deploy GeoTel's call
routing technology as part of its new Internet-based network. Mine
said that partnership may be why Cisco agreed to pay such a hefty
sum for GeoTel.
</P>
<P>
   This is Cisco's largest purchase since it bought StrataCom Inc.
for $4.5 billion in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ammar Hanafi, a director in Cisco's business development
division, said Cisco paid $2 billion for GeoTel because the company
has strong growth, often beating Wall Street estimates by 20 to 40
percent, and is a leader in its field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel we paid a very fair price for a company in this
marketplace,'' Hanafi said. He said the overlapping customer base
also helped cinch the deal, but would not comment on whether the
Sprint ION project played a significant part.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts said the price tag reflects the increasing
competition in the data networking field and Cisco's need for
specific technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at GeoTel, this is a real company with real
products,'' said Michael Cristinziano, an analyst at Gerard Klauer
Mattison &AMP; Co. in New York. ``If you get this into the hands of
Cisco, it becomes another weapon in their arsenal to compete with
Lucent.''
</P>
<P>
   Cristinziano said the purchase will help Cisco grab a share of
e-commerce by offering Internet call centers _ which exist today,
but are expected to become ubiquitous as more companies sell
products online.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're at a Web commerce site, you want to buy something, but
you can't find the answer to a question. You click on a button and
a window opens and you're talking to a live attendant at a call
center,'' Cristinziano said. ``This is an area to attack. ... Cisco
can afford to pay $2 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition comes on the heels of two other
telecommunications purchases. Last week, Cisco agreed to buy Fibex
Systems and Sentient Networks Inc. for a total of $445 million in
stock to get products that add voice services to data networks.
</P>
<P>
   GeoTel jumped $11.69 to $55.94 yesterday. Cisco fell $3.63 to
$114.13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
