<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR ESCALATES AS SERBS RAID VILLAGE IN ALBANIA 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton on Tuesday announced the
escalation of the air campaign in Yugoslavia as Serb forces made a
foray into Albania and NATO bombers continued to target strategic
sites, including the country's biggest oil refinery.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with lawmakers, Clinton said that the sustained
bombing has weakened Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's war
effort, damaging refineries and ammunition plants while destroying
aircraft and artillery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have reduced his ability to move, sustain and supply the
war machine in Kosovo,'' Clinton said in remarks from the Rose
Garden. ``Now we are taking our allied air campaign to the next
level; with more aircraft in the region, with a British carrier
joining the USS Roosevelt and French carrier in the region.''
</P>
<P>
   The president said that ``our humanitarian effort is also
increasing to meet the daunting challenge of providing food and
shelter for the hundreds of thousands of refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton compared Milosevic's campaign to rid Kosovo of ethnic
Albanians to the genocide of the Jews and others in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that is was Holocaust Remembrance Day, the president
said: ``On this day, let us resolve not to let this `ethnic
cleansing' and killing by Mr. Milosevic go unanswered.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials have requested the use of 300 more U.S. aircraft,
and the Pentagon has said that more helicopters also may be added
to the air campaign. Twenty-four low flying Apache helicopters are
headed to Albania, where they are expected to be used for more
precise bombing of Serb ground operations in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's supreme commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, said Tuesday he has
requested hundreds of new aircraft not only from the United States
but from other NATO countries to double the force attacking
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has more than 500 aircraft at its disposal. Those planes
have flown 5,924 sorties in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kevin Bacon said NATO bombers would ``fly
more intensively during both day and night hours ... and strike a
wide range of targets.''
</P>
<P>
   Bacon also said that the increased air campaign would involve
the call-up of military reserves, including pilots and army civil
affairs specialists who can work with local populations in Albania
and Macedonia, where many of the refugees from Kosovo are now
situated. At least 2,000 may be called, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Britain said it was sending 1,800 more soldiers to Macedonia and
Greece, where officials said they would be used as part of a
peacekeeping, not an invasion force. There are already 6,300
British troops in the region.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO planned to step up its campaign against Yugoslavia,
it appeared that Serbs were also preparing to escalate their
military effort.
</P>
<P>
   Serb forces threatened to dramatically expand the scope of the
military engagement when they pushed into northern Albania, fought
Albanian forces and briefly took control of a village.
</P>
<P>
   Albania's interior minister, Petro Koci, said that Serb troops
exchanged gunfire with Albanian border police before entering the
village of Kamenica. Serb troops had shelled the village for
several days before the incursion into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   While the Serb forces later retreated, U.S. officials condemned
the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made clear within NATO as well as the United States
specifically that widening of this conflict by the Serbs to other
countries in the region would have severe consequences,'' said
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, who was in Oslo, Norway,
meeting with Russia's foreign minister about the two nations'
differences over NATO's Yugoslav mission.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said that despite the bad weather they have hit a
number of strategic targets, including Yugoslavia's largest oil
refinery, which they contend will choke off fuel supplies to the
military.
</P>
<P>
   But at NATO headquarters in Brussels, Belgium, Clark was forced
to explain the bombing on Monday of a train filled with civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Clark said the pilot was assigned to destroy a railroad bridge
that is part of a communications supply network in Serbia. But
Clark said when the pilot realized that the bomb had targeted the
train rather than the bridge, it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unfortunate incident which he (pilot) and the crew
and all of us very much regret. We certainly did not want to do
collateral damage,'' he said, referring to deaths of 10 civilians.
Despite the blasting of the train, NATO officials said that the air
campaign has weakened the Serb air defense system and its supply
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are becoming stronger and Milosevic is becoming weaker,''
said NATO spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   But Shea said that officials from member countries, who met
earlier this week, acknowledged that military campaign is far from
over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood of the foreign ministers yesterday is that it may be
a long haul and we have to be ready for it,'' Shea said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
