<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6840 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      04-13 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: Fish Processor Zapata Giving a Green Light to Its  Internet
Spin-Off 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Mark Veverka &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
The once derailed Internet spin-off of Zapata may be back on track.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston holding company, founded by George Bush but no
longer controlled by the former president, grabbed national
headlines last year when it boldly announced that it, too, was
going to dive into the dot-com pool.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata's bid to buy a bunch of Web sites gave off a detectable
odor largely because the company's primary businesses were in the
nondigital worlds of fish processing and sausage casings.
</P>
<P>
   But the scent didn't throw all investors off the trail. Some
financial pundits took Zapata seriously because the company's core
assets were strong and its chief executive, Avie Glazer, was viewed
as a smart guy.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata zapped its designs on an Internet spin-off last summer
when the initial public offering market got weak in the knees. But
now, Zapata is taking another shot. Yesterday, the company filed
documents with the Securities and Exchange Commission, saying it
plans to spin off its Internet subsidiary, Zap.com.
</P>
<P>
   The difference this time is that Zapata is shunning Wall Street
bankers and underwriting the deal itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Self-written deals are sort of in no man's land, and very few
have worked,'' says Ben Holmes, president of IPOPros.com, an
independent research firm in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   But ``who knows? They'll be the first to go from fish meal to
the digital world. I applaud them,'' Holmes says.
</P>
<P>
   According to the filing, Zap.com ``plans to create an
advertising network and e-commerce platform by building a branded
network.'' The Zap.com Network would be linked by banner
advertisements displayed on Web sites owned and operated by third
parties.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Zap.com is a small fry. The operation currently
consists of a couple of Web magazine sites Zapata acquired from
Qwest Communications International in April 1998. The unit has 21
employees.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, no self-respecting Internet concern could be taken
seriously if it wasn't bleeding at least a little red ink. Zap.com
lost $148,000 during the 11-month period ended February 28 on zero
revenues. (The division was created last April, the filing stated.)
</P>
<P>
   The spin-off will be unconventional, which is par for the course
with Zapata. In fact, it will be a rights offering, where Zapata
shareholders will be given rights to buy Zap.com common stock at $8
a share. Zapata shareholders will have the right to buy a share of
Zap for each share of the parent they own.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata will invest $8 million in Zap.com in exchange for 10,000
super-voting preferred shares and 13.6 million rights to common
shares, which it will offer to holders of Zapata. Upon completion
of the offering, Zap.com will be a majority-owned subsidiary of
Zapata.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, for those investors who would actually like to get their
hands on some of these somewhat gamey shares, you'll have to wait
until Zapata shareholders sell their Zap.com stock over the counter
on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Zapata investors weren't thrilled with the filing, including an
announcement that three legal battles had been brought to an end.
The company stated that to pay the settlements, it plans to take a
pretax charge of about 14 cents a share during the first quarter.
Zapata shares, which trade on the Big Board, fell nearly $2 to
$10.38 in bumpy trading yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   Viva Zapata!
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINAL THOUGHT: &LR;  Look out below. First, Dell dropped a bomb in
February, when it revealed slower-than-usual sales growth for its
personal computers. Then, Compaq launched a Scud on Friday, saying
its PC sales will be even worse.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, yesterday, Intel admonishes Wall Street to cool its
jets regarding expectations for its chip sales. And yet the
tech-sector is still supposed to be the engine driving this
high-flying market?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the Internet bulls are saying that their darling Net
stocks are now at the throttle. And that's a sobering thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
