<SLUG> BC-USANET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Plans for Billion-Dollar `Ultimate' Internet
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Jon Swartz &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Telecommunications giant Cable &AMP; Wireless PLC yesterday said it
will build a billion-dollar phone network in the United States that
will handle Internet and data traffic at blur-fast rates. The
network will be available in 60 metropolitan areas, including the
Bay Area, by the fall of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The American subsidiary of the London company, Cable &AMP; Wireless
USA, announced it is now spending $670 million on 15,000 miles of
fiber-optic cabling for the as-yet-unnamed network, whose price tag
eventually will top $1 billion. When complete, the new network will
deliver voice, data and Internet services at speeds more than 10
times faster than the commercial Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're creating the ultimate Internet for consumers and
businesses,'' said Art Medici, senior vice president of marketing
at Cable &AMP; Wireless USA in Vienna, Va.
</P>
<P>
   The vast network eventually will be hooked up to Cable &AMP;
Wireless' global Internet network, with operations in Europe and
Asia. Cable &AMP; Wireless USA plans to make segments of the U.S.
network available as soon as they are ready. Half a dozen unnamed
cities are scheduled to be switched on in September.
</P>
<P>
   Pricing for the network has not been finalized, Medici said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable &AMP; Wireless _ which paid $1.75 billion for MCI
Communications Corp.'s Internet business last year _ is in the
midst of a five-year, $1 billion plan to construct a similar
high-speed network in Europe. The British company is already one of
the largest telecom companies in Asia through its majority stake in
Hong Kong Telecommunications Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom rivals are scrambling to develop global phone services
using Internet-based technology to cash in on an online boom. The
number of Internet users is expected to double, to 300 million, by
2005.
</P>
<P>
   Among the competitors creating worldwide networks:
</P>
<P>
   _AT&AMP;T Corp. and British Telecommunications PLC said they will
join forces to sell global phone services to multinational
companies using Internet-based technology.
</P>
<P>
   _Internet2, a coalition of 130 universities and high-tech
companies, in February flipped the switch on a key segment of its
private research network that connects 70 college campuses. The
3-year-old nonprofit organization includes the University of
California at Berkeley and Stanford University, as well as
corporate sponsors Cisco Systems, IBM and Qwest Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The 13,000-mile Internet2 network is up to 45,000 times faster
than the commercial Web, but it is not available to the public.
Only researchers and employees at the colleges and corporate
sponsors can use it. Consumers eventually will be able to use
cutting-edge applications created on Internet2 but only after they
have been developed and sold by Internet2 members for commercial
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   _Project Oxygen ( &LR; www.oxygen.org &LR; ) _ a $10 billion commercial
venture that hopes to leapfrog the nonprofit Internet2 _ would pump
video, sound and data at speeds up to 5.5 million times faster than
the Web to users in 78 countries. The underwater network of
fiber-optic cables will traverse the Atlantic and Pacific oceans by
2003.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said they have raised $1.8 billion from investors,
loans and corporate sponsors such as Lucent, Pacific Telesis,
Japan's NEC and France's Alcatel. They also said they have deals
with 40 telecom carriers. Launched in mid-1997, Project Oxygen will
undergo several phases before it is completed in early 2003.
</P>
</TEXT>
