<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 How to Keep Your 800 Number
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Peter Sinton &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  I signed up for a U.S. long-distance 800 number for my
business with one telephone company but was unhappy with the
service.
</P>
<P>
   When I tried to change to another service, my provider refused
to release my 800 number and disconnected my number. As a result, I
lost calls and business.
</P>
<P>
   I have called them at least five times to complain. Although
they promised to fix the problem, they have not. Isn't the 800
number mine to keep?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  The answer is yes. Once you sign up with any company
for an 800 number, it is yours to take with you if you change to
another telephone service, says Mari Gottdiener, who runs Outsource
Solutions ( &LR; www.outsolve.com &LR; ) in Menlo Park.
</P>
<P>
   A self-described ``recovering attorney,'' Gottdiener has created
a home-based business to help folks resolve disputes out of court.
</P>
<P>
   She suggests that you should write the CEO of the offending
company, documenting the number of times you called, as well as the
dates, times and persons with whom you spoke.
</P>
<P>
   Demand an immediate release of the 800 number to a designated
phone company.
</P>
<P>
   You can also demand compensation for lost business if you can
document and quantify it. (If nothing else, this should at least
get you a quick release of the number.)
</P>
<P>
   Send a copy of your letter to the California Public Utilities
Commission. Also be sure to notify your local phone company of the
new provider.
</P>
<P>
   Deducing Deductions
</P>
<P>
   Q: In 1997, I spent $13,000 developing a safety device for
automobiles. (About $10,000 was for materials.)
</P>
<P>
   I believed I had a buyer and this still may occur. But if not,
can I write my expenses off as a loss on my taxes when (if) it is
rejected? If so, how do I do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: If you are unincorporated and operate as a sole
proprietorship, you should file a Schedule C to report income and
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   At least some of your $13,000 investment is likely deductible as
an expense. However, if you have no income and never had any,
accountant Carolyn Amster of Burr, Pilger &AMP; Mayer in San Francisco
says the IRS might be skeptical.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is to report the development costs as a
Section 212 expenditure on the Schedule A itemized deduction
portion of your individual tax return.
</P>
<P>
   The $13,000, or a portion of it, might fall under ``expenses
incurred for the production of income.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Amster suggests that you consult with a tax adviser
because your situation could be complicated.
</P>
<P>
   If, like most of us, you report income and expenses in the year
they are incurred, you probably should have reported expenses in
1997. You might want to amend your tax return for that year.
</P>
<P>
   Your situation could be complicated further by the fact that
some of your investment, such as equipment or patent costs, might
need to be deducted over a number of years, rather than all at
once.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send small-business questions to  &LR; entrepreneurs(at &LR; 
 &LR; sign)sfgate.com &LR;  or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business column, 901
Mission St., San Francisco, Calif., 94103
</P>
</TEXT>
