<SLUG> BC-NORTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Nortel to Buy Shasta for $340 Million
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By Deborah Solomon &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &QL; 
Northern Telecom Ltd., which bought Bay Networks last year, is
buying Sunnyvale's Shasta Networks Inc. for $340 million in cash
and stock.
</P>
<P>
   Nortel said it will pay $318 million in stock and $22 million in
cash for the privately held networking company.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta, which has 70 employees, makes gear that helps phone
companies run Internet-based networks. Nortel said it is buying
Shasta to gain the firm's expertise in that arena.
</P>
<P>
   As telecommunications companies migrate to an Internet-based
network, equipment-makers like Nortel, Lucent Technologies and
Cisco Systems Inc. want to be able to sell products for these
next-generation networks.
</P>
<P>
   Clarence Chandran, Nortel president of carrier packet solutions,
said Shasta will help the company develop value-added services for
these networks of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Shasta's headquarters will remain in Sunnyvale and the company
does not expect any layoffs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
