<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE: COMBAT, DIPLOMACY, REFUGEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO bombers destroyed a railway bridge in southern Yugoslavia
where, just hours before, allied bombs hit a train. Yugoslavia said
10 people on the train were killed.
</P>
<P>
   _ The allies also hit two oil refineries in Yugoslavia and a
Belgrade suburb. Eight explosions were heard from the southern
outskirts of Pristina, the capital of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ Yugoslav forces reportedly crossed the Albanian border to
attack a village, and Albanians called on the allies to stop such
incursions.
</P>
<P>
   _ Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, asked allied
governments for 300 more warplanes to intensify the bombing.
President Clinton said that the air campaign was moving ``to the
next level,'' and that he planned to ask Congress for emergency
funds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Britain said it plans to send 1,800 more troops to the
Balkans, bringing its contingent to just over 6,300, based in
Greece and Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   _ Senior Russian and American diplomats concurred at talks in
Oslo, Norway, on the principles for a political agreement in Kosovo
but remained divided over the proposed deployment of an
international force under NATO command to police any accord.
Britain wants Russia to be part of a peacekeeping force, but doubts
that Moscow can mediate an end to the dispute with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Kofi Annan, the U.N. secretary-general, who has offered to
attempt peace talks with President Slobodan Milosevic, is to attend
a special summit meeting of the European Union Wednesday to discuss
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ The U.N. human rights commission voted 46-1 to condemn
Yugoslav authorities for their ethnic purges in Kosovo. Only Russia
voted against the resolution, which was sponsored by Pakistan and
supported by the United States and the European Union. China, Cuba
and India were among those abstaining.
</P>
<P>
   REFUGEES
</P>
<P>
   _ Thousands more Albanian refugees streamed out of Kosovo into
Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro. NATO estimated the total since
the bombing began on March 24 at 448,000; U.N. refugee officials
say an additional 150,000 migrated between March 1998 and March
1999.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clark said he doubts the alliance can deliver aid to Albanians
stranded in Kosovo, and Clinton said this facet of the refugee
problem is particularly acute.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Russian aid convoy arrived in Belgrade after a two-day
diplomatic dispute with Hungary over eight fuel tankers in the
convoy, the Yugoslav state news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   _ A former Australian prime minister, Malcolm Fraser, flew to
Moscow to seek Russian help to secure the release of two Australian
aid workers who face spying charges in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Kosovo is available from
The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
