<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH OFFICIAL SAYS NATO MUST DECIDE ON ARMING KOSOVO REBELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ French Defense Minister Alain Richard said Tuesday that
the Serbian campaign against armed ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo
was raising questions about whether the NATO allies should try to
arm the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the information we have indicates that the Kosovo
Liberation Army has not been destroyed,'' said Richard. ``It's
fallen back, it's been forced to regroup, but in some areas it is
still as much a force as it was last Jan. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Richard said, ``we have to think hard about distributing
military aid that might just insure that Kosovo became a permanent
field of battle.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a political decision to make,'' he told a group of
correspondents for British and American news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Some 8,000 NATO troops, including 700 French soldiers, are now
being sent to northern Albania to help deal with the crisis caused
by the arrival of several hundred thousand refugees from Kosovo in
that poverty-stricken and remote area in the last three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said the allied troops might soon be in situations where
they had to decide whether to turn a blind eye to Kosovo Liberation
Army fighters trying to infiltrate across the Albanian border to
continue the battle against the Serbs there, or to prevent them
from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a decision we have not yet made,'' Richard said.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO mission in Albania is purely one of providing relief
aid, according to the allies. But Richard described the mountainous
northern part of the country where most of the soldiers are to be
sent as a ``security vacuum,'' without any effective Albanian
government security or police presence.
</P>
<P>
   In the French view, Richard said, the Kosovo Liberation Army is
a representative organization that had every right to a voice in
what was to become of the province.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel representatives took part in the failed peace talks at
Rambouillet Castle outside Paris in February, and were part of the
Kosovo Albanian delegation that signed the draft accord in Paris in
March.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's refusal to accept that
accord, or the 28,000 NATO peacekeepers that it provided for, led
the alliance to start bombing military targets throughout
Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   The Rambouillet accords also provided that the KLA would disband
and be disarmed under the supervision of the peacekeepers as all
but a few hundred Yugoslav army border guards withdrew from the
province.
</P>
<P>
   Allied foreign ministers agreed at a meeting in Brussels on
Monday that the Rambouillet agreement would still be the basis of a
political settlement of the Kosovo crisis, but they are also
exploring the possibility of imposing some kind of international
administration over the province if Milosevic continues to refuse
to negotiate.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian television Tuesday accused NATO of putting helicopters
at the service of ``terrorists'' from the KLA and said allied
planes had given the rebels air cover and bombing support for their
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said a French helicopter had evacuated a French citizen
whom news agencies identified as Franck Brucker from the Albanian
border region near Padesh on Monday after he and some rebel
fighters were wounded in a Serbian mortar attack on the village.
</P>
<P>
   Richard said all the French military on the scene knew about him
was that he was apparently French. A Reuters news agency report
from Tirana said that Brucker was believed to be a freelance
journalist, and that the French Embassy in the Albanian capital
said he was not a French government employee.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials in Brussels say the alliance has no contact of
any kind with Kosovo Liberation Army forces inside Kosovo. They
have described rebel operations as ``sporadic'' after the
destruction of seven rebel field headquarters by Serbian military
and heavily armed police units. The allies are trying to attack
Serb forces with an air armada that will soon number more than
1,000 planes.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Wesley Clark, the American who is NATO's supreme commander,
said he could not confirm reports from Albania on Tuesday that
Serbian forces had briefly crossed over the border from Kosovo to
pursue rebel troops.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
