<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0342 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6850 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-MIDWAY-SPI &LR;      04-13 1190
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MIDWAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERANS' ACCOUNTS HELP SAVE `MIDWAY' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   War isn't fun. This startling revelation from Robert Ballard,
master plumber of the briny deep, comes at the end of Wednesday
night's latest National Geographic ``Explorer'' special, ``The
Battle for Midway,'' on TBS.
</P>
<P>
   One would hope Ballard didn't have to poke around in the
subaqueous ooze for the USS Yorktown to reach his conclusion, but
it's a safe bet TBS Superstation would be airing this overwrought
documentary regardless of Ballard's position on armed global
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Ballard the philosopher doesn't weigh in Wednesday night on the
relative value of making a living looking for scrap metal on the
ocean floor. Having already found the Titanic, the Bismarck and the
``lost fleet'' of Guadalcanal, his position is obviously secure
among the folks at National Geographic.
</P>
<P>
   But the producers of ``The Battle for Midway'' obviously
realized that trolling for sunken hulks has all the dramatic appeal
of an 8 a.m. oceanography lecture on the first day after spring
break. To compensate, Wednesday night's two-hour special is as much
a retelling of the Midway story as it is a documentary on Ballard's
latest deep-sea spelunking. After all, one shot of a submersible
floating above a barren oceanscape goes a long, long way. About
20,000 leagues, give or take.
</P>
<P>
   To keep ``Midway'' from becoming a snoozefest, National
Geographic introduces a compelling human element: four veterans of
the famous battle _ two Americans and two Japanese _ who
accompanied Ballard last spring as he searched for traces of the
aircraft carrier Yorktown and four Japanese carriers that sank in
the Pacific during or shortly after the battle in June 1942.
</P>
<P>
   It's a clever manipulation that succeeds in tugging at the
emotions. But, aside from some overused claptrap about providing
``closure'' for the vets, no one ever explains exactly why the
Yorktown had to be found. Or why Ballard was in a ``race against
time,'' as narrator Peter Coyote points out early in the program.
The Yorktown, stuck in the muck about three miles down, certainly
isn't going anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the other half of ``The Battle for Midway'' is an
eminently serviceable documentary about the conflict itself. As one
of history's great sea battles, the story hardly needs introduction
or embellishment, especially with the 1976 movie ``Midway'' showing
up on American Movie Classics every few days.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss of the Yorktown and the enormous sacrifice of
American torpedo-bomber crews, an incredible combination of
courage, luck, skill and chance gave the U.S. Navy a turning-point
victory against Japanese forces in the battle of Midway.
</P>
<P>
   By interspersing historical footage with coverage of last year's
search for the Yorktown, producers Peter Schnall and Brian Berger
created a passable program that's strong on history and weak on the
high-tech material. Perhaps leery of boring us, ``The Battle for
Midway'' stints on the sort of scientific reportage that makes
PBS's ``NOVA'' series so fascinating. It relies on the most
rudimentary technical coverage, glossing over the really hard stuff
and focusing instead on the connection between the veterans and the
battle that occurred more than a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's a transparent attempt to add weight to a weak story, and
the artificially created drama diminishes the heroic efforts of the
four veterans who accompanied Ballard. No doubt the cruise was
meaningful and emotional for them, but using them to create a
viable premise for a documentary on Ballard's penchant for probing
the depths is, well, shallow.
</P>
<P>
   One of the four, Harry Ferrier, lives in Oak Harbor, Wash., and
remembers last year's trip fondly. Ferrier, who spent 30 years in
the Navy and retired with the rank of commander, was a
radioman/gunner in a torpedo bomber squadron that was nearly wiped
out during the battle of Midway. Of the group, a unit that was
attached to the carrier Hornet but was based at Midway, only
Ferrier and his pilot survived, both wounded and somehow able to
limp home in a tattered Grumman Avenger that was essentially a
flying piece of Swiss cheese.
</P>
<P>
   In reflecting on his contribution to the battle, Ferrier isn't
so much philosophical as he is matter-of-fact.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was afternoon,'' he said, ``and it became obvious that our
airplane was the only one that had come back, that the other five
did not, and we eventually just had to accept the fact that all
five were shot down.''
</P>
<P>
   If we need Robert Ballard to remind us of such heroic sacrifice,
then ``The Battle for Midway'' serves a purpose. But just as
Ballard looks at war and asks why, it's easy to look at Ballard's
efforts and ask the same question.
</P>
<P>
   Racing to save a film legacy
</P>
<P>
   If you believe film is art, just as worthy of preservation as a
Michelangelo fresco or a Mick Jagger recording, you might
appreciate the spirit in ``The Race to Save 100 Years.'' But you
likely won't have a better understanding of how films are
preserved.
</P>
<P>
   The one-hour documentary, airing Wednesday night on the Turner
Classic Movies cable channel, is a noble attempt to drum up support
for preserving and restoring films of the past. It includes rarely
seen excerpts of movie history, such as the only surviving footage
from Greta Garbo's 1928 silent film, ``The Divine Woman,'' plus
many before-and-after examples of painstakingly restored films.
</P>
<P>
   But for film buffs interested in the actual process of
restoration and preservation, it's merely a tease. While ``The Race
to Save 100 Years'' does a good job of explaining the deterioration
of old films on nitrate stock and even newer acetate stock, it
falls way short of illuminating the effort to put the magic back in
the great films of the past century.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned: As a production of Turner Entertainment Co., the
documentary also spends the requisite amount of time applauding Ted
Turner's efforts to preserve films, but it doesn't detract from the
film or from a 24-hour ``restoration marathon'' Wednesday on TCM.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends
</P>
<P>
   NBC will air what amounts to its first three-hour season finale
May 22 when a one-hour episode of ``The Pretender'' at 8 p.m. leads
into a two-hour cliffhanger at 9.... Fans of Donna Abandando, take
note: Gail O'Grady will reprise the character in an appearance on
ABC's ``NYPD Blue'' April 27.... The animation frenzy continues.
David Spade (``Just Shoot Me'') has begun production on the
animated comedy series ``Sammy'' for NBC. The series borrows from
Spade's real-life relationship with his father, Sammy Spade. David
Spade will do the voices of both characters. Others in the cast
include Andy Dick and Maura Tierney of ``NewsRadio.'' NBC has
ordered 13 episodes and plans a midseason launch next year....
Beginning April 26, ``The Tonight Show With Jay Leno'' will begin
nightly broadcasts in high-definition digital format....NBC says
its decision this week to cancel the soap opera ``Another World''
has generated fewer than 50 complaints.
</P>
</TEXT>
