<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LERACH-LEXECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAW FIRM TO PAY LONGTIME FOE $50 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach, a New York law firm that
has grown rich by suing Corporate America, agreed to pay $50
million Tuesday to its longtime foe, Lexecon Inc., a Chicago
consulting firm, which had contended in court that the law firm had
tried to destroy its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   In a long-running feud, Lexecon and one of its prominent
consultants, Daniel Fischel, the dean of the University of Chicago
Law School, had accused lawyers at Milberg Weiss of having tried to
discredit the consulting firm by unfairly trying to tie it to the
billion-dollar collapse of Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan.
</P>
<P>
   After hearing the consultants' contentions that the law firm had
abused the legal process to discredit Lexecon, a jury in U.S.
District Court in Chicago on Monday awarded the consulting firm $45
million in compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   Before the jury could decide whether punitive damages should be
added to that amount, the two sides talked through the night,
reaching the $50 million settlement Tuesday morning. The settlement
takes the place of the $45 million jury verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest and most powerful class-action plaintiff's firm
was found liable for abuse of process,'' said Alan N. Salpeter, a
lawyer at Mayer, Brown &AMP; Platt in Chicago, which represents
Lexecon. ``This sends a message that lawyers should not abuse the
law.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers at Milberg Weiss said Tuesday that they did not wish to
comment. Lexecon referred all questions to Salpeter.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg Weiss agreed to wire $50 million Tuesday to Lexecon's
account, Salpeter said. And both firms agreed not to sue each other
again over the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Milberg Weiss and Lexecon have often appeared on
opposite sides of the court room in class-action lawsuits filed
against public companies alleging they committed securities fraud.
Milberg Weiss has brought hundreds of those lawsuits on behalf of
shareholders, while Lexecon has often been hired by the
corporations being sued to testify as an expert witness and punch
holes in the suits' claims.
</P>
<P>
   Fischel has long been an outspoken critic of the securities
fraud cases. In 1995, in testimony before a congressional panel, he
said that the lawsuits were ``legalized extortion.''
</P>
<P>
   The class-action cases, which have earned fortunes in
contingency fees for Milberg Weiss and other plaintiffs' law firms,
are typically filed when bad news causes a company's stock price to
drop. The suits often contend that corporate executives misled
shareholders by not disclosing the problems.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit settled Tuesday revolved around a move made by
Milberg Weiss in 1990 to add Lexecon as a defendant in a securities
fraud case brought against Lincoln Savings &AMP; Loan, the Irvine,
Calif., institution controlled by Charles Keating that collapsed in
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Milberg Weiss had pointed to reports by Lexecon consultants that
said that Lincoln was sound. Lexecon had argued that the lawsuit
was frivolous. But it agreed to settle the claims, paying the
plaintiffs about $700,000, which was about how much it had received
from Lincoln in consulting fees.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement, when Lexecon appeared as an expert witness
in other securities cases, Milberg Weiss lawyers brought up the
Lincoln Savings case to try to discredit Lexecon's testimony, the
consulting firm contended in the lawsuit. And that, in turn, hurt
the firm's business, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   Lexecon was founded in 1977 by two University of Chicago
professors. Late last year, Lexecon was acquired by Nextera
Enterprises Inc., a company controlled by Michael Milken. Nextera
has plans to soon sell shares to the public. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
