<SLUG> BC-DEADBEAT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADBEAT DAD SENTENCED TO 18 MONTHS IN FEDERAL PRISON  

</HEADLINE>
 DAD-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ED ASHER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Shirley Malone Price had grown to enjoy a fairly
comfortable life here.
</P>
<P>
   Her family had maid service six days a week in their two-story
home.
</P>
<P>
   She had jewelry and furs. It was ``a joy,'' she says, to be a
stay-at-home mom raising four children.
</P>
<P>
   The youngest was 9 months old and a ``crawling child'' when her
husband of 18 years left her in 1982 and moved to California.
That's when Price began to see her life erode.
</P>
<P>
   She had to find outside work and eventually had to move back to
the one-story, cracked-brick house where she grew up ``on a very
rough street'' in inner-city Houston.
</P>
<P>
   She was grateful for food stamps, but her children were
embarrassed that other kids knew they were on a free lunch program
at school.
</P>
<P>
   Price reached the point she had to pawn her jewelry and furs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in the upper class to begin with (in her marriage) and
we had to come all the way down,'' said Price, 52, now a telephone
representative for Continental Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   But Monday, Price says, she finally saw justice when her former
husband, Wendell Price Sr., was sentenced to 18 months in a federal
prison for failure to pay child support and ordered to pay his
former wife more than $173,000.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge David Hittner ordered Price, 56, to prison
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence ended the first felony ``deadbeat parents'' case
heard in federal court in South Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Price was charged under the Deadbeat Parents Punishment
Act of 1998, signed into law by President Clinton last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The law stiffens the Child Support Recovery Act of 1992 by
upgrading failure to pay child support from a federal misdemeanor
to a felony when the amount owed is greater than $10,000 or has
remained unpaid longer than two years.
</P>
<P>
   The government has an interest in these cases because custodial
parents often end up on welfare when child support is not paid,
Assistant U.S. Attorney Andrew Bobb said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal benefits,'' he said, ``are used at an alarming rate
when these deadbeat parents don't pay up.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecuting deadbeat parents ``is working toward Congress' and
the president's goal of reducing welfare rolls,'' Bobb said.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Attorney General's Office, which investigates these
cases, says the law puts more teeth into the prosecutorial process.
</P>
<P>
   The AG office refers any case dealing with a noncustodial parent
living outside of Texas to federal prosecutors. But child support
advocates have complained that such cases were not a high priority
for the feds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main difference is, making it a felony gives U.S.
attorneys more of an incentive to pursue the case,'' AG spokesman
Matt Winslow said. ``Everybody operates with limited resources, and
a felony is going to be a higher priority than lesser crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Child support advocates say it's too early to tell the new law's
impact, if any, but they are happy about the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a clear message to people who go to other states to
avoid paying that this crime will no longer be tolerated,'' said
Debbie Kline, national chapter development director for the
Association for Children for Enforcement of Support Inc., a
nonprofit group based in Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Kline agreed that child support cases were never a priority for
federal prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   But Bobb says the Price case is proof the federal government is
now serious about prosecuting such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Price's case is particularly egregious, because he had money,
Bobb said.
</P>
<P>
   In the couple's 1985 divorce, Price was ordered to pay $1,500
per month in child support. Shirley Price said he never paid more
than $400 at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Houston, her husband was earning about $300,000 a
year operating a welding shop and a machine shop on contract to
several large oil equipment companies, she said.
</P>
<P>
   When indicted, Price was living in a $400,000 house in San
Bernadino, Calif., and managing a lucrative restaurant owned by his
second wife's cousin, Bobb said.
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Price said her ex owns two Mercedes-Benz cars and two
pickup trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made a very good living,'' Bobb said. ``He could have paid
his child support payments, but he let his children live in poverty
and struggle.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Price says Price was once a good husband and father, and
she is not pleased he is going to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main objective was to get the money to take care of my
family,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so horrible for children to have to go without when their
parents have money. It would be different if my husband didn't have
money all these years. He has money and would not give it to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she expects her ex-husband to pay up now, Shirley Price
said, ``I hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
