<SLUG> BC-BBA-WHITESOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SOX HITTERS SHOW INEXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- The Chicago White Sox must be wondering what the big
fuss is about Fenway Park. Never mind the Green Monster. What do
you do to combat Boston's veteran pitching?
</P>
<P>
   The inexperience of Chicago's Kiddie Corps showed time and again
in a 6-0 loss to the Red Sox and Bret Saberhagen Tuesday. Nothing
in their two previous series _ on the road in Seattle and at home
against Kansas City _ could have prepared the young hitters for
their Fenway Moment.
</P>
<P>
   They almost had Saberhagen on the ropes in the first inning,
loading the bases. But he repelled them with three called third
strikes. For the day, the White Sox struck out seven times, though
the Boston pitchers got some assistance from plate umpire Dale
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a Saberhagen on the hook early, you have to
take advantage of it,'' said Chicago manager Jerry Manuel, whose
team has lost five straight. ``We didn't do that. We sent up six
men in the first inning and didn't score. They had an experienced
pitcher who knew what he was doing and how to get out of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we had Albert Belle and Robin Ventura batting fourth
and fifth for 162 games. It's a little different when you have to
replace them with a young man coming up from Double A ball (Jeff
Liefer) or another man (Magglio Ordonez) who is just 22 years old.
It's a learning experience and hopefully we can grasp it and run
with it a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox' motto for this rebuilding season is ``The Kids
Can Play.'' They can . . . but right now they're overmatched by
good pitching. Even though Frank Thomas, one of the few veterans in
the lineup, is hitting a league-beat .591, the White Sox have
scored just one run in their last 20 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had opportunities and didn't take advantage of it,''
said Thomas. ``Anytime you get runners on base three times like we
did today and don't get anything out of it, there is a good chance
you're not going to win ballgames.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saberhagen pitched out of a jam in the first because he's a
veteran who can spot the ball where he wants it. We have a bunch of
young, talented guys who are used to having control of the strike
zone. Up here, sometimes you can't control some things. You have to
take your knocks, and that is just what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The seven called strikeouts bothered Manuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a hitter gets into a strikeout situation,'' said Manuel,
``you would hope they would be able to foul that pitch off to get a
better pitch, not just take it and leave it in the hands or
judgment of whomever. Leave yourself some room for the pitcher to
make the mistakes. We just can't continue to say we're learning.
I'd like for us to make some adjustments and do some things to
enhance that process.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel also wasn't pleased that his starter, Jim Parque (1-1),
walked two batters to set up Boston's three-run rally in the
second. There were two outs when Parque walked Jason Varitek and
Donnie Sadler. Jose Offerman then tripled them home and scored on a
single by Darren Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our pitch selection wasn't the best in that inning,'' said
Manuel.``We were 2-0 on Varitek and he threw a curveball. I'd much
prefer to see him go after a guy rather than throw a pitch like a
breaking ball and fall behind further, then end up walking him and
the next guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could come into Boston knowing we'd give up only three
runs, I could accept that. But with the way our offense is going,
you have to evaluate from that perspective. We have to be able to
score. One run in 20 innings is too much pressure. You can't expect
your pitchers to out and hold a team to no runs or one run.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't be this way forever, said shortstop Mike Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just getting started,'' he said. ``We're just getting
things to fall in place. The important thing is to keep playing
good defense. As the season goes on, we will start hitting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
