<SLUG> BC-BABIES-PARENTING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO SCHOOLS OF THOUGHT ON HOW TO RAISE, DISCIPLINE BABIES 
</HEADLINE>
 SIDEBAR-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CECELIA GOODNOW  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ What the Ezzos say:
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two related dangers that threaten successful
parenting. The first is not rightly understanding the significance
of the husband-wife relationship in the parenting process, and the
second is the danger of child-centered parenting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Your choice in parenting philosophy will actually determine
your child's hunger patterns, sleep patterns and even his or her
basic disposition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``...Consider mealtime an opportunity to teach basic skills. For
example, instruct your baby daughter in the appropriate use of her
hands and her voice, and begin to teach her early table manners....
If you have to, hold your baby's hands away from her food. Even
better, teach her where to place her hands while being fed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Teach the child to obey according to the character of true
obedience _ immediately, completely, without challenge and without
complaint.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If soiling continues to be a problem with a child who is over
two-and-a-half years of age, hold the child accountable for his or
her accidents. By that, we mean the child should clean up himself
or herself, plus the soiled clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   -From ``On Becoming Babywise'' and ``On Becoming Babywise Book
Two'' by Gary Ezzo and Dr. Robert Bucknam.
</P>
<P>
   What Penelope Leach Says:
</P>
<P>
   ``...Taking a baby's point of view does not mean neglecting the
viewpoint of parents or other caring adults, because they are
inextricably intertwined.... Raising children is hard work.... For
almost everyone it means making compromises.''
</P>
<P>
   ``New babies sleep exactly the amount that their personal
physiology tells them to sleep. There is nothing that you can do to
make your baby sleep more than this amount and nothing that the
baby can do to sleep less.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Problems over an older baby's or toddler's eating often
dominate the lives of whole families for months on end. You can do
a great deal to avoid them by cultivating relaxed and accepting
attitudes now.... Expect a mess and arrange to cope with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Smacking children can't teach them how to behave and the proof
is that once a child starts to be punished that way, he'll get
smacked all through childhood. In fact, it's because physical
punishments are so ineffective that they tend to escalate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't try to force the child to sit on the potty, even if you
can see that she is about to have a bowel movement.... The clearer
you make it that you really want her to sit there, the less likely
she is to want to.... Above all don't imply that use of the potty
is a moral issue.''
</P>
<P>
   -From ``Your Baby &AMP; Child'' by Penelope Leach
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
