<SLUG> BC-KOSOV0-COST-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: ILL.)  
 ADMINISTRATION ASKS FOR $4 BILLION TO PAY FOR WAR
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the air campaign against Yugoslavia continues to
widen, the Clinton administration presented Congress with the bill
Tuesday: over $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And Defense Secretary William Cohen is asking President Clinton
to call up thousands of air force and army reservists to fly and
maintain many of the 300 additional airplanes requested by NATO
this week, as well as to serve in other parts of the operation.
</P>
<P>
   In closed door sessions with members of the Senate and House,
officials from the administration said the Pentagon would need at
least $3 billion for the air war itself and another $500 million
for the refugee operation through the fiscal year that ends Sept.
30, according to senior officials who attended the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said the emergency
request, not counting the refugee relief operation, could reach $4
billion by the time it is formally submitted sometime this week.
``It's all in the early stages of planning,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen is expected to ask the president to call up pilots to fly
some of the refueling tankers that are part of the latest request
made this week by Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme commander of NATO
forces, for 300 planes that include combat jets for ground attack
and air defense suppression as the campaign over Yugoslavia becomes
a 24-hour operation.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the Pentagon said it would need to call up specialists
in the Army reserve to serve in Macedonia and Albania, particularly
in civil affairs units.
</P>
<P>
   Since the campaign began, the armed forces have been under a
growing strain. All air patrols over northern Iraq have been
suspended because combat jets were sent to fight over Yugoslavia.
The only aircraft carrier normally in Asian waters has been
deployed to the Persian Gulf, allowing the Theodore Roosevelt to be
sent for duty to the Mediterranean.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's stock of air-launched cruise missiles has been
depleted to below 100 missiles, according to Pentagon officials.
And this week, the Pentagon asked for a ``supplemental
solicitation'' for jet fuel and other petroleum products for forces
in Europe because the air war has drawn down the jet fuel supplies.
</P>
<P>
   And as the air war moves into what President Clinton described
Tuesday as a new phase, ``a more intense version of the current
phase,'' according to the Pentagon, operating around the clock and
increasing the number of daylight raids, the demands on the U.S.
air force are growing.
</P>
<P>
   Clark ``would like to fly more intensively during both day and
night hours _ in other words, more sorties; and strike a wider
range of targets,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   To wage such an widening war and take advantage of the damage
already inflicted on the Serbian armed forces, Clark has made two
requests since Saturday for a total of 382 additional airplanes,
squeezing certain areas _ especially on the fleet of refueling
tankers. As the air war has intensified the need for aerial
refueling has grown dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the Kosovo war has called on 63 percent of the active
duty force of KC-135 tankers, according to Lt. Col. Charles Wynne
of Scott Air Base, in Illinois, and the base just hit a record of
sending 100 tankers to the European theater, which includes some
planes earmarked for southwest Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we increase the tankers sent over, the national guard and
the reserve will have to make the crew,'' said Wynne. ``We can
squeeze a few more from active duty, but the majority will have to
be the guard and reserve.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   All of these demands add up to the request for emergency funding
described to Congress Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Although that is a rough estimate, several Clinton
administration officials told Congress that the refugee relief
operation would cost from $515 to $560 million, which would be
shared between the State Department's refugee office and the
Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration officials told congressional leaders that
it cost from $70 to $100 million a day to fight the air war over
Yugoslavia, according to a spokesman for Trent Lott, the Senate
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion of the campaign at this cost, with the strain it
places on the military, led some congressional leaders to ask
whether the military remained prepared to fight two major wars at
the same time, as required under defense policy.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional leaders said they wanted to approve the emergency
supplemental funding but they had yet to determine whether they
would have to look for cuts in other domestic programs to offset
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
