<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOERNE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$     04-13 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOERNE-MUSIC-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SCHUBERT, AGE YIELDS ITS RANK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Art isn't a question of age. I can't think the way someone else
does just because he's older and famous. One argument that
(italics)never(end italics) counts is `I'm right, because I have
more experience.'''
</P>
<P>
   So says the German baritone Matthias Goerne, who is 32, still
legitimately within the category (popular with publicists, who
treat it as infinitely elastic) of the ``young'' singer.
</P>
<P>
   But if the label suggests promise for the future rather than
mastery at the present hour, it does not apply. Like any performer
in a classical discipline _ a discipline, that is, with an
established literature and technical standards about which there
exists a reasonable degree of consensus _ Goerne had to learn his
craft along the way. Yet like Cecilia Bartoli and Bryn Terfel, he
burst on the international scene as a personality fully formed.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of seniority arises in connection with Goerne's new
recital partner, the professorial Austrian pianist Alfred Brendel,
who is 68. Together, they have been investigating Schubert song
cycles. New Yorkers will hear the duo for the first time on
Thursday evening at Carnegie Hall in ``Winterreise,'' that
agonizing cycle of heartbreak and alienation. The more varied
``Schwanengesang'' follows on April 28.
</P>
<P>
   Listeners expecting performances in any sense directed from the
keyboard, a possibility Brendel's eminence might in theory make
plausible, are in for a surprise. The pianist's last association of
this sort goes back to Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau, who towers over
the postwar landscape of song like a lone colossus.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I heard Herr Goerne,'' Brendel said recently, ``nobody
since Fischer-Dieskau has inspired me to go back to lieder.''
</P>
<P>
   Not, however, because Herr Goerne and Herr Brendel (as the
partners call each other with old-school formality) always think
alike. Far from it. Goerne tells the story that when they reached
an especially fraught moment of ``Winterreise,'' their interpretive
instincts were diametrically opposed. Brendel wanted to underscore
the pain by broadening the tempo. Goerne thought the passage should
be drier, simpler. Brendel invoked ``tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where is it written?'' Goerne wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here,'' Brendel insisted, with a thump on the score. ``In the
notes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking at the notes, too,'' Goerne came back.
</P>
<P>
   Three years have passed since Goerne first sang in New York, in
a recital at the Frick Collection. That week, he and Graham
Johnson, his pianist for the occasion, paid a visit to Robert
White's lieder class at the Juilliard School.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in a leather jacket, metal trim jangling, shod in biker
boots, with dark hair buzzed down to a shadow on the skull, the
singer looked to have wandered onto the set of a very wrong movie.
But the instant he got to work, running through Brahms' ``Four
Serious Songs'' (Op. 121), he showed what it means to be in
command, or perhaps to be possessed. The Biblical text rang out in
tones as momentous as they were beautiful, the message both
timeless and immediately personal, distilling the bleak wisdom of
ages into the inflection of a syllable.
</P>
<P>
   At Christmastime last year, Goerne was back in New York, this
time at the Metropolitan Opera, as Mozart's birdman Papageno. ``Die
Zauberflote'' teaches its life lessons by means of fable, and here
again, Goerne proved an interpreter of genius.
</P>
<P>
   On the concert stage, he affects a Nehru jacket, an
unconventional choice, but his peculiarly expressive rubber-jointed
body language shows through any costume. Constant, too, is the look
on his round face and cornflower eyes, wide with wonder, the mirror
of a mind to which the world is ever new. His voice _ a smooth,
seductive instrument rather than a mighty engine _ touches the
music with gentle assurance, like a hand in a velvet glove.
</P>
<P>
   We are a long way from the formal graces of the star vocalists
of yesteryear, yet among the new generation of recitalists, no one
has absorbed more from the postwar paragons or had more of their
attention. In the age of the master class, the (``young'') singers
entitled to list Dietrich Fischer-Dieskau and Elisabeth Schwarzkopf
on their resumes are legion. Those who have studied with either of
them for an extended period are few. Goerne did so with both.
</P>
<P>
   But even more important than these, Goerne says, was the unsung
Hans-Joachim Beyer, who took him on in the Communist East Germany
of his adolescence at the Mendelssohn Hochschule in Leipzig. At the
time, Beyer was a lowly assistant. Goerne was his first student.
For two years, they worked together an hour and a half a day. Other
than that, Goerne did not practice at all, he says. ``We only did
exercises, no singing. Lots of la-la-la-la, ne-ne-ne-ne.'' Any
songs and arias were strictly as required for exams.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, he was my most important teacher,'' Goerne says.
``He made it possible for me to study with the others. Going to
them, you need to be able to sing reasonably well. Then they get
all the laurels. It's not really fair.''
</P>
<P>
   The first time he sang for Fischer-Dieskau, one of his songs was
``Am Meer,'' from ``Schwanengesang.'' ``Herr Goerne,'' he recalls
the great man saying, ``you have a very attractive voice. It speaks
to people. You have a way of focusing a listener's attention, very
personal, very honest, not dry. But now, let's sing this song
right.'' In the event, Goerne worked with Fischer-Dieskau regularly
for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to accept that teachers like this are strong
personalities with strong points of view,'' Goerne says. ``You
can't expect to change them. You have to take what they give you.
And in the long run _ on the stage, at the latest _ you have to do
what works for you. Fischer-Dieskau never wanted to make people
sing like him. He had great distance. He said what he had to say,
you did it or didn't do it, and either was OK
</P>
<P>
   ``The greatest thing I got from him is concentration, the
ability to be in a piece from the first note. A song is so short.
There are great possibilities, but little time. You have to start
with great clarity, so people know where you're going.''
</P>
<P>
   And what lessons did he draw from Ms. Schwarzkopf?
</P>
<P>
   ``She focuses a lot on interpretation, too. But she also has the
courage to intervene in technical matters. She had a great
influence on the timbre of my voice. When we started, I sounded
like a tenor on top, like a bass at the bottom, and in the middle a
little bit like a baritone. The differences in color were too
great. She always tries to find the point where a voice rings out
in the most beautiful and natural way.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the purpose of all this study is to find yourself,
to find your individual tone, not to fit into a whole class of
nobodies.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly there is nothing anonymous about Goerne's instrument
or manner, and his approach to repertory is also distinctive. In a
recital, he looks for what he calls a ``story,'' though it need not
be of the narrative sort. ``It's more of an emotional thing,'' he
explains. ``I want to take a listener through the program, giving
clear emotional direction, step by step, with smooth transitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Though signed to an exclusive recording contract by
Decca/London, Goerne casts a wary eye on executives who want to
groom ``all-around'' artists, with portfolios ``from Baroque to
Broadway.'' He does not believe that a baritone who has sung
Mozart's Count Almaviva needs to do Don Giovanni, too. He has no
designs on Rossini's Figaro, although he has the notes for the
part. And he turns down offers for Debussy's Pelleas, for which he
has the sensitivity but not the French.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, his discography stretches from Bach's cantata ``Der
Streit Zwischen Phoebus und Pan'' (on Hanssler) to Hanns Eisler's
``Hollywood Songbook'' (London) by way of Schubert's Goethe songs
(London) and ``Winterreise'' (Hyperion). Last December, the Eisler
appeared on the front page of the influential French newspaper Le
Monde as the classical recording of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Goerne does not mind confessing that Bach's quasi-instrumental
treatment of the voice makes his music hard to sing, though you
would not guess it from his performance. He thinks of the Eisler as
a latter-day ``Winterreise'': not linear, as Schubert's is, yet no
less searching on the subject of exile. In November, at the Zurich
Opera, he takes on Berg's ``Wozzeck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Time and patience are the most important things,'' the singer
reflects. ``In every phase, whether you're 21 or 31, you need to
feel that this moment is the ne plus ultra. You can't tell yourself
that in five years you'll do a piece differently or better. But
five years later, you look back and you can see that you're in a
new place. It's a sign that you've been working hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
