<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6871 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS &LR;      04-13 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB INCURSION INTO ALBANIA HEIGHTENS WAR FEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN AND ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Yugoslav forces shelled and briefly occupied a
small village on the Albanian side of the Albania-Kosovo border
Tuesday, sending waves of fear through a nearby camp of 90,000
refugees, some of whom began fleeing toward the Albanian capital of
Tirana.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were no casualties and the invaders soon withdrew,
the incident was the most serious along the border in several
weeks, and it raised the spector of expanded fighting while dealing
a blow to hopes that the refugee crisis in the region was coming
under control.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, meanwhile, political support spread for use of
NATO ground troops in Kosovo, if that is necessary for victory. But
US and alliance officials said they still expect to win without
having to invade Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton spent much of his day briefing members of
Congress on the crisis and urging them to be patient and give the
air campaign time to work. Participants in the sessions said
Clinton did not rule out the use of ground troops, though the White
House said the president has no intention to use such forces.
</P>
<P>
   In other major developments Tuesday, the 21st day of the effort
to stop Serb-dominated Yugoslav abuses of ethnic Albanians in the
Kosovo province:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gen. Wesley Clark, the supreme commander of NATO, said in
Brussels the allies are grinding down the Serbian armed forces but
are still far short of delivering a knockout punch. Some elements
of the Serbian military machine ``would recover rather quickly if
we were to let go of our attack . . .,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Clinton said he would ask Congress to fund the military
operation through an emergency supplement, estimated by the
Pentagon at $3 billion to $4 billion through the fiscal year ending
October 1. Administration officials said the Pentagon could soon
call as many as 2,000 US reserve troops, mostly Air Force
personnel, to active duty.
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO said it attacked two major oil refineries in Serbia and
various targets near the Kosovo capital of Pristina in overnight
air strikes. The refineries at Pancevo, east of Belgrade, and in
the northern city of Novi Sad have been attacked several times.
Yugoslavia's official news agency Tanjug said NATO again attacked
targets around Novi Sad at about 1:20 a.m. on Wednesday. Tanjug
said NATO also attacked the Bistrica hydroelectric plant near the
southern Serb town of Nova Varos on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and Russian Foreign
Minister Igor Ivanov met for four hours in Norway, and, while
neither side changed its basic positions, Ivanov's remarks
afterwards were free of the harshness with which Russia has
condemned the NATO bombardment in recent weeks. US officials
suggested Russia could play a constructive role in ending the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   _ A Russian government minister said the air campaign had killed
more than 400 civilians in Yugoslavia, and a Yugoslav official
called a missile attack that killed 10 civilians and wounded 16 on
a train a war crime.
</P>
<P>
   NATO said the missile was fired at a key bridge between Kosovo
province and the rest of Serbia. A film of the attack, released by
NATO in Brussels, showed the train entering the pilot's view only
an instant before the missile was fired.
</P>
<P>
   _ A defense official in Washington said an aerial photograph
showed signs of a mass grave near the Kosovo town of Velika Krusa,
where a human rights group reported Yugoslav forces apparently shot
and killed 40 ethnic Albanian men.
</P>
<P>
   _ More than 3,000 Kosovo refugees streamed into Albania,
international monitors said. Hundreds also poured into Macedonia,
the biggest group to cross since Yugoslavia closed its borders last
week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Australian Foreign Minister Alexander Downer said his country
has been notified that Yugoslavia will charge two detained
Australian humanitarian workers with espionage. Aid workers Steve
Pratt and Peter Wallace were detained March 31.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the president Tuesday, Senator John F. Kerry,
a Massachusetts Democrat, said Clinton told members of Congress
that neither Clark nor the NATO allies are calling for use of
ground troops, and the president ``does not personally believe at
this time that they will be necessary to achieve the goal. I also
heard him say... he will accept nothing less than the achievement
of our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said subsequently that the administration had made a
mistake by stating, initially, that use of ground troops would not
be considered and ``that now has been reversed.''
</P>
<P>
   Numerous Democratic and Republican lawmakers urged Clinton to at
least begin preparations for ground troops so it could be done
quickly if they were deemed necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a general feeling among those making the decisions
that it's premature'' to be talking about use of ground troops,
Kerry said, but ``there has been a general movement toward
acceptability'' of such a step. He said he did not know if there
was majority support in Congress for a ground war, ``but there is
definitely majority sentiment that we need to follow this through,
and we need to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Congressional expression of this sentiment could come within two
or three weeks, Kerry said, predicting votes approving American
involvement in the NATO operation would come far in advance of the
60-day deadline specified in the War Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   The Serb incursion into Albania occurred at 1 p.m. Tuesday,
Albania time, when about 50 troops entered Kamenica, a village of
six houses separated from Kosovo by a 16-foot-wide road. The Serbs
fired mortars, set four of the houses on fire, then fled back
across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Langis Langlois, a field monitor for the Organization for
Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE), said there were no
casualties on either side, and no involvement in the skirmish by
the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), which is fighting for Kosovo's
independence from Yugoslavia. Neverthless, Langlois said this was
the most serious of recent skirmishes along the border.
</P>
<P>
   Albania said the Serb push into its territory would carry
consequences. Sokol Gjoka, an Albanian Foreign Ministry official,
said his country would take necessary steps to defend itself, ``in
close coordination with our allies.''
</P>
<P>
   Kamenica's civilian residents left long ago, followed by the
OSCE border station, which moved to Bajram Curri, 12 miles away,
several weeks ago as tensions with the nearby Serb forces rose.
</P>
<P>
   The gravest impact of the incident could be the alarm it is
spreading among refugees from Kosovo who have fled to Albania.
After the firing, unconfirmed reports swept Kukes, where one of the
largest camps of displaced persons from Kosovo is located, that the
Serbs intended to shell the town.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the refugees tried to flee, but many roads in the area
were impassable and few vehicles were available.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials said incursions have occurred periodically,
and some suggested the latest incident might actually be a positive
sign for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   ``To a certain extent, the ones that occurred today may be seen
as a sign of the Yugoslav forces' desperation,'' Kenneth H. Bacon
said. ``They have failed in their goal to cut down the KLA...
(which) continues to engage the Yugoslav forces. And they obviously
have increased in size. They have been recruiting a lot from
displaced persons within Albania.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from Globe wires services was used to prepare this
report. Kornblut reported from Albania.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
