<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN FROM KOSOVO, ALBANIANS STREAM INTO MACEDONIA AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 
(REPEATING to add photo note)  (Eds: 2nd take to follow expeditiously.) 
 (ART ADV: Map and photo are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVAC, Macedonia _ In the week since President Slobodan
Milosevic announced that he had halted offensive military
operations in Kosovo, Serbian paramilitary groups and Yugoslav
soldiers have systematically expelled tens of thousands of
Albanians from a swath of southeastern Kosovo, according to reports
from refugees arriving here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, among a group of 800 Kosovo Albanians allowed to
cross the border near here, described methodical attacks by
Milosevic's forces that cleared out a 10-mile-by-12-mile area that
appears to have little military value.
</P>
<P>
   In each account, Serbian paramilitary units or Yugoslav soldiers
were said to have expelled civilians and burned or shelled homes in
at least 15 villages around the town of Urosevac in southeastern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees described well-organized attacks in which masked
Serbian soldiers descend on an Albanian village, ordered everyone
to leave, and then shot or burned to death the defiant, infirm or
aged who stayed in their homes. It was impossible to determine how
many Albanians were forced from their homes by the attacks, but
roughly 50,000 people lived in the area before NATO bombing began
three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Western diplomats said that the rural area refugees have
described as the focus of the attack has not been a base of
operations for the Kosovo Liberation Army, the Kosovo Albanian
guerrilla group fighting for independence. And several of the
remote villages attacked did not seem to have a strategic purpose
in terms of thwarting a NATO invasion or rebel efforts to smuggle
supplies into Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslav forces essentially sealed the border with Macedonia
last week, but the number of people allowed to cross here doubled
over the last three days.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the United Nations High
Commissioner for Refugees, said that the increase in the number of
refugees crossing into Macedonia in recent days could signal that
vast numbers of Albanian may soon flee Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It does sound very clear from the refugees that there is a
much larger number of people who want to come in,'' she said. ``But
we never know what to expect. The last time, it was 40,000 people
in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, two dozen of the refugees arriving in Macedonia
Tuesday described the same type of expulsions by Yugoslav forces
and paramilitary units that previous waves of Albanian refugees
experienced.
</P>
<P>
   Luzlim Shala, a 28-year-old teacher, said Yugoslav Army soldiers
in armored personnel carriers descended on his village last Monday.
His village, Mirash, is a quiet, farming village of 1,000 people
nestled at the base of a 2,500-foot mountain and is five miles from
the main road. The soldiers ordered all civilians out of their
homes and burned a handful before departing. That same day, in an
attack potentially carried out by the same group, Yugoslav soldiers
descended on the village of Prelez i Jerlive on the main road
running north of Urocevac, according to Fadil Zeqir, a 32-year-old
agricultural engineer. There, he said, the town's 300 families were
told they had twenty minutes to leave the town. Resident scurried
into the surrounding hills and no homes were burned.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
