<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JUDSON-DANCE-2TAKES-$     04-13 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JUDSON-DANCE-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INCUBATOR'S CHILDREN COME HOME TO SAY THANKS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Allen Hughes is a former music and dance critic of The New York
Times.  
 By ALLEN HUGHES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the not too distant past it was my good fortune to
chance upon the performance of an arresting, unconventional work. A
luminous fabric comprising music both vocal and instrumental,
literary fragments from varied centuries and civilizations, and
everyday movement functioning as dance, it projected an
irresistible aura of good will and celebrated the wonderful power
of artistic persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   And, for the best of reasons, it reminded me instantly of the
Judson Dance Theater, that whirlpool of restless creative spirits
performing at Judson Memorial Church at Washington Square in the
1960s. This was not just because the performance I was experiencing
was being given in the St. James Memorial Chapel of Union
Theological Seminary and had been conceived and directed by
Meredith Monk, but because its unrelated elements had been
juxtaposed so imaginatively into an expressive whole. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. The Judson dance activity of the 60s was
taking place in a period of general youthful rebellion, and the
rambunctious avant-garde goings-on in the name of dance seldom
achieved anything approaching an ``expressive whole.'' But
combinations of wildly disparate ideas and doings were commonplace,
and occasionally they coalesced into something communicative.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 37 years after they first began enjoying Judson's
hospitality, a group of those formerly young would-be creators, who
found performance and exhibition space when they needed it most,
are expressing their gratitude in ``No Limits _ A Celebration of
Freedom and Art to Benefit Judson Memorial Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Judson Dance Theater are joined by those
of the Judson Poets' Theater and visual artists whose works were
displayed in the Judson Gallery. Some 75 dancers-choreographers,
poets, painters and sculptors are expected to participate in events
that began at the church last Friday and will run through this
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   More than 50 works donated by artists are being offered for
sale, and dance programs will be presented on Thursday and Friday
evenings. Among the dances scheduled are reconstructions of Yvonne
Rainer's ``Trio A With Flags'' and David Gordon's ``Chair Dance,''
new works by Kenneth King, Gus Solomons Jr., Wendy Perron with Dan
Froot, and a duet performed by Sara Rudner and Douglas Dunn, who
will be dancing together for the first time in more than 20 years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rainer, an organizer _ with Ruth Emerson and Steve Paxton _
of the Judson Dance Theater in 1962, became one of its most
prolific choreographers and possibly the least concerned with
audience response to what she did. Sometimes her extreme
self-absorption and aloof indifference to the public seemed almost
hostile. But some of the group movement in the Meredith Monk
performance at St. James Chapel brought back memories of an oddly
affecting work by Ms. Rainer.
</P>
<P>
   Entitled ``We Shall Run,'' it had a dozen people running to the
music of the ``Tuba Miram'' from the Berlioz Requiem. They were not
professional dancers, and there were no costumes; whatever they
wore that day, they wore. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is how I reported it in The Times: ``Sometimes they ran as
a pack, sometimes they divided into groups, sometimes they huddled
for an instant, but only as a respite from the gentle rhythmic
running that almost became hypnotic before it ended. And all the
while, the singing of Berlioz went on.'' Nothing could have seemed
more illogical as an artistic concept, but it worked, it really
worked. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That performance took place in Judson's gym, but most of those I
recall were given in the sanctuary upstairs, a big open space
without fixed church pews. There, one evening, ``a big
chandelierlike construction of self-playing drums rose from the
lowered position in which it had been playing (agitatedly but
quietly) in almost total darkness.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A spotlight focused abruptly on a white curtain,'' I
continued. ``An imperious whirring sound arose and through the
curtain, Fred Herko flashed in, looking beatific. He wore black
tights, a yellow-and-blue jersey with JUDSON emblazoned across the
front, and, on one foot, a black shoe and his means of locomotion _
a roller skate. Continuing to look beatific, he skated around the
floor for a time, moving his arms and the unencumbered foot through
various balletic positions. Before vanishing behind the white
curtain he did a bit of toe-dancing _ roller skate and bare foot
notwithstanding.'' This was part of something he called
``Binghamton Birdie.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Herko, whose work in the very first Judson Dance Theater event
on July 6, 1962, was ``Once or Twice a Week I Put On Sneakers to Go
Uptown,'' always appeared to me to be one of the cheeriest and
least complicated of the early Judsonites, but by 1965 he was being
memorialized by James Waring in a Judson dance program. He had
jumped through a window to his death, possibly as a result of
taking amphetamines.
</P>
<P>
   He was, I think, one of the most naturally gifted of the early
Judson dance people. Some of the others, it seemed to me, could get
hung up on theorizing. Ms. Rainer may have been one of those; in
1973 she gave up dance altogether to go into filmmaking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The one thing you could be sure of at a Judson dance event was
that matters of audience comfort would never trouble the
performers. If you were lucky and arrived early, the reward might
be a platform, a bench or maybe an odd chair on which to sit.
Otherwise you stood. But, of course, you could never be sure before
you got there which way you would want to be facing.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The sanctuary's usable floor space had no real front or back or
sideways, and the performers could deal with it as they wished. In
any case, standing did not seem too bad when the proceedings proved
interesting in one way or another. But because everything was not
only experimental but new (as long as I was a Judson regular,
nothing was ever repeated after its initial performances), and some
of the stuff was simply boring. Quality control did not seem to
figure in the scheduling of works, at least not quality as
conceived by the average viewer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As a group, these young choreographers _ who also included,
among others, Elaine Summers, Deborah Hay and Lucinda Childs _
disdained the conventions not only of classical ballet and modern
dance as represented by, say, Martha Graham, but also the artistic
practices, if not the movement technique, of Merce Cunningham, the
teacher of many of them.
</P>
<P>
   And since they were rebelling against so much, they had to forgo
borrowing almost anything related to theatrical dance unless the
intent was to make fun of it. This left them with a lot to invent,
too much in some cases. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Because Dada and the casual theories of John Cage suggested that
training and skill in an art were not necessarily required to be
creative in it, some painters and composers got into the Judson
Dance act. Some of their pieces could have been identified in the
programs as ``happenings'' (the name then given to what would now
be called ``performance''), but they were not.
</P>
<P>
   These nondance people also took part in other people's
creations. The most famous of them was the painter Robert
Rauschenberg. I remember seeing him in works by Steve Paxton, but I
do not recall that he had charisma as a performer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I cannot say who was most addicted to multimedia
experimentation, but there was a lot of it. Bits of movies, both
homemade and commercial, projections of almost anything
photographable, tapes of music of all kinds, of sounds of nature
and the street, of speeches by the famous and otherwise, the
playing of random radio shows _ all, in varied combinations, were
familiar elements of the dances at Judson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Except for The New York Times and The Village Voice (with Jill
Johnston), the New York dance press ignored what was going on at
Judson Church in the early years, declaring that it was not dance,
period. But word began to get around that something vital was
involved there, and, before long, opportunities to perform
elsewhere were forthcoming.
</P>
<P>
   Within the first two years, several venues opened up for various
groups of Judsonites in and around New York (one at a farm in New
Jersey), and early in 1964 there was an engagement as far afield as
the Once Festival in Ann Arbor, Mich. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Over time, new participants _ including Monk, King and Solomons
_ joined Judson Dance, but in 1964, the fervor, intensity and
inventiveness that characterized its beginnings had begun to
dissipate as opportunities to perform elsewhere increased. And in
1968, dance performances at Judson Church came to an end. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perceptive writing about avant-garde dance of the time was
beginning to be found in a variety of publications by 1965. Among
them was a monograph on dance in New York destined for a German
anthology. The author was George Jackson, an experienced dance
observer, who cited with enthusiasm the ``living dolls'' at
Judson. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Living dolls! Did they merit that encomium? Yes, I think so.
Unpredictable, irrepressible and, at times, exasperating they
surely were. But they managed to be entertaining more often than
not, and I feel that _ for the most part _ they sincerely believed
in what they were doing. They burst straitjackets of dance in their
time, and the effects are still with us today. Who could ask for
more?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
