<SLUG> BC-OHIO-TORNADOAID-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FEMA officials tour tornado destruction
 &HT;    By Joann Rouse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARREN CO., Ohio _ Investigators from the Federal Emergency
Management Agency toured the Warren County townships of Deerfield,
Salem and Hamilton on Tuesday to assess Friday's tornado damage.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bob Taft's administration hopes to get results of the
federal government's preliminary damage assessment in the next few
days, so Taft can decide whether to ask Washington to provide
federal loans and grants for rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton will have to declare the region a disaster
area to release federal aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The county's had at least $2.2 million of damage,'' said
county emergency services director Frank Young. ``About $1.5
million of that is in Deerfield, the rest is in Hamilton and about
1 or 2 percent is in Salem.''
</P>
<P>
   The twister destroyed six homes in Deerfield Twp. and one in
Hamilton Twp., according to the final official count.
</P>
<P>
   The tornado also caused severe damage to 10 Deerfield Twp. homes
and two homes in Hamilton Twp. Between 30 and 40 Deerfield Twp.
homes suffered minor damage, as did 25 in Hamilton Twp. and seven
in Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   During the windshield tour, one FEMA team assessed damage to
individual homes and another team searched for damage to public
structures. Officials said no public property damage had been
reported yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be showing them around (because) we're hoping we get a
declaration,'' Young said. ``We already had the state and county
declaration to get FEMA.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor will use information collected on the tour to
support his claim that the combined city, county and state
resources are insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   The governor will then submit a written request to the president
through the FEMA regional office.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA also provides the president with an analysis and a
recommended course of action.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency personnel from Carlisle and Mason said they hope they
can bill the federal government for overtime hours used after
helping the affected townships. But FEMA officials said they may do
so only if their mutual aid agreements compensates officers for
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   FEMA does not reimburse for services that are not usually paid,
federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   County and local officials - including building inspectors who
said they will waive the inspection fees for reconstructed houses -
are compiling a list of costs they hope to bill to the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get the declaration, the paperwork will really be flying
then,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Joann Rouse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio. This
article includes information from the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
