<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     04-13 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Raising bar is necessity for Rockets
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't it odd to hear the U.S. Davis Cup team's recent triumph
over Great Britain referred to as an inspiring upset?
</P>
<P>
   Is that what men's tennis in America has come to? After all, the
Brits haven't reared a male Grand Slam champion in more than six
decades.
</P>
<P>
   And it was equally strange to hear the TV types Monday night
gushing over the Rockets' win at Minnesota as a breakthrough _
their first ``quality'' victory on the road this season.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota? Is that what the Rockets have come to?
</P>
<P>
   Afraid so.
</P>
<P>
   In fairness, the maturing Timberwolves are a respectable outfit.
They were five games over .500, despite a recent swoon, until the
Rockets hit town. But, for a team with reasonable NBA championship
aspirations, the Rockets' standards require a significant upward
adjustment. Particularly because the winning script in Minneapolis
once again included that dreaded
hanging-on-for-dear-life-at-the-finish wrinkle.
</P>
<P>
   A comfortable lead, as is usually the case, begat a late swoon
and there the Rockets were, unsure of their fate until the waning
seconds. When Rudy Tomjanovich said a loss would have been
``devastating,'' he probably understated the case.
</P>
<P>
   On stage and screen, dramatic conclusions never are bad. On the
hardwood, if they are unnecessary, they only contribute to
self-doubt and excessive wear and tear on the body. The impact of
the latter, of course, is magnified in this mad scramble of a
season, especially with a talent core as old as Houston's.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley, not long removed from knee surgery, should have
been comfortably ensconced under a towel at the close Monday
evening, not shooting clutch free throws and then having to make a
crucial steal (granted, that bit of heroics became necessary
because he missed a couple of clutch free throws) to secure the
win.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets must find a way to cut themselves slack over their
13 remaining games. The fact nine of them are at home and a 10th is
an afternoon start in San Antonio is fortuitous scheduling, but it
seems an easy blowout tonight against Vancouver with Portland
coming in 24 hours later is beyond obligatory.
</P>
<P>
   Remember the crazy lineup Rudy put on the floor to start the
second quarter of the Utah game? It was Bryce Drew, Sam Mack, Matt
Bullard, Antoine Carr and Othella Harrington, and that's who should
play most of the fourth quarter against the hapless Grizzlies, a
7-31 shipwreck.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets also have two games remaining against both the
Mavericks and the Clippers, and three of them are at Compaq Center.
Combined with the nine off days sprinkled semi-liberally through
the season's presumed soft landing at Denver on May 5, the Rockets
should have plenty of energy to spare for the more demanding tests
against Seattle, Phoenix and Minnesota plus, of course, the
measuring-stick faceoffs against the Trail Blazers, the Spurs, the
Lakers and the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, the Rockets have a 1-6 record against the latter
quartet, their alleged peer group in the West.
</P>
<P>
   It's not about the Rockets sending messages, either. It's not
about them proving anything to the bad guys. It's about proving
something to themselves. Until they whip the good teams, they can't
be sure they can. Simple-minded stuff perhaps, but this is how the
human mind works.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie triumvirate of Cuttino Mobley, Michael Dickerson and
Drew doesn't know how it feels to beat the elite because it has no
reference point, save for the lonely W against Portland. The
superkids need positive reinforcement before the playoffs, or they
won't be ready for the entirely different level of intensity that's
going to smack them in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Scottie Pippen is in a similar boat. He might have a
hand full of rings plus one, but it's apparent his remarkable
Chicago experience has had little carry-over effect on his second
life in Houston. The same as the rookies, he has no self-validating
point of reference to make him believe he can win here, no matter
how often he might have won there.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen has become a completely different player in Rockets
pinstripes. Even his natural instincts appear stifled, if not
missing. But, if he could produce just one huge game against a team
that it's not so easy to be huge against, perhaps muscle memory
would kick in, the light would come on, and he would find his
wings.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie's teammates try to help. Barkley insists Pippen needs to
take at least 15 shots per game to be in the flow and that he would
be honored to surrender a share of his. Yet, against Minnesota,
Pippen launched a mere six attempts _ to Barkley's 12 _ and played
just 31 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder about Pippen's back. If the problem is he's in pain,
then his underperforming is understandable, and there might be no
salvation possible. Still, we keep hoping.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we keep hoping the Rockets can learn how to protect a
lead _ and figure out a way to defeat a team worth defeating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
