<HEADER>
A6890 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HILLARY-CLINTON14-COX     04-13 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-CLINTON14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    First lady attends campaign dinner for husband's defender
 &HT;    By Brian E. Crowley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOCA RATON, Fla. _ First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton thanked
U.S. Rep. Robert Wexler for ``standing up against the right wing
fanatics'' who wanted to impeach her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was here for a campaign dinner for Wexler, a Boca Raton
Democrat who was one of the president's most ferocious supporters
during his impeachment hearing and trial.
</P>
<P>
   A member of the House Judiciary Committee, Wexler often shouted
into the microphone accusing Republicans of attempting to oust the
president because they despise him, not because he had committed an
impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill Clinton is the first elected official that I was ever
able to believe in,'' Wexler told a crowd of several hundred at the
Boca Raton Hotel and Resort. ``What happened to him was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, Wexler broached the question that was on everyone's mind,
especially the many former New Yorkers who live in his district:
Will Mrs. Clinton run for the U.S. Senate seat being vacated by
Patrick Moyniham of New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``As a congressman who represents more former New Yorkers then
any other congressman in the country,'' Wexler said with a wink,
``I have standing to say that people in this room and New Yorkers
all over the world wish her very well in her pursuits.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton acted as if she were about to say something serious
about the possibility of running and then laughed, saying, ``I
won't go there.'' Noting that Wexler wins his district by large
margins she added, ``It's clear he could send a few of you back
since his margin is so enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   She then spent much of her 20-minute speech defending the record
of her husband, saying that he has worked diligently on issues that
are important to the country.
</P>
<P>
   Reminding the audience that while America is prospering, people
in Kosovo are dying, she said it is tragic that as the century
comes to a close the world must face another crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day she attended a Yom Hashoah ceremony
remembering the Holocaust at the Jewish Federation in Boca Raton.
In a somber voice, she said, ``There has always lurked in the human
soul a dark evil.''
</P>
<P>
   In Kosovo, she said, ``the people you see on television are not
abstractions, they are mothers and daughters, parents and
grandparents.'' She said the United States and NATO cannot afford
to ignore the atrocities there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Europe right now, inhumanity and evil have once again
raised its fists,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Kenneth Brander of Boca Raton told a crowd of more than
2,000 that when he sees the refugees on trains it reminds him of
the Holocaust. ``When I see the children I see the face of my
father,'' he said. ``When I see their parents I see the faces of my
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dare not forget the Holocaust,'' he said. ``And today, we
dare not be silent.''
</P>
<P>
   Yom Hashoah, an annual ceremony to remember the millions of Jews
killed during the Holocaust began at sundown on Monday and ended at
sundown on Tuesday. During the ceremony at the Jewish Federation
Center, survivors of the Holocaust, people who lost members of
their family and young Jews lighted candles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need young people,'' Clinton said, ``not only to hear the
stories of the Holocaust but to tell the stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian E. Crowley writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm
Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
