<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTEL'S RESULTS SLIGHTLY BEAT EXPECTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Intel Corp. reported Tuesday that first-quarter
earnings increased 57 percent, slightly higher than analysts'
estimates, with slower sales offset by improved profit margins.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had braced for a disappointment after Compaq Computer
Corp. announced Friday that its results would fall far below
estimates. Intel's relatively strong performance is one indication
that Compaq's problems are solely its own _ stemming from issues
like the integration of Digital Equipment Corp., rather than the
mark of a broad slowdown in PC sales.
</P>
<P>
   The results were released after the market closed. Shares of
Intel closed Tuesday at $60.50, down 75 cents in Nasdaq trading.
But in after-hours trading, it fell to $57.75. Analysts said
investors were reacting to sales growth that was slower than
expected. The first quarter is typically down seasonally from the
fourth, and Intel had said in January that it expected sales to
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a quarter where investors really fretted over results
and everybody assumed the worst, but the actual results are
considerably better than that,'' said Mark Edelstone, an analyst
with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. ``Relative to our own
expectations, sales are a little bit below where we thought they
would be, but that is consistent with the environment. The offset
was that margins were a little bit better, which shows Intel's
control of the cost structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel warned that it expected revenue for the second quarter to
be flat to slightly down, because of seasonal factors. The company
also said it expects its gross profit margin in the second quarter
to be about the same as it was in the first quarter _ 59 percent.
Intel said its gross margin expectation for 1999 is 57 percent,
plus or minus a few points.
</P>
<P>
   For the first quarter, Intel reported earnings of $2 billion, or
57 cents a diluted share, up 57 percent from $1.27 billion, or 36
cents a share in the first quarter of 1998. Revenues rose 18
percent, to $7.1 billion from $6 billion in the first quarter of
1998. All per-share amounts have been adjusted to reflect Monday's
2-for-1 stock split.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts expected Intel, which is based in Santa Clara, Calif.,
to earn 55 cents a share, according to First Call Corp. Analysts
said income from the sale of investments added about 2 cents a
share to Intel's earnings. Intel sold some or all of its stakes in
Broadcast.com Inc., Inktomi Corp. and Cnet Inc. during the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with our substantial year-over-year growth in
profitability resulting from our cost-control efforts,'' said Intel
president and chief executive Craig Barrett in a statement. ``As we
expected, revenue declined from the prior quarter reflecting a
seasonally slower selling period.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said Intel's strong margins reflect not only cost
controls, but the success of the company's strategy to segment the
market. By offering the Celeron at the low end, Pentium II and
Pentium III in the middle, and the Pentium Xeon at the high end of
the market, Intel can fight a price war with Advanced Micro Devices
Inc. and National Semiconductor Corp. for the below-$1,000 personal
computer market, while maintaining premiums on high performance
chips for work stations and servers.
</P>
<P>
   But competition at the high end of the chip market should
increase as Advanced Micro Devices increases production volumes of
its fastest chips. At the same time, demand could stall because
Microsoft Corp.'s newest version of Windows NT has been delayed,
and many corporations see little reason to upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts are predicting that the pricing for
microprocessors will soften further in the second quarter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
