<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ECONOMISTS STARTING TO SEE A PAYOFF FROM TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, most of the nation's leading economists
have questioned the economic payoff from information technology _
the billions upon billions spent each year by companies and
households on everything from computers to software to cellular
phones.
</P>
<P>
   But now economists are wondering whether higher productivity
growth _ averaging about 2 percent in the last three years, roughly
double the pace from 1973 to 1995 _ is the long-awaited
confirmation that the nation's steadily rising investment in
computers and communications is finally paying off.
</P>
<P>
   SEVERAL COMPANIES IN PHONE DEALS
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems, the maker of data-networking equipment, announced
a $2 billion acquisition of Geotel Communications, expanding into
telephone software, while two of the biggest makers of traditional
phone systems, Ericsson and Northern Telecom, said they would
acquire private data-networking companies. Shares of Geotel
Communications rose $11.6875, to $55.9375.
</P>
<P>
   MOTOROLA'S PROFIT INCREASES 20 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Motorola said that its first-quarter profit rose 20 percent,
helped by cost cuts and improved sales of mobile phones and chips.
</P>
<P>
   BELL ATLANTIC SAYS MARKET IS OPEN
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, in a meticulous march toward the $80 billion
long-distance market, told New York state regulators that it had
fully opened its network to competition, as required.
</P>
<P>
   DOW GAINS, BUT OTHER AVERAGES FALL
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average climbed 55.5 points, to
10,395.01, another record, but other gauges slipped as investors
took profits, especially in technology issues. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index fell 8.82 points, to 1,349.82, while the
Nasdaq composite index declined 15.31 points, to 2,583.50.
</P>
<P>
   A PROPOSAL TO CUT AUTO POLLUTION
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is preparing to announce as early as
next week that it will require cleaner gasoline and tougher
pollution standards for autos, including forcing large sport
utility vehicles and pickup trucks to meet the same emission
standards as cars.
</P>
<P>
   INQUIRY OF AMERICA ONLINE SOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   At least seven former volunteers who helped maintain America
Online's virtual community have asked the Labor Department to look
into whether the online service's use of unpaid labor violates
federal law.
</P>
<P>
   BARCLAYS CHIEF QUITS, CITING HEALTH
</P>
<P>
   Barclays, Britain's second-largest bank, is looking for its
fourth chief executive in six months after Michael O'Neill resigned
because of ill health, touching off speculation that the bank may
be vulnerable to a takeover. O'Neill, 53, fainted twice last week
and was found to have an irregular heartbeat that could be
aggravated by stress, a bank spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN BANK SALE IS IN TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   An agreement by the South Korean government to sell Korea First
Bank to a consortium led by Newbridge Capital has foundered over a
disagreement about how to value the bank's assets and establish a
sale price.
</P>
<P>
   STUDY ON FAST DATA CONNECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   The battle over access to high-speed Internet connections moved
to the Senate Commerce Committee, whose chairman, John McCain, said
he would seek a study on how to make the technology more widely
available.
</P>
<P>
   In another move aimed at providing music over the Internet, Real
Networks agreed to buy a software company, Xing Technology, for up
to $75 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   MILBERG WEISS TO PAY $50 MILLION
</P>
<P>
   Milberg Weiss Bershad Hynes &AMP; Lerach, a New York law firm that
has grown rich by suing corporations, agreed to pay $50 million to
Lexecon, a consulting firm that often testifies for corporations.
Lexecon had accused the law firm of trying to destroy its
reputation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
