<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tait is moveable mountain
 &HT;    By Chick Ludwig
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As a kid growing up in Tempe, Ariz., John Tait
was Mr. Softy on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   Too much baby fat and too little coordination kept him on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   Well, if his friends in Tempe's Pop Warner League could see him
now, they'd find that things have changed.
</P>
<P>
   The pillow-soft cushion in his midsection has disappeared,
replaced by rock-hard muscle. And he has turned all that
awkwardness into elegance.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the kid is all grown up. Now the 6-foot-6, 310-pounder from
Brigham Young _ he bench presses 470 pounds, squats 660 and runs
the 40-yard dash in 4.9 seconds _ is poised to be the first
offensive left tackle taken in the NFL draft on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a big, clumsy kid who got beat up in practice,''
Tait said. ``I was always big, so I had to play against kids two
years older. I wanted to quit, but my dad wouldn't let me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was even involved in a protest because me and another kid
weren't playing. Each of us was supposed to play five plays. We
didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Tait was never be accused of being lazy, however. So while he
was developing his skills at Tempe McClintock High School, the big
boys came calling.
</P>
<P>
   He chose BYU over UCLA, Texas, Colorado and Arizona State
because the Cougars' offensive line coach, Roger French, impressed
him.
</P>
<P>
   After a redshirt freshman year, he took off on his Mormon
mission for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people go to place like China,'' he said. ``I went to
Knoxville, Tenn., where there was barbecue and pinto beans. I was
one of those guys on bicycles wearing badges. Whenever people there
saw me, the first thing they asked, because of my size, was if I
played football. Football is a religion there. It was a great
icebreaker. We ended up talking about the Vols.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an intense learning experience, two years of being on
your own. Your focus was totally on serving other people. But some
people, when they come back from their mission, are not nearly as
good or don't have that desire. I had to relearn how to play. But
none of that desire was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to the Provo, Utah, campus in 1996, he needed
to add 20 pounds to return to his playing weight of 270. He gained
that, and more.
</P>
<P>
   Tait won the starting job at left tackle that spring and didn't
leave the lineup until the end of the '98 season _ his junior year.
He earned first-team All-Western Athletic Conference honors two
straight seasons, then decided to go to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people said, `Stay for the Outland (Trophy),' '' he said.
``But I'm not big on that stuff. I was getting good reports back
from the NFL and thought I was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Draft expert Mel Kiper Jr. calls Tait the eighth best player in
the draft and predicts he'll be the first offensive lineman chosen.
</P>
<P>
   Another expert, Jerry Jones, said Tait is so valuable because he
does more than just protect a right-handed quarterback's blind
side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other than the fact he's enormous and moves quite well, what
differentiates him from other BYU linemen is he can run block,''
Jones said. ``BYU guys make wonderful pass blockers. Some think
that's all they can do, but this kid is an exception to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Tait be nervous on Saturday? No way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to enjoy the whole thing,'' he said. ``And I'll play
anywhere. They're writing checks. I'm strapping it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
