<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRV-BOOST-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MRV HOLDS ONTO MOST OF SURPRISE GAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHATSWORTH, Calif. -- Shares in telecommunications equipment
maker MRV Communications treaded water Tuesday after unexpectedly
gaining 36 percent the day before.
</P>
<P>
   MRV stock closed at $8.4375, down 25 cents, after 2 million
shares changed hands in a day of trading volume roughly nine times
the issue's 30-day average.
</P>
<P>
   In similarly heavy trading Monday, MRV shares rose 36 percent,
leaving armchair analysts wondering just what had happened. With no
official word out of the company, speculation in Internet chat
rooms ran to complex put-option executions and possible secret
product news.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said analyst Vivek Rao at Gruntal &AMP; Co., there was no
single factor that pushed the shares so high, but a combination of
events. Most significant, Rao said, was the fact that the company's
new network router for Linux-based computer systems was being
well-received in trade journals. The company announced the product
April 6.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up also was influenced by a public offering last Friday
that gave Extreme Networks, a company that makes equipment similar
to MRV's products, a $2 billion-plus market capitalization. ``That
was clearly encouraging it,'' Rao said. ``The (MRV) stock is cheap
relative to some of the other companies now being traded.''
</P>
<P>
   MRV will announce earnings later this month. While most analysts
expect the company to report a net loss, they see this as a
turn-around quarter just before MRV is back in the black. Rao said
he expects the company to report a quarterly loss of 4 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, MRV officials were clearly pleased Tuesday
with the renewed interest in their firm. In particular, Chief
Financial Officer Edmund Glazer said MRV's entry into the Linux
market could lead to a huge new business for the company, a fact
investors have apparently recognized. Linux is a free, open-source
operating system gaining popularity among corporate network
operators.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have an enormous potential for us, certainly enough
for us to be excited,'' Glazer said.
</P>
<P>
   MRV makes network switching equipment and fiber optic systems
that improve the performance of networks. The company saw its share
price melt last year after revenues were seriously hurt by weak
demand in Europe and delays in the launch of new products. Weaker
margins also took a toll while the company spent more heavily on
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   The result was that, from an all-time high of $38.75 in
September 1997, shares fell to $7.5625 in late August 1998 and
continued to lose ground intermittently, closing the year at
$6.1875.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
