<HEADER>
A6909 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-ART-CENTURY-     04-13 1156
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-ART-CENTURY-2TAKES-$ADV18-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY OF ART: JUST HOW AMERICAN WAS IT? 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, APRIL 18)  
 (af)  
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Artwise, was this really the American century? We take the
cliche for granted because, well, because we are so arrogant. Never
mind that it's just a catch phrase cooked up in 1941 by Henry Luce,
the most thoroughly unreconstructed of American chauvinists, partly
out of missionary zeal and partly to sell his magazine.
</P>
<P>
   We accept it because, let's admit it, we're proud to have taken
over the planet. We only feign embarrassment that people living in
remotest Borneo drink Coke and like Mike. Better us, we think,
than, say, the French, heaven forbid, because then we would all
have to speak their language and eat their food and have shorter
work weeks and maybe even live in Paris for a while, and wouldn't
that be awful?
</P>
<P>
   The American Century is the title of what looks to be an immense
two-part survey at the Whitney Museum of American Art, the first
part of which, covering the years 1900 to 1950, will open Friday.
It's one of several century-ending extravaganzas (the Modern is
planning another). And no doubt they all, to some degree, will
confront the cliche of American predominance in visual art,
deciding what it means and whether it really makes sense.
</P>
<P>
   Why doubt it? For starters, of course, because during half the
century not even most Americans cared about American art. Artists
like Hartley, O'Keeffe, Weston, Dove, Demuth, Davis, Lawrence,
Benton and Marin made little impact here or elsewhere. Their
profiles have gone up considerably in the United States as we've
had more chances to see their work, but they're undervalued and
still hardly ever exhibited elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   People abroad mostly regard them as provincials, the way we
regard artists like Ben Nicholson and Stanley Spencer as provincial
British painters. It may be unfair but it's the case. John Marin
was perhaps the most admired American artist in the United States
at midcentury. I'd wager that Marin today is no more familiar even
to an art-savvy European than Francis Gruber and Cornelis Corneille
are to us.
</P>
<P>
   So when we boast about the American century in art, we really
mean the American half-century. Then we must figure out what, if
anything, is specifically American about American art during the
last 50 years, because otherwise we easily make the mistake of
confusing the quality of American art with the impact of the
American dollar: to acknowledge that we have dominated the
marketplace and the media since World War II is not to say that the
visual art that we have produced has been truly distinctive and,
more than anyone else's art, has shaped worldwide taste.
</P>
<P>
   There's no question about the influence everywhere of jazz and
rock and Hollywood films. But we're talking here about painting and
sculpture.
</P>
<P>
   And from the beginning, as Robert Hughes has written, American
art has oscillated between dependence and invention. Another way of
putting it is that American art, for much of this century, couldn't
decide how American it ought to be. On the one hand were the
regionalists (John Sloan, George Luks, George Bellows, Grant Wood,
John Steuart Curry and so on).
</P>
<P>
   And on the other hand were the modernists, who, whether they
were pure abstractionists or Surrealists, pursued a European model
of what you might call pan-nationalism or universalism (Burgoyne
Diller, Ilya Bolotowsky, Peter Blume, O. Louis Guglielmi). We
devalued them both: American art seemed to us either too derivative
of Europe or too local, a contradiction that we never quite
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Then Abstract Expressionism came along, and it was soon touted
as the first distinctly American brand of modernism. America, it
was said, had finally invented an abstract art that owed nothing to
Europe. The American century had begun.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least, that's the standard account. Politically minded art
historians during recent decades have added to it the notion, which
has become fashionable, that artists like Pollock and de Kooning
were then aggressively exported to further an American agenda
during the Cold War. Abstract Expressionism, according to these
historians, became a form of propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that the Abstract Expressionists enjoyed a freedom
of expression that was not possible in the Soviet Union. So the
United States government and the Museum of Modern Art conspired to
promote them abroad, in exhibitions like the Venice Biennale and
the Sao Paulo Bienal, and pretty soon American art had insinuated
itself around the globe along with other American products.
</P>
<P>
   Is it true? Looking back, the Abstract Expressionists don't seem
quite so all-American. We can see, for example, how much de
Kooning, the Dutchman who sneaked into the United States as a
stowaway in 1926 and changed the course of art here, continued to
owe to previous Dutch painters like Hals.
</P>
<P>
   And there's not much strong evidence that the Abstract
Expressionists were ever embraced by the government during the
early 50s; nor were they extensively pushed elsewhere until they
had already begun to be supplanted here by a new generation that
included Johns, Rauschenberg, Lichtenstein and Warhol.
</P>
<P>
   The first Pollock retrospective to tour Europe was in 1958. By
then he was already dead. No one abroad seemed terribly impressed,
anyway. Shows in Europe of new American art were panned throughout
the 50s.
</P>
<P>
   The first Americans to achieve global fame were probably the Pop
artists during the 1960s, whose success was obviously linked to the
ascendance of American pop culture generally. But it's useful to
recall that British artists like Richard Hamilton, Malcolm Morley
and Eduardo Paolozzi, and Germans like Sigmar Polke and Gerhard
Richter, at the same time and for different reasons, were also
using pop images in their work.
</P>
<P>
   So you could say that cutting-edge American art during the early
60s did not so much dominate or shape world taste as dovetail with
it, or with a part of it. Meanwhile, America, having developed an
inflated ego, no longer seemed to feel it had to pay the same close
attention to what was going on elsewhere, and it wasn't until the
1980s, when a booming art market buoyed interest in almost
everything, that many myopic Americans finally noticed what Polke
and Richter (and also Beuys and Kiefer and various others) had been
up to.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back on the generation that emerged during the late 50s
and early 60s, it's a guess that internationally speaking, Polke
and Richter will be remembered with Rauschenberg, Warhol and Johns
among the major figures, and that American art will seem neither as
distinct nor as dominant as we tend to think it was.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Prognosticating, of course, is a risky enterprise, but while
we're at it, let me also suggest that the most singular
agglomeration of Americans in the century may turn out to be the
ones who came next: the Conceptualists, Minimalists and
Post-Minimalists, among them Donald Judd, Bruce Nauman, Eva Hesse,
Richard Tuttle, Ana Mendieta, Robert Irwin, Richard Serra and the
artists of diverse stripes who went to work on a vast scale in the
American West: Walter De Maria, Robert Smithson, James Turrell and
Michael Heizer.
</P>
<P>
   I might add the exceptional case of Philip Guston, an Abstract
Expressionist in the 50s, who in the 70s, ignoring almost
everyone's advice, remade himself, until he died in 1980 producing
what the artist Elizabeth Murray has called sad, nutty songs: wild,
angry, cartoonish pictures that caused many people to say he'd lost
his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Today, when there's so much new art that involves cartooning and
surrealism, his weird late works seem astonishingly prescient and
moving. Guston has turned out to be one of the most influential
American painters at the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
   I don't mean by all this to say that the artists to emerge in
the late 60s and 70s are necessarily the best ones we've ever
produced. I mean they belong to the first American generation in
this century that depends principally on what, by now, had become a
modern American tradition: they built on works by Pollock,
Rauschenberg, Johns, David Smith, Ad Reinhardt and others who were
not even strictly visual artists, like John Cage.
</P>
<P>
   What they produced, moreover, bespoke a specifically American
context. Artists like Smithson were working in the American
landscape, and Minimalists and Post-Minimalists like Judd and Serra
were exploiting a vocabulary of industrial forms that grew out of
the American cityscape. Their art actually resembled the streets of
SoHo, then still an industrial neighborhood only beginning to be
taken over by artists.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Americans like Demuth and Sheeler had painted pictures
of industrial buildings in a streamlined style. But the sculptures
by artists of the late 60s and early 70s consisted of steel and
tar, their stripped-down esthetic evoking not only an urban present
but also a Puritan past.
</P>
<P>
   Now we're at the end of the century, and the American paradigm,
it seems, has gradually shifted. No doubt all the big
century-ending exhibitions will have to confront this fact.
Throughout our history, the notion has prevailed that there could
be a distinctly American art, as if a particular form or style
might encapsulate the nation's identity. Assimilation was an
underlying assumption.
</P>
<P>
   But there really has been no national art. It's curious but true
that we do not, as a nation, identify with specific American
paintings, or at least not with any paintings of serious quality,
as Mexicans identify with the works of Rivera and Italians identify
with the works of Raphael or Titian. I put it this way to exclude
the work of an illustrator like Norman Rockwell.
</P>
<P>
   Can you name any American picture, which, if it were to be sold
and end up in another country, would provoke anything like the
national heritage debate that surrounds the Greeks and the Elgin
marbles? Certainly not a Pollock or a Warhol. And if you cite
``Washington Crossing the Delaware'' then consider the fact that
not more than a handful of Americans have even heard of the man who
painted it (Emanuel Leutze).
</P>
<P>
   We're so enamored of the free market that we don't think of
American art in terms of national treasure. But more to the point,
we're so diverse culturally: the goal of a synthetic American art
remains illusory because the idea of an American identity is, in
the end, an illusion. If we cling to the melting pot idea, we have
also become increasingly alert to its inadequacies.
</P>
<P>
   This is why the paradigm has begun to change. The 90s are a
pluralist decade in art, the legacy of multiculturalism, economics
and technological change. The breakdown of old borders, thanks to
the end of the Cold War and the burgeoning of the Internet, has
hastened American awareness of culture globally, and vice versa: we
see more new art from around the world, and people elsewhere see
more easily the art we make.
</P>
<P>
   If, consequently, art around the world today isn't actually more
varied than it used to be, we have become more respectful of a
wider range of it. We're regularly given chances to view
contemporary work from Japan, Korea, India, Africa and Central
America, not to mention Europe, and emigre artists here trumpet
their roots.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity is now regarded as an asset. That is a prevailing
theme in American art at this moment. And America, particularly New
York City, as the world's economic epicenter, remains the
crossroads for new art, so by extension, diversity is a message
being spread around the world. We may be leaving the American
century without having produced an American art that speaks for us
collectively as a nation, but as a nation we have developed into
the nexus for world art.
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? In the future, the American century, if it's
still called that, may be defined, paradoxically, not by the art we
began to invent at midcentury but by the global culture we helped
to disseminate at century's end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
