<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-REDS-PITCHING14-C     04-13 0671
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-REDS-PITCHING14-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Starting pitchers staying course for beleaguered Reds bullpen
</P>
<P>
   By Hal McCoy
</P>
<P>
   C. 1999 COX NEWS SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The Sears Tower and The John Hancock Building both
peer down from 100 stories above the Chicago landscape, but as far
as the Cincinnati Reds are concerned the tallest objects in Chicago
right now are the team's starting pitchers standing atop the mound.
</P>
<P>
   When Pete Harnisch trudges up that little hill this afternoon in
Wrigley Field to face the Chicago Cubs, he will try to extend the
starting staff's string of pitching at least into the seventh
inning to six straight games.
</P>
<P>
   And that has been a nifty little gift for manager Jack McKeon
because he hasn't had to rely so much on the beleaguered bullpen
that was bruised and battered by the San Francisco Giants the first
three games of the season _ all defeats.
</P>
<P>
   The Reds have won three of the first four games on this six-game
trip to St. Louis and Chicago and while the bullpen has awakened
somewhat from its early nightmares, it has been the starters
staying the course that made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   The past five games:
</P>
<P>
   Steve Avery, 7 innings, 1 run, 3 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bere, 6.1 innings, 2 runs, 8 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Tomko, 7 innings, 2 runs, 4 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Harnisch, 9 innings, 0 runs, 6 hits.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Avery, 7.2 innings, 3 runs, 3 hits.
</P>
<P>
   For those five games, the starters have pitched 37 of a possible
45 innings and given up eight runs (1.95 earned-run average) and 24
hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What pays off for us is that we stretch our pitchers out early
in spring training, get 'em to pitch four innings in their first
outing instead of a couple, and increase it each time,'' McKeon
said. ``So they're ready to go at least seven innings on Opening
Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery is a mystery for opposing hitters, who watch his
meandering fastball flutter at 83 miles per hour. It looks as if
they could bust it to Katmandu, but Avery seldom puts it in The Hit
Zone. It is on the outside corner, on the inside corner, down
around the knees.
</P>
<P>
   And he surrounds that fastball with an abundance of changeups,
so that when he goes to the fastball it looks speedier, or as
Chicago's Sammy Sosa said after Monday's game, ``When he throws so
many changeups (40 out of 108 pitches), you look for it and the
fastball seems to come at you like a speeding train.''
</P>
<P>
   Avery believes he can, and will, be better.
</P>
<P>
   ``My control is still off at times (11 walks in his 14 innings),
so when I get my control going and my fastball going, I'll be more
effective,'' he said. Amazingly, of those 11 walks, only one has
scored.
</P>
<P>
   And Avery said despite the early awfulness, he isn't distressed
when he turns the ball over to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every person we have in the bullpen has a lot better stuff
than I have, so I don't worry about those guys . . . they're all
very good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Avery was the one question mark of the starting staff before
spring training because Harnisch, Brett Tomko and Denny Neagle are
tried and proven. Neagle, though, reported to camp with a dead
shoulder and is only now ready to step into the rotation, probably
Sunday in Cinergy Field against Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   What Harnisch did also was remarkable _ missing the last two
weeks of spring training and his Opening Day assignment with lower
back spasms, then pitching a six-hit complete-game shutout against
the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   McKeon is happy with the 16 home runs his team has hit in seven
games to lead the majors, but he realizes championships are won and
lost with pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good pitching is just the ticket,'' he said. ``When we get
good pitching, hold the other team to three runs or less and get
six or more innings from our starters, we have a chance to win a
lot of games. Harnisch was the backbone of our staff last year and
we missed him Opening Day. If he had been able to pitch and lead
the way, we might be 6-1 instead of 3-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
