<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Standard to buy back stock
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Standard Register plans to repurchase up to 1
million shares of its stock, a move that could cost about $30
million and send a message of confidence to the investment
community, said Robert J. Cestilli, associate vice president for
investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a way to say we believe in what we're doing,'' Cestilli
said. The move may or may not drive the stock price up, he said.
The company's stock hit a 52-week high of $40 a share nearly a year
ago but then dropped off last fall. It has languished around $30 a
share this year.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Register's board of directors authorized the repurchase
last month. The repurchase isn't likely to begin until after
Standard Register announces its quarterly earnings and holds its
annual meeting April 21.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Register will use some of the cash from the $100
million sale of its Communicolor division, a deal that closed April
5. Cestilli said the remainder of the cash is likely to be used to
buy other companies and pay down the $234 million in debt incurred
when Standard Register bought UARCO
</P>
<P>
   Headquartered in Dayton, Standard Register makes business forms,
has a nationwide network of printing facilities and sells document
management systems.
</P>
<P>
   Standard Register's stock (NYSE: SR) closed Tuesday at 30, up
7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Laura A. Bischoff writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
