<SLUG> BC-SCI-STEROIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USING STEROIDS HELPS PATIENTS REPAIR MUSCLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HOLCOMB B. NOBLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two anabolic steroids, muscle-building male-hormone substitutes,
have given renewed strength to patients who had been severely
weakened from being on kidney dialysis and to patients who suffered
marked weight loss from the AIDS virus, researchers report.
</P>
<P>
   The authors of two studies published in Wednesday's issue of The
Journal of the American Medical Association recommended that a low
dose of the drugs, which in higher quantities are known to have
serious side effects, be put to immediate use for the sickest of
both groups of patients.
</P>
<P>
   But the authors, along with an editorial, cautioned against
wider use of anabolic steroids, which in similar synthetic
compounds have been used in large doses by some professional and
amateur athletes to build muscle mass and enhance weight lifting or
other forms of physical performance. These steroids are substitutes
for human testosterone, which is responsible for male
characteristics like increased muscle tissue, facial hair and a
deep voice.
</P>
<P>
   The medical researchers said that much more study was needed to
learn more precisely the levels and length of time the drugs can be
safely taken. Among the side effects known to occur at high levels
are stimulation of prostate tumors, liver disorders, worsening
cholesterol levels, uncontrolled aggressive behavior and, more
cosmetically, body hair growth in women.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results with low doses for seriously ill patients were
very encouraging _ enough so to warrant the use now for these
patients,'' said Dr. Kirsten Johansen, an assistant professor of
medicine at the University of California at San Francisco, who led
the study of dialysis patients.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Johansen estimated that as many as 10 percent of the 250,000
patients who are using dialysis machines warrant the steroid
treatment. Loss of muscle mass has been associated with a
significantly reduced life span among patients in long-term
dialysis programs, as it has in patients infected with HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   In the accompanying report on patients infected with HIV, Dr.
Alison Strawford, a researcher at the University of California at
San Francisco and the lead author of the study, said a similar drug
when used with a supervised weight lifting program produced a
significant gain in muscle strength.
</P>
<P>
   For the dialysis study, researchers looked at 29 patients with
end-stage kidney disease. To build muscle mass, 14 of the patients
were given synthetic anabolic steroids made of the chemical
compound nandrolone decanoate, administered in combination with
exercise periods of walking and stair climbing. Fifteen patients
received placebo injections.
</P>
<P>
   After six months, the researchers found that the patients given
steroids had increased their lean mass, or nonfat body weight, by
an average of 5.5 pounds more than the average gain in the placebo
group. The group on steroids walked 10 percent faster, while the
placebo group slowed down by 10 percent. Using a measurement known
as the Profile of Mood States, the steroid group was also found to
have become significantly less fatigued, Dr. Johansen said.
</P>
<P>
   In the research project aimed at reversing weight loss related
to HIV, 22 patients were tested. Eleven were given a synthetic
steroid made of the chemical compound oxandrolone, and 11 received
a placebo. In addition, all 22 were put on a modest resistance
weight lifting program. The gains for upper and lower body strength
among those on the steroid were significantly greater than for the
placebo group, Dr. Strawford said. Those given the steroid gained
an average of 16 pounds compared with a gain of 8 pounds for the
placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   The one adverse side effect, Dr. Strawford said, was a
significant drop in high-density lipoprotein cholesterol _ the good
kind _ which helps prevent arterial clogging and heart attacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
