<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pending reports provide look at chip business
 &HT;    By Kirk Ladendorf
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Earnings reports from Motorola Inc., Advanced
Micro Devices Inc. and Intel Corp. today and Wednesday should give
investors a first-quarter snapshot of the health of the Central
Texas microchip business.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are modestly upbeat about the earnings prospects for
Motorola and Intel, which will release their results this
afternoon. AMD, which reports its results Wednesday, has already
warned it will post a sizable loss for the quarter due to
production problems and falling prices for its Austin-made
microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola is expected to report earnings of 24 cents a share, due
in part to an upturn in its Austin-based semiconductor business.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is expected to report earnings of $1.09 a share, up from
81 cents a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Intel's stock dropped $4.12 1/2 to $61.25 a share. AMD
closed down 56 1/4 cents at $15.06 1/4 and Motorola fell $1.43 3/4
to $81.56 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Ladendorf writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
