A6927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-ABORTIONBAN-COX     04-13 0590
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-ABORTIONBAN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abortion ban fails in Florida committee
 &HT;    By Charles Elmore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ A ``partial-birth'' abortion ban failed in a
Senate committee Tuesday, the most prominent legislative defeat for
anti-abortion groups in Florida in three years.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-abortion groups threatened political retaliation against a
moderate Republican senator whose swing vote made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Burt Saunders of Cape Coral was the sole Republican on the
prevailing side in a 4-3 vote in the Senate health committee,
saying he did not think it would survive a constitutional challenge
in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to take Saunders out,'' said an angry John
Dowless, executive director of the Christian Coalition of Florida,
after the vote. ``He basically lied to us. There will be serious
repercussions in the next election.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders said, ``I did not tell anybody I was going to vote for
that bill. I consider the procedure barbaric, and I voted for (a
similar) bill last year, but I think it's inappropriate to waste
taxpayers' money making a political statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Saunders was elected last year to replace Fred Dudley, who left
office to run unsuccessfully for attorney general. Saunders is up
for election again in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   A federal court in Miami struck down last year's ban, saying it
was too broadly written and protect the health of the woman seeking
the procedure. The state had to pay nearly $100,000 in attorneys
fees for the other side defending it.
</P>
<P>
   The procedure involves terminating a pregnancy after the birth
of the entire body except the head. It is rare enough that sponsor
Sen. Anna Cowin, R-Leesburg, at an earlier hearing, could not cite
a single instance of its use in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Jack Latvala had also questioned the
constitutionality of the bill but left the committee room during
the vote to work out a deal on lawsuit reform, leaving Saunders in
the hot seat. Saunders said later he could have walked out also _ a
3-3 tie along party lines would have killed the bill _ but felt
honor-bound to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Abortion-rights attorney Charlene Carres said Saunders was just
one of several senators who looked at the facts and saw a case that
couldn't be won in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really think the senators on this committee thought hard
about what they were doing,'' Carres said. ``Today we were
fortunate that a majority of senators felt they way they did.''
</P>
<P>
   A ``Choose Life'' license plate and a bill requiring parental
notice for abortions for girls under 18 are expected to pass, with
legal challenges expected. The Senate health committee earlier
rejected a bill placing additional regulations on clinics that
perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 partial-birth ban narrowed the definition of the
procedure but did not include an exemption for the health of the
mother. That was by design, with the expectations of a renewed
legal battle, sponsor Cowin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it will be challenged and we will follow that in the
courts,'' Cowin said during debate.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ron Klein, D-Boca Raton, was one of the three Democrats to
vote against the bill. His own sister had a similar procedure
because of health complications.
</P>
<P>
   ``My personal view is I'm still concerned is if we have to make
a decision between the baby being born and the health of the mother
that we would want to sacrifice the health of the mother,'' Klein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
