<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOLVOUCHERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Student voucher plan runs into senatorial roadblock
 &HT;    By Shirish Date
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Gov. Jeb Bush's plan to give private school
vouchers to the students attending the state's worst public schools
hit a snag Tuesday, courtesy of a state senator Bush helped elect
last month.
</P>
<P>
   What Democrats tried and failed to do in the House two weeks ago
and for two hours on the Senate floor Tuesday, novice Jacksonville
Sen. Jim King managed in just a few minutes, successfully pushing
an amendment that narrows the reach of Bush's voucher plan.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush and the House want to offer ``opportunity
scholarships'' to every child in a school deemed failing by the
state for two years running, King's amendment would give vouchers
only to those students in those failing schools who also score in
the bottom fourth on statewide assessment tests.
</P>
<P>
   King said he had not researched how many students at the four
schools now considered failing would meet that criterion. Bush
spokesman Cory Tilley said the governor's office hadn't produced
that statistic, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it something we support? We don't,'' Tilley said, but added
that the amendment doesn't destroy the point of the bill. ``We're
confident we can still come up with a piece of legislation that's
good.''
</P>
<P>
   King said he wanted to make sure that those students who most
need the help get it, and not unnecessarily expand an experimental
program to those students who many not need it. His first attempt
to pass the amendment fell short on a 20-20 tie, which was undone
minutes later on a motion to reconsider the vote by Sen. Pat
Thomas, D-Quincy.
</P>
<P>
   The second time around, King's amendment passed 23-17, with a
total of eight Republicans _ King included _ voting with the
chamber's 15 Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   King said later he meant no disrespect by his action _ ``The guy
came down and helped me get elected. He walked precincts with me''
_ and he understands if Bush feels a proprietary ``pride of
authorship'' for the voucher bill. Nonetheless, he said he clearly
spelled out his cautious attitude toward private school vouchers
before his special election last month and felt he couldn't now
change his view just because the governor asked him to.
</P>
<P>
   Senate bill sponsor Anna Cowin, R-Leesburg, said she hoped to
remove King's addition after the bill passes the full Senate and
she can negotiate differences with the version passed by the House,
which, more closely follows Bush's original proposal.
</P>
<P>
   That passage probably won't happen until Friday _ originally
planned as a short work day for the Senate. King's amendment was
just the second of 11 he has filed, and the seventh of some 50 the
chamber needs to hear before voting on the bill. Senate President
Toni Jennings originally planned it for Thursday, but now will
spend that day dealing with the remaining amendments.
</P>
<P>
   ``You really need to make arrangements to be here on Friday,''
Jennings warned her senators.
</P>
<P>
   Shirish Date writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
