<SLUG> BC-GLF-NUHN-OLAZABAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Golf not too unlike life for Olazabal
 &HT;    By Gary Nuhn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ It was last Tuesday night, just before the
Champions' dinner in the clubhouse at Augusta National Golf Course.
The then-reigning champ, Mark O'Meara, was serving chicken and
steak fajitas, and sushi.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the crew sat down, Gary Player pulled Jose Maria
Olazabal aside.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what happened next, you must understand that
Player, 63, considers himself a grandfather figure to all of golf's
non-U.S. players.
</P>
<P>
   Player, from South Africa, set the standard to which they all
aspire. He has won all four major professional championships, one
of only four men (Gene Sarazen, Ben Hogan and Jack Nicklaus are the
others) to do so.
</P>
<P>
   So Player said to Olazabal, ``I'd like to talk to you for about
five minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal: ``OK. Whatever you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Player: ``How are you playing?''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal: ``Ok. So-so.''
</P>
<P>
   Player: ``How is your confidence?''
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal: ``Not really great.''
</P>
<P>
   And then Olazabal said Player looked at him ``with those eyes _
you know how he looks with those eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   (Player has a stare of steel.)
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a great swing,'' Player said. ``If you didn't, I
wouldn't tell you this. But you have a great swing, and you have to
believe in yourself, you know? Look at me.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Olazabal got up and went into a linebacker's
stance with his arms straight out in front of him, hands extended,
palms to the floor.
</P>
<P>
   He said Player went into this stance and said, ``Look at me!
Look at me!''
</P>
<P>
   And then he quoted Player:
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to believe in yourself. You have to believe in
yourself. You play 18 holes. If you don't play well, it doesn't
matter. You go to the driving range and practice hard. After that
you go to the putting green and you keep on putting there. That's
how you achieve things.''
</P>
<P>
   It was like Knute Rockne in the Notre Dame dressing room before
the Army game.
</P>
<P>
   Olazabal laughed as he stood up out of his crouch.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``you have to see him like that. The
determination and his words and the way he said it. It helped me.
It helped me to believe in myself, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days later, while all around him were being exposed by
gusting winds, pavement-hard greens and jelly nerves, Olazabal was
playing the final 13 holes in 4-under-par to win his second
Masters.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Jose Maria Olazabal was born, his mother was hard
at work, setting pins on her greenskeeper husband's golf course.
No, not putting the pins in, putting the cups in.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up on that course, near the Spanish fishing village of
Fuenterrabia, being handed his first cut-off club when he was 2 and
actually playing at age 4.
</P>
<P>
   At 33 and a millionaire many times over, he could have built a
mansion anywhere. Instead, he still lives in the 250-year-old
Basque farmhouse in which he was born with his mother, father and
younger sister, a common practice in Spain, where generations live
together through their lifetimes.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal San Sebastian putting green is 20 yards from his front
door.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the first one in my family who had an option,'' he said.
``Until me, we've been very poor and had to work all day long to
survive.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he has considered joining the U.S. tour more than once,
each time he has decided to stay loyal to the European Tour.
</P>
<P>
   Because, for Jose Maria Olazabal, there was no option.
</P>
<P>
   He's still the kid from the small town. Only the stage is
bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Nuhn writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
