<SLUG> BC-PHOTO-FULL-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/13/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) STENKOVAC, Macedonia -- April 13, 1999 --
KOSOVO-MACEDONIA, 04-13 -- Tearful Albanian refugees arriving
Tuesday at the camp in Stenkovac, Macedonia. Most came from
Urosevac, where, they said, Serbian forces had systematically
expelled tens of thousands of Albanians. (Alan Chin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) DURRES, Albania -- April 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-COST, 04-13
-- A woman refugee digs out a channel between tents in a camp near
the city of Durres, as her neighbors look on. Although it is a
rough estimate, several Clinton administration officials told
Congress that the refugee relief operation would cost from $515 to
$560 million, which would be shared between the State Department's
refugee office and the Pentagon. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) LAS VEGAS -- April 13, 1999 -- FARM-EQUIPMENT, 04-13 --
Earthmoving equipment, a Caterpillar staple, at the company's booth
during a recent convention in Las Vegas. All three heavy-equipment
makers - Caterpillar, John Deere and Case, the biggest names in
farm and construction equipment - are moving into new fields in an
effort to buffer themselves from the wrenching up-and-down cycle of
their core businesses. (John Gurzinski/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- April 13, 1999 -- SCI-HEALTH-HEARING-2,
04-13 -- A House subcommittee hears testimony Tuesday from a
variety of witnesses who all want financing for research for
various illnesses. Erin Bosch, 17, who suffers from a congenital
heart defect, appeared for the third time. She recently had surgery
to reduce the size of her enlarged heart, a procedure that was
pioneered with federal money. (Scott Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- April 13, 1999 -- SCI-HEALTH-HEARING-1,
04-13 -- A House subcommittee hears testimony Tuesday from a
variety of witnesses who all want financing for research for
various illnesses. The session was laden with hearbreaking stories,
most of them carefully orchestrated to grab the attention of the
media and, more important, Rep. John Porter, R-Ill., who chairs the
subcommittee. (Scott Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- CHINA-U.S.-REACT, 04-13 --
Tibetans near the United Nations protested Tuesday against the
visit of Prime Minister Zhu Rongji of China, calling for the
independence of Tibet. At its peak, protesters numbered about 200
outside the Hilton Hotel, where Zhu attended a dinner with the
United States-China Business Council. (Angel Franco/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 13, 1999 -- OBIT-RATHBUN, 04-13
-- Mary Jane Rathbun in 1996 at her San Francisco Cannabis Buyers
Club, now defunct, with baked goods and Larry Anderson, who worked
there. Rathbun, who became known as the grandmotherly Brownie Mary
who handed out brownies laced with high-grade cannabis to sick
people to relieve their pain and nausea, died Saturday, April 10 at
a hospital in San Francisco. She was 77. (Jim Wilson/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BETTY'S BAY, South Africa -- April 13, 1999 --
SAFRICA-WILDLIFE, 04-13 -- Mike Tannett, with green hat, a founder
of Sea Watch, a citizen's anti-poaching patrol, checks the licenses
and the catch of two divers at the Betty's Bay Marine Reserve.
Their catch of lobsters was legal, but Sea Watch has arrested more
than 500 poachers since 1995. Much of the poaching in South Africa
is not of well-known items like elephant tusks and rhinoceros
horns, but of abalone, cycads, snakes, beetles, aloes and medicinal
plants. (Donald G. McNeil Jr./New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- SIMON-DANCE-REVIEW, 04-13
-- Very young dancers bring an extra verve and emotional
wholeheartedness to performing that is seldom sustained as they
mature and become full-fledged professionals. The young members of
Eliot Feld's Ballet Tech student-dancer company strut their stuff
in ``Half Time'' at the Joyce Theater. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- SPROUTS-EATING-WELL, 04-13
-- Micro greens or sprouts, the very first leaves of plants, will
certainly make you think of spring, even though every leaf, with
the exception of the chives and garlic chives, was grown in a
greenhouse. Mixing and matching these micro greens is a wonderful
new way to play with your food. Even though virtually no nutrition
information exists for them, they are vegetables-in-waiting, so
likely provide some of the same nutrients. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) BOSTON -- April 13, 1999 -- TRUE-HEMINGWAY, 04-13 --
Patrick Hemingway, son of Ernest Hemingway, addresses authors,
scholars and fans, who gathered for the Hemingway Centennial
Conference at the John F. Kennedy Library in Boston. Some attendees
had varying opinions on the wisdom and taste of producing a work
like ``True at First Light,'' the posthumous Ernest Hemingway novel
to be published by Scribner this summer. (Michael Quan/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) WASHINGTON -- April 13, 1999 -- KOSOVO-CONGRESS, 04-13
-- After meeting with members of Congress at the White House,
President Clinton addresses the media in the Rose Garden. He told
reporters that the NATO airstrikes are ``diminishing and grinding
down'' Slobodan Milosevic's military capabilities and that ``we are
taking our allied air campaign to the next level.'' Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) BRAZDA, Macedonia -- April 13, 1999 --
REFUGEE-CAMP-2-BOS, 04-13 -- Inside the Israeli Defense Forces
Medical Corp tent, Dr. Jacob Adler, center, tries to remove bullet
casing fragment from Ibandete Dormishi. Ms. Dormishi was shot by
the Serbs while fleeing Pristina, Kosovo. ``There are mental
pictures in this place that bring back memories to all of us,''
says Adler reflecting on his own family's harrowing escape from the
Nazi invasion of Czechoslovakia in 1940. ``I think everyone feels
it.'' (Bill Greene/Boston Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) BRAZDA, Macedonia -- April 13, 1999 --
REFUGEE-CAMP-1-BOS, 04-13 -- A young boy rests on a makeshift swing
inside a tent that displays notes and pictures of missing family
members. Many families were separated during the atrocities
committed by Christian Serbs on Muslim Albanian Kosovars. (Bill
Greene/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) PLYMOUTH, Mass. -- April 13, 1999 -- INS-DETAIN-BOS,
04-13 -- In Unit BN1 of the Plymouth County Correctional Facility,
Gerardo Ruiz Esposito represents a growing presence among prison
inmates: Immigration and Naturalization detainees. This is where
Ruiz, a Nicaraguan citizen, will stay until he is granted asylum or
deported, an unlikely possibility in the near future because
Hurricane Mitch ravaged his country. (Barry Chin/Boston Globe
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) HARWICH, Mass. -- April 13, 1999 -- RUN-MARATH-KELLEY,
04-13 -- After 63 years, Johnny ``The Elder'' Kelley, a fixture and
the very symbol of the Boston Marathon, this year says: ``I will be
there in spirit. I wish all the runners good luck.'' At 91, the
two-time Boston Marathon winner, decided not to appear this year's
race as Grand Marshal to avoid risking a reoccurrence of the
pneumonia he suffered following abdominal surgery last winter. (Tom
Landers/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- MET-TICKET, 4-13 -- The Met
raised its suggested museum admission by 25 percent to $10 to
compensate for a drop in money from the Reader's Digest
Association. Even with the new fee, the museum expects to close the
books for its current fiscal year, which ends on June 30, deeper in
the red than last year, when the deficit totaled $1.5 million.
(Angel Franco/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- LANGOUSTINES-2, 4-13 -- At
La Fourchette in New York, langoustines are grilled and served atop
wilted arugula. Like anything unfamiliar that is pushed into the
limelight, langoustines have to battle some misconceptions as to
what they are. They are frequently confused with langoustes, or
spiny lobsters, and are also often sold as prawns, though
biologically they are only distant cousins. (Michael Rogol/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- April 13, 1999 -- LANGOUSTINES-1, 4-13 --
Langoustines are valued for their succulent tail meat. These
creatures, which look like sawed-off lobsters and taste a little
like lobster and a little like shrimp, have long been a delicacy in
European restaurants but, until recently, have played second fiddle
to shrimp in the United States. (David Corio/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) PARIS -- April 13, 1999 -- FRANCE-BISTROS-2, 04-13 --
Chez Catherine caters to the residents of its Right Bank
neighborhood. The regulars here (a business clientele at lunch;
local residents for dinner) are as bourgeois as its neighborhood.
This is a set-piece of a local bistro, hidden away on a quiet
street a short walk from the Galeries Lafayette department store on
the hectic Boulevard Haussmann. (John Giannini/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) PARIS -- April 13, 1999 -- FRANCE-BISTROS-1, 04-13 --
Restaurant des Beaux-Arts has served classics like pot-au-feu for
100 years. This bistro caters to art students and neighborhood
antiquarian book dealers and, up until the 1960s, used to save
regulars the 25-cent charge for napkins by storing each for a week
in a chest of 56 small drawers. (John Giannini/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- April 13, 1999 -- RAW-EGGS, 04-13 -- Chef
Erik Blauberg, the chef at the ``21'' Club, reports a revival of
requests for Caesar salad and steak tartare, a house specialty.
Here he breaks an egg onto a steak tartar plate. (Michael Rogol/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
