<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6940 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT-ART-NYT     04-13 0652
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL-DRAFT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: COUCH IS THE BEST QUARTERBACK IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There could be at least five quarterbacks picked in the first
round of this weekend's NFL draft. The player to be chosen at No. 1
depends on which of the 50 million draft analysts, scouts, coaches,
personnel men or stat geeks you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   The group of quarterbacks is cluttered, like a menu at a tourist
restaurant on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Browns decide to pick a quarterback with the first
pick in draft, it should be Tim Couch. He stands out the way
lobster distinguishes itself from a quarter-pounder with cheese.
Nothing against the other passers available, but few of them can
run an offense the way Couch can.
</P>
<P>
   In just two years as a starter for Kentucky, he put up numbers
never before seen in the Southeastern Conference. He threw for more
than 4,000 yards with 36 touchdown passes. In six different games,
he threw over 50 passes. Couch has something that is difficult to
teach: an ability to feel a football game, a talent that many
quarterbacks spend years trying to develop.
</P>
<P>
   The great ones wrap themselves in a cocoon, and nothing
penetrates that shield. Not screaming fans. Not a drooling
defensive tackle. Not even a coach like Bill Parcells hollering at
his quarterback in front of teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Couch has the calmness needed to function in today's
high-intensity game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I call it,'' said one personnel director
whose team is in position to draft Couch should the Browns pick
someone else. ``I just call it cool. He is cool under pressure,
kind of cocky in some ways. That's good as far as I'm concerned.
You want your quarterback to act like everything is fine, even if
he knew the world was going to end next Friday.''
</P>
<P>
   Couch does have some things to learn. He took too many
blind-side hits in college, which in the pros usually leads to a
concussion. And he had a tendency to throw off his back foot, and
hold the ball at ear level, instead of around his shoulder. But
these are minor flaws that Browns coach Chris Palmer, excellent
working with quarterbacks, can help fix.
</P>
<P>
   And please, do not talk about how Couch got his big numbers
because of the run-and-shoot offense, and how those kinds of
players don't make it big in the pros. Couch completed over 70
percent of his passes, and run-and-shoot or not, that is
impressive. He is also smart enough to adapt to a more pro-style
system.
</P>
<P>
   Andre Ware and David Klingler were run-and-shoot busts, but one
of the originals, Neil Lomax, was a productive NFL player. Couch's
arm strength is also questioned. But while his power may not be
measured in megatons, it is more than good enough.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he doesn't throw the ball across a river. At
Kentucky, he could drop it into a wide receiver's hands anywhere on
the field. And there were no questions about his arm when he lit up
a talented Florida team last year for 406 yards and three
touchdowns. That Gator defense could have three players drafted in
the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The same questions about arm strength swirled around Peyton
Manning before last year's draft. But after settling team and NFL
rookie records for attempts, completions, yards and touchdowns,
those questions went the way of the eight-track tape. A
quarterback's arm does not need to be strong _ just strong enough.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone can be Phil Simms, and Joe Montana did just fine
without a cannon arm. Couch will be a starter in this league for a
long time. He is the kind of player a franchise can build around
for the next 10 years. Think hard, Cleveland, pick the safe
quarterback, the best quarterback, and then sleep tight knowing
that if Couch is the choice, you made the right one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
