<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0399 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6945 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-DROPOUT-SCANDAL     04-13 2062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-DROPOUT-SCANDAL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    School officials omit names from dropout lists to state
 &HT;    By Michele Kurtz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Austin school district, attempting to
prevent its high schools from being rated ``low-performing,''
worked hard to purge students' names from dropout lists sent to the
state, documents subpoenaed by a Travis County grand jury show.
</P>
<P>
   School district administrators in 1996 and 1997 calculated
exactly how many students _ of each ethnic group at each school _
could drop out before a school would receive the state's lowest
rating, internal school district memos show.
</P>
<P>
   Kay Psencik, the deputy superintendent who last week was
indicted along with the district in the test-tampering
investigation, wrote a 1996 memo to area superintendents directing
them to coach principals ``in strategies to improve their dropout
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether the Austin district violated any laws or
whether it merely took advantage of various ways it could improve
its dropout data under the state's reporting system. Several former
and current school district employees interviewed for this story
said no one told them to do anything inappropriate when reporting
dropout data.
</P>
<P>
   But some acknowledged that the reporting system for dropouts has
potential for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Falling dropout rates statewide and in Austin have come under
increasing scrutiny in recent months. Legislators, public interest
groups and now the grand jury have questioned the numbers'
validity, with some critics calling the figures laughable and the
state's reporting system too lax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please understand that I am holding you responsible for the
efforts of your campuses in lowering their dropout rates and
preventing a low-performing rating for 1996-97,'' Psencik wrote on
Nov. 19, 1996 _ a week before the schools' deadline for reporting
dropout numbers to the district.
</P>
<P>
   In her memo, Psencik said five high schools had preliminary
dropout numbers high enough to warrant low-performing ratings. But
in the spring of 1997, not one received that low-performing
designation.
</P>
<P>
   Psencik has refused to discuss the memos, citing her pending
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorney, Roy Minton, said Psencik wanted dropout
information reported accurately. Previously, some students on
schools' dropout lists were attending school elsewhere, but the
Austin district discovered them too late to take them off the
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced that she was never telling anyone to change
something from accurate to inaccurate,'' Minton said.
</P>
<P>
   The school district has implemented several strategies to combat
the dropout problem, including creating Garza Independence High
School, designed to lure students back to school and keep others
from quitting.
</P>
<P>
   Schools were also expected to whittle down their dropout numbers
by finding students who had left school and either enrolled
elsewhere or planned to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   And Ricky Arredondo, the district's formerdata analyst and the
central figure in the test-tampering investigation, emphasized in a
handful of memos to his supervisors that schools could also remove
students from their dropout lists if the students have ``intent'' _
the word appeared in bold type _ to enroll in General Education
Development (GED) programs.
</P>
<P>
   Arredondo and his attorney did not return phone calls requesting
comment for this story.
</P>
<P>
   In an August 1997 memo, Arredondo predicted that a more rigorous
state-required reporting system would produce soaring dropout
numbers that would ``shock'' Austin and other communities this
spring. He referred in the memo to students whom the district
reported as having enrolled in other districts, but who never
actually did. The state for the first time can now track those
students. The dropout figures tallied under the new system are
expected to be released statewide later this month.
</P>
<P>
   The issues mentioned in the Austin district memos are central to
the grand jury investigation into dropout statistics, Travis County
Attorney Ken Oden said. Oden began an investigation into Austin's
test tampering last fall and expanded it a few months ago to
include the possible manipulation of dropout data.
</P>
<P>
   Oden said the questions about dropout reporting, which he calls
a ``wink-and-nod system,'' likely aren't unique to Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is strong reason to be very suspect or very
concerned about the accuracy of dropout data produced by our school
district and, I'm afraid, by the statewide system,'' Oden said.
``There is great incentive by administrators at every level to
minimize those numbers because the truth may be disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the Texas Education Agency said the state
keeps better records of dropouts than it did 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are moving to a more comprehensive reporting system this
school year that we hope will provide a more complete and accurate
listing of students who leave their public schools,'' said
spokeswoman Debbie Graves Ratcliffe.
</P>
<P>
   Oden, whose office this week began interviewing school
record-keepers under oath, said that even if the Austin district
has manipulated dropout statistics, the actions might not rise to
the level of criminal offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Playing with numbers in the Austin schools
</P>
<P>
   Several Austin schools in 1995 or 1996 _ including Austin,
Bowie, Lanier and Reagan high schools _ had earned the state's
low-performing designation because of high dropout counts. In the
two years following, district correspondence shows, school
officials dedicated significant energy to avoiding similar ratings
among the high schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was there, there were quite a few high schools that
were rated low-performing. There was a lot of pressure to clear the
record on that, to get them out of low-performing,'' said Hector
Montenegro, an area superintendent in the Austin district in
1995-96 who is now San Marcos' superintendent. ``After I left, the
pressure was stepped up quite a bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicki Baldwin, principal of Garza and a former principal of
Fulmore Middle School, recalled going to great lengths to locate
students who had quit attending school during her tenure at
Fulmore. She said that her school's reporting was always accurate
but that it's conceivable some schools might have bent the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure there are some practices that are unscrupulous. Part
of that has to do with sheer volume,'' Baldwin said.
</P>
<P>
   Memos show that the district took a two-pronged approach to
fixing its dropout problem: It spends about $4.5 million on
dropout-prevention programs a year. Among those programs is Garza
Independence High School, which opened in January 1998. And in the
mid-1990s, the district started the Delta Program, an
individualized learning program available at each high school.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few years, the district has focused more heavily on
cleaning up data and reducing dropout numbers. Sometimes, the
district dispatched visiting teachers to track down students and
sent data experts and district officials to help schools cut their
dropout lists.
</P>
<P>
   In October 1996, Arredondo sent area superintendents a memo with
two attachments: the most recent bimonthly preliminary dropout
count for schools, and a report that listed the precise number of
students at each high school _ in each ethnic group and those
considered from low-income homes _ that could drop out before a
school would be rated low-performing. Schools are ranked
low-performing if 6 percent or more of their students drop out, or
if 6 percent of any subgroup drop out. Arredondo asked the area
superintendents to pass along copies of the data to the principals
in their districts. Defining a ``dropout'' Reducing dropout numbers
is a complicated and time-consuming endeavor for schools.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, a student who stops coming to school is generally
considered a dropout unless a school district has documented one of
several things, such as that the student has transferred to another
school, enrolled in college early, enrolled in a GED program or
died. Parents mustsign a form specifying the student's plans. If a
school has no record of a transfer and doesn't know the student's
whereabouts, the district mustreport him or her as a dropout.
</P>
<P>
   The TEA expects districts to make a ``good-faith effort'' to
check whether former students attend programs they say they will _
and have not merely dropped out of school, said L.T. Bailey of the
agency's data inquiry unit, which investigates data anomalies in
districts.
</P>
<P>
   For students classified as seeking GEDs, Bailey said state
investigators prefer more than a form with a parent's signature as
proof the student enrolled. But several other TEA officials said
districts need only a parent's signature _ or that of the student
if he's or she is at least 18 _ indicating plans to pursue a GED.
</P>
<P>
   As Arredondo saw it, schools had to to show only that a student
has ``intent'' to enroll in a GED program, which he noted in a few
memos to Psencik and then-Superintendent Jim Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where this documentation indicates the student has intentto
re-enroll in a graduation or GED program, the no-show can be
removed from a campus dropout list,'' Arredondo wrote in 1997 and
again in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   When state investigators questioned large numbers of withdrawals
among some Austin high schools in 1997, they urged Austin officials
to try to confirm former students' enrollment in GED programs. But
Arredondo said in a memo to Psencik that district officials asked
state investigators whether they were required to track those
students, and the investigators said, ``No, but it is a good
idea.'' Clerical staffs at the high schools said the task would be
a huge burden, Arredondo wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin district is now trying to establish communication
with area GED programs, said Susan Kemp, interim director of
accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Almost 10 years ago, the state suspected that large numbers of
students reported as dropouts had transferred to other Texas
districts. So beginning in 1990, state officials tried to find the
students. The process, dubbed ``dropout recovery,'' also lowered
the state's dropout numbers _ by 4,452 students for the first year.
It later was expanded to include other students, such as those who
had earned GEDs. Last year, the state's recovery process shrank the
dropout list by more than 16,000 students.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, districts like Austin have begun their own
``recovery'' efforts, trying to track down missing students to get
them back in school or show they're attending school elsewhere or
plan to attend. Each fall, the district generates a preliminary
dropout list _ middle and high school students who failed to show
up for school and who apparently quit with no legitimate record for
withdrawing.
</P>
<P>
   Counselors and other school employees locate former students by
making phone calls and even visiting homes. They may try to
re-enroll students, learn they are attending elsewhere or suggest
adult education classes.
</P>
<P>
   Some involved in tracking former students said the general idea
is a good one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think overall the main concern is that they find a program
for the students,'' said Bonnie McDonald, Austin High's registrar.
``Of course, there's a lot of pressure to get students off the
dropout list. I can't deny that at all. I feel it. But it won't do
them any good if you just get them off the list. You've got to get
that student in a program that works for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Interim Superintendent A.C. Gonzalez and other top-level
administrators would not comment on the memos or the district's
dropout reporting, citing the grand jury's ongoing investigation.
But Gonzalez, who took the district's reins in April 1998, stressed
that the district should spend the bulk of its dropout efforts on
keeping kids in school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our focus should be on the quality of the educational system
we are providing students, and not how to focus on refinements to
make ourselves look better,'' Gonzalez said. ``There is a very
legitimate function for us to be getting information that is
correct, but the emphasis needs to be on the success of children,
not on a particular score or rating.''
</P>
<P>
   Michele Kurtz writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: mkurtz(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
