<HEADER>
A6946 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WHIRLPOOL-OHIO-COX     04-13 0286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHIRLPOOL-OHIO-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Whirlpool to expand Ohio plant
 &HT;    By Scott Elliott
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Whirlpool Corp. will expand its Greenville plant
to add 180 jobs, thanks in part to a $500,000 state grant.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio Department of Development on Tuesday awarded the Darke
County Community Improvement Corp. $150,000 to acquire land and
$350,000 for road work to expand KitchenAid Way, a small access
road near Ohio 127 and Children's Home-Bradford Road that serves
the Whirlpool plant.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to build a 70,000-square-foot building to
house a production line for its new generation stand mixer product.
Whirlpool is the world's leading manufacturer of home appliances,
including washers, dryers, refrigerators, dishwashers and electric
mixers.
</P>
<P>
   The 181,000-square-foot Greenville plant is the exclusive maker
of KitchenAid small appliances, including mixers, toasters and
blenders.
</P>
<P>
   Whirlpool consolidated four Greenville plants at the KitchenAid
Way location in 1996 and has since added 200 jobs. Employment at
the plant ranges from as many as 850 workers during its peak season
near the end of the year to as few as 600.
</P>
<P>
   With the new $9.4 million building, the company plans to add 180
more jobs in the next three years, plant manager Stan Kinnett said.
At its peak employment, Whirlpool employs more workers than any
other business in Greenville.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had great growth. It's time for an addition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kinnett said the expansion could not take place without better
road access. The company does not have a date for when work will
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
