<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC POLICE UNION REBUKES COMMISSIONER, URGES HIS SUSPENSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The union representing city police officers cast a
vote of no confidence in Police Commissioner Howard Safir on
Tuesday, questioning many of his actions in recent months and
saying that officers are under tremendous pressure to make arrests
and issue summonses.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolmen's Benevolent Association president James Savage said
the Giuliani administration's zero-tolerance approach to crimes,
particularly quality-of-life offenses, had outlived its usefulness
now that crime has gone down. Further, he said that officers were
being pressured to make arrests and issue summonses in every
incident, which he said has harmed the public's perception of
police officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When zero-tolerance tactics were first introduced by the
department, crime was at an all-time high,'' Savage told the
delegates. ``Now that crime is way down, an adjustment of the
strategy is required. If we don't strike a balance between
aggressive enforcement and common sense, it becomes a blueprint for
a police state and tyranny.''
</P>
<P>
   The vote has no practical effect and comes from a union that has
frequently clashed with the Giuliani administration over pay and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the unanimous vote by the PBA's delegates signals that
the commissioner has lost the public support of many of his
officers at a time when the department itself is on the defensive
for its aggressive tactics in the wake of the Feb. 4 shooting of
Amadou Diallo, who was killed in a barrage of 41 police bullets.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous vote by the 400 delegates also comes as Safir's
leadership of the department has increasingly been called into
question after several incidents, including his acceptance of a
free trip to attend the Academy Awards and his use of detectives to
investigate a car accident involving his wife and to provide
security at his daughter's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   At their meeting, the union cited these incidents in calling on
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani to suspend the commissioner from duty until
these incidents can be investigated for possible ethical
violations. Savage, who faces a hotly contested election campaign
to keep the union's presidency, said that officers who engaged in
such actions would be disciplined.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are actions that ordinary police officers can be and
have been suspended for,'' he said. ``This is a police commissioner
who boasts that he has disciplined and fired more cops than his two
immediate predecessors combined. But he has a double standard _ one
for our members, and one for himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who has strongly defended Safir as the commissioner's
actions have been questioned in recent weeks, continued to stand by
Safir on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get to appoint the commissioner, not the PBA, so it's my
vote of confidence that counts,'' Giuliani said in Austin, Texas,
where he was meeting with Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Safir accused Savage of using the no-confidence vote to bolster
his campaign for the union presidency, calling the vote ``a
desperate act by a desperate man who is in trouble in his
election.''
</P>
<P>
   The union is facing a contested election for the first time in
years. Savage, the acting president, is running for re-election.
</P>
<P>
   One of his opponents, Jimmy Higgins, the union's recording
secretary, criticized Tuesday's vote, saying, ``I think it was a
publicity ploy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the department's crackdown on quality-of-life crimes _
minor offenses, usually misdemeanors, like subway fare beating,
reckless bicycle riding and shoplifting _ Safir again denied that
the department has quotas for summonses and tickets. ``Part of the
reason crime continues to be reduced is the enforcement of
quality-of-life crimes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of union delegates at meeting Tuesday in Queens
complained that police officers have been driven to make arrests
and write tickets by commanders.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Officer Michael Wilson, a delegate at the Police Academy, said
the increase in summonses written by officers had harmed their
relationship with the public and cast cops as the heavies in many
of their interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Rosenthal, a former police chief who now teaches at John
Jay College, marveled at the recent turn of events. ``It's really
fascinating times when the PBA is setting the standard for values
and conduct and the police commissioner is the target and subject
of the investigations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Reppetto, head of the Citizens' Crime Commission, said
that tension between police commissioners and the police union was
nothing new, noting that the union booed Commissioner Stephen
Kennedy in the 1950s and picketed the home of Commissioner Michael
Codd in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   ``The normal condition of the police commissioner is to be
embattled,'' he said. ``I calculated that 85 per cent of
commissioners were either dismissed or resigned. So I say to
Commissioner Safir, `Welcome to the club!' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
