<SLUG> BC-TRADERS-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: DAY TRADERS ARE FORMIDABLE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: In references to E(ASTERISK)Trade, replace (ASTERISK) with
the typographical symbol, no parentheses . )  
 (bl)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having evolved from a nation of savers to one of investors,
America is rapidly becoming a country of traders.
</P>
<P>
   As proof, several brokerage firms have just reported record
profits, fueled in large part by a surge in stock trading among
both individuals and institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the frenzy comes from day traders, who take advantage of
the low cost of trading stocks over the Internet to buy and sell
rapidly and profit from small changes in stock prices. A formidable
market force, this group has recently focused on one of the areas
they like best, brokerage firms, bidding up the stocks of the very
companies profiting from their business.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest stocks belong to Charles Schwab, E(ASTERISK)Trade,
Ameritrade Holding and the Knight/Trimark Group, which profit from
the growth in online trading by individuals. But traditional
brokerage giants like Merrill Lynch and Paine Webber, which
reported record first-quarter profits Tuesday, are also being swept
up in the enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price of Schwab, which operates the largest online
brokerage, has soared 40 percent in the last five days. Tuesday, it
gained $15.50 a share, to $150.50, giving the company a total
market value of more than $61 billion _ more than the combined
value of four old-line Wall Street firms, Merrill Lynch, Lehman
Brothers, Paine Webber and Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Ameritrade, another online discount broker, have more
than doubled in the last five days, climbing $31 Tuesday, to
$173.25; since the depth of the global financial crisis last
October, the shares have risen more than thirtyfold, from $5.625.
E(ASTERISK)Trade, another online broker, and Knight/Trimark, which
executes many of the trades placed with the online brokerage firms,
have each gained more than 50 percent in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the online brokerage firms have yet to post results for
the first quarter. But the surprising strength of the early group
has investors salivating over the possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Financial analysts had expected Paine Webber and Merrill Lynch,
for example, to earn less in the first three months of this year
than they did a year in the comparable period a year earlier. But
Paine Webber said Tuesday that its profit surged 31 percent, to
$1.01 a share from 77 cents a share in the first quarter of last
year, as commission income, the company's largest source of
revenues, climbed 17 percent. Paine Webber also said it would begin
offering online trading in the third quarter; the company's shares
gained $3.6875, to $47.25.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch, meanwhile, marked a rebound from the global
downturn in financial markets last year by reporting first-quarter
earnings of $1.44 a share, up 14 percent from $1.26. The company,
which recently introduced online trading for some customers, saw
its commission revenues jump 7 percent, to a record $1.6 billion.
Merrill Lynch's share rose as high as $102.50 early Tuesday, their
highest level since last July, but finished the day down $2.5625 at
$97.375.
</P>
<P>
   The excitement about brokerage firms that do business online is
part of the broader enthusiasm for any company linked to the
Internet. But unlike their peers in many other industries, several
of the online brokers are already profitable.
</P>
<P>
   And their valuations are exponentially larger than those of
traditional brokerage firms. Schwab, which said Tuesday it was
seeking to hire 1,000 additional people, is trading at 170 times
earnings and 42 times book value, which is the value of the
company's assets minus its liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, shares of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, whose
market value of $65 billion makes it the only pure brokerage firm
with a value bigger than Schwab's, is trading at less than 18 times
earnings and 5 times book value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, the investors who are paying those prices are not
relying on the valuation models that have been taught in business
school for the last 30 years,'' said A. James Ellman, manager of
the AIM Global Financial Services fund, which owns shares of Schwab
and Knight/Trimark. But the online firms are attractive because the
potential return on every dollar they invest is far higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have brokers sitting around in branch offices,''
Ellman said. ``They're trading human capital for technological
capital. It's akin to moving from a craftwork factory to an
assembly line factory.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors have reacted, however, as if those factories are
spinning gold from dross. Schwab's market value is more than double
the $26 billion that will be assigned to Goldman, Sachs _
traditionally Wall Street's most profitable firm _ if Goldman's
initial offering is priced at $55 a share, the top of the predicted
range.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, if the stock market cools and day traders take a break,
the online brokerage stocks could be vulnerable. That goes for a
Schwab, which has a big mutual fund business to fall back on, and
more so for transaction-oriented firms like E(ASTERISK)Trade and
Ameritrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The margin of safety in owning Schwab has been removed,'' said
Kenneth Feinberg, co-manager of the Davis Financial fund, which
owns shares of Schwab but has a bigger stake in Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter. ``But anyone who has ever sold their shares of Schwab has
regretted it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
