<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNX-RETURN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS FOURTH LYNX DIES, COLORADO SCALES BACK REINTRODUCTION EFFORT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Colo.)  (rk) 
 By   MINDY SINK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ An effort to reintroduce the lynx to Colorado suffered
another setback this week after a fourth cat died of starvation.
</P>
<P>
   The adolescent female cat, which died on Saturday, had been in
the wild in southwestern Colorado for about six weeks, wildlife
officials said on Monday. Since early February, 12 Canada lynxes
have been released in the wild with radio collars for tracking. The
first two females released have died of starvation. A male also
starved in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were surprised and saddened'' by the latest death, said
Todd Malmsbury, a spokesman for the Colorado Division of Wildlife.
``But we did tell people there would be mortality with any
reintroduction, maybe even as high as 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary diet of the elusive, large-pawed wildcats, which
weigh about 18 to 25 pounds as adults, is snowshoe hare. Malmsbury
said there was evidence that the most recent cat to die had eaten
rabbits and squirrels, but not enough to survive.
</P>
<P>
   After decades of trapping, the lynx was believed to have become
extinct in the state after 1973, when the last sighting was
reported, near Vail.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Division of Wildlife had planned to release about
50 of the small cats this year in the first phase of a three-year,
$750,000 reintroduction program. The project is being scaled back
to 42 releases this year because of the deaths and because the
animals trapped for the program were not the strongest specimens.
</P>
<P>
   No more animals will be trapped for the program this year in
Alaska and Canada, after the arrival of seven more Tuesday from
Alaska. The new arrivals brought to 30 the number of animals
awaiting release next month.
</P>
<P>
   Malmsbury said the lynxes would be held in captivity for about
21 days so that they could put on more weight before their release.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those changes were made to make sure the animals are in the
best shape before they're released,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The handling of the project has drawn criticism from animal
rights advocates and environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``It breaks my heart,'' said Marc Bekoff, a biology professor at
the University of Colorado at Boulder who is organizing a protest
rally there this weekend, his third since February.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the reintroduction program is in serious need of
a very, very deep reassessment,'' Bekoff said. ``I'm not against
reintroduction, but I've argued against this all along because I
feel it's been hastily put together. They haven't done their
homework on the basic biology of the lynx.''
</P>
<P>
   Malmsbury conceded that ``with any reintroduction effort there
are no guarantees.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the same time,'' he said, ``there is no way to restore a
population that has been eliminated by humans without a
reintroduction effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Bekoff said the predicted 50 percent mortality rate was too
high. ``I hope I have egg on my face, but I really think many more
are going to die,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2236EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
