<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6953 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF--ROLFFEATURE-HNS &LR;      04-13 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF--ROLF </SLUG>
 FEATURE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
After near-fatal accident, Rolf finds her way back
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Laura Rolf doesn't remember anything about the night of Dec. 20,
1997.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she recalls nothing about the six months before that
date. Or several weeks after it, part of which were spent in a
coma.
</P>
<P>
   All Rolf knows about that hole in her memory is what friends,
doctors, nurses and her mother have told her. What they have said
is that by all rights she shouldn't be gearing up for the
PaineWebber Futures Classic this week at Cypresswood Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she shouldn't be here at all. She's playing golf this
week when almost everybody thought she would never survive the
injuries suffered in a horrible auto accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody calls me the miracle girl,'' Rolf said Wednesday
before a practice round at the Tradition Course at Cypresswood.
</P>
<P>
   On that fateful night 16 months ago, Rolf was driving home from
Florida to Boling, the little town 50 miles southwest of Houston,
to see her parents for Christmas. Less than seven miles from home
on a rainy evening, an oncoming car hydroplaned, turned sideways
and slid over into Rolf's lane. Her car, going about 55 mph, plowed
broadside into the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The other driver died before emergency crews arrived. Rolf
suffered a severe brain injury, in addition to a punctured lung,
broken leg, dislocated ankle and other problems.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after the injury, there wasn't time for thoughts of
Christmas. The Rolf family was too busy praying that Laura would
survive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The injury I had can cause the brain to bleed and swell,''
Rolf said. ``You can get a lot of high pressures inside it. I was
bleeding in the middle of the brain. The nurses wouldn't give any
of my family or friends any hope because that's not a good place to
be bleeding.''
</P>
<P>
   For 13 days, she was in a coma. Her mother remembers the eerie
moment when her daughter woke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time she opened her eyes, she looked straight
through me,'' Carol Rolf said. ``It was like I wasn't there. I
didn't have much hope. She should not be here today.''
</P>
<P>
   But Laura Rolf's story is one of beating the odds. With help of
doctors and therapists at Herrman Hospital and The Institute for
Rehabilitation and Research (TIRR), she not only survived, but has
returned to a virtually normal life.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf, who will turn 25 on April 27, played golf at the
University of North Texas until she graduated in the spring of '97.
She then began playing the SBC Futures Tour. Later that year, she
moved to Florida to play on a winter tour and have more time to
devote to working on her game.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers nothing after graduating from UNT. She doesn't
remember living in Florida at all.
</P>
<P>
   But what wasn't lost was her passion for golf. After she
regained consciousness and began an arduous regimen of therapy, she
committed herself to getting back on the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say it's amazing for me to be playing golf, much less
to be on the tour,'' Rolf said. ``But golf has been my life and my
goal. It's just what I want to do. I need to do it. It's funny to
hear people say it's unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Rolf began playing golf at age 9. She has a goal of playing on
the LPGA Tour.
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not she ever makes that, her progress since
returning from the near-fatal injuries of the car wreck are nothing
short of extraordinary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's come a long, long way,'' says Carol Rolf. ``She was in a
coma for 13 days at Herrman. And we weren't given a whole lot of
hope. But she struggled through there and came out of the coma.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had the best of care we could have hoped for. When we
got to TIRR and the therapist started working with her, we saw a
lot of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Laura would always tell me that whatever she had to do to
get better, she would do it.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly, she made it back. Now, Laura is almost completely
recovered. She still has some lingering problems. She cannot smell
anything. The muscle tone on the right side of her body, which
suffered the brunt of the damage in the wreck, is not the same as
the left.
</P>
<P>
   But when she began playing golf about five months after the
wreck, everything seemed to be getting better. At the time, the
doctors and therapists told her she should be happy that she ever
got back on the golf course again.
</P>
<P>
   Now, she's playing in tournaments again and credits the
attention she got during rehabilitation as a prime factor.
</P>
<P>
   The TIRR people were fantastic,'' she said. ``Dr. (Gerard)
Francisco and Dr. Levin (Ellen Levin, the clinical director for
TIRR's outpatient brain injury program) and everybody else was just
great.''
</P>
<P>
   The TIRR program was designed to get Rolf's mental and physical
capacities rehabilitated as much as possible. Clearly, the therapy
was successful.
</P>
<P>
   As for her golf game, Rolf did not play well in her first
competitive tournament back. She played in the Futures Tour event
near Dallas last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all right,'' she said of her game. ``I'm hitting it
fairly good. I started playing again competitively last week in
Dallas and I'm going to play these two weeks, then see what I need
to work on. I wanted to play a couple of times to see what it'll
take to get back shooting well. After this, I'm not scheduled for
another tournament for three or four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``But starting in late May and through June, I'll play all the
Futures Tour events.''
</P>
<P>
   What Rolf didn't remember, she said, was the competitiveness of
playing on tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it is that I just didn't remember the nerves and
pressure, the nervous energy that you have,'' she said. ``And I'm
finding out that, since the wreck, I don't have as much energy as I
used to. I can't do as much without getting really tired fast.
Because of that, I haven't been able to practice as much as need
to. It's just going to take a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Her energy is returning slowly and everything else about Rolf's
recovery has been excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's had a little bit of a personality change,'' her mother
said. ``Otherwise, she's back 96 percent of what she was before.
But we still notice little changes in her daily.''
</P>
<P>
   Her memory of those six months in her life before the crash
probably will never return, although her mother was encouraged when
the two of them attended the LPGA Qualifying School as spectators
in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we pulled through the gates of the complex, Laura said,
`I recognize this place,' and she had only been there when she was
living in Florida,'' Carol Rolf said. ``I'm hoping there will be
other things that jog her memory.''
</P>
<P>
   But even if that hole in her memory bank is never filled, it
can't take away from the fact that Laura Rolf is here.
</P>
<P>
   As her mother said, ``She's my walking miracle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
