<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GIULIANI EXTOL EACH OTHER'S CHANCES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The Republican Party's most-talked-about
potential presidential contender and its most-talked-about
potential candidate for U.S. Senate met for 90 minutes Tuesday
afternoon at the governor's mansion here.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping outside to meet the press amid thick humidity, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush and New York City Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani
said they had spent the afternoon talking about education, about
baseball and _ oh, yes _ about politics.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has formed an exploratory committee to consider running for
president next year. Giuliani has formed a similar committee to
plan a run for the U.S. Senate in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Standing shoulder to shoulder, smiling and joshing like old
pals, Giuliani and Bush each promoted the other's prospective
candidacy Tuesday afternoon, exchanging hearty praise and firm, yet
respectfully restrained, encouragement.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of the real hopes that the Republican Party has of
regaining control of the United States and moving it in the
direction that it should move,'' Giuliani said of Bush. ``So, I am
very very hopeful that it all turns out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Giuliani's Senate prospects, Bush said, ``I think
he'd make an excellent candidate.'' He added, ``The mayor has got a
record, a strong record that he can run on, and he's a good, tough
campaigner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush ducked the most obvious question raised by the
spectacle of two of the most prominent, well-known and ambitious
Republicans sharing a microphone on a random April afternoon:
whether their futures might be fused into a ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the first thing that I have got to do is get the
nomination, should I decide to run,'' Bush said. ``I am leaning
that way, obviously. I have got an exploratory committee that's up
and running.'' But, he added pointedly: ``It's too early to be
talking about the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said at a news conference outside the governor's mansion
after the meeting that after visiting New York City Hall in 1997,
he had given the mayor a standing invitation to come to Texas. ``I
said, if you ever come back to Texas, knock on my door. And today
he did, and I opened it,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he would begin traveling around the country after the
close of the Texas state legislative session this spring. He is
scheduled to go to Iowa in June. The governor also noted that the
mayor could face Hillary Rodham Clinton. ``It could be one of the
great campaigns in the history of the United States Senate, the way
the rumors are shaping up,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   But they each stopped short of calling their comments an
endorsement. ``I don't know,'' Bush said when asked if he was
endorsing Giuliani. ``Put it down as people liking each other.''
The mayor piped up, ``That's a good way to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, the mayor also hedged when asked if he was endorsing
Bush. ``Well, it's an encouragement,'' he said. ``I think it's
premature to endorse anybody for president at this point. The
governor hasn't announced. I haven't announced for the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   When a reporter asked Giuliani if he had specifically urged Bush
to run for president, Bush suddenly thrust his arm behind his back
toward Giuliani. ``He twisted my arm,'' the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the cue, the mayor grabbed Bush by the wrist. ``Run!'' he
shouted, jokingly. ``Run!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
