<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR COACHES, INDULGENCE IS A BAD RECIPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The psychiatrist called the hotel room 10 minutes
after Larry Brown had finished talking about Allen Iverson on
sports talk radio Tuesday. He was offering a personality quiz that
would help Brown understand himself so he could then determine the
best approach to take with his young star.
</P>
<P>
   Brown took his number, thanked him, hung up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept it,'' he said, never knowing when the next Iverson
crisis would come, where he might have to turn.
</P>
<P>
   The spindly guard with the jet fuel in his calf muscles leads
the National Basketball Association in scoring and markets himself
as The Answer, which he might yet be if he ever acknowledges the
questions. Brown, at Madison Square Garden on Tuesday night with
Iverson and his Philadelphia 76ers to play the Knicks in a game
laced with playoff implications, may not survive long, or even want
to, by standing up to Iverson, as he recently did. But he is
pushing 60 and has been around long enough to know this: He has no
chance unless he does.
</P>
<P>
   So Brown reclined in his courtside seat while his players _
without Iverson _ loosened up with pre-game jumpers, and continued
to sound more like Iverson's tough-talking guidance counselor than
his coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear him comment that people don't want to see him do well
_ the media, the league,'' Brown said. ``That's baloney. I think
people in the league really want him to succeed.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown tries not to forget that Iverson is 23, and that he has
already come a long way, from being virtually uncoachable. He
remembers that not many of the young and gifted come bounding into
the pros, onto bad teams, off the college assembly line like Magic
Johnson and Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these players will remain rooted in self-absorption
until it becomes their personal prison and there is no escape, and
no chance to win. Iverson is a long way from there, but every time
he curses his coach for having the audacity to remove him from the
game, or whatever he interprets as an unproductive show of
disrespect, he most surely takes one step closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time I've taken Allen out since I've been here, I've had
the same response,'' Brown said. ``And I understand he just wants
to play, but he doesn't understand how it affects his teammates or
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Eleven days ago, Iverson sat on the bench too long to suit him
and gave Brown an earful. Brown benched him for the remainder of
the first half. Iverson had to be talked out of leaving the arena
by, of all people, his bodyguard. Brown later had to throw the
bodyguard out of the post-game locker room, where he didn't belong.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a season of dramatic improvement, the 76ers are
combustible at the core, with Iverson and his moody, would-be
mentor, a disciple of Dean Smith who has always been hardest on
point guards. Brown, with a long-term contract and a front-office
title, took the position knowing the baggage Iverson brought. The
teacher and reformer in Brown couldn't resist the biggest challenge
of his career.
</P>
<P>
   He knows Iverson was indulged everywhere he played, even at
Georgetown. ``I watched him play there, and that wasn't the way
John Thompson coaches,'' Brown said. Thompson didn't handle Iverson
the way he did Patrick Ewing, but then, as Brown said, ``He only
had Allen for two years.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown, always an admirer of Ewing's, knows Ewing would never
curse Jeff Van Gundy, which means, from the view on the 76ers'
bench, Van Gundy seems blessed. Ewing, of course, has wielded his
own institutional leverage around the Garden for years. He's just
done it with less attitude and lip.
</P>
<P>
   When Ewing was Iverson's age, he rebelled against his first
coach, Hubie Brown, and when he was supposedly all grown up, he
tuned out the only other coach who came along and told him things
he didn't want to hear.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't move with a posse and never tried to storm out of the
building. He just stopped playing hard and gave the team no choice
but to fire Don Nelson in early 1996. Even William Goldman knows
that when Van Gundy was promoted, he was hired to be the
anti-Nelson, restorer of the Knicks' offense to what it had been
and still too often is.
</P>
<P>
   Unpredictable as they are, these Knicks play their best when
their smaller players drive the ball, and Ewing gets his shots as a
spot-up shooter. Sooner or later, Van Gundy will have to admit
this, refocus his offense and explain why to Ewing. Before he does,
he may want that psychiatrist's number Brown is saving for another
bad ear day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
