<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GIULIANI-BUSH-COX     04-13 0650
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GIULIANI-BUSH-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Giuliani stops by, says Bush should run
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The most famous Texas Ranger fan and one of the
most prominent backers of the New York Yankees met Tuesday at the
Governor's Mansion and agreed to disagree _ not just on baseball,
but on a potentially explosive issue in the fight for the
Republican presidential nomination: abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who used to own a piece of the Texas
Rangers, and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, a diehard Yankee fan,
met for more than an hour to discuss a range of issues, including
Bush's presidential run, education and the crisis in Kosovo. Asked
what he thought of Giuliani's moderate brand of Republicanism, Bush
said he wasn't troubled by the mayor's support for abortion rights.
The governor, who opposes abortion, recently drew fire from some
conservatives when he said he wouldn't push a constitutional
amendment outlawing abortion because most Americans wouldn't
support it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just goes to show that good people can disagree on certain
issues and that there's far more that we agree on than we don't
agree on,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, in Texas to address the Greater Dallas Crime
Commission, was the latest in a long line of Republicans who have
come to Austin to express their support for a Bush candidacy. But
the mayor characterized the visit as ``encouragement'' rather than
an endorsement, which he said would be premature since Bush hasn't
officially announced his intention to run.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gov. Bush has the capacity to organize the Republican Party in
a way where we can avoid some of the mistakes we've made in the
past,'' Giuliani said. ``There are other good candidates, but I
think he's one of the real stars of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   New York is fertile fund-raising ground, and Giuliani would be a
valuable ally for Bush as he strives to raise the more than $45
million it would take to be able to skip federal matching money and
the spending caps it brings.
</P>
<P>
   Many prominent New York Republicans reportedly have declined
thus far to open their checkbooks for the Bush campaign because New
York Gov. George Pataki still hasn't ruled out a bid for the GOP
nomination. But Giuliani said Bush is likely to enjoy strong
support in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although it's seen very often as a Democratic stronghold,
Republicans can win,'' Giuliani said. ``I've won New York City
twice in a row, and I believe he would be a very strong and
competitive candidate in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier on Tuesday, Bush expressed support for raising the
federal individual contribution limit above $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush backers have collected more than $7 million for his
campaign despite the fact that the governor has stuck to his pledge
to remain in Austin until the end of the legislative session on May
31. Aides to Iowa Rep. Greg Ganske said Monday that Bush would be
in the congressman's district on June 12 to help him raise money.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani also defended Bush's foreign-policy credentials, noting
that former President Ronald Reagan, who was former governor of
California when he ran for president, also lacked foreign-policy
experience when he went to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who was criticized for being slow to express his views on
Kosovo, promised Tuesday that he'll be ``up for the task'' of
foreign relations if he reaches the White House. Bush declined to
directly criticize President Clinton's Kosovo policy but said
Clinton ``better have a plan to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``America ought to be slow to engage our military. But once
engaged, we've got to engage to win,'' Bush said. ``I hope the
president has a plan to do so, and I hope the president has a plan
to get us out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott S. Greenberger writes for the Austin American-Statesman,
Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
