<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LENNON-PHOTO-SUIT-NYT     04-13 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LENNON-PHOTO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-AIDE TO LENNON IS SUED BY WIDOW OVER USE OF PHOTOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ANDREW JACOBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Frederic Seaman was a close friend of John Lennon, at
least according to a television special on the murdered Beatle that
was broadcast in February. During the Fox Family Channel program,
which featured him as a ``an expert on Lennon's childhood and adult
life,'' Seaman showed off snapshots of Lennon taken in the two
years before his murder in December 1980.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem, according to lawyers for Yoko Ono, Lennon's
widow, is that the photographs were stolen from the Lennon
household and that Seaman, the singer's former personal assistant,
is a confessed swindler, not a trusted confidant.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman admitted as much to the Manhattan district attorney in
1983, and he agreed to return the cartons of photographs, personal
letters and private journals he had carried out of the Lennon
residence in the Dakota apartment building on Manhattan's West Side
during the two years he worked for the family.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, Ono filed a lawsuit in U.S. District Court in
Manhattan claiming that Seaman failed to return everything and that
he plans, once again, to profit from his crime.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Ono, Paul LiCalsi, said Seaman threatened to sue
Capitol Records in February, saying that liner notes accompanying a
new boxed set of Lennon recordings included a photograph that he
owns.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has extraordinary gall to continue to take advantage of the
Lennons after all he did to them,'' said LiCalsi, who added that
Ono decided to file the suit after learning of Seaman's threatened
suit against the record company.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman, a Brooklyn resident, denied that he had any of the
stolen items. ``I don't know what she's talking about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The squabble between Seaman and Ono began soon after Lennon was
shot on Dec. 8, 1980, as he entered the Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   According to LiCalsi, Seaman told Ono he was too devastated by
the murder to work and asked for some time off. But instead of
mourning, LiCalsi said, Seaman spent the time formulating an
ambitious plan to publish books about the Lennons.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the scheme ``Project Walrus,'' he and his college
friend, Bob Rosen, came up with merchandising ideas like a ``John
and Yoko'' doll, LiCalsi said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next year, Seaman stole hundreds of family photographs,
piles of private letters, unreleased recordings and journals that
Lennon kept between 1974 and 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Ono, who was deep in mourning, never noticed the thefts. She
dismissed Seaman only after she found him taking a bath in her
private bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman was caught after Rosen, angry that his co-conspirator was
trying to cut him out of the project, turned him in to Ono, who
called the police.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman was arrested in April 1983, and he pleaded guilty to
second-degree larceny.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for receiving five years' probation, he agreed to
return ``any and all property,'' which he says he did. ``I don't
have anything,'' he said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Seaman published ``The Last Days of John Lennon: A
Personal Memoir,'' an unflattering portrait of Lennon and his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman, who served no jail time for the thefts, said he was not
aware that the lawsuit had been filed until he was called by a
reporter Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have hundreds of photographs that I took with my own camera
and they're copyrighted,'' he said
</P>
<P>
   LiCalsi disagreed, saying a pre-employment contract that Seaman
signed stipulated that any photographs he took of the family are
the property of the Lennons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how after admitting that he betrayed the
family, he still thinks he has a right to the Lennon legacy,''
LiCalsi said.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for Seaman, Paul Karl Lukacs, said the lawsuit was
meritless. ``The bottom line is that Yoko does not like Fred Seaman
and this is an attempt to smear him,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
