<SLUG> BC-LEADERSHIP-AWARD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    University announces annual award
 &HT;    By Mark Fisher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The University of Dayton and its national alumni
association Tuesday unveiled a ``Leadership with Virtue'' award
that will be presented annually to a nationally or internationally
recognized leader who blends a high level of personal honor with
professional achievements.
</P>
<P>
   UD will sponsor a leadership symposium to accompany the
announcement of the first award, scheduled for February 2000.
</P>
<P>
   An eight- to 10-member award selection committee will be named
in the next few months. The committee will accept nominations and
will generate possible nominees of its own, said Jack Proud,
president of UD's national alumni association.
</P>
<P>
   Proud said the Leadership with Virtue award has been in the
works for 18 months, before the name Monica Lewinsky blazed into
the national consciousness. But he acknowledged that ``the amount
of noise from Washington probably reinforced our belief that this
was important to do.'' The diverse and bipartisan nature of the
selection committee will help prevent partisanship from affecting
the award, Proud said.
</P>
<P>
   A full-page advertisement UD placed in today's Midwest edition
of USA Today and in the Dayton Daily News, and which UD officials
released Tuesday, seems to seize upon the scandals in Washington
and elsewhere. ``It's time to take a stand,'' it reads. ``It seems
now, more than ever, there is a national hunger for leaders
throughout all walks of life with high moral and ethical
standards.''
</P>
<P>
   UD's president, Brother Raymond Fitz, said the award does not
imply UD officials believe there are leaders who have no faults.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be human is to have failed and perhaps often,'' Fitz said.
``We want to identify persons who have undertaken a personal
journey in which they strive to integrate moral commitment in the
ways they lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Proud said the award ``is about virtue, not about sainthood.''
</P>
<P>
   Selection committee members will look for national and
international leaders who exhibit characteristics such as
integrity, vision and emotional balance, although Fitz said the
criteria will likely evolve in future years.
</P>
<P>
   UD chose Joan Swedlund to serve as project director for the
award and symposium. Swedlund served as administrative director of
Hauer Music Co., chief of public affairs for Five Rivers MetroParks
and marketing manager for the Downtown Dayton Association.
</P>
<P>
   UD also plans to endow a one-year scholarship in each
recipient's name to be awarded to a UD junior.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Fisher writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
