<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FARM-EQUIPMENT-ART-2T     04-13 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARM-EQUIPMENT-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKERS OF FARM MACHINERY STEP UP EFFORTS TO DIVERSIFY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The name John Deere conjures up tractors, farm
equipment and big green machines lingering in the distance, on a
huge cornfield somewhere in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   While it receives most of its revenues from the farm, Deere &AMP;
Co., the world's largest maker of agricultural machinery, also
peddles lawn and turf products. Case Corp., a rival in farm
machinery, has broadened its reach as well, financing dump trucks
and marine equipment. And Caterpillar Inc., the world's largest
maker of earthmoving equipment and a major agricultural supplier,
is selling truck engines while leveraging its vast distribution
network to move Chrysler auto parts and Puma sneakers.
</P>
<P>
   All three heavy-equipment makers _ the biggest names in farm and
construction equipment _ are moving into new fields in an effort to
buffer themselves from the wrenching up-and-down cycle of their
core businesses. At the moment, they are trying to break out of a
nasty slowdown that in the last few quarters has sapped the profits
of virtually every maker of farm equipment. When the farm economy
here in the Midwest sagged with the Asian economic crisis and the
construction business showed signs of slowing late last year, the
big-equipment makers stepped up their efforts to diversify in hopes
of maintaining profitability, even in a down cycle.
</P>
<P>
   The sector has been upgraded recently by some Wall Street
analysts who believe that the heavy machinery cycle is very likely
to start moving upward, but most analysts are unimpressed by the
steps toward diversification. Fundamentally, the companies are
defined by their core businesses _ and so are still captives of the
business cycle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what they're trying to do, but it's just not showing up
in the numbers,'' Tobias Levkovich, an analyst at Salomon Smith
Barney, said about Case. ``They've gotten reamed by the cycle, and
that's with the U.S. construction business doing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most recent downturn has been a big impetus in a
trend that has been in place for some time.
</P>
<P>
   Case, for instance, now receives about a third of its revenue
from sales of construction equipment. Deere receives nearly
one-fifth of its revenues from lawn and consumer products.
Caterpillar, which originated in 1925 with the merger of two farm
tractor companies, is dominant in excavating and earthmoving
machines, but now receives a third of its revenues from engine
sales and about 5 percent from financial services.
</P>
<P>
   The three companies say they are also outsourcing more
operations to cut fixed costs and venturing further afield into
unrelated businesses, such as health care, distribution management,
toys and clothing. Caterpillar has a new line of ``Cat'' boots,
caps and jeans. Deere likewise has a major licensing deal involving
toys and clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar executives are hammering away at a consistent
message. ``If the U.S. construction market slows down we've been
telling people, `Look, we are not a U.S. construction industry
business,''' said F. Lynn McPheeters, chief financial officer at
Caterpillar. ``This is a global, multifaceted company that has
taken a lot of the cyclicality out of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street remains skeptical, however. Despite diversification,
when the farm and construction economies weakened last year,
particularly in Asia, so did the profits of these companies.
</P>
<P>
   At Case, earnings dropped 80 percent in 1998. Deere, which has
laid off at least 300 workers in the last six months, saw profits
decline 75 percent last quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar, by contrast, had a year of record revenues, $21
billion. But profits are expected to slip 50 percent when it
reports quarterly results this week compared with the similar
quarter a year earlier because of weaker sales of agriculture and
mining products and a slump in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Investors had been dumping the Big Three stocks until recently,
when the shares began to recover somewhat on hopes that the cycle
might be on the verge of an upturn. But it was a long plunge
downward: Case stock, for example, fell below the price of its 1994
initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   Case says it has drastically changed its operations since it was
spun off from Tenneco that year. Now, the company says, it is
quicker to react to downturns. Executives also say the company has
cut fixed costs in recent years and moved rapidly to idle plants.
And it has counted on geographical diversification and benefited
from stronger sales of construction equipment and growth in its
financing of marine and commercial vehicles, such as municipal
garbage trucks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm absolutely convinced we're a dramatically different
company than we were in the last down cycle,'' said Steven Lamb,
president and chief operating officer. ``In the last downturn we
weren't profitable. But since then we've grown our construction,
credit and international businesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Wall Street analysts, however, are far from convinced that
either Case or its competitors have fundamentally changed their
reliance on cyclical businesses. When Lisa Shalett, an analyst at
Sanford C. Bernstein &AMP; Co., raised doubts about the new efforts,
executives at Case summoned her to their offices in Racine, Wis.,
for a review of the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the day, it's great these companies have
attempted to diversify,'' Ms. Shalett said. ``But the key struggle
for investors is that they don't make tons of money outside of the
core business.''
</P>
<P>
   When the farm equipment market turned down in the early 1990s,
Case lost more than $2 billion, including restructuring charges;
Deere lost $920 million in 1993 alone. Caterpillar was also
hemorrhaging. Though the farm slump could deepen in 1999, Lamb says
Case executives are comfortable with Wall Street projections that
Case will be ``solidly profitable'' in 1999, despite a slowdown in
earnings growth over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jean-Pierre Rosso, the chief executive at Case, says his
company's stock has fallen far too sharply. ``At $25 it's still
undervalued,'' Rosso said a few weeks ago, just days after shares
of Case bounced back from their low of $18. ``At $20 it was so
grossly undervalued for a company with $6 billion in sales and
excellent assets.'' On Tuesday the shares closed at $28.75.
</P>
<P>
   Deere is more diversified. Its commercial-equipment division,
which includes lawn and turf products, saw an 88 percent jump in
operating profits in 1998. Its diesel engine business is also
strong, and its managed health care operation improved greatly in
1998, after a large loss in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar is the most diverse of the three, but falling demand
in Asia has hurt crucial sales of earthmoving equipment, used for
construction projects like the Hong Kong airport. The company is
expanding its agriculture business, making a run at Deere in the
sale of giant combines, but the biggest growth area for Caterpillar
may be engines.
</P>
<P>
   With its acquisition last year of Perkins Engines, the former
subsidiary of Lucas Varity PLC, Caterpillar is now one of the
world's largest makers of diesels for construction. Caterpillar
engines are also under the hood of about one-third of all big
trucks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Caterpillar is also promoting mobile electric generators, which
are in high demand in the developing world. And it has leveraged
its distribution network, called the Caterpillar Logistics
Services, founded in 1986. The division now has 2,600 employees and
handles, warehouses and distributes more than $4 billion worth of
products each year, including parts for Sun Microsystems and Land
Rovers.
</P>
<P>
   Profit margins are much richer in farm vehicles than in the
affiliated businesses, analysts say, and that means profit
downturns in that business can be disproportionately sharp.
</P>
<P>
   ``The highest margins business at cyclical peaks is farm
equipment,'' said Levkovich of Salomon Smith Barney. ``They're
trying to grow all those other things, but the buck still stops in
farm.''
</P>
<P>
   The last big pure farm-equipment maker in the United States is
Agco Corp. of Duluth, Ga., which had $2.9 billion in sales in 1998.
The company says that because it outsources most of its business
and focuses primarily on assembly, it is less susceptible to sharp
downturns. Nonetheless, for the fiscal year ended Dec. 31, Agco's
revenues fell 9 percent, to $2.94 billion, and the company
announced that it was cutting 1,400 jobs. Its shares are now
trading at $6.9375, down from $27 a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agriculture is cyclical, and since that is our primary
industry, so are we,'' said Robert Ratliff, the company's chief
executive. But Agco, which has grown in recent years by acquiring
companies like Massey-Ferguson, said it would continue to seek
acquisitions and would diversify to mitigate downturns.
</P>
<P>
   In diversifying, however, Case, Deere and Caterpillar are
poaching in one another's backyard. Construction companies and farm
companies are now construction-farm companies with a growing
interest in peripherals, like forestry equipment. Caterpillar and
Deere are both selling diesel engines, in the hope that they will
be a cyclical antidote.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts who follow the industry talk about Caterpillar taking
on Deere with big combines, Deere and Caterpillar taking on
Ingersoll-Rand in a mechanism called the skid-steer loader, a small
and easily adaptable multipurpose construction vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   These searches for a cure, some analysts say, involve
considerable risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to diversify their exposure so they're not
dependent on the farmer,'' said David Bluestein, an analyst at
Paine Webber. ``But these guys are all diversifying into other
companies' core markets and that's going to lead to overcapacity,
which causes pricing pressure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
