<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. DEMOCRATS DROP NOVEL FUND-RAISING IDEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Concerned about perceptions that campaign finance
laws could be violated, an adviser to Hillary Rodham Clinton now
says it is highly unlikely that Democrats will form a committee to
raise money for an unspecified Senate candidate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   Any money raised by such a committee, first proposed by New York
Democrats last month, could theoretically have been used for the
campaign of whoever the Democratic candidate for Senate turned out
to be. The committee was planned to ease the concerns of those
Democrats who said Mrs. Clinton's prospective Senate campaign was
disrupting the fund-raising efforts of other potential candidates
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   In February, Mrs. Clinton announced her interest in the seat to
be vacated in 2001 by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, but threw
Democrats into a minor uproar when she said she would not announce
her decision until ``later this year.'' Rep. Nita Lowey of
Westchester County has said she wants to run if Mrs. Clinton does
not.
</P>
<P>
   Last month New York Democrats cited a 1977 advisory opinion from
the Federal Election Commission that approved the formation of a
fund-raising committee for an unspecified Republican candidate for
the Senate from Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers now say that two of six election commissioners
dissented in the opinion, and that it is not necessarily relevant
in Mrs. Clinton's situation and under current election laws, which
have changed in the 22 intervening years.
</P>
<P>
   The adviser to Mrs. Clinton said he was not inclined to ask the
election commission for a new ruling that might not be in Mrs.
Clinton's favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fraught with a lot of difficulties and probably more
trouble than it's worth,'' the adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's advisers are eager to avoid anything that
resembles the kind of campaign finance scandals that consumed the
White House after the last presidential election. The party's
practices led to criminal charges against some Democratic
fund-raisers and the return of $3 million that had come from
questionable sources.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Wertheimer, a longtime advocate of campaign finance reform
and a critic of the Clinton White House fund-raising practices in
1996, said Tuesday that Mrs. Clinton's advisers were being being
highly cautious to avoid potential criticism from Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may be not wanting to raise any kind of opportunity for
questions at this stage of the game,'' Wertheimer said. ``Because
they don't need it for something that's not necessary in the first
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton has apparently decided to quiet Democratic concerns
about fund-raising by raising money specifically for New York
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In May she is to appear at a $1,000-a-plate dinner in Manhattan
for Mrs. Lowey, who expects to raise $500,000 to $1 million from
the event. During three days in New York next week, Mrs. Clinton is
to appear at a fund-raiser for Rep. Jerrold Nadler, the Manhattan
Democrat who was one of President Clinton's leading defenders
during the impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats say Mrs. Clinton will have no trouble raising money on
her own should she decide to run for the Senate seat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
