<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KVAERNER-SHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MAJOR SHAKEUP, NORWAY'S KVAERNER WILL SELL SHIPYARDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ The reorganization of European industry
reached into the heartland of Norway on Tuesday, when Europe's
biggest shipbuilder announced plans to sell all its shipyards and
other money-losing businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement by Kvaerner SA, an engineering conglomerate
troubled by poor management and bad acquisitions, is the latest
example of a revolution in European corporate culture.
</P>
<P>
   After snubbing shareholders for years by pursuing murky
strategies and producing mediocre profits, many of Europe's biggest
industrial companies are now slashing costs and getting rid of
businesses that don't measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Siemens AG of Germany unveiled plans to jumpstart
profits by selling off businesses with sales of $10 billion.
Alcatel SA, the huge French manufacturer of telecommunications
equipment, announced plans last month to eliminate 12,000 jobs by
the end of the year 2000. ABB Asea Brown Boveri AG, the
Swiss-Swedish engineering firm, eliminated more than 12,000 jobs
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But the shakeup at Kvaerner is one of the most drastic. If
carried out in full, the company would abandon a business that had
also been a bedrock of Norwegian industry. It would shrink itself
to about one-third of its current size, shedding 25,000 of its
80,000 workers. The moves are likely to lead to job cuts at
shipyards around Europe and possibly in the United States as well.
</P>
<P>
   Kvaerner, which builds everything from offshore oil rigs to
cruise ships, had been planning to build ships at the old
Philadelphia Naval Shipyard and employ about 1,000 people there.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans could change abruptly, depending on what the
shipbuilder's new owners decide to do. Kvaerner executives said
they have not decided whether to simply sell the shipyards, spin
the business off as a separate entity to shareholders or retreat
more gradually by putting them into a joint venture with some other
shipbuilder.
</P>
<P>
   Whichever course prevails, the changes will be drastic. Kjell
Almskog, who took over as chief executive last December, said the
company had set aside 4 billion kroner, or about $500 million, to
cover reorganization costs.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to unloading the shipyards, which employ about
10,000 workers, the company plans to sell businesses with another
11,500 workers in areas like metal equipment, mechanical
engineering, pulp and paper products and a real estate development.
Several thousand other jobs would be eliminated in the companies
that remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep in mind that this is an old, traditional Norwegian
company,'' said Ottar Haugerud, an analyst at Orkla Securities in
Oslo. ``They have turned the company upside down. It is a
completely different company today than it was yesterday.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost any change would be an improvement. Under Kvaerner's
previous chief executive, Erik Tonseth, the company's 1998 losses
totaled 1.4 billion kroner, or $290 million. The company's stock
plunged nearly 80 percent last year, though it had partly recovered
since Almskog took over and made it clear he would shift course.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the problems can be traced to Tonseth's disastrous
purchase of Trafalgar House, a sprawling British engineering
company that also owned the Cunard Line of cruise ships, for $1.38
billion in 1996. Trafalgar was loaded with debt and problems, which
drained capital at a time when the shipbuilding industry was in a
recession.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kvaerner sold off numerous chunks of Trafalgar, including
Cunard Line and the Queen Elizabeth 2 cruise ship, it still ran up
big losses last year and was plagued by high costs and its
disjointed mish-mash of companies.
</P>
<P>
   Almskog, a former top executive at ABB Asea Brown Boveri, is now
trying to refocus the company and return it to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we want to be a world champion, or in the world class
anyway, we need to scale back,'' he told a news conference in
London today. ``The plan for this `new Kvaerner' is to create a
group that is significantly smaller and much leaner, but infinitely
stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Though investors had been expecting a fairly broad
reorganization plan, most were surprised by the decision to abandon
shipbuilding. In Oslo, Kvaerner stock dropped 3 kroner, or 2.2
percent, to 136 kroner Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said it may be difficult to find buyers for Kvaerner's
12 European shipyards. Beyond that, Almskog's description of the
problems at other businesses was bleaker than some analysts had
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``My gut feeling is positive, but the state of the company was
worse than expected,'' said Haugerud, of Orkla Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, most said the plan was a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to get rid of shipbuilding yards in Europe these
days, but in the long run this is the right decision,'' said Olof
Jonasson, an industry analyst at Handelsbanken Markets in Oslo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
