<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-SCHOOL-TESTSTANDA     04-13 1472
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-SCHOOL-TESTSTANDARDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Public schools feeling pressure to raise test scores
 &HT;    By Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In May 1996, the Texas Education Agency notified
Lanier High School it would be rated ``low-performing'' _ a
designation that Texas public schools receive when their students
score poorly on the state achievement test or when too many
students drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Kane, who was principal at Lanier at the time and who
subsequently led the campus to its ranking as a national ``Blue
Ribbon School,'' found that clerical errors in administeringthe
Texas Assessment of Academic Skills caused the low-performing
label. A mismatch between birth dates and Social Security
numberscaused the tests of two students to be eliminated from
consideration. That _ the removal of two passing scores from the
school's overall average _ prompted the low-performing label.
</P>
<P>
   The school district appealed, and the education agency raised
Lanier's ranking to ``acceptable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two and a half years since then, the Austin Independent
School District's handling of TAAS data has evolved from simple
cleanup to criminal tampering, a Travis County grand jury charged
last week as it indicted the district and its deputy
superintendent, Kay Psencik. Psencik has denied wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   The charges of ``tampering with governmental record'' against
Psencik and AISD _ believed to be the first school district in the
country to be indicted _ illustrate the increasing pressure on
public schools to perform. The TEA has investigated high numbers of
erasures on the TAAS test in 11 school districts, and prosecutors
are investigating the Houston Independent School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message was never said but was an underlying message all
of us felt,'' said Suzzie Bragg, who was principal at Johnston High
School during the 1997-98 school year and who testified before the
Travis County grand jury recently. ``The message is, `You will not
be low-performing.' At no time did I feel like I was told, `Suzzie,
do what it takes,' but I do think the pressure is there, and it
depends on how people internalized it.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined not to have another school mistakenly get a low
rating, the district hired Ricky Arredondo in July 1996 from TEA.
</P>
<P>
   At the education agency, Arredondo had worked with Kaye
Contreras, who left TEA in 1995tobecome the executive assistant to
former Austin Superintendent Jim Fox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kay Psencik had talked to Fox about a position for an analyst.
She was looking for an analyst and was asking everybody for
recommendations for a good person for the job. I had given her that
recommendation,'' Contreras said. ``She (Psencik) interviewed him,
and she hired him, and I was not even in the room.''
</P>
<P>
   On March 25 of this year, Arredondo pleaded no contest to the
same tampering charge for which AISD and Psencik are being
prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
   When they hired him, Arredondo had a reputation in education
circles as a computer whiz. Many considered him a ``magician'' with
numbers _ a research analyst so skilled that he could do in minutes
what would take others hours.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Arredondo was hired, the school district again was
appealing the ratings of schools. Fox wrote a letter to Texas
Education Commissioner Mike Moses on July 16, 1997, and said Bailey
Middle School and Brown and Summitt elementary schools deserved to
be rated ``recognized'' _ one step above ``acceptable'' _ and that
errors by the company that developed and graded the test cost those
schools a higher rating. Fox, in his appeal, said the district
needed to make changes to demographic and ethnic data of some
students.
</P>
<P>
   Moses denied the appeal in August.
</P>
<P>
   Fox pressed the issue in a Sept. 11, 1997, letter. ``I have
attached copies of 18 documented cases of erroneous Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills data. . . . It is precisely these
types of errors which have caused me to appeal three campus
ratings,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Moses stood by his decision but in November agreed to have a
third party review it.
</P>
<P>
   John Stevens, executive director of the Texas Business and
Education Coalition, reviewed the 1997 Austin appeal and came away
believing AISD was trying to manipulate the system.
</P>
<P>
   In rating a school, the TEA considers not just how the student
body as a whole scores on the TAAS but also how ethnic and other
demographic subgroups perform. At schools with fewer than 30
students in a particular subgroup, those tests are not counted
toward the school rating.By reducing the numbers of a
low-performing subgroup to fewer than 30, a campus' rating can be
elevated.
</P>
<P>
   ``They went through and scrutinized information but did it only
for students they believed would affect the TAAS results. It was
pretty clear what was going on that year,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   Moses had echoed the sentiment to Fox in an Aug. 11, 1997,
letter: ``Given your expressed concerns in past meetings . . .
about the potential for manipulation of accountability indicator
data by school districts, I want to make you aware of TEA findings
regarding student information changes . . . made by Austin ISD
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly, economic status and special education status can
easily change between the end of October and the end of April
within a given school year. However, ethnicity is not a transient
characteristic,'' Moses wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Fox declined to be interviewed for this story. The school board
bought out his contract last year forabout $258,000, for issues
unrelated to the TAAS data tampering.
</P>
<P>
   The TEA didn't move to discipline Austin for what happened in
1997, but the agency was on alert.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, when the Austin district wanted to make more
changes,the TEA took a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes up a second time, that adds more credibility to
the position that this is something that was a real manipulation of
the system because it demonstrated a pattern,'' said Joe Neely, a
former deputy education commissioner who currently is the
superintendent of the Rockwall school district, east of Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving preliminary TAAS scores, the district made
changes to the student identification numbers of 16 students by
swapping them with the students' Social Security numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The swap created a data mismatch, and once again, the computer
eliminated tests from accountability calculations. Not all the
students performed poorly. In many cases, a student in a subgroup
was targeted so his or her test would be eliminated, bringing the
subgroup to less than 30. That would disqualify the group
altogether. For Blackshear, Bryker Woods and Travis Heights
elementary schools, the fewer tests counted in the system produced
higher ratings. AISD also attempted to change data at McCallum High
School, but the changes inadvertently were not reported to the
education agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin district called the testing company to find out why
the changes at McCallum weren't reported. The testing company
notified the TEA, and the agency _ already suspicious because of
1997 _ began asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It made us look,'' Moses said. ``We determined we were going
to ask questions about it, and we were going to ask for an
explanation.''
</P>
<P>
   That's when Austin interim Superintendent A.C. Gonzalez hired
consultant Lynn Moak for an independent audit.
</P>
<P>
   Moak concluded that the changes were intended to falsely
increase the ratings of the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Management established a perception that the only reason to
correct data was to achieve a ratings change,'' the report said.
``There was clearly a climate in which changes for the purpose of
changing a rating were understood to be an acceptable practice if
they stayed within the law, which is what they believed they were
doing,'' Moak said.
</P>
<P>
   The district and county attorneys' offices began investigating
the district after the Austin American-Statesman reported on the
TAAS controversy in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their zeal to produce the best ratings possible for the
Austin school district, several of our employees took liberties
with student data that was, at best, unprofessional,'' Gonzalez
said in September.
</P>
<P>
   On April 6, the grand jury found it was more than unprofessional
when it returned 16 indictments against the school district and one
16-count indictment against Psencik.
</P>
<P>
   Arredondo is scheduled for sentencing June 11 and faces up to a
year in jail and a fine of up to $4,000. No date has been set for
Psencik's court appearance. If convicted, she also could face a
year in jail and a fine of up to $4,000. The Austin school district
faces a fine of up to $160,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Jayson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail: sjayson(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
