<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-1STLD-WRI     04-13 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON MOVES TO RESTART TRADE NEGOTIATIONS WITH CHINA
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with Tuesday night's dinner at
Economic Club in New York, ADD fresh Zhu quote; Pickup 3rd graf
pvs, `They were happy ...'; Combines 2nd take, which has no
changes.) 
 (ac) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After coming under strong criticism that he backed
away from a trade deal with China because of domestic politics,
President Clinton telephoned China's prime minister Tuesday
afternoon to restart the negotiations in Beijing this month.
</P>
<P>
   The White House announced the effort as Prime Minister Zhu
Rongji, who has complained repeatedly about the failure to reach a
deal during his tour of the United States, was visiting New York
before heading to Canada. Zhu had spent much of his day lobbying
business executives about the benefits of an accord on trade.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner in New York on Tuesday night sponsored by the
Economic Club, Zhu said he had told Clinton during their phone call
that ``I feel very confident that in the near future we will see
the successful conclusion of negotiations that are favorable to
both sides _ but especially to the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's phone call to the Chinese leader followed a meeting on
Monday in which nearly two dozen business executives lobbied the
White House to emphasize how important the deal was to American
companies seeking access to the world's largest market.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were happy with the progress we made but were worried
that the deal would not come to fruition,'' an administration
official said. The official said that Clinton's telephone call,
which lasted about 20 minutes, was intended to send a signal to the
business community that the White House was doing all it could to
seal the deal and as a signal that it intended to lock China into
concessions it had made on numerous trade issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, the two countries said they would ``move
intensively'' to resolve the remaining issues that blocked them
from reaching a deal last week while Zhu met with Clinton in an
official three-day visit to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   China's entry into the World Trade Organization, the group that
determines the rules for global commerce, was the prize that Zhu
came seeking but was denied after talks collapsed at the last
minute. Some administration officials said that anti-China
sentiment on Capitol Hill was so intense that they thought they
could not get any deal through. At the same time, officials
familiar with the negotiations said, Clinton was distracted by the
Kosovo conflict and had not fully conveyed to his negotiators how
much he wanted to complete the deal himself.
</P>
<P>
   And some Democrats in Congress were leery of an accord with
China, predicting it would trigger a divisive battle in their
party.
</P>
<P>
   Zhu said during his visit here that he believed the deal fell
through because of domestic American politics and that Washington
had politicized what was essentially an economic issue. Republicans
on Capitol Hill have been furious over Clinton's policy of
engagement at a time when China has reportedly stolen military
secrets from the United States, is cracking down on political
dissidents and was accused of making illegal financial
contributions to Clinton's 1996 re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Trent Lott, the Republican leader, said last week during
Zhu's visit that he strongly opposed a deal and was suspicious of
whether China would commit to fair trade practices. The United
States has a $57 billion trade imbalance with China.
</P>
<P>
   China made several broad concessions last week in order to gain
entry to the trade organization, a step it has been working toward
for 13 years. Entry would require China to demolish its tariffs and
trade barriers but would give it broad access to the markets of
many other nations.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese concessions included allowing foreign companies to
sell their products directly to consumers, an enormous opportunity
in a land of 1.2 billion people. China also agreed to allow foreign
companies to invest as much as 49 percent in telecommunications
industries and to give greater access to foreign-owned insurance
companies. In a separate civil aviation deal, it agreed to allow
more flights from the United States. And it signed an accord to
lift restrictions on imports of U.S. wheat, citrus fruits and meat.
</P>
<P>
   But still outstanding were areas such as trade in financial
services and assurances that the United States could enforce its
agreements with China.
</P>
<P>
   After Zhu left Washington on Saturday, he criticized Clinton,
saying in cities across the United States that the president ``does
not dare'' take a political risk in allowing China to join the
trade organization. One senior official traveling with the prime
minister said, ``We had a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Clinton called Zhu, Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, said on Capitol Hill Tuesday that the president was
committed to seeing that negotiations would be finished in time for
China to join the WTO this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will re-engage with the Chinese shortly,'' she said in
testimony before the Senate Finance Committee, promising to ``work
on each of the issues that are open to bring this full agreement to
closure.''
</P>
<P>
   While some senators were hostile, others said they were worried
that the deal would unravel and that China would withdraw the
concessions it made last week. Zhu himself complained that the
administration had ``made public many documents and said we had
agreed to them, but in fact we have not agreed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, accused the administration of ``raw,
rotten protectionism'' at the behest of American textile and steel
companies, which are worried about the low price of Chinese
imports.
</P>
<P>
   He said the administration was trying to force China to keep
limits on textile exports to the United States for five years
longer than currently allowed under the trade organization's rules.
And he said that America's high barriers in this area had already
cost the average family of four $700 more in clothing bills each
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to lose more jobs by protecting noncompetitive
American industries than we are going to possibly gain in those
areas,'' Gramm said.
</P>
</TEXT>
