<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 23:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7001 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MACK-HNS &LR;      04-13 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-MACK-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Mack finds life's niche as a Rocket
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Sam Mack's thumb was still aching. He had missed the previous four
Rockets games after taking a hard fall in Dallas, absent-mindedly
using his right hand, his shooting hand, to cushion the impact.
</P>
<P>
   He had joined the Rockets in Utah and was giving himself a final
pre-game test, firing shot after shot until the sweat poured off
him and his thumb throbbed.
</P>
<P>
   He had reached the left corner, having circled the 3-point line
with shots. Taking passes from a Jazz ball boy, he had found his
touch. Shot after shot fell. Every motion was smooth, efficient, at
the same time workmanlike, like a carpenter hammering nails with
the practiced combination of work and art.
</P>
<P>
   He could have stopped, and probably should have. But each arc
was too true, the shots too sweet to leave that stroke
unappreciated by walking away. Finally, he turned and smiled and
announced his return to the Rockets' arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's changed,'' he said, and walked to the visitors'
locker room, the swagger of a gunslinger realized.
</P>
<P>
   When the Rockets reacquired Mack in a last-minute trade-deadline
deal for Rodrick Rhodes, ESPN didn't blink, newspapers reported the
news in small type on the pages that carry bowling scores and
soccer standings. In contrast to the signing of the Rockets' other
small forward, whose acquisition inspired the nation's basketball
media to encamp in Houston for however long it took to place a
`Scottie Pippen' on the bottom line, Mack's return to Houston was
barely noticed outside the Loop.
</P>
<P>
   When Pippen signed his five-year, $67 million contract, he
whisked around town in a stretch limousine with a police escort
befitting his place as one of the game's most celebrated champions.
With Mack, the Rockets picked up the last months of a Vancouver
contract and laid down the law, detailing the professionalism and
dedication that was expected in his second tour of duty with the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   Mack, 28, offered his deliverance from Vancouver to a
championship contender and to a city he had made his home, quickly
agreed. Six weeks later, it is unclear whether the Rockets or Mack
are happier with the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks he's in paradise,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question, no question,'' Mack replied. ``This is paradise
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   After Mack, who will play his former team tonight for the first
time since the trade, finished off the Timberwolves on Monday,
Tomjanovich and his assistants found themselves musing to one
another about their good fortune. They landed Mack almost as an
afterthought, then found themselves with a player who beyond his
role as a game-winner Monday, has become one of the keys to the
Rockets' chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coaches were just talking about how big that trade was for
us,'' Tomjanovich said. ``I love Michael (Dickerson) and Cuttino
(Mobley). But here's a guy that gives us a chance to rest the
rookies, a guy who had all that experience in Vancouver, and has
been out there. That experience is so valuable because he had to go
against front-line players starting those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he was gone, you've got to put a lot of those things in
the past, but we were thinking, `If that guy applied himself and
did it the right way, this is the best place to be for him.'''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the expected offensive lift off the bench, Mack
has provided protection for the nights the guards' shots are not
falling. He has even provided time for Pippen to reclaim his
offensive strut. Pippen has averaged just 8.8 points in April. But
in the five games since Mack's cameo upon his return in Utah, he
has averaged 10.5 off the bench, making 20 of 35 shots.
</P>
<P>
   Mack's 3-pointer with 1:17 left on Monday ended a fourth-quarter
Rockets collapse and gave them a win they had to have.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the shots they brought me here to make,'' Mack
said. ``The last couple of games, I've made my shots. Every time
they double or on a fast break, I can get open for my shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Mack always has been a shooter. His touch from the 3-point line
earned his initial escape from the Continental Basketball
Association to his shot with Rockets. But he and Rockets teammates
said that three seasons ago, he probably would not have made the
shot that would have shocked them had it missed in Minnesota on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' Mack said when asked if that shot would
have gone in during his first stint with the Rockets. ``By them
trading me away, I got out and had to prove myself. I had to work
hard to make things work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing in Vancouver, (opposing teams) did not have to double.
I had to get my own shots, and gain confidence. In Vancouver, I was
the first 3-point shooter there when they brought me in. They
needed my 3s at the end of games.''
</P>
<P>
   Said forward Othella Harrington, a Rockets teammate then and
now: ``When he was here the first time, he would miss shots with
the game on the line. Now, he's making the big shots. He's expanded
his game. He can put the ball on the floor and he's going to the
hole more. He's really playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Mack has fit perfectly into the Rockets' system,
but he has gone beyond simply making the shots earned by defenses'
obsession with Charles Barkley and Hakeem Olajuwon inside. He has
started with the 3s, but then built a well-rounded game around
them.
</P>
<P>
   Where Pippen must work to get shots off the dribble in the hope
a groove will enable him to make the 3-pointers always available in
the Rockets' offense, Mack has gotten on a roll outside, then used
that confidence and outside threat to broaden his offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was gone,'' Mack said, ``I worked on improving my
overall game, handling the ball, playing defense and making big
shots.''
</P>
<P>
   Because he has improved his overall game, he has been more than
the Rockets expected. But as happy as they are with his development
and play, it remains unclear whether the Rockets will be able to
bring him back next season.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets have 11 other players who will remain under contract
beyond this season (only Barkley and centers Antoine Carr and
Stanley Roberts signed one-year deals). If the Rockets want to do
any larger free-agent retooling, there is little flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Mack has improved so much, especially defensively, and has
so lived up to the criteria given him the day of the trade, the
Rockets seem likely to repeat the postgame conversation Tomjanovich
and his assistants shared Monday in Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   There is no question about Mack's interest in his future in a
Rockets uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know so many people in Houston. I have family there,
relatives there, I went to school and still have a lot of people
and business friends there,'' Mack said. ``There are so many things
I like to do there. That's where I want to live.''
</P>
<P>
   But for now, every night is another chance to fill whatever need
arises, another circle of open 3-pointers to swish. In that sense,
nothing has changed. For now, every night is another day in
``paradise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
