<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERVITE LINEMAN COMMITS TO USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ USC received an oral commitment from offensive
lineman Joe McGuire of Servite High in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire (6-foot-6, 275 pounds), considered one of the top
juniors in the state, is the second prep player to commit to the
Trojans in recent weeks. Quarterback Matt Cassel of Chatsworth
previously committed to USC.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard has surgery: As expected, sophomore linebacker Mike
Pollard underwent knee surgery Monday for a torn anterior cruciate
ligament in his left knee and will be lost for the season.
</P>
<P>
   Pollard will redshirt this season and have three years of
eligibility remaining.
</P>
<P>
   In the middle: With Pollard out, USC's depth at middle
linebacker has suddenly become an issue. USC coach Paul Hackett
said freshman Armand Holland would probably be the current No. 2
linebacker behind starter Zeke Moreno. Holland redshirted last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is John Fox. After starting at quarterback, moving to
tight end and returning to quarterback last season, Fox is now at
middle linebacker and had five tackles in Saturday's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was OK,'' Fox said. ``Those tackles weren't all by myself. I
should have been on a lot more plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox said he is more comfortable now than at any other time in
the past year, finally settling in at a position. But his days at
quarterback may not be over.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Fox is USC's emergency No. 3 quarterback, now that
Jason Thomas has decided to transfer.
</P>
<P>
   And on the outside: With Sultan Abdul-Malik moving to outside
linebacker, there is some curiosity about where Long Beach City
College linebacker Markus Steele will end up when he arrives this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Steele was rated the No. 1 JC linebacker in the country by most
recruiting services, and it's expected he'll start. But where?
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Abdul-Malik and sophomore Darryl Knight are the
starting outside linebackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really counting on him,'' Hackett said of Steele. ``I
think he's going to battle with whoever comes out of spring. I
think he's a tremendous athlete. He's tall and lean.''
</P>
<P>
   Hackett said Steele would not be moved to middle linebacker to
compensate for the loss of Pollard.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to compromise his career,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Fulmer calls: Tennessee coach Phil Fulmer called Hackett to
inquire about Thomas. Tennessee, Nebraska and Nevada-Las Vegas are
among the schools vying for Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Split-back formation: Malaefou MacKenzie participated in drills
for the first time Tuesday since undergoing knee surgery last
September. Hackett said he envisions MacKenzie, Jabari Jackson and
Frank Strong playing in split-back formations next season.
</P>
<P>
   That means they might line up along with Chad Morton, but would
not be considered fullbacks. Hackett said MacKenzie is strictly a
tailback.
</P>
<P>
   That means junior Brennan Ochs, sophomore Charlie Landrigan and
freshman Chad Pierson will try to win the fullback position.
</P>
<P>
   Perry nears decision: Former USC wide receiver Rod Perry is
expected to make a decision this week on where he will play
football next season. Perry, who quit the Cal State Fullerton
baseball team last month, is considering USC, UNLV, Penn State and
Wisconsin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
