<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7098 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VW-AD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-13 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VW-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: A VOLKSWAGEN SPOT HAS TWO PUNCH LINES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   An unconventional commercial for the Volkswagen Passat, with a
twisty plot that curves more than a rain-slicked highway in a
traditional automotive spot, has people talking _ and buying, too.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial, which began running in January, returned to
television this month. The 30-second spot, titled ``Brief
Encounter,'' tells the tale of a man engaged in a pastime that is
almost as old as the internal combustion engine: flirting with a
woman whose car, identical to his, is momentarily stopped next to
him at a traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   But in this instance, the commercial, created by Arnold
Communications in Boston, takes not one but two surprising turns,
for the drivers are not who they seem. The one-two punch lines are
a key reason for the continuing appeal of the spot among both
viewers and car buyers.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial for Passat, a family sedan that was recently
redesigned, is indicative of the efforts being made by the big
automakers and their agencies to walk the fine line between the
hard and soft sells. The goal is to strike the right balance
between advertising that entertains but also moves the iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's worked for us is creating a great brand image that
makes people really want to check out our cars,'' said Liz Vanzura,
director for marketing and advertising at Volkswagen of America in
Auburn Hills, Mich., a unit of the German automaker Volkswagen AG.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to ``create an image or vibe around the car,'' she
added, ``and let the car sell itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkswagen of America is increasing its 1999 sales projections
for Passat by 14.3 percent, to 80,000 from 70,000. March was the
best month ever for Passat as sales totaled 5,782, up 80.8 percent
from March 1998. Sales for the first quarter totaled 13,239, up
55.9 percent from the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Passat contributed to a strong month and
quarter for Volkswagen of America, which sold 26,488 cars in March,
up 52.1 percent from March 1998, and 63,525 cars in the first three
months of 1999, up 60.6 percent from the period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The designation last month of Passat as the ``best family
sedan'' in the annual automotive issue of Consumer Reports will
obviously help sales. But so does the advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think of our ads as a little more cerebral, a
little more intuitive,'' Ms. Vanzura said, ``showing the people who
drive the cars.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We take our cars seriously,'' she added, ``but we don't take
ourselves too seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Other examples of that approach include a 1997 commercial for
the Volkswagen Golf, which featured two 20-something people
aimlessly driving around to a tune called ``Da Da Da,'' and a
recent spot for the Volkswagen Jetta, known as ``Synchronicity,''
in which a stylish couple cruising the streets of New Orleans
notice that passers-by are moving to the beat of the rhythmic song
playing on their cassette deck.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Clio Awards organization, part of VNU NV, will name
Volkswagen advertiser of the year, for campaigns for the last three
years in five countries including Arnold's work in the United
States. The award will be presented at the annual Clios ceremonies
in New York, scheduled for May 19 and 20.
</P>
<P>
   The Passat commercial begins as the man and the woman drive up
to the traffic light in matching Passats. They exchange flirtatious
glances, seemingly encouraged by the music on the soundtrack, a
tango titled ``Palomita Blanca.''
</P>
<P>
   Then the first punch line comes. A toy octopus hits the man,
interrupting his amorous reverie. The camera cuts to the back seat
of his car, where a child is seated. The man drives away with a
sheepish expression.
</P>
<P>
   The woman is seen smiling as she drives away. Then the second
punch line comes. The camera cuts to show that she, too, has a
child in her car.
</P>
<P>
   ``You realize both of them actually have kids,'' Ms. Vanzura
said. ``You may not catch that the first time you see the spot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our advertising is meant to be seen over and over again,'' she
added. ``And every time you see it, you'll notice something more.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise of the commercial is intended to ring a bell among
members of the target market for Passat, drivers in their 30s and
40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a car for people who haven't stopped living, who aren't
ready for minivans, who've still got it going on a little bit,''
said Ron Lawner, managing partner and chief creative officer at
Arnold, a unit of Snyder Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's easy for them to relate,'' he added, ``to the idea of
an innocent glance at someone who's driving the same car you are.''
</P>
<P>
   While the commercial could be read as the title suggests _
``Brief Encounter'' is the 1946 film about an affair between a
couple who part at the end _ it could also be interpreted in a more
contemporary way.
</P>
<P>
   What if the man and woman at the traffic light are both single
parents, free to go beyond flirtation?
</P>
<P>
   ``They could be single parents,'' Lawner replied when that was
suggested to him. ``Who could say?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we need to see them again,'' he added, chuckling.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vanzura said: ``They could be single parents. We kind of
leave that to your imagination. They could even be married to each
other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
