<SLUG> BC-CISCO-GEOTEL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CISCO, ERICSSON AND NORTEL MAKE DEALS TO EXPAND REACH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass., Md.)   (rk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The worlds of cyberspace and traditional telecommunications
continued their clash Tuesday as the leading maker of
data-networking equipment announced a $2 billion acquisition to
expand into telephone software while two of the biggest makers of
traditional phone systems said they would acquire private
data-networking companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the morning, Cisco Systems Inc., the No. 1 maker of the
equipment that forms the synapses of the Internet, said that it had
agreed to buy the Geotel Communications Corp., which makes software
for telemarketers and customer-service call centers, for $2 billion
in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ericsson of Sweden, the maker of cellular phones and
both wireless and traditional telephone networks, said it had
agreed to acquire the Torrent Networking Technologies Corp., a
private maker of advanced data switches based in Silver Spring,
Md., for $450 million in cash. Ericsson also agreed to acquire
Touchwave Inc., a private developer of telephones that use Internet
technology based in Palo Alto, Calif., for $46 million in cash.
</P>
<P>
   After major financial markets closed, Northern Telecom of
Canada, the No. 2 maker of traditional telephone gear in North
America after Lucent Technologies Inc., said that it had agreed to
acquire Shasta Networks Inc., a private data-networking company
based in Sunnyvale, Calif., for about $340 million in stock and
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's four deals were the latest salvos in a battle that is
sure to pit young networking companies reared on the Internet
against decades-old telephone giants for years to come. As the
technical barriers between voice communications and data have begun
to fade, so too have the business barriers separating the two
industries.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco has been one of the key drivers of the convergence between
the voice and data-networking industries. Having basically defeated
its main initial rivals in data networking _ Bay Networks and 3Com
_ Cisco, along with Ascend Communications, became a leader in
selling data-networking equipment to traditional telephone
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Ascend has agreed to be acquired by Lucent for about
$20 billion, Cisco has become perhaps even more aggressive in
trying to win business away from the old-line communications
equipment makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that an Old World provider provides to this customer
base, we think it's important to provide a New World version of
that,'' said Donald J. Listwin, a Cisco executive vice president,
using the company's jargon for traditional communications and
Internet-based systems. ``The key issues that we have not delivered
to our customers yet are messaging technology and call center
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   Geotel will help with that. Geotel, based in Lowell, Mass.,
makes software that helps distribute calls among corporate
operators and helps keep telemarketers operating at peak
efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco agreed to trade 0.5138 of its shares for each share of
Geotel. Based on Cisco's closing price of $117.75 on Monday, that
represents a 36 percent premium over Geotel's closing price of
$44.25.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco was advised by Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. Geotel was advised by
Dain Rauscher Wessels.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Cisco tries to extend its reach into telephone
systems, the traditional telecommunications manufacturers are
trying to expand their capabilities with Internet technology.
Nortel, for instance, hopes that Shasta's technology will allow it
to deliver reliable and flexible services to business customers
using Internet systems rather than older technologies. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
