<SLUG> BC-NJ-ORANGE-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TWISTING HUNT FOR AN OFFICER'S KILLER 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By N.R. KLEINFIELD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pursuit of the killer of an Orange, N.J., police officer, a
case that at first seemed so linear and logical, has evolved into a
perplexing tangle of events that are billowing to transform the
matter into something well beyond the death of an officer in a city
where police officers do not get killed.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than resolution, three arrests have produced riddles and
unanswered questions, charges and countercharges. Even some of the
police officers immersed in the case are wondering: Do they have
the right man? How many men are they really after?
</P>
<P>
   So many questions lingered Tuesday because officials involved in
the investigation were not willing to provide even some of the most
rudimentary answers about what happened when and why.
</P>
<P>
   What is clear is that three men were brought into custody over
the weekend, either directly or indirectly because of the quest for
the killer. One of the men died an hour after being arrested. Law
enforcement officials, who said the man was not a suspect in the
killing, suggested Tuesday that he suffered an asthma attack. His
father contended that he was beaten to death by the police, even
though an initial examination by the Medical Examiner's office
found no evidence of a beating.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, the only one of the three who has been charged with
the crime, showed up in court with a bruised eye. No officials
would comment on how it happened. The third man was charged with
drug possession, but some police officers said he may have been
involved in the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   The series of events unfolded quickly. Officer Joyce Anne
Carnegie, 38, of the 113-member Orange police force, was shot to
death last Thursday evening when she got out of her squad car to
question a man who fit the description of someone who committed
armed robbery nearby. One Orange police officer said Officer
Carnegie was first shot in the stomach and, while on the ground
clutching the gunman's foot, was shot a second time point-blank in
the head.
</P>
<P>
   She was the first officer killed in the line of duty in 33 years
in Orange, a pinpoint of a town of 29,000 people just northwest of
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Carnegie's death prompted a manhunt by dozens of
investigators from the Orange police, the Essex County prosecutor's
office and the Newark police, and it produced quick results.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, police found Terrance Everett, 24, at a
well-kept white stucco house he shares with his mother in East
Orange. There was a late-model pearl-colored Cadillac El Dorado
parked in front of an old sedan in the driveway. Two girls who
lived nearby said that Everett drove a red two-door car of a make
they could not identify. Authorities said that Officer Carnegie's
killer fled in a 1986 blue Honda Accord.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities have not said why they homed in on Everett. He
was charged with robbery and weapons possession in addition to the
murder charge.
</P>
<P>
   Raids as part of the hunt for Officer Carnegie's killer
continued Sunday, though it unclear why, if investigators believed
that they had found the killer.
</P>
<P>
   Two more men were arrested Sunday night. James (Malik) Coker,
29, of Newark, was taken into custody at the Douglass-Harrison
Homes, where he was visiting his aunt. Police charged him with
possession of crack and with trying to swallow the drugs when
officers came to the apartment. It is not known what led
investigators to Coker, and he has not been formally linked to the
shooting.
</P>
<P>
   But one Orange police officer said that he and some colleagues
were unconvinced that Everett was the killer and were looking hard
at Coker. Essex County Prosecutor Patricia Hurt refused to answer
questions about the case Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The most bizarre twist in the case involved Earl Faison.
According to investigators, the 27-year-old Faison inadvertently
came to their attention Sunday night when he was hailing a cab at
South Day Street and Freeway Drive West, a block from where Officer
Carnegie was shot. Feeling he bore a resemblance to a composite
police sketch of the killer, authorities said, officers working the
area approached him. A police officer said Faison ran and was
chased for three blocks before he was caught. When he was frisked,
officials said, they found a semiautomatic gun, and they arrested
him on gun possession charges.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Essex County prosecutor's office, Faison
collapsed and died an hour later as he walked into the warrant room
at Orange police headquarters. The prosecutor's office said Tuesday
that the Medical Examiner's office had been unable to determine the
cause of death and was doing further tests. But officials said the
medical examiner ruled out blunt force trauma as a possible cause
and found no evidence of kicking, beating or strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   A law enforcement official said Faison had an asthma attack at
the police station, which can be fatal if not treated quickly. Earl
Williams, Faison's father, confirmed his son had asthma but said he
had never suffered a seizure and the condition was under control.
Faison's girlfriend, who did not want to give her name, said he did
not have a regular doctor but took medication and occasionally went
to the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   Williams said that he went to the morgue Monday but was not
allowed to see his son's body. Instead, he was shown a picture of
him. ``From the moment I saw the picture, I knew he was beaten to
death,'' he said. ``He was beaten very badly. It looked like he was
dragged by a truck.'' Williams said there were multiple cuts and
bruises on his face, and his face was swollen.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Weiss, a spokesman for Ms. Hurt, would not comment on the
case beyond saying that the investigation is continuing. First
Assistant Essex County Prosecutor Patrick Toscano said, ``It is my
understanding that the Orange police officers did nothing wrong in
this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   According to his girlfriend, Faison was on probation and had
served 10 months in jail before being released in June. She said
she did not know why he had gone to jail or whether he owned a gun.
She said he was with her on the night the officer was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Faison was an aspiring rap singer, according to his sister,
Kytria Faison. And over the weekend, relatives said, he took a bus
to Virginia with another rap group, Naughty By Nature. He returned
Sunday afternoon, they said, and spent the rest of the day moving
his studio equipment from his aunt's house in Newark to his
girlfriend's house in Orange. He was leaving his girlfriend's
house, getting into a cab, she said, when police approached him.
</P>
<P>
   Little was immediately known about Coker. Ursula Scott, 37, the
aunt he was visiting when he was arrested, said he was unemployed,
but she did not know where he was living or much else about him.
She said he did look like the sketch of the killer. ``He did say,
because he had a bald head and some weight, he was afraid to go out
on the street,'' Ms. Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   When Everett, the man charged in the killing, appeared in court
on Monday and pleaded not guilty, he had a blackened left eye.
Raymond Hamlin, his lawyer, told the judge that his client had
incurred facial bruises since he was arrested, though he did not
accuse the police of inflicting them. Later, he told reporters that
he could establish that Everett was elsewhere at the time Officer
Carnegie was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt has indicated that she had four people who have
identified Everett. Like so many other things in this twisting
case, it is not known who they are and what they identified him for
_ robbing someone or killing a police officer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2315EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
