u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SLUG-NYT &LR;      04-13 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLUG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELL ATLANTIC SAYS ITS NETWORK IS FULLY OPEN TO COMPETITION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Continuing its long march toward the $80 billion long-distance
market, the Bell Atlantic Corp., the nation's biggest local
telephone company, told New York state regulators Tuesday that it
had fully opened its network to competition.
</P>
<P>
   While Bell Atlantic, along with other Bells, routinely describes
its markets as open in informal contexts, Tuesday's filing with the
New York Public Service Commission formally signaled the last
chapter in negotiations and testing that began last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the New York commission and the Justice Department
said they would support Bell Atlantic's long-distance goals if the
company complied with a highly technical plan to prove that its
local network was open to competitors.
</P>
<P>
   KPMG Peat Marwick, the consulting firm, has tested Bell
Atlantic's computer systems to determine if they work easily with
its competitors'. Such compatibility is important to ensure that a
customer can switch local phone companies quickly and without
glitches.
</P>
<P>
   Draft reports from KPMG in recent weeks have said that Bell
Atlantic passed more than 90 percent of the tests, but that it
failed as many as 50 specific exercises, according to executives
with access to the reports. Bell Atlantic must fix those problems
by late May or early June, when the New York commission is likely
to hold its final hearing.
</P>
<P>
   If Bell Atlantic has accurately judged its progress, and if it
convinces the New York regulators, this fall Bell Atlantic could
become the first local Bell phone company admitted into the
long-distance business. To get there, Bell Atlantic would also have
to pass a three-month review by the Federal Communications
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Executives close to Bell Atlantic said Tuesday that a
long-distance petition to the federal regulators would come perhaps
two weeks after the New York commission signed off on the
application.
</P>
<P>
   That would be about a year later than Bell Atlantic originally
predicted. Last spring, the company said it expected to be in the
long-distance market by the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it does not appear that any other Bell company is close
to winning long-distance approval. Bell Atlantic has followed an
extremely cautious approach, delaying applying to the FCC until it
believes that the petition will succeed.
</P>
<P>
   After this apparently rigorous process, when the company finally
applies, the FCC will come under enormous pressure to approve the
petition.
</P>
<P>
   The BellSouth Corp., in contrast, has filed numerous
applications with the FCC that few people in the industry outside
of BellSouth thought had any chance of success. All have been
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, the Justice Department only advises the FCC on
long-distance applications, but in practice the two sides rarely
differ. The Justice Department, meanwhile, has been working closely
with the New York state regulators.
</P>
<P>
   While it would not be fair to view the New York commission as a
functional proxy for the Justice Department, it is unlikely that
the state regulators would approve a petition that the Justice
Department might reasonably reject. Such a conflict would be highly
embarrassing for the New York commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
