<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7111 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN--GIANTS-HNS &LR;      04-13 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--GIANTS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Quiet Giants remain NL West threat
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN FRANCISCO _ The Los Angeles Dodgers opened their checkbook this
offseason, signing baseball's first $100 million player and staking
a claim as the team to beat in the National League West.
</P>
<P>
   Eager to shed its expansion label, Arizona joined the spending
spree and landed free-agent pitcher Randy Johnson, among others.
Colorado added one of baseball's best managerial masterminds with
the hiring of Jim Leyland.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the San Francisco Giants, with the lowest
payroll in the five-team NL West at $45 million, remained
relatively quiet this winter. Guess who is near the top of the
standings after the first week of the season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Money helps,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ``Money
doesn't always prevail.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants might not need much of the green stuff. Armed with an
explosive offense, a solid pitching staff and the guidance of
Baker, there is no reason to believe the Giants can't contend for a
division title. Heading into Tuesday's late game with the Astros at
3Com Park, San Francisco (6-1) was off to its best start since
1973.
</P>
<P>
   Not bad for a team picked to finish as low as fourth in several
preseason publications.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole offseason, with all the signings in our division,
it's going to be like the last two years,'' first baseman J.T. Snow
said. ``We'll be in the background. We'll be overlooked. Maybe
that's the best way to go into the season. That's the way it went
the last few years. I think the guys are confident we can be there
at the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, the Giants were the laughingstock of the NL
West, finishing last at 68-94. Since that disaster, the Giants
quietly have established themselves as one of the top teams in
baseball, winning the division in 1997 and coming within a one-game
playoff of the NL wild card last year.
</P>
<P>
   Only three teams _ the New York Yankees, Atlanta Braves and
Astros _ have had more success than the Giants' 179-146 record the
past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   A major part of the Giants' resurgence is Baker, who took the
job in 1993 with no managerial experience. Baker has twice won NL
Manager of the Year honors.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be a club that has to be reckoned with,''
Leyland said. ``When you have Dusty Baker and the caliber of
players he has, they go quietly about their business, but they've
become as professional as any team in the league the last couple of
years. Dusty gets the most out of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've got Dusty Baker, they're going to be in the hunt.
You can take that to the bank.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on this winter's transactions in the NL West, it would
appear the Giants did nothing to help themselves while several of
the other clubs made considerable improvements. The Dodgers made
the most noise with the signing of pitcher Kevin Brown to the
richest contract in baseball history. Along with Johnson, the
Arizona Diamondbacks spent close to $100 million alone on pitching,
adding Todd Stottlemyre, Armando Reynoso and Greg Swindell.
</P>
<P>
   Defending NL champion San Diego actually got worse, saying
goodbye to many of the players that helped the Padres get to the
World Series _ Brown, Greg Vaughn, Ken Caminiti, Steve Finley and
Joey Hamilton among them.
</P>
<P>
   But Padres general manager Kevin Towers isn't ready to anoint
the Dodgers as division champions just yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because a team like the Dodgers spends more money, it
doesn't mean they're going to be a better club,'' Towers said. ``It
just means the Padres and Giants need to be a little wiser. I'll
say it right now, and I'll go on record with it, that either the
Giants or the Padres will finish in front of the Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Giants are to contend, they will do so with the same cast
of characters that has stayed intact the past three years. San
Francisco's biggest moves this offseason were spending $15 million
to keep right fielder Ellis Burks and pitcher Mark Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants feature an explosive offense led by sluggers Barry
Bonds, Jeff Kent and Burks. Offensively, Bonds and Kent combined
for 68 home runs and 250 RBIs last season. Shortstop Rich Aurilia
is off to a sizzling start, batting .467 with one home run and
seven RBIs through seven games; center fielder Stan Javier has
three home runs.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of firepower has the Giants believing they can win any
time. During a season-opening sweep at Cincinnati, San Francisco
rallied on three consecutive days, including overturning a six-run
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe from the bottom of my heart that this is supposed to
be our year,'' Baker said. ``No explanation. I just feel it. I just
think we've got things going in our favor.''
</P>
<P>
   In the rotation, Gardner, Shawn Estes and Kirk Reuter are a
formidable threesome, along with second-year pitcher Russ Ortiz.
Estes is the biggest question mark in the rotation. After becoming
a 19-game winner in 1997, he struggled to seven victories last
year.
</P>
<P>
   As for the bullpen, All-Star Robb Nen became only the second
Giants closer to save at least 40 games in a season.
</P>
<P>
   After coming so close to making the playoffs last season, the
Giants have unfinished business in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players who were here last year have an unsatisfied
feeling,'' Kent said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
