<HEADER>
A7115 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1STL     04-13 1234
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MACEDONIA-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVEN FROM KOSOVO, ALBANIANS STREAM INTO MACEDONIA AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 
(SUBS to insert new 4th, 5th, 8th, 11th and 12th grafs. Some
rewriting in rest of story.)  (ART ADV: Map and photo are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ac) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STENKOVAC, Macedonia _ In the week since President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia announced that he had halted offensive
military operations in Kosovo, Serbian paramilitary groups and
Yugoslav soldiers have systematically expelled tens of thousands of
Albanians from a swath of southeastern Kosovo, according to
refugees arriving here Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees, among a group of 800 Kosovo Albanians allowed to
cross the border near here, described methodical attacks by
Milosevic's forces that cleared out a 10-mile-by-12-mile area that
appears to have little military value.
</P>
<P>
   In each account, Serbian paramilitary units or Yugoslav soldiers
were said to have expelled civilians and burned or shelled homes in
at least 15 villages around the town of Urosevac, in southeastern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   With access to Kosovo limited by the Yugoslav government, the
accounts could not be confirmed. Each refugee was interviewed
individually about personal experiences. A comparison of their
accounts indicated the pattern of alleged Yugoslav attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Western officials fear the actions signal a continuing attempt
by Yugoslavia to shift the ethnic balance in Kosovo; before the
NATO bombing began, on March 24, Albanians made up 90 percent of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   The diplomats said the rural area the refugees have described as
the focus of the attacks has not been a base of operations for the
Kosovo Liberation Army, the guerrilla group fighting for
independence. It is not close to the border, and the villages
cleared are miles from the major roads, making it unlikely that the
area was cleared for military reasons, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees described well-organized attacks in which masked
Yugoslav soldiers descended on an Albanian village, ordered
everyone to leave, then shot or burned to death the defiant, infirm
or aged who stayed in their homes. It was impossible to determine
how many Albanians were forced from their homes, but about 50,000
people lived in the area before the bombing began.
</P>
<P>
   Although hundreds of thousands of Kosovo Albanians have been
sent fleeing into Albania, Macedonia and Montenegro since the
bombing started, few people had been forced out of Urosevac.
Yugoslav forces essentially sealed the border with Macedonia last
week, but on Friday refugees began to straggle across again, saying
that thousands of villagers had been forced into the city. On
Friday, about 400 refugees arrived from the area, and the number
increased to about 800 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Ghedini, a spokeswoman for the U.N. high commissioner for
refugees, said the renewed flow could signal that vast numbers more
may soon try to flee Kosovo. ``It does sound very clear from the
refugees that there is a much larger number of people who want to
come in,'' she said. ``But we never know what to expect. The last
time, it was 40,000 people in 24 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews with about two dozen of the refugees arriving
Tuesday, they described methodical attacks by Yugoslav forces and
paramilitary units to expel civilians.
</P>
<P>
   During the war in Bosnia, similar groups were accused of
systematic efforts to move Muslim civilians from areas controlled
by Serbs, including rape, torture and looting.
</P>
<P>
   All of the refugees said they ended up fleeing to Urosevac after
the village attacks, and believe they were intentionally driven
into the town. They said thousands of other ethnic Albanians are
hiding in Urosevac and the surrounding hills, and are running out
of food. The refugees all used the Albanian names for their
villages.
</P>
<P>
   Luzlim Shala, a 28-year-old teacher who arrived Tuesday, said
Yugoslav army soldiers in armored personnel carriers descended last
Monday on his village, Mirash. Nestled at the base of a 2,500-foot
mountain, the quiet farming village of 1,000 people is five miles
from the main road through the area. The soldiers ordered all
civilians out of their homes and burned some homes before
departing, the teacher said.
</P>
<P>
   That same day, Yugoslav soldiers arrived in Prelez i Jerlive, on
the main road north of Urosevac, said Fadil Zeqir, a 32-year-old
agricultural engineer. The town's 300 families were told they had
20 minutes to leave, he said. Residents scurried into the
surrounding hills and no homes were burned.
</P>
<P>
   The following day, Tuesday, two adjacent villages five miles
southeast of Urosevac were attacked by paramilitaries, the refugees
said. Sami Tahiri, a 61-year-old retired teacher, said regular
Yugoslav army soldiers first came to his village, Sojeve, and
warned the 230 families over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Tuesday, Serbian paramilitary soldiers in black masks
roared into the village in jeeps. Most of the villagers fled into
the hills, but two young men were captured, an Albanian and a
Muslim who had fled the war in Bosnia. Both were killed, he said,
and an elderly couple were burned alive in their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who stayed were killed,'' Tahiri said.
</P>
<P>
   As the Albanians watched from surrounding hills, the
paramilitaries set fire to two-thirds of the homes in the village,
he said. That same day, he added, houses in Terstenik, a nearby
village, were also set on fire.
</P>
<P>
   The following morning, Wednesday, Yugoslav forces shelled the
Albanian village of Preshtine, which lies five miles in the
opposite direction of Urosevac, to the west. Jonuz Bytyqi, a high
school teacher from Urosevac who had fled to the area after NATO
bombing began, said he woke to the sound of explosions.
</P>
<P>
   Six shells hit Preshtina, he said; no one was injured. But 30
shells fired on an adjacent village, Zaskok, killed at least four
people, refugees said. Residents of both villages fled immediately
after the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the shells hit a tractor near where I was,'' Bytyqi
said. ``I couldn't sleep at all after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that day, Serbian paramilitary units carried out a
separate attack on Varosh, on the main road three miles south of
Urosevac, refugees said. Zeqir, who was sleeping in a nearby field
after fleeing the earlier attack on his village, said one young man
who refused to leave his home was killed.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing the pattern of attacks on Thursday, Yugoslav forces
shelled and then burned Zlatar, seven miles west of Urosevac, said
Shala, who fled the village with his wife and two young daughters.
This attack was the farthest from the city.
</P>
<P>
   Shala said he and his family then fled to Mirosale, but that
village was attacked over the weekend, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a surreal end to their cat-and-mouse game with Yugoslav
forces, the refugees said they were allowed simply to buy a $20
train ticket in Urosevac on Monday morning and ride in a packed
train to the border. Many Serb-run stores refused to sell food to
them before they left.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot stand it psychologically,'' Bytyqi said. ``For 21
days, I never knew what was going to happen next. I promised myself
I would not leave. But my daughter lost ten pounds from the tension
and I have two sons. I came here for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
