<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0429 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7119 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-5     04-13 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-GRETZKY-540(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GREAT GRETZKY RETIREMENT WATCH BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Late last week, as speculation increased about his
possible retirement, Wayne Gretzky said that ``I don't want to be
the center of attention,'' and that John Muckler, the Rangers'
coach, would be the first to know of Gretzky's decision.
</P>
<P>
   As to whether Rangers management would be willing to pick up his
$5 million contract option for next season, Gretzky said, ``I don't
think either one of us wants to embarrass the other side. So,
that's not a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, Gretzky had made no definitive public statement
regarding retirement. Although the Rangers announced that they want
him back and would pick up his contract option, the news media were
filled with speculation that Gretzky would soon announce the end of
his great career, perhaps this week, as the NHL completes its
regular season and prepares for the Stanley Cup playoffs without
Gretzky's Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The most definitive statement of the day came from Gretzky's
father, Walter. According to The Associated Press, he told radio
station CKGL in Kitchener, Ontario, that he strongly suspected that
Sunday would be his son's final game. The Rangers end the regular
season that day against Pittsburgh at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't talked to him personally,'' Walter Gretzky said of
his son. ``He's talked with his mom, but most likely he will
announce a retirement. He's 38 now.''
</P>
<P>
   So as the Rangers prepared to play in Ottawa Thursday night
Gretzky was indeed the center of attention he didn't want to be.
And if Walter Gretzky sounded pretty certain of how his son was
leaning, Muckler, who was supposed to be the first to know, didn't
seem so sure if Gretzky's 20th season in the NHL and his 21st as a
professional, would be his last.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not mentioned a word to me,'' Muckler said in a
telephone interview. ``And I have not mentioned a word to him
because I just didn't think it was proper. We just want to let him
get through this year and then let him make the decision he will
make.''
</P>
<P>
   When he was asked if he had a gut feeling about Gretzky's plans,
Muckler replied: ``I still think he's going to come back. That's
still my opinion. Maybe that's wishful thinking on my part, I don't
know, because I'd like to see him back.''
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to Gretzky and to his agent, Michael Barnett,
were not returned Tuesday. On Monday night, after a 2-1 Rangers
victory over Tampa Bay at the Garden, Gretzky said of retirement
speculation: ``It's become a hot topic. We'll see what happens over
the next five or six days. Nothing has been decided.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Neil Smith, the general manager of the Rangers, said
Tuesday that the Rangers, in writing, would offer Gretzky a
contract extension this week for next season.
</P>
<P>
   Will Gretzky accept the offer?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm leaving that up to him to make his own personal
decision,'' Smith said. ``He has not informed the club.'' Smith
said that he had placed a call to Gretzky Tuesday ``to have a
personal conversation about the issue'' but that Gretzky had not
returned it by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to have him back,'' Smith said. ``To formalize it and
put it so that it is a legal thing, that will say more than all my
words can say. We're making the declaration that, yes, we are
taking up the option.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Should Gretzky retire, his departure would come within a year of
Michael Jordan's retirement from the Chicago Bulls of the NBA.
Although Gretzky's hockey career began when Magic Johnson and Larry
Bird started their careers in basketball, it is Jordan to whom
Gretzky is most often compared as a singular icon of a sport and an
era.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky began his career with one season in the defunct World
Hockey Association, 1978-79. In both major leagues combined, he has
scored 1,072 goals, regular season and playoffs, one more than
Gordie Howe. No player has scored more.
</P>
<P>
   Howe, Gretzky and Bobby Orr are generally considered to be the
three best players in the history of their sport and Gretzky holds
most of the scoring records of significance in the N.H.L.,
including 894 regular-season goals, 1,962 regular-season assists
and 2,856 regular-season points.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are Gretzky's fourth team in the NHL and this is his
third season here. In his first nine seasons in the league, he
played with the Edmonton Oilers, who won the Stanley Cup four times
while he was there and one time after he left. In 1981-82, Gretzky
scored 92 goals, the most ever of any player in a single season. In
1985-86, he scored 215 points, goals and assists combined, the most
ever by any player.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he has only nine goals, along with 52 assists. He
missed 12 games with a disk injury in his neck, the first games he
missed as a Ranger. During his absence, the Rangers went 6-3-3 and
played with considerable spirit. In the plus/minus ratio that
measures a player's presence on ice for goals scored for or against
his team at even strength, Gretzky is minus 23, the worst on the
Rangers and among the worst in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Through most of this season, both Gretzky and Smith said they
expected Gretzky to return for 1999-2000. But certain events have
indicated that it was not such a sure thing. Despite Gretzky's wish
for more veteran players to take advantage of his setup passes from
the center position, Smith made no major trades for scoring wings.
</P>
<P>
   And when Gretzky suggested in February that the Rangers bid for
veteran free agents this summer, Smith reiterated, in a general way
that wasn't critical of Gretzky, that the Rangers are committed to
rebuilding with youth.
</P>
<P>
   For most of his career, Gretzky, although smaller than most
hockey players, has been more agile than fragile, able to avoid the
hardest collisions from opposing checkers. But this season, Gretzky
has been hit hard many times and often has left the ice wincing in
pain.
</P>
<P>
   On some of Gretzky's teams, especially in early stages of his
career, such disrespect would have been met with retaliation by
Gretzky's teammates. In Philadelphia last week, with this team,
there was no response when Luke Richardson flattened him along the
boards, except for Gretzky's compliment to Richardson. ``I told
him, `Good hit,''' Gretzky said. ``I was vulnerable. He got me
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mark Messier played for the Rangers, his teammates would
retaliate vigorously when opponents even jostled him legally, even
though Messier was big and tough on his own. Although his Rangers
teammates always speak of Gretzky with respect and admiration, he
has never had Messier-like stature on the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As speculation about retirement has grown through the season,
fans and players, especially on the road, have paid tribute to
Gretzky, particularly in the second half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In Calgary, Gretzky said the cheering left him with tears in his
eyes. In Chicago last Thursday night, when the scoreboard showed
highlights of Gretzky's career, the fans stood and applauded while
players from both teams tapped their sticks on the ice in tribute.
Gretzky smiled and waved from the bench. After the game, his father
and his wife, Janet, were there to greet him, not an every-game
scene, especially on the road.
</P>
<P>
   In Dallas the next night, Gretzky was walking down a corridor
after the game when he was stopped by Brett Hull, the Stars'
sharpshooter, who put his arm around his shoulders and shook his
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Gretzky has been saving sticks and pucks from most of his games
this season and giving them as mementos to people close to him. An
extra-large contingent of reporters is expected Thursday night when
he plays in the Canadian capital, in a country where he is a
national hero. And then comes Sunday's final game, in the Garden,
where his stature over the last three years has never quite reached
that level. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
