<SLUG> BC-SKATE-SEX-SCANDAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX MISCONDUCT GRIEVANCE FILED AGAINST SKATING COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Craig Maurizi, who has accused his former coach and colleague,
Richard Callaghan, of sexual misconduct, filed a formal grievance
Tuesday with the U.S. Figure Skating Association, seeking to revoke
Callaghan's membership in the sport's national governing body.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of recent interviews, Maurizi has said that he does
not believe Callaghan should be allowed to coach anymore. If
Callaghan's membership in the skating association were revoked, he
would still be able to coach, but he would not be allowed to
participate in any of the Olympic-style competitions that the
national governing body sanctions. Tonya Harding faces such a
lifetime ban for her role in the clubbing attack of Nancy Kerrigan
in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi declined to be interviewed Tuesday, saying he had been
advised by his lawyer not to speak to reporters and that he needed
to spend time with his family during what he described as an
emotional period. He has said previously that he hoped rinks will
be reluctant to hire Callaghan in the future, thus effectively
derailing his coaching career.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan, 53, one of the dominant figures in figure skating for
years, has vehemently denied having a sexual relationship with
Maurizi. He has dismissed any suggestion that he behaved improperly
during his association with Maurizi, who was a student and coaching
colleague of Callaghan's for two decades and rose through the ranks
of pairs skating to finish fifth at the 1986 national
championships. Until now, Maurizi has never filed a formal
grievance against Callaghan.
</P>
<P>
   Callaghan has resigned as director of competitive skating at the
Detroit Skating Club and has announced his retirement from the
competitive side of the sport, saying he was tired of the incessant
travel. He plans to remain in the sport as a consultant.
</P>
<P>
   USFSA president Jim Disbrow said Maurizi's grievance was filed
with its ethics committee. The association has 30 days to decide
whether the complaint is valid and whether a grievance process
should be initiated, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carole Shulman, executive director of the Professional Skaters
Association, a national coaches unit, said it also received a
formal grievance Tuesday from Maurizi and that it would have 20
days to decide whether a grievance process was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Groulx, Callaghan's lawyer, said that neither he nor his
client had been notified of the grievances. ``At this time we don't
have anything to say,'' Groulx said. ``As far as we know, nothing's
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The grievance filed with the USFSA is considered the more
significant one.
</P>
<P>
   Disbrow said a statute of limitations regarding alleged
misconduct could complicate matters. He said that according to the
skating association's guidelines, a grievance must be filed within
60 days or six months _ he could not remember which _ of any
alleged violations of the organization's rules.
</P>
<P>
   Maurizi, who is now 36, has accused Callaghan of engaging in
inappropriate sexual conduct with him when he was 15 and has said
that Callaghan later abused his position of authority to initiate a
full sexual relationship when Maurizi was 18 and barely out of high
school in 1981. The sexual relationship, Maurizi said, continued
off and on until two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply can't be looking at all rumors running around left,
right and center for 100 years,'' Disbrow said. He added, however,
that the skating association would examine Maurizi's allegations to
determine whether extenuating circumstances made them actionable
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure we look at this realistically,'' Disbrow
said. ``Anything that gets this much publicity, we want to make
sure we act properly.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
