<SLUG> BC-NY-ABORTION-DOCTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION DOCTOR'S KILLER HID GUN NEAR SCENE, INVESTIGATORS
THEORIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JOSEPH BERGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials say they think that the killer of an
upstate New York doctor who performed abortions probably buried the
rifle in the ground days before the shooting, unearthed the weapon
to fire the fatal shot, then hurriedly reburied it before fleeing.
</P>
<P>
   Erie County District Attorney Frank Clark said investigators
reached that conclusion after agents discovered a high-powered
rifle last week. The gun was buried a foot deep in woods 200 feet
behind the stately brick house in Amherst, N.Y., where Dr. Barnett
Slepian was slain about 10 p.m. on Oct. 23 by a bullet fired
through his kitchen window. The rifle, which the authorities have
refused to describe, has been sent to the FBI laboratory in
Washington for ballistics tests and fingerprint checks that could
determine whether it was the murder weapon.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Tuesday, Clark said that in the days
after the killing, police assumed that the sniper had fled with the
weapon, and did not consider the possibility of a buried weapon.
They used a metal detector, he said, but scanned only the area
around the tree where they presumed the sniper had fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this business 27 years and worked directly or
indirectly on thousands of homicides, and in not one did the
perpetrator bury the gun at or near the scene,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But as no rifle turned up, he said, investigators began to
theorize that the killer carried the gun into the woods at a time
when no one was on the streets, probably after midnight, and came
back on another day to shoot Dr. Slepian when he would be at home
and awake. Clark described the neighborhood as an affluent
community ``where people are leery.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How a person got out carrying a weapon puzzled'' the
investigators, he said. ``And it puzzled them to the point that
they started wondering, what if he didn't take it out? What if he
left it there?''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, he said, investigators decided to sweep a broader
area with metal detectors, but had to wait until the ground thawed
or until the heavy snowfall melted.
</P>
<P>
   Police have not formally identified a suspect, but have focused
their manhunt on James Kopp, an abortion opponent who drifted
around the country from demonstration to demonstration. Clark said
that about 10 days before the slaying, a jogger became suspicious
of a black 1987 Chevrolet Cavalier with Vermont plates that was
parked in the area at 6 a.m. The jogger wrote down the license
plate number, which was traced to Kopp.
</P>
<P>
   So far, federal agents have not found him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
