<SLUG> BC-NJ-TAX-CUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITMAN SIGNS BILLS CUTTING PROPERTY TAXES
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JERRY GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELLEVILLE, N.J. _ Gov. Christie Whitman signed a bipartisan
package of bills Tuesday giving New Jersey residents the first
installment of promised property tax relief and giving herself a
powerful new talking point in her race for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today is about helping local officials across the state find
efficiencies; it's also about honoring a promise I made to the
taxpayers of the state of New Jersey to relieve them from higher
property taxes,'' Whitman said at a bill-signing ceremony at a
public library here.
</P>
<P>
   The four bills she signed into law Tuesday amount to a modest
$35 million in spending and are intended to encourage the 1,600
local governments in the state to consolidate services like schools
and fire protection in order to save money and hold down property
tax increases. That legislation is likely to help her senatorial
prospects, as is a bill giving residents $1 billion in direct
property tax relief, the installments timed to arrive within weeks
before Election Day for the next five years. The governor intends
to sign that bill on Thursday, the deadline to file tax returns.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman tried to play down, at least for the day, any
political advantage she might gain from the property tax cuts,
which took seven months from the time they were proposed to reach
her desk.
</P>
<P>
   ``For government work, it's not bad to take ideas from a
commission and get them into legislation that is actually signed
within seven months,'' she told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   In her first term as governor, Mrs. Whitman delivered on a
campaign pledge to cut the state income tax by 30 percent for most
middle- and low-income taxpayers. But in November 1997 the
notoriously restive New Jersey electorate came close to turning her
out of office in favor of a long-shot Democratic candidate,
Woodbridge Mayor James E. McGreevey, and much of that voter anger
was over paying some of the highest property taxes and automobile
insurance rates in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But in the first three months of this year, with the help of a
Legislature controlled by her fellow Republicans, Whitman has moved
swiftly to shield her political weak spot on property taxes as she
turns her attention toward a race for the Senate seat being vacated
next year by Frank Lautenberg, a Democrat who is retiring after
three terms.
</P>
<P>
   Late last year, Whitman established a property tax commission to
provide her with ideas for controlling property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate shouldn't be about relief vs. reform,'' Whitman
said Tuesday. ``I believe anything that we can do to help ease the
property burden is worth doing, and we can do all these things.''
</P>
<P>
   One bill that Whitman intends to sign on Thursday _ a week after
she announced that she was forming a fund-raising committee for a
Senate race _ is clearly the highest-profile piece of legislation.
It will provide $1 billion over five years for property tax relief,
eventually giving homeowners, regardless of income, an average
annual rebate check of $600.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tax reduction to individuals is simultaneously a tax bill
and a statement of political philosophy,'' said Joseph J. Seneca,
the chairman of the N.J. Council of Economic Advisers, a
five-member panel that analyzes economic conditions and forecasts
trends. ``It's a response to the perceived request of homeowners
for direct property tax relief. That concern has been expressed for
many years, especially at the ballot box on many Novembers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
