<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DRAFT-SMITH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SMITH IS THE BEST QUARTERBACK IN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NFL-DRAFT) 
(rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OK, so Tim Couch is 6 feet 4 inches and the golden boy. He was
the darling quarterback throughout the college football season, and
for good reason. Full of range. Throws the short stuff with
precision. Smart. An aw-shucks, down-home Kentucky fella. I would
draft him No. 1, too, if not for one other quarterback: Akili
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   In a season and half as the starting quarterback at Oregon,
Smith turned the Pacific-10 inside out. He will eventually do the
same in the NFL. That is why the Cleveland Browns must select him
with the draft's first pick.
</P>
<P>
   It is not simply Smith's size (6-3, 221 pounds), arm strength,
intelligence or presentation.
</P>
<P>
   Pro football in the next decade will become a game where
quarterbacks must be mobile. Today, that quality is a luxury.
Tomorrow, it will be a necessity. Mobility and athleticism are
becoming essential because pro defenses are faster and are more
insistent on rushing the passer from all positions, employing an
assortment of tricky tactics.
</P>
<P>
   To combat that, a quarterback not only must be able to think
quickly on his feet, but he had better have quick feet. Murderous
mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Akili Smith is this draft's best quarterback when combining
thunderous arm and magical feet.
</P>
<P>
   We are talking, truly, a thunderous arm. Football veterans say
the only quarterback they have seen who throws a ball similar to
Smith's tight, multirevolution, swift ball is Warren Moon. And
several others say his passes are better than Moon's. Smith passes
will cut through the fierce Cleveland winter winds. And he
possesses the size and stamina to excel in cold weather.
</P>
<P>
   Mobility? This guy scrambled for a long run of 58 yards as a
junior, and then for 62 yards as a senior. Couch's long runs in the
last two years were for 31 and 14 yards. The yardage, however, is
not the thing. It is his ability to escape, and the threat that
poses. Smith is a passer first, scrambler second. But scrambling on
his terms, in his manner, keeps defenses on edge. In fear.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so there are the issues of his draft testing (supposedly not
impressive) and of his college background (scrapes with the law in
Oregon). Really, now, can a guy direct an offense in the Pac-10 and
throw for 3,763 yards, for 32 touchdowns and only eight
interceptions in his senior season and be dumb?
</P>
<P>
   And really, now, Smith had an altercation with some guys outside
a bar (unfortunate) and a driving-under-the-influence charge
(terrible judgment) weeks after he first arrived at Oregon. He was
a model student and citizen afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The key is that Smith made initial mistakes and learned real
lessons. He grew up.
</P>
<P>
   He is 24, and there is concern that he only played a year and a
half of big-time football at Oregon because he tried two years of
pro baseball first. Hey, give me a football player, any player,
willing to step out and to live, who took a challenging route to
greatness. He will appreciate it later in his life, and show it.
Smith does.
</P>
<P>
   That trait is the real bonus in drafting Akili Smith at No. 1.
He will have an impact on his teammates in real and lasting ways.
They will love playing for and with him. They will latch on to the
real, tangible and touchable person that he is. He has charisma, a
winning smile and attitude, the kind of personality that says jump
on board.
</P>
<P>
   The Browns will love him, and so will the town.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland is building a new franchise on old, historic soil.
Picking Smith sets the foundation for this franchise for the next
decade, a decade for which he is primed because of the way he plays
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderous arm, murderous mobility.
</P>
<P>
   Come draft day, Smith should go to Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Aw-shucks. Because Smith is golden.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
