<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BULLPEN HAS PICKED UP SLACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND _ How have the Angels survived the big losses to their
lineup (Mo Vaughn, Jim Edmonds and Gary DiSarcina) and the poor
performances by their starting pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   The bullpen, for starters.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Tuesday's game against the A's, the seven Angels
relievers were a combined 2-0 with a 2.17 ERA. Five of the seven
hadn't allowed an earned run, including Al Levine (two appearances,
6 2/3 innings), Mark Petkovsek (two appearances, five innings) and
Mike Magnante (three appearances, 4 2/3 innings).
</P>
<P>
   All three played for other teams last season -- Levine with the
Rangers, Petkovsek with the Cardinals and Magnante with the Royals.
But all have come together with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know how to pitch, Angels manager Terry Collins said.
``One thing they have is they know what they've got -- they don't
try to do what they can't.
</P>
<P>
   With closer Troy Percival serving as the bullpen's anchor,
Collins says he manages an eight-inning game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best bullpen we've had in the three years I've
been here, set-up man Shigetoshi Hasegawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Because Angels starters completed five innings in only two of
their first seven games, the Angels are benefitting from carrying
12 pitchers. But Collins said he doesn't know how long he'll be
able to have that luxury.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no telling when he might have to make a change, he
said. ``Sometimes you run into the problem of finding enough work
for all of them. ... But I tip my hat to the pitching coaches. They
were absolutely correct in saying we needed 12 pitchers out of
spring training.
</P>
<P>
   Center fielder Jim Edmonds is eligible to come of the disabled
list today, but he won't. And he will not join the team here.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds has not played this season because of a strained groin
and a cyst in a muscle in his right shoulder. It's the shoulder
that continues to bother him, and there is no prognosis on when he
might be able to return.
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Ned Bergert only shrugs when asked about Edmonds.
Collins said he's through guessing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't done very good at predicting that stuff, Collins
said. ``I said Gary would be back opening day, and he's out four
months. I said Jimmy would be playing (today), and he's not even
here.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels certainly didn't envision it, but Jeff Huson was
their starting left fielder Tuesday, and Tim Unroe will be the
starting left fielder tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Without Edmonds and Vaughn, the Angels have had to move things
around. Orlando Palmeiro had started the previous six games in left
field before Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an opportunity to get the bench guys a game, Collins
said. ``I can't tell you how important that's going to be.
</P>
<P>
   Unroe, a longshot to make the team, led the team with five
spring homers.
</P>
<P>
   Collins said Todd Greene, who caught six innings Monday in
Texas, felt good and had no stiffness in his shoulder Tuesday.
He'll likely get another start behind the plate toward the end of
the week. ... In the third inning Tuesday, the A's Mike Macfarlane
hit a foul popup to the first base dugout area, where first baseman
Darin Erstad gave chase. But unlike on Mo Vaughn's injury, when the
opposing team occupied the first base dugout, about seven or eight
Angels got off the bench and prevented Erstad from falling into the
dugout. ... The Angels and A's resume their series tonight (7:05)
at the Oakland Coliseum. Chuck Finley (1-0, 6.00 ERA) will start
for Anaheim against Oakland's Kenny Rogers (0-1, 5.79).
</P>
</TEXT>
