<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAVES INTERVIEW NAIA'S MEYER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Don Meyer, one of college basketball's winningest
coaches, interviewed on campus Tuesday for the vacant men's head
coaching position at Pepperdine.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer's interview was his second for the job. Pepperdine
athletic director John Watson flew to Nashville last week to meet
Meyer and former Vanderbilt coach Jan van Breda Kolff.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, 54, is 665-179 in 24 seasons at Lipscomb University, an
NAIA school in Nashville, and 702-220 overall. The Bisons won the
NAIA national championship in 1986 and have averaged almost 28 wins
per season under Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, whose motion offense has produced two players who scored
more than 4,000 points in their careers, presents a coaching
contrast to another leading candidate for the job, Pepperdine
assistant Randy Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett's specialty is defense; the Waves were second in the
West Coast Conference in scoring defense this past season, giving
up an average of 63.2 points per game. Pepperdine also held its
opponents to 29.2 percent shooting on 3-point attempts, an all-time
conference low.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, who was inducted into the NAIA Hall of Fame in 1993, may
be an unknown on the national scene, but he is well-respected
within the coaching community. He runs the largest summer
basketball camp in the nation _ from which he earns a reported
$300,000 to $400,000 _ and he has put out 30 instructional
videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   He also runs a coaching academy that draws 300 high school and
college coaches each year. Besides his impressive coaching resume,
Meyer has another factor in his favor: Lipscomb, like Pepperdine,
is affiliated with the churches of Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer, who earned a Ph.D. from the University of Utah in 1972,
was turned down for the Vanderbilt job last month. He reportedly
wants to leave Lipscomb because the school is considering a move up
from NAIA to NCAA Division I.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't want to go through that probationary period and
build from scratch,'' a source at Lipscomb said.
</P>
<P>
   Other candidates for the job are UC Santa Barbara assistant
Marty Wilson, Biola head coach Dave Holmquist, Rhode Island
assistant Jim Harrick Jr. and UCLA assistants Michael Holton and
Jim Saia.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine is expected to introduce its new head coach by the
end of next week. Former coach Lorenzo Romar resigned March 5 to
take the head coaching position at Saint Louis University.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
