<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' WINNING BLUEPRINT IS A BOUNCE AND A BASH
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Angelos, the Baltimore Orioles' principal
owner, thought that along with being a very good team, the Yankees
have been very lucky, and it would have been hard to argue with him
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   A ground ball that should have ended the eighth inning took a
fortunate bounce for the Yankees, extending their rally and
permitting them to go on and score four runs in the inning, for a
6-3 victory. The Yankees have won six consecutive games since
losing their first game of the season, while the Orioles find
themselves in a familiar position. They have lost eight consecutive
games at Yankee Stadium and already the Orioles _ an old team that
could use a quick start _ are four games out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees tied the game in the bottom of the sixth, 2-2, and
in the bottom of the seventh, Baltimore Manager Ray Miller, needing
to win the first game of this series, inserted left-handed relief
pitcher Arthur Rhodes, whose power stuff matches up well against
the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Rhodes stifled the Yankees in the seventh and retired the first
two batters in the eighth, before Bernie Williams worked a two-out
walk. Tino Martinez poked a grounder down the third base line,
where Cal Ripken set himself to catch the ball and throw out
Martinez at first. But the bounder hit the bag and skipped over
Ripken's head, rolling down the left field line, a fluke double.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles elected to walk Chili Davis _ the American League
player of the week _ and load the bases, bringing Jorge Posada to
the plate, with an .067 batting average. But Posada would get to
bat right-handed, his strong side: In 1998, he hit .357
right-handed, .228 left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   On the seventh pitch of the at-bat, Rhodes skipped a ball in the
dirt, allowing Williams to score the lead run and thrilling the
crowd of 25,254. Once the fans settled, however, Posada smashed a
three-run home run to right, finishing off the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did not commit an error in their first six games,
and in fact, they have only 13 in their last 47 games, dating back
to Aug. 29 and including the post-season. Placing that rate of
efficiency in perspective, the Yankees would commit only 48 errors
over a full season, or little more than half of the existing major
league record for fewest errors in a single season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees played the first four innings last night as if
it were the first week of spring training. After Brady Anderson led
off the game with a single, Baltimore's Mike Bordick hit a bouncer
right to the third baseman Scott Brosius, who deftly gloved the
ball, turned and threw to second for the start of what should have
been a double play.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, the Yankees' second baseman, caught the ball
with plenty of time but threw the ball into the dirt and past
Martinez at first.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs in the inning, Albert Belle swung and missed at a
sinking fastball, strike three _ but the pitch glanced off the
glove of catcher Jorge Posada as Bordick took second and the inning
continued. Harold Baines pulled a single to right and Bordick
scored.
</P>
<P>
   When Jeter lifted a fly toward right, Belle slowly retreated,
appearing as if he might catch the ball well in front of the
warning track. But Jeter's fly drifted a few feet over the right
field fence, Jeter's third home run of the season. Yankees 1,
Orioles 1.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch's second fielding gaffe cost the Yankees' another run.
Leading off the third inning, Will Clark hit a grounder to second,
where Knoblauch bent over and watched the ball go between his legs,
the Yankees' first error of the season. Belle singled and, once
more, Baines drove in a run with a single to give the Orioles a 2-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter had tied the score in the first, and he countered again in
the sixth, opening the inning by hammering a changeup to
straightaway center field. This one landed short of the wall,
leaving Jeter with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill then smashed a grounder that Clark at first speared
with a lunge, a play so difficult that Jeter rambled home from
third with the run that evened the score at 2-2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
