<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEDICARE-HMOS-NYT </SLUG>
  
 EDITORIAL: MISINFORMATION FROM HMOs  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, April 14:
</P>
<P>
   Two troubling reports by the federal General Accounting Office
show how difficult it can be for Medicare beneficiaries to get
accurate information about their health coverage from their
managed-care plans. These plans now provide health care to about 7
million out of 39 million Medicare recipients, a figure that has
doubled in the past three years. Yet a spot check of 16 plans found
that all of them provided enrollees with either inaccurate or
misleading information.
</P>
<P>
   Congress revamped the Medicare managed-care program in 1997 to
expand choices for beneficiaries, with the expectation that more
competition among managed-care plans would provide better benefits
and lower out-of-pocket fees. A recent federal survey found that
most Medicare enrollees were satisfied with their health plans. But
for beneficiaries to make informed choices, they have to be able to
get truthful, understandable information about benefits and the
rules of coverage.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO examined 16 out of more than 340 managed-care plans
serving Medicare enrollees. Nearly half of the study group
misstated benefit coverage. For example, several told enrollees
they needed to get a doctor's referral to obtain a mammogram, when
in fact Medicare policy explicitly prohibits plans from requiring
such a referral and even requires health plans to notify enrollees
of this benefit. Some plans simply did not give out detailed
benefit information. One plan provided enrollees with a
prescription drug benefit that was substantially less than what it
had promised to provide in its Medicare contract with the
government.
</P>
<P>
   Such abuses may not be surprising in the unregulated private
sector. But these failures took place even though federal Medicare
officials were supposed to review and approve all marketing
brochures and materials sent out by the managed-care plans. The
lack of standard terminology about benefits makes it hard for
government reviewers, not to mention Medicare recipients, to
determine the actual scope of benefits offered or to compare
competing plans.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report, the GAO found that even though Medicare
recipients have extensive rights to appeal benefit denials, health
plans often failed to inform them of those rights. In some
instances enrollees were not told the reason for the denial.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare officials say they are moving toward requiring
standardized benefit information, and will improve oversight of the
appeals process. Despite these problems, Medicare enrollees still
have far more rights against unfair health plan decisions than
people covered by private insurance. But the GAO reports show the
need for stronger enforcement in Medicare, even as Congress debates
whether to extend similar protections to privately insured
individuals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
