</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-POLICE-SAFIR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE POLICE COMMISSIONER'S GAFFES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Wednesday, April 14:
</P>
<P>
   For starters, Police Commissioner Howard Safir needs to repay
New York City the $3,600 that it cost taxpayers to provide eight
on-duty detectives for his daughter's wedding.
</P>
<P>
   Then he needs to either explain more fully or apologize for an
earlier blunder. That was the charge made in a lawsuit against one
Monica Nascimento that she was intoxicated when she ran into Mrs.
Safir's car. The Safirs have already dismissed the lawyer who filed
their original lawsuit. The new attorney said the charge is not
included in the amended suit because it does not ``comport with
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The larger reality, of course, is that Safir is at a critical
juncture in his public career. He needs to reassure the public that
he is not abusing his office and can provide an example of stable
leadership to a troubled Police Department. The steps outlined
above would be a start. The Patrolmen's Benevolent Association has
just given Safir a vote of ``no confidence.'' Some critics and
journalistic commentators are calling for his removal. Those
responses seem extreme to us, for the time being. But it is clear
that Safir has to end the pattern of misjudgments and
public-relations gaffes that have made it difficult for him to deal
with the fallout from the Amadou Diallo shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Both Safir and his boss, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, need to take a
placatory rather than a defensive tack. Before he flew to Texas on
Tuesday to talk national Republican strategy, Giuliani was in
reflexive counterpunching mode. He praised the commissioner as ``a
very ethical man,'' ``a terrific police commissioner'' and ``the
most loyal police commissioner I've ever seen.'' The endorsement
came salted with criticism of the commissioner's critics, including
the media and the police officers' union. In particular the mayor
called Tuesday PBA vote ``one of the more treacherous things that's
being done in the name of politics.''
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, of course, such criticism always comes with
political and labor-management spin. But it cannot be dismissed
entirely, because Safir has been on a run of executive
misjudgments. First there was the all-expense-paid trip to Los
Angeles for the Oscars when he should have been at home stabilizing
the department after the Diallo shooting. Then came the messy
lawsuit against Ms. Nascimento. The use of city detectives to
investigate her looked suspicious, but she had given a fake name at
the scene of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, blaming the dismissed lawyer for what was said
about the woman in a lawsuit bearing his name is not acceptable for
the city's senior police officer. Even in private legal matters he
has a duty to provide a public example and to eschew claims of
naivete or ignorance. Amending the $1.25 million lawsuit to
eliminate unsubstantiated charges that Ms. Nascimento was
intoxicated from drugs or alcohol was a correct if belated step.
</P>
<P>
   As for the use of city detectives for 119 man-hours at his
daughter's wedding, the writing of a reimbursement check should be
only the first step. The commissioner needs people on his staff
with the duty and authority to remind the boss of the lines between
public and private use of police personnel. When there are gray
``security'' areas, as Safir said there were at this celebration,
he should err on the side of paying his own way. After all, he
commands a force of 40,000 officers who are not supposed to take a
free sandwich at the corner coffee shop.
</P>
<P>
   Safir has just received a vote of confidence from Giuliani. He
needs to work hard and fast to make sure the rest of the public has
reason to share that confidence.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
