<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN HOOP STAR FACES MARIJUANA CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Khalid El-Amin, the star point guard who
helped lead the University of Connecticut to the national
basketball championship, was charged with possessing marijuana
Tuesday night after police here had stopped him on suspicion of
running a red light.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton, the team's all-America forward, was riding in
the red Cadillac driven by El-Amin but faces no charges, police
said. Lt. Michael Manzi said El-Amin had a ``nickel bag'' of
marijuana _ a plastic bag containing $5 worth of the drug. Police
said he had ``a very minor amount,'' less than an ounce.
Connecticut officials say that possession of less than four ounces
is a misdemeanor, and that was the charge against El-Amin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was very reserved and somber,'' Manzi said of El-Amin's
demeanor as he was arrested on Vine Street at 5:30 Tuesday evening
in the city's North End, a crowded, busy neighborhood where dozens
of curious residents gathered immediately as it became clear who
had been stopped.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd cheered as El-Amin vaulted past reporters into a
cruiser for the trip from a police substation to the city's booking
unit, where he was fingerprinted and photographed. El-Amin was
released at 7:05 p.m. on his written promise to appear in court,
which is standard when such a small amount of marijuana is
involved, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest came only four days before UConn is to be honored
with a milelong parade through this city, which has been giddy with
Husky-mania since the team upset top-ranked Duke, 77-74, on March
29 in St. Petersburg, Fla., giving the school its first NCAA men's
basketball championship.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin, a sophomore who is 19 years old, is a crowd favorite,
in part because of his unusually stout stature for a basketball
player; he is 5 feet 10 inches tall and weighs 203 pounds. He is a
business major.
</P>
<P>
   Amid speculation that he might leave the team for the National
Basketball Association, he announced last week that he would return
for his junior year to try to lead the Huskies to back-to-back
titles.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, his high school, Minneapolis North in Minnesota,
retired his jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, 21, is widely expected to turn pro instead of playing
for UConn in his senior year.
</P>
<P>
   A wild scene unfolded on Vine Street when two plainclothes
officers from a narcotics task force pulled El-Amin over after they
said he had run a red light.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two faces in the car were immediately recognized,'' Manzi
said, allowing himself a small chuckle after a tense evening.
</P>
<P>
   He said he did not know what led officers to search El-Amin. The
car, which apparently belongs to a friend of El-Amin's, was
searched and then towed, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton was left on the street to fend for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neighbors were extending offers of rides and to use the phone
and so forth,'' Manzi said.
</P>
<P>
   UConn athletic officials said Tuesday night that they were only
now learning details of the incident and had no immediate comment.
They said they believed El-Amin attended class Tuesday at the
campus in Storrs, about 30 miles northeast of Hartford.
</P>
<P>
   A test at police headquarters confirmed that the substance found
on El-Amin was marijuana, Sgt. Daniel Meehan said. He said that
during the 35-minute booking process, El-Amin was ``very cordial,
very cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   Police said El-Amin also got a summons for running a red light.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin was the fiery leader of UConn's championship team, which
often fed off his enthusiasm and intensity.
</P>
<P>
   He was only the third UConn player to score 1,000 points as a
sophomore.
</P>
<P>
   He has averaged 14.9 points and 4.1 assists for the past two
seasons, finishing second in scoring to Hamilton by averaging 13.8
points this past season. He led the team in assists with 140.
</P>
<P>
   El-Amin was named to the all-Final Four team after scoring 30
points and handing out 10 assists in the semifinal victory over
Ohio State and the championship game over Duke.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
