<HEADLINE>
CLINTON LAWYERS SAID TO OPPOSE APPEAL OF CONTEMPT CITATION
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: The following story, previously eliminated from The New
York Times News Service budget, is now restored) (nk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's legal advisers are strongly
leaning toward recommending that he not challenge a federal judge's
finding that he was in contempt of court for giving false testimony
in the Paula Jones case, a lawyer who has spoken with members of
the legal team said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer said that while the team had not presented a final
recommendation to Clinton, several members were inclined to urge
the president not to appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Clinton had decided whether to appeal, the lawyer
said, ``My guess is that he has not.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Susan Webber Wright of federal District Court in Little
Rock, Ark., declared on Monday that the president's testimony had
been ``false, misleading and evasive'' in the sexual-misconduct
suit brought by Mrs. Jones, a onetime Arkansas state clerical
worker who contended that Clinton, then governor, had made a crude
proposition to her in a Little Rock hotel room in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The judge cited Clinton for civil contempt, determining among
other things that he gave misleading answers in a deposition on
Jan. 17, 1998, in Washington. In that session, held before Wright,
the president said he had not had sexual relations with a former
White House intern, Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, Clinton acknowledged that he had had a
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. The relationship was at the center
of a monthslong impeachment battle in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said Tuesday night through a spokesman that it
had no comment on the thinking of the president or his advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Under the civil contempt finding, Wright ordered Clinton to pay
``any reasonable expenses'' including legal fees incurred by Mrs.
Jones as a result of Clinton's misleading testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The people who are known to be advising Clinton are Robert
Bennett, who represented him throughout the Jones case; David
Kendall, Clinton's personal lawyer; Charles F.C. Ruff, another
White House lawyer, and Bruce Lindsey, a White House lawyer and
close friend.
</P>
<P>
   The judgment evolving among the advisers is said to be that,
having settled the Jones lawsuit last fall and having survived the
impeachment crisis, the president should put the episode behind him
for good by declining to appeal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-13-99 2355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990413.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-13 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-PETTWAY-     04-13 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TRINIDAD-PETTWAY-520&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNANIMOUS DECISION: PETTWAY DOESN'T HAVE A CHANCE TO BEAT TRINIDAD
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)   (rk) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Felix Trinidad defends his IBF welterweight title against
Vincent Pettway next month, it could be an embarrassing mismatch.
</P>
<P>
   Even HBO, which is televising the bout at Roberto Clemente
Stadium in San Juan, P.R., on May 29, acknowledged the potential
for a one-sided Trinidad victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time we made the deal for Pettway, I just remembered
that he was a former champion,'' Lou DiBella, HBO's senior vice
president of programming, said. ``We didn't really do the homework.
I have no possible explanation of how he could be the mandatory
after looking at his record.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is exactly what Pettway is: the IBF's mandatory
challenger to Trinidad. And though he has a creditable record of
41-6-1, Pettway also has the credentials to support all the
skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   After all, he has not fought anyone with a winning record since
1995, and has not fought a welterweight with a winning record since
1991.
</P>
<P>
   In Pettway's last two fights, a journeyman named Gerald Reed
took him the distance both times, and in the first bout between
them Pettway broke his hand and was sidelined for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Bottjer, a matchmaker for Cedric Kushner, who saw Pettway
fight Reed on Feb. 6 in Washington, said: ``I think Vincent Pettway
is a shot fighter. I saw him against Benji Singleton, a fighter
from North Carolina with a losing record, and Benji Singleton gave
him life and death. He rocked him a couple of times. He's still got
some skills, but his ability to take a shot has diminished
greatly.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the fight against Trinidad, Bottjer said: ``On paper, he
definitely deserves a shot. But the reality is that Trinidad will
destroy him. They put him on that February card in Washington not
to showcase his skills, but to keep him busy. But his expiration
date expired a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettway believes that HBO is trying to move him out of the way
to keep alive its plans for a possible welterweight championship
showdown between Trinidad and Oscar De La Hoya in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people don't think I'm a worthy opponent, but I'm a
dangerous opponent,'' Pettway, 32, said in a recently from suburban
Baltimore, where he lives and trains. ``People say that I can't
take a punch. But Trinidad doesn't take a punch that well either.
HBO doesn't want me to have a big payday and they know that there's
a chance that I can knock Trinidad out and upset their plans for
him to fight De La Hoya.''
</P>
<P>
   Don King, the promoter for Pettway and Trinidad, said the
network was simply having a knee-jerk reaction to last month's
controversial Evander Holyfield-Lennox Lewis decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the wake of Holyfield-Lewis, all of a sudden it's like
they've gotten an echo from the heavens, a trembling coming out of
the sky that is saying `Don't do Trinidad-Pettway!''' King said.
``Pettway is a very capable opponent.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pettway-Trinidad bout came about because it was a part of
HBO's negotiations with King for a Trinidad-Pernell Whitaker bout,
which took place Feb. 20 at Madison Square Garden. HBO had to take
Pettway as a mandatory challenger for Trinidad in order to make the
Trinidad-Whitaker fight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``Pettway is a nobody as far as they're concerned,'' Mac Lewis,
who has trained Pettway since he was 9 years old, said. ``He's lost
a few fights, sure. A lot of people lose fights. But his record is
still good. Why is everybody trying to pull him back?''
</P>
<P>
   The last time Pettway fought someone with a winning record was
in 1995, when he lost his IBF junior middleweight title to Paul
Vaden by a knockout. The next year, Terry Norris knocked Pettway
out in a 154-pound WBC and IBF title fight.
</P>
<P>
   Pettway then fought Singleton in his first welterweight bout
since 1991. He beat Singleton. Singleton's record at the time was
13-18-1; he is now 20-46-4.
</P>
<P>
   After the victory over Singleton, Pettway moved up to No. 4 in
the IBF rankings at welterweight. Next, Pettway fought Harold
Bennett and knocked him out in the third round. It was Bennett's
fourth loss in five fights, three by knockout. That moved Pettway
up to No. 2. In 1997, Pettway moved up as the No. 1 contender
without lifting a glove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was active, fighting guys,'' Pettway said. ``That's why I
moved up. Guys in front of me weren't busy, so I moved up.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettway had been No. 2 behind Patrick Charpentier. But when
Charpentier announced he was going to challenge De La Hoya for the
WBC welterweight title he was dropped from the IBF's No. 1
contender spot to No. 5. Pettway moved up to No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 13, 1997, Pettway fought Reed, who was 37 years old and
had a 15-19-3 record at the time. Reed took Pettway the distance
and Pettway broke his hand in the fight and had to have surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gerald Reed was a crafty fighter,'' Pettway said. ``People say
Vincent Pettway must not have been right, because he couldn't knock
this guy out. But the guy was a survivor. I hurt him a couple of
times, but he knew how to hold and head-butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettway was inactive all of 1998 after the surgery. That medical
suspension did not hurt his ranking. He remained No. 1 in the IBF
On Feb. 6, Pettway returned. He wound up fighting Reed again,
because his opponent backed out of the fight at the last minute and
was replaced by Reed, who was a year older and whose record was
15-23-3. Again, Reed took Pettway the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Pettway has remained atop the IBF rankings at welterweight _
ahead of other contenders like Vernon Forrest, Pernell Whitaker and
Ike Quartey.
</P>
<P>
   The rating system of the sanctioning organizatio
</P>
</TEXT>
