<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MLICKI COULD BE ODD MAN OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna could rejoin the
Los Angeles Dodgers by the end of the weekend, which has caused
Dodgers manager Davey Johnson to run through a number of scenarios
on what to do with his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   There are various paths the Dodgers could take, but the most
likely conclusion always seems to be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know there's a lot of interest in (Dave) Mlicki,''
Johnson said before Tuesday's game with Arizona at Bank One
Ballpark.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was referring to constant trade speculation that has
engulfed Mlicki since Kevin Brown signed his $105 million
free-agent contract in December. It effectively bumped Mlicki out
of the starting rotation and into the Dodgers' bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would help the organization, not only today but down the
line, we would have to do that,'' Johnson said. ``I'd like to keep
him, but maybe in the best interest of the club and Mlicki, it's
something that has to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna pitched one inning in his second rehab stint with Single-A
San Bernardino on Tuesday and in one inning walked one batter and
struck one out. He threw 23 pitches. Johnson said he wanted Osuna
to pitch two or three innings, but it was scaled back to one on the
advice of pitching coach Charlie Hough.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said it was possible the
Dodgers could send Osuna to Triple-A Albuquerque instead of
activating him, but that was just one of a few options. Malone
wouldn't comment on the trade interest in Mlicki.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is going with 12 pitchers and sending one of
three catchers to the minors. The likely candidate is Rick Wilkins,
who has one at-bat this season and is clearly the backup to Paul
LoDuca.
</P>
<P>
   Another issue is the Dodgers' new regime not being familiar with
Osuna's ability during a season, though Johnson said he'd be
inclined to use Osuna in a dual set-up role with Alan Mills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know him,'' Johnson said of Osuna. ``I heard what
he's like and I've seen him throw.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson is in search of a second right-handed set-up man in the
bullpen because Mel Rojas is struggling. Rojas, who gave up five
runs in one inning Monday, has a 15.75 ERA in four outings.
</P>
<P>
   Hollandsworth update: In a week or so the Dodgers will have
another roster decision to make. Johnson said he's eyeing April 23,
the beginning of a three-game series with the St. Louis Cardinals,
as a possible return date for Todd Hollandsworth, on the disabled
list with a pulled hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   Malone said Hollandsworth would be sent to the minors for a
rehab stint before joining the Dodgers. That could happen when L.A.
returns from San Diego on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to have to hit the ball and show that he can run
and perform in a game,'' Malone said. ``We're not going to rush
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Runnin' the bases: The Diamondbacks stole two bases in the first
three innings against the Dodgers, meaning the only would-be base
stealer the Dodgers have caught this season came when Carlos Perez
picked off Colorado's Neifi Perez. Opponents are 10 for 11 against
the Dodgers and have been successful on all nine attempts against
Todd Hundley's reconstructed right elbow.... The Dodgers entered
Tuesday 14 for 75 (.187) with runners in scoring position, but
Johnson said not to fret. ``There hasn't been enough chances for a
reading to be taken,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
